<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO NEWSPAPER CAN BE SOLD, JUDGE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in San Francisco ruled Thursday that the Hearst
Corp.'s $660 million purchase of The San Francisco Chronicle did
not violate antitrust laws and that the company would have had
legal justification for closing The San Francisco Examiner had it
chosen to.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle has been a fierce journalistic rival of The
Examiner, the newspaper that gave William Randolph Hearst his start
in publishing, for more than a century. The two newspapers have
also been business partners for the past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Judge Vaughn Walker noted that The Examiner's
financial condition was so weak that it ``imposes a substantial
drain on the profitability'' of the newspaper agency whose profits
were shared by both. The Chronicle's circulation of 464,943 is more
than four times that of The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Since the closing of The Examiner would have been economically
justified, its subsidized sale to the politically influential Fang
family in San Francisco was laced with what Walker called
``malodorous aspects,'' in reference to the complicated political
and legal dance behind the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Hearst agreed to sell the newspaper to the family's
business, ExIm, and give it a subsidy of up to $66 million for
three years to help keep a truncated version of the newspaper
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's decision, if it survives possible appeals, paves the
way for Hearst to act on its plans to merge the newsrooms of the
two newspapers and begin renewed competition with its rivals in the
San Francisco Bay area. The most prominent of these rivals, The San
Jose Mercury News, which is owned by Knight Ridder, this week began
delivering a special San Francisco edition, firing the first shot
in the latest battle for readers in one of the country's wealthiest
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
