<SLUG> BC-MENS-HEALTH-EDITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN'S HEALTH MAGAZINE, TRYING TO WIN YOUTH BACK, NAMES EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men's Health magazine, the onetime upstart that rocketed to the
top of the men's magazine world during the 1990s before stalling,
is turning to a 30-year-old editor to help it win younger readers
from surging competitors like Maxim.
</P>
<P>
   David Zinczenko, who has spent the last two years in Europe
tending to the growth of some of the magazine's 21 foreign
offshoots, was named editor in chief of the U.S. edition Thursday
by Steven Murphy, president and chief operating officer of Rodale,
Inc., which owns Men's Health.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Men's Health has a circulation of 1.6
million, but the number of advertising pages has declined in the
last year, according to Cory Shield, a spokesman for Rodale, which
is based in Emmaus, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Zinczenko is the second top-level management
change at Men's Health since Murphy joined Rodale from Walt Disney
Co.'s Disney Publishing Worldwide, where he was managing director,
three months ago. A week ago, Paul J. Turcotte was appointed vice
president and publisher of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge for Men's Health, Murphy said Thursday was
``the temporary advertising love affair with the lad magazines'' _
a British slang term for magazines like Loaded, Maxim and FHM,
newer entries in a field that Men's Health helped create when it
was started in newsletter form in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what changes he would make in Men's Health, Zinczenko said
Thursday: ``The magazine's pretty buff already. There's no reason
to go into wholesale changes. I do want to bring in fresh voices,
fresh points of view.'' Murphy, in a separate interview, said,
``David's Rolodex of writers includes a new generation _ folks who,
10 years from now, will be names.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's focus, Murphy added, would continue to be on
health, fitness, sex and relationships, with an added emphasis on
personal finance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
