<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE POLICE OFFICERS BEING PUNISHED, BUT NOT MORE SEVERELY
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since federal authorities began reviewing the police
disciplinary process three years ago, the Police Department has
punished many more officers for a wide range of misconduct,
according to police statistics.
</P>
<P>
   From 1997 through 1999, the number of officers who received
serious formal punishments _ firings, suspensions without pay and
forfeited vacation days for infractions ranging from rule
violations to excessive force _ has increased by 28 percent, to 450
from 352, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   But while the statistics and a separate analysis by Mark Green,
the public advocate, show that the overall number of officers being
disciplined by the department has increased, the severity of
punishments has not, and in fact has dipped in some instances.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the number of officers fired dropped to 88 in 1999
from 116 in 1997, and the average number of days forfeited in cases
in which disciplinary charges were brought declined to 24.8 last
year from 30.1 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the number of punished officers comes as the
department is facing the prospect of a federal monitor or a lawsuit
to install one by federal prosecutors. A three-year inquiry by the
office of the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, prompted by the 1997
station house torture of Abner Louima, found that the department
was so lenient with officers in excessive force cases that it had
bred a climate that failed to deter brutal acts.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials contend that the significant jump in the number
of officers subjected to formal discipline is a result of their
increased vigilance and efforts, over four years, to improve the
disciplinary process. Critics of the department say the increase is
a direct response to the federal investigation, and is an attempt
to head off the appointment of a federal monitor.
</P>
<P>
   But Police officials cite a 25 percent drop last year in the
number of legal claims filed against the city that alleged police
brutality and a drop in the number of complaints filed against
officers with the Civilian Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kelleher, the department's first deputy commissioner,
disagreed with suggestions that the increased discipline was a
response to greater outside scrutiny of the department. ``You're
not going to reduce civilian complaints overnight,'' he said.
``This is the real world. You can't say, `OK, everybody be good.'
It took a lot of hard work, a lot of getting the message out. And
again, I think the proof is in the pudding.''
</P>
<P>
   The report by Green concluded that despite the recent increase
in the number of officers disciplined, the department's
disciplinary process was plagued by ``systemic failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a review of cases of police misconduct substantiated
against 664 officers, Green said he found that 75 percent of the
officers disciplined received insignificant penalties that he
characterized as a ``slap on the wrist.'' Those punishments, he
said, consisted of discipline like a reprimand from a superior, a
note in an officer's file or the loss of a few vacation days.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found is a Police Department that fights crime well,
but fights police misconduct far less well,'' said Green, who is
expected to run for mayor in 2001, at a news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani dismissed Green's report, calling it
partisan and saying that it glossed over what the mayor
characterized as the department's significant achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Kelleher said that the efforts of Commissioner
Howard Safir had raised the discipline rate and had helped send a
message to officers that misconduct would not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the discipline is strong, I think its fair, I think
it's consistent,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
