<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE PLAYERS' ASPIRATIONS GO BEYOND TOKEN APPEARANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Masafumi Kawaguchi isn't trying to be an
ingrate.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that Kawaguchi _ one of two Japanese football players
to join the Cowboys yesterday as part of the pageantry of the
American Bowl exhibition game in Tokyo on Aug. 5 _ has bigger
dreams than being an honorary member of an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   Kawaguchi, a 5-foot-11, 180-pound linebacker, played high school
football in San Clemente, Calif., before starring at college at
Ritsumeikan University in Japan. After playing the past four years
in NFL Europe with the Amsterdam Admirals, Kawaguchi is thirsting
for more.
</P>
<P>
   So while the NFL and the Cowboys are using the American Bowl
against the Atlanta Falcons as a public relations tool to market
the game and the league abroad, Kawaguchi, and receiver Masato Itai
hope to use their practice time with the Cowboys and the game to
prove they can play in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always dreamed of playing over here,'' said Kawaguchi,
who was introduced to the game as a child when his family lived in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my goal. I want to play in this league, not as a guest
like this. I'm here trying to make the team. I want to show what I
can do on special teams and as a linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   Kawaguchi already has a role model of sorts in Cowboys
linebacker Dat Nguyen, the first Vietnamese-American to play in the
NFL. However, Kawaguchi didn't realize how big Nguyen (5-11, 231)
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him,'' Kawaguchi said. ``I didn't know he was that big.
They said he was small. But he is not small.''
</P>
<P>
   Itai, who learned the game in the college and corporate leagues
in Japan, is also a veteran of NFL Europe and the Admirals. He
became the first Japanese player to catch a touchdown pass in NFL
Europe when he caught a 12-yard scoring toss in Week 9 of the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   Itai said the technique and teaching in Japan is the same as the
NFL, but the size and speed of NFL players are a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo and owner Jerry Jones welcomed both to
the team yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said they will get a chance to show what they can do,
though he pointed out that they have an uphill battle of achieving
their long-term dreams because they aren't on any team's
training-camp roster.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said it's unlikely the two players will play Sunday when
the Cowboys open the preseason against the Pittsburgh Steelers at
Texas Stadium. However, he said the coaching staff will diagram
plays and packages to best utilize Kawaguchi and Itai in the
American Bowl. \Nsubheds:Briefly Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith
(sprained toe) didn't practice for the second consecutive day.
However, the Cowboys have yet to rule him out of Sunday's preseason
game against Steelers. Tight end David LaFleur (strained groin) is
questionable for the Steelers game. Campo said the Cowboys, who are
1-9 the past two years in the preseason, will be looking to put on
a good show Sunday. He said the focus, though, will be on
evaluating players. Guard Tony Hutson, who has been limited in
practice after undergoing surgery in the off-season to repair a
torn anterior cruciate ligament, will not play against the
Steelers, offensive line coach Hudson Houck said. Former Haltom
High School offensive lineman Kelvin Garmon will start at left
guard in place of the injured Larry Allen (fractured hand), Houck
said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
