<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK FUND-RAISING TRICKERY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   In spreading money around to New York state's 62 Republican
county committees this month, Rep. Rick Lazio has resorted to a
legal but unsavory campaign scheme long favored by the state's
political leaders. This ersatz philanthropy by a Senate candidate
is simply another fund-raising gimmick. It is a way candidates for
federal office can sidestep federal contribution limits in New
York. And Lazio's use of that dodge is the latest signal that the
state Legislature still needs to fix a campaign financing system
that is nothing short of a national embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   This particular ploy works when a candidate sets up a state
political action committee ostensibly to nurture grass-roots
campaigns and encourage local candidates. Under this state-approved
guise, a donor can write a much larger check than for a federal
campaign. An individual can contribute only $2,000 directly to
Lazio's Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton, for
example. But state law allows that same individual to contribute an
additional $76,500 a year to Lazio's state PAC.
</P>
<P>
   The PAC money cannot be used directly for a candidate's
campaign, but a spokesman for Lazio said that the funds could be
used to set up local phone banks and get out voters for all the
party's candidates, including Lazio. Although the Lazio campaign
protests that this PAC is separate, Clifford Levy of The Times
reported this week that some donors contributed the maximum to
Lazio's Senate campaign at the same time they contributed thousands
more to his state PAC.
</P>
<P>
   The doling out of money to local parties is one of the quickest
ways for a politician to gain statewide strength and recognition,
either as a candidate or as a political rainmaker. Most recently in
New Jersey, for example, Jon Corzine, the multimillionaire
Democratic Senate candidate, spent tens of thousands of dollars of
his own money to enrich local Democratic committees around the
state. Local workers helped him thrash Jim Florio, the former
governor, in the party primary last month.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Lazio's state PAC is not the only fund-raising
contrivance that deprives New York voters of a fair contest this
political season. Both the Lazio and Clinton campaigns are
benefiting from unregulated contributions, or ``soft money,'' spent
for them by national party committees. But Lazio's active PAC also
offers the latest evidence that New York's Legislature prefers
preserving tainted fund-raising habits for another election year.
Despite a few weak promises, legislators concluded their business
in Albany this summer without making a single improvement in the
worst state campaign finance system in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
