<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-TRIBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS QUESTION VALIDITY OF U.S. TRIBAL RECOGNITION 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Concerned that the federal government may soon
recognize two more Indian tribes in Connecticut, two state
officials said Thursday that they planned to convene dozens of
state and city officials in September to discuss the legitimacy of
the tribes' land claims and the validity of the recognition
process.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement, made in a news conference by state
Attorney General Richard Blumenthal and the state Senate's majority
leader, George C. Jepsen, is the latest in a weeks-long series of
moves by elected officials troubled by recent indications from the
federal Bureau of Indian Affairs that it is poised to confer
recognition on the two tribes within a matter of months.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the prospect of that recognition a ``time bomb,'' Jepsen
said, ``There's a need in this state to bring elected and community
officials together so that we can all get up to speed together on
this enormously complex process and all the facts that go along
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials' concern stems from the assumption that once
recognized, the two Indian tribes under consideration _ the Eastern
Pequots and the Paucatuck Eastern Pequots _ will do what the
Mohegan and Mashantucket Pequot tribes have already done: use their
autonomy to build monumental casinos in hopes of making millions of
dollars a year in gambling revenue. Many residents fear losing
property to land claims, as well as traffic congestion and the
social costs of legalized gambling.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, Kevin Gover, the top official in the Bureau of
Indian Affairs, a unit of the Interior Department, issued a
preliminary finding that the two tribes deserved official
recognition. The finding is the penultimate step in a years-long
federal process that Blumenthal and members of Connecticut's
Congressional delegation have repeatedly criticized as favoring the
tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Those criticisms center on their belief that Gover, the Interior
Department's assistant secretary in charge of approving recognition
claims submitted to the BIA, is predisposed to grant recognition to
tribes even if they have not completed the seven-step approval
process.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's news conference, Blumenthal sent a letter to
John Leshy, the Interior Department's solicitor, asking him to
recuse Gover, who is a Pawnee from Oklahoma, from the recognition
process for the two Connecticut tribes. The letter included a
quotation attributed to Gover in The Day, a New London newspaper,
in May. ``I would rather recognize someone who should not be
recognized than fail someone who should,'' Gover was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, Blumenthal wrote a letter to Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt, urging him to freeze all tribal
recognition requests until the department developed a way to ensure
they would be evaluated fairly and honestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bureau of Indian Affairs is changing its criteria,
altering the rules of the game in the middle of the tribal
recognition process,'' Blumenthal said Thursday. ``It is unfair,
it's susceptible excessively to the interests of politics and
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedra Darling, a spokeswoman for the BIA, said the bureau's
process was fair and rigorous. ``We're following a code,'' she
said. ``It's a lot of roll-up-your-sleeves research and analytical
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other tribes in Connecticut, the Golden Hill Paugussetts and
the Schaghticoke Tribal Nation, which have been recognized by the
state for more than a century, have pending petitions for federal
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal and Jepsen said they would hold a summit, which they
said would include state and local officials and business and
tribal leaders, on Sept. 14 in a location to be named near
Bridgeport. They said they would invite Indian leaders as well as
officials from the BIA, though when contacted Thursday, only the
Schaghticoke chief, Richard Velky, said he planned to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their process is broken down,'' he said of the federal bureau.
``You've got too many groups out there calling themselves a nation
or a tribe.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael D. O'Connell, a lawyer for the Golden Hill Paugussetts,
whose 100 members live on two reservations, in Bridgeport and near
Colchester, Conn., said he was wary of attending the meeting. ``My
fear is that it's just intended to be another opportunity to bash
the various Indian tribes,'' he said. ``We'll wait to see if we're
invited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
