<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PLAN TRIBUTE TO TOM LANDRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones unveiled
yesterday the initial plans for a seasonlong tribute to legendary
coach Tom Landry, who died in February.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the tribute, a patch bearing a tiny replica of
Landry's trademark Fedora will be emblazoned above and to the left
of the numbers on the Cowboys' jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hat says it all,'' Jones said. ``It's the same hat we have
in the ring of honor. I think that it will be recognized throughout
the world of sports immediately as the recognition of Coach
Landry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who fired Landry when he bought the team in 1989, said
the Cowboys have many other things in store to recognize ``what
coach Landry was and is about to this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones only revealed one other element yesterday: Cowboys game
tickets will feature a different photo of Landry each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said he is the most significant person and personality
in the history of the franchise,'' Jones said. ``What we are going
to do on our tickets is in keeping to what we are doing on the
jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry, who died at age 75 after a battle with leukemia, was the
head coach of the Cowboys for the franchise's first 29 years. Under
Landry, the Cowboys were 270-178-6, including two Super Bowl titles
and five conference crowns.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys head coach Dave Campo, who came to the Cowboys with
Landry's successor Jimmy Johnson in 1989, said the tribute is
``applicable and appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, when you talk about the Dallas Cowboys, you are
obviously talking about Tom Landry,'' Campo said. ``The tradition
is there. What he did for football is without question one of the
top stories in sports. It's an honor for our guys and me especially
to have that distinction on the uniform.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
