<SLUG> BC-NY-BROKERAGE-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.H. BLAIR BROKERAGE AND EXECUTIVES INDICTED IN FRAUD CASE
</HEADLINE>
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ D.H. Blair &AMP; Co., a defunct Manhattan brokerage firm,
and 15 of its officers and employees were indicted Thursday on
securities fraud charges by a grand jury in Manhattan. The firm's
executives, prosecutors said, reaped illegal profit by manipulating
stock prices, engaged in high-pressure sales tactics to generate
excessive commissions and stole investor data from other firms to
increase their customer base.
</P>
<P>
   The 173-count indictment, announced by District Attorney Robert
M. Morgenthau, charged that from 1989 to 1998 executives and
stockbrokers at D.H. Blair ran the firm as a criminal enterprise.
Morgenthau said that Kenton Wood, Blair's chairman, supervised the
fraud, as did Alan Stahler and Kalman Renov, the vice chairmen.
D.H. Blair ceased operation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began in the fall of 1997 and grew out of
Morgenthau's prosecution of A.R. Baron, a fraudulent brokerage firm
that bilked investors out of $75 million. When Baron closed in
1996, most of its brokers moved to D.H. Blair.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50,000 customers invested with Blair in the period
covered by the indictment, prosecutors said. One victim, a
56-year-old disabled man from Colorado, lost $150,000 from a
disability settlement that he had allocated for medical bills and
living expenses. A 70-year-old Florida man lost $250,000 from his
retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``D.H. Blair's was a sophisticated fraud,'' said Daniel J.
Castleman, chief of the investigation division in the district
attorney's office. ``They were dealing with real companies, but
manipulating prices of stock by illegal means in order for favored
customers to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Castleman said Blair officials falsified business records,
suppressed clients' complaints and misled securities regulators to
evade detection. The firm's chief stock trader and 11 of its
registered representatives were also named in the indictment. Three
former brokers have admitted securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Stahler and Wood called the charges baseless and
said their clients would contest them vigorously. Renov's lawyer
did not return a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors could not specify how much was stolen from
investors. They said Blair manipulated shares of 10 companies taken
public by an associated firm, D.H. Blair Investment Banking. The
investment bank was not named in the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the National Association of Securities
Dealers took action against D.H. Blair, which resulted in a $2.4
million restitution fund.
</P>
<P>
   D.H. Blair Investment Banking, which was spun off from the
brokerage firm in 1992, is now run by J. Morton Davis, who presided
over D.H. Blair &AMP; Co. for more than 20 years. Eight years ago, he
turned the brokerage operation over to family members. Stahler and
Renov, the vice chairmen indicted yesterday, are sons-in-law of
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Davis wrote a book entitled ``From Hard Knocks to
Hot Stocks: How I Made A Fortune Through Smart Investing and How
You Can, Too.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the investigation of D.H. Blair &AMP; Co. is
continuing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
