<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS' EARLY HAUL FILLS OFFENSIVE-LINE NEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MILLER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Addressing areas of need in recruiting can be as vital as the
number of blue-chip recruits a school signs.
</P>
<P>
   More than six months before national signing day, Texas coach
Mack Brown has almost filled the Longhorns' top priority.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns are looking to sign a strong offensive-line class
on Feb. 7, national signing day, and have picked up commitments
from six top recruits at the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have identified a need and they have wrapped it up pretty
well,'' said Jeremy Crabtree, director of college recruiting for
Rivals.com. ``All those guys are in the top 100 at their position.
It allows them, now that they have their big need addressed, to go
after need No. 2 \Rdefensive tackles\S and need No. 3
\Rlinebackers\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Carter High School offensive lineman Jonathan Scott
(6-foot-7, 282 pounds) was the first player to commit to Texas and
is the most highly regarded. Rivals100.com ranks Scott as the
third-best offensive lineman in the country. Max Emfinger's
National Blue Chips Online evaluated Scott as the top weakside
offensive tackle in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Scott committed to Texas after attending the Longhorns' summer
camp in early June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like I was just in awe,'' Scott said. ``Everything
there was just top notch and first class. The team was really
committed to winning a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas stole one of its offensive-line commitments from its
biggest rival. Galena Park's Mike Garcia committed to Texas A&AMP;M
during his junior year, but switched his commitment to Texas in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Blinn College offensive lineman Alfio Randall has committed to
Texas for the second time. Two years ago at Houston Yates, he was
considered one of the top offensive linemen in the nation and
committed to Texas, but had to go to junior college after not
qualifying academically.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Robinson of Jersey Village, Roman Reeves of Livingston and
Will Allen of Cypress Falls round out the Longhorns' early haul of
offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Scott is glad Texas is signing a large number of offensive
lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the competition,'' Scott said. ``The more competition,
the better I can get as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns have also gathered commitments from two players
with local ties to help them out at safety in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity High School quarterback Braden Johnson had a strong
showing at summer camps this year and was offered a scholarship to
Texas in June and committed to the Longhorns on June 19.
</P>
<P>
   Former Stephenville quarterback Kendal Briles, who transferred
to Wolfforth Frenship after his father, former Stephenville coach
Art Briles, took an assistant coaching position at Texas Tech, did
not follow his father to the Red Raiders. Instead, he chose to
switch positions to safety and committed to the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I've talked to kept asking, `When are going to
commit to Tech?' '' Kendal Briles said. ``I've liked UT since I was
young, and dreamed of getting a scholarship and going there. I was
open to whatever position I'd play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies have also looked to secure their future at the safety
position, where they return only two players with playing
experience for the upcoming season. Two of Texas A&AMP;M's three early
commitments have come from safeties: Dallas Kimball's Jarvis Mays
and Friendswood's Jaxon Appel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done a good job,'' Crabtree said of A&AMP;M. ``Any time
you get a kid from Kimball, you know you are getting a very
athletic player that can fly all over the field.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU has picked up two early commitments, from Snyder wide
receiver Matthew Grimmett (37 receptions, 858 yards) and Midland
Lee kicker Michael Wynn.
