r s BC-BBO-SELIG-TEX     07-28 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SELIG-TEX </SLUG>

(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By SIMON GONZALEZ c.2000
Fort Worth Star-Telegram
Baseball commissioner Bud Selig has had two weeks to digest the
findings of the Blue Ribbon Panel on Baseball Economics
commissioned by Major League Baseball. The panel recommended
increased revenue sharing and the possible relocation of struggling
franchises. The commissioner recently took a few minutes in a
question-and-answer session with Star-Telegram staff writer Simon
Gonzalez to share his thoughts on the panel's conclusions, and on
the state of the game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What do you think of the report from the blue-ribbon
committee?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Obviously, it shows we have a problem. I think the report
is a very powerful document that has more economic backup
information than we've ever released before.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The report graphically illustrated the economic disparity
between clubs. The Yankees generated $177.9 million in revenue last
season, while the Expos generated $48.8 million. Is that disparity
the biggest problem facing the game?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``There's no question. There's no doubt that that's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you sell that to owners who are going to be asked to
give up even more of their money in revenue sharing?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``That's something that, if I move this process along, they
gave me the authority last year to do that. There's no question
there's a problem. If the renaissance, which is remarkable right
now, if we want this to continue, we have to solve this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're referring to the so-called ``best interests of the
game'' powers. Can you use that to force increased revenue sharing?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I don't want to get into the specifics, but, yes, there are
some things I can do. I hope I'll be able to do it in a little
different style, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Without using the word ``force,'' perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Right.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: One criticism of the commissioner is that as the former owner
of a small-market franchise, you are too focused on the plight of
the small-market clubs at the expense of the large-market clubs. Is
that valid?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I don't hear that much any more. I think the disparity
problem has been so detailed out _ and I think this report helps _
that my experience as an owner has really turned out to be a very
helpful experience. I have 30 clubs to worry about, and I don't
have any previous disposition to help one over the other. But it's
the small and medium-market clubs, including the one there in
Texas, that are being affected by the disparity. One needs to be
fair, but we have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: There is some skepticism about the claims in the report that
all but three teams are losing money. Locally, people look at the
Rangers playing in a revenue-generating ballpark before 35,000
people every night and wonder how they can be losing money. Are the
numbers accurate?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I know that there are people who say they have different
books and who's kidding who, and that is so galling. Independent
audits are conducted on all clubs. Every club has their own
auditors, just like every major company in America. They're
rechecked by Ernst &AMP; Young on behalf of Major League Baseball.
Then, PricewaterhouseCoopers comes in, and they conduct a separate
audit for revenue-sharing purposes. Also, the Basic Agreement
provides the Players Association access to all club data and the
right to conduct its own independent audit if they have any
problems. Rob \RManfred, MLB's executive vice president for Labor
Relations and Human Resources\S tells me they've never asked for
any further audit. These are being audited three times by three
different firms. So, this business of, well, anybody can do
anything they want, that's just nonsense. That's just sheer
nonsense. I've run a team. I know my own team's figures, I know
everybody else's. I've spent hours going over it. It's just
malarkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: If only three clubs are making money, how can teams afford to
share more revenue?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``It's a question of moving revenues around, which I think
helps everybody, including the big-market clubs, frankly. There are
only three clubs making money, there isn't any doubt about that.
But I do think that revenue sharing and a more sensible economic
system will help all the clubs. We have a system now that's
producing very few profitable clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Attempts by the owners to change the system in the past have
caused labor strife. Do you have any indication that there will be
major problems with the union when it comes time to negotiate the
next collective bargaining agreement?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I can't tell you that. Their response has been quite muted
and controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Based on history, is it possible to get a new collective
bargaining agreement without some kind of work stoppage?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I hope so. I think that's one of the challenges that lies
ahead. I think we've had eight of them, and we just have to find a
different way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the fact that the game suffered so much because of the
strike in '94 likely to make both the owners and the union leery of
more labor strife this time?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Only time will tell, but I certainly think all of us are
very sensitive. Very sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The report also recommended that struggling franchises be
allowed to change cities. Do you anticipate that happening?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I don't know right now. It's something I'm going to take a
look at in the coming months.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Realignment was postponed until 2002, at the earliest. Is
geographic realignment a goal at some point?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``We need to have some realignment at some point, but I'm so
delighted we got to an unbalanced schedule. That was my major
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you surprised that, given the opportunity the Rangers
seemed to have to get into a division with teams from the same time
zone, they opted to stay in the West?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I understand why they made that decision. They had a
different view than \Rformer part-owner\S George W. Bush did, but I
wasn't surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The report details the economic disparities and says that 27
franchises are losing money, while at the same time attendance is
up and new stadiums are being built. On balance, as you look to the
future of baseball, are you optimistic or pessimistic?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I'm very optimistic. I think this renaissance is
unbelievable. We're going to set an all-time attendance record this
year, and I think the game has never been more popular. I don't
think there's any doubt about that. But I also know for us to take
advantage of what we have, that we've got to solve the disparity
problem. How we solve that remains to be seen; I know I have to be
sensitive to all the agendas here. But the fact of the matter is we
have to solve this problem. There's no ifs, ands or buts about
it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
