LOSS DRIVES SHARES OF ACCELERATED DOWN 49% &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   MOORPARK, Calif. _ Shares of Accelerated Networks lost half
their value Thursday, one day after the Moorpark-based
telecommunications equipment maker reported a loss greater than
analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   Accelerated lost $20.69 a share, or 49 percent, on volume of
7million shares, its heaviest trading since the Ventura County
company went public in June. It closed at $21.31 a share in a day
that saw losses across most of the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   Accelerated's chief financial officer, Fred Boyer, would not
comment on the volatility of the market but concentrated on the
bright side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to remain very positive in our outlook of our
business,'' he said. ``We're here to build shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   The company reported losses of $8.3 million, or 19 cents a
share, in the second quarter. A First Call/Thomson Financial
consensus of analysts had predicted a loss of 17 cents a share. The
company also reported sales of $8.8 million compared with $1.2
million in the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Three brokerage firms began tracking Accelerated last week,
rating its stock a ``buy'' or ``strong buy.'' Analysts from the
three firms did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Accelerated operates a 23,000-square-foot facility in Moorpark
and a 15,000-square-foot facility in Simi Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
