<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT     07-28 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES $288 BILLION MILITARY BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate joined the House on Thursday in
approving a military spending bill of $287.8 billion for next year,
more than $5.1 billion more than requested by the Pentagon or the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which was adopted by a vote of 91 to 9, is an
increase of more than $21.7 billion over the current fiscal year.
That figure alone is greater than the entire foreign aid budget.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which will next go to the president, includes a 3.7
percent increase in military pay. The additional $5.1 billion over
the nearly $16 billion increase requested by the administration
would go mainly for military research contracts that are in states
and Congressional districts of influential lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In the brief debate over the bill, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
criticized his colleagues. McCain noted that nearly $2 billion
worth of items that had not been requested by the administration
and were not part of the bills originally passed by the House and
Senate had been added by House-Senate conferees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the surplus,'' McCain said in an interview in response to
a question of how so many spending items ended up in the bill.
``This kind of spending just grows and grows. And these are
Republican fiscal conservatives. It's disgraceful and it's obscene
and I am embarrassed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the passage of the bill Congress has completed its work on
about half the $600 billion in discretionary spending that it says
it wants to spend in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But after a week of frenetic activity on a number of spending
bills, including those financing the Treasury, Labor, Health and
Human Services, departments and the White House, Congress had
little to show for its work as it moved toward its month-long
August recess. At the beginning of the week, Republicans were
hopeful that the House would complete work on all 13 spending
bills, and perhaps even approve at least one measure that had
emerged from a House-Senate conference. But problems soon cropped
up. Senate Democrats stalled consideration of a spending measures
covering operations for the Department of the Treasury, the White
House and other federal agencies as a protest over what they
considered the body's slow pace in confirming President Clinton's
judicial appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the bill became bogged down the White House and
Congressional Republicans entered into tentative negotiations early
in the week over three spending measures. But the talks never
progressed beyond the staff level.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, Senate Democrats halted their delaying
tactics. But time had run out for any of the spending bills _ other
than military _ to be considered before the recess. ``It's
disappointing,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla. and the Senate
whip. ``And I don't think the Democrats' strategy is a defensible
one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want us to pass these bills because they want to
force us into some big summit with an omnibus bill so they can get
more spending,'' said Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the House Majority
Whip. ``Well, we ain't going there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate minority leader, Tom Daschle, D-S.D., did not dispute
the notion that his party slowed down spending bills. But Daschle
replied that Democrats did so in response to the Republican's
reneging on a promise to hold hearings on a raft of judicial
appointments, including at least one nominee for appellate court
judge who had been waiting for 42 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0017 </DOCNO>
