<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WENDY'S-SLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANTS PLEAD NOT GUILTY IN KILLINGS OF WENDY'S WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
  By EUN LEE KOH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The two men accused of killing five workers in a
massacre at a Wendy's restaurant in Queens on May 24 pleaded not
guilty Thursday to murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   The men, John B. Taylor, 36, and Craig Godineaux, 30, were
arraigned in the Queens County Courthouse on 50 counts, including
murder, attempted murder and robbery, in the slayings at the
Flushing restaurant, where seven employees were shot one by one in
the head.
</P>
<P>
   Five were killed: Ramon Nazario, Anita C. Smith, Jean Dumel
Auguste and Jeremy Mele and Ali Ibadat. Two other workers _
Jaquione Johnson and Patrick Castro _ survived the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   With the arraignments, the Queens district attorney, Richard A.
Brown, has 120 days to decide whether to seek the death penalty in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The lead prosecutor, Gregory L. Lasak, said in court Thursday
that the defendants made several incriminating statements to
detectives after their arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ```OK, I tell you the truth _ I shot five of them,''' Lasak
quoted Godineaux as saying to detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Godineaux denied killing Smith, the lone female victim, blaming
Taylor, Lasak said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers declined to comment on the statements read in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of the victims wept as they left the courtroom,
and some expressed a hope that the district attorney would seek the
death penalty for the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting back tears, Benjamin Nazario, the brother of Ramon
Nazario, said, ``I want them dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't give none of those people in Wendy's any kind of
mercy,'' Nazario said. ``They're lucky they are going through the
trial system.''
</P>
<P>
   Godineaux's lawyer, Colleen Brady, said she hoped that the
publicity surrounding the case would not influence Brown's decision
on whether to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The two defendants are being held without bail and are scheduled
to return to court on Nov. 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
