<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGER-AD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREEN ACTORS GUILD UPSET BY TIGER'S CAR COMMERCIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tiger Woods may be the world's most dominant and
admired golfer, but to the Screen Actors Guild he's just another
commercial actor who should _ repeat (italics) should (end italics)
_ be on strike.
</P>
<P>
   Only days after Woods' triumphant win at the British Open, the
actors union notified him Thursday that he will be called before
its trial board to explain why he filmed a Buick commercial in
Canada this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Woods violated rule No. 1 of the current commercials
strike by accepting nonunion work,'' said SAG President William
Daniels. ``Accordingly, Screen Actors Guild plans to notify him of
the date and time of his trial board, whereupon he will be asked to
explain his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The date and time of the inquisition were not announced.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising industry strike negotiator and spokesman Ira Shepard
called the SAG announcement an ``empty threat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the union gets anywhere by threatening an
American hero,'' Shepard said. ``As the strike continues, more and
more major celebrities of all kinds will adhere to their
contractual obligations to the major advertising agencies and cross
the union picket line.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, though, teen star Britney Spears and members of boy
band 'N Sync endorsed the strike, with Spears cancelling a
lucrative Clairol commercial and pledging, along with 'N Sync
members, to donate proceeds from upcoming concerts to the SAG
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The strike is now in its 14th week with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting in New York last week intended to restart negotiations
quickly fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Striking commercial actors want to be paid for each airing of a
commercial on cable television, a residual system now used for
network ads. They also want union jurisdiction over Internet ads.
</P>
<P>
   The ad industry opposes residuals for cable and Internet ads and
wants to eliminate the pay-per-play network residual system with
one based on a flat fee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5321 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRO     07-28 1656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE APPROVES SALE OF S.F. CHRONICLE TO HEARST CORP.
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By WILLIAM CARLSEN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge Thursday approved the Hearst
Corp.'s purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle, finding that the
sale did not violate antitrust law, and reluctantly cleared the way
for the publishers of the thrice-weekly Independent to acquire the
Examiner.
<P>
   Under the terms of the two deals, Hearst is expected to quickly
complete its purchase of The Chronicle, then operate the Examiner
during a four-month transition period before giving the paper _
along with a $66 million three-year subsidy _ to the Fang family,
which publishes the Independent.
</P>
<P>
   But in scorching comments Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Vaughn
Walker called the Fang deal ``malodorous'' and noted that the
transaction could violate antitrust laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge was also clearly offended by what he called the
politics of the transaction. He blamed ``cronyism'' for delaying
The Chronicle sale for seven months, then agreeing to back off only
after Hearst agreed to give the Examiner to the Fangs, who are
ardent political supporters of Mayor Willie Brown and the city's
entrenched Democratic political machine.
</P>
<P>
   Walker specifically noted that Brown and Sen. Dianne Feinstein
intervened in the process in a way that strongly influenced the
Hearst Corp. to cut a deal with the Fangs _ apparently in exchange
for dropping their pressure on the Justice Department to
investigate The Chronicle sale.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's most scathing comments were reserved, however, for
the Department of Justice. He said he was ``astonished and
disappointed that the DOJ would allow itself to be put in a
position where the inference can be so easily drawn that its action
or inaction in the case was political favoritism masquerading as
law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, the San Francisco attorney who represented the
Hearst Corp., said he was extremely pleased with the judge's
ruling. ``It strongly vindicated the position that Hearst has taken
throughout the proceedings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed that Hearst has a binding contract to transfer the
Examiner to the Fang family.
</P>
<P>
   But another attorney close to the case, who asked not to be
identified, noted that Walker all but invited a competitor such as
the San Francisco Bay Guardian or SF Weekly to challenge the Fang
deal as a violation of antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Any such challenge would go to Walker and the Fang deal could be
ruled illegal, which would absolve Hearst of its contractual
obligation to the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Lindstrom, one of the lawyers who represented the Chronicle
Publishing Co., said: ``Obviously, we're gratified that the judge
has vindicated the Chronicle's position. ... Not only did the judge
find that the transaction does not violate antitrust laws, he found
... that it is pro-competitive and good for the Bay Area.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. announced it was buying The Chronicle last
August 6 at staff meetings in the Examiner and Chronicle newsrooms.
Hearst's Chief Executive Officer Frank Bennack Jr. calmed the fears
of both newspaper staffs by telling them that they would be
guaranteed jobs in the new Hearst-owned Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it was also putting the Examiner up for sale,
including the paper's masthead, archives, subscribers' and
advertisers' lists, but no hard assets such as printing presses,
offices or delivery trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Examiner is an afternoon paper with a declining
circulation _ a lethal formula that has sent dozens of papers to
their graves _ few expected anyone to take Hearst up on the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst said it would dissolve the 34-year-old joint operating
agreement that had allowed the two papers to combine business
operations and split the profits evenly, but kept the two newsrooms
editorially separate.
</P>
<P>
   Based on U.S. Justice Department approval in similar earlier
newspaper takeovers, Hearst officials expected The Chronicle
purchase to go quickly. But the plan ran into obstacles almost
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next nine months, the deal was sidetracked by a
remarkable convergence of hidden agendas, backroom maneuverings and
political alliances intended to serve the city's top Democratic
political figures.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, the proposed deal claimed the job of the
Examiner's publisher, embarrassed top officers of both newspapers,
raised questions about journalistic ethics and lifted the lid on
the long-secret finances that had allowed The Chronicle and
Examiner to dominate Bay Area media for over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of the August announcement, Mayor Willie Brown
called U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno, who promised to look into
any antitrust implications of the sales.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ted Fang contacted Warren Hellman, a prominent San
Francisco financier and civic leader, for advice about buying the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the Independent began a grassroots ``Stop the
Monopoly'' campaign blasting The Chronicle sale, which resulted in
a flurry of public hearings and resolutions by city leaders
questioning the proposed transaction.
</P>
<P>
   By November, Justice Department lawyers had opened an formal
inquiry into the deal and officials from the Examiner and Chronicle
turned over 174 boxes of documents to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst officers said that they had received no solid offers for
the Examiner and were preparing to close the paper. But in
December, the government lawyers told Hearst officials that the
Examiner sale had been inadequate. If they proceeded to shut down
the paper and complete the Chronicle purchase, Hearst faced a
possible department antitrust suit.
</P>
<P>
   In his second inaugural address, Brown announced in January that
saving the Examiner was a priority and that he hoped to put
together a group of investors to buy it. He held several meetings
with Hellman and Fang.
</P>
<P>
   Later that month, the political pressure mounted. Brown led a
delegation to Examiner publisher Tim White's office to insist that
the Hearst Corp. ``sweeten'' the terms of the Examiner sale. The
delegation included Rep. Nancy Pelosi and City Attorney Louise
Renne.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, on January 21, Feinstein, a member of the Senate's
powerful judiciary committee, invited White to a lunch with
Florence Fang, the matriarch of the Fang family.
</P>
<P>
   Fang told White that her family wanted the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, as it had indicated a month earlier to the
Justice Department, Hearst reoffered the Examiner for sale, this
time with delivery trucks, a printing plant, news racks, a computer
system and office building _ everything needed to publish the paper
without missing an edition.
</P>
<P>
   But there were still no takers and the Justice Department
pressed Hearst hard to offer its share of the lucrative joint
operating agreement _ due to expire in 2005 _ or an equivalent in
order to keep the Examiner from folding.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations continued, real estate investor and former
mayoral candidate Clint Reilly jumped into the fray. On January 11,
he filed suit to block the Chronicle sale, contending that the deal
violated federal antitrust laws and would give Hearst a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   In February, in settlement talks with Hearst, Reilly also made a
bid for the Examiner. But on March 17, Hearst announced that it had
cut a deal with Ted Fang, giving the Examiner to the Fang family
with a three-year subsidy of $66 million.
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, the Justice Department cleared the transaction. But
Reilly, who said a subsidy as large as $250 million would be needed
to save the Examiner, had refused to drop his suit.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, Walker granted Reilly's request for a temporary
injunction blocking the Chronicle sale and the transfer of the
Examiner to the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   The trial that ensued proved to be a public spectacle for two
publishing companies that had always _ as privately held
enterprises _ operated behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, the opening day, Examiner Publisher Tim White
testified that he had offered to ``horse trade'' favorable
treatment for Mayor Brown in the paper's editorial pages in
exchange for Brown's support for the Chronicle deal.
</P>
<P>
   The remark set off protests on the staffs of the Examiner and
Chronicle. Embarrassed Hearst officials suspended White and started
an internal investigation into whether any journalistic ethics had
been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   The second day, Chronicle Publishing's top executive John Sias,
was caught in misstatement during cross-examination by Reilly
attorney Joseph M. Alioto, and he quipped that he had been exposed
as a ``perjurer.''
</P>
<P>
   Reams of financial data about the papers' revenue, expenses and
profits emerged during the trial, some of it showing that Hearst
was making considerably more profit than The Chronicle from their
joint operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto argued that the sale of the Examiner to the Fangs was a
``sham,'' designed to fail and leave Hearst with a newspaper
monopoly in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But Hearst attorneys defended the unusual subsidy to the Fangs
as a ``business'' decision they did not like but believed was
necessary to avoid a lengthy court battle with the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Walker appeared bothered by the subsidy and the appearance that
politics may have influenced the final outcome. In two unusual
written exchanges with the Justice Department, he pressed for
explanations of why the department held up the sale for seven
months then dropped its investigation after Hearst cut its deal
with the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   Did the department conclude that the Hearst purchase of The
Chronicle really violated antitrust law before the Fang deal, he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   But the department never gave him the clear answers he wanted,
stating instead that it never reached the hard antitrust issues
because the Fang transaction satisfied its concern that some form
of newspaper competition in San Francisco continue.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
