<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5322 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-QUACKENBUSH- &LR;      07-28 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE ATTORNEY GENERAL RULES QUACKENBUSH FOUNDATIONS ILLEGAL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Former Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush
acted illegally when he set up nonprofit foundations to settle what
were alleged to be insurance companies' violations arising from the
Northridge earthquake, the state attorney general said in a formal
opinion released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion by Attorney General Bill Lockyer may add weight to
the criminal investigation of Quackenbush and his activities at the
department and help earthquake victims recover money either through
lawsuits or reopened claims.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before legislative hearings earlier this year,
Quackenbush and his top lawyer at the department had insisted that
the establishment of the foundations was legal. Quackenbush later
resigned to avoid almost certain impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinion, I believe, makes it very clear for all of us that
the conduct of the insurance commissioner was illegal,'' said state
Sen. Jackie Speier, D-Hillsborough, who requested the opinion. ``He
did not have the authority to make those settlements or request or
demand that money be contributed to foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   During the legislative inquiry, department officials testified
that they had recommended that insurance companies pay hundreds of
millions of dollars in fines. Instead, Quackenbush permitted the
companies to pay $13 million into nonprofit foundations, most of
which went to commercials featuring the commissioner and other
political activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us had a sense of disbelief, incredulity and outrage
that much of the activity going on in the Department of Insurance
was in (Quackenbush's) belief legal,'' Speier said. ``We now have
evidence that it was not legal, it was not politics as usual _ it
was downright wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The opinion by Lockyer states that although the insurance
commissioner has authority to set up foundations, their purpose
must be directly tied to the enforcement action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner may not include a term of a settlement
requiring payment of funds to a private charitable foundation for
the purpose of supporting activities unrelated to the regulatory
enforcement responsibilities of the Department of Insurance in the
proceeding,'' the opinion states.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's lawyer said the former commissioner took the legal
advice he was given.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he did with the settlements was based on legal
advice,'' said Sacramento attorney Donald Heller. ``He acted in
good faith. He was told that he was acting appropriately and
lawfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller said Quackenbush used the foundations for outreach, which
is part of his statutory obligation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are additional facts that might change the
conclusion of the opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer said in Los Angeles that the opinion took time because
there was no legal precedent to build on.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The opinion) clearly outlines that the insurance commissioner
has some serious limitations on his ability to direct settlement
monies to private, nonprofit foundations,'' Lockyer said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much weight the opinion will have in the
continuing state and federal criminal investigations. Lockyer has
confirmed that a federal grand jury is hearing evidence in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not in any way binding on the court, but it might be a
signal that the attorney general thinks a crime was committed,''
said Michael Vitiello, a law professor at the University of the
Pacific's McGeorge School of Law in Sacramento. ``What has to
happen next in federal court is that (Quackenbush) must be indicted
by a grand jury. The state attorney general's view on a violation
of state law is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vitiello said, ``This can't be good news for
Quackenbush.''
</P>
<P>
   With the legal authority to create the settlements now in doubt,
Speier said she believes that the Department of Insurance should
reopen its examinations of the insurance companies' handling of
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those settlements are void, and you always have the right to
set aside void acts,'' Speier said. ``I think the new insurance
commissioner should reopen the negotiations with the insurance
companies, reopen the market-conduct exams and reopen the
possibility of fines.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Kelso, a law professor, has been acting insurance
commissioner since Quackenbush resigned. In a brief statement, he
said Thursday that the opinion ``raises complex legal issues'' and
that he will consult with Lockyer on the full implications of the
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis said he will appoint a permanent successor to
Quackenbush next week. The nominee, who must be confirmed by the
Legislature, will serve out Quackenbush's term through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The market-conduct exams _ sensitive audits detailing insurers'
alleged claims-handling violations after the Northridge earthquake
in 1994 _ have been at the center of the allegations surrounding
Quackenbush.
</P>
<P>
   The documents say state regulators found that some insurance
companies had a tendency to lowball policyholder claims and delay
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Victims may not directly receive restitution even after this
ruling, Speier acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurance commissioner generally cannot get restitution,''
she said. ``But there is the right to fine and order companies to
reopen claims. I think there is a strong opportunity to have claims
reopened.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several lawsuits have been filed on behalf of
Northridge victims and taxpayers, demanding a return of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Kronland, a San Francisco lawyer representing taxpayers,
said Lockyer's opinion will be ``very helpful to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it supports the same theory that we are arguing _ that
the commissioner did not have the authority to put the money not in
the general fund, but in private funds used for political
purposes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of the insurance companies said Thursday
that the money paid to the foundations was not related to the
market-conduct exams and that no fines are warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our voluntary participation in (the foundation) was not a part
of the market-conduct survey,'' said Bill Sirola, a spokesman for
State Farm. ``It was for what we think is a very important
scientific study of earthquake damage assessment on residential
buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sirola said State Farm has responded to the market-conduct exams
and maintains its position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We paid no fine, and we will pay no fine,'' he said. ``We
still have a claims office in Northridge, and we continue to say
that any policyholder who feels they have problem should recontact
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
