r a BC-NAPSTER-APPEAL-SFCHRO     07-28 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-APPEAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NAPSTER APPEALS FEDERAL COURT INJUNCTION  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As its fans threatened cyberspace unrest,
embattled Napster Inc. appealed Thursday a federal court injunction
that would disconnect the online music-swapping service at midnight
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The San Mateo startup asked the U.S. Court of Appeals in San
Francisco for an emergency stay of the preliminary injunction that
a federal judge ordered Wednesday. No hearing was immediately
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   If Napster is not granted a stay, said interim chief executive
Hank Barry, the company plans to shut down the service to comply
with U.S. District Judge Marilyn Hall Patel's order.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would essentially destroy Napster as a business and
deprive the more than 20 million Napster users of their service,''
Napster's attorneys said in their motion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the ripples from the impending shutdown spread rapidly
throughout the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Napster's Web site was slowed to a crawl by fans seeking the
latest news and alternatives. According to Nielsen//NetRatings,
traffic to Napster's Web site increased about 56 percent since
Patel made her landmark copyright infringement ruling.
</P>
<P>
   And traffic to the Web site of a Napster alternative called
Scour has increased by 80 percent since last week.
</P>
<P>
   The more defiant Napster fans are calling for mass boycotts
against the record companies and general ``civil disobedience'' by
switching to decentralized file swapping programs like Gnutella and
Freenet. Neither is not controlled by a company that could be sued
by the record industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're engaged in here is cultural warfare,'' said John
Perry Barlow, co-founder and vice-chairman of the Internet civil
liberties group Electronic Frontier Foundation of San Francisco.
``This is a battle between the powers that were and the powers that
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Patel agreed with members of the Recording Industry Association
of America, which complained that the Napster program violates
copyright laws by allowing people to swap free MP3-formatted copies
of music.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Napster attorneys said they are
contesting Patel's ruling on several grounds, including claiming
that Patel ``wrongly stated that Napster users were engaged in
direct infringement'' and ``ignored substantial evidence that
Napster is helping, not hurting, the record industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Napster attorneys also said Patel's ruling ``extended copyright
law to cover new technologies, ignoring the counsel of the Supreme
Court that such extensions should be left to the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Neil Rosini, a copyright law expert not connected with
the case, said he does not expect the appeal to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very difficult for any judge to look at trading of
other people's copyrighted work without payment as being condoned
under copyright law,'' said Rosini, an attorney with Franklin,
Weinrib, Rudell &AMP; Vassallo of New York. Rosini also represents
Myplay.com Inc., a Redwood City Internet company that offers online
storage of MP3 songs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the ruling stands, Napsterites say this is not the day
the music died. Tracy Bixler, 33, of Pennsylvania, wrote in an
e-mail that if Napster is shut down, ``I will look into other
programs that allow me the same capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bixler said she bought only about five CDs last year, but since
finding new music with Napster, has already purchased about 70 this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster is technology, and the greedy RIAA and some of its
artists just can't stop it,'' Bixler said. ``There will always be
another way to find MP3s, and their best efforts aren't going to
change that. All this has accomplished is to make people more
determined than ever to find free music.''
</P>
<P>
   Napster's Web site took almost 70 seconds to access since the
ruling, compared to an average of 5 seconds earlier this week, said
Daniel Todd, director for public services of the Web monitoring
firm Keynote Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But to stay in business, Rosini said, Napster most likely will
be forced to reach a settlement with record companies and music
publishers that would allow some form of swapping to continue, but
still give money to artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the user base is so large and so valuable that
something will come of it,'' Rosini said.
</P>
<P>
   However, winning the preliminary injunction gives the recording
industry a powerful weapon to force Napster into a potentially
costly settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Recording Industry Association general counsel Cary Sherman said
Napster executives have informally approached individual record
companies with business plans that would appease both sides. But
now that the record industry has a court judgment in hand, Napster
must become more motivated to forge a settlement, Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Online music portal MP3.com Inc. lost a similar but unrelated
copyright suit against the record industry last month and is now
forced to set aside $150 million to cover settlement costs.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego company has agreed to pay $20 million each to
Warner Music Group and BMG Entertainment Inc. and has reportedly
agreed to a similar settlement with EMI.
</P>
<P>
   However, Napster, which received a $15 million investment from
Hummer Winblad Venture Partners, does not have the same financial
strength of MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   And the preliminary injunction, if it stands, will prevent
Napster from attracting a higher number of users that could have
given the company the advantage in negotiations with the record
industry, said Steve Vonder Haar, senior Internet consultant with
the research firm Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Napster has the chance to reinvent itself by generating
revenues, through subscription fees or advertising, that would then
be used to pay licensing or royalty fees to the music industry,
Vonder Haar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As ironic as it might seem, you could see Napster becoming a
valuable tool for the record labels themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is unclear how many of Napster's 20 million users would
stick with the program if they no longer were able to download free
songs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
