<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5326 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ENERGY-GOVERNOR-SFCHR     07-28 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-GOVERNOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GOV. DAVIS SEEKS REGULATOR INTERVENTION IN LOWERING POWER BILLS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis called Thursday for state regulators to seek
lower electricity rates amid a doubling of power bills in San
Diego, the first California city to feel the full effects of energy
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   He also urged the state Public Utilities Commission, which is
slated to discuss soaring electricity charges next week, to ``take
all actions necessary to assure that electricity supplies are
adequate and that prices paid by California consumers are just and
reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   As The Chronicle reported Thursday, average power bills in San
Diego have soared from about $55 to $103 during the past three
months as the local utility, San Diego Gas and Electric Co., passes
along its rising wholesale costs to ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Gas and Electric Co. said the same situation could occur
in Northern California when an electricity rate freeze is lifted
here, perhaps as soon as next year.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer activists and politicians at all levels have been
calling on Davis to take steps to relieve the sticker shock among
San Diego ratepayers and ease the impact of deregulation statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Californians are willing to pay their fair share of the cost
for a reliable supply of electricity, but I believe the current
situation is unjust and totally unacceptable,'' the governor said
in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that that state's 1996 deregulation bill promised
consumers that they would pay ``stable, if not reduced, prices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is clearly not the case in California,'' Davis said.
``The result is uncontrolled price spikes with no end in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on the California Independent System Operator, the
nonprofit agency that oversees electricity flow throughout the
state, to apply to federal regulators for an extension of its
authority to establish wholesale price caps.
</P>
<P>
   These caps are set to expire in November unless the ISO &LR; 
 &LR; Independent System Operator requests an extension.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Winter, chief executive of the Independent System
Operator, said his organization already was planning to apply for
an extension. But he said he was pleased that the governor has
taken an interest in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Independent Service Operator iSO  &LR; cut
California's power price cap to $500 per megawatt hour from $750.
The ISO &LR; It is expected to lower the cap even further to $250 at its
next meeting on August 1.
</P>
<P>
   Power generators are fighting such moves, arguing that price
caps are contrary to the spirit of deregulation and discourage
energy companies from investing in new power plants.
</P>
<P>
   In a move almost sure to draw the wrath of power companies,
Davis called on the state PUC Public Utilities Commission  &LR; and the
state Electricity Oversight Board to ask federal regulators to rule
that California does not have a competitive energy market.
</P>
<P>
   Such a determination would allow the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission to set ``just and reasonable'' rates for California
electricity users, which would almost certainly be lower than
current ones. rates. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  However, if federal authorities determine that the state's
energy market is indeed competitive, current market rates would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Lynch, the PUC president, said she is glad that Davis is
coordinating unified actions among state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy that California is speaking with one voice,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her commission is scheduled to take up the matter of
skyrocketing San Diego electricity bills at its meeting next
Thursday, but the only proposal on the table, in essence,
encourages the PUC to allow deregulation to run its course.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Davis asked Lynch to facilitate the return of $100
million in refunds to San Diego ratepayers. SDG&AMP;E &LR; San Diego Gas and
Electric already has said it is working to return the money,
amassed through the sale of its generating assets, to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Nettie Hoge, executive director of the Utility Reform Network in
San Francisco, said she was heartened to see the governor taking
the initiative in relieving the impact of energy deregulation on
utility customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that he's using the bully pulpit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hoge said that most of Davis' recommendations concern
developments that are already under way and that the governor is
not breaking much new ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's said anything bold here,'' Hoge said. ``But
Davis is on the right track. Everyone should now rally around
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
