<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HATE CRIMES RISE IN CALIFORNIA AFTER YEARS OF DECLINE  &HT;     By STACY FINZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
After years on the decline, hate crimes in California rose by 12.1
percent last year, according to statistics released Thursday by the
California Department of Justice.
<P>
   Until 1999, most hate crimes appeared to be falling. In 1998,
there were 1,750 hate crimes reported in California, with a 7.6
percent drop in attacks based on race, ethnicity, sexual
orientation or religion from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, the total number jumped to 1,962 with more than
60 percent of the offenses motivated by race or ethnicity,
according to the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each hate crime is an attack on a human being's personal
identity or beliefs,'' state Attorney General Bill Lockyer said in
a statement. ``This latest hate crime report unfortunately shows
that while we live in one of the most diverse places on the planet,
there is still ugly intolerance and violence focused against people
who are different.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Bernstein, director of the Anti-Defamation League for
the Central Pacific region, said not only are the numbers of
concern, but the severity of some of last year's events are
horrifying.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the state was rocked by a shooting rampage at a Los
Angeles-area Jewish center, injuring a woman, a teenager and three
young boys and finally ending with the death of a Filipino mail
carrier. A month earlier, a gay couple was killed in their home
near Redding. And in June, three Sacramento synagogues were
torched. Authorities have said that the crimes were fueled by
hatred and racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think last year's high-profile attacks contributed to the
rise in numbers,'' Bernstein said. ``There were copycats and public
awareness about the incidents probably contributed to more
reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer said efforts are being made to make the public more
aware of the importance of reporting crimes motivated by racism or
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of HATECRIM (61169 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Anyone familiar with hate crime reporting knows there still is
a problem of underreporting of incidents,'' Lockyer said. ``This is
a major issue being tackled by the Attorney General's Civil Rights
Commission on Hate Crimes. The commission is hearing
recommendations from local communities in forums throughout the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said while the numbers fluctuate from year to year,
there is no question in his mind that hate crimes have become more
violent and the perpetrators are younger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to teach more tolerance in the schools,'' he said.
``Police agencies also need to be educated and they need to educate
their communities.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the hate crime report:
</P>
<P>
   --Violent crimes last year accounted for more than 67 percent of
the incidents.
</P>
<P>
   --Race or ethnicity was the motivation for 1,173 crimes, sexual
orientation for 436 attacks and religion for 338 incidents.
</P>
<P>
   --Hate crimes occurred at a home or in a driveway nearly 31
percent of the time or on a highway, street, alley or sidewalk 26.2
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   -- Prosecutors filed 372 hate crime complaints last year, with
nearly 62 percent resulting in convictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
