r a BC-YOSEMITE-SPILL-SFCHRO     07-28 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-SPILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 RAW SEWAGE SPILLS INTO MERCED RIVER AT EDGE OF YOSEMITE  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A huge sewage spill has contaminated the Merced
River below Yosemite National Park at the height of the summer
tourist season, forcing a health advisory urging local residents
and visitors to stay out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 gallons of raw sewage poured into the Merced
Thursday between 6:30 a.m. and 7:15 a.m. from a new sewer line that
runs between the park and a sewage treatment plant at El Portal, a
hamlet just outside the park's boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The spill occurred during tests to determine the condition of
the line, said park spokeswoman Christine Cowles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sewer line became clogged when we were running the tests,
probably with material that fell in during recent construction on
Highway 140,'' said Cowles, referring to a road that runs along the
river and is a popular route to the park.
</P>
<P>
   Cowles said about 60 percent of the spill was freshwater, the
rest untreated sewage. The amount of water and sewage that spilled
would have filled about 25 tanker trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were running the lines at 100 percent of capacity,'' Cowles
said. ``Under normal conditions, the (flow) is usually at 50
percent (capacity) or less.''
</P>
<P>
   Park officials immediately posted advisories along five miles of
river frontage downstream of the spill site, directing people to
stay away from the water until tests indicate fecal coliform
bacteria have fallen to safe levels.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of YOSEMITE (109839 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Cowles said the National Park Service is working with Mariposa
County and the Regional Water Quality Control Board to monitor
bacteria levels. ``We're recommending no contact for at least 24
hours,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacteria test results from samples of river water taken after
the spill are not expected to be available until Friday, Cowles
said.
</P>
<P>
   The spill could not have occurred at a worst time. Yosemite's
tourist season is in full swing, and guests who stay at the large
hotels in El Portal often cool off by taking dips in the pools of
the normally pristine Sierra Nevada river.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is also  &LR; exacerbated by the river's low summer
flows.
</P>
<P>
   Bacterial contamination is dissipated more quickly by high
volumes of water. Thursday, the Merced's flow was about 150 cubic
feet a second; springtime flows on the river can sometimes &LR;   &LR; exceed
10,000 cubic feet per second.
</P>
<P>
   Although the levels of fecal coliform bacteria are expected to
fall off fairly quickly, other hazards associated with the spill
may last longer, health officials warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fecal coliform bacteria are easy to monitor, but it's
impossible to monitor for pathogenic viruses such as those
associated with hepatitis and a variety of gastrointestinal
diseases without some pretty sophisticated equipment,'' said Dave
Spath, chief of drinking water and environmental management for the
California Department of Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of YOSEMITE (109839 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``That's why viral monitoring typically isn't done (after a
spill),'' Spath said. ``The problem is that viral agents tend to
hang around longer than (coliform bacteria), particularly if the
water is pretty cold, as I assume it still is in the Merced.''
</P>
<P>
   Spath said a 200,000-gallon spill translates into a significant
recreational health risk, ``particularly because it was raw sewage
only diluted by about a one-to-one ratio. People shouldn't swim or
wade in the river until it's clear that it's safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries and wildlife can be affected by heavy sewage spills.
Fish kills, in particular, are common. But no dead fish had been
reported yet in the Merced, Cowles said. The river supports a good
trout fishery.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Yosemite's sewer lines have sullied
the Merced _ but that doesn't mean there is anything inherently
inadequate about the system, Cowles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some spills last year, but they were also
associated with tests,'' said Cowles. ``We don't have any doubts
about the basic soundness of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists said the spill is one of many indications
that Yosemite and its environs are overbuilt, threatening the
natural beauty and biological integrity of the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very significant event, and it points out that we
need less development in Yosemite and the surrounding area,'' said
Janet Cobb, president of the Yosemite Restoration Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us want to be close to the river and appreciate it, but
we need to be mindful of the impact our activities have on it,''
Cobb said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
