<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5332 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-28 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING CRUZ, THREE YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When did you finally feel comfortable as a Toronto
Blue Jay?
</P>
<P>
   ``This season,'' said Jose Cruz Jr.
</P>
<P>
   As Monday's trading deadline approaches, with the slavering
hordes itchy for the Mariners to bust a move, it is instructive to
hear from a chunk of meat what it felt like almost three years ago
to have become a chunk of meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My world,'' he said, ``flipped upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have said the lights went out on his world, but that is
more appropriate to ridiculously overpriced baseball stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, one-time darling of the Mariners farm system, only
recently has gotten over being swapped July 31, 1997, for relief
pitchers Mike Timlin and Paul Spoljaric.
</P>
<P>
   Middle of the game in Milwaukee. Getting ready to bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, come over here,'' Cruz recalled manager Lou Piniella
saying. ``And bring your glove.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clubhouse, he got the word from assistant general manager
Lee Pelekoudas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' he said before starting Thursday
night's game in left field against the Mariners. ``I was ...
bewildered. It really didn't set in until the guys came over to the
hotel room to say their good-byes.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-nine games into what he, the Mariners and most of their
fans figured to be a long, decorous solution to the chronic
franchise problem of left field, Cruz was adrift in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started to feel good in the city, knowing where things
were,'' he said. ``I had friends, I was comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I just got my cable TV hooked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Many can relate to that epochal achievement. There are pockets
of Puget Sound where cable hookups happen slightly less quickly
than whale gestation.
</P>
<P>
   For Cruz, however, not only was there no one to share the
majesty of the triumph, he now had to unhook the cable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no obligation on the part of fans to feel sorry for
Cruz, or any of his uprooted brethren. Whether in Seattle or
Toronto, Cruz remains a major league ballplayer, a form of living
exceeded in previous times by only sheiks, emperors and the minor
deities.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, 26, is fully aware of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of my goal was to be a major league ballplayer,''
he said. ``That's still true.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as with anyone when a dream is kinked, Cruz was hurt, a
little irked and helpless when his fate was rearranged beyond his
control. He fancied himself as a Mariner in the Kingdome almost
from the time he was taken in the first round of the 1995 major
league draft from Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   As the son of a major leaguer who played 13 seasons with one
team, the Houston Astros, the notion of baseball vagabond was not
prominent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone taken by an organization sees himself with them the
whole time,'' he said. ``Sure, you know it's a business, but that
isn't what you think about. You make friends, you think about
playing with them in the majors. Suddenly you're ripped away, going
to a place that you know nothing about, and don't know anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did I go from West to East, I went from America to
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   In major league sports, young players are rarely given the
courtesy of a heads-up, much less a choice. In the week prior to
the trade, then-general manager Woody Woodward declared flatly that
the popular youngster would not be traded. So Cruz relaxed a bit,
only to be bushwhacked.
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal was condemned at the time, relievers Timlin
and Spoljaric did help the Mariners reach the 1997 playoffs with a
club-record, 90-win season. But as Baltimore demonstrated in its
3-1 division-series triumph, the '97 team was far from a serious
challenger. Both pitchers eventually were traded.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Cruz has not rivaled the aurora borealis in the
Canadian sky. He has yet to return to his rookie-year Seattle
production levels, when he hit .268 with 12 home runs and 34 RBIs
in 49 games.
</P>
<P>
   He hit .231 the rest of that season in Toronto. In 105 games in
'98, he hit .253, and .241 in 106 games in '99, with stretches in
Class AAA both years. This year he has played every game, hitting
.233 with 21 homers and 49 RBIs. He still struggles with off-speed
pitches. Although improving, he remains a least-likely candidate
for a Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz professes no disillusionment with baseball, but can't avoid
wondering, along with Seattle fans, what would have been. It
doesn't appear he will become the glamorous star forecast by some.
But perhaps a dozen clubs would be willing to take a chance on him
if the Blue Jays figure a trade would give them a shot to stay with
the Yankees in an up-for-grabs year in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Having experienced the nature of the commodities market
personally, his world likely would not again be flippable. But as
most ordinary folks can tell him, neither is there joy in spending
a valued portion of one's life waiting for the cable guy.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
