<HEADLINE>
FRENCH `FANATIQUES' KNOW U.S. WAY OFF TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the Web site of the often-droll French sports daily,
``L'Equipe,'' news of our Olympic stupidity predictably failed to
go unnoticed this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnson, Greene disparu!'' Yes, they certainly did.
</P>
<P>
   And I have this vision of sports fanatiques, throughout ``la
belle France,'' perusing the dispatches from Sacramento and
wondering, ``And these guys defeated the Germans?''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, yes, we will be sending a track and field team to
Sydney without either the reigning world champion or the world
record holder in the men's 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on our democratic society. Blame it on the lawyers.
Blame it on too many hours of Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the world's No. 1 track and field team,'' Craig
Masback, the chief executive officer of USA Track and Field,
repeated _ more than once _ during last week's Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   And by the glare of the rented spotlight that USATF enjoyed for
10 days in California's Central Valley, it was hard to argue. The
infatuated Sacramento fans cheered for 9.93 sprinters and 26-foot
long jumpers alike.
</P>
<P>
   Masback based his ``No. 1'' claim on previous results at the
Olympics, the 1998 World Cup and the '99 World Championships of
Track and Field, when the first eight places are scored as a normal
U.S. track meet. Which they aren't, of course, but Masback was
getting so much ink in the Sacramento paper last week, the trials
became a tent revival, of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   He was selling. And lots of folks _ NBC, Nike, the city of
Sacramento, which wants the trials again in '04 _ apparently were
buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have a good team in Sydney,'' said U.S. men's
team assistant coach Bubba Thornton, head coach at Texas and a
native of Keller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a good mix of the old and new.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet I think Thornton is only half-right. The team that was
selected in Sacramento does have an intriguing blend of old and
new. But the new faces, as well as some of the old ones, are yet
unproven.
</P>
<P>
   With seven weeks to go before the Sydney Games, this figures to
be the weakest track and field team that the United States has sent
to an Olympics in 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men's team at Montreal in 1976 won only one individual
running event _ Edwin Moses' victory in the 400-meter hurdles. The
American women won no events, track or field. The other five men's
gold medals came in the decathlon (Bruce Jenner), long jump (Arnie
Robinson), discus (Mac Wilkins) and both relays.
</P>
<P>
   Can this U.S. men's team win six golds in Sydney?
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene reminded the Sacramento
tent faithful last weekend, don't count your chickens, even if you
think they're tape-delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is the world's fastest ever at 100 meters, but his
inconsistency was underscored in Sacramento. His fastest race was
his first, a 9.93-second 100 meters in the prelims, and he was
pushed to the tape in his first 200-meter heat.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's running mates in the Sydney 100 meters will be TCU ex
Jon Drummond and Curtis Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond is a veteran with solid credentials, but the fact that
he competed so well in Sacramento will send an encouraging message
to the sprinters in Jamaica, Nigeria and Canada. Curtis Johnson, on
the other hand, was once eighth in the U.S. championships and has
never been ranked in the world's top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``In just about every event, across the board, we have new
upstarts along with seasoned veterans,'' argued '76 Olympic
medal-winner Fred Newhouse, who will serve as manager of the U.S.
team in Australia. ``And I think that's absolutely wonderful news
for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, but when people sit down to watch the Olympics on NBC,
they don't want to hear about the rebuilding program _ they want to
see Americans beating Russians, Germans, Canadians, et al., to the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson, still splendid at 400 meters, should do that.
Allen Johnson, likewise, remains the best 110-meter high hurdler on
the planet. And young Angelo Taylor may well carry on Moses' golden
tradition in the 400 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   But in front of an expected rowdy Aussie crowd of mates and
sheilas, the Americans won't have the homefield advantage that they
enjoyed in Atlanta. The 13 gold medals won in '96 and the 12 in '92
seem a distant possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the system of picking the U.S. teams would help. But
the enduring appeal of the Olympic trials lie in the all-or-nothing
drama. It isn't likely to change, especially now that the CEO
recognizes it as a showcase event, a chance to strut and to finally
draw a countable TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   But we're No. 1?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not this time. It's a rebuilding year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
