<SLUG> BC-NIEVES-CONVICT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER CONVICTED OF KILLING FOUR DAUGHTERS IN FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOLLY EDWARDS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FERNANDO, Calif. _ After deliberating just five hours, a
jury found Sandi Dawn Nieves guilty of murdering her four young
daughters and trying to murder her teen-age son in a 1998 arson at
their home in northern Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Nieves, wearing a dark-green jacket and skirt, hid her face with
a piece of paper and two jurors wiped away tears as the judge
pronounced her guilty Thursday of four counts of first-degree
murder with special circumstances, as well as attempted murder and
arson charges. The same jury that convicted her will determine
whether she should get the death penalty or spend the rest of her
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdicts were read, the stepmother of two of the girls
read a statement on behalf of the family outside the Superior Court
in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts go out to all the children in this country who are
used by one of their parents to seek revenge on their ex-spouses to
manipulate and to hurt one another,'' said Charlotte Nieves, who
was flanked by Sandi Nieves' ex-husbands, Fernando Nieves and Dave
Folden.
</P>
<P>
   ``These girls had to pay with their lives because their mother
did the unspeakable act of killing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members were not allowed to speak extensively about the
verdict, however, because they are expected to testify during the
penalty phase of the trial, which is scheduled to begin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Sandi Nieves was seeking revenge against her two
ex-husbands and an ex-boyfriend July 1, 1998, when she lured the
girls into the kitchen of her Seco Canyon home for a slumber party.
She set gasoline-fueled fires throughout the house, then called 911
to say she could not awaken them.
</P>
<P>
   Sandi Nieves and David, her son from her first marriage, were
hospitalized for smoke inhalation. The boy testified against his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-month trial, Deputy Public Defender Howard Waco
tried to paint Sandi Nieves, 36, as a woman emotionally destroyed
by child custody and boyfriend problems. He has said she still has
no memory of the fire that killed Jaqlene Marie Folden, 5; Kristl
Dawn Folden, 7; Rashel Hollie Nieves, 11; and Nikolet Amber Nieves,
12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for the jury because they didn't hear the case I
hoped to present,'' Waco said, referring to numerous objections
that interrupted his presentation. ``The jury may feel cheated
later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Waco said he would appeal the verdict, but acknowledged there is
a slim chance that it would be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they were gratified by the jury's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief to hear those words after two years and a lot of
work,'' said Deputy District Attorney Beth Silverman, in tears
after the verdict was read. ``You live and breathe these kind of
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict was read and the jury of five women and seven
men was escorted from the building, Waco asked Judge Jeffrey Wiatt
for permission to delay penalty arguments for a week to allow Sandi
Nieves' out-of-state family members time to get into town.
</P>
<P>
   When the judge denied the request, Sandi Nieves muttered, ``He
doesn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard what you said, Ms. Nieves, and anything you say in
court can be used against you,'' Wiatt responded.
</P>
<P>
   Waco also asked the judge to arrange special transportation for
the defendant from the jail to court because she has been
`'verbally and physically abused'' by other inmates on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   However, Waco said such arrangements must be made through the
Sheriff's Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
