<HEADER>
A5336 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBO-FAT-ALLSTARS-SPI &LR;      07-28 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FAT-ALLSTARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TEAM REALLY STEPS UP TO THE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Lance Armstrong's body-fat percentage is approximately
that of an aluminum bike frame. Michael Jordan is 6 feet, 6 inches
of lean, tapered muscle. Marion Jones looks like she just walked
out of a Tae-Bo workout videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just hate them?
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of baseball, though, is that even in this
androstenedione-charged world of personal trainers, you can have a
body like Kirby Puckett, Tony Gwynn or David Wells and still be
among the best players in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, today's ballplayers increasingly look like they were
sculpted by Rodin. But fortunately, there still is room for the
more distinctively built players, the ones who provide hope to
every couch potato. The ones who are built, well, like
sportswriters.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we've come up with this All-Star team of players who
make us all feel a little better when we step on the scales. We're
thinking of players such as Kent Hrbek, whose idea of
cross-training was riding the stationary bike while eating a Dove
bar. Or former Philadelphia first baseman John Kruk, who epitomized
what our All-Star team is all about when he once told a woman,
``Lady, I'm not an athlete, I'm a ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   We had only two criteria in selecting this team. One, the player
was never a candidate to sashay down a Milan catwalk modeling
Versace's latest spring line. And two, he had to be good. Every
player on this team played in an All-Star Game or was a key member
of a title-winning team.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about these guys, they're ballplayers.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher: There's a lot of competition here. There was
Mickey Lolich, who didn't let his weight prevent him from regularly
pitching 300 innings a season (he fittingly opened a donut shop
after his retirement from baseball). And there was Jim Bibby, who
was large enough that a pitching coach said he pitched Bibby on an
especially windy day because he knew Bibby couldn't be blown off
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, we go with Toronto's Cy Young candidate David
Wells, who pitched a perfect game in 1998 and who has five more
wins this season than that Boston beanpole, Pedro Martinez. The
competition was close, but what puts Wells over the top is his
trademark unbuttoned jersey _ and the time he showed up to spring
training with a case of gout.
</P>
<P>
   Relief pitcher: Could there be anyone else for this spot other
than Terry Forster, the man David Letterman labeled the Fat Tub of
Goo? Forster took the kidding in good humor _ when he appeared on
the show later, he showed up with his clothes stuffed with food.
Years later, some of his ex-teammates still refer to him as
``Goo.''
</P>
<P>
   First base: So many players, so many choices. There's George
Scott and Boog Powell, Mo Vaughn and Hrbek. But in the end, we went
with Kruk, who always looked right at home on a ballfield _ a
softball field.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 21, 1990, the Phillies were losing 11-1 in Los Angeles
in the eighth inning, and the game was dragging on so long that
Kruk grew upset because ``we weren't going to get back to the hotel
in time for room service.'' But the Phillies rallied to win the
game, inspiring this gem from our hero: ``If you're going to miss
room service, you might as well win.''
</P>
<P>
   Second base: Carlos Baerga. He was one the best hitters in the
American League in the early '90s, even though he showed up to
spring training each year looking a bit too much like the Michelin
Man.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop: Kevin Mitchell. Sure, Mitch was relatively trim when
he played shortstop briefly with the Mets, but the former MVP makes
the team on his body of work over a long career, which included
missing a couple of games when he pulled a muscle while throwing
up.
</P>
<P>
   The man would eat anything, including this odd, cold recipe.
Rather than spread it on his body, he said he ate Vick's VapoRub.
</P>
<P>
   Third base: Bob Horner. Big Bob Horner, who ruled the hot
corner, had a clause in his contract with Atlanta that paid him
$100,000 if he weighed 215 pounds or less every Friday home game.
Horner later played for the Cardinals. When asked what he liked
best about St. Louis, he replied, ``Frosted beer mugs (in the
clubhouse.)''
</P>
<P>
   Outfield: Greg Luzinski. A member of the 250-250 club (250
pounds, 250 home runs), the Bull played alongside Philadelphia
center fielder Garry Maddox, of whom it was said, ``Water covers
two-thirds of the earth, Maddox covers the rest.'' By the end of
his career, when he was at his uniform-challenging peak, the same
was true of Luzinski.
</P>
<P>
   Outfield: Babe Ruth. The Granddaddy of Poundage, Ruth began his
career as a relatively trim pitcher but became the most popular
sports figure of his day when he bulked up into the Sultan of Swat.
Perhaps the greatest player in the game's history, Ruth had such a
legendary appetite that when he was hospitalized in 1925 with an
intestinal abcess (``the bellyache heard 'round the world'') the
popular legend (perhaps untrue) was he had overindulged in too many
hot dogs and too much soda pop.
</P>
<P>
   Outfield: Matt Stairs. What a beauty. The natural heir to the
Kruk legacy of ballplayers, Stairs is a fire hydrant of a man who
played for the Canadian Olympic team, loves pro wrestling and paid
his dues with seven years in the minors and a season in Japan
before developing into one of the league's top power threats with
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to love this guy. Commenting on his physique, Stairs
once said that since everyone said he had a beer-league swing, it
makes sense to have a ``beer-league body.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher: It's tempting to go with someone named Pudge, but both
Carlton Fisk and Ivan Rodriguez are a little too solid for this
team. However, Pittsburgh's Mike LaValliere, a Gold Glover, made a
nice target behind home plate by the end of his career, spreading
some 225 pounds over his 5-foot-9 frame. Plus, you've got to love a
guy nicknamed Spanky.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter: There are many to choose from, but the nod
goes to Cecil Fielder. After he hit a massive home run in spring
training 1990 (his 50-homer season), one pitcher said he could hear
Fielder rattling his chains in the on-deck circle. A Twins
infielder went further than that in 1996 when Big Cecil finally
stole his first base, saying he could ``hear him coming'' down the
basepath.
</P>
<P>
   Manager: Tommy Lasorda. Pre-Slim Fast days, of course.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
