<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD ON PACE FOR YET ANOTHER RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Darin Erstad's remarkable season _ his
major-league-leading hit total, 166 at game time, his major
league-leading multihit games, etc. _ has been well chronicled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one more:
</P>
<P>
   Erstad is on pace to become the first major-leaguer to record
100 RBI from the leadoff position.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad started the night with 73 RBI, tied with Garret Anderson
for second on the club behind Mo Vaughn's 77.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Erstad needs just one home run and two stolen bases to
become only the fourth Angels player with at least 20 homers and 20
stolen bases in a season. Don Baylor did it three times (1977-79),
Bobby Bonds had 37 homers and 41 steals in 1977 and Devon White did
it in most recently, in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   CAN'T GET ENOUGH: Angels manager Mike Scioscia was pleasantly
surprised when he showed up Thursday afternoon at Edison Field and
saw his entire squad ready to take batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Batting practice was optional since we got home so late (early
Thursday morning from Texas),'' Scioscia said. ``I left it up to
them. Guys need a little breather. By the time we landed, bused to
the stadium and then drove home .. . I'm sure some guys didn't get
home until 3:30 in the morning. And, look, everybody showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge. This is awesome. It shows how much these guys
love the game, how much passion they have for the game, knowing the
price they have to pay to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see, really. (But) it doesn't surprise me,
knowing the makeup of this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   BEING FRANK: Chicago White Sox manager Jerry Manuel, talking
about slugger Frank Thomas:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made the proper adjustments, and that's made his season
even more than (being in good) health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a while for the league to figure him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``For seven years (1991-98, when he became the first
major-leaguer to bat .300 or better with at least 20 home runs, 100
RBI, 100 walks and 100 runs scored seven consecutive seasons, and
earned two MVP awards) no one figured him out. Then they figured
him out for a couple of years (he hit only .265 one year).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's made an adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some adjustment. Thomas went into Thursday night's game hitting
.331 with 29 homers and 90 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Left-hander Kent Mercker, sidelined since May 12
because of a cerebral hemorrhage, will begin his rehab this
weekend. Mercker, who was 0-1 in 12 appearances including two
starts before he was stricken, will pitch for Lake Elsinore in a
Single-A California League game Saturday at Stockton against the
Mudville Nine. Scioscia figures Mercker will need three or four
rehab starts before he's ready to return to Anaheim. Mercker will
be restricted to 30 pitches Saturday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
