<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; LAYOFFS _  &LR; Now that the Internet bubble has burst and dozens of
companies are laying off employees, are dot-coms doing a better job
of handing out pink slips than brick-and-mortar companies?
</P>
<P>
   Not really.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that said they could reinvent the wheel for doing
business are, at best, following well-worn tire tracks when it
comes to reductions in force. At worst, they're treating cast-off
workers like spam mail that they can't wait to delete.  &UR; BY CAROLYN &LR; 
 &UR; SAID (WITH TWO SIDEBARS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; STORES _  &LR; Greg White stopped in at the Virgin Megastore in downtown
San Francisco on Thursday to check out the latest from rapper DJ
Quik. He bopped his head in time with the music at one of the
store's listening stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes me 10 minutes to download something on the Net,''
27-year-old White said. ``Here, you just push a button.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't kiss off the old economy quite yet. Most people agree that
despite a federal court judge's decision to put the brakes on
Napster, online music resources are here to stay. Still,
record-store customers and employees say you just can't beat the
feel of a CD in the hand.  &UR; BY DAVID LAZARUS &LR;
</P>
