<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWERS-FINANCING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FARMERS PIN HOPES ON FINANCING PLAN  &HT;     By KELLY YAMANOUCHI 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ron Martella could use a new tractor, and maybe
a new truck. The peaches are ripe and ready to be picked off the
trees on his 1,000-acre farm in Hughson, Calif., not far from
Modesto.
</P>
<P>
   But the tractor and the truck will have to wait. That's because
the processor he supplies, Tri Valley Growers, filed for bankruptcy
July 10, and can afford to pay Martella only 70 percent of the
negotiated price for his peaches.
</P>
<P>
   Growers like Martella are members of Tri Valley, an agricultural
cooperative that buys fruits from them and then processes and cans
them.
</P>
<P>
   Tri Valley is scheduled to appear Friday before U.S. Bankruptcy
Court Judge Edward D. Jellen, seeking final approval for $270
million in financing from a consortium of banks.
</P>
<P>
   If the financing plan is approved, the cooperative will be able
to continue processing fruit and could be in a stronger position to
pay Martella and other growers 70 cents on the dollar for their
crops. The financing agreement also calls for the sale of Tri
Valley to a new party by February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all eyes are on (Friday's) activities in U.S.
bankruptcy court in Oakland (Calif.),'' said Tri Valley spokesman
Fred MacFarlane.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to only getting 70 cents on the dollar for their
crops, the growers are upset because the cooperative is taking only
85 percent of the peaches it agreed to in their contracts. Grape
and pear growers are facing similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit, though, are the tomato growers, who were told that
the processor would buy only 30 percent of their produce.
</P>
<P>
   The growers say they have little room to maneuver. If they break
contract with Tri Valley, Martella said, it would be difficult to
find other processors that would take their peaches without
approval from Tri Valley.
</P>
<P>
   That has left fruit growers in California's Central Valley
scrambling to find a place to unload tons of surplus fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the California Tomato Growers Association Inc.
asked the U.S. Department of Agriculture to spend $40 million to
$50 million to purchase members' surplus crop. Those funds will be
used to benefit the association's members who belong to the Tri
Valley cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Their action followed the lead of pear growers, who were told
Monday that the USDA will purchase 32,000 tons of canned pears,
which will be donated to the federal school lunch program and other
USDA programs.
</P>
<P>
   And in an effort to keep peaches out of the market to prevent
prices from dropping, the California Canning Peach Association is
implementing a tree-pull program. The growers will pull about
16,000 tons of peaches and put another 5,000 tons into juice
production.
</P>
<P>
   Growers hope the move will provide Tri Valley with the funds to
pay them for the fruit they supply to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really concerned that in two to three weeks, Tri Valley
will take our crop and not pay for it,'' said Dan Stephens, who has
100 acres of peaches on his farm in Yuba City, Calif., and was
planning on pulling 25 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Martella, also chair of the peach association, said it is
unusual to pull peaches this time of the year. He said they are
usually pulled in the fall, after the fruit has been harvested, or
early in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling the trees before the harvest eliminates jobs in the
field and at the canneries at a time when jobs are badly needed in
the valley, Martella said.
</P>
<P>
   Tri Valley says two tomato canneries, in Thornton and Los Banos,
Calif., have been idled, putting residents there out of jobs and
reducing the load that can be processed.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this month, Crown Cork &AMP; Seal, which had an
agreement to supply cans to Tri Valley, shut down. The cooperative
had racked up $74 million in debt to the canmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Martella said some growers are close to bankrupt, and will
likely be forced to liquidate their farms as a result of Tri
Valley's decision.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at  &LR; kyamanouchi &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
