<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORES-CDSALES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOREOWNERS SAY CD SALES STRONG DESPITE RECENT ONLINE
MUSIC  HOOPLA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Greg White stopped in at the Virgin Megastore in
downtown San Francisco on Thursday to check out the latest from
rapper DJ Quik. He bopped his head in time with the music at one of
the store's listening stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes me 10 minutes to download something on the Net,''
27-year-old White said. ``Here, you just push a button.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't kiss off the old economy quite yet. Most people agree that
despite a federal court judge's decision to put the brakes on
Napster, online music resources are here to stay. Still,
record-store customers and employees say you just can't beat the
feel of a CD in the hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I buy a CD, I want the whole thing,'' said Travis
McDonnell, 19. ``I love shopping for CDs. It's one of my favorite
things in the world. I wouldn't trade it for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry insists that download technologies like
Napster, which Thursday appealed a federal judge's ruling that it
shut down, pose a grave threat to record companies' and artists'
earnings. But the reality appears to be that CD sales are as strong
as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business has never been better,'' said Joe Goldmark, manager
of Amoeba Music on Haight Street in San Francisco. ``We're doing
better every year.''
</P>
<P>
   He accepted that a certain segment of the consumer population
will be drawn to downloading tunes on the Net but said the new
economy still has a way to go before replacing the old.
</P>
<P>
   ``People enjoy the shopping experience,'' Goldmark said. ``They
like to find things they didn't know they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America has estimated that
Napster's 20 million or so users have cost record companies about
$300 million in lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   But that's still a relatively small fraction of the $40 billion
the U.S. recording industry rakes in every year. And it seems that
for every never-say-die Napster user who demands the right to free
downloads, there are numerous others who see things differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get it free but you're not paying off the artist,''
said Jason Mitchell, 25, while browsing Virgin's racks. ``I think
that's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   He cast his eyes around the store's crowded aisles. ``I prefer
walking into a shop,'' Mitchell said. ``It's more exciting walking
around and looking at CDs and giving things a listen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like the feel of things,'' agreed Tracey Gray, 33,
checking out songs at a listening station. ``I like to see what
other people are buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Shayde Sartin, a CD salesman at the Borders outlet on Union
Square, said Wednesday's Napster ruling upset him so much that he
spent much of Thursday chatting about it online with other music
buffs.
</P>
<P>
   But whether or not tunes can be tasted for free on the Net, he
said he has no doubt that people will keep buying CDs for their
collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be record stores,'' Sartin said. ``There
will always be people who have to have record stores.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get no argument from Stan Goman, chief operating officer
at Tower Records, headquartered in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster was never something that scared me, other than that it
gave an impression that music can be had for free, and that's just
not true,'' Goman said.
</P>
<P>
   Napster, he added, ``was originally like a college prank, and
then it became a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Goman admitted he tried it out for himself. He recently
downloaded a song onto his computer and listened to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what?'' he said. ``It sounded like crap. I mean,
what's the big deal there?''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
