<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-WEBSITES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NET PROJECT HOPES TO BOOST VOTER PARTICIPATION  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Internet is offering you a chance to set the
agenda for the coming presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   Through a Web site set up by the Commission on Presidential
Debates, you'll be able to suggest topics you would like to hear
discussed in the televised debates.
</P>
<P>
   The site,  &LR; www.debates.org &LR; , was set up in an effort to get
voters _ especially young people _ involved in the election
process. The public's interest in political campaigns has been
sinking in recent years, said Heather Balas, the commission's
director of special projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1998 election, 18-to-24-year-olds voted in lower
numbers than they ever had ever before. Tidbits like that led the
debate commission to look fundamentally at our voter education
efforts for this election,'' Balas said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, the commision realized, would be a good vehicle
for reaching out to youth. The commission also hopes to hook people
of all ages who have not participated in other voter education
projects.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's results will be turned over to debate moderators,
who have not yet been chosen. However, the moderators will have
final say on the topics the candidates debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't insist upon it, but we would be surprised if the
survey results weren't taken into account,'' Balas said.
</P>
<P>
   The polls were created by market research firm Harris
Interactive, and the Web site is designed and powered by sponsors,
including AT&AMP;T, 3Com and Sun Microsystems. The companies behind the
project provided the services and equipment, worth several million
dollars. The commission is a nonprofit organization that has been
organizing the presidential debates since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The predebate survey, available now, also asks how debates
should be conducted. For example, voters can recommend the
traditional, standing-at-a-podium debate or a more-informal town
hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site will host chat sessions after each debate where
citizens can discuss what they saw and heard. That feature is an
extension of the commission's DebateWatch program, which, since
1996, has encouraged people to gather at libraries and other
locations to view debates in a group and discuss them afterward.
</P>
<P>
   After each debate, viewers can register their reactions in a
postdebate survey. TV viewing audiences have ranged from 30 million
to 90 million for recent debates.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
