r f BC-LAYOFFSIDE1-COPING-SF     07-28 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAYOFFSIDE1-COPING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HAVING A HEART CAN MAKE JOB CUTS EASIER TO HANDLE  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Getting laid off is a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the economy is great and unemployment is low. Yes, dot-com
workers have great skills and should be able to land new jobs
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   That does not obviate the human factor when it comes time to cut
staff, said psychologists and human-resources experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a fundamental understanding: This is a very, very
important event in the life of the person being terminated,'' said
Jacques Leger, managing consultant in San Francisco for human
resources consultancy Watson Wyatt Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll remember everything; time will slow down for them,
just like in a car accident it feels like you see the other car
coming at you for 20 minutes,'' Leger said.
</P>
<P>
   In short, be nice. ``The overriding frame is apple pie and
motherhood. Treat everybody with dignity and respect,'' said Jered
Stifter, marketing manager at HR consulting firm Hewitt Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Ways to handle layoffs humanely include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Communicate in person. This is the cardinal rule of layoffs.
Leaving a message on someone's home phone or sending an e-mail is
the worst way to go about it. Experts recommend meeting one-on-one
and keeping it simple. ``Just say that unfortunately, for XYZ
reasons, they don't have a job with us anymore,'' Stifter said.
</P>
<P>
   Having cabs waiting to take people away; having security guards
escort them from their desks; packing up their desks for them are
techniques guaranteed to rankle workers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Remember the survivors. ``One of the dangers when you go into
a layoff mode is losing some people you don't want to lose. We
typically suggest to clients: Pay as much attention to the people
you absolutely want to retain as to those who unfortunately will
get laid off,'' said Stifter.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested having senior management identify by name the
folks the firm absolutely wants to retain, then having the chief
executive officer or a senior vice president meet individually with
them to reinforce how important they are to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   One big way to reassure your remaining employees is to treat the
laid-off workers fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to send a message to the survivors: If this were to
happen to you, you too will be protected,'' said Mitchell Marks, an
organizational psychologist based in San Francisco who works with
companies in transition.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't waffle, don't fudge. ``You have to do what you said you
were going to do,'' said Marks. ``It doesn't matter what the
criteria is (for who gets laid off) as much as if you stick to the
criteria. If you say it's going to be seniority, productivity or
performance, you'd better stick to it. It's extremely disruptive if
you say one thing and do another.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Be generous. Companies are not obligated to offer a severance
package, unless a union agreement or other contract covers this
issue. But financial assistance to tide them over is the top thing
workers will want.
</P>
<P>
   The rule of thumb for severance packages is two weeks for every
year of tenure with the company. Giving more is certainly fine, if
you have it. Although under COBRA Compliance Systems Inc.
regulations, employees are guaranteed that they can continue their
medical insurance at the group rate a corporation is charged, and
companies can help even more by continuing to subsidize health
benefits for a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   The company is under no obligation to offer early vesting of
stock options, unless an employee had negotiated that when hired.
But if employees are just weeks away from rounding out a year of
service, allowing that year to vest is another generous thing to
do.
</P>
<P>
   -- Offer emotional support. People being laid off go through the
same stages of grief as someone suffering a bereavement. Providing
individual counseling services and hiring a facilitator to conduct
a meeting where people can vent are steps that can benefit the
laid-off workers and survivors. ``Recognize that people have to let
go of the old before they accept the new,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Provide job-hunt help. ``One of the best things you can do is
say, `We've contacted the following four competitors, and you can
send them your resume,' '' said Leger. ``It's a really positive
message to leave people in terms of your competence as an
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiring an outplacement firm is another traditional approach.
John Challenger, CEO of outplacement firm Challenger, Gray &AMP;
Christmas of Chicago, said his firm has worked with more than 100
laid-off dot-com workers in the past year. It offers individual
counseling, resume writing and design, computerized ad answering
and a database of employers, among other services. The company
declined to say how much it charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
