<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSOLIDATED-RELOCATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCKING COMPANY SEIZES OPPORTUNITY IN BAY AREA REAL ESTATE  MARKET

</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Taking advantage of the Bay Area real estate
run-up, Consolidated Freightways has sold its 2.3-acre Menlo Park,
Calif., headquarters for tens of millions of dollars and will move
to Washington state next month, the company announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Transferring its headquarters to a less-expensive area has a
secondary advantage of helping the trucking company recruit
employees who can't afford to live in the Bay Area, Consolidated
said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Portland, Ore., in 1929, Consolidated moved to Menlo
Park in 1956, paying about $2 million for its offices. The
headquarters, located in a suburban office park, was recently sold
to an unidentified buyer for ``north of $30 million,'' said company
spokesman Mike Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The Menlo Park office's 99 employees, which include chief
executive Pat Blake and other top executives, will move next month
to Vancouver, Wash. The company will also sell a 12-acre Portland
administrative campus and move those 837 workers to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said centralizing its administrative functions is the main
reason for the move, but Bay Area expenses also weighed heavily in
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlocking the tremendous real estate value that has grown
under our Menlo Park property over 40 years makes excellent
financial sense for our shareholders,'' Blake said in a statement.
Profits will be used to build new terminals, he said. Blake was
traveling and could not be reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Consolidated has had difficulty recruiting
administrative assistants to work in Menlo Park, even for healthy
annual wages of $40,000 to $60,000, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also faced problems when it wanted to transfer
middle and upper managers from around the country to work short
stints in Menlo Park. ``We have had managers say they just can't
consider that kind of traumatic move'' because of the high cost of
living, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated was the country's biggest trucking company in the
'60s, but has since been surpassed by several rivals. It is the
country's third-largest ``less-than-truckload'' freight company,
meaning that it carries shipments for multiple customers in the
same truck.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated's performance has been spotty in recent years, with
sales declining slightly in 1998 but then rising to $2.4 billion in
1999. Profits slipped to $7.9 million last year from $52 million in
1998 as the company wrestled with its mix of light and heavy
freight.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SYMANTEC-ACQUISITION-     07-28 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMANTEC-ACQUISITION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SYMANTEC STEPS UP SECURITY WITH ACQUISITION DEAL  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Symantec, the maker of security software for
personal computers, said Thursday that it will acquire corporate
security software company Axent Technologies for $975 million in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is approved by shareholders, it will create a giant
in the computer security software industry serving both consumer
and corporate markets.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed acquisition is designed to expand Symantec's
offering of business products, especially for large corporations,
and allow Axent to grow more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Symantec, based in Cupertino, Calif., is best known as the
manufacturer of Norton AntiVirus software, which protects millions
of personal computers from online attack. Axent of Rockville, Md.,
creates software that defends corporate computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   The combined companies, to be called Symantec, are expected to
take in $1 billion in revenues for the fiscal year ending in March
2001. That would rank the company as among the leaders in the
computer security software industry, along with Check Point
Software Technologies of Redwood City, Calif., and Network
Associates in Santa Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Both the consumer and corporate industries are growing rapidly
as the expansion of Internet commerce and communication creates
greater opportunity for computer virus attacks and snooping.
</P>
<P>
   International Data Corp., a market research and publishing
company in Framingham, Mass., predicts that the consumer and
corporate markets for computer antivirus software, firewalls and
intrusion detection will at least double by 2003 to between $5
billion and $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Prince, an analyst who covers network security, computer
networks and software for Forrester Research, a market research
company in Cambridge, Mass., praised Symantec's acquisition of
Axent. He said that it allows Symantec to offer a broader range of
products to businesses, especially the bigger ones.
</P>
<P>
   However, Prince added that Symantec should be cautious about
expanding too much. He said Axent had previously considered
building and running computer security systems for companies, an
idea that he called a potential ``rat hole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They stand to shoot themselves in the foot if they try to cast
the net too broadly,'' Prince said.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Hodges, president of McAfee, a computer antivirus
softwaremaker and Symantec competitor, gloated over the news of the
acquisition and predicted that his company will gain an advantage.
He said that it will ``defocus'' Symantec as it tries to integrate
Axent employees with its own and make the company too big to react
to a rapidly changing marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that we are very happy that Symantec is doing
this,'' said Hodges, whose company is part of Network Associates.
``They will execute less well.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Gail Hamilton, a senior vice president for Symantec's
business software division, said that her company's acquisition
will create one of the biggest groups of computer security experts
in the world. It will allow the two companies to grow more rapidly
and create better products.
</P>
<P>
   The deal put a 67 percent premium on Axent's stock as of closing
price Wednesday. Axent shareholders will get one-half of a Symantec
share, valued at $31.84.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, shares of Symantec fell to $50.25 from $63.69. Axent's
shares increased from $19.06 to $24.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
