<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5345 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LAYOFFSIDE2-REHIRE-SF     07-28 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAYOFFSIDE2-REHIRE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MOST LAID-OFF TECH WORKERS DON'T STAY JOBLESS FOR LONG  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ No one likes the sound of a startup's dreams
shattering into little pieces or the slow gurgling of a dot-com
whose stock price is sinking.
</P>
<P>
   For Jerry McLaughlin and other employers in desperate staffing
straits, though, it's an opportune time to move quickly and grab
laid-off workers before they find other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   To lure tech workers laid off from nearby startups, McLaughlin
hung a bright yellow sign in the window of his customer relations
company, User Interface, which said: ``Your dot.com in trouble? Get
in here!''
</P>
<P>
   Other Bay Area recruiters use more traditional methods such as
calling struggling companies' human resources managers or
contacting individual workers. Some even post job openings on Web
sites such as StartUpFailures.com, where employees of failed
ventures congregate.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of job search has paid off. FamilyWonder.com, a video
and toy e-tailer, has interviewed former employees of defunct
companies Petstore.com, Reel.com and Toysmart.com in recent months,
and gotten about 15 percent of its new hires from those companies,
said founder Jonathan Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we hear about XYZ Co. not doing well, we've contacted HR
departments and said, `We have these job openings, and we just
wanted to let you know we can help,' '' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies compete fiercely for access to laid-off employees
before their last day at work. When Hollywood Entertainment said
last month that it would shut its Emeryville Reel.com division,
human resources received inquiries from about 50 hopeful companies
in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Entertainment HR executive Michelle Van Hoose invited
several of the earliest and most aggressive hiring companies to
come in and meet employees.
</P>
<P>
   One East Bay dot-com brought in a keg of beer to convince
Reel.com employees to stay after work and talk, Van Hoose said.
Blockbuster.com offered to pay for a job fair including other
companies, but Van Hoose turned them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids didn't want it,'' Van Hoose said, referring to
Reel.com's mostly young staff. ``All they wanted to do is take the
summer off.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, says headhunter Derrek Milan, is that once a layoff
is reported by the news media, it's often too late to land the
engineers and other valuable employees who have already found new
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters try to stay ahead of the curve by subscribing to
insider e-mail newsletters detailing each week's layoffs and
checking gossip Web sites regularly. But beating other recruiters
requires sniffing out company problems before the layoff, Milan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a company pulls back and puts off its IPO, we react to
it,'' said Milan, whose recruiting firm, Monday Technology
Solutions, has gotten half its job candidates from near-death
companies in the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   One tactic recruiters employ is searching online resume
databases such as Monster.com or Dice.com for resumes from specific
local startups.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any given day you see three resumes from one company's
employees, you gotta wonder what's going on,'' said David LaVigni,
staffing director for the tech news Web site ZDNet.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet tries to be vigilant about anticipating layoffs, but the
company still missed a downsizing that happened right under its
nose, said LaVigni.
</P>
<P>
   When Linuxcare, one of six companies that share ZDNet's Townsend
Street building, reduced its staff by an estimated 70 people in
May, ZDNet didn't hear about it until the cutbacks were public
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have put a sign in the deli downstairs if we had
known earlier,'' LaVigni said.
</P>
<P>
   He's considering assigning interns the task of studying
vulnerable companies' quarterly reports and other financial news,
looking for cracks in the armor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be part of our strategy in this job market,''
LaVigni said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
