<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-KENNEDY-HOSTAGES-1STL     07-28 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-HOSTAGES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN HOLDS PILOT HOSTAGE AT KENNEDY AIRPORT; PASSENGERS ESCAPE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout; subs byline)  By ANDY NEWMAN and SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man with a handgun walked quietly into the cockpit
of a National Airlines jet at Kennedy International Airport about
10 on Thursday night and took the pilot and co-pilot hostage, then
released the pilot an hour or so later with a list of demands, the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey said.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the man with the gun heading for the cockpit, the
passengers rushed off the plane and all escaped unharmed,
passengers and Greg Trevor, a Port Authority spokesman, said. Many
passengers on the plane, which was to have left for Las Vegas,
described scenes of pandemonium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat down, got buckled up and the next thing I know everybody
was screaming,'' said Misty Nichols, 27, a nurse from Carmel, N.Y.,
who was leaving for a vacation. Then, she said, people started
rushing to get off the plane. A little girl next to her was knocked
over, she said, but an older man picked her up and helped her.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said she later tried to retrieve some of her belongings,
but someone yelled, ``Get off the plane _ your life is more
important than your stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Weiss, another passenger, told CNN that he was sitting
near the front of the first-class section when he ``heard a voice,
a very low voice, saying `Be quiet.''' He said that he looked up
and saw ``a dark-skinned man in his late 20s with a 10- to 12-inch
gun in his right hand, walking very briskly toward the cockpit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked into the cockpit and closed the door,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   The man was wearing a white long-sleeved shirt and did not
appear to be an airline employee, at least not one in uniform,
Weiss and some other passengers said.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently made his way onto the plane simply by running past
security workers, Trevor of the Port Authority said.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers go through a metal detector right before the enter
the jetway.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the gunman pulled his gun out right before the
metal detector, told a group of elderly people to get out of his
way and boarded the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after all the passengers left the plane, several police
officers with ``big guns'' boarded, Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   The flight, National Airlines Flight 19, a Boeing 757, was
scheduled to take off at 9:30 p.m. but did not begin boarding until
after 10 p.m., passengers said.
</P>
<P>
   One passenger, who was not identified, told ABC News that the
man held the gun down in front of him with both hands to make it
clear to passengers that he was armed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to be quiet,'' the passenger said. I grabbed my
friends and we just piled off the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Another passegner, Frank Clark, 30, a computer engineer from
Brooklyn, was in first class and had just been served a drink when
he heard the commotion and saw the gunman enter the cockpit. The
passenger sitting next to Clark said, ``The guy's got a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all it took,'' Clark said. ``It was a road race from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the passengers appeared to panic, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy sitting next to me really tripped me out because he
kept his drink,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   National, formed a year ago and based in Las Vegas, is a small
airline, with a fleet of 11 Boeing 757-200's flying nonstop to Las
Vegas to eight other cities. But it is growing fast. It began
turning a profit in March, after only 10 months in the air,
becoming one of the fastest new airlines in history to make money,
according to Aviation Daily, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   National runs four flights a day from Kennedy Airport to Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The airline itself declined to comment on the crisis. A man who
answered the phone at National Airlines's toll-free reservation
number said, ``We have no comment and no numbers for you to call,''
then hung up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
