<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5348 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LAYOFFS-DOTCOM-SFCHRO     07-28 1542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAYOFFS-DOTCOM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DOT-COMS HANDLE LAYOFFS THE OLD-FASHIONED WAY  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID  
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Now that the Internet bubble has burst and
dozens of companies are laying off employees, are dot-coms doing a
better job of handing out pink slips than brick-and-mortar
companies?
</P>
<P>
   Not really.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that said they could reinvent the wheel for doing
business are, at best, following well-worn tire tracks when it
comes to reductions in force. At worst, they're treating cast-off
workers like spam mail that they can't wait to delete.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing anecdotally when dot-com people get laid off
is it's generally been handled well but not great,'' said Jacques
Leger, a managing consultant in San Francisco with human resources
consultancy Watson Wyatt Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many companies have communicated poorly. When they lay off 20
out of 100 people in the company, you'd think they could do a
better job with the other 80. Severance packages tend not to be
planned as directly or clearly as at big companies going through
massive layoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs continue to mount. According to outplacement firm
Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas of Chicago, more than 7,500 dot-com
workers have been laid off nationwide this year, almost 2,200 of
them just in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   There are only so many ways to tell people they are out of a
job. Employers can soften the blow by providing a cushion of money,
a shoulder to cry on and a hand in finding a new job. But many
fledgling startups have neither the financial resources, the time
nor the inclination to offer much practical support.
</P>
<P>
   Will Dunkak, 48, left a job with an ``old economy'' firm _ he
was a senior financial analyst at Prudential Securities _ in
October to go to a San Mateo, Calif., startup, PrivateExpress.com,
as business development manager.
</P>
<P>
   He was impressed by the company's business plan and technology:
It was trying to be the FedEx of the Internet, providing a digital
way to deliver huge documents across the country instantaneously
and securely.
</P>
<P>
   On July 5, the day after a four-day holiday weekend,
PrivateExpress called two meetings for its two dozen U.S.
employees. In one conference room, eight people were told they were
being let go; in the other room, the attendees were told they would
remain. Dunkak was in the laid-off group.
</P>
<P>
   PrivateExpress paid the laid-off workers for their outstanding
vacation time. Dunkak said the company chairman had assured workers
that a severance package would be forthcoming in a couple of weeks.
After numerous phone calls, Dunkak said he was told that some
severance money might be available in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're starting to play games,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it would accelerate vesting for the
laid-off workers as if they had worked a full year, according to
Dunkak. He was 3-1/2 months away from completing a full year, which
would have given him 25 percent of his stock options. He doesn't
know if PrivateExpress will make good on that promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened so far has been nothing more than lip service.
They haven't come through on anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Levy, PrivateExpress chairman, said he felt the company had
been straightforward in dealing with laid-off workers. He declined
to discuss specifically how it handled severance and vesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are private personnel and payroll matters that no one
inside a company in their right mind would ever discuss publicly,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; `Reasonably Humane'
</P>
<P>
   At some other firms, laid-off employees felt they were better
treated, at least on the financial side.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's MedicaLogic/Medscape gave two months' salary, plus pay
for unused vacation time, to all 110 of the workers it cut from its
San Francisco office, even those who had been with the company just
a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were reasonably humane,'' said a former
MedicaLogic/Medscape employee, who was laid off in June. ``It
seemed like they went out of their way to give us a decent
severance for laying us off wholesale.''
</P>
<P>
   The company offered an additional six weeks' pay to employees
who agreed not to participate in any potential class-action suits
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Severance pay was also ample at San Francisco's Healthshop,
which laid off most of its 65 employees in April before being sold
to rival HealthCentral.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a quite generous severance package,'' said Francine
Schwartz, who was a writer at Healthshop. ``I'd been there less
than six months, and I received four weeks severance.''
</P>
<P>
   COBRA Bite
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes the money just isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   Violet.com, an 18-person online boutique in San Francisco,
closed in April when it couldn't land new funding. Up until the
last minute, the founders were conducting ``a full-court press'' to
seek additional funding or a merger partner, according to Karen
Wickre, Violet.com vice president and executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks before they ran out of money, they told
employees that they still hoped to make a deal but wanted to give
them a heads-up. No deal came through, and when the company closed,
there was just enough money to pay employees for their unused
vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Wickre found to her dismay that COBRA, the federal law
guaranteeing that terminated workers can continue their insurance
coverage through their company's health plan, does not apply when a
company goes out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned the following surprising fact: There's no COBRA
benefits if there's no group plan. There's no group plan if the
company folds,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lesard, co-author of the book ``NetSlaves: True Tales of
Working the Web'' and co-founder of the NetSlaves Web site, said he
thinks companies on the verge of extinction could handle things
differently. ``These companies will go and go and go until there's
no gas left in the tank. When it would be time to give employees
some severance, they can't do it because there's no gas left,
rather than stopping earlier and saying `We're not going to make
it, let's save something for severance.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some ways companies can support laid-off employees don't cost
money. For example, they can use their networks to help laid-off
workers find new jobs. SameDay.com, which is backed by IdeaLab, a
Pasadena, Calif., startup incubator, contacted other IdeaLab
companies to try to find new jobs for the dozen workers it laid off
last month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it had an in-house recruiter assist the employees,
according to Erin Mills, a marketing associate at the Los Angeles
firm.
</P>
<P>
   But many dot-com firms are so new, and their executives are so
inexperienced, that they don't have a sense of how to handle
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the people who run these businesses have been on an
economic upswing their whole life,'' said Leger, the HR consultant.
``The chase has been about acquiring talent, not letting it go.
They look at (having to lay people off) and go, `Holy hell, what do
I do now?'''
</P>
<P>
   That can result in poor communications that increase unease
among remaining workers. Leger told of one company that shrank from
240 employees to 150, without ever discussing the situation with
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't do anything dramatic; (they) used some attrition,
closed down some projects. It was unplanned and unstructured in
appearance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Leger, the company neglected to reassure the
remaining workers, even as they saw colleagues disappear around
them. ``They never transmitted to people the message that they
shouldn't panic and run,'' he said, noting that a more-experienced
organization would have handled the situation better.
</P>
<P>
   No Time to Mourn
</P>
<P>
   The go-go pace of Internet time means companies are in a rush to
cut costs and move on. ``Traditional companies are likely to
realize that surviving employees have got to go through a mourning
period,'' said Mitchell Marks, a San Francisco organizational
psychologist who works with firms in transition. ``They might
sponsor certain events: venting meetings where people can talk
through what they've lost. In younger companies, it's more, `The
pain is over, let's get on with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to stock options, companies generally are under no
obligation to laid-off workers. Stock options usually are granted
over a period of time, with one-quarter vesting each year for four
years, for example. Some companies have accelerated vesting so
laid-off employees get vested as if they have completed that year
of service.
</P>
<P>
   But those stock options may not be worth anything. The markets
are not currently receptive to new dot-com offerings and dot-coms
that already went public are largely trading underwater.
</P>
<P>
   For people who have worked 70-hour weeks in hopes of cashing in
big-time, this reality can be traumatic.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Kaye, a San Francisco psychologist, said he has seen
this among clients. ``Their expectations were that they'd find gold
in these dot-com hills. Some have sacrificed quite a bit in terms
of personal life, emotional commitment to the company. If they
don't get vested, they feel as if everything they've sacrificed was
for naught.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
