<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5351 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-28 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS TALK IS GAINING URGENCY AT AMAZON.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many years from now, Amazon.com may become famous as the company
that wrote the book on e-commerce but couldn't survive long enough
to prosper from its own lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The company this week posted yet another big loss, which was
more than double last year's second-quarter loss despite an 84
percent surge in sales for the same period. During its five-year
history, the conventional accounting wisdom on Wall Street puts the
company's cumulative losses at over $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The validity of this stupendous number has been challenged by
some interesting financial analysis, however, most recently in The
New Yorker. ``Financial Page'' columnist James Surowiecki said the
actual cash loss has been $60 million at best, and possibly $130
million at worst, using more conservative accounting methods.
</P>
<P>
   Surowiecki said much of the $1 billion figure usually cited is
due to paper losses from ``goodwill charges'' incurred during
acquisitions of other companies. What has also helped Amazon.com,
he said, is the company's ability to control inventory tightly,
which has enabled it to keep operating costs down.
</P>
<P>
   If this is indeed the accounting reality, it lends substantial
credibility to the company's claims that it still has plenty of
cash available to ride out its loss-ridden early years long enough
to generate the profits critical to its eventual survival.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, when measured by its sales, it has been the most
incredible success story of the young e-tailing age. This explains
why stock investors until recently treated it as the retail phenom
it had become.
</P>
<P>
   Contrarians, however, kept claiming its lofty stock price
couldn't last unless the company began to show signs of becoming
profitable. Devotees of new-economy analysis demurred, saying that
as long as sales were expanding, earnings could wait. Everyone,
they said, understood profits would materialize after Amazon got
through its difficult start-up stage.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking of the old-economy disciples is being vindicated of
late, though, as the once high-flying Amazon stock has thudded to
earth. Even before the latest bad news, the stock had been off
nearly 70 percent from its 52-week high, and the latest
discouraging word sent it lower.
</P>
<P>
   The question increasingly facing fans of Amazon.com is whether
the company can survive its youthful growing pains long enough to
emerge as an enterprise profitable enough to justify the bets made
by its long-term stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   Even its boss has begun to understand the need to shed the loser
image. After the latest red ink was revealed, Chief Executive Jeff
Bezos said the company had focused more on the need for earnings.
Analysts saw this comment as reflecting a significant change in a
corporate philosophy heretofore heedless of the need for profits.
</P>
<P>
   For investors who have kept the faith, The New Yorker analysis
was heartening. Surowiecki noted that Amazon.com's early history
had a remarkable resemblance to Wal-Mart's. Amazon.com in 2001, he
said, should look a lot like the Wal-Mart of 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The question mark for Amazon.com, he said, is not so much a
matter of having enough money to get through the lean times, but
whether it can retain the loyalty of its customers after achieving
profitability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
