<HEADER>
A5353 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ADS-POLITICS-KAN &LR;      07-28 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADS-POLITICS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POLITICAL AD SEASON IS HEATING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get ready. Get set. Brace yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   A dazzling cacophony of points and counterpoints, nice-guy
images and Darth Vader contrasts is beginning to emerge from your
TV.
</P>
<P>
   They're political ads, and they're aimed at getting you to do
one thing:
</P>
<P>
   Vote for Candidate X over Candidate Y.
</P>
<P>
   And with more competitive races than usual and more money in the
system than ever, expect more ads _ a whole lot more _ than before.
That means more talking heads, more confusing claims, more
politicians speaking/lecturing/preaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tsunami,'' said Chuck Hatfield, campaign
manager for Jay Nixon, the 1998 Missouri Democratic Senate
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a voter to do?
</P>
<P>
   Well believe it or not, ads can teach you some things about the
candidates. So why not arm yourself with a few tools so you can
evaluate the ads during the long haul between now and Election Day?
</P>
<P>
   You'll need them. Campaigns usually try to run each of their ads
so that a typical viewer sees a spot at least 10 times on various
TV shows. In a race like this year's U.S. Senate contest in
Missouri between Democrat Mel Carnahan and Republican John
Ashcroft, each candidate will run, say, eight to 10 different ads.
</P>
<P>
   That means Mr. or Mrs. Typical Viewer will see 80 to 100 ads per
candidate. That's 200 ads for the race, and that's only one race.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis, Missouri's largest TV market, already has been hit by
a tidal wave of political ads from Missouri candidates for U.S.
Senate and governor. In Kansas City, the first Missouri ads began
this week. They feature the candidates for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Rule One for viewing political ads: Don't make up your mind
about how to vote in a race based on a single ad. Shading the truth
is, of course, what many of these spots do best.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, media critic Norman Soloman suggests that when it comes
to political ads, you should believe nothing. Zip. Nada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisements really are an obstacle course that voters need
to run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another view comes from G.R. Boynton, a University of Iowa
political scientist and an expert on political advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few political ads are outright lies,'' he said. ``But
they are misleading. They take statements out of context. In that
sense, they distort.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider two hard-hitting ads that recently ran in St. Louis
that do exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, Mel Carnahan tried a state government takeover of
your health care,'' claimed an ad sponsored by the Missouri
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Counters a Missouri Democratic Party spot: ``Senator John
Ashcroft's record on seniors' issues is one of the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. The comment about Carnahan is an exaggeration
aimed at frightening voters. The criticism aimed at Ashcroft comes
from a group that even Democrats have criticized as one prone to
``scaring the bejesus out of seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   But sitting at home, it's hard to make those judgments. The
tricky thing about political ads is that they enjoy a special
freedom. Thanks to the First Amendment, they can pretty much claim
anything, true or not. Hawking beer or cars or potato chips falls
into a different category where a degree of truthfulness is
required.
</P>
<P>
   Political ads also tend to be nasty, unpleasant little
exchanges. They are, in a word, negative. And they are negative
because that tactic works.
</P>
<P>
   Voters hate negative ads. Still, they remember them, Democratic
consultant Jill Buckley once said in Congressional Quarterly Weekly
Report. ``The problem with positive (ads) is that you have to run
it again and again and again to make it stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``With negative (ads), the poll numbers will move in three or
four days.''
</P>
<P>
   Negative or not, the power of advertising is not in doubt.
Studies show that one of the best ways to predict the winner of a
congressional race is to check which candidate spends the most on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the power of the TV medium has been very much
in evidence in Kansas and Missouri. In 1998, for example, 3rd
District congressional contender Dennis Moore's use of an ad where
he played his guitar was viewed as a big hit. It cut through the
clutter of other ads and made Moore, who won the election, as
something more than just a politician.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Snowbarger, Moore's Republican opponent, aired just three
ads, none of which revealed anything about Snowbarger the person.
That was a mistake, his camp admitted later.
</P>
<P>
   With so many campaigns vying for attention this year, expect the
unexpected. Candidates, particularly those who aren't well-known,
may take more risks than usual in their TV ads, said David
Israelite, political director for the Republican National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're likely to see more gimmicks and pageantry,'' he said,
``than at a professional wrestling match.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
