<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTES COLUMN: I WAS WRONG ABOUT SCIOSCIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Pres-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I snickered when the Angels hired Mike Scioscia as their manager
last November.
</P>
<P>
   I figured they did so for no other reason than he was willing to
work for a mere $350,000 pittance.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Mike Scioscia wasn't exactly a proven managerial
commodity, guiding the Albuquerque Dukes to a 65-74 record last
summer that left Dodgers management so unimpressed that it gladly
accepted Scioscia's resignation from the organization at the end of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, what could Mike Scioscia do with the Angels that, say,
Terry Collins couldn't do?
</P>
<P>
   Well, as it turns out, plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Scioscia, despite a Pick Your Starter &AMP; Pray pitching
staff, has kept the Angels over .500 throughout the season and in
contention in the AL West Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wrong, Mike, you certainly turned out to be a much
better manager than I thought you'd be,'' I said late Thursday
afternoon to Scioscia, who was seated in his office in the Angels'
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, and if we were to go on an eight-game losing streak,
you'd start writing I'm a lousy manager,'' smiled Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   Not now.
</P>
<P>
   Not after the way Mike Scioscia has brought desperately needed
stability into an Angels clubhouse that imploded a year ago with
Terry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Not after the way Mike Scioscia has managed to keep the Angels
competitive despite DL injuries to veteran pitchers (Ken Hill, Kent
Bottenfield, Kent Mercker and Tim Belcher) and despite having to
rely on an array of untested young pitchers (Seth Etherton, Scott
Schoeneweis, Brian Cooper and Jarrod Washburn).
</P>
<P>
   Not after the way Mike Scioscia has his players performing with
intensity on a regular basis and even taking batting practice when
they aren't obligated to, which was the case Thursday after the
team had returned from Texas early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see these players go out there on their own and hit when
they didn't have to shows me how much they want to win,'' said
Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn credits Scioscia with the dramatic change in the
Angels' attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no garbage on this team,'' said the first baseman
before the Angels faced the Chicago White Sox at Edison Field.
``Everyone is pulling for everyone else, and Mike is responsible
for that. He's a very positive person who knows how to get the most
out of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also sees everything out there on the field. Mike
definitely knows baseball, and the players have come to respect
that knowledge and the leadership he has provided us.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia says he's enjoying his first season with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you this job has given me a new-found respect for the
people who have done it over the years,'' he said. ``It's
tremendously time-consuming and very demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes up basically your whole life. You have to have more
than a love for baseball to be a manager. You have to have a
passion for it. It's not easy. There are new challenges facing you
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing Mike Scioscia is that the Angels aren't
going to go out and get a Denny Neagle like the New York Yankees
did or a Curt Shilling like the Arizona Diamondbacks did.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to take the group of guys I have and win with
them,'' said Scioscia. ``I can't worry about things I have no
control over.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia has been making the 140-mile round trip commute from
his Thousand Oaks residence to Anaheim for the Angels home games,
but is renting a place in Newport Beach for the next month. ...
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, on the hit-crazed Darin Erstad: ``He's definitely been
our MVP. You ask any player in the clubhouse, and he'd tell you the
same thing''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have an exceptional public address announcer in David
Courtney, who also handles such chores for the Kings. Courtney was
the one doing PA duties in the Disney movie ``Angels In The
Outfield.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure it's a mere coincidence that the Seattle Mariners
are in first place after bringing back Long Beach's Bob Harrison in
the offseason as a scout after a 14-year absence from the team. ...
</P>
<P>
   I thought either the Dodgers or San Francisco Giants were
capable of dethroning the Arizona Diamondbacks in the NL West
Division until Wednesday. That's when the Diamondbacks assured
themselves of another division title and a probable postseason
showdown against the Atlanta Braves when they acquired Curt
Shilling. Shilling and Randy Johnson in the same pitching rotation?
Why couldn't we have Jerry Colangelo as a baseball owner in
Southern California?. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers sure did go out and get a proven macho tough guy in
Ismael Valdes to fill a desperate starting pitching void, didn't
they? ...
</P>
<P>
   If I were voting today for the NL's Most Valuable Player, I'd
cast my ballot for the Dodgers' Gary Sheffield. ...
</P>
<P>
   He might not be Mr. Sunshine to the media, but I'm not sure
there is a better pitcher in the NL than Kevin Brown. And you can
be sure his popularity among teammates soared the other day in
Denver when he plunked the Colorado Rockies' Todd Helton in
retaliation for Sheffield getting drilled earlier in the game. ...
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State's very own version of Martha Stewart, the
lovely Dede Rossi, reports that the recent Jewels of the Night gig
raised a record $150,000 for the school's athletic scholarship
fund. Incredibly, a dinner with me at Phil Trani's Restaurant was
auctioned off for a mind-boggling, sanity-defying $550. Two couples
whose names won't be revealed to spare them public ridicule shared
in the bid. ...
</P>
<P>
   Gee, I can't wait to go to the National Sports Collectors show
now going on at the Anaheim Convention Center through Sunday to pay
Johnny Bench $125 to sign a jersey, or Magic Johnson $180 to sign a
basketball, or Reggie Jackson $220 to sign a bat.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, on second thought, I think I might blow $10 to have
one of my all-time idols, Honky Tony Man, ink his John Hancock on a
piece of paper for me. Once one of Southern California's biggest
athletic heroes, Roman Gabriel is also charging a mere $10 for his
autograph, a reflection of how fleeting fame can be. ...
</P>
<P>
   The fight publicist, Honest John Beyrooty, called excitedly from
Phoenix ON Thursday to inform me that ravaged, over-the-hill,
38-year-old Julio Cesar Chavez has worked himself into the best
shape of his career for Saturday night's Showtime match against
Kostya Tszyu at Veterans Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   So what?
</P>
<P>
   Who can ever forget the marvelous shape Muhammad Ali got into
for his ill-starred match against Larry Holmes?
</P>
<P>
   Chavez should have retired after quitting against Oscar De La
Hoya in September of 1988, should have retired after losing a
10-round decision against Willy Wise last October, and will retire
after the rugged, hard-punching Tszyu beats him up in their WBC
super lightweight title match that I wish were never made. ...
</P>
<P>
   Serving a one-year suspension for violating baseball's
substance-abuse policy, Darryl Strawberry recently purchased a
membership to Trapeze II, a swingers club in Ft. Lauderdale.
According to Sports Illustrated, Strawberry, who wrote the book
``Recovering Life'' with his wife last year, has left with a
different woman in each of his visits. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The McDonnell Show, featuring Press-Telegram columnist Doug
Krikorian and radio personality Joe McDonnell, can be heard Sunday
night between 9 p.m. and midnight PDT on KABC-AM (790). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
