<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIMELSTOB UPSETS PHILIPPOUSSIS
</HEADLINE>
 
Eds: Leads with night match (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hometown hero Justin Gimelstob pulled off the
biggest upset of the Mercedes-Benz Cup, knocking off top-seeded
Mark Philippoussis 3-6, 7-6 (7-5), 7-6 (7-3) in Thursday's second
round at UCLA's L.A. Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Unseeded Gimelstob, formerly of UCLA, had lost to Philippoussis
in two previous meetings, but he got the best of the hard-hitting
Australian in key situations.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a matchup for purists. Long rallies were few and far
between as both employed a similar combination of overpowering
serves and aggressive passing shots. It was more like a boxing
match than anything Bill Tilden would have conjured up.
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis got off to a better start, surging ahead 4-1, then
ending his 6-3 first-set victory with consecutive aces, the last a
136-mph crowd-pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   But Gimelstob wasn't particularly intimidated. He rebounded by
holding service six consecutive times to force a tiebreaker, then
rallying from a two-point deficit in the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   SURPRISING RESULTS: The media has been consistently focusing on
the missing persons of this event, starting on Monday when
top-seeded Andre Agassi, by far the tournament's biggest name,
withdrew because of a lingering back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Wednesday, Davis Cup player Vince Spadea dropped out
(overhydration) and Marcelo Rios was defaulted for cussing out an
official.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament director Bob Kramer might be reeling, but he's doing
his best not to show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are actually working out better than I expected,''
Kramer said. ``(Before the tournament started), ticket sales were
up 30 percent from last year and we're having some nice weather.
Our plan is to have 46 good matches and so far the tennis has been
good and exceeded our expectations. That's the way things are; you
might want to ask me again later in the week.''
</P>
<P>
   CRAZY FROM THE HEAT? Wayne Ferreira needed almost 2 hours _ in
100-degee heat _ to defeat Paradorn Srichaphan on Wednesday
afternoon. Nevertheless Ferreira took time immediately afterward to
hit a few shots with youngsters from the Southern California Tennis
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a nice experience for the kids and it exposes the
SCTA programs to all the spectators,'' spokesman Toby Zwikel said.
</P>
<P>
   PASSING SHOT: Defending Mercedes champion Pete Sampras, who
decided not to participate this year, was spotted tossing a
football with some the UCLA football players at the practice field
ajacent to the tennis stadium.
</P>
<P>
   THAT WAS QUICK: Jason Stoltenberg of Australia and Orlando,
Fla., needed just 50 minutes to eliminate Goichi Motomura 6-1, 6-2
in the second round. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
