<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-HOSTAGES-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN FREES HOSTAGE PILOTS AFTER ESCAPE OF PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   By ANDY NEWMAN and SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man carried a handgun onto a National Airlines jet
at Kennedy International Airport at 10:15 on Thursday night,
shushed the passengers and walked calmly into the cockpit, taking
the pilot and co-pilot hostage for two hours, passengers and the
authorities said. Neither the seven crew members nor the 143
passengers were injured in the incident, the Port Authority of New
York and New Jersey said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman released the pilot around midnight with a list of
demands, including his wish to speak to someone from the Argentine
Consulate, the police said. An off-duty officer at the Argentine
Consulate, Beatriz Bustos, said that a police officer called and
asked her to put him in touch with the Argentine ambassador,
Guillermo McCough. She said she passed the message on, but had no
further information.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman released the co-pilot around 1 a.m., the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the man with the gun heading for the cockpit, all
the passengers rushed off the plane and escaped unharmed,
passengers and Greg Trevor, a Port Authority spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1:30 on Friday morning, the authorities said, the gunman
was alone on the plane, a Boeing 757 that was to have left for Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Many passengers described scenes of pandemonium. ``I sat down,
got buckled up and the next thing I know everybody was screaming,''
said Misty Nichols, 27, a nurse from Carmel, N.Y., who was leaving
for a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she said, people started rushing to get off the plane. A
little girl next to her was knocked over, she said, but an older
man picked her up and helped her.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said she later tried to retrieve some of her belongings,
but someone yelled, ``Get off the plane _ your life is more
important than your stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Weiss, another passenger, told CNN that he was sitting
near the front of the first-class section when he ``heard a voice,
a very low voice, saying `Be quiet.''' He said that he looked up
and saw ``a dark-skinned man in his late 20s with a 10- to 12-inch
gun in his right hand, walking very briskly toward the cockpit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked into the cockpit and closed the door,'' Weiss said.
The man was wearing a white long-sleeved shirt and did not appear
to be an airline employee, at least not one in uniform, Mr. Weiss
and some other passengers said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman apparently made his way onto the plane, at Gate 33 of
Terminal 4W, simply by running past security workers, Mr. Trevor of
the Port Authority said.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers said they had to pass through only one metal detector
before boarding the plane, and it was located right before the
jetway.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the suspect pulled his gun out right before the
metal detector, told four elderly people to get out of his way and
boarded the plane.
</P>
<P>
   CNN reported that a National Airlines spokesman had said the
gunman was a ticketed passenger on the flight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moments after all the passengers left the plane, several police
officers with ``big guns'' boarded, Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   The flight, National Airlines Flight 19, a Boeing 757, was
scheduled to take off at 9:30 p.m. but did not begin boarding until
after 10 p.m., passengers said.
</P>
<P>
   One passenger, who was not identified, told ABC News that the
man held the gun down in front of him with both hands to make it
clear to passengers that he was armed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to be quiet,'' the passenger said. I grabbed my
friends and we just piled off the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Another passenger, Frank Clark, 30, a computer engineer from
Brooklyn, was in first class and had just been served a drink when
he heard the commotion and saw the gunman enter the cockpit. The
passenger sitting next to Clark said, ``The guy's got a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all it took,'' Clark said. ``It was a road race from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the passengers appeared to panic, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy sitting next to me really tripped me out because he
kept his drink,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that airline employees and security personnel at the
terminal seemed completely baffled by the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passengers were running down the jetway, and the two
airline people at the ticket counter were bugged out,'' he said.
``They had no idea what to do. There was security guy was waving
people towards an exit, the other one was just standing there like
he just steppped on a rake.''
</P>
<P>
   National, formed a year ago and based in Las Vegas, is a small
airline, with a fleet of 11 Boeing 757-200's flying nonstop between
Las Vegas and eight other cities. But it is growing fast.
</P>
<P>
   It began turning a profit in March, after only 10 months in the
air, becoming one of the fastest new airlines in history to make
money, according to Aviation Daily, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   National operates four flights a day from Kennedy Airport to Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The airline itself declined to comment on the crisis. But CNN
reported that a National Airlines spokesman had said the gunman was
a ticketed passenger on the flight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
