<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ (Caracas, Venezuela) _ He promised a
revolution, and he has kept his word. Since being swept into power
here 18 months ago, Hugo Chavez has uprooted every institution,
assaulted every elite group and derided every orthodoxy with the
unrelenting combativeness of the army paratrooper he used to be. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT10,11) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GREENHOUSE-GAS (Undated) _ Scientists have found rising
concentrations of a newly identified gas in the air that traps heat
more effectively than all other known greenhouse gases, the dozens
of compounds released by industry and the burning of fuels that act
like a greenhouse roof and may be warming the global climate. By
Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DNA-TESTS (Los Angeles) _ Prosecutors in southern
California plan to offer free DNA tests to some inmates, which may
overturn their convictions. San Diego County prosecutors have been
reviewing the cases of about 560 inmates to determine whether DNA
tests developed since their convictions can link biological
evidence from a crime scene to someone other than the person
convicted. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE (New York) _ Statistics released by the New York City
Police Department show a marked increase in disciplinary actions
against police officers over the past three years, which the
department says demonstrates increased vigilance in punishing
misconduct. Critics contend that the department has manipulated the
numbers to avoid federal oversight. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PAIN (Undated) _ Rats, when hurt as infants, stay more
sensitive to pain into adulthood. Experts say this may have
implications for pain treatment in neonatal wards. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-PLATFORM (Philadelphia) _ The proposed Republican
platform would drop several of the more hard-edged conservative
positions adopted four years ago _ like calling for the abolition
of the Department of Education _ and transform much of the
document's tone to reflect the ``compassionate conservatism'' of
Gov. George W. Bush. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Austin, Texas) _ A look behind the scenes at the
process that resulted in the selection of Dick Cheney as George W.
Bush's running mate. By Frank Bruni and Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-VOTE-VOICES (Evanston, Ill.) _ Interviews with voters in
this diverse, middle-class suburb in a swing state show that people
are still skeptical and wary of the presidential candidates. In the
absence of a single urgent issue, voters are sizing up candidates
as managers, stewards and leaders worthy, or not, of respect. By
Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONFIDENTIAL-SALARIES (Undated) _ The job market may be
extraordinarily employee-friendly these days, but that does not
necessarily mean you get to tell colleagues about your pay, perks
and bonuses. Some managers still warn employees not to discuss pay,
under penalty of dismissal. And every so often, one makes good on
the threat. By Mary Williams Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   AUDITORS-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ Arthur Levitt, the chairman
of the Securities and Exchange Commission, wants to end his term by
enacting new rules to increase the independence of auditors from
their corporate clients. ``This is,'' Levitt said near the end of a
long day of public hearings, ``a cultural change we are talking
about.'' By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-AD-COLUMN (Washington) _ In what both sides hailed as a
big step in online privacy protection, the government reached
agreement Thursday with a group of Internet advertisers on how they
will glean information from Web surfers and what they will do with
it. By David Stout
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Gail Collins reviews the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Thomas L. Friedman argues that it's
time for Yasser Arafat to make some decisions in the Middle East
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-NASHVILLE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ I wouldn't know a Gibson
from a Stratocaster. My favorite guitarists are Django Reinhardt,
Eddie Lang and Andres Segovia, and none of them, as far as I know,
ever played a single note at the Grand Ole Opry. That could cast a
rather long shadow, I suppose, over my qualifications as a guide to
Music City, USA, except that there is a lot more than picking and
fiddling, a lot more than ballads of love and loss, in Nashville's
past, present and future _ especially its future. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DINNER-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews the
revival of ``The Man Who Came to Dinner,'' at the American Airlines
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-OUTDOOR-SCULPTURE (New York) _ When it comes to outdoor
sculpture in New York City this summer, the animal kingdom seems to
have walked off with the main prizes. For quality and sheer size
there is Jeff Koons' ``Puppy,'' a 43-foot-tall flower-covered
sculpture in the shape of a West Highland terrier. For quantity,
ubiquity, relentless aw-shucks hokeyness and stupidity at toxic
levels, the prize goes hoofs-down to ``Cow Parade,'' a herd of
nearly 500 life-size Fiberglas heifers. Even without these two
unusual occurrences, the summer's outdoor sculpture offerings cover
a great range, especially if you stretch your definition of public
sculpture. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   MONGOLIA-RELIGIOUS-ART (New York) _ Mongolia, the land of
Genghis Khan, windswept steppes and tough ponies, is seldom
associated with religious art. Yet such art always thrived there,
in the expressive ritual forms of a native shamanism and in gilded
icons produced in Buddhist monasteries. ``Dancing Demons:
Ceremonial Masks of Mongolia,'' at the Asia Society, presents masks
and other objects. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NUTTY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Elvis Mitchell reviews ``Nutty
Professor II: The Klumps,'' starring Eddie Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   GIRL-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Girl on the Bridge,'' a
soap-bubble of romantic attitude and second-hand glamour, Patrice
Leconte succeeds by discovering something sexier than sex, at once
a perfect metaphor and a convincing substitute for it. By A.O.
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   WIND-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Iranian director Abbas Kiarostami's
absorption in the wide emptiness of the rural Iranian landscape, in
a remote corner of which ``The Wind Will Carry Us'' takes place,
yields views that seem almost otherworldly in their clarity and
depth. By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   WONDER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Michael Winterbottom's
``Wonderland'' could be called ``The Three Sisters'': A modern-day
London turn on Chekhov, it deals with the anguish of three women
whose lives are in varying stages of disintegration. Reviewed by
Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   MONNIER-DANCE-REVIEW (New York) _ The French modern-dance
choreographer Mathilde Monnier has been a major link with an
emerging experimental dance scene in Africa. ``Pour Antigone,''
which she choreographed in 1991, is the final dance event presented
by Lincoln Center Festival 2000, and it is a landmark work in this
new cross-polinization. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND (Undated) _ Julie Salamon spotlights ``A House
Divided,'' starring Sam Waterston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
