<HEADLINE>
SPARKS GET REVENGE ON SEATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Sparks got even, blowing the expansion
Seattle Storm out of the Forum on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has changed since these teams last met. With a handful of
games remaining, the Sparks are the WNBA's leading team and the
Storm has the league's worst record. This time the Sparks left no
room for error as they won their seventh consecutive game and final
regular-season home game 76-63 in front of 6,455.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Sparks (23-3) a full-game lead over their
next opponent, the three-time defending champion Houston Comets
(22-4), who were idle Thursday. That game begins a six-game road
trip. The next time the Sparks play in the Forum will be in the
playoffs. In the meantime, they will be trying to hold down the No.
1 seed for home-court advantage throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we come,'' Sparks coach Michael Cooper said about heading
to play Houston in a nationally televised game Saturday. ``We've
beaten them twice this year and I'm pretty sure they've had this
date penciled in and here we come.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the Sparks were repaying the Storm for their 69-58
overtime loss in Seattle back in June.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Storm had no answer for the Sparks, who got
double-figuring scoring from five players. Sparks center Lisa
Leslie, a serious candidate for league's most valuable player, had
18 points and seven rebounds. DeLisha Milton had 13 points and
Mwadi Mabika, who celebrated her 24th birthday Thursday, Tamecka
Dixon and Allison Feaster had 10 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a well-played game by Seattle,'' Cooper said. ``I
thought we did a good job of getting out on them. We were able to
get into our rhythm. The last time we played they took away our
inside game. This time we were able to get our high-low game
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks shot 49 percent and held down the edge on the boards
35-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted them because they beat us twice,'' said Mwadi, who
was adding the exhibition loss to Seattle. ``They never give up,
even if we go up by 20. We stayed focus and got the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Leslie: ``I thought we did a good job of taking it inside
to them. They had some really long players, but I thought we were
very aggressive, especially on the boards and getting offensive
rebounds, so that probably put us over the top in terms of post
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks fell behind 6-2 but later stretched out a tight game
with an 8-0 run to go up 21-16, while the Storm was held to one
field goal in five minutes. Tamecka Dixon made a 10-footer and
followed it with a 3-pointer to give the Sparks a 10-point lead.
They never looked backed as they took a 39-26 advantage into the
break.
</P>
<P>
   They shot 52 percent in the period with DeLisha Milton leading
the way with nine points, Leslie with eight and Dixon with seven.
Milton did not miss in four attempts from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Henning had a career-high 19 points for Seattle. She was 6
of 10 from the 3-point line. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
