<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SKID REACHES THREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While Safeco Field starts to show its age, the
Mariners are starting to show their vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Cast in the shadow of a 17-minute delay when the Safeco Field
lights began to systematically go out, the Mariners' 101st game of
the season Thursday night showcased a struggling offense.
</P>
<P>
   Another in a series of unproductive offensive nights was broken
only by a two-run rally in the fifth inning that gave Seattle a 2-1
lead over Toronto. That lead evaporated in a rare implosion on the
part of left-handed reliever Arthur Rhodes as the Blue Jays came
roaring back, scoring five times in the seventh to claim a 7-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're struggling offensively; we need to pick it up,'' manager
Lou Piniella said. ``It happens to everybody. Teams better than
this have gone through the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you can do is go out again tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager said he hopes that the recent flurry of speculations
regarding possible deals _ the trade deadline arrives Monday _
haven't had an impact on his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to stand here and say that's the reason,''
Piniella said. ``The trade deadline comes around every year; every
team has to go through it. But sometimes you can lose focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may talk to them about that tomorrow. We need our focus.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen's focus was on trying to protect the 2-1 lead
inherited from starter John Halama. The relief corps, strong all
year, wasn't Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to take over from reliever Jose Paniagua in the seventh
with one out and no one on, Rhodes gave up two hits and an
intentional walk to load the bases. Rhodes got the inning's second
out with a pop fly, but after going 0-2 against pinch-hitter Todd
Greene, Rhodes gave up a single up the middle for two runs and a
3-2 Blue Jays lead.
</P>
<P>
   One walk later, Rhodes (3-5) was gone. His replacement, Jose
Mesa, struggled as well. Alex Gonzalez singled in two runs, and a
third scored on an error charged to third baseman David Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off their first losing series at Safeco Field in almost
two months against Oakland, the Mariners now have lost three in a
row at home _ matching the club's longest losing streak of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the home-stand, the Mariners have actually lost
a game on the four-game lead they brought home, and would be
looking at a two-game slippage had not the A's blown a 4-3 lead in
the late going against Boston in Oakland Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing is that teams are going to come after you when
you're in first place,'' Piniella said. ``We're in first, and they
came after us pretty good tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are 7-8 since the All-Star break, and in six of the
13 games they've scored two runs or less, including three times in
the past five games at home.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle put together a couple of doubles, by Dan Wilson and
Rickey Henderson, for one run and a subsequent Alex Rodriguez
single for another in a two-run fifth. The rest of the night was a
struggle against Esteban Loaiza, making just his second start for
the Jays after being dealt north by Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners lefty John Halama entered the game a winner in two of
his three July starts. Although he put runners on base by the
bushel, he pitched competitively.
</P>
<P>
   A two-out RBI double by Carlos Delgado in the first inning
earned the Blue Jays a run, but they didn't get much after that
because Halama, whose best success comes working down in the strike
zone, stayed down.
</P>
<P>
   As long as he was down in the zone, he was able to get
double-play grounders. And it was those double-play grounders,
accrued in the first, third and fifth innings, that were
instrumental in keeping the Blue Jays from mounting a concerted
charge.
</P>
<P>
   At least until the seventh. The seventh inning has been a
problem child for the Mariners, who have been been outscored 75-50
in the seventh this year, by far the team's worst scoring
differential in any inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes was one strike away from getting out of the inning when
he was 0-2 against Greene, but after Greene fought back to get even
in the count at 2-all, things were never the same. Greene took the
Blue Jays from behind to ahead with one swing, and Rhodes and Mesa
had trouble keeping back the floodwaters after that.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
