<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RALLY FALLS SHORT AGAINST WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Angels got the Chicago White Sox' full
arsenal Thursday night _ home runs, a deluge of hits, stolen bases,
hit-and-run plays, the works _ and still managed to get the tying
run to the plate in the bottom of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where it stayed, and the White Sox escaped with a 6-5
win in front of a crowd of 24,394 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, Chicago regained its distinction of having
baseball's best record: 63-39.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was another great comeback,'' said Angels manager Mike
Scioscia, after Anaheim spotted the White Sox a 6-0 lead after only
4{ innings before scrambling back to make it a game.
``Unfortunately, it fell short.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' seventh one-run game in their last 12, and
the wear is beginning to show. The Angels have lost three games in
a row, matching their longest losing streak of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets to be a grind,'' Scioscia acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   This was a bigger grind than most.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox unloaded 18 hits on the Angels, including a pair
of two-run home runs by Herbert Perry and Chris Singleton, both off
of loser Brian Cooper (4-5).
</P>
<P>
   They were the ninth and 10th home runs allowed this season by
Cooper, but he's been tagged for six in his last four starts, over
18 innings. He was raked for 10 hits in 42/3 innings after giving
up 10 hits in 31/3 innings his previous start against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the second consecutive rough start for (Cooper),''
Scioscia said. ``He never got his feet on the ground. His whole
thing is command, location ... and he had trouble with his command.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the team you want to struggle with your command.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put pressure on you in every phase of the game ... they
run, they hit-and-run, they go the other way, they hit the long
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And they take advantage of other club's misfortunes. Such as the
Angels helping out with three errors and a passed ball. Even a fan
in the right-field bleachers helped out, reaching out and getting a
hand on a drive in the fourth inning by Brook Fordyce, just enough
to knock it away from Tim Salmon. Instead of a double Fordyce wound
up with a triple and, one batter later, he scored on a passed ball.
</P>
<P>
   The only consolation for Scioscia, the fan was removed from the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox' lead was 4-0 when Cooper appeared to escape a
two-on, nobody-out jam in the fifth, when Paul Konerko grounded
into a double play. But Singleton followed with his eighth homer _
and second of the season off of Cooper _ and the lead was suddenly
6-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, meantime, were restricted to three singles in the
first four innings by Chicago's Jon Garland, at 20, the youngest
pitcher in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so concerned as I am cautious,'' White Sox manager
Jerry Manuel said when asked if he had concern over his young
pitching staff. ``There's still a lot to be done, a ways to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been here (this far in first place) before,
there's no history. With youth what you get is the unexpected. It
brings energy, but it also brings the unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the fifth, when the Angels came to life with four runs, a
rally that started when Garland walked the first two batters.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad, who drove in three runs for the night to give him
76 RBI for the season, singled home two in the fifth-inning rally.
</P>
<P>
   Garland regained his touch in the sixth, retiring the Angels in
order, then turned it over to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels left two on in the seventh, another in the eighth
and, in the ninth, Adam Kennedy led off with a triple off closer
Keith Foulke. Erstad got Kennedy home with a one-out sacrifice fly
_ after fouling off five successive 0-2 pitches _ but Kevin Stocker
flied to center to end it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
