<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 02:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5363 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-GARLAND-WHITESOX-     07-28 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GARLAND-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL BOY DOES GOOD AGIANST ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Jerry Manuel didn't care that his starting
pitcher was only 20 years old, had a losing record, an 8.22 ERA and
was making his hometown debut in just his fifth major-league
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox manager knew that the pitcher was Jon
Garland and reminded skeptics of the right-hander's habit of
remaining poised and playing beyond his years. Pitching in front of
family and friends _ in a stadium where he grew up attending games
_ wouldn't be any more of a challenge than anything Garland had
accomplished to get there, Manuel figured.
</P>
<P>
   Garland didn't disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander, who made a rapid rise through the minors after
being a first-round draft pick of the Chicago Cubs out of Kennedy
High of Granada Hills, Calif., in 1997, was in control early during
his start Thursday against the Angels at Edison Field, a game the
White Sox won 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Garland gave up five hits and two earned runs in six innings to
improve to 2-2 and show why Manuel considers him a key factor in
Chicago's ability to maintain the best record in the major leagues
and its large lead in the American League Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon Garland's obviously the type, he might get emotional, but
I don't think he'll go overboard,'' Manuel said before the game.
``He's the same guy that was recalled from A-ball to pitch in the
Triple-A World Series. I think it'll be a good nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland began by striking out one of the league's top hitters,
Darin Erstad, on three pitches. The crowd of Garland supporters
seated along the first-base line had reason to keep cheering as the
White Sox defense allowed Garland to get through the first two
innings facing the minimum number of batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't find myself in awe,'' Garland said. ``It's just like
pitching anywhere, I try to keep my team in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland, throwing in the low 90s with a sinker that was working
better than in recent games, routinely got ahead in counts and was
able to induce ground balls to quickly erase baserunners for four
shutout innings. None of the Angels' five baserunners through the
first four innings advanced past first.
</P>
<P>
   A leadoff walk to Kevin Stocker in the fourth drew a visit from
pitching coach Nardi Contreras. Garland responded by retiring the
heart of the Angels' lineup in order.
</P>
<P>
   Garland, who had lasted more than 41/3 innings in just one of
his previous four starts, saw his luck begin to turn in the fifth
inning. He walked the first two batters, but was hurt just as much
by two errors, which led to four runs, two of which were unearned.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of his days as a high school All-American, Garland
remained composed and retired the side in order in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an impressive effort by him to continue to pitch the
way he did,'' Manuel said. ``Even though he gave up the walks,
after the errors, he seemed to take it up another notch. It was
good to see.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the type of outing the White Sox envisioned when they
traded for him in 1998 and that has made him one of Baseball
America's top prospects each year since he turned pro.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps fellow Southern California product Jim Parque was right
about the value of coming home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling,'' said Parque, who is scheduled to start
the final game of the series Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After cruising through the International League for the first
few months of this season _ his nine wins led the league at the
time of his promotion and his 2.26 ERA with Charlotte is still a
league best _ Garland made his major-league debut July 4 and was
greeted with rough times.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up seven earned runs for a loss in his first game and
five earned runs for another loss last weekend. His only other win
came July 17 against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   At 20 years old, Garland fits right in on a team with an average
age of less than 27 years. Garland is used to being the youngest,
though. Before becoming the youngest White Sox pitcher in 15 years
to make his major-league debut, he was the youngest player in the
International League. In 1999, he was the youngest player in the
Southern League.
</P>
<P>
   Garland spent most of last year at Single-A Winston Salem and
Double-A Birmingham before being promoted to Triple-A Charlotte in
September. He made three playoff starts for the International
League champions, going 1-0 with a 3.18 ERA. His eight strikeouts
in Game 3 against Vancouver set a Triple-A World Series record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt real good to be here,'' Garland said. ``I had a lot of
people here. But you try to do this every game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
