<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 PM-CONCORDE-CRASH-0728-1STLD-C &HT;    EDs: recasts lede to reflect Air France denial...
 &HT;    FUEL PUMP IN AFTERBURNER OF DOOMED CONCORDE REPLACED BEFORE
FLIGHT CRASH, NEWSPAPER REPORTS
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONESSE, France _ Air France denied a newspaper report Friday
that mechanics replaced a fuel pump in the afterburner equipment in
two left-side engines of the doomed Concorde hours before the
aircraft took off from a Paris airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said its mechanics performed routine daily
maintenance on the Concorde the day it crashed but said that the
afterburner pump on the No. 2 engine was not replaced. The airline
said the maintenance ended with tests of all four of the Concorde's
engines.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also expressed criticism of media speculation
swirling around the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the wake of the tragedy, Air France deplores unfounded and
wrong reporting in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing Air France sources, Le Parisien said that the lengthy
repair to engine No. 2 was made in the morning before the afternoon
take-off. Engine No. 2 is the engine that burst into flames as the
supersonic Concorde took off before crashing into flames killing
113 about two minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde is the only passenger aircraft to have
afterburners, which are common on supersonic military jets.
Afterburners inject fuel into hot jet engine exhaust gases
providing the explosive power for take-off.
</P>
<P>
   Le Parisien quoted an unidentified mechanic as saying: ``The
afterburner pump pushes out a great volume of fuel at high
pressure. If it goes wrong or breaks, there's a risk it can turn
the back of the engine into a real blowtorch.''
</P>
<P>
   Government investigators said Thursday that the aircraft lost
power in two of its four engines as it was taking off, and the
flight crew was unable to retract the aircraft's landing gear.
</P>
<P>
   The swan-like supersonic aircraft also left pieces of tire on
the runway and had dropped debris along the 4-mile trajectory of
its brief flight, the French Bureau of Accident Investigation, or
BEA, also said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Readings from one of the so-called ``black boxes'' recovered
from the aircraft indicated that the left No. 1 engine
malfunctioned as the Concorde rotated for take-off. This engine was
next to the No. 2 engine, which also received a replacement reverse
thruster just before take-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aircraft was in flight for less than one minute when the
parameters of engine No. 1 decreased again, the plane lurched
strongly to the left and crashed,'' the BEA said. ``In the sound
recording, we noted that the crew announced a problem in engine No.
2 and a little later they said the undercarriage would not come up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flight data recorder shows that on take-off engine No. 2
lost power to the point that it stopped, and that engine No. 1
temporarily lost power,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Tower controllers told the pilots that flames were streaming
from the rear of the plane during take-off, but the Concorde was
traveling too fast to halt the flight, the BEA said.
</P>
<P>
   A French aviation engineer who serves as an official adviser to
French courts said initial findings suggested that a tire might
have exploded on take-off sending pieces into an engine, setting
off a chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have ingestion of foreign objects in the engines, and
then you have problems in the
</P>
<P>
   engine,'' Raymond Auffray told the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Thursday, Air France's remaining five Concorde's
remained grounded today as the investigation progressed. British
Airways, the only other airline to fly the high-speed transport
planes, resumed its Concorde flights between New York and London
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The BEA _ the French equivalent of the U.S. National
Transportation Safety Board _ is studying about 600 pieces of
technical information including mechanical readings and the
aircraft's altitude, speed and position contained in the black
boxes recovered from the aircraft, which crashed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Government experts have extracted all the information from the
flight data and cockpit voice recorders, the BEA said Thursday,
adding that it planned to finish a preliminary report at the end of
August.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said it was unclear how soon the data would yield
more clues about what caused the crash that killed 113 people when
the Concorde crashed into a small hotel near Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also intend to study the amateur video aired Wednesday
on television news reports to determine if, for example, the color
and size of the flames can determine the temperature and source of
the fire, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde was carrying 100 passengers _ 96 Germans, two
Danes, an American and an Austrian _ and nine French crew members.
Two Polish women were among the four people killed on the ground.
Six members of one German family died in the crash, including a
10-year-old boy and a seven-year-old girl, the newspaper France
Soir reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the BEA report was released, Auffray, the aviation
expert, told La Croix newspaper that evidence and observations
suggested that an engine turbine blade might have failed. He told
the newspaper that investigators should focus on turbine blades
inside both Rolls-Royce engines under the left wing.
</P>
<P>
   Auffray said the pilots' loss of control indicates that a
ruptured blade may have caused the engine to break up inside.
</P>
<P>
   Local government officials said Thursday that the bodies of all
113 victims had been recovered from the wreckage and transferred to
a mediurch, which holds about 1,000 people, was filled with
uniformed Air France pilots, cabin crew and other staff and the
families of many of those who died. German relatives of the
victims, some holding one another for support, arrived in buses
provided by the Paris Airports Authority. Many wore dark glasses in
the bright summer sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Outside the church, a priest in purple and white robes greeted
mourners. Passers-by laid bunches of flowers in tribute. President
Jacques Chirac, who did not attend the service, sent a large
bouquet of pale pink roses and other flowers.
</P>
<P>
   A priest began the service with these words: ``We are gathered
here united in our pain and if possible, united in our hope.''
</P>
<P>
   At Charles de Gaulle airport, where the Concorde took off
Tuesday on its journey to New York, travelers and Air France
employees observed a moment of silence. A similar ceremony took
place at Orly Airport, Paris' other major airport which is served
by Air France.
</P>
<P>
   Air France said Thursday it would pay $20,000 each to surviving
families to help defray immediate expenses such as funeral costs.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Genosse, a working-class town of 20,000, plan to
hold a silent march to the crash site Friday. Merchants said they
would close shop to honor the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the Val d'Oise region prosecutor officially
opened an investigation into the accident to determine whether
charges could be brought for ``involuntary homicide and involuntary
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   And French newspapers reported that investigators had seized
maintenance documents relating to the repair work on the engine's
thrust reverser. Such an investigation is not unusual in France
following such a large accident.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
