   In making the case for the above proposition, let's start with
this question: If campaigns don't count, why do people think they
do? The answer is clear: the polls. The poll numbers ``move''
during the campaign year. Therefore, the assumption goes, people
must be paying attention to campaign events.
</P>
<P>
   (If campaigns always ended the way they start out looking in the
polls, nobody would be surprised and the universally accepted
explanation would be that the voters don't pay any attention to
politicians during campaigns. It would seem obvious.)
</P>
<P>
   But does movement in polls mean anything? Let's look at the
course of the polls in 1992. Bill Clinton was doing badly for most
of the year, relative not only to George Bush but to Ross Perot. A
Washington Post and ABC poll in late April showed Bush at 36
percent, Clinton at 31 and Perot at 30. It was, remember, the
pathetic condition of the Democrats _ confronted with an apparently
vulnerable president _ that fostered Perot's entry into the race in
the first place. All the big-name Democrats had decided not to seek
the presidency, and Clinton was winning the nomination by
semi-default over a weak field, despite being damaged by the draft,
adultery and Whitewater issues and the resulting widespread qualms
about his character.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic convention _ which came before that of the
GOP _ resulted in a huge gain for Clinton. He came away with a big
lead, which he never lost. A CNN/USA Today/Gallup Poll, which had
Clinton behind Bush by 8 percentage points a couple of weeks before
the Democratic convention, had him ahead by 18 after.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Clinton's surge seemed to a lot of people like just
another turn in a tumultuous political situation. After all, in
early 1991, when the American military drove Iraq's Saddam Hussein
out of Kuwait, George Bush's approval rating in the polls soared
toward 90 percent. In the end, though, Bush got only 39 percent of
the popular vote, though his opponents were damaged and dubious.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Perot had come out of nowhere, gone up to 40
percent in match-ups with the other candidates and dropped back
below 20 percent before rising again.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in the media and politics talk about the changes in
Bush's standing as changes in the public ``mood.'' But are the
American people really so ``moody'' as to think in the spring of
1991 that Bush's presidency was a success and by the late summer of
1992 that just about anybody any party might nominate could do
better? After all, not much happened concretely between mid-1991
and late 1992, other than the passage of time after the military
victory, and the fact that the American economy improved, which
normally would be expected to move the numbers in favor of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   POLLS MEASURE INCLINATIONS
</P>
<P>
   If these changes in the polls reflected changes in the public's
mood, the country had a bigger problem than the deficit, crime,
drugs, poverty and family break-up combined. It had an electorate
that, if it were an individual, would be a candidate for
mood-controlling drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, however, what many polls measure is not moods but
vague inclinations. The pollsters are getting top-of-the-head,
shrug-of-the-shoulder responses about a question voters haven't
focused on.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called experts are always quick to say election polls
provide only a ``snap shot'' of the electorate's views. But even
that metaphor grossly overstates the usefulness of early campaign
polls. What we are likely to get, really, is a blurry, awful,
underdeveloped snap shot, one in which we can't even tell what
we're looking at.
</P>
<P>
   Came the summer of 1992. Why did Clinton get a great boost in
the polls out of his convention, while Bush failed to get the usual
``bounce'' out of the Republican convention? (A Washington Post and
ABC poll concluded that Bush got a six-point ``bump,'' but other
polls showed even that evaporating in a few days, which is not the
norm with these things.)
</P>
<P>
   The political media addressed this question head-on at the time
and generally concluded that many Americans had found the
Republican convention off-putting. Pat Buchanan _ Bush's opponent
in the primaries _ had given a prime-time speech about the
necessity off ``taking back'' the country from forces corrupting
its culture. Other speakers had concentrated on assaulting the
Democrats, especially on ``family values.'' It all seemed so
negative, or so this theory goes. ``GOP Sees Its Stress on Values
Backfire'' was the headline on a Boston Globe analysis on Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic convention, on the other hand, evoked the future
and embraced everybody, giving off warm vibes.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP convention of 1992 was run by roughly the same
people as the successful conventions of 1980, 1984 and 1988. In
1988, they had a candidate _ George Bush _ who went into the
convention season having been way behind in the polls for a year.
He came out of his convention ahead and _ like every candidate
since 1948 who has come out of the conventions with a clear lead _
remained ahead all the way.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little hard to believe Republican masters of media
manipulation had simply lost their touch by 1992.
</P>
<P>
   COMPLETING THE PICTURE
</P>
<P>
   A better theory: Public opinion about Clinton in 1992 was not
well formed before the conventions, but opinion about Bush was.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had not spent much time on the national stage, and when
he was there he was mainly dealing with embarrassments relating to
sex and the draft. At the convention, however, the American people
saw other sides of him. They saw a major national party embrace him
enthusiastically. They saw his accomplishments highlighted, and
they saw him behave presidentially. In short, they saw _ if not a
guy they just had to have _ at least a respectable alternative to
the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And the swing voters were more than open to the idea of change.
The economy had been sour through almost all of Bush's term; when
it wasn't in recession, it was growing only weakly. The deficit was
out of control. The crack-cocaine epidemic had fostered a crime
wave. Almost all the measures of a society's success were going the
wrong way (except in the area of foreign policy).
</P>
<P>
   And the government wasn't doing much about it. Before Bush
became president, the term ``gridlock'' referred to road traffic;
on his watch, it became a political term.
</P>
<P>
   There comes a time when more talk can't do much. That was what
happened to Bush in the summer of 1992. The public had made up its
mind about him before the conventions. It just had not decided
whether Clinton was a respectable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   A comparison with 1988 makes the point. Then-Vice President
George Bush's numbers could be moved by the GOP convention because
he was still a fuzzy figure to the public. Having been in Ronald
Reagan's enormous shadow for eight years, he was widely seen as
some sort of ``wimp.'' The ``wimp factor'' was the subject of a
news magazine cover story. But the convention highlighted a
substantive career, the high regard in which Bush was held by many
notable people, and his military record.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when the country was doing well, the swing voters were
ready to stick with the incumbent party. They just weren't sure
Bush was a respectable choice. But conventions can just about
always convince people that a nominee is a respectable choice,
because he just about always is.
</P>
<P>
   If we are talking about ``convincing,'' are we talking about
media manipulation, after all? No. All the Democratic convention of
1992 and Republican convention of 1988 did was the inevitable: They
completed the pictures of the candidates. They didn't successfully
sell the public bills of goods about alleged supermen.
</P>
<P>
   Running a convention is not rocket science. If you're the
incumbent party, you emphasize how good things are or you try to
change the subject away from how bad things are. If you're the
challenging party, you emphasize how bad things are or try to
change the subject away from how good things are.
</P>
<P>
   Whether your arguments resonate depends upon how things actually
are. That's the heart of the matter, and the judgment of the
American people is almost always clear after the conventions and
often not clear before them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
