   Inevitably, the matriarch asked the future Laura Bush, ``And
what do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Her reply, ``I read,'' quieted everyone within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Bush couldn't believe her ears,'' Barbara Bush recalled.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY FIRST
</P>
<P>
   They were a family first, before they became a public entity,
before everyone from The New York Times to Vogue wanted to tell
their story.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge he and Laura have faced wasn't the '94
governor's race nobody thought he would win, said George W. Bush.
It was the birth of their children, after Laura was ordered to bed
late in her pregnancy. He was in Midland and she was hospitalized
in Dallas when he got the call from her doctor. ``Your children
will be born tomorrow; either that, or your wife's kidneys will
fail.''
</P>
<P>
   He got on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves our daughters more than anything,'' he said, ``would
lay her life down for them. And nearly did so at birth . . . She
was absolutely determined to do whatever she could to make sure
those little girls came into the world healthy and safe. And she
did.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the story later.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Laura at her best, kind of hanging on with the
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   She has fond memories of their early years as a family in
Midland, of wheeling the twin girls around in their stroller on hot
summer afternoons as the cicadas trilled loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Now the girls, named for their grandmothers, are 18. Barbara,
following in the footsteps of her father, grandfather and great
grandfather, will attend Yale University in the fall. Jenna has
enrolled at The University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush sounded wistful when she spoke about the days when
she could throw her arms around them easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very natural for them at this age to want to spread
their wings, and George and I are certainly aware of that,'' she
said. ``We are aware of how much less relevant we are in our
children's lives each day as they grow up and want to be with their
own friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls, whose privacy is zealously protected _ they don't
give interviews and they haven't appeared in campaign
advertisements _ haven't been overly concerned with their father's
political plans, their mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like every teen-ager, they are mainly concerned about
what they're going to be doing this weekend; at the same time they
are very proud of their dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their lives, when their grandfather was
vice-president, then president, and when their father became
governor in 1994, the Bushes have ``tried to make a normal life for
our daughters,'' Laura Bush said. Both the former president and
Barbara Bush said they have felt a protective surge as Texas' first
family has moved into the national political arena. But neither
admits to offering any guidance on how to survive a presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I awaken every morning with advice,'' Barbara Bush
joked, ``but I don't give it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes have been encouraged by the way the national media
have treated Chelsea Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some things the girls have not been able to be
shielded from. At a Texas Book Festival event, when hecklers
shouted down former President Bush, ``Jenna walked out of there and
burst into tears,'' Laura Bush said. ``It's hard for a teen-ager
when people yell mean things at your grandfather.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult, too, to hear things said about your husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like that's what I dread the most, the criticism, but
also the totally unfounded rumors,'' Laura Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a tragic piece of the candidate's wife past has been
campaign fodder: Earlier this year, a tabloid newspaper revealed
details of a fatal car accident 35 years ago in which Laura Bush
was one of the drivers. According to reports, Laura Welch, then 17,
ran a stop sign in Midland, colliding with a vehicle driven by a
high school friend; the teen-age boy was killed.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, who's been more even-tempered on his own
campaign trail than when his father was the target of criticism,
has voiced concerns about his wife, about what she might have to
endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to be the candidate where people say ugly
things about you than the person who loves the person about which
ugly things are said. I know first-hand,'' he said, before the news
about his wife's decades-old tragedy surfaced. ``I know
first-hand.''
</P>
<P>
   CHECKS AND BALANCES
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your vantage point, they're an odd couple or a
completely complementary pair.
</P>
<P>
   She straightens up when she's nervous, attacking bookshelves and
countertops with zeal. He admits to leaving piles of dirty clothes
and sweaty gym gear in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   She's reserved and shy; he's a fiery extrovert.
</P>
<P>
   Their contrasting personalities _ his high-energy temperament
and her laid-back style _ have provided ``a good check and
balance,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush says her daughter-in-law is ``a sort of catalyst in
our family. She brings out the best in us.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says much the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura has always been a very positive influence on me . . . in
terms of forcing me to ask the right questions. On the occasions
where I drank too much, she reminded me I was drinking too much.
And I listened.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when everyone else was urging him to run for governor,
Laura Bush was one of the last people to get behind the idea.
</P>
<P>
   She reminded him he was ``living a dream'' as an owner of the
Texas Rangers, he says. Both of them enjoyed their time together
watching games, the Florida Gulf Coast vacations that centered on
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura's not the first to say, `Oh boy, let's go do that,' sort
of shovin' me into the limelight,'' the governor says. ``She's the
opposite of that. She says, `Wait a minute, buddy, are you sure?
Are you sure you're going to ask our family to make a life change?
Are you sure that this is something you really want to do?'
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew close during the baseball games because of the amount
of time we spent with each other,'' he says. ``We could think about
things and talk. We grew very close during the (1994) campaign
because it was like we were in combat to a certain extent, fellow
warriors.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush ``is in a life that I don't think she ever
envisioned,'' her husband says. ``But she has seized the
opportunity and made a difference in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her projects, the Texas Book Festival, has raised nearly
$900,000 for the state library system. Last year, after she
championed early childhood initiatives, the Texas legislature
approved $17 million for preschool reading programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would most like to be known as an advocate for children,''
she says. ``I would like to help parents be well-informed so they
can make great decisions for their young children. I think being a
parent is the most important job any of us will ever have and out
relationships with our families and our children are our most
important relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Her work to empower other families would be expanded if her own
were to occupy the White House. Her self-assured answer to the
oft-asked question: Would Hillary Clinton, or Barbara Bush be a
role model? ``I think I'll just be Laura Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother-in-law can see her there, reveling in the history and
``majesty'' of 1600 Pennsylvania Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a good little nester,'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
