<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You can uncover much if you are willing to rake the muck
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ Picking up trash at the annual Marshall
clean-up isn't a problem for me. I guess you could say I've been
nothing but a muckraker all my life.
</P>
<P>
   My first real job was picking up trash off the parking lot of a
foundry that employed about 500 people. It seemed like a good deal
to me, I got paid $40 a week to keep it clean no matter how many
hours I worked. If I could keep it clean by working two hours a
week, that was a cool 20 bucks an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it turned out to be about $2 per hour and, instead of
being cool, it was the absolutely back-breaking task of removing a
short ton of beer bottles and cans from what I unlovingly termed
``Hell's Half Acre.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right, almost all of what I picked up were empty beer
containers.
</P>
<P>
   While we regularly beat ourselves up these days about drugs in
the workforce and talk about how terrible work intoxication can be,
the truth is that in the early '70s no one really cared a bit. The
management of this plant _ now out of business, by the way _ either
did not have a rule or did not care about drinking on the job.
</P>
<P>
   So when the noon-time whistle blew, every employee would stream
out of the plant, head to an automobile and guzzle as much beer as
humanly possible in 30 minutes. If you couldn't do at least a quart
you were a piker and destined to be hounded from the job.
</P>
<P>
   Most people either did two quarts of beer or an entire six-pack
in 30 minutes and still managed to squeeze down a sandwich or two.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, if you will, picking up 5,000 empty quart bottles of
beer each week and you'll get a sense of what I'm talking about. I
got less than a penny for every bottle I picked up. It was not a
great deal.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years later I got an actual full-time job in the
plant and I learned that not everyone drank beer during lunch as I
had first thought.
</P>
<P>
   No, a full half of them were smoking marijuana or doing other
drugs during the noon hour.
</P>
<P>
   My first day on the job I was slipped a marijuana cigarette by a
co-worker _ the same co-worker who would, about 30 minutes later,
be on the other end of a small pot of molten aluminum we were
pouring into a mold.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with 1,200-degree aluminum was enough to make me urge my
fellow employees to ``just say no.'' Let's just say that I avoided
pouring much aluminum after lunch. Not that it hardly mattered, in
the morning everyone had a stumbling hangover, including me.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, which made important parts for Air Force jet fighters
(makes you feel safe, doesn't it?), also used, as an alloy, a great
deal of magnesium, one of the few natural substances that will burn
under water.
</P>
<P>
   So every year or so you would hear a thunderous roar in the
plant and look up to find that the roof was gone, along with a
hand, arm, leg or two. Inspectors, both state and federal, would
come to the plant, taking copious notes, interviewing dozens of
workers and asking thousands of questions. They would investigate
the building from top to bottom and walk away scratching their
heads, wondering what had gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But never, not once, did they inspect the one place that would
have told them all they needed to know. They never went to the
employee parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   (Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas)
News Messenger. His email address is platham (at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
