<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We don't need government to create cell phone etiquette
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ More than 10 years ago I test drove a 12-cylinder
BMW that cost more than my house.
</P>
<P>
   One of the features packed into this luxury high-performance car
was a hands-free telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The phone wasn't hooked up, but I was told that the voices of
the driver and passengers were picked up clearly by a built-in
microphone. The person on the other end of the conversation was
heard through the car's excellent speaker system, which
automatically muted other signals going to the speakers when the
phone was in use.
</P>
<P>
   I considered this a nifty development. Now I own a hands-free
telephone that doesn't require the purchase of a $150,000 car. It's
a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, America is turning into a nation of Nervous
Nellies determined to have the government protect them from all
risks. Chronically nervous Americans have targeted cell phone use
for government regulation, oversight and criminalization.
</P>
<P>
   A subgroup of the Nervous Nellies are the Wet Blankets who are
determined to dampen any new movement that appears to be catching
on with the public.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous Nellies and Wet Blankets (NNs and WBs) have succeeded in
some places where cell phone use now is banned or regulateapers,
cell phone use in public ranges from outrageously rude to deadly.
The solution, according to NNs and WBs, requires new laws,
penalties, enforcement, prosecution and punishment.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, rather than allow society to develop a code of
accepted behavior, a quaint concept formerly called good manners,
NNs and WBs want the government to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are upset when they see shoppers using cell phones.
I think it makes good sense. When you get to the store and can't
remember what that third item was, you call home. Cell phones are
handy when someone at home calls when you are shopping and asks you
to pick something up. There may be a time when you don't know if
Italian stewed tomatoesam new to this woodworking hobby so please
bear with me. My sister wants me to construct for her a simple
bench that will be outside in her garden.
</P>
<P>
   She wants it to be six feet long by 12 inches deep and 16 inches
tall. What would be a good wood to use in making this bench? I
thought it best to use some type of hardwood instead of pine so it
will hold together better.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, most of the more enduring outdoor woods are soft and
relatively weak, even weaker than pine. Redwood, western red cedar
and cypress all endure relatively well outdoors, but the
construction will have to be heavier than usual; 8/4 stock
throughout, with a good support in the middle of that six-foot run.
</P>
<P>
   Teak, of course, is the classic outdoor wood, and it is a very
strong wood. Unfortunately it is also a very expensive wood, and
one of the most difficult woods there is to work. It is full of
silica, and thus is very hard on edged tools.
</P>
<P>
   Another woodworker who responded to this question suggested oak
if a hardwood is definitely required. My only experience with oak
in outdoor furniture was a disaster, but perhaps I used the wrong
finish or didn't apply it properly. This fellow recommends ``a
couple of coats of clear or semi-transparent deck stain. Look at
Cabot's Deck Stains for good quality.'' He suggests the same thing
for the softer woods, too.
</P>
<P>
   Another novice woodworker reports he bought a nice jack plane,
``brought it home, put a good start on tuning it, and it didn't
need much. Started fiddling with some old oak. Adjusted it so I had
very fine shavings leaping from its mouth, turned the wood over and
suddenly it is like I got too much blade out and it doesn't want to
go any more. What's up? The grain of the wood seems to want me to
work from the same end on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Determining the direction of grain visually is an extremely
difficult thing, in my experience. Sometimes it's obvious, but very
often it isn't at all obvious.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds to me as though the wood is telling him he's cutting
against the grain. Most of the time if the grain runs in one
direction on a given surface of a board, it will run in the
oppposite direction on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, when your plane is running nicely on one side
and balks on the obverse, the first thing to do is to try planing
from the other direction. If that doesn't work, then the likelihood
is that you've run into some wild figure that has grain going in
every direction.
</P>
<P>
   This is why scrapers and sandpaper were invented.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
