r s BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES29-CO     07-28 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tight points race prompts anticipation at Atlanta track
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta Motor Speedway officials are preparing for what might be
the track's most highly-anticipated Winston Cup race since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   AMS officials held extensive meetings this week to discuss plans
for the Nov. 19 NAPA AutoCare 500. If the Winston Cup points
standings race remain as close as it has, and the sport's biggest
names, including Dale Earnhardt, Jeff Gordon and Dale Jarrett, stay
in contention, the AMS event will attract unprecedented ticket
sales and media attention.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett fans have been calling the track after Jarrett
moved past Earnhardt into the No. 2 position last week. Seven
drivers are within 307 points of leader Bobby Labonte with 15 races
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   AMS has already sold out of infield parking, but tickets are
available for the race.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, five drivers _ Davey Allison, Bill Elliott,
Alan Kulwicki, Kyle Petty and Harry Gant _ were mathematically
eligible for the Winston Cup championship heading into the season
finale at Atlanta. It was also the circuit's debut event for rookie
phenom, Jeff Gordon, and final race for legendary driver Richard
Petty. The late Kulwicki didn't win, but scored enough points to
hoist the Winston Cup trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Busch circuit honors Irwin
</P>
<P>
   In the Busch Series, the No. 42 Chevy is co-sponsored by
BellSouth Mobility. The car was driven by the late Kenny Irwin in
10 Busch races earlier this year. Sterling Marlin will finish out
the final six races on the team's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Busch car's number will be switched to No. 01 to honor the
memory of Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny was a great teammate and competitor and is greatly
missed,'' Marlin said. ``Kenny would've wanted us to finish the
season and the team hopes to make him proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlin is slated to enter the Busch events at Bristol,
Darlington, Richmond, Charlotte, Memphis and Homestead-Miami.
</P>
<P>
   MB2's sponsor search
</P>
<P>
   There is a remote possibility Johnny Benson could drive his
final race of the season for MB2 Motorsports at the Brickyard 400
on Aug. 5. The organization cannot fund the race team after the
next race without the assistance of a primary sponsor. MB2 is
talking to at least four businesses and could reach an agreement in
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   If MB2 fails to sign a sponsor, look for Benson to appear as an
interim or relief driver for other teams for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Benson is under contract with MB2 for the 2001-02 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett makes move back into points race
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the Winston Cup points standings, ``repeat champion''
are two words many NASCAR fans haven't mentioned this season until
now.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, who won the 1999 title, has come out of nowhere to
threaten again as the stock-car racing's season speeds down its
final stretch.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 races remaining, the Ford No. 88 has slipped past Dale
Earnhardt for the runner-up position in points behind Bobby
Labonte. It's perfect timing for Jarrett, as he is also the
defending champion of the Brickyard 400, which is the next stop for
the major-league circuit on Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything just right here (at Indianapolis) last
year,'' Jarrett said. ``We had a really good car. It was fast on
new tires, and it was fast on old tires. We did the right strategy
and almost everything went just perfect. Hopefully, we can do that
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett is doing the same thing he did to win the title last
year: consistent top-10 finishes (11 in 19 races). It also helps
that no one has raced away with points lead like he did last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sibling rivalry takes on new meaning behind the wheel
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR is a family affair, especially when it comes to brothers.
Three sets of brothers participate in the top three series of
stock-car racing: the Bodines (Geoffrey and Brett in Winston Cup
and Todd in Busch Grand National), the Wallaces (Rusty and Kenny in
Winston Cup and Mike in Craftsman Trucks), and the Greens (Busch
drivers David, Mark and Jeff).
</P>
<P>
   It is rare when three siblings compete against each other
full-time in one series. In the CarQuest 250 Saturday at St. Louis,
the Green brothers will race against each other for a record 50th
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been very special for me in many ways,'' said
Jeff, who leads the Busch points standings. ``Not only has this
been a dream season for me performance-wise, but being able to
reach a milestone with my brothers is preichael Waltrip's worries
are over for at least the next 17 months. The new owner of the his
race team, Jim Smith, revealed his future plans for Ultra
Motorsports. Waltrip and crew chief Bobby Kennedy will be retained
through the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, however, did announce some immediate changes: For the
last five races of this season, Waltrip will switch from a Chevy to
a Ford and use Penske engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love our driver, we love our crew chief, and we love
working with our sponsor,'' said Smith, who bought the team from
Jim Mattei.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the switch to Ford will give us the best race car,
and the switch to Penske will give us the best engines,'' Smith
said. ``If we're going to be the best _ and, believe me, that is
our top priority _ then we need to have the best on our side. We
think this is a giant step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Needed: Crew chief, driver
</P>
<P>
   Long-time Winston Cup team owner Junie Donlavey will announce a
new driver and crew chief within several days.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie driver Ed Berrier and crew chief Dean Johnson left the
No. 09 Ford team last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the hard work that everyone has put into this program,
we were not getting the results we know we can produce,'' Donlavey
said. ``It's not any one person's fault. Everyone put forth their
best effort but there was a lack of chemistry on this team, and Ed
and Dean and I agreed that it would be best for everyone if we
ended the relationship and moved forward.''
</P>
<P>
   No contest in the Busch Series
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Dale Jarrett had the Winston Cup championship wrapped
up by mid-summer, while the Busch title went down to the
next-to-the-last event. This season, the opposite is happening on
the two circuits.
</P>
<P>
   While as many as 10 contenders are battling it out on the top
circuit, Jeff Green leads the Busch standings by a whopping 552
points.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the remaining dates on the 2000 Busch Grand National
schedule:
</P>
<P>
   July 29 _ Carquest Auto Parts 300, Madison, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 4 _ Kroger 200, Clermont, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 19 _ NAPAOnline.com 250, Brooklyn, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 25 _ Food City 250, Bristol, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 2 _ Dura Lube 200, Darlington, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 8 _ Autolite Platinum 250, Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 23 _ MBNA.com 200, Dover, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 7 _ All Pro Bumper to Bumper 300, Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 21 _ Rockingham 200, Rockingham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 29 _ Sam's Town 250, Millington, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 4 _ Outback Steakhouse 200, Avondale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 11 _HotWheels.com 300, Homestead, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
