<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONE VOICE NO MATCH FOR MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   So, this new telephone
mysteriously shows up in the mail along with a note from the phone
company thanking us for ordering Caller ID. I ask around the house.
There has been no order, no interest at all in getting Caller ID.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We try not to encourage phone companies. For a long time the
automatic response has been, ``No thank you. We do not want to
change phones or phone companies.''
</P>
<P>
   But this bugs me. I don't want the service. I don't want the
phone. I don't want to pay to send the phone back.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the deal is if you order Caller ID, for which you
will be charged a certain extra sum every month on the phone bill,
they send you a new phone as a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   I call the phone company to tell them I don't want either. But
you don't just call the phone company any more. You enter voice
mail hell.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the phone company convinced the rest of us we need
voice mail, it has built its own impenetrable fortress. Sometimes
we like voice mail. It's a great way to slither when you don't
really want to talk to someone but need to go on record as at least
making the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   However, it seems that, of all places, the phone company should
be reachable by phone.
</P>
<P>
   I go through the options and there is nothing for someone
wishing to report an unwanted phone.
</P>
<P>
   No recording is saying, ``Press 3 if you don't like what we sent
you.''
</P>
<P>
   I keep punching buttons until I get the one for customer service
but that sinks me even deeper in the land of the well-modulated
voice offering options but no people.
</P>
<P>
   I finally choose the one that tells rotary phone callers to stay
on the line. I imagine that they provide this service for the three
people in the country who really do have phones that must be
cranked and who will be directed to a clunky old switchboard in
Iowa staffed by someone in a print dress and rolled hair practicing
her Lily Tomlin ``one ringy dingy'' imitation.
</P>
<P>
   I get her. She's real and I'm grateful. I tell her my troubles
and she says she'd like to help but I need to talk to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it has to be a real person,'' I plead. ``Don't send me
back to voice mail.''
</P>
<P>
   She promises she is transferring me to someone who talks.
</P>
<P>
   The line is busy. I imagine Lily bent over laughing. I don't
want to hang up because it will cut my only living link with the
phone company.
</P>
<P>
   The line goes dead.
</P>
<P>
   I wait until the next day and start over and I never penetrate
the wall. By the third day I get a breathing human being. She says
she'll take the customer ID charge off my account, although it will
take a couple of billing cycles. She has no idea how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   What about the phone? Will they come and get it? She pauses as
if she's thinking and then says, ``Keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep the phone I didn't order? Was she testing my integrity? If
I nab the phone will that suggest a larcenous nature that might
also fib about not wanting Caller ID?
</P>
<P>
   It's a hassle to send it back, she says. Surely, I could use a
new phone.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I could and replaced the kitchen phone, which has been
there so long the numbers were rubbed off the buttons.
</P>
<P>
   My new phone rang the next night and guess who? It was a
customer service rep from the phone company. I figured someone
snitched and I was about to confess to having a hot phone when he
said he didn't care about my telephones. He wanted to sign me up
for DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
