<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, July 29 and Sunday, July 30,
2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ More than 10 years ago I test
drove a 12-cylinder BMW that cost more than my house. One of the
features packed into this luxury high-performance car was a
hands-free telephone. The phone wasn't hooked up, but I was told
that the voices of the driver and passengers were picked up clearly
by a built-in microphone. The person on the other end of the
conversation was heard through the car's excellent speaker system,
which automatically muted other signals going to the speakers when
the phone was in use. I considered this a nifty development. Now I
own a hands-free telephone that doesn't require the purchase of a
$150,000 car. It's a cell phone. Unfortunately, America is turning
into a nation of Nervous Nellies determined to have the government
protect them from all risks. Chronically nervous Americans have
targeted cell phone use for government regulation, oversight and
criminalization. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ Picking up
trash at the annual Marshall clean-up isn't a problem for me. I
guess you could say I've been nothing but a muckraker all my life.
My first real job was picking up trash off the parking lot of a
foundry that employed about 500 people. It seemed like a good deal
to me, I got paid $40 a week to keep it clean no matter how many
hours I worked. If I could keep it clean by working two hours a
week, that was a cool 20 bucks an hour. (Latham, Marshall News
Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ATLANTA _ The notion that
some things never change has gone out the window in the 21st
century. Everything changes. If you don't believe it, look what's
happening in the Army, the Navy, the Air Force and even in the
Marines. According to a story in USA Today, basic training has gone
to what amounts to social promotions in public schools. Everybody
graduates. The new Army is bending over backward to help sad-sack
trainees. Instead of being thrown to the mercy of tough old
sergeants, recruits who arrive too soft and flabby for regular
training get an easier course. The nervous and fearful get
counseling to calm them down. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Mary McCarty's column will return Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ East Texas women, love 'em or
leave 'em alone.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a couple of stories, as true as anything you'll read in
today's paper. (Murray, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORIAL, OP-ED AND POLITICAL EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are in charge of explaining American politics
to the American people don't understand American politics. They
think it's largely about imagery, but it's really about reality.
The national conventions are the occasions when the swing voters
finally pause to take note of the real national circumstances that
will determine their votes.'' This excerpt is from Dayton Daily
News editorial writer Martin Gottlieb's new e-book _ ``Campaigns
Don't Count: How the Media Get American Politics All Wrong.'' The
book, which is available free in its entirety at
www.coxnews.com/2000, is the topic of a full page layout that will
run on Sunday, July 30 in the Daily News. The page will be
available Wednesday, July 26 after 5 p.m. EDT with an embargo until
the 30th. It can be found via the Budget Tool by doing a WAN search
with a rundate of 0730, a location of Dayton and a category of
Op-Ed and Editorial. If you have questions or need more
information, contact Daily News Editorial Page Editor Ellen Belcher
at 937 225-2286 (ebelcher(at)coxojio.com) or the CoxNet desk in
Atlanta at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Following a consistent 52-year pattern, the
Palestinians have managed again to make the least of an
opportunity. This time, at President Clinton's Camp David
negotiations, they dodged the creation of a substantial,
internationally recognized Palestinian state with significant
authority in the Muslim quarter of Jerusalem. (Tom Teepen is
national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ A reader wrote that he was told a billion
means a thousand million in the United States but that in the
United Kingdom, it means a million million. Yes, a newspaper
confirmed, there is a difference _ a difference that totals 999
thousand million, which is a helluva more ones and ones than ever I
could count. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ The mobile phone scene has changed since 1984,
when an attorney friend told me that he would be getting a car
phone in return for having done legal work for a pioneering telecom
provider. In time, he passed up that swap. But I bought a phone, to
the surprise of dinner hosts who directed us into their unmarked
cul-de-sacs. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in the
Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ HIGH POINT, N.C. _ DISPATCHES FROM
DREAMSVILLE: Reliving some memories, like visiting an old ball park
that is falling down, can be heartbreaking. (Joe Murray, Cox News
Service). MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
