<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN29-COX     07-28 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: East Texas women
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ East Texas women, love 'em or leave 'em alone.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a couple of stories, as true as anything you'll read in
today's paper:
</P>
<P>
   Story No. 1
</P>
<P>
   A prospective jury panel had been called for a criminal case
involving a shooting that had resulted from a child custody
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   One of the defense attorneys, questioning the panel as a group,
asked for a show of hands of anyone who had been divorced. A number
of hands went up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who suffered a particularly ugly divorce?'' he then
asked.
</P>
<P>
   A well-dressed, grandmotherly-like lady in the fourth row raised
her hand immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this was, of course, a very difficult time for you,'' the
attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   The lady nodded, her face sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever fear for your life?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Again she nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``And has this carried over into your present life?'' the
attorney asked in a most sympathetic voice. ``Do you still have
reason to be fearful?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' she said, rather brightly. ``He's dead now.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief pause as every eye in the courtroom turned
toward her.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly added, in a reassuring manner:
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story No. 2:
</P>
<P>
   A lady, who by all appearances was a very proper lady, had
stopped at a discount store with her husband to pick up a number of
items.
</P>
<P>
   When they reached the check-out line, there was a number of
people ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to the car and start the air-conditioning,'' the
husband said, which at best was a lame excuse for not wanting to
stand in line.
</P>
<P>
   As he headed out the door, a woman next to the lady snorted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that just like a man,'' she said, shaking her head with
disgust.
</P>
<P>
   This woman, wearing short shorts and a crop top, looked anything
but a lady. Her hair was a brassy yellow, and her skin, the victim
of entirely too much sun, had begun to take on the appearance of
tooled leather.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice was somewhat brassy as well, with a harsh, husky edge
that indicated there was most likely a crushed pack of king-size,
menthol cigarettes inside her large, satchel-like purse, a
purported designer-series of questionable authenticity,
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' she sniffed, ``my husband's the very same way. I spend
most of the day working in the yard in the hot sun while he sits at
his computer in the air-conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   The lady, nodding and smiling and _ as always _ being the
pleasant kind of person that a lady is, tried to offer a bit of
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, yard work can be quite rewarding,'' she said, ever
so sweetly.
</P>
<P>
   The woman looked at her a long moment, sighed deeply and shook
her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey,'' she said, smiling a sad smile, ``I'm talking about
the wrecking yard.''
</P>
<P>
   East Texas women, you can't help but love 'em.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; Website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
