<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5538 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      07-28 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHELSEA WILL PLAY HOOKEY THIS FALL TO HELP HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chelsea Clinton will miss classes at Stanford
University this fall to help her mother campaign for a Senate seat
from New York and to be around the White House when her father
winds up his last few months as president, according to a White
House aide.
</P>
<P>
   The aide said that Chelsea, 20, a senior at Stanford, will still
be able to graduate in June because she has racked up enough
credits.
</P>
<P>
   After zealously guarding her privacy for years, the President
and Mrs. Clinton are allowing the public spotlight to fall on their
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea was very visible as her father's companion during the
Mideast summit talks and walks at Camp David. She even attended
dinners with the Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat where the substantive issues were discussed.
</P>
<P>
   So it was natural that she would be sitting in the White House
press room when a despondent Clinton announced the collapse of the
intensive, two-week-long negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   She kept her eyes on the podium and avoided contact with the
reporters in the room.
</P>
<P>
   While Americans will see more of her in the limelight of the
White House, she actually has had more public exposure abroad,
having traveled to several continents with her mother.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White House aides were shocked by the vitriolic fundraising
letters sent by William Powers, New York Republican chairman,
demonizing Hillary Rodham Clinton and her senatorial candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Powers hardly skipped any derogatory adjectives in his missives
soliciting donations from the party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   One letter addressed to ``Dear Friend'' called the first lady
``opportunistic, hypocritical, and egotistical.`` Powers goes on to
say she is ``abrasive and annoying, brash and bitter, calculating
and scheming, distant and deceitful, polarizing and power hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``in her ruthless quest for power, she claims to
be a 'New Democrat' but ``she's a fraud, a phony and a pretender.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a matter of time,'' Powers wrote, ``before she
attempts to become President Hillary Rodham Clinton. Our nation
couldn't survive that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows that some campaigns spend more time on personal
insults than on the substantive issues and that's the only way they
can attempt to get elected,'' a White House aide said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent editorial, the Buffalo News said: ``Powers' bitter
personal attack on Democratic candidate Hillary Rodham
Clinton...should be an embarrassment to both the party and its
candidate who has publicly aspired to a higher standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper editorial also commented that Powers' blast puts
the credibility of her opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio's, ``on the line
when it comes to mounting an issue-oriented campaign that he
promised and the voters deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only in America: At a ceremony in the White House State Dining
Room, President Clinton presented Connie Mariano, the White House
physician, with shoulder boards promoting her to the rank of rear
admiral in the Navy. Mariano's Filipino-American relatives burst
with pride as they witnessed her promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano, 45, a White House staffer since February 1994, has come
a long way for a woman in the Navy hierarchy. Always calm and
professional, she likes to point out that her father, Angel
Mariano, served six admirals as a steward, the only job Filipinos
could hold when he joined the Navy shortly after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Basking in the warmth of well wishers and old friends, Mariano
said: ``I am pleased to stand before you today as proof that
Filipino-Americans in the Navy no longer must go through the
kitchen, the back door or garage.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her medical staff have administered to the president and
vice president and their families as well as the hundreds of
employees in the White House compound.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Clinton's term in January, Mariano may take
another command or retire from the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The late pharmaceutical tycoon Justin Dart, Sr., a powerful
member of President Ronald Reagan's ``kitchen cabinet,'' might have
been startled at the high praise his son heaped on President
Clinton at a ceremony commemorating the 10th anniversary of the
American With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Wheelchair-bound from a post-polio affliction, Justin Dart Jr.,
is considered the father of the campaign to have the disabilities
law enacted during the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   He told the ceremony at the Franklin D. Roosevelt Memorial: ``I
love Bill Clinton. But even if I didn't, his record would command
my respect...Like Abraham Lincoln, Bill Clinton has fought to
preserve the authority of our federal union to guarantee the rights
of its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Dart told the president that his ``continuing leadership'' was
needed ``to help millions of disabled Americans who are still
unemployed, poor, in prison and in nursing institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, delivered a moving speech and
``signed'' his remarks when he related that his commitment to
disability was aroused by his brother, Frank, who died a month ago.
As a young man Frank Harkin couldn't get a driver's license because
he was told `deaf people don't drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said that when his brother was sent to school for the
``deaf and dumb,'' he said, ``I may be deaf but I'm not dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons traveled twice to Fayetteville, Ark., to visit
their old friend, Diane Blair, a professor at the University of
Arkansas, before she died of lung cancer. They also attended a
memorial service for her in Fayetteville where the first lady
spoke, telling several stories about her friendship with Blair who
shared her feminist outlook and love of tennis. Mrs. Clinton said
Blair who had good eyesight and ``never dropped a stitch when
working on needlepoint'' sometimes wore oversize glasses as a gag.
</P>
<P>
   The president laughed at times during a video showing Blair as a
young girl on a tricycle, as a professor addressing her students at
commencement and as a ``prankster wearing a Richard Nixon mask and
flashing the V sign.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cheney, who is Texas Gov. George W. Bush's choice of
running mate, is going to have a hard time defining himself as an
``outsider'' the way Bush would like to depict the GOP ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians from both parties are typically tempted to distance
themselves from Washington when they run for high office.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, 59, is a Washington fixture, having arrived first as a
congressional aide years ago. He later became a Nixon
administration aide, President Ford's White House chief of staff, a
six-term congressman from Wyoming and defense secretary in
President Bush's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he rushed back to Wyoming from Texas where he is an
oil company CEO, to register to vote in his native state. But he
and his wife still maintain a home in McLean, Va., a wealthy suburb
of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
