<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5574 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-NUDE-WEBSITE-HNS &LR;      07-28 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUDE-WEBSITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN ANTONIO GOES AFTER PROVACATIVE WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROY BRAGG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The controversy that has swirled around
Rackspace.com this week for hosting Web sites displaying
provocative images of nude children isn't the San Antonio company's
first brush with the issue.
</P>
<P>
   On May 5, Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon slapped the firm,
which offers Web space for hire, with a cease-and-desist order for
hosting a Web site that contained sexually explicit photos of
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Rackspace.com officials moved very quickly to remove the site,
Nixon spokesman Scott Holste said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very cooperative with us,'' Holste said of year-old
Rackspace.com. ``As soon as they got that order faxed to them, they
took that site down. It was a situation where Rackspace was caught
in the middle, but they reacted well.''
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the cease-and-desist order, Missouri's Nixon claimed
the Web site, which is now defunct, violated that state's consumer
protection laws by falsely claiming that advertising and selling
the images of children did not violate federal law.
</P>
<P>
   But Rackspace.com was hit with criticism again this week, when
an anti-child pornography group complained that it has been hosting
more than a dozen Internet sites that feature pictures of nude
children, and the company was confronted by the San Antonio
Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Rackspace.com's chief executive, Graham Weston,
vowed to follow through on his promise, made a day earlier, to
remove the 13 sexually explicit sites -- all of which prominently
feature pictures of nude minors -- from the company's computer
servers.
</P>
<P>
   And he promised to remove any further sites brought to his
attention that depict children in any sexually explicit situations.
Rackspace.com will continue its policy of offering free server
space to any child-advocacy organization, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Had the sites been deemed illegal by law enforcement or a court
order, Rackspace.com could've pulled the plug immediately, Weston
said. But since the cancellation of service is based instead on
Rackspace.com's desire to get rid of the sites, the contracts
stipulate the company give the site owners 30 days' notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I doubt it will take most of them that long (to move
their sites off Rackspace.com servers),'' Weston said.
</P>
<P>
   Weston defended his actions in the handling of the situation,
saying that it's impossible for him or his 130-person staff to
monitor the tens of thousands of Web pages on the company's 2,000
servers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Better A Millstone, a Monterey, Calif.-based
children's advocacy group, said they have tried since April to
convince Rackspace.com's staff to shut down the controversial
sites, but were stonewalled.
</P>
<P>
   The Rackspace.com staff, Weston said, was following company
policy, which was to remove illegal pages. None of the pages
involved, however, has been found to be pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know every single thing that goes on (at
Rackspace.com),'' he said. ``I didn't have any knowledge of these
sites. We have never condoned (those types of images), and we have
gone a step further than any other company would.''
</P>
<P>
   He likened his position to that of a cyberlandlord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we own an apartment complex,'' he said. ``What you
do in your unit, we don't know about (until someone complains).''
</P>
<P>
   The Web-hosting business is based on computer servers, which are
housed en masse in big rooms dubbed ``server farms.'' Companies
contract with Rackspace.com to rent a server, and that company is
responsible for the content that's placed on it, Weston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like they send us material and we put it up for
them,'' he said. ``They don't share information with us. They get
full access. We give them passwords, and they do everything else.
We're not involved in what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's technically impossible to (watch all of the sites
generated by customers),'' he said. ``We'd need an army of people
to pull that off. And that's why we rely on people to call us and
alert us to these sites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had been illegal, we'd have already shut them down,''
he said. ``We don't like what they show. We decided to take a stand
on it. And we're probably the only company that has taken this
stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Aaron, who runs San Francisco-based MySpace.com, an online
storage company that also hosts Web pages, says his company's
policy is to remove any material that exploits children, even if it
doesn't fit the legal definition of child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   When Better A Millstone notified MySpace.com of objectionable
material last year, the staff was at a company party. But the site
was yanked within an hour, said Aaron and Better A Millstone
founder Mike Echols.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron agreed with Weston's assessment that it's impossible to
police every Web page stored on a firm's computer servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be brought to our attention because of the privacy
involved,'' he said. ``We aren't aware of what (consumers) are
storing. We rely on people out there, surfing the Web, who see the
pages and call us.''
</P>
<P>
   Children's advocates applauded Rackspace.com's move. Julie
Posey, who runs the Lafayette, Colo.-based site Pedowatch.org, said
explicit pictures of children can be found all over the Internet
and on the servers of lots of companies besides Rackspace.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all over the Web,'' Posey said.
</P>
<P>
   Echols was pleased but wary of Rackspace.com's change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to see it, but I'm not happy to see his remarks,''
Echols said of Weston. ``He hasn't gotten religion yet.''
</P>
<P>
   By that, Echols meant that Rackspace.com only reacted because of
pressure exerted by his group and the Express-News inquiry into the
sites. He said his organization is prepared to bring more pressure
onto Rackspace.com.
</P>
<P>
   Echols wants Weston's company to become more aggressive in
seeking out and eliminating all exploitative pictures of children
off the company's servers, even before complaints arrive.
</P>
<P>
   He said Better A Millstone can influence the company's policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can organize and we can send hundreds of e-mails to their
other customers,'' he said. ``We've done it before. We've sent out
e-mails hundreds at a whack.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will leave them in droves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
