 NOW YOU CAN TAKE YOUR OFFICE TO THE GYM
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.  
 By DAPHNE PALMER GEANACOPOULOS  
 c.2000 New York Times  
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happened while I was working out at my local gym not long
ago, warming up on a treadmill and humming a jazzy tune. From the
treadmill next to me came the sound of a woman giving a speech
about economic policy. I turned to look, and sure enough, a fellow
exerciser was reading out loud from a set of 3-by-5 index cards she
held firmly while she ran 12-minute miles.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, another song. A man on an adjacent Stairmaster was
editing legal articles, scribbling in the margins (and dotting the
pages with perspiration) as he listened to music on his headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Still another afternoon, a phone rang. It was the Lifecycle next
to me. A man wearing a ``Just Do It'' T-shirt answered his cell
phone and gazed up at a ceiling-mounted television tuned to a
financial channel. ``Sell!'' he shouted.
</P>
<P>
   This was beginning to feel like a trend. Eager to learn more, I
sought out the man on the Stairmaster and asked him why he had
chosen to take his work to his workout.
</P>
<P>
   He turned out to be Ken Anderson, a 44-year-old law professor at
American University in Washington, who replied that he was pressed
for time, juggling his family, job and five workouts a week. ``It's
the only way I can justify my time at the gym,'' he said. ``I can't
afford to be checked out of the day for two straight hours. It's a
time management thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Occhipinti, the president of American Fitness Professionals
and Associates, a certification and educational organization in
Ship Bottom, N.J., confirms that Anderson has lots of company.
``It's a fitness trend of big cities and affluent suburbs, where
people need information and are very stressed,'' Occhipinti said.
``It's a symptom of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Health clubs, once havens for relaxation, have responded to the
new demands by providing equipment that enables members to mix
efficiency with exercise. Televisions are tuned to the news,
courtesy phones are within easy reach, and at some clubs, Netpulse
stations (computers providing Internet access) are attached to
Lifecycle and Stairmaster machines. They enable members to do work
(and earn frequent-flier miles from Netpulse's airline sponsors for
every mile they pedal or step), from their gym-desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fact of life that people are busy,'' said Maeve
McCaffrey, a spokeswoman for the International Health, Racquet and
Sportsclub Association, a trade group in Boston. ``If members need
to be productive while they exercise, we are going to do everything
we can to make it easier for them to enjoy their time at the gym.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is convinced that this is a good idea. ``Doing
anything while on the treadmill is dangerous,'' said Dr. Nicholas
DiNubile, an orthopedic surgeon in Havertown, Pa., who is an
adviser to the President's Council on Physical Fitness and Sports.
``Talking on cell phones or reading while exercising can cause
nerve strain in the head and neck. Workout form is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Multitasking may be an efficient use of gym time, but it
compromises the quality of a workout, said Matt Johns, the former
director of operations at the Regency Sport and Health Club in
McLean, Va. ``You still burn calories, but the workout is not the
same,'' he said. ``There has to be a mind-body connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Brown, a behavioral scientist with the federal Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention, said that although there was
little research on working while working out, ``in general,
disassociating from the exercise experience, by doing something
other than exercise, can lead to risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Occhipinti knows that firsthand: he once saw a man fall and
break his arm while reading on a treadmill. But he adds that health
clubs are reluctant to reproach their clients. ``It's a delicate
situation,'' he said. ``You don't want to offend or upset the
client. We try to educate them about safety, but people are going
to do what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cotton, the chief exercise physiologist for the American
Council on Exercise, a nonprofit watchdog organization in San
Diego, agreed. ``Clubs provide all sorts of equipment _ TVs,
Netpulse, E-Zone,'' he said. ``It would be difficult to tell
someone not to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond safety, however, is another concern. Despite the lack of
research, many experts share the view that people who take their
work to their workout are missing a prime benefit of exercise: its
ability to reduce stress. ``Exercise is one of the few leisure
activities for relaxation,'' DiNubile said. ``Working while working
out is a missed opportunity at stress reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   But he won't find much sympathy at my health club. ``Working
while working out is stress-reducing,'' Anderson said. ``I'm away
from my office, the computer, and I'm further ahead in my work.
It's a sanity-saving device.''
</P>
<P>
   (Daphne Palmer Geanacopoulos writes for The New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
