 ANTIQUERS SEEKING AMERICANA FLOCK TO NEW HAMPSHIRE
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is foruse by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.
 (ART ADV: Photos of antiques from last year's New Hampshire shows
are available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In August 1957, the first New Hampshire Antiques Show _
sponsored by the New Hampshire Antiques Dealers Association _ was
held in two small rooms in Concord's New Hampshire Highway Hotel.
Seventeen dealers displayed Windsor chairs, hand-carved decoys,
pewter chargers, step-back cupboards and other American treasures.
</P>
<P>
   According to East Hebron, N.H., dealer Howard Oedel, one of the
event's founders and still an exhibitor, the show attracted a
lively following right from the beginning. ``The original group was
small,'' Oedel recalls, ``but enthusiasm was high and the caliber
of objects exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of those pioneers could have imagined that 43 years later,
the NHADA New Hampshire Antiques Show _ now held in the Center of
New Hampshire Holiday Inn in Manchester _ would still be going
strong, attracting thousands of enthusiasts annually and sparking a
weeklong celebration of Americana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the antiquing highlight of the summer,'' says collector,
appraiser and ``Country Living'' contributing editor Helaine
Fendelman, who has attended the show for nearly 20 years. ``There
are so many things to see and so many dealers to speak with. Simply
observing the wide range of objects is an education process in
itself''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the variety of items offered for sale _ painted
furniture, trade signs, folk portraits, redware pottery, and
colorful quilts to name but a few _ regulars share a sense of
excitement about seeing so many high-quality pieces in one place.
</P>
<P>
   ``People plan vacations around this show and travel long
distances to get here,'' says Judith Milne, co-owner of Judith &AMP;
James Milne Antiques in New York City, and a first-time exhibitor
at the NHADA New Hampshire Antiques Show. ``It's one of the major
destinations on the antiquer's calendar: New York City in January,
Philadelphia in April and New Hampshire in August.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, New Hampshire's Antiques Week begins on August 5 with
a live auction and ends with the week's cornerstone event, the
65-dealer NHADA New Hampshire Antiques Show, August 10 to 12. The
week's events include the Americana Celebration Antiques Show on
August 8 and the Mid-Week in Manchester show on August 9 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wait all year long for this show,'' says Rye, N.H.,
dealer Russ Goldberger, a nine-year participant, along with his
wife, Karen. ``Exhibitors often hold on to their best pieces for a
good part of the year to bring them here.''
</P>
<P>
   What people consider to be their ``best'' has changed over the
years. Oedel notes that when he started doing the show 43 years
ago, ``art pottery, Dedham pottery and ephemera weren't really
collected; today they're in demand.''
</P>
<P>
   At last year's show, some of the top-quality items included
Victorian alphabet blocks, blue-and-white transferware, Hitchcock
chairs, green-glass apothecary bottles, a circa 1880 folk art
birdhouse and 18th- and 19th-century pewter.
</P>
<P>
   While novices and seasoned attendees alike know that it's a good
idea to arrive at an antiques show early for the best chance to
score the great items, Goldberger advises checking back
periodically throughout the show's run, explaining that most
dealers park antiques-filled trucks nearby so they can restock
their booths as pieces sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're interested in American country antiques, this event
is something you need to experience at least once in your life,''
Goldberger says. ``But don't be surprised if you start coming back
year after year.''
</P>
<P>
   PLANNING YOUR TRIP
</P>
<P>
   While in Manchester, you will not fail to see the Amoskeag
Mills, built in the 19th century. This complex of brick buildings
still stretches for a mile along the Merrimack River and was once
the largest textile factory in the world. The mill buildings now
house dozens of other industries.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester has an excellent fine art museum, the Currier Gallery
of Art, with collections of American decorative art and paintings
by significant Americans ranging from 19th-century portraitist Ammi
Phillips to such 20th-century artists as Andrew Wyeth, Edward
Hopper and Georgia O'Keefe.(Web site: www.currier.org)
</P>
<P>
   The Zimmerman house designed by Frank Lloyd Wright belongs to
the Currier and is open Friday through Monday. Visitors must take a
guided tour ($7) with advance reservations required. (603-626-4156)
</P>
<P>
   Nearby Concord, with a population of just over 36,000 people,
has been the capital of New Hampshire since 1808. The state
Legislature _ with 424 representatives, the largest in the nation _
still meets in its original chambers. The New Hampshire State
House, built in 1819, has exhibits about the state's history and is
open year-round.
</P>
<P>
   South of Manchester is America's Stonehenge _ 4,000-year-old
granite slabs of unknown origin. Their alignment suggests to
scientists that they were part of an ancient calendar constructed
by people who had sophisticated knowledge of the movements of the
sun, moon and stars. (Admission: $7.95. For more information, call
603-893-8300.)
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations in the Manchester area range from the 250-room
Center of New Hampshire Holiday Inn (603-625-1000) to cozy country
inns like the four-room Stillmeadow B&AMP;B (603-329-8381.) For a free
New Hampshire visitors' guide call 800-386-4664.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the antiques shows offer food on site. In addition,
two dealer favorites in Manchester are Cafe Pavone (603-622-5488)
and Shorty's Mexican Roadhouse (603-625-1730).
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
