<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBO-HALL-LONG-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     07-28 1830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-HALL-LONG-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... -- him.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He didn't have any football heroes because he didn't have any
interest in the game. He was as slow and timid as he was large, a
target for roving bullies, and it wasn't until he was 13 that he
``realized I didn't have to take this crap.''
</P>
<P>
   But he got a lot more out of those Albion adventures than black
eyes and bloody noses. ``It was sport in its purest form,'' says
Long. ``That's where I developed a love for competition. No adults.
Just kids playing all day long. And we seemed to settle things OK
for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That also was the case at home. The bond was ironclad, if not
traditional. ``I was fortunate,'' says Long, ``to have family
members who cared very much about me.'' It wasn't the classic
nuclear lineup. But the affection he received from his mother's
four brothers _ John, George, Mike, and Bill Mullan _ Bill's wife,
Aida; Mike's wife, Edie; and above all, Howie's maternal
grandmother, Elizabeth, known to one and all as ``Ma'' before her
death two years ago, was just as enduring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howie didn't have a conventional upbringing,'' says Millen,
who got to know Long's family well during their Raider days. ``But
Ma Mullan loved him to death.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so, says Capone with a laugh, ``that if Ma walked into a
room and there was a dead body and Howie was standing on the other
side with a smoking gun, she'd say, `My Howie couldn't have done
that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not to that extreme, but Long recalls, ``My
grandmother always thought that I was going to be something
special. Why I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seemed to know one thing _ he wasn't going to be
especially successful if his environment didn't change drastically.
``I lacked discipline and direction,'' says Long, and in the
tumultuous days of court-ordered busing to integrate Boston's
schools, he also lacked a desire to attend class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was supposed to go to Charlestown High,'' he says, ``But it
was surrounded by police. A lot of kids weren't going to school at
all. I think because no one was going, I wasn't about to say,
`Well, I'll be the first one to go to school.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So as a 13-year-old high school freshman, he majored in truancy.
Long says he missed 45 days of classes. Other published estimates
have ranged from 40 to 60. ``It's like trying to figure out exactly
how many billions Bill Gates has,'' says Long. ``The number's so
big, who really knows for sure? But it's somewhere in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma Mullan wasn't amused. She decided it was time to get her
grandson to a place where he could study something other than
skipping school. A family council was convened at 7 Albion, and
Bill Mullan _ who worked two jobs, at the Boston Housing Authority
and as a part-time painter, to pay for the split-level home in
Milford where he lived with his wife and four children _ agreed to
take in a fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mullans considered this a chance to escape the volatile
atmosphere that had left Long's hometown under siege; Long had his
doubts. ``I tended to think in terms of the box,'' he says. ``I
thought you don't go outside the box, don't go outside that
realm.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lengths to which the Mullans were willing to go for him
made him sure of one thing: ``My uncles were great examples of
being someone your family could be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he had a long way to go to join them, starting 40 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that season-opening football epiphany, Bill Mullan
showed up outside the guidance office at Milford High with his
nephew. The mission: to get involved with football. To see if
athletic director and football coach Dick Corbin could use a big,
raw kid who wanted to be part of something.
</P>
<P>
   Corbin chanced upon the two in the hall. He was immediately
struck by several things. The new kid was big but quiet,
respectful. He and his uncle were refreshingly honest about the
boy's lack of football experience and scholastic inclination.
Corbin liked the way the boy made eye contact with him when he
spoke. And he admired the uncle's volunteerism in the name of
family. That was it. He took the two down to the locker room. He
would gladly give the new kid a chance, nothing more. No
expectations. No illusions. ``I certainly wasn't there because he
thought I'd lift the team's grade-point average,'' Long says.
</P>
<P>
   But that was hardly the extent of Corbin's and his wife Ruth
Ann's involvement with Long. ``I had some older kids, juniors and
seniors, who I put on him,'' says Corbin, who later became a
Harvard assistant under Joe Restic and now is Sharon High's AD,
``to give him direction and make him feel more at home.''
</P>
<P>
   And Long was deeply grateful for the attention. ``I felt like an
outsider when I went to Milford,'' he says, ``but then I met these
guys. I was fortunate to have become a member of the football team.
What the football team did for me was give me a sense of
belonging.''
</P>
<P>
   There's the other half of the equation. Maybe deep down, Long
felt out of place on the gridiron. But that uncertainty was
entirely self-generated. The people in his life _ his grandmother
and uncles, his cousins, his teammates, the Corbins, and later his
coaches in college and the pros _ displayed no such reservations.
They embraced him unequivocally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-boggling to think of the sacrifices that were made
in my behalf by so many people who never expected a thing,'' Long
says.
</P>
<P>
   As Ruth Ann Corbin puts it, almost incredulously: ``We never
knew he was going to be famous.''
</P>
<P>
   She says this not to exalt some noble gesture on her or anyone
else's part but merely to indicate that people helped Long because
they wanted to. He was that kind of kid _ not troubled or
troubling, just needing a little guidance. Ruth Ann, a longtime
high school English teacher at Blackstone Valley Regional, helped
provide it by tutoring Long in English and history, spending
endless hours at the Corbins' dining room table during the summer.
Dick helped provide it by nurturing Long as a player _ good enough
to help the 1975 Scarlet Hawks win the state title his junior year
_ but even more as a surrogate counselor, helping steer him away
from higher-profile, high-pressure colleges like Maryland and
Syracuse and Boston College and toward a smaller-scale atmosphere,
Villanova's, where his chance of thriving would be enhanced. And
Uncle Billy helped provide it by keeping his ward in line.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Mullan was a stickler for discipline, and certain rules
were inflexible. ``I was the only 220-pound kid in the neighborhood
who had a 9 o'clock curfew,'' says Long.
</P>
<P>
   Not that young Howie didn't push the envelope. Two of the older
players who initially guided Long and quickly befriended him, Tom
Cullen and Pat Cornelius, ``boosted him through the window some
nights,'' recalls Cullen, now the AD at Amherst High.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Billy had his suspicions, and one night, he set a trap.
``His uncle left a stack of tires under the window,'' says Cullen,
``and Howie made all kinds of noise climbing over them.''
</P>
<P>
   Long recalls the fallout from that arrival as ``one of five life
sentences I served'' while living with his uncle. ``I was always
getting grounded for life. It was a poor man's Walpole prison.''
</P>
<P>
   The facetiousness can't mask the affection. Long is devoted to
his uncle, who, through Corbin, declined to be interviewed but told
the former Milford coach last week, ``Howie realizes how much I
loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   With no visions of some grand reward. As Cullen put it recently
when he talked to Long, ``No disrespect, Howie, but you weren't
that good a player when you started out.''
</P>
<P>
   What he was, from the inauspicious beginning, ``was just so
appreciative of anything you did for him,'' says Ruth Ann Corbin.
Like when he attended a summer football camp with the Corbins and
he'd worn out his socks halfway through his stay; Ruth Ann bought
him a dozen pair ``for $3.99 or something at Bradlees,'' and Howie
acted as if he'd just received an Armani wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen believes Long was fortunate to come under the care and
guidance of the Corbins, just as he was that other people entered
his life at opportune times.
</P>
<P>
   There was his future wife, whom he met at Villanova and who
helped tutor him there. There was Lou Ferry, his position coach
with the Wildcats and a former NFL player who told pro scouts,
``This kid is just starting to learn football. If he gets with an
organization that shows some patience, you're going to have one
great football player.'' There was Restic, then a Miford resident,
who made Long a late addition to the North squad for the Blue-Gray
college all-star game; after Long won defensive MVP honors, pro
teams belatedly began to crank up their interest. There was
Leggett, who considers Long ``like a son to me'' and promised him
as a rookie, ``If you listen to me, I'm going to make you All-Pro,
I'm going to make you a lot of money, and I'm going to put you in
the Hall of Fame.'' There were his mentors among the Raiders
veterans, such as future Hall of Fame offensive linemen Art Shell
and Gene Upshaw, who waged some bloodcurdling battles with Long in
practice. ``He was crazy,'' says Upshaw, now executive director of
the NFL Players Association. ``When I say crazy, I mean intense. He
was always willing to take advice, learn how to go after guys.
Howie figured, `We're out here _ let's go.' It didn't matter to him
if you were in pads or just your underwear; it's football `and
let's go at it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There was Millen the iconoclast, who used to scorn Villanova's
virtually imperceptible impact on the NFL but made Long an honorary
alumnus of Millen's alma mater _ Penn State _ after the Wildcats
temporarily dropped football. ``I'd prepare him for the guys he was
going to play against,'' says Millen. ``I'd say, `This guy's from
USC,' and Howie would say, `I hate him.' Or I'd say, `This guy's
from Nebraska,' and Howie would say, `I really hate him.' And then
he'd go out and destroy them.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, there was Long himself. And that was the main
ingredient, despite his self-deprecation. ``Howie had a lot of
influences,'' says Mike Sayles, a successful businessman who was a
senior soccer player when Long entered Milford and remains one of
his closest friends. ``A lot of them played instrumental roles in
helping him along. But Howie's the one who's responsible for where
he is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Where he is is on the doorstep of becoming the first Boston-bred
Hall of Famer. Or is it the first Milford-bred Hall of Famer?
Cullen shakes his head over the tug-of-war surrounding claims to
Long. ``This was like college for Howie,'' he says. ``He came here
for three years and did what he had to do. But his roots are in
Charlestown. I always say, `His home is in his heart.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Where he seems to have plenty of room. ``The Hall of Fame is an
individual thing,'' says Long. ``But I hope a lot of people can
take a little piece of this and feel they're in the Hall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
