<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE HAS A FEW PASSING THOUGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Three days and counting to Miller Time and
the kickoff of the Bill Belichick era _ or at least the preseason
portion of the Belichick era.
</P>
<P>
   With Dennis Miller's Monday night opener _ New England and San
Francisco have been invited along for the festivities _ fast
approaching, Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe Thursday touched
several bases and summed up where his team is at this point in
training camp at Bryant College.
</P>
<P>
   --On exhibition games and Belichick's plan to get a good look at
quarterbacks Michael Bishop and Tom Brady Monday night and probably
again Friday at Detroit: ``I'd be happy with two preseason games.
I'd be ready to go. Five preseason games is a lot and I don't feel
I need to play all those games to be ready for the season, but
that's what we have. So I'll see a little bit of time in the first
two and then we'll pick it up for the last three.''
</P>
<P>
   --On Bishop: ``Mike's making a lot of progress. He's playing
much smarter football than he was a year ago. I think he has a much
better understanding of the offense and what's expected of him in
the passing game. I think he's really coming along.''
</P>
<P>
   --On the running game: ``You really don't know much about your
running game until you get into a game situation. But Kevin Faulk
has been running the ball very well. It looks like he's ready to
step into that role and maybe be a full-time back for us. He's
really doing a good job. We'll see.'' --On the team's
injury-wracked and makeshift offensive line that Thursday still had
second-year center Damien Woody as its most experienced player:
``They're doing well and I think Dante (Scarnecchia) is doing a
great job with them. The important thing for the young guys coming
in is to be in the right place and block the right guy, which
sounds easy but is actually an extremely complicated process. As an
offensive lineman in the league, it can be very, very complicated
to figure out who you have in the different pass protections and
different runs.''
</P>
<P>
   --On what it might be like behind that line on Monday night:
``Generally, early in the preseason you don't see a whole bunch of
looks. That should help us a little bit and then we can also
simplify things a lot with our play calls. I haven't seen the game
plan yet, but I don't anticipate coming in with seven or eight
different protections. I assume we'd just have two, three
protections where we can get somebody in front of everyone and we
should be able to do fine.''
</P>
<P>
   --On another way of looking at the patchwork line: ``You can
look at it two ways. One, yeah it is a little bit of a concern to
go into these games with a lot of untested linemen. But the flip
side of that is that you get a lot of young guys with some
experience who normally wouldn't have had it. Hopefully it will
benefit us down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   --On life ABC _ After Ben Coates: ``Those guys (tight ends Eric
Bjornson and Rod Rutledge) are playing well. They each have,
obviously, their own strengths. Rod is an excellent blocker who has
become much more proficient as a receiver. He's catching the ball
very well and he's become a much better route runner over the past
couple years. Eric is an excellent receiving tight end with good
speed and good hands and knows how to get open. He catches the ball
well but he's a little bit light (he's listed at 240 pounds to
Rutledge's 270) so we're not going to ask him to take on defensive
ends too much if we can avoid it. I think those two guys combined
should serve us well.''
</P>
<P>
   --On the offense overall: ``I think we can be explosive. I
really like the offensive scheme and I like Charlie (Weis) and his
philosophy on offense. I think we're going to be able to score
points. I don't think we have an incredible amount of depth at a
lot of positions, but if we stay healthy, I think that with this
scheme we can put up a lot of points.''
</P>
</TEXT>
