<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-AFTERMATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE BEAT WILL GO ON, AFTER NAPSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Don McLean and the old war horse ``American Pie.''
Friday, July 28, will go down in history as the day the music died
_ at least for the 20 million or so users of Napster.
</P>
<P>
   In the past nine months the wildly popular music-swapping
service has become a sort of cultural glue that defines a
generation that has grown up on the Internet. That was set to end
Friday night at midnight (Pacific Daylight Time), when the court
order to shut the service down went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens next? Will some other college dropout in a
baseball cap emerge as the poster child for digital music on the
Internet? Will millions of irate Napster users migrate to other
file-sharing services, sparking another slew of lawsuits? Or will
the recording industry figure out how to woo Napster users by
marketing its products online?
</P>
<P>
   It all comes down to a simple verb. Napster defenders insist
that music needs to (itals)be(unitals) free, while record-label
execs contend that music just needs to (itals)feel(unitals) free.
And therein lies the crux of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The folks in the ``be free'' camp include free-speech zealots,
open-source advocates, and millions of college students and
teenagers accustomed to collecting and listening to music online.
These folks will likely migrate to (and aggressively promote) other
file-sharing programs available online. The Napster chat rooms were
abuzz with options Thursday as users pointed one another to Web
sites like www.napigator.com or www.cuteMX.com and to programs like
Gnutella, Freenet, or Scour Exchange. (The founder of Napigator
said traffic to his site had tripled Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   A user who goes by the handle Knotpine put it this way: ``We
will find new ways to download music . . . and there is no way on
earth that the music industry or anyone else can stop it.'' Others
spoke in revolutionary terms: ``We need to attack! We need to
provoke a riot!'' wrote a user called Operatorz.
</P>
<P>
   John Perry Barlow, former songwriter for the Grateful Dead and a
champion of free information online, was quick to advocate radical
action. ``I suggest massive civil disobedience,'' he wrote shortly
after the ruling came down. Thursday he said that the injunction
would create a backlash that is unstoppable _ and ultimately more
threatening to the record industry. The folks who are developing
other file-swapping programs will now work harder to create systems
that are impossible to trace. ``In that sense, (the record labels)
have created a whole new class of Hezbollah,'' he said. ``They have
radicalized the Internet community. Instead of developing networks
to address a problem, they are now doing it to make a political
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Clarke, in fact, is one of those people. The 23-year-old
Irish computer engineer is the mastermind behind Freenet, a
decentralized file-sharing network that offers complete anonymity
for its users. Napster shares all of its files through a central
server that can be shut down, but Freenet creates a spiderweblike
network of computers with no central source, making it impossible
to shut down. ``The ruling is sad, and it is dangerous,'' he said
Thursday. ``It also demonstrates that when you design a network to
promote free speech, you must design it so it isn't susceptible to
the form of legal attack that Napster has seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, recording-industry executives don't agree that music
needs to be free. But while they have been lagging behind in
getting their product online, their marketing executives have
absorbed one critical lesson from Napster: Music needs to feel
free. That was the rallying cry at Plug-In, a digital music
conference in New York that ended the day before the Napster
decision. At that conference, the ``be free'' folks sparred openly
with the ``feel free'' contingent. When Elizabeth Brooks, Napster's
vice president of marketing, said, ``We absolutely respect
copyright,'' Ted Cohen, EMI's vice president of new media, snapped
back, ``How many payments have you made?''
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen, an industry veteran, also said that he would be
willing to work with Napster under the right circumstances. That's
where the ``feel free'' notion comes in. All of the major record
companies and scores of Internet start-up companies are struggling
to develop online music services that make money but seem free to
consumers. Ultimately, these services will enable users to listen
to digital music not only on their computers, but also on stereos,
portable players, and even cell phones. Some, like EMI, are
planning to launch music-subscription services, which, like cable
television, seem free to users who simply turn on the switch
whenever they feel like it. The Internet company eMusic, in fact,
launched a subscription service this week; it has gained licenses
from scores of independent labels whose music is featured on the
service.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, musicbank, a San Francisco-based start-up, has been
negotiating licensing deals with the major record companies to
offer a service that will enable users to store music they own in
an online locker that they can access from any computer hooked up
to the Internet. This week, it signed a deal with Universal Music
Group, the major record label that is widely viewed as the least
likely to work with Internet start-ups and the most protective of
its music catalog. Users won't pay a dime for musicbank's service,
which is set to launch in September. The service will support
itself with advertisements; like radio, it simply feels free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first to sign agreements with all the labels will be well
ahead of the pack,'' said musicbank cofounder Pierce Ledbetter.
</P>
<P>
   And so the race is on to become the It brand in the post-Napster
era. A company called Click Radio offers a personalized Net radio
service that enables users to customize their song lists. Its
source of revenue: advertising. Another new company, called
Gigabeat, just launched a music portal that suggests music to its
users. Ditto for Music Buddha, which offers a music-recommendation
service.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these start-ups were founded by young engineers who seem
similar to Napster founder Shawn Fanning. The difference is that
they are not openly defying the music industry. And they're all
trying to capitalize on the Napster ruling by touting their
companies as ``legal alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the major labels are trying to figure out how to use
the idea of Napster and make money at the same time. One idea
encourages music sharing as a kind of viral marketing scheme. For
instance, one user buys a digital version of an album and then
sends it to a friend. That friend has two days to decide whether to
buy the music before it expires. In addition, the labels are also
quietly exploring ways to launch Napster-like sharing services that
make money via advertising or subscription fees.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the Napster revolution? Isn't part of its appeal
based in its underground status? ``It's like any revolution,'' said
Talal Shaloom, senior vice president of media at the Internet
security company InterTrust. ``The revolutionaries never get to see
the promised land.''
</P>
<P>
   That very notion infuriates the folks who started the movement
and who are now more determined than ever that music must be free.
``You cannot kill it,'' said Barlow.
</P>
<P>
   But many observers think that it will be business as usual in
the recording industry once the dust has settled around the Napster
case. The powers that be in the entertainment industry, after all,
can just keep suing and suing and suing while they buy time to
develop their own digital delivery systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you combat a black market?'' asked Shaloom. ``You don't
go after the pirateers. You compete. You create value.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the ``feel free'' folks are beating the ``be free''
folks, at least in the courts. Meanwhile, the developers of
alternative systems are vowing to keep the music flowing. That
tension has yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the decision, Napster CEO Hank Barry was asked
what would happen if his company lost the case. ``Maybe we'd have
the Napster memorial site,'' he said, without smiling. It doesn't
look like anyone will need it. One way or the other, digital music
will be available online.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
