<HEADER>
A5623 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      07-28 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIDO GIVES THANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Career boosts can come from unexpected sources. Try this one: A
new English singer named Dido suddenly gets a package in the mail
from chart-topping rapper Eminem. It's a copy of Eminem's song,
``Stan,'' complete with an added sample of Dido's voice lifted from
her tune, ``Thank You.'' Eminem asks permission to use the sample
and she says yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know the real story of how he got a hold of the
record,'' says Dido. ``The story I got is that (Eminem and his
management) heard it on TV and sampled it. Then they sent me a copy
of their song and I loved it. I thought it was great. I love the
way they made a sweet song about, basically, a psycho-obsessional
fan.''
</P>
<P>
   That description is putting it mildly. The song ``Stan'' is
about a male groupie who goes nuts because the protagonist, Slim
Shady, won't see him or send an autograph. So the fan drives off a
bridge, killing himself and his pregnant wife. The song is now a
hit on rock radio, though its subject matter has forced Dido to
answer some tough questions about why she would give permission to
sample her voice on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, some people have accused me of being homophobic and
misogynistic,'' she says. ``But I tell them, `Wait a minute. Let's
back up here. Just because someone sampled my track doesn't mean
that I'm a horrific character.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Eminem's album. I think he's a great entertainer. Yes,
he's out to shock, but that's his thing.''
</P>
<P>
   So who exactly is Dido (pronounced DYE-doe)?
</P>
<P>
   She's a former literary agent who grew up in London right around
the corner from pop-soul singer Sade (one of her early influences)
and is now 28. She was given the name Dido by her mother, who loved
classical literature. Dido is a queen in Virgil's ``Aeneid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a name that people typically call their children.
It's a pretty cruel thing to do, I'd say,'' notes Dido. ``I took
some bullying when I was younger because of the name, but you know,
you have to fight to counteract such things and that was actually
good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a great show-business name, because people certainly
remember it. ``My mother says, `You have a nice name now, don't
you?' '' Dido says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Dido was singing for fun, but spending most of
her time at her day job and working nights to get a law degree.
``But I burned out,'' she says. ``So I finally said, `Let me try
doing music.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She was in a band called Faithless, then opted to go solo, which
led to some dates on the Lilith Fair tour and to her solo CD, ``No
Angel,'' an instantly likable, ambient-pop record that includes the
sampled tune ``Thank You.'' It's a love song addressed to a
boyfriend (``Darling, I want to thank you for giving me the best
day of my life'') and is one of many personal songs on the CD.
Other songs express self-determination, plus the will to go on
after a romantic loss, self-acceptance (the song ``Honestly Ok'')
and a tune from which the CD title was taken, ``I'm No Angel,''
with the verse, ``I'm no angel, but please don't think I can't
cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote that song as an apology to my boyfriend,'' she says.
``The whole point of the album is being human and not being afraid
to make mistakes, never regretting what you've done, and learning
from your mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dido has a beautiful voice that has been compared to those of
Beth Orton and Sarah McLachlan. ``Beth Orton is on my same label,
but she's more of a folkie than I am,'' says Dido. ``As for Sarah,
I never heard her stuff before I came over to America, but when I
heard her at Lilith, I was blown away. I don't mind being compared
to people, as long as they are people that I like. These people are
great singers and I buy their albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was making my album, I was into Wiliam Orbit, Massive
Attack, and Portishead,'' adds Dido. ``And when I was younger, I
was really into the Police.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Dido's songs were written on guitar and piano, but a
couple are written around loops provided by Pascal Gabriel from
Belgium, who appears on the album credits as P. Gabriel. That has
made some people wonder if that stood for Peter Gabriel, but Dido
says, ``I wish!''
</P>
<P>
   The way she's going right now, Peter Gabriel and the rest of the
music world will know about her soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Godsmack moves up in Ozzfest: Boston's Godsmack has just gone
triple platinum (3 million sold) with its self-titled debut album,
which keeps spawning hits. Godsmack has also moved up the pecking
order for Ozzfest. Godsmack plays third to last, followed only by
Pantera and the man himself, Ozzy Osbourne. ``It's all good,''
Godsmack singer Sully Erna says from the road, ``though I must
admit we're kind of burnt out.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense that Godsmack is somewhat fried after being on
the road almost continuously for the past two years. ``But we'll
get a break after Ozzfest,'' Erna says. ``I plan to just sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Erna adds that it has been a real thrill to be followed at
Ozzfest by Pantera. ``They're the kings. There is no heavier band
than Pantera,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Godsmack was to have issued its second album later this summer,
but the release date has been pushed to Halloween. There's no title
yet for the album, though. ``We're still working that out,'' says
Erna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
