<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-GYM-MOCEANU-BOS &LR;      07-28 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-MOCEANU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOCEANU LOOKING TO GET BACK ON THE BEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ She will not talk about the lawsuit, the restraining
order, or any of the domestic nastiness that once plucked her off
the sports pages and dumped her into the tabloids. ``My family
situation is a closed subject,'' Dominique Moceanu says flatly.
``I'm here to talk about gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   After a hellish time when Moceanu ran away from home, sued her
parents to get her independence, then got a court order to keep her
father away, going back to the familiar simplicity of bars, beam,
vault, and floor has been a welcome refuge.
</P>
<P>
   The gym had been her home since she was 3, but when Moceanu went
back last year to work toward a return trip to the Olympics, she
went back in somebody else's body.
</P>
<P>
   She had been the youngest (14) and tiniest (4 feet 5 inches, 75
pounds) of the Magnificent Seven who found gold in Atlanta. Now,
Moceanu is nine inches taller and significantly (she won't say how
much) heavier. ``When I was little, I could flip around very
fast,'' she says. ``But just a couple of inches throws you off. I
had to relearn everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Why even bother? Why put yourself through a brutal grind just to
go where you've already been? ``A lot of the time people are, like,
`Why do you want to come back?' '', acknowledges Moceanu, who is
competing in the women's prelims at the US championships at the
Kiel Center. ``You've done it once, and you've got a gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else had moved on after Atlanta. Kerri Strug and Amy
Chow had gone on to college. Dominique Dawes had gone to Broadway,
then to college. Shannon Miller, Amanda Borden, and Jaycie Phelps
retired. Moceanu was the only one who returned for the 1997 world
championships. She was still only 15. Where else was she going to
go?
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Moceanu hadn't planned on continuing on to Sydney. ``I
was just tired of everything and wanted to get a break from it,''
she says. ``I didn't know if I wanted to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu's personal life, meanwhile, was coming apart. Her
father, Dumitru, had looted her trust fund of millions to fund his
Houston gym. In the fall of 1998, when she'd just turned 17,
Moceanu asked to be declared a legal adult. Then she got the
restraining order to keep her father from stalking her. (Moceanu
has since made peace with her parents and lives with her mother and
sister in Ohio.)
</P>
<P>
   She moved from Houston to Orlando to Colorado Springs and
finally to Cincinnati, where she began training this year with
coach Mary Lee Tracy alongside Olympic contenders Alyssa Beckerman
and Morgan White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be hard, and it definitely was,''
Moceanu says. ``But if you set your mind to do something and you
have the right people around you to help you, anything is
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the road back was more demanding than Moceanu had imagined.
She hadn't competed in two years, and she looked it. After he
glimpsed Moceanu at his first monthly boot camp in January, US team
coordinator Bela Karolyi, Moceanu's old coach, declared that she
was kidding herself, that she was looking for short cuts, and he
refused to invite her back.
</P>
<P>
   There were no short cuts, Moceanu finally realized, and set to
whipping her womanly frame back into competitive shape with
twice-daily four-hour workouts. Then she went to the US Classic
earlier this month and placed fifth, easily qualifying for
nationals. ``That helped me get all my jitters out,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, getting back on the Olympic squad is an uphill quest.
There are only six roster places, and Moceanu needs to be in the
top three after nationals and next month's trials at the
FleetCenter to get an automatic spot. All but one of last year's
world team members are in the chase, and Miller, Chow, Dawes, and
Phelps are all making comebacks, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to give it 100 percent and know that I can look back
and say I tried and I did the best that I could,'' Moceanu says.
``It would mean the world to me. I would be in tears just to be
back up there and bring home a medal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
