<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5637 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBO-HALL-LONG-2TAKES-     07-28 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-HALL-LONG-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S BEEN A LONG TIME COMING 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't easy to find a tree to provide camouflage _ at 6 feet
1 inch, 220 pounds, the new kid was a pubescent redwood himself _
but that's what he wanted. Something to stand behind so he wouldn't
stand out.
</P>
<P>
   At 14, Howie Long had arrived in Milford, Mass. with a
misleading label. Despite the rough-and-tumble presumptions
inspired by the deluxe physical package and the hardscrabble return
address _ 7 Albion Place, Charlestown _ there wasn't a lick of
aggressiveness or intimidation in him.
</P>
<P>
   Being uprooted from inner-city intimacy to suburban sprawl, he
``might as well have been moving to Europe, there were so many
differences socially,'' as far as he was concerned after his
grandmother, the family matriarch, had mandated the relocation to
salvage his education and his future. And he was basically shy, a
bit awkward in these foreign surroundings 40 miles west of downtown
Boston on the map but a world removed in the mind. He was a
curiosity seeker who didn't want anyone seeing him as a curiosity.
So he stood behind his hardwood shield and peeked at the strange,
fascinating autumn ritual unfolding in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   A red-and-white phalanx of his fellow students, lined up two by
two as if they were boarding Noah's ark, marched purposefully over
a wooden footbridge traversing a brook and linking acres of
practice space _ more green in one glance than he'd maybe seen in
his whole life in the city _ with the football stadium behind the
high school. And suddenly, where there had been synchronization,
now there was hysteria: cheerleaders cartwheeling around the goal
posts; the red-and-white legion's leaders bursting through a huge
horseshoe banner framing the uprights and featuring a giant scarlet
hawk, the school logo; and then the Scarlet Hawks themselves
shredding the welcoming artwork, the wings on either side of their
helmets making it look as if they just might take flight from the
end zone; the aluminum stands shaking beneath the 1,200 pairs of
stomping feet and bellowing lungs on either side of the field; the
band high-stepping smartly around the adjacent track that was wider
than some of the streets he'd frequented back home; the cacophonous
voices accompanying the strains of the Fighting Irish pep song,
with the key exhortation modified to cheer, cheer for ``Milford
High'' rather than ``old Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Norman Rockwell couldn't have painted it better,'' the new kid
thought. Only one thing was missing from the enchanting tableau:
Him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy,'' Long told himself, ``I want to be part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing, this business of belonging. It can be a two-way
street. And Howard Matthew Moses Long _ as his grandmother was wont
to call him in her sterner moments _ unwittingly traveled it in
both directions before winding up somehow with a harmonious
convergence rather than a head-on collision.
</P>
<P>
   Belonging. He had a visceral fear of its potential absence. But
that was rendered groundless by the fact that he was engulfed in it
virtually every uncharted step he took. As a result, he's at a
place where he can no longer deny it: at the threshold of the Pro
Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio, where Saturday he will be
ushered into immortality as a member of the Class of 2000, along
with former San Francisco 49ers Joe Montana, Ronnie Lott, and Dave
Wilcox, plus Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   The awe is evident as Long sits in his bucolic manse in
Charlottesville, Va. _ headquarters for the center of his universe:
wife Diane and sons Christopher, 15; Kyle, 11; and Howie, 10 _ and
considers the scope of his achievement in purely numerical terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it this way,'' says Long, 40. ``There have been
over 18,000 players in the National Football League. Of those, 171
(strictly) players are in the Hall of Fame. And of those, seven are
defensive ends. And now I'm joining them. Do you know how that
makes me feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed, obviously. But more important, accepted. Which is
something he never felt _ or allowed himself to feel _ for even one
play during three years at Milford High, four at Villanova, and 13
with the Oakland-Los Angeles Raiders (1981-93). Especially at the
last, most elite level. The eight Pro Bowl berths and the 1984
Super Bowl championship ring and the universal acclaim that ``for
five years, he was untouchable,'' as former Raiders teammate Matt
Millen puts it, meant nothing to Long. You couldn't take your
reputation out of the bank in times of crisis, so he ignored his.
All that mattered was that the next snap of the ball could expose
his overriding sense of inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   That's what fueled him to play the position as voraciously as
any man in the game's history. It's what longtime Raiders line
coach, Earl Leggett, who will present him for enshrinement,
recognized during their first lengthy conversation after Long was
Oakland's surprise second-round selection, the 48th overall, in the
1981 NFL draft: ``He was afraid _ afraid of not being a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen, now Long's teammate in the Fox NFL broadcasting lineup,
saw the corollary: ``The man's greatest asset was his insecurity.
He never thought he was good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Long supplies the almost mournful epilogue: ``I never enjoyed my
13-year career. It wasn't until afterward that I looked back and
thought I was pretty good. It was a 300-round fight, and you can't
sit around and say, `That was a great round.' It's on to the next
round.''
</P>
<P>
   Until finally, if you're lucky, you've knocked out all the
self-doubts. Long will receive that message Saturday, etched in
bronze. His bust in Canton will be the evidence of what he has come
to suspect more and more strongly since he transferred effortlessly
from a Hall of Fame career to a studio of fame career: ``I don't
have anything left to prove to anybody. I've had my time in the
sun. Everything else now is gravy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stirring this mix of metaphors, the fact is that the glare never
has been brighter, and if anything, the bowl is overflowing.
</P>
<P>
   Long's visibility has increased exponentially in his
post-football life. He would be enough of a household fixture just
for his featured studio analyst's work on Fox. But beyond that are
his ubiquitous television commercials for Radio Shack _ in which
his banter with his pretend spouse is so convincing that many
people think he's married to his costar, Teri Hatcher, rather than
his college sweetheart, Diane Addonizio _ and Coors.
</P>
<P>
   And there is his burgeoning film career, which includes a
supporting role to John Travolta in 1996's ``Broken Arrow'';
headliner status in the 1998 action adventure ``Firestorm''; and
support for Kevin Costner and Kurt Russell in the upcoming ``3,000
Miles To Graceland.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems his granite looks, conveying at once severity and
serenity, and his demeanor, sardonic yet somehow soft and
reassuring, are irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at the top of his game in all areas,'' says his manager,
Brian Medavoy. ``The hardest part is not getting him jobs, because
everybody loves him. It's availability.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because show business ambition is low on his priority
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in Charlottesville (not Hollywood),'' Long says. ``I
don't go to meetings. I tell (his management people), `If somebody
wants me and I can do it, I'd love to go out there.' But I don't
actively pursue it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Long's major focus is devoting time to his wife, a
college classics scholar and former corporate attorney whom he
calls ``my rock, my best friend, my everything,'' and his sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really impresses me is the way he is with his family,''
says former Villanova assistant Bob Capone, who recruited Long. ``I
told him, `It's almost like you've got a degree in child
psychology.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's one reason Long has turned part of his property
into a playground shrine, replete with a batting cage and pitching
machine, plus a basketball court with lights. Perhaps that's why he
considers his favorite indulgence ``watching my kids play. I'd
rather have 14 kids playing in my yard than not know where my kids
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prevailing wisdom, that is not a reflex
counteraction to his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His mother and father, Howard and Margaret, who separated when
he was 11, were not a presence in his formative years. He lived
through adolescence in Charlestown, which some consider a code word
for ``mean streets.'' But that doesn't automatically define a
Dickensian youth. Fifteen years later, Long still bristles at a
national magazine profile he considers to have overdone the urban
urchin angle _ ``Let's not beat this poor white kid thing to
death'' _ and his wary relatives generally shun the press, the
feeling of victimization lingering and hurting.
</P>
<P>
   What he grew up on, Long maintains, were close-knit streets.
Outside the three-decker on Albion where he lived for most of his
first 14 years, he and his friends would engage in endless games of
street hockey. The street was a dead end, so narrow that cars had
to park halfway up on the sidewalk to let traffic through, and if
two vehicles were headed in opposite directions, one would have to
back up so the other could get by. The clatter of the elevated
Orange Line running behind the street provided the background
music, and in those days of the Big, Bad Bruins, Long imagined it
was serenading Albion's answer to Bobby Orr _ him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
