<HEADER>
A5644 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-SENSES-BOS &LR;      07-28 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SENSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFT TOUCH KEEPS `FIVE SENSES' FROM BEING DULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE FIVE SENSES 
Written and directed by: Jeremy Podeswa 
Starring: Gabrielle Rose, Nadia Litz, Molly Parker, Mary Louise
Parker, Marco Leonardi, Daniel MacIvor, Philippe Volter, Pascale
Bussieres 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Five Senses,'' with its interweaving of five alienated
people, living in the same building in Toronto, emerging from their
respective states of isolation through their senses, sounds
suffocatingly schematic in outline. The five senses _ touch, sight,
taste, smell, and hearing _ are as prominently spotlit as the
actors. What saves the film from falling on its face is the light
touch of writer-director Jeremy Podeswa. ``The Five Senses'' is a
deft, elegant, melancholy tapestry of flawed outreach, and the big
reason it succeeds is Podeswa's courage in dispensing with a lot of
exposition and trusting the audience _ and the faces of the actors
_ to fill a lot of what otherwise would be gaps.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't do to hit too hard the melodramatic device that gets
the film rolling when massage therapist Gabrielle Rose, who is
stung by how out of touch she is with her teenage daughter (Nadia
Litz), asks the latter to take a client's child for a walk in the
park across the street. The daughter, dreamy and voyeuristic, loses
sight of the child. When the missing child can't be found, the
outlook turns grim. The teenage girl doesn't dare tell her mother
she's attracted to a young boy she met, who shares her interest in
voyeurism. The teenager herself hasn't figured out where she wants
to go with her feelings, or even what they are. Meanwhile, the
search for the little girl intensifies, along with everyone's
anxiety levels.
</P>
<P>
   Mary-Louise Parker's commercial baker, Rona, whose custom-made
party cakes look great but taste bland, finds her anxiety level
rising on the eve of the arrival of a chef, Roberto, whom she met
while vacationing in Italy. At the time, it seemed like a good idea
to continue the fling that had brought zest and savor to her life,
but now that he's coming to visit her on her home turf, she's not
so sure. She discusses the situation with her longtime pal, Daniel
MacIvor's Robert, a professional housecleaner who insists that he
can smell love, and means to look up all his former lovers, male
and female, to see if he can sniff some out in order to fill what
has become an amorous void in his life.
</P>
<P>
   The often catty repartee of Rona and Robert is as close as the
film comes to comic relief, a quality that does not figure much in
the life of their neighbor, Richard (Philippe Volter). He's an eye
doctor who is losing his hearing, and with sad desperation is
trying to amass a sonic memory bank against the day when he will be
completely deaf. These efforts include a phone call to his young
daughter, living in France with his estranged wife. There's a
danger that the senses will supersede the people embodying them.
But Podeswa stays cool and stays tasteful, and the actors carry
``The Five Senses'' past its pitfalls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
