<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BRYSON-BOS &LR;      07-28 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BRYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IRREVERENT LOOK AT DOWN UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MACDONALD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
IN A SUNBURNED COUNTRY 
By Bill Bryson. 
Broadway Books. 307 pp. $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting in a hotel bar in Canberra on about his fifth beer, Bill
Bryson is taking notes on how absolutely dull Australia's capital
city is, and makes a notation ``Buy socks.'' Inspiration flashes,
and he draws a cartoon of two salmon resting in a pool midway
through their exhausting swim upstream to spawn. One salmon tells
the other that solitary sex would be easier.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of comment you don't get from most travel
writers, and it is what makes Bill Bryson so much fun. For a while,
as he proclaims his love for Australia in the preface, there is
fear that Bryson might have softened, lost his edge _ but fear not.
</P>
<P>
   Travel writers don't always pay for their trips, and hence tend
to paint glorious pictures and omit the nitty-gritty that the rest
of us encounter _ the absence of laundromats in Vail, Colo., say,
or what happens to a jar of freeze-dried coffee in your luggage on
an overseas flight.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson writes with a frankness that probably gives the tourist
bureau fits, but the places he visits seem no less attractive for
his humorous honesty (certainly the Appalachian Trail hasn't
suffered much from his best-selling ``A Walk in the Woods''). The
quirks he focuses on provide a fuller sense of where he has been,
such as the little Australian town that has a combination
pet-supply-and-pornography store. He is fascinated, almost
obsessed, by the fact that, in December 1967, Prime Minister Harold
Holt went for a dip in the ocean and was never seen again. Bryson
even visits the site of what he calls the Swim That Needs No Towel,
where a guide tells him that Australia has built a memorial to Holt
_ a municipal swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Bryson has logged some considerable hours of
dull research (his bibliography lists 66 books) so that he can
present his readers with the more interesting highlights, such as
the discovery of an ant _ the missing link between wasps and ants,
actually _ thought to be extinct. There followed a lapse of 50
years before anybody was able to find such an ant again, and the
second sighting came by accident, when the expedition's truck broke
down 800 miles from the site where scientists hoped to find the
creature.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on this, Bryson notes that Australia is ``at once
staggeringly empty and yet packed with stuff. Interesting stuff,
ancient stuff, stuff not readily explained.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aborigines, for example, must have come to Australia by raft
or boat _ long before anybody else was using either. Once they
arrived, however, they forsook seafaring and apparently forgot
about it. The author grows somber when discussing the plight of
these people, whose treatment brings to mind that of Native
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson gives us a feel for Australia's vastness as he crosses
parts of it by train and automobile. Instead of singing Ninety-nine
Bottles of Beer on the Wall,'' he copes with the bleak Outback by
making up ``approximately forty-seven'' new verses to Australia's
unofficial national anthem, ``Waltzing Matilda.'' (The bawdy stanza
he reveals to readers makes about as much sense as the original.)
So sparse is some of the countryside that ranches have to be
enormous to support their livestock. Australia's biggest ranch is
larger than Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone knows some part of the story of how rabbits were
brought in and overran Australia, devouring everything in sight,
Bryson gives us an update. A deliberately introduced virus that
affected rabbits and nothing else killed 99.9 percent of them. The
10th of a percent that survived were, of course, resistant to the
virus, so rabbits are on the rise again.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a number of Australia's unique creatures are
endangered, many being killed by, of all things, the common cat, of
which there are 12 million thriving in the country's wilds. People
are slow to recognize that species are disappearing because most of
them are nocturnal and seldom seen.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson's favorite animal-disappearance story involves a
naturalist named Gerard Krefft, who, he recounts, ``in 1857 caught
two very rare pig-footed bandicoots. Unfortunately for science and
for the bandicoots, Krefft soon afterward grew hungry and ate them.
They were, as far as anyone can tell, the last of the species.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-NUTTY-BOS &LR;      07-28 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-NUTTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NUTTY' MURPHY GOES FOR LATEX, NOT LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
NUTTY PROFESSOR II: THE KLUMPS 
Directed by: Peter Segal 
Screenplay by: Barry Blaustein &AMP; David Sheffield, Paul &AMP; Chris
Weitz 
Starring: Eddie Murphy, Janet Jackson, Larry Miller, John Ales,
Jamal Mixon 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (crude humor and sex-related material) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a whole lotta latex goin' on in ``Nutty Professor II:
The Klumps.'' The trouble is that not enough else is going on,
apart from marathon workdays for Eddie Murphy. Except for the latex
Martin Lawrence got away with in ``Big Momma's House,'' Murphy
corners the market on the stuff in ``Nutty Professor II.'' Of
course, Murphy got there first. The Klump family, which stole his
first ``Nutty Professor'' movie, can be viewed as a six-pack of Big
Mommas, with Murphy, then as now, playing all the Klumps except for
the teenaged one embodied by Jamal Mixon. Here they get a lot more
screen time than they did the first time around. But while their
roles are _ no double entendre intended _ meatier, they can do only
so much to ward off sequelitis.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Nutty Professor'' delivers laughs, especially if you
like flatulence jokes. Some, like those involving the indignities
of aging, are laid on pretty thick, especially when it comes to
salty but saggy grandma, who all but runs corpulent Sherman's
troublemaking alter ego, Buddy Love, off the screen. Buddy's back,
embodying repressed Sherman's inner sex maniac. It must have been a
relief for Murphy to play Buddy, if only because it meant he didn't
have to climb into makeup and a big rubbery envelope that day, as
he did when playing each of the five Klumps.
</P>
<P>
   More interesting than the film is the way it was made. Murphy
played one Klump per day until a given scene was completed. Then
all the footage would be edited together. The result is more of a
tribute to Murphy's concentration and memory than to his comic
inventiveness. Even Buddy isn't quite as outlandishly devilish this
time around. He's merely larcenous, out to steal Sherman's new
invention, a beaker of youth serum, so he can sell it to a
pharmaceutical company for big bucks before the university does.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sherman already won Denise's heart the first time around,
when Jada Pinkett played her, there isn't that much for Janet
Jackson to do as Denise this time around, although she does it
prettily, right down to putting on an enthusiastic face when she
sits down to Klump family dinners and, later, forgiving Sherman for
the words Buddy puts in his mouth. The first movie peaked with the
Klump dining room scene. This time, there are a couple of Klump
bedroom scenes that will make nobody's heart beat faster, and an
eating scene in which the Klumps wipe out an establishment foolish
enough to offer an all-you-can-eat buffet. Otherwise, no bodily
function is neglected in this film, whose theme repeatedly
confronts the ways in which the body betrays, or at least
embarrasses, one.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can say that Murphy doesn't knock himself out to keep the
laughs coming in ``Nutty Professor II.'' Some are rudely funny,
including a sight gag involving Larry Miller's sleazy university
president and a giant hamster. But there just aren't enough
successful jokes and sight gags to get around the fact that a lot
of ``Nutty Professor II'' plays like filler. You know a film is
desperate when it throws in a lame ``Star Wars'' gag, as ``Nutty
Professor'' does. The Klumps are as sweet as they are crude. That's
the secret of their appeal. That and their ability to always be
bickering yet loving. But ``Nutty Professor II'' is neither funny
nor endearing enough to conceal the fact that, like its star, it
fills the screen with a lot of padding. Less rubbery and more nutty
would have been better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5653 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-MESSINA-BOS &LR;      07-28 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MESSINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JO DEE MESSINA SHARES THE GOOD TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A work ethic was deeply ingrained in Jo Dee Messina from an
early age. She grew up in the Boston suburb of Holliston, where she
was one of four children of a single mom who worked long hours to
make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom worked until she was falling off her seat,'' says
Messina, noting how her mother, Mary, did everything fromrun an
answering service to serve as a substitute math teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Messina watched and learned and, now, by dint of her own hard
work as a country singer who wouldn't accept failure, has become
one of the biggest stars in Nashville. Messina's last album, ``I'm
Alright,'' sold 2 million copies. She also became the first country
female to notch three consecutive No. 1 singles _ an incredible
feat considering that only two years before, she was starving and
didn't have enough money to buy a Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't have a lot of time for myself, but it doesn't
bother me,'' says Messina, 28. ``I love to work _ and I get a lot
of happiness out of working, so to work all of the time doesn't
bother me. I truly believe you have to work hard for the things you
get out of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Messina has continued to perform 200-plus shows per year. She
also has a new CD, ``Burn,'' due Tuesday _ an edgier record than
her last, filled with exuberant songs of survival and hope that
form a logical step forward from ``I'm Alright.''
</P>
<P>
   She no longer gets to Holliston very often _ only about once a
year _ but has taken many of the touchstones from those days with
her. Her mom and her aunt run her fan club. Several friends from
Holliston work for her in various capacities.
</P>
<P>
   Messina does not forget early loyalties, and now that she has
had some success, she is giving back in ways that even have her
business managers nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get hollered at all the time to stop giving it all away!''
says Messina. ``But I'm now able to take care of those around me
and it feels great. My sister has four kids, and I help her with
them. And my mother lives (in Nashville) and I help her. And I help
with miscellaneous things here and there. Some things you read
about, some you don't. . . . I really believe the best part of this
career is being able to help other people.''
</P>
<P>
   An example was when someone left a letter at the merchandise
stand at one of her shows, describing a person who needed a
wheelchair ramp to a van. ``I didn't get the letter until two shows
afterward,'' Messina says. ``Then I read the note to an audience
and said, `Let's set up a box by the T-shirt stand. Throw your
spare change in and whatever you get, I'll match it and we'll send
it to this guy.' So that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   As we speak on the phone from her Nashville home, Messina is
almost embarrassed because, that morning, her coproducer, Tim
McGraw (who is also a multiplatinum performer), presented her with
a gift of a 1957 silver Thunderbird in honor of her success. Why a
silver Thunderbird? It's the title of one of her songs.
</P>
<P>
   Messina is rare in this day and age when celebrity usually means
self-indulgent displays of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as going out and spending a lot of money, I don't do it
for myself,'' she says. ``I can look at something, and whether it
costs $10 or $10,000, I don't know the difference and it just
doesn't matter to me. I'm totally not consumed by price tags.''
</P>
<P>
   She is even embarrassed that her fiance, Don Muzquiz, who is
also her tour manager, gave her a diamond ring that she considered
too extravagant. ``I almost downsized it,'' she says. ``It screams
money and I can't stand that. Money is important to live, but it
doesn't make you a good or a bad person. It doesn't mean you're
better than, or not as good as, another person.''
</P>
<P>
   This philosophy was likewise ingrained during her Holliston
childhood, where her family never had much money. ``Good God, no.
We were lower middle-class, but as middle-class as my mother could
make it,'' she says. ``My mother raised us by herself. Here's a
woman who has four kids and she's trying to keep a roof over their
head in Massachusetts, where the taxes are extraordinary and the
cost of living is higher than normal. And she just did the best she
could. She didn't have a lot, but we had a lot of love and a very
close family. And that's what is most important.''
</P>
<P>
   Messina has sometimes been said to be estranged from her father,
Vincent, who was an athletic director and football coach in
Holliston, and is now a school principal in St. Johnsbury, Vt. Yet
the truth is that she's on good terms with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We e-mail each other all the time,'' she says. ``He's one of
my biggest fans, and I'm his. My dad didn't live with us, but I get
a lot of my energy from him. He'd always come over and spot me in
gymnastics. There's no hard feelings there. He's my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Like fellow Nashville sensations the Dixie Chicks, Messina has a
young, passionate audience that relates to her effervescent
personality and her will to succeed. ``I have a huge teenage fan
base,'' says Messina. ``Seventy percent of my crowd is under 25. I
haven't been able to figure out why. Maybe it's because I'm a kid
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Messina's new album captures her spirit in such songs as the
rocking ``Dare to Dream'' (``We're still young and in love . . . We
believe we can do something if we dare to dream''), the ballad
``Burn'' (``Be anyone you want to be / Bring alive your
fantasies''), the sexy ``Closer,'' the change-of-pace, socially
conscious ``Angeline'' (a warning to a young girl ``hanging out
with the wrong crowd''), and the percolating ``Saturday Night''
(``Let the night begin'').
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the songs were penned by female songwriters
(Messina didn't write anything for this album, though she has
written before), Messina says she didn't realize the preponderance
of female-written songs until someone pointed it out. ``I was just
looking for good songs that I could relate to,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did she consciously look for songs that express the ``I'm
Alright'' philosophy for which she's become known.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the way I've evolved,'' she says. ``When we were
searching for songs, they would have to hit me and be something
that I feel. And it just so happened that (survivor songs) struck
me. I'd listen to them and say, `You go, girl! I know how that is.'
These were the songs I gravitated to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
