<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-CHENEY-NAT     07-28 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CHENEY-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        WITH CHENEY AT HELM, HALLIBURTON BANKROLLED GOP
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Anand Giridharadas  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (July 28) - The private sector may have taken Dick
Cheney out of politics, but it did not take the politics out of
Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking the helm at the world's largest oil services
company, Cheney has been an active financial patron of Republican
causes - and appears to have led his firm to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based Halliburton Company - where Cheney has been
chief executive since 1995 - has become a stalwart backer of
conservative causes, pumping hundreds of thousands of dollars into
Republican war chests since Cheney's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Keith, a vice president at Halliburton, said Cheney's
position had brought the company higher visibility in Washington.
And records suggest that visibility was buttressed by a stream of
cash from the company's political fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know him and he has been a presence up there. If you have
a personal knowledge of somebody, you might pay more attention to
them,'' she said. ``We try to persuade Congress to see things our
way. I would think his stature adds immeasurably to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Cheney took over, Halliburton has given around $400,000
each election cycle, totaling $1.2 million over six years. All but
$40,000 of it has gone to Republicans, either as soft money - the
loosely regulated gifts to parties - or through political action
committees, which fund clusters of political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cheney arrived, Halliburton's political contributions
were far smaller and fell somewhat more evenly between the parties.
In the 1992 cycle, the company gave $67,000, a quarter of it to
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have seized on Cheney's selection as an opportunity to
color the ticket as an instrument of ultra-conservative corporate
interests, particularly the oil industry. Texas Gov. George W. Bush
is also a former Texas oilman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Cheney got to Halliburton, their donations to the
Republican party shot up,'' said Democratic National Committee
spokesman Jenny Backus. ``It is no secret that captains of big
industry see Bush as their guy. I think the American people are
going to reject that. They don't want a government of big oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney himself has donated $52,000 to Republicans since joining
the company. His giving list favors the most conservative members
of Congress: Sens. Trent Lott of Mississippi, Phil Gramm of Texas
and John Ashcroft of Missouri, as well as Reps. Henry Hyde of
Illinois, and Dick Armey and Tom Delay of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton has given most of its money to the political action
committees and to the Republican party, which in turn spends it on
individual races. Company officials have also spent tens of
thousands of dollars sponsoring the annual House-Senate dinners,
which earns them invitations to mingle with party bigwigs.
</P>
<P>
   Even the personal donations of company employees go
overwhelmingly to the Republicans. Federal Election Commission
records show nearly 300 gifts in the last decade, all but a handful
to the GOP. More recently, 17 employees wrote checks to the Bush
campaign. Most of them gave the maximum $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think I'm the token Democrat at Halliburton,'' said
Keith, who gave Bill Clinton $1,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Already in this election cycle, the company and its employees
have put $293,000 into political coffers, and only $9,000 of it to
Democrats. That includes $124,000 to the political committees and
$129,000 in soft money. The company gave $500,000 in the 1998
off-year election, and $418,000 in the 1996 race.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5704 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SPI &LR;      07-28 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST EXCITEMENT MAY BE OUTSIDE AS GOP CONVENES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican National Convention, which begins
Monday in Philadelphia, will be a big, boisterous affair,
expensive, tightly scripted, colorful and occasionally dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   But is it important? Will it mean something in the great
democratic process? Or will it be a relic from another era, an
excuse for delegates to take a nice trip, to party and get free
political memorabilia?
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and delegates insist conventions play an important
role, even though the two most important jobs _ selecting a nominee
and writing a party platform _ will already be done.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, conventions have become sophisticated exercises in
public relations and the art of throwing elaborate parties.
Educating the public and energizing party activists _ what one
political operative calls ``cheer practice'' _ are the most
important byproducts of conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state Rep. Jennifer Dunn, a convention co-chairwoman
who will be attending her seventh convention, said the gathering in
Philadelphia is significant even though it will have no surprises
or intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of convention that every political leader
loves to see and every political pundit hates,'' she said. With no
issue or question to be settled, Dunn said, the convention will
reward people who've worked hard for Republican causes. For the few
who will watch it from afar, ``it will project'' GOP issues.
</P>
<P>
   Polly McWhorter could be Exhibit A for Dunn. A retired teacher
from Auburn, McWhorter has been a loyal and reliable GOP activist
for three decades. The convention, she says, is the big payoff for
all that effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a very exciting thing to go and see how it all works
at the very top of the process,'' said McWhorter, 77. ``And I just
think its going to be a really thrilling thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For most Americans, however, the words thrilling and convention
do not fit together. Dull and tedious are heard more frequently.
Television ratings have fallen for each of the past three
conventions. Indeed, one of the most memorable moments of the last
Republican convention in 1996 was when Ted Koppel packed up and
left in the middle of it, complaining there was no news to cover.
</P>
<P>
   What excitement there is will likely come from outside the
convention hall. More than 20,000 protesters have converged on
Philadelphia to draw attention to an array of topics, including the
death penalty, global trade, police brutality and the need to find
a cure for AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Only two protest rallies have been officially sanctioned,
however. The first will come on Saturday when protesters stage
their March for universal health care. The Unity 2000 march and
rally will follow on Sunday. Additional events are planned Monday
to draw attention to poor and homeless families and Tuesday to
protest the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Another sideshow is the Shadow Convention organized by
influential Republican Arianna Huffington, designed to focus on
issues that the traditional parties ``just won't touch'' such as
poverty, campaign finance reform and the drug war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties' flimsy and farcical platform process points up
the vacuum at the center of what we call our political debate.
Their addiction to massive doses of campaign cash has distorted our
policy priorities and led to the neglect of critical issues,''
Huffington said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the speakers scheduled to appear at the Shadow Convention
are Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz. (who also will speak at the real
convention), Russ Feingold, D-Wis., and Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.;
actor Warren Beatty; comedian Al Franken; the Rev. Jesse Jackson;
and former GOP vice presidential candidate and former Housing
Secretary Jack Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   GOP convention planners are so sensitive about the public's
short attention span and competition from the Shadow Convention
they are going to great lengths to quicken the pace and attempt to
add spice to the proceedings. Republicans are striving to keep
speeches to 5 minutes or less and by showcasing ``real people''
rather than politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The convention is built around a theme a day and a noticeable
shortage of politicians with major speaking roles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there will be people like retired Gen. H. Norman
Schwarzkopf, who will appear Tuesday evening via satellite from the
USS New Jersey to underscore the importance of military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, California small-business owner Hector Barreto
will be the GOP's human face of its commitment to Latino voters.
Barreto will discuss diversity. Also on Wednesday, single mother
Kim Jennings from Arkansas will discuss the need for tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   The convention also will offer a prominent spot to Erik
Weihenmayer, who has climbed some of the world's tallest mountains
despite being blind. Weihenmayer will lead the Pledge of Allegiance
on the convention's first night.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Craig, a Republican from Idaho who is responsible for
getting the party's message out to the public, said the convention
is important even when public interest is low.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're going to hear from both conventions are the
priorities of both of the parties. Those priorities are ultimately
going to make it into policy,'' he said. ``And it's significant. It
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Craig and Dunn are invited to all the A-list parties and
receptions underwritten by corporations and wealthy interest groups
that run non-stop through convention week.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of the GOP fully recognize the public's
disinterest in their marquee event and they have taken pains to
attract attention and entertain viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts, however, could not convince the networks. Just as
they did four years ago, the networks are avoiding the convention.
The problem was so acute that in 1996 the Republicans spent $1.3
million to buy time on the Family Channel.
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen this year because GOP organizers believe there
will be sufficient coverage by cable stations and over the
Internet. The heavy-duty lifting will be left to cable stations
such as CNN and C-SPAN, which will televise both conventions
gavel-to-gavel.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the audience will be small. In 1992, less than
one-third of the available audience watched any of the events,
according to the networks. Viewership fell even more in 1996, when
less than 20 percent of people watched.
</P>
<P>
   None of this comes cheap. While TV audiences have declined, the
cost of staging conventions has soared.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention will cost $63 million, while Democrats
say they expect to spend $35 million. Each party gets $13 million
in public money for conventions. Much of the rest is raised through
corporate donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
