<HEADER>
A5708 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BKO-PATTERSON-HNS &LR;      07-28 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-PATTERSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SHE NEVER LOST LOVE OF THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _When Leone Patterson decided to give up
international basketball in 1996, New Zealand coach Carl Dickel
implored her to keep playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if I couldn't hold on for just another four
years,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   But she had to say no. She was in her 30s, and had played nearly
a decade for the New Zealand national team. So, even though she was
the captain of the squad, which was slowly building toward a
possible berth in the 2000 Olympics, it was time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson was set on pursuing a business career, and the
accounting firm she was working for had transferred her to the San
Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the background, though, basketball still tugged at
her. As a pastime, she began playing in leagues like the San
Francisco Bay Area Pro-Am, against good competition, including
several WNBA players.
</P>
<P>
   The skill, and the love of the game, were still there.
</P>
<P>
   She kept in contact with Dickel, who brought the New Zealand
national team here in November to play several college squads.
Patterson was then a member of a Pro-Am all-star team that was
meeting the same area's collegians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did better against them than New Zealand did,'' Patterson
said. ``I thought then that I still could be a part the national
team.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing led to several others, including three exhausting
plane trips home and back for Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   In early January, despite the fact that she had been away from
international competition for more than three years, she made the
cut from 24 to 16 players. Last month, at 37, she was on New
Zealand's final Olympic Games roster of 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard,'' she said. ``All the other players have their
own coaches and trainers. I have to do all my training on my own.
But I've been helped a lot by Chiron, the biotech firm in
Emeryville that I work for, and my boss, David Smith. They've been
really supportive. When I told David that I was keen on trying for
the Olympics, he said, `That's great. So what's the problem?'''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, a slim, 6-foot-1 forward who played at Chapman
College in Southern
</P>
<P>
   California and has lived six years in the United States, is a
member of the Marin team in the Pro-Am league this summer, and
scrimmages against male players whenever she can. She also had a
tryout with the WNBA Los Angeles Sparks and works out frequently at
Stanford with ex-Cardinal players turned pro.
</P>
<P>
   But this is different, because it will be the first Olympic
appearance ever for the New Zealand women's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some feeling that we didn't deserve to be there,''
she said. ``Australia, as the host nation, got an automatic bid, so
we were able to qualify in the Oceania zone. But then we played
Slovakia (one of the higher-rated European teams), and even though
they had six players taller than our tallest player, we won one
game against them and lost the other two by less than four points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really turned our team around in terms of confidence.
After we beat Slovakia, we said, `You know what? We deserve to be
in the Olympics.'''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has stopped worrying about her own level of play, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the better players when I left New Zealand in
`96,'' she said, ``and I left on a high note. So it was quite a bit
of a risk, from a pride standpoint, to put myself on the line
again. It's been very satisfying to me to learn that I can still do
it, that it's still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson hasn't decided exactly what's next, basketball-wise,
after Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just assessing things as they come now,`` she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she has her green card, and likely will keep working in the
Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work here is much more challenging than back home,`` she said.
``There are no biotech companies in New Zealand. But my family is
all there, and I still have a house there. I can't afford to buy
one here.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
