<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-NUTTY-PROFESSOR-HNS &LR;      07-28 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTTY-PROFESSOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (For release Saturday, July 28) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `NUTTY PROFESSOR II' FILM ABOUT FLATULENT FAMILY IS A GAS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By WESLEY MORRIS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.2000  &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the four years since we first encountered Sherman Klump, the
overweight genetics nerd has traded Jada Pinkett for Janet Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   It distinguishes Eddie Murphy's first ``Nutty Professor`` remake
from its more raucous, extra-strength redux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutty Professor II'' is about how the Klumps (all five of the
grown-ups are played by Murphy) are the engorged American Family,
made flagrantly obese lest you mistake them for people who would
fit comfortably within the confines of a sitcom. And what lies
beneath the geriatric sex talk, incendiary flatulence, sagging
breasts and sprints to the buffet spread is a family saga about
home fires and familial oneness and the time-honored acquisition of
a daughter-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   After years of crushing on Jackson's Professor Denise Gains,
Sherman has asked her to marry him, or rather he's thrown a
pheromone at some CGI fireflies to do the magic. Apparently,
wedding bells and chow bells make the same joyful noise: Mama Klump
starts a kitchen-bound outfitting for Denise in the wedding gown
she was married in.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman, for his part, is experiencing jitters that make him
turn into the Eddie Murphy-who-looks-like-Eddie Murphy, but who
flails and shouts like Little Richard.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for Sherman's wedding, this Murphy _ the
ultra-randy Buddy Love _ has returned to resume the battle of the
``Ehhhddeees`` (to borrow a Murphy coinage from ``Raw``) in the
not-inappropriate guise of an erection, jabbing at Sherman's tux
during a riotous dream-time wedding to Denise.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy's head pops through the zipper like a Trojan condom
jack-in-the-box; the rest of him crawls through the seat of his
pants. He's both brilliant secretion and horrendous excretion: For
those of you keeping score at home, they're one and the same. The
seam is split on the fabric of good taste, but it's a lewd image
with the summer's only psychological yuck, a declaration of war
between a fat man and his skinny id.
</P>
<P>
   It immediately kicks ``Nutty Professor II'' into a chaotic quest
for control, something Murphy's love interest has had for years.
(Convincing any Jackson to star in a gene-manipulation comedy, by
the way, passes for shrewd.) A shrink informs Sherman that there's
a little Buddy Love dying to get out of everybody's zipper, but
Sherman's case is more acute.
</P>
<P>
   It's like Teddy Pendergrass trying to suppress his inner Sisqo -
that hyperactive sexual question mark dubiously wild about thongs,
who, for 15 minutes, seized hold of America and, for 15 seconds,
the film's soundtrack. Sherman has just discovered the formula for
the fountain of youth, and a big pharmaceutical outfit is offering
Sherman's university a hefty sum. But since Sherman extracted Buddy
Love from his DNA makeup, and Buddy has come to crass life thanks
to a moment of weird science starring a single dog hair, he wants
to sell Sherman's formula, while poor Sherman's IQ free falls.
</P>
<P>
   The film becomes a beat-the-clock story, written by a four-man
crew that includes ``Mr. Show`` co-creator Steve Oedekerk and the
``American Pie`` production team _ ``Chuck and Buck`` actors Paul
and Chris Weitz.
</P>
<P>
   The film's narrative pleasures pale next to the marginalia and
incidentals that Murphy supplies. ``NP II's'' sketch affinities and
gross-out factor are all-you-can-eat, so is the doppelganging.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a hamster that's in heat and shoots its droppings,
Murphy inhabiting a runaway toddler with a lactation fixation that
almost surpasses Jim Carrey's in ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' and the
triumphant return of the sexed-up Granny Klump, who sans her
dentures is as nasty as she wants to be. No disrespect to Peter
``Tommy Boy'' Segal, but his tasks as a director seem limited to
Eddie-wrangling, getting prime reaction shots and seeing that the
hamster launchings hit the extras properly.
</P>
<P>
   Segal's juggling, which gets understandably sluggish by the
finale, is impressive. But the movie's real point of interest _
Murphy to the infinite power _ seems out of his hands. If you want
a clue as to how deep Murphy's inspiration reaches, simply watch
his mouth and eyes in the quick reaction-shot cutaways. The
difference between Carrey and Murphy is the difference between
refraction and embodiment.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is playing six characters, which brings him closer to the
human comedy of Peter Sellers than Carrey's contortionist
caricatures, which only recently have discovered moderation and
compassion. One man's an ebullient, scary comic strip, the other's
a graphic novel.
</P>
<P>
   And from under Rick Baker's eerily astute prosthetic makeup,
Murphy affectionately saves the Klumps from fatsploitation, giving
them a boundless humanity that imparts black familial
keepin'-it-realism, while letting the rest of America in on the
joke.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, meanwhile, is locked in a reflexive battle of his own
between his lovable-cuddly side and the crass self of yore. His
Buddy Love isn't so much a surrogate for old-school Murphy so much
as the stand-up that ``Delirious'' and ``Raw'' hath wrought.
</P>
<P>
   The Buddy-Sherman skirmish is about the debasement and
subsequent rescue of black comedy from the clutches of ``Comic
View'' and the sorely missed, defunct ``Russell Simmon's Def Jam.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as staggering as Murphy is, the problem remains - how can
Jackson's Denise love Sherman as hard as she does? It's a little
disappointing that the film is so literal about the Buddy-as-dog
bit, keeping him mostly away from Jackson, though she did once
declare that nasty boys don't mean a thing. Finding Sherman's
insult of her mother merely odd, Denise clearly represents the
love-is-blind lobby. Does love have a nose? Maybe she just agrees
that as flicks about dangerously flatulent families go, this one's
a gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1501EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5714 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BUCHANAN-PROFILE-SPI &LR;      07-28 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-PROFILE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN STILL RUNNING HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pat Buchanan is running hard for president again,
rebellious and incendiary as ever. But this time, he's a rebel
without a party _ the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old Buchanan, who was a senior aide to such
Republican icons as Richard Nixon and Ronald Reagan and who, as a
candidate for the GOP presidential nomination in 1996 scared the
daylights out of Bob Dole, walked away from the party last October
to join the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons _ and the words _ were vintage Buchanan. The
Republican Party and its candidates, he said, were going soft,
sacrificing long-held values, even diminishing the Constitution.
According to Buchanan, both the Republican and Democratic parties
had become ``front groups for corporate power and special
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, Buchanan said in an interview, Republicans are
nearly indistinguishable from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are Xerox copies of each other,'' Buchanan said of
Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush, citing such issues
as trade, immigration and defense. ``The Republicans have been
Clintonized. It's like professional wrestling. ... They engage in a
wild brawl and then afterward you go into a bar and they're buying
each other a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan made the same point in a speech earlier this year.
``Clinton hails NAFTA, GATT, the WTO and globalization, and like
trained seals, Republicans clap in unison,'' he said. ``Mr. Clinton
favors open borders, a million new immigrants a year and handing
over high-tech jobs to low-wage workers from foreign lands. Bush
and (John) McCain cheer him on, and the congressional Republicans
applaud.''
</P>
<P>
   While he walked away from the party that sustained him for so
many years, Buchanan did not abandon the views that make him such a
political flash point. Indeed, those views remain the anchor of his
long-shot presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He opposes racial preferences in any form, promises to ``defend
our borders'' and slash the number of immigrants entering this
country. He wants to sharply reduce foreign aid, void global trade
agreements such as NAFTA and put an end to more liberal commerce
with China. He would severely limit U.S. military involvement in
places such as Kosovo. He would loosen America's ties to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Critics accuse Buchanan of being an isolationist, a charge he
rejects. ``I think America ought to be involved in the world,'' he
said in the interview. ``All I want to isolate America from is from
wars that don't involve U.S. interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan vows to be tough on crime, underscoring that pledge
with one of his best applause lines. ``When I raise my hand and
take that oath of office, I promise you, the first thing I do, I'll
turn to Bill Clinton and say, `I'm president, sir, and I'm the
chief law enforcement officer, and you have a right to remain
silent.'''
</P>
<P>
   What he wants, in short, is to take a right-hand turn from the
``cattle-fed conservatives inside the Beltway'' who control today's
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has undeniable charisma and had some successes in
previous campaigns. But this time, while Buchanan's supporters may
be just as passionate as in the past, they are not nearly as
numerous. Buchanan's campaign is limping along, registering about 6
percent, according to a recent Washington Post/ABC News poll. That
compares with about 9 percent for the other third-party candidate,
Ralph Nader of the Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   It is far less support than Buchanan got in 1996. Then, as a
Republican, Buchanan tapped into voters' nervousness about the
economy, about jobs being siphoned overseas and a general unease
about the United States' stature in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues have all but disappeared in the roaring economy.
Peace has broken out across much of the globe, calming fears about
America's role in the world. All of that has drained the vigor _
and the attention _ from Buchanan's best audience, disaffected
white males.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the support he inspires burns hot. It includes
influential _ and rich _ conservative insiders such as Roger
Milliken, a billionaire textile magnate from South Carolina who has
stood with and financed Buchanan for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the handmaiden of any other interest except the
nation's interest,'' said Jock Nash, Milliken's representative in
Washington. ``We love the guy. He's for America first, friends
second and everything else third. He's his own man. He doesn't give
some stock answer written for him by some technocrat. He's without
guile.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan vehemently disputes suggestions that he traffics in
discrimination. He rejects charges that he is locking arms with
anti-Semites or far-right militia groups.
</P>
<P>
   But in the tone that made him a nationally known television
personality on such shows as CNN's ``Crossfire,'' Buchanan refuses
to apologize for his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our campaign and our Buchanan brigades and our new Reform
Party, they are folks who want to fight,'' he said during a news
conference last week. ``They are folks who are willing to stand up
and go down to defeat. They are folks who don't care what The
Washington Post or the Washington press corps says about them. They
believe ideas and ideals matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is right about that. In 1996, he seriously challenged
Kansas Sen. Dole, the eventual GOP nominee, in the early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   He later was criticized for fatally weakening Dole by forcing
him to embrace a more conservative platform that voters rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as then, Buchanan's pitch is strident and unbending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party speaks for the forgotten Americans whose jobs
were sent overseas to finance the boom market of the 1990s that the
rest of us enjoy,'' he said in his farewell speech to the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   His glory days, however, appear to be behind him. This year, he
is fighting a bitter battle within the Reform Party to earn its
nomination. He is also fighting _ on the airwaves as well as in
court _ a decision by the Commission on Presidential Debates to
lock him out of the fall contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Beltway thugs have ganged up to be beat up the new boy on
the block,'' Buchanan said during a July 20 news conference. ``Why
are they reflectively hostile to the idea of third parties? Quite
simply, they don't control us. They don't have a golden hook in us.
We speak our own minds; we speak our beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest fight of all, he is locked in a tight struggle
with John Hagelin, the former Natural Law Party nominee, to carry
the Reform Party banner in November. The outcome is meaningful,
because whoever is the nominee will qualify for $12.5 million in
federal matching funds. Buchanan says he can't campaign without the
money, and he can't win unless he's allowed to take part in the
debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is clearly to get this nomination, to secure the
$12.5 million which we are due, to get us on the ballot in all 50
states, then to go hard from the 15th of August to the 20th of
September,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he earns the nomination and, more important, gets into the
debates, Buchanan is confident the votes will come. ``I think these
issues will resonate, I think we can make a persuasive case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
