<SLUG> BC-POP-KDLANG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S THE SUNNY SIDE OF K.D. LANG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Singer-songwriter k.d. lang is enjoying an invincible summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Performing in the summertime is the very best,'' lang said in
a phone interview from Los Angeles. ``There's lots of fresh air,
you get to be outside and you get rejuvenated by the sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   Summertime was an appropriate time for lang to launch her latest
tour. Her new retro-pop album, ``Invincible Summer,'' was inspired
by her move several years ago to Southern California _ the land of
endless summers _ and several years of self-discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The lush, romantic ``Summerfling'' sets the tone for an album
that recalls the wistfulness and good vibrations of the Beach Boys
and the Mamas and the Papas, as well as the sun-kissed sounds of
'60s bossa nova.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet, sometimes melancholy collection includes ``It's
Happening to You,'' a psychedelia-tinged love song inspired by a
day at the beach, and ``Love's Great Ocean,'' a Roy
Orbison-inspired tune written with longtime songwriting partner Ben
Mink.
</P>
<P>
   The album's title comes from a line by writer Albert Camus: ``In
the depths of winter, I finally learned that within me there lay an
invincible summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The album is very positive and it reflects where I am in my
life,'' lang said. ``But I'm certainly well aware that this will
pass. Unfortunately, that's just the way of life. I think I'm just
trying to appreciate the moment, but being realistic as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The personal journeys that led to lang's ``Invincible Summer''
began in the mid-'90s after an exhaustive tour in support of her
``All You Can Eat'' album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really burned out because I had been touring and
recording since I was about 21 _ about 15 years straight,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I just needed to stop and take stock, I guess, and reflect
on what I had accomplished. Because when you're on the treadmill,
you don't really see any results.''
</P>
<P>
   The eclectic Canadian-born singer took about four years off,
going back to work just long enough to record ``Drag,'' the 1997
follow-up to ``All You Can Eat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Drag'' was a wonderful album, exploring human need and
addiction through such songs as ``Don't Smoke in Bed,'' ``Smoke
Rings'' and Steve Miller's ``The Joker.'' But the album's title
might have described lang's growing sense of ennui.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the music business, you become very isolated just being
backstage, in a car, in a hotel room, not having any real
day-to-day life with any real people,'' lang said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I took some time to sort of settle down, get a house, get a
new dog, have a relationship and look at my career. And I
discovered that those things were powerful, powerful influences on
my personality and my relationship toward my music. And I found
that I really did love music.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang, who began her career in the early '80s as a ``torch 'n'
twang'' singer inspired by the music of Patsy Cline, left her
native Canada and bought a home in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go to the Home Depot and had like 25 people working on my
house. I went to see Wynonna Judd at the Greek Theater and did
things I never really had a chance to do for a very substantial
part of my adult life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I realized that life is art and that music is my craft. It
took a huge burden off my music because I realized that I don't
have to put all of my artistic nature into an album. It's just an
album. I don't have anything to prove anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme of ``Invincible Summer'' was in place before lang had
written any songs. ``I shot the album cover before I recorded the
record. I designed the songs around the idea of my head space. The
concept was fairly focused from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories of childhood and youth played a role in the songwriting
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of my childhood, I think very often of summer
things. And summer just reflects so many attitudes. When you're in
a comfortable stage in a relationship it's kind of like summer to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-producing the album with lang was Damian LeGassick, who has
worked with Madonna and techno artist William Orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to update my sound and have some new blood,'' lang
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took the k.d. lang sound and, using the same musicians that
I've worked with for years and years, updated it without
overproducing it or making it a dance record. There's a little bit
of a new lacquer on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though lang began her career as an alternative-country artist,
her connection to Nashville today is almost nil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a connection with country music in my soul,'' she
said. ``And I would expect that two or three records down the road
I'll make the most legitimate, the most raw and the most
straight-ahead country record I've made yet. I can feel it. I just
have to sit down and write it. It'll be thrilling because I love
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
