<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPER CASING WILL RESIST ROT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July   30, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The trim around my exterior doors is decaying. You can chip
out wood with your fingernail. This softness goes halfway up the
trim from the floor. The trim is only five years old. Can I restore
it or replace it?
</P>
<P>
   BRANDY BRANDON, Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The trim may be too thin to try to dig out the decay and fill
with an epoxy wood filler. The reason the decay occurred is, I
think, because the casing (the trim) was applied and then caulked.
The idea was to keep out moisture, but if any moisture got behind
the trim it was trapped, causing the decay. Old-fashioned casing
was installed loose, uncaulked, so if moisture got behind it, it
would drain away, allowing the casing to last longer.
</P>
<P>
   So, to replace, try this: Use pressure-treated wood to avoid a
similar semi-disaster in the future. Such wood takes primer and
paint and/or stain very well. Cut off the old trim, being sure to
take all the decayed wood. Cut a new trim to match the old, and
nail it. Do not caulk it, except where the two pieces meet. Or,
replace the whole casing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I spilled ammonia on an old dark oak table, and you can
imagine what happened. It made a big white spot. Can I remove that
spot, or do I have to refinish the top?
</P>
<P>
   J.F., Boxford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the ammonia bleached the finish, so the top must be
refinished. Usually, cloudy stains such as water rings from a glass
left on the table, or from heat, are on the very top of the finish,
and can be rubbed off with an abrasive. But you can still try the
abrasive technique on the ammonia stain. Rub the stain with
toothpaste, which has an abrasive in it. If the stain is reduced,
keep at it. If not, refinish.
</P>
<P>
   Sand the top to the bare wood, apply a penetrating oil stain to
match the old color, and apply two or three thin coats of an
oil-based polyurethane varnish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I live on the waterfont and get a lot of storms. I noticed
that lighthouses have orange-shingled roofs, but roofers don't seem
to know why. Do you? I figure if lighthouses, subject to high winds
and bad weather, have roofs that stand up to the weather, I could
install a similar roof on my house. My roof shingles tend to blow
off more than normal, or more than on houses inland. What is the
best shingle to resist winds and bad weather?
</P>
<P>
   JAMES ADAMS, Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I looked up the lighthouses in the western Great Lakes (my
old stomping grounds), and many had orange or red roofs, similar to
those in the East. While some of those roofs are asphalt, I imagine
some are clay tile, very durable and resistant to blowing off. And,
very expensive. There are companies that do tiles, but they are not
that common anywhere except in the South and Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   For you, I think organic shingles will work well. Organic
shingles have a saturated felt core, as opposed to modern shingles
that have a fiberglass core. All are covered with asphalt, and
gravel for color. Organics are more flexible than fiberglass, and
should resist winds better.
</P>
<P>
   Also, have the roofer put a slather of roofing cement under each
shingle along the edge of the roof, where the roof goes up at an
angle. This roofing cement should also go under the shingles along
the eave edge of the roof. It is along the edges that wind often
gets a bite, and mostly edge shingles get blown away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The black stripes on my aluminum awnings are faded. Can I
paint them with black paint? I think the paint is baked enamel. I
want to keep the contrasting white, which is in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   SAM DANIELS, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sand the stripes reasonably heavily, then wash with Spic and
Span and water. Let dry, and paint with a thin coat of an oil-based
primer and finish with latex house paint. Or, use a Krylon aerosol
spray primer and finish. Mask the stripes thoroughly to avoid
getting paint where you don't want it.
</P>
<P>
   While expensive (as paints go), the Krylon spray cans are a
convenient way to spray certain painting projects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The bathroom in my 1850 house is 7 by 12 feet, and runs
parallel to the roofline. There is an attic above the suspended
ceiling, and five horizontal beams connecting the two walls, which
act as a base for the flat ceiling (attic floor). I'd like to
remove the existing ceiling and make it a cathedral ceiling. Can I
take those horizontal beams down?
</P>
<P>
   LEVON Chorbajian, Billerica, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you can, especially since their full length will not
be removed, with their remaining length over the adjacent bedroom
ceiling. But to be safe and legal, consult an architect or
structural engineer, for a fee, to make sure you can, and how to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   You might be allowed to remove all the beams or just one, two,
or three. If you have to leave some, they can act as a decorative
part of that cathedral ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
