</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Repeating for Springfield, Mass. and all needing.)  
 ANDREA NICHOLSON MAKES BUYING SWIMWEAR A LITTLE BIT EASIER  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEYMOUTH, Mass. _ In a strip-mall storefront near the former
naval air base lies an emotional front line for body-image angst.
And Andrea Nicholson may as well be the Florence Nightingale of
this battlefield, selling swimsuits at Ujena to women who mostly
see flawed hips, abdomens, or chests taunting them in the dressing
room mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   For four summers Nicholson, a 20-year-old dental hygienist in
training, has had what seems like a simple job: Be attentive. Keep
the store clean. Watch that the clip hangers don't snag the
merchandise. And most important, make sure customers leave with the
most flattering suits.
</P>
<P>
   The last is the difficult part _ convincing women that they can
look good in a bathing suit.
</P>
<P>
   One recent cloudy day, a middle-aged shopper heads straight to
the racks, quickly scours them for two-piece suits, and strides
into a fitting room. A few minutes later, the customer hands over
the pile of rejects and leaves before Nicholson can say, ``May I
help you?''
</P>
<P>
   This Nicholson knows for certain: She's not the only woman who
would like the figure of a supermodel, even though she's fit and
thin enough that some customers might be satisfied to swap bodies
with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see women in here that are beautiful. Look awesome in
bathing suits. Everybody has something about their bodies that
they're self-conscious about,'' Nicholson says. ``It definitely
makes me feel more comfortable with the fact that it's just not me
who feels that way. You can pick your body apart and let it consume
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson's neighbor, Peter O'Keefe, who owns two Ujena
franchises, told her she could work for him when she turned 16.
She's been here every summer since then, and now earns money for
college textbooks while getting an education she never expected in
self-image and fragile psyches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing my boss ever said to me is `Don't ever let
somebody leave the store looking bad.' I thought, `How can I say
that to them?' But they're very open to other people's advice. We
usually tell them if something doesn't look right,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just helping them look good in a bathing suit,'' she
adds. ``You're boosting their self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson tries to stanch customers' frustration by making sure
they have the right size, immediately. But alas, on this particular
morning, the only person in the store who seems happy _ besides
Nicholson _ is the delivery man.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about guys and bathing suits?
</P>
<P>
   She thinks it's ``ridiculous'' when women let their boyfriends
or husbands choose the bathing suit they buy instead of just
offering advice. ``There are some guys who are angels. But guys are
guys,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I tell boys I work at a bathing-suits store, it's like
`ooooh,' '' she adds. Then the wisecracks start: Do you model them?
``It's not like that,'' says Nicholson, who, on this particular
day, is wearing a handkerchief-print sundress and platform sandals,
not the merchandise, at work. ``It's just retail.''
</P>
<P>
   This retail store specializes in D cups, allowing customers to
choose the bra of a two-piece suit in one size and the bottoms in
another. So maybe it's to be expected that the figure dilemma most
of Nicholson's customers face is above, not below, the waist. ``So
many girls, even myself, have big chests,'' she says. ``It's a
self-conscious thing. You're showing more than you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Her advice? Go up a size in the top and down one size for
bottoms because they stretch when they hit water. Sagging bikinis,
Nicholson notes, like everything else that sags, can be really
unattractive.
</P>
<P>
   Think again, she adds, before opting for a one-piece suit to
cover a large chest. Often maillots offer little support _ even
with those elastic-bands-as-underwires _ and hence don't always
look best. Surprisingly, bandeau tops look better on many women
than customers believe. Larger-busted women should consider a
properly fitting bikini, as should more average sizes. A 34B woman
should pick a medium-size top, she says, pointing to a wall of
suits, and ``take the pads out.''
</P>
<P>
   To the customer concerned about her hips (but not her belly),
Nicholson suggests that string bikini bottoms _ believe it or not _
can be slenderizing. ``Sometimes if you have chubby legs,'' she
advises skeptical customers, ``it's best not to get something
fuller.'' And it takes ``pencil-thin legs'' to make shorts-style
bottoms flattering. ``I can't wear them for anything,'' Nicholson
says.
</P>
<P>
   What about skirted suits? Here Nicholson is the equivocating
saleswoman. ``Um,'' she says, ``people like the coverage. A lot of
mothers come in for tankinis and skirts.''
</P>
<P>
   And style? Thongs are popular this year. ``To each his own,''
Nicholson says. Matching mother/daughter suits, she adds, are
``very cute.'' And silver lame is a trend on the upswing.
</P>
<P>
   To the customers who wander in looking for beach chairs or
plastic nose protectors to block the sun, Nicholson says sorry, she
sells only bathing suits and cover-ups.
</P>
<P>
   During the lull between customers, Nicholson vacuums the gray
industrial-grade carpeting or straightens the racks and racks of
bikinis, strings everywhere. She wipes down the two tanning beds,
tucked in the back of the store, after each use.
</P>
<P>
   After watching customers, many of whom ``are addicted'' to the
20 minutes of solitude under the tanning lights, Nicholson was
moved to try it herself. She was so nervous the first time she
tanned that she accidentally left on her socks. Now, she does it
once a week, for free, and hopes she's not doing it often enough to
tempt skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   So it's hard to tell from looking at her that, between work and
summer school, Nicholson doesn't get much chance to go to the beach
in the cornflower blue string bikini that she bought with an
employee discount at Ujena.
</P>
<P>
   But when she does, she says, ``I get so excited when I see a
Ujena suit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
