<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-SOC-MILBRETT-HNS &LR;      07-28 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MILBRETT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOCCER STAR TO SHINE IN SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JERRY BRIGGS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one sense, Tiffeny Milbrett highlights the glorious recent
past in U.S. women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett, a native of Port- land, Ore., scored the deciding goal
in the gold-medal game at the 1996 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Kawasaki 5000'' for her speed on the field, she also
led the team in scoring during its run to the 1999 Women's World
Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   Golden memories, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   But the 27-year-old Milbrett also represents the future of her
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett not only will play a critical role in the team's quest
for a second Olympic gold in September, she also will rev her
engine for the high-visibility New York franchise in the Women's
United Soccer Association inaugural season next year.
</P>
<P>
   Tony DiCicco, the WUSA's acting commissioner, said the 5-foot-2,
130-pound forward can live up to the marquee billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways,'' said DiCicco, ``Tiffeny is considered our most
dangerous player. She will be playing for the New York team, and
her star qualities will be very visible.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco coached the women's national team for six years before
he resigned last fall to help start the professional league. He
predicted that Milbrett, with an engaging personality, would be a
good fit in the spotlight of the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a bit of a nut,'' DiCicco said. ``Tiffeny and Julie
Foudy, they will say anything, and it's all genuine. But the real
reason she'll be in New York is her star quality. We needed a
big-time star there. She was one of the few we considered, and she
was excited to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with the national media in May, Milbrett brushed
off a suggestion that the women's team needed to win a gold medal
in Sydney to boost the pro league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we want to win (the gold), for sure,'' Milbrett said.
``(But) I don't think the pressure to have to win is there. I think
most definitely that pressure was there in 1999 (at the World Cup).
This year, it's not so much pressure from the outside anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. team has stormed through Europe in its Olympic
preparation, Milbrett has been hotter than a South Texas summer
day.
</P>
<P>
   She has scored three goals in six games this month, and DiCicco
sees a different player than the one who joined the national team
on a limited basis in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiffeny was always a tremendous talent,'' DiCicco said in a
telephone interview. ``She was one player who had scoring instincts
and tremendous acceleration. She shot righty or lefty. The
difference now is, she's more mature.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the early '90s, Milbrett lacked high-level
endurance and needed ``bushels'' of opportunities to score a goal,
DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   She beat Brazil with the only goal of the game in the DFB 100th
Anniversary Tournament in Germany on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' DiCicco said, ``she doesn't need a bushel-full of
opportunities, and that's a sign of maturity. She can win a game
for you in the 90th minute. I think she wants to be known as the
best striker in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, Milbrett has been overshadowed to an
extent by teammates Mia Hamm and Brandi Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   But Milbrett believes that name recognition is high for all the
players among fans who have purchased tickets and sat in the stands
for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite possibly, people who don't attend our games know only a
couple of names,'' Milbrett said. ``But the people who come to our
games, they know everybody's names. I noticed that back in 1998 at
the U.S. Cup in Boston, against Mexico. That's when I noticed a
change in the crowd -- the excitement, the passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they knew everyone's names. I was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett, who has eight goals and eight assists in 18 games this
year, said players have adjusted to life under first-year U.S. head
coach April Heinrichs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was nervous at first,'' Milbrett said. ``But we've
gained confidence with her, because we've had time to learn her
style. Nobody knew her style. Nobody had spent too much time around
her as a head coach. But everything is fine. Now, it's just back to
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett, one of the team's all-time leaders in minutes, goals
and assists, predicted the change from DiCicco to Heinrichs would
yield positive results at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The national team had been under the same coaches for six
years,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
