<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-CONCORDE-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR FRENCH, CRASH OF CONCORDE ALSO MARKS DEATH OF A GREAT SYMBOL
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONESSE, France _ Outside his creme-colored house on a quiet
flowered suburban street, Marc Girel trims his roses with an eye on
the cloud-filled sky.
</P>
<P>
   Every few minutes, a passenger jet flies over Girel's house from
Charles De Gaulle International Airport three miles away. The
68-year-old retired civil engineer takes pleasure in the sound _
some would say, noise _ made by the jets because of his lifelong
love affair with airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   But today, something is missing. ``It's not the same,'' he says,
after pausing with his clippers to watch a plane pass overhead. ``I
miss the Concorde.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, one of Air France's six supersonic Concordes crashed
less than two minutes after take-off, killing 114 people in a
violent white-hot explosion that disintegrated the aircraft and
incinerated a small hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The accident site is a short drive from Girel's house, where the
Concorde's passage overhead had been a daily highlight.
</P>
<P>
   The thunderous roar made by the world's only supersonic
passenger plane was so distinct that Girel could hear it long
before he could see it. ``A lot of my neighbors hate that sound _
that roar, really. But for me, it was a familiar comfort. It was a
sound of France.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a sound the French may not hear for a while. Air France
grounded its Concorde fleet indefinitely as government
investigators try to piece together what brought the elegant
aircraft to earth. It was the Concorde's first fatal accident in
the 31 years since its maiden flight.
</P>
<P>
   For many like Girel, the crash of what the French call ``the
great white bird'' signaled the passing of an era _ the death of a
great symbol.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde _ originally the dream of legendary leader Charles
de Gaulle _ long has been an important symbol not only of European
technology and design, but also of a success that is decidedly not
American.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the influential daily Le Figaro wrote that
the Concorde after three decades remained the envy of even the
Americans. ``In 2000, this plane, whose technology goes back to the
1960s, still incarnates modernity,'' the newspaper wrote. ``It also
represents genius of Europeans.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Turcat, the test pilot who first flew the Concorde in 1969
is a national hero _ the French equivalent of America's Chuck
Yeager. The plane flown by Turcat is honored in a museum with the
machines of Louis Bleriot and other Gallic aeronautical pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where it has become painfully ordinary to have a
Big Mac combo for lunch washed down by a Coke, and then head home
to veg on the couch with reruns of ``Frazier'' and ``Friends,''
such symbols are few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of Europeans, the Concorde represented more than a
symbol of European technical virility; it embodied the spirit of
triumph unbridled by a concern for the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, after all, killed their supersonic transport
because the insipid Yankee bean-counters in the 1960s deemed it
unprofitable. It took the visionary French _ and reluctant Britons
_ to persevere in the quest for the elegant super-fast aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   They built Concorde to prove a point _ the point being that they
could build it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it was our moon landing,'' Girel said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Concorde has had about the same commercial success
as a moon trip. With one-way tickets costing $5,000, the cramped
supersonic airliner has been steadily losing passengers to slower
but cheaper competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Also, like the space program, the Concorde was an idealistic
government product. French and British taxpayers spent about $2.5
billion to develop the aircraft, and only 16 were built. Three were
retired in recent years, leaving Britain's British Airways with
seven and France's Air France with six before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   In 24 years of passenger service, the Concorde held a flawless
safety record. But with technology more than 30 years old, the
remaining Concordes are scheduled to be taken out of scheduled
service by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the world is a successor to the Concorde on the
drawing board. Boeing has lost interest in the idea, and European
aircraft manufacturer Airbus, the only other manufacturer capable
of building such a plane, is focusing on its triple-decker super
jumbo-jet the A3XX. It is expected to be the largest passenger
plane in the world with more than 650 seats.
</P>
<P>
   French experts have estimated that it would cost upwards of $25
billion to develop a 250-seat supersonic passenger plane _ twice as
much as the Airbus is investing in the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   While France can claim other famous technical marvels such as
the TGV _ the train that speeds along at nearly 200 mph _ it is
easy to get the feeling here that the country is being left behind
technologically.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, which the French are eagerly embracing, is clearly
the domain of the United States, with up to 80 percent of European
Internet traffic routed across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps seeking to recapture the mythic success of the Concorde,
France this year embarked on a quest to find its successor. The
government has funded 19 research projects, intended to gauge the
prospects of a post-Concorde project.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the nation must cope with this week's grim reality. The
nearly universal feeling among people on the street has been
profound grief for the people killed in the crash _ and a sense of
melancholy for the Concorde itself.
</P>
<P>
   Le Figaro, the French daily, put it this way the day after the
crash: ``Without doubt, Concorde died yesterday at the age of 31,''
Le Figaro said. ``For France this is a double day of mourning. All
that will remain is the myth of the beautiful white bird. The
Concorde represented a France which sought to convince itself that
it was still the center of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Arnould, the owner of a small tobacco shop in Gonesse,
said on Friday that he has been depressed all week. ``I think it's
because the Concorde was so perfect, such an ideal _ and then to
crash, it hurts, really,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A myth crashed with the Concorde Tuesday, said the daily
Paris-Normandie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symbol of triumphant technology, speed and luxury, European
know-how and competition with the United States, the plane
incarnates our end of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.airfrance.com
</P>
<P>
   www.nmsi.ac.uk
</P>
<P>
   www.british-airways.com
</P>
<P>
   www.concorde-jet.com/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
