<HEADLINE>
UPDATE: MP3, EMI REACH AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service) (Eds: Stock
figures are not up to the minute.) 
 By TIM ARANGO   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online music distributor MP3.com (MPPP:Nasdaq) reached a
settlement with another major record label, giving the former
adversary of the recording industry licensing agreements with three
of the five major record labels, the companies said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement will allow MP3.com to offer songs owned by EMI
for its My.MP3.com service. Major record label content was pulled
from the service in May pending resolution of the lawsuits. In
April, a judge found that the company violated copyright law. The
MyMP3.com service offers a digital locker in cyberspace where
people can store and download music for free _ but only if they own
the compact disc first.
</P>
<P>
   The service will not resume until MP3.com secures agreements
with all five major record labels, said Michael Robertson,
MP3.com's chief executive officer, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com settled with Time Warner's (TWX:NYSE) Warner Music Group
and Bertelsmann's BMG Entertainment in early June. It still has
lawsuits pending with Seagram's (VO:NYSE) Universal Music Group and
Sony's (SNE:NYSE) Sony Music Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In its recent quarter, the company took a $150 million charge,
money that was set aside to pay the costs of the legal battles. The
charge still gives the company about $150 million in cash,
Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement with Sony is not imminent, according to a source
close to that company. A representative from Universal could not be
immediately reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego-based MP3.com was off 3/4, or 7 percent, at 9 9/16.
Its 52-week high is 64 5/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
