<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIGER BURNS BRIGHT, EVEN WITH NON-GOLFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM WONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One hates to be part of the herd, but I cannot help but add to
the
</P>
<P>
   chorus of golf writers and commentators who have run out of
superlatives to describe the Tiger Woods who made golf history last
weekend at the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, golf isn't something that excites me. I don't play, and
when
</P>
<P>
   Woods isn't playing, I don't watch golf tournaments on TV. When
he is playing, apparently a lot of people are like me. We watch.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the British Open, Woods was the odds-on favorite, and
he
</P>
<P>
   didn't disappoint. For a short while on Sunday, David Duval, the
world's
</P>
<P>
   second-rated golfer, gave Woods a run, causing Tiger fans some
moments of
</P>
<P>
   anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Then Duval's game fell apart in the final nine holes. Woods won
</P>
<P>
   comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about this 24-year-old prodigy _ other than the
youth, good
</P>
<P>
   looks, talent, intelligence, exemplary work ethic and wealth _
that
</P>
<P>
   fascinates me and many other non-golfers?
</P>
<P>
   After Woods won the Master's in April 1997, I wrote that,
whether he liked
</P>
<P>
   it or not, Woods had become an icon to both African Americans
and Asian
</P>
<P>
   Americans. Because he is a one-man United Nations, he had the
potential to
</P>
<P>
   bring together ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Even in our celebrity-drenched culture, Woods holds a special
place. Few
</P>
<P>
   people or things promoted in the ubiquitous media live up to the
hype, but
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods does.
</P>
<P>
   After he won the Master's, golf writers anointed him the
successor to the
</P>
<P>
   great Jack Nicklaus. But Woods faltered somewhat until mid-1999,
when he
</P>
<P>
   worked out kinks in his stroke and his game turned around.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he had been favored to win each of the most recent
Grand Slam tournaments (the Master's, U.S. Open, British Open and
Professional Golf Association) and did win three of them.
</P>
<P>
   But has he brought fractious racial and ethnic groups in the
United
</P>
<P>
   States closer together? Hardly, but it was unrealistic of me or
anyone
</P>
<P>
   else to expect that of him.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Earl Woods, has been the most prominent proselytizer
of
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's messianic potential. At a dinner honoring Woods as
America's
</P>
<P>
   outstanding college golfer of 1996, Earl Woods said, ``This
young man is
</P>
<P>
   going to be able to help so many people. He will transcend this
game and
</P>
<P>
   bring to the world a humanitarianism which has never been known
before.
</P>
<P>
   The world will be a better place to live in by virtue of his
existence and
</P>
<P>
   his presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has enriched himself, the men's golf tour, TV networks and
</P>
<P>
   corporations pay him to endorse their products. He has inspired
young
</P>
<P>
   people of different ethnic groups to try the game once thought
to be the
</P>
<P>
   exclusive preserve of rich white people.
</P>
<P>
   It appears, however, that the golfer himself isn't embracing the
mantle of
</P>
<P>
   world savior. As Sports Illustrated wrote in its April 3, 2000,
cover
</P>
<P>
   story about Woods, ``Earl often declares that his son will be an
agent of
</P>
<P>
   social change, but Tiger feels at home in the world of the rich
and
</P>
<P>
   powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, his political views ``make him fit for the Republican
</P>
<P>
   nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unrealistic to expect one person _ even one as gifted and
</P>
<P>
   interesting as Tiger Woods _ to save the world from its own
</P>
<P>
   transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean, however, that I and others won't
</P>
<P>
   continue to get up at ungodly hours to watch him hit a small
ball into a
</P>
<P>
   hole in finely manicured lawns on real estate out of reach for
most of us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
