<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5773 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-BUSH-ASSESS-ECONOMIST     07-28 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ASSESS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GETS HIS CHANCE TO SHOW HE'S `READY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors - This is cover story)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   This has been something of a rollercoaster year for George W.
Bush. Last autumn, his nomination as the Republican presidential
candidate seemed inevitable: the governor of Texas boasted a decent
record, a likeable character, a well-known name, a new slogan
(''compassionate conservatism'') and the most formidable money
machine modern politics has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the McCain insurgency; by February Bush had quashed
the turbulent senator, but only by spending virtually all his
$70-million treasure trove and losing a good deal of both his
likeability and his moderateness. A snarling right-winger, he won
his party's nomination, but had apparently handed the November
election to Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Republican convention beckoning next week in
Philadelphia, Bush has repainted himself once again. The
likeability is back; so is much of the moderation; and he has added
considerably more depth to the portrait.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four months, the supposedly lightweight Bush has
dominated the presidential campaign, unfurling policy after policy
and surrounding himself with serious-looking advisers; meanwhile,
Gore, the supposed policy wonk, has seemed stuck in a series of
tired relaunches.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is slightly ahead in the polls; and unless something
terrible happens at what promises to be a heavily overscripted
convention, he can expect to increase his lead.
</P>
<P>
   Where does this leave Bush? In with a real chance. Of course,
Gore will get his own post-nomination bounce in the polls after the
Democratic convention later in August. When it matters, in
November, the vice president may have the edge: Gore has the
incumbent's benefit of a remarkably strong economy (so far) and he
is an impressively brutal debater, whereas Bush's showing against
McCain was dismal.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how endearing Bush seems at the podium next Thursday
night, the appeal of his new self-portrait will not really be
tested until his televised contests with Gore in October.
</P>
<P>
   With that caveat, there is still plenty to be said _ much of it
good _ about the Bush who comes to Philadelphia. Those who worry
about him tend to bring up two charges. They are the ones that
dogged the rise to the presidency of another western conservative
governor, Ronald Reagan. Bush is said to be too extreme and lacking
the intellectual capacity to be president. Those charges ring
hollow.
</P>
<P>
   On some counts, Bush does seem too conservative. He has been a
strong opponent of gun control, something that will deservedly do
him few favors with women voters. Texas also has a poor
environmental record, which Gore will blame, not altogether
unfairly, on Bush's ties to the energy industry.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the popularity of the death penalty in the United
States, Bush's record as a serial executioner may come back to
haunt him, particularly if it becomes clear that some innocent
people have been executed.
</P>
<P>
   Probably none of these issues will cost Bush the election. The
previous Republican candidate, Bob Dole, lost his way with
independent voters, the ``soccer moms'' of lore, by seeming
socially illiberal yet fiscally profligate. On the key social issue
of abortion, Bush may have done just enough to win himself a pass.
Officially, he has stuck to the anti-abortion record of the
Christian right; but there have been enough nods and winks to guess
that Bush, like his father, would not strive hard to outlaw it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on taxes, the economy is helping. Like Dole, Bush put
forward a big tax cut. The new predictions for future budget
surpluses have not only made that seem a bit less reckless;
crucially, they have encouraged Gore to offer a big cut of his own.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, Bush can claim to be a genuine reformer in
the vital matter of education. It would be better if he openly
campaigned for vouchers; but he is a far keener proponent of
structural reform in the public-school system than Gore, who is
firmly on the side of the teachers' unions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also been much braver about Social Security: Unlike
Gore, he would allow people to invest some of their public pension
in the stockmarket. Compassionate conservatism also introduces
fresh ideas about making more use of the private sector and
churches in helping America's poor.
</P>
<P>
   In foreign policy, too, Bush deserves some credit. He has been
more solid than Gore on free trade. There are question marks about
his grip of the missile-defense debate, and more generally of basic
facts about the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who once called Greeks ``Grecians'' has tried to
bone up on the issues and to provide himself with competent
advisers. A Bush administration with Richard Cheney as vice
president and perhaps Colin Powell as secretary of state would be a
force to be reckoned with abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Take these policies, add Bush's long record of working together
with the Democrats in Texas and his Reaganesque record of picking
good advisers, and he surely has a plausible candidacy. Of course,
one can wish for more _ much more.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike McCain, Bush will not shake up Washington's lamentable
system of money politics. On the other hand, there is precious
little hope of Gore doing so either. Bush may not be the perfect
candidate; but now his challenge is merely to prove he is a better
one than the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Purely in terms of the policies, Bush is certainly ready for
that comparison. But the next three months will probably be even
more about character: not just intellect, but temperament. The
American people, most of whom have paid scant attention to the
events so far, will have to get used to Bush, and to trust him.
</P>
<P>
   This was the part of the test that that other supposedly
ignorant western governor, Reagan, passed so triumphantly 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans may decide whether Bush is ``ready'' in this
sense only when they come to pull the lever on Nov. 7. Philadelphia
offers his first real chance to convince them that he is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5774 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CHENEY-ASSESS-ECONOMI     07-28 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-ASSESS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY ADDS LITTLE TO THE TICKET AND DETRACTS LESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors - This is ``Lexington'' column)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When George W. Bush first described the running mate he wanted,
he said his choice would be ``electrifying.'' It ``would make your
eyes light up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was when his campaign wanted a bright new face _ someone
who would reshape the political landscape and epitomize the
generational change by moving the Republican Party away from those
ghastly people in Congress. Evidently Bush has now had second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is a rock-solid candidate, with all the charisma of
that inorganic substance. He fulfills the Hippocratic requirements
of a vice president (''First, do no harm''). He will not
contradict, embarrass or outshine Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Vice presidents are sometimes required to be the campaign's
attack dog. Cheney is easy-going, civil and patient, more like a
guide dog for the blind than the Hound of the Baskervilles.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, those may prove useful qualities. Cheney has
managed to play influential roles in Washington for a quarter of a
century _ most recently as defense secretary for Bush's father and
before that as No.2 in the Republican Party's hierarchy in the
House _ without making too many enemies in his own party (both
wings of which applauded this week's choice) or even among
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In picking his running mate, it was the cautious side of Bush's
personality that came to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   Caution has limitations as well as merits. One of Cheney's
advantages is that he seems to be no slash-and-burn Republican, no
Newt Gingrich. But note how he comes by this reputation: as a
leader of the generation that preceded the Republican revolution of
1994, not the one still recovering from it. When Cheney left
Congress to join President Bush's cabinet, the man who stepped into
his job as House minority whip was none other than the gentleman
from Georgia, Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney finally ends the Gingrich revolution. He brings the party
full circle. Personifying the status quo ante, he backs up Bush's
claim to be a new kind of Republican only if you think that going
back a political generation counts as going forward.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney does fulfill the two other requirements Bush made
when he drew up the vice-presidential job specifications: that he
could step into the president's shoes if need be, and that he
should get along well with Bush personally. Even here, though, he
does so in ways that have a downside.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Cheney is qualified to take over the presidency is
putting it mildly. In terms of executive experience, he is probably
the running mate best qualified to be president in modern times. He
was in the Oval Office at a daunting time in recent White House
history _ when Gerald Ford set about rebuilding the executive
branch of government after the disasters of Watergate (Ford picked
Cheney to be his White House chief of staff at the ripe age of 34).
More recently, he actually served as defense secretary during a
war: the one in the Gulf, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has borrowed this splendid curriculum vitae to provide
himself with some surrogate gravitas and instant credibility in
foreign affairs. This is widely seen in America as a smart campaign
move. For the rest of the world it could prove more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself brings _ how to put this politely? _ no great
burden of preconception about the world's affairs. His
foreign-policy advisers do not lack for experience; but they also
include more than the normal ration of people who want to make some
radical changes in foreign and military policy (step forward
Richard Perle, Ronald Reagan's Soviet-squashing ``prince of
darkness''). Having a relatively cautious old buffer around to wag
a wary paw is obviously an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the president himself is relying partly on the
foreign-policy judgments of others, Cheney's prudence and rather
mainstream hawkishness may not be enough. Especially when dealing
with new strategic threats, America may need a vice president who
can stand up and shove Bush in one direction or another _ and it is
not clear that Cheney would do that. This is one area where you
might want the vice president to bark more forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the other quality that got Cheney
picked: loyalty. Even by the paranoid standards of American
politics, Bush insists on and inspires undivided allegiance. He
said a big reason for picking Cheney was his confidence that he
could work well with him, a judgment based partly on Cheney's
service with Bush's father. The younger Bush was disgusted by the
people who abandoned the elder one in the latter days of that
troubled presidency. Loyalty, argues the governor of Texas, is the
glue that keeps his campaign staff a successful unit.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, loyalty has much to commend it. Bush's team remained
remarkably undivided even during the dark days (for them) of the
McCain insurgency. But so much is loyalty prized in this circle
that there is a real danger that Bush will shut himself off from
the variety and richness of views that comes from getting
conflicting advice.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Eisenhower, the modern president with the greatest
organizational experience, once said: ``I know of only one way in
which you can be sure you have done your best to make a wise
decision. You must get courageous men of strong views, and let them
debate with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not the Bush style. He surrounds himself with
long-serving allies. Many of them are no doubt highly capable
people. But there is a danger that they are too similar for Bush's
own good. Cheney, who until this week was the chief executive of
Halliburton, is even an oilman too.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that the Bush campaign, even more than most, will
rise and fall on the candidate's own qualities. Cheney's lack of a
dowry in the form of votes from his home state expresses this
nicely (most of his political career was in Wyoming, which has a
grand total of three electoral-college votes, and where Democrats
are anyway on the endangered-species list).
</P>
<P>
   He adds little to the ticket and detracts less. The real lesson
from the Cheney nomination concerns Bush's growing self-confidence.
The name at the head of the ticket is the only one that matters.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, the choice of Cheney says that the
governor of Texas thinks he can win this li'l election all on his
own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
