<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CAMP-DAVID-AFTERMATH-     07-28 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMP-DAVID-AFTERMATH-ECONOMIST-900&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-SUMMIT TALK MORE CONDUCIVE TO GUNFIRE THAN NEGOTIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Their return from Camp David was markedly different. Yasser
Arafat came home a hero, absorbing praise for not having buckled to
Israeli and American pressure. Ehud Barak came back to a crumbled
government, angrily blaming the collapse of the 15-day summit on
Arafat. The Palestinian, he said, had failed to make the ``historic
decisions necessary to end the conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's reply is simple. ``The Arab leader has not been born
who would give up Jerusalem,'' he reportedly told Bill Clinton
during a heated exchange.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jerusalem that unravelled the negotiations, though the
Palestinians say there were also no firm agreements on the right of
return of the Palestinian refugees, or where the borders of a
future Palestinian state would lie.
</P>
<P>
   The news blackout that persisted through the summit has turned
into storytelling. The Palestinians say Barak was offering them
sovereignty over several districts on the edge of Jerusalem's
municipal borders _ Israeli sources say these included Beit Hanina,
Kalandia and Shuafatin _ in return for Israel annexing three large
Jewish settlements, Maale Edumim, Gush Etzion and Givat Zeev, and
making them part of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In the Old City and areas adjacent to it, the offer was
apparently ``broad civilian and administrative autonomy'' over
Palestinian neighborhoods, including the Muslim and Christian
quarters within the Old City, and ``signs of sovereignty'' at the
Dome of the Rock. Israel would retain ``residual sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   By Israeli standards, these are far-reaching concessions. Barak
described on July 25 how he had offered Arafat a redrawn, and in
effect divided, Jerusalem. Clinton went out of his way to praise
him for his ``very bold decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is barely any Arab leader who could have countenanced
these new arrangements, let alone Arafat. Apart from its numerous
Muslim and Christian shrines, the Old City is home to 37,000
Palestinians, against 3,000 Jews. And like the rest of East
Jerusalem, in international law it is occupied territory.
</P>
<P>
   The depressing thing is that since the talks did not lead to a
deal, all the positions taken at Camp David are now ``null and
void.'' Although they broke important taboos, they will not, at
least in theory, be the point of departure for future talks.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, like Barak, put his name to a statement reasserting that
negotiations based on United Nations resolutions were the only way
to reach an agreement, and committing the two sides to avoid
unilateral actions that prejudge the outcome of talks.
</P>
<P>
   This was a signal to Israel to ease up on settlement
construction. But mainly it was a message to Arafat about his
declared intention, endorsed by the PLO's Central Council earlier
this month, to announce a state by Sept. 13, the deadline both
sides have accepted for reaching a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Alive to the consequences of a unilateral declaration _ Barak
has said Israel would respond with unilateral steps of its own,
possibly annexing settlements, and America's Congress is preparing
laws to stop all aid _ Arafat is anxious to find some way out.
Doing nothing is probably not an option.
</P>
<P>
   But if negotiations on an interim deal could restart, Arafat
might be able to fudge the statehood declaration in exchange for
Israeli recognition of a Palestinian state in principle, and
another swathe of West Bank territory.
</P>
<P>
   For the ``third redeployment'' that is still owed the
Palestinians under the Oslo accords, Arafat, who now controls only
40 percent of the West Bank, has asked for another 45 percent.
Benjamin Netanyahu, when he was Israel's prime minister, offered 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative to negotiations could be grim. Israeli
intelligence experts believe that with the West Bank and Gaza now
convolutedly carved up between the Palestinian Authority and the
Israeli army and settlers, a declaration of independence by Arafat
would trigger widespread and violent demonstrations that could
quickly grow into wholesale military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   If his armed policemen side with the demonstrators, as they have
done in isolated incidents in the past, Arafat would have a hard
job quelling the clashes even if he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army issued machineguns and sniper rifles to
settlers in the northern West Bank this week, and urged them to
help with fencing and fortification work around their settlements.
The chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, gave warning that if a
body of Palestinian civilians marched on any settlement, the army
would regard this as a mortal danger to Israeli citizens.
</P>
<P>
   With this kind of talk in the air, the post-summit atmosphere in
Israel is hardly conducive to reopening negotiations. Barak, in a
somber address to ``the citizens of Israel'' from Frederick, Md.,
on Tuesday, seemed to anticipate violent times ahead. We will know
how to unite, he said, as we have so many times in the past.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Barak urgently needs to shore up his ragged government. He
prefers to do so with parties of the center, or even the right,
rather than try to rule with a minority leftist coalition dependent
on the votes of the Arab parties.
</P>
<P>
   But if peace talks with the Palestinians continue to dominate
the government's agenda, the parties that abandoned him before Camp
David _ Shas, the National Religious Party, and the Russian
immigrant party Yisrael B'Aliyah _ are unlikely to agree to return.
Even more damning, in the eyes of these parties, is the gradual
emergence of Barak's position on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Key members of the Likud, the main opposition party, said they
would rather leave the party than participate in a Labour-Likud
coalition under Barak. Wednesday, the Likud leader, Ariel Sharon,
promised publicly that he would not enter into such an arrangement
_ although several of his colleagues maintain that he would if
Barak asked him.
</P>
<P>
   On the prime minister's left, the Meretz Party, and possibly
some members of his own Labor Party, would turn against him if he
struck a deal with the Likud.
</P>
<P>
   Peaceniks in Israel are trying to find consolation in the fact
that Israel's decades-long, dogmatic insistence that Jerusalem is
non-negotiable has now been irrevocably punctured. Barak spoke
approvingly of the debate that the summit has generated inside
Israeli society over what parts of the area that Israel arbitrarily
defined as Jerusalem in 1967 are in fact of overwhelming national
importance to the Jewish state and Jewish identity.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the Palestinian state, too, can have its capital
in parts of Jerusalem has been put on the table. Clinton says it
needs time for the idea to percolate among both nations. But the
clock, as Clinton also noted, is ticking against us all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
