<HEADER>
A5776 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-OKINAWA-SYNDROME-ECON     07-28 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKINAWA-SYNDROME-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SUMMITS PROMISE MUCH AND DELIVER NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Maybe they should take tips from the leaders of millennial
cults. They aren't yet predicting the apocalypse, but the heads of
government who gather each year at the G8 summit do tend to make
startling pledges.
</P>
<P>
   As the most powerful people in the world (the leaders of the
seven big industrial democracies plus Russia, together with the
president of the European Commission), they promise every summer to
tackle some of its worst troubles: poverty, disease, warfare, crime
and pollution, to name but a few.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a year on, they face the occupational hazard of humbler
soothsayers everywhere: how to explain to their followers why
nothing much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's summit in Okinawa between July 21 and July 23,
they found an answer: say it all again with feeling, plus Internet
initiatives. But respect tradition as well.
</P>
<P>
   That is presumably why their communique was laced as usual with
the anesthetizing gunk of globocratese _ ``partnership among
stakeholders,'' ``step changes,'' ``cultural diversity,'' even
``deeper peace of mind.''.
</P>
<P>
   On a more concrete level _ what had actually been done since
last year _ there was less to say. The leaders could only
``reaffirm'' last year's big idea: to speed up the Heavily Indebted
Poor Countries (HIPC) scheme, meant to cut the debts of 41 of the
world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   When they met in Cologne a year ago, the G8 set as a target that
25 of these countries should receive debt relief by the end of this
year. So far only nine have qualified, and of those, only one _
Uganda _ has reached ``completion point,'' making it eligible for
cancellation of some of its debt. The others have reached
``decision point,'' allowing them partial relief.
</P>
<P>
   The delays can partly be blamed on the poor countries' own
corruption or war-mongering. But some, such as Tanzania, one of the
nine qualifiers, complain that last year's decision to make HIPC
``broader, deeper and faster'' actually increased the number of
hoops they have to jump through.
</P>
<P>
   This year's new idea, meriting its own ``Okinawa Charter,'' is
that something must be done about the ``digital divide'' caused by
unequal access to information technology. The leaders agreed to
establish a ``Digital Opportunity Taskforce'' _ yes, ``dotforce'' _
to help spread the wonders of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They are right to worry about the potential for technology to
widen the gulf between rich and poor. But it is hard to dispel the
impression that the main thing was to give the summiteers something
new to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   In more measurable promises, of more immediate import to the
world's poorest people, the leaders endorsed specific targets and
timetables for the spread of primary education (to be universal by
2015) and the eradication of diseases (deaths from TB, for
instance, to be cut by half, and HIV/AIDS-infection among young
people to be reduced by 25 percent by 2010). It would be wonderful
if these could be met. A number of global initiatives are in the
works. Progress reports next year!
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible not to mock when governments skirt politically
difficult issues such as trade liberalization in favor of bland
generalities. Or when they fearlessly proclaim unpopular truths
such as: ``Every child deserves a good education''; or ``Health is
key to prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   They even addressed aging _ oddly failing to pledge that they
would wipe it out by 2020, and instead plunging further into
controversy by promising to ``promote a culture that values the
experience and knowledge that comes with age.'' That was brave.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders said they would keep in touch (by e-mail, of course)
between now and the 2001 summit in Genoa. It is the least they can
do now that ``a new era dawns''; it is probably also the most they
will do.
</P>
<P>
   How about using this exciting new channel of communication to
concentrate next year's agenda on action, not self-indulgent
blather? Alternatively, how about abandoning this sorry exercise
altogether?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
