<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5778 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-THAI-TYCOON-ECONOMIST     07-28 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THAI-TYCOON-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM TYCOON AIMS TO WIN POWER IN THAILAND  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It is too soon to write off Thaksin Shinawatra, the telecom
tycoon who wants to rule Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   His new party suffered a blow last Sunday, when Bangkok's voters
turned out in droves to choose a new governor. His candidate
managed to push the man from the ruling Democrat Party into third
place. But she lost heavily to Samak Sundaravej, a veteran
conservative whom most people seemed to think could get something
done about the capital's many problems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Thaksin is hoping that the parliamentary elections, which
must be called later this year, will be a very different story.
</P>
<P>
   They may be. Since forming the Thai Rak Thai party in 1998,
Thaksin has emerged as the main threat to Chuan Leekpai and the
ruling Democrats. Chuan became prime minister in November 1997 and
has done well to last this long, given the notoriously short
lifespan of Thai governments and the unwieldy seven-party coalition
with which he started.
</P>
<P>
   But a spate of no-confidence motions, a walkout by a large
number of opposition MPs last month in an attempt to force an
earlier general election and some controversial reforms leave his
government vulnerable to opposition attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Thaksin, who stands on a pro-business platform, has been
sharpening his knives.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the governor's election in Bangkok would have been the
ideal start. In any event, Samak's toughness and previous
experience in government won the day. But his party is a local
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Thaksin has good reason to be more optimistic about the national
elections, where the advantages of incumbency and mass campaigning
benefit big parties. To compete better with the Democrats, Thaksin
has convinced more than 100 MPs from smaller parties to defect to
his Thai Rak Thai party.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these faces from the past may undermine his fresh,
reforming image. So, too, might widespread accusations that he is
paying MPs to change sides. Nevertheless, he is betting that their
political connections in the upcoming election will be invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   The poll will be the first national one to be held under the new
1997 constitution and monitored by a new electoral commission. In
theory this should make it easier for unknown candidates to win
seats.
</P>
<P>
   The new commission showed some toughness in Thailand's
first-ever Senate elections in March, when it disqualified several
candidates for campaign violations such as vote-buying, and ordered
many reruns. But the commission may not dare to act as bravely
during a general election.
</P>
<P>
   Sunai Phasuk, an academic with the Asian Network for Free
Elections, says a tough electoral commission will be essential for
an honest and free poll, but he does not expect it to bare its
teeth and eliminate cheating candidates entirely. He points out
that around a quarter of the 200 new senators who were elected were
disqualified in one of the earlier rounds, but nevertheless
eventually prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   If Thailand's voters do reject incumbent politicians in favor of
fresh faces, it will mark a genuine break with the past. But unless
that happens it looks as if the Democrats and Thai Rak Thai will
emerge as the two main forces in the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
   That would open the door for a frantic scramble to gain the
support of smaller parties. This being Thailand, there are bound to
be plenty of scandals along the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5779 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-JAPAN-PROPERTY-MARKET     07-28 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-PROPERTY-MARKET-ECONOMIST-700&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS JAPAN'S REAL ESTATE MARKET AT LAST NEARING A BOTTOM?  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For all the fickleness of Japan's stop-and-go economic
performance over the last ten years, the economy has had one
reliable feature: falling property prices. Since 1990, the value of
Japanese real estate has plunged by over 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, commercial property has shed more than three-quarters
of its value. This deflationary wrecking ball is still hard at
work. Leading a nasty selloff of Japanese shares this week were the
same companies that have haunted the market ever since the property
bubble burst: construction firms, property developers and the banks
that financed their now-crumbling empires.
</P>
<P>
   At last, though, a glimmer of light is intruding on the gloom.
Refreshingly, it does not come from the usual quick fixes that are
favored by the government _ public land purchases, accounting
tricks and bail-outs. Rather, Japan is aiming its new reforms
squarely at the market's more deep-seated financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bank loans finance almost all Japanese property purchases. The
poor health of their customers and the sorry state of their own
finances have, however, put banks off property loans. So developers
have no money for new investments. Japan hopes to break this
gridlock with new financial tools, imported from America's
sophisticated capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   One much-trumpeted development is the arrival of commercial
mortgage-backed securities (CMBS), bonds serviced out of the
proceeds of property loans, and secured on the value of commercial
property and the rent that it produces.
</P>
<P>
   For lenders, these bonds have one big advantage over ordinary
property loans. They are traded in a secondary market, which
attracts pension funds and other investors.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowers, meanwhile, can finance their property development
``off balance sheet'': beneficial ownership of a building and the
debt that financed it are transferred to a separate company
specially set up for the purpose. In this way, they can tidy up
their balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, in part, the attraction in Japan, where big, heavily
indebted property developers such as Sumitomo Realty have started
using the CMBS market to trim their borrowings.
</P>
<P>
   Moodys, an American credit-rating agency, expects new CMBS
issues this year of as much as 700 billion yen ($6.4 billion), more
than four times the amount sold last year, when the first CMBS
issue appeared.
</P>
<P>
   CMBS issues can be backed not just by healthy mortgages but also
by pools of non-performing property loans, of which there is no
shortage in Japan. Pioneering this part of the market are American
investors such as Cerberus, Lonestar, Morgan Stanley and Goldman
Sachs, which have been quietly buying deeply discounted portfolios
of non-performing loans from the banks. Industry sources say these
foreigners have invested $7 billion to $10 billion in such loans.
</P>
<P>
   Provoking even louder cheers is the pending introduction of
real-estate investment trusts (REITs), perhaps early next year. A
REIT is a specialized property investor. Like CMBS issues, REITs
offer holders of their securities the comfort of secondary trading:
their shares are listed on the stockmarket.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of official enthusiasm for REITs in Japan is the
unusual speed with which the required legal and tax arrangements
are being put in place. Sensing, perhaps, the government's resolve
to make the market work, property developers and investors have
announced their own initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Nomura, a securities firm, has teamed up with Mitsui Fudosan, a
big property company, to develop REITs. Mitsubishi Estate, another
big property developer, plans a REIT with Tokio Marine &AMP; Fire and
Dai-Ichi Mutual, two insurers. Sumitomo Life, Mitsubishi Trust and
Mitsui Fudosan, meanwhile, are putting together a property index
that will help the markets new investors to track their
performance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM -- STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One unanswered question, however, is why Japan needs REITs at
all. Unlike America, all the big property companies are listed on
the stock market. Investors wanting to trade in the property market
can deal in the shares of these companies.
</P>
<P>
   As Etsusuke Masuda of HSBC, a British bank, points out, the
result will be that REITs will compete for investors with existing
property companies, with REITs holding several important
advantages. These will include: exemption from corporate taxes,
provided they pay most of their earnings out in dividends; balance
sheets that do not groan under mountainous debts; and no nagging
fears of hidden losses tucked away in dummy companies.
</P>
<P>
   The existing property companies are the most aggressive
promoters of Japanese REITs, so there will inevitably be some
conflicts of interest. If the property companies transfer some
existing assets into REITs, their own balance sheets are likely to
weaken further. This is because the market will probably demand
that REITs invest only in prime property, at least at first,
leaving the property companies with all the rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   Even if REITs invest only in new property development, they are
likely to attract investors who would otherwise have bought
property-company shares. Either way, REITs will hurt property
companies' share prices, suggesting that the latter have not yet
thought through their enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, says Masuda, is ahead of them. After a
REIT-inspired rally earlier this year, their share prices have
collapsed again.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is timing. In America, REITS flourished only
after the CMBS market had taken off. Investors first acquired a
taste for low-risk bonds; only then did they start making racier
equity investments in property.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese CMBS market, however, is in its infancy.
Mortgage-backed bond issues require a sophisticated appreciation of
credit risk. Every issue is sliced up into several tranches, with
each one carefully priced according to the likelihood that
investors will get their money back.
</P>
<P>
   But in Japan deadbeat borrowers pay little more interest than
the best credits.
</P>
<P>
   Also lacking is the catalytic role that America's Resolution
Trust Corporation (RTC) played in creating the CMBS market, by
repackaging large volumes of bad loans for sale at market-clearing
prices. Japan's version of the RTC, the Resolution and Collection
Corporation (RCC), has no such plans. It fears a public outcry
should it start selling discounted loans. Most would be bought by
foreigners, who would then seem to benefit at the expense of the
Japanese taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   More important, discounted sales would require more public money
for the RCC, which Japan's politicians would resist.
</P>
<P>
   Yet without such fire sales, investors may have no confidence
that prices have cleared properly. ING Barings, an investment bank,
guesses that as much as 19-trillion-yen-worth of property is still
hanging over the market _ tied up in bad loans or hidden as
security behind banks bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   Until this hits the market, all the effort that Japan is putting
into developing mortgage-backed securities, REITs and other foreign
exotica, welcome as they are, will seem rather beside the point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
