<HEADER>
A5780 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-REPUBLICANS-CONGRESS-     07-28 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-CONGRESS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS IN CONGRESS MIGHT HAVE GOT IT RIGHT THIS TIME  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There must be something to this
compassionate-conservatism business. It claims it can help even the
most disadvantaged. And there is evidence to support this.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, one of the stupidest, most self-destructive groups in
America has started to improve its behavior. We refer, of course,
to the Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The majority party in Congress usually sticks to the same
script. It works itself into a lather, demands vast tax cuts, fails
to agree on its spending proposals in an orderly fashion, and then
stages a big confrontation with the president over the final
make-up of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the president wins that battle, largely because the
public does not much care about the tax cut on which Congress has
lavished so much care.
</P>
<P>
   Not this year. For the first time in living memory, the House of
Representatives may pass every one of the 13 bills that make up the
budget before it breaks for a recess at the end of July. The Senate
is only a little behind that cracking pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever remember there being this sort of turbocharged
activity in July,'' says Bob Reischauer, a former head of the
Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Republicans dumped all their tax cuts into one
basket _ a proposed income-tax reduction of $792 billion. This
year, they have parcelled out the cuts into bite-sized chunks.
</P>
<P>
   They have passed a bill to end the ``marriage penalty,'' the
extra tax that married couples pay above two people who file their
taxes separately (this would be worth some $290 billion over ten
years); and they propose to scale back the ``death tax'' on
inherited property ($100 billion). Both measures command widespread
support, which makes them harder for the president to veto.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have been costs. Republicans who came into
office in 1994 as fiscal lions have abandoned their budget
principles and are going out like lambs. Unless there is a
last-minute change, Congress is likely to spend at least 7 percent
more than the limit it had previously promised to stick to.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Moore of the libertarian Cato Institute reckons the
106th Congress (1999-2000) is likely to boost spending in all by 11
percent, making it the most profligate since the 95th (1977-78),
when Jimmy Carter was president.
</P>
<P>
   This splurge has involved ignoring all sorts of self-imposed
restrictions on spending. For example, tax cuts are supposed to be
offset by equal amounts of spending cuts. Congress has ignored that
rule and dipped into the surplus _ which is also formally
forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Special ``caps'' are supposed to prevent spending above pre-set
limits. These caps have been routinely ignored, were raised in
1997, and are now being ignored again. Obviously, the increase in
tax revenues and the forecast expansion of the budget surplus make
all this possible. But those forecasts assume spending restraint
that Congress is not showing.
</P>
<P>
   There is not even any guarantee that the Republicans will end up
with an amicable settlement with the president this year. Clinton
has promised to veto the Republicans' tax cuts unless Congress
agrees to his version of a bill to improve medical coverage. He has
separately threatened to veto some of the spending proposals
(because they are too small).
</P>
<P>
   Still, compared with the last few years, the Republicans in
Congress have been clever. They have passed tax cuts people have
liked. They are not cutting popular government agencies. They have
their answer ready to the deadly charge of being a ``do-nothing
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   To politicians in an election year, that is pretty much all that
matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
