<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5781 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-ECONOM     07-28 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMITING CAMP DAVID'S DAMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attention: Commentary editors)
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Locked in a comfortless marriage, Israelis and Palestinians can
manage neither reconciliation nor divorce. The collapse of the
15-day marathon at Camp David showed that even the most zealous
marriage-guidance counselor couldn't do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   If Bill Clinton was not able, in pressure-cooker conditions, to
get Ehud Barak and Yasser Arafat to compromise their positions, it
probably means that those positions, at least in the short term,
are irreconcilable. Yet history dictates that there can be no
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctant partners have to find some less-than-perfect way
of coexisting on their patch of land. The statement released by the
White House as the summit broke up without agreement Tuesday said
that the two understood ``the importance of avoiding unilateral
actions that prejudge the outcome of negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, both Arafat and Barak are anxious to avoid the
direct, and probably bloody, clash that would follow if the
Palestinians go ahead and declare themselves an independent state
without Israel's agreement, and if Israel in return annexes bits of
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Their good intentions may melt in the heat of the summit's
post-mortems. Arafat, who is returning a hero, having resisted an
equivocal Israeli offer on East Jerusalem, short of the sovereignty
that his people see as their right, can afford to be more generous
in his assessment than Barak, who is returning to a messy domestic
scene, and is therefore blaming Arafat squarely for his obstinacy
in refusing the best offer the Palestinians are likely to get.
</P>
<P>
   Only a little more diplomatically, the Americans are also
blaming Arafat, which confirms Arab suspicions that, despite
Clinton's heroic dedication to deadlock-breaking, America's
pro-Israeli bias lives on.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, there seems little point in continuing the
search for a solution on Jerusalem _ though it is important in the
meantime that Israel does not make a bad situation worse by
unilaterally building more Jewish settlements in the Arab parts of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   So far as one can tell, the two leaders did fairly well on the
other big questions, including the borders of a Palestinian state.
The debate, airing taboo subjects, was useful in itself. But the
domestic vulnerability of both Barak and Arafat led them to insist
that the concessions they have made be kept secret _ which means
that they can now be spun into something rather different.
</P>
<P>
   As the Syrians and Israelis have already discovered, when
nothing is down on paper, it is difficult for new talks to start
from where the old ones broke off.
</P>
<P>
   The aim now has to be damage control. Above all, there must be
interim arrangements to preserve a sense of momentum, and soften
the coming confrontation over statehood. It is not possible to
leave things as they are.
</P>
<P>
   In the belief that it would help Barak to be elected, Arafat
broke an earlier pledge to announce statehood unilaterally. Without
considerable help, he will not be able to break, or modify, his
second pledge to declare it by Sept. 13, the date by which a final
agreement should have been signed.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Palestinian statehood is no big deal. The Israelis now
accept that it would be part of any final agreement. The
Palestinians currently control only about 40 percent of the West
Bank and Gaza, in non-contiguous chunks. Palestinian independence,
say the Palestinians themselves, would, at this stage, be
sovereignty over ``statelets in Israel's belly.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, for that matter, is Israel's threat to annex further
territory the menace it is made out to be. So long as Barak remains
in charge, he is likely to annex only the Jewish settlements that
he is anyhow determined to keep.
</P>
<P>
   However, if either action is performed in a deliberately
provocative way, the results could be tragic.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the line are in fiery mood, angry both
with each other, and with their own government. Right-wing Israeli
settlers believe Barak to be giving away the store; Palestinians
are sick to their hearts with the unending frustrations of their
trapped existence. Even this week, radical Palestinians have been
demonstrating in Gaza, calling for a resumption of the intifada,
the youthful uprising of the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the Israeli army solemnly warns its government, a new
uprising would not be stone-throwing boys versus Israel's rubber
bullets. The West Bank and Gaza are now rich in weaponry. And if
things get out of hand, the swollen Palestinian police could join
the battle, rather than prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   How to avert this clash? Perhaps by incorporating discussion of
Palestinian statehood in a new set of interim negotiations. Going
back to the interim business is a sad, boring comedown after the
high expectations of a full agreement, but it may now, after the
collapse of the summit, be the most useful approach.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Oslo calendar, Israel still owes the
Palestinians another withdrawal, and should be releasing more
political prisoners. A generous interpretation of both measures
might recapture some of the goodwill that has been forfeited at
Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   And Palestinian statehood, a threat only if Israel perceives it
as such, would not change the reality on the ground, if carried out
on agreed terms. Nor would it make life better for most
Palestinians, let alone bring a permanent settlement closer.
</P>
<P>
   But if it stopped this sad, bad marriage from going up in
flames, that, for the moment, might be blessing enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
