<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5784 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-NAPSTER-SWAN-SONG-ECO     07-28 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-SWAN-SONG-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIPPING NAPSTER IN THE BUD WON'T STOP FREE INTERNET MUSIC  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 450-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Hippy dreams have a habit of ending _ particularly
when they clash with the money-making instincts of the music
industry.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the suits seemed to win another battle against peace,
love and happiness, when they were awarded a court injunction
effectively closing down Napster, a company whose software allows
its commune of users to trade songs for free.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, most of the signs are that free music may
win, man.
</P>
<P>
   Napster's software allows users to exchange songs directly,
matching them up by maintaining a central who's-got-which-song
database. This directory has been closed. But only for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal is planned by Napster's legal team (which is headed by
the lawyer who led the antitrust team against Microsoft). And other
communal software devices will prove much harder targets to
vanquish through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Song-trading software programs such as Gnutella have no central
bits vulnerable to legal attack. Instead, users find songs by
linking one to the other, forming a sort of network akin to the
Internet itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America has only itself to
blame. Music lovers wanting to collect songs on their computers _
hardly an unreasonable request _ have little choice but to do so
with Napster and its like.
</P>
<P>
   True, the industry's own Secure Digital Music Initiative is
creeping along, but it is about two years too late.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the very notion of secure music may be an illusion: a
song needs to be decrypted to be played, at which point it can be
digitized and traded. Already the betting is that the RIAA and
Napster will strike a deal, averting an expensive court case. More
generally some sort of compromise about online music is likely.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, this week author Stephen King released to the Web
the first chapter of his latest serialized horror story. Users can
download it for free, but are then supposed to send $1 per chapter.
So far most have. Though such a trust-based system will not work
for all artists, it might work with some.
</P>
<P>
   Another pointer is the fact that the music industry has cried
wolf before; the first time the enemy was cassette tapes, which
also seemed to portend the end of copyright.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, tapes did little damage: most fans were willing to
pay for the real thing, to get the colorful insert and other
accompanying miscellany.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that, if the music labels can put their songs
online in a format that is more organized and more appealing than
their illegal competitors can, fans would be willing to pay
something for that privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Internet music, like rock and roll, is here to stay.
Hey, hey. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
