<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5785 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-28 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANFORTH REPORT SHOULD QUELL DAVIDIAN CONSPIRACY CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad news for the Mount Carmel conspiracy nuts: David Koresh set
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us already knew that, of course, but special counsel
John Danforth made it official when he issued his preliminary
report in the latest investigation of the federal government's
handling of that Branch Davidian business back in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, a former U.S. senator from Missouri and an Episcopal
priest, is renowned in and out of government for his competence and
integrity. If Danforth says that Koresh was responsible for the
fire that consumed him and 80 or so members of his cult, we can
stop arguing about it _ Koresh was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's own assessment of the conclusions produced by his
investigation told us everything that we needed to know. Danforth
is most assuredly not a man who is prone to overstatement, and yet
he couldn't have been more emphatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give you these conclusions with 100 percent certainty,'' he
said as he released the preliminary report at a news conference
last week.
</P>
<P>
   He urged reporters and the public to read his preface to the
report to confirm how strongly he felt about the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This interim report summarizes the exhaustive efforts
undertaken to date to investigate every lead and to test every
theory,'' Danforth wrote. ``There is no doubt in my mind about the
conclusions of this report.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth said that the investigation not only proved that the
Davidians started the fire that destroyed their compound on April
19, 1993, but also refuted allegations that federal agents shot at
the Davidians that day and that military forces were used
illegally.
</P>
<P>
   It bears repeating: Danforth is not inclined to overstatement.
Now here's some more of his preface:
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, what is remarkable is the overwhelming evidence
exonerating the government from the charges made against it, and
the lack of any real evidence to support the charges of bad acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth said that the lack of evidence implicating the
government in wrongdoing was ``particularly remarkable in light of
the widespread and persistent public belief that the government
engaged in bad acts at Waco.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth referred to a 1999 Time magazine poll saying that 61
percent of those surveyed believed that federal agents started the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing, isn't it? If the poll was accurate, we must conclude
that six out of every 10 Americans suspected the government of the
greatest democracy on earth of incinerating a building full of men,
women and children.
</P>
<P>
   It's especially amazing when you consider that it isn't true.
</P>
<P>
   How could so many people come to believe such a horrifying lie _
such a preposterous piece of fiction?
</P>
<P>
   Start with reckless, irresponsible members of Congress who must
have known the truth but decided that undermining the nation's
respect for law and order was a fair tradeoff for a chance to
pummel President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno. For
Clinton/Reno haters, it was far more rewarding to blame the
government for the lethal debacle near Waco, Texas, than to concede
that it was perpetrated by a murdering, child-molesting
megalomaniac known as David Koresh.
</P>
<P>
   With some of America's most powerful lawmakers leading the
charge, it became politically and socially acceptable for seemingly
legitimate television and radio talk-show hosts to jump on the
misinformation bandwagon right along with the countless goofballs
who spend their days wondering when government agents will start
kicking down doors and methodically replacing America's hard-won
liberty with some mysterious tyranny known as the New World Order.
</P>
<P>
   And the mainstream media is not without blame. Maybe some
newspaper or TV news outlet made a serious effort to set the record
straight, but if so, it slipped by me. For the most part, the media
chose to fuel the conspiracy theories by treating unfounded
allegations against the government as if they might have some basis
in fact.
</P>
<P>
   So. Thank you, John Danforth. The truth was long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
