<HEADER>
A5799 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX     07-28 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL MY .EXES LIVE IN TEXAS, I THINK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: A recent article made reference to dumping
files with either a .Vbs or .Js extension and also files with .Exe,
.Com and .Bat extensions. I have been unable to find any extensions
on my e-mail files.
</P>
<P>
   _ No Dots
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NO: Microsoft dumbed down Windows when they introduced 95
to keep it from scaring people, and that included hiding certain
extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the goofy legacy of DOS is that file types are
identified by extensions rather than internal coding. For example,
when you click on an .Exe, Windows knows it should run it.
</P>
<P>
   That column warned about opening e-mail attachments with the
extensions you mentioned, since they are potential virus carriers.
Those extensions are among the hidden ones.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing I do every time I install Windows _ aside from
enjoying a large cocktail _ is to turn all that stuff back on. In
Win98, go to Settings in the Start menu, then Folder Options. Click
the View tab, then select ``show all files'' and uncheck ``hide
file extensions for known file types.'' In Win95, open up My
Computer, then pick Options in the View menu, where you'll find a
similar dialog box.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I moved my pixel setting to the ``most''
position and blanked out my screen. A friend got my display working
again, but everything is grainy and my daughter's games cannot be
played because the computer is only working with 16 colors. I'm
sorry I was toying with my computer, and I will never do it again.
</P>
<P>
   _ Learned My Lesson
</P>
<P>
   DEAR LESSON: Nonsense. Goobering up your computer is the only
way to learn about it. You now have the wonderful opportunity to
teach yourself all about video cards, monitors and software
drivers, you lucky guy.
</P>
<P>
   You attempted to make your system do more than it could and it
freaked. Go into Safe Mode to patch things up. Just hit F8 when you
see the ``Starting Windows'' message.
</P>
<P>
   Delete the video card and monitor from the Device Manager (Look
in System in the Control Panel), and hope that Windows recognizes
your specific hardware when you reboot. If it doesn't, you get
stuck with generic drivers that will limit you to 16 colors in a
640-by-480 display.
</P>
<P>
   Latch onto the specific drivers for your hardware at the
manufacturer's Web site, and follow the instructions that should
come with them. Then maybe your daughter will speak to you again.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I take exception with one piece of advice you
gave recently when you suggested using a program to block the ads
on Web pages. How can sites operate without income? Is there a
program to remove the ads from the newspaper page that your column
is on?
</P>
<P>
   _ Morally Outraged
</P>
<P>
   DEAR OUT: I guess it shouldn't have been a surprise to find all
those banner ads _ including one for a cheesy matchmaking service _
cluttering up your own Web site, which appears to be a
conglomeration of half-baked commentaries by semi-literate
``writers'' striving desperately to feel their own importance.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I think that's good. The Internet is the
last frontier of independent commentary, a democracy where even a
loon is entitled to 15 minutes on the soapbox.
</P>
<P>
   But now I'm confused. I quote from your own article:
``Sponsorships ... can influence the information you read, hear or
see. Therefore, much of the news you're presented (with) should be
greeted with a measure of skepticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't have said it better myself.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and please patronize our fine advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay especially enjoys being next to lingerie ads
in case the person who designs his page is reading this. Write to
him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
