<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5803 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-KATHIE-LEE-BOS &LR;      07-28 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KATHIE-LEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATHIE LEE GIFFORD FADES OUT _ QUIETLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was, of course, doomed from the start. Short of announcing
that she would divorce Frank, collaborate with Eminem, or get an
on-air sex change, there was simply no chance that Kathie Lee
Gifford's last day on the job Friday was going to live up to the
media hype of the past week _ let alone 15 years filled with the
sort of fierce adoration and unbridled loathing reserved for
controversial politicians and talk-show hosts.
</P>
<P>
   So like most highly anticipated events, Kathie Lee's final hour
co-hosting ``Live with Regis and Kathie Lee'' was strangely
anti-climactic. There were no poignant outpourings of affection, no
sly glimmers of relief, and precious little of that famous
chemistry. There wasn't, in fact, an unguarded moment. Ironically,
our (anti) hero's final hour was characterized by a marked absence
of spunk and spontaneity _ the very qualities that made her a
household name.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we scrolled back through the archives, fondly
chronicling the hairdos, the repartee, the amusing animal segments.
Famous friends (Rosie, Letterman, Howie Mandel, Susan Lucci) sent
videotaped farewells. Illustrious colleagues appeared in person,
most notably Disney chief (and Kathie Lee's boss) Michael Eisner,
to present her with a ``Mouscar'' award and a plea for one more
farewell week. Protracted departures, he sensitively pointed out,
get great ratings. Cody and Cassidy padded dutifully onstage to
deliver a gift basket of cookbooks and foodstuffs in the hope that
mom ``could learn to make cereal.'' Even Kathie Lee didn't look
amused, and who can blame her. The future is now.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, we were left with a handful of archetypal images. A
final dusting off of Regis's suit jacket (Sweet Kathie Lee). A
sassy red dress with a plunging neckline (Saucy Kathie Lee). A
written proclamation from Rudy Guiliani encapsulating her career,
prompting Kathie Lee to inquire if every scandal was included
(Teflon Kathie Lee).
</P>
<P>
   In between flashbacks and tributes she swallowed hard and
blinked back tears. Not that revisiting her quips through the years
about Regis's hemorrhoids wasn't entirely appropriate. But more
important, it relieved her of the impossible task of saying
good-bye. In the end, Kathie Lee folded her winning hand in the
noble _ but oh so disappointing _ pursuit of keeping it together.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne and cake were wheeled out. The kids made a beeline for
the dessert table. ``Good-bye, sweetie,'' said Regis. ``I love
you,'' said Kathie Lee. Then, in a last gesture she'll probably
regret for the rest of her life, Kathie Lee unfolded her napkin and
threw it over her face.
</P>
<P>
   It is, finally, a wrap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5806 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-PANAM103-TRIAL-NEWHOU     07-28 2365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM103-TRIAL-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FAMILIES OF PAM AM 103, MORE IS AT STAKE IN TRIAL THAN FATE OF
LIBYANS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, July 28, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With two photos, of Aphrodite Tsairis (NNS1) and Suse
Lowenstein (NNS2)
 By BOB BRAUN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Libyans are on trial here for mass murder.
</P>
<P>
   But to many of the families of the 270 men, women and children
killed in the terrorist bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 in 1988,
considerably more is at stake than the fate of two Libyans.
</P>
<P>
   Especially for the relatives of 189 dead Americans -- the
largest number of American civilians ever killed in a terrorist
attack.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the ability of the American government to protect its
citizens from terrorist attack is still an issue. So is its
willingness to care more about justice than about the politics of
oil.
</P>
<P>
   So is the meaning of justice. Or vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   And how to go on living without irreplaceable children or
parents or husbands or wives or sisters or brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what justice is anymore,'' says Gerry Buser of
Glen Rock, N.J., here for the trial, which adjourned Thursday for a
three-week break. ``I don't know whether I'll find it here. But I
came to see whether I could look them in the eye. And I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Buser, 73, here with her daughter Eileen and granddaughter Kate,
lost her husband, a son, a daughter and an unborn grandchild when a
semtex bomb, placed inside a cassette tape player and wrapped in a
blue baby jumper, tore through the fuselage of a Boeing 747 at 7:02
p.m., Wednesday, Dec. 21, 1988, some 31,000 feet over the small
Scottish town of Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
   All 259 passengers and crew members were killed. On the ground,
11 residents of a housing project in Lockerbie were vaporized when
the jumbo jet's engines crashed into four homes, creating an
inferno of burning aviation fuel that still haunts the memories of
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all grown up now, but my children still fear the sound
of the wind,'' says Donald Bogie of Lockerbie. ``It was the wind
that carried the flames through the town.''
</P>
<P>
   Debris from the disintegrating plane was strewn over 850 square
miles. Local residents still fear they may yet find grisly
reminders of the tragedy. The bodies of 17 victims were never
found.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 years, a criminal trial is what many of the victims'
families wanted -- a way to obtain justice, to fix blame, to learn
what has been heretofore hidden in the secret files of American and
Scottish investigators.
</P>
<P>
   A trial, yes, but, to some, not this trial. Not here in an
abandoned NATO air force base. Not here among a mixed collection of
empty and expensively refurbished buildings adjacent to a Dutch
military museum surrounded by hulks of decommissioned airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's designed to ensure few people here will even know it's
going on,'' says Susan Cohen of Cape May, N.J. She and her husband,
Daniel, have been its most ardent critics. They lost their only
child, a daughter, Theo, 20, one of 35 Syracuse University students
returning from a semester in London.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the victims was 27. The youngest was 2
months.
</P>
<P>
   The trial takes place in a courtroom separated from spectators
by a wall of bulletproof and soundproof glass, a courtroom
populated by men and women who wear wigs, presided over by judges
in white robes emblazoned with red crosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking of `Alice in Wonderland,''' says Helen Tobin
of Hempstead, N.Y. She lost her son, Mark, 21, a Fordham student.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Scottish trial, conducted under Scottish law by
Scottish judges and, by quirk of international treaty, sited in
what is considered Scottish soil guarded by Scottish cops bearing
semi-automatic rifles and patrolled by two Scottish bomb-sniffing
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   That's the result of a compromise. The accused, Abdelbasset Ali
Mohmed al-Megrahi, 48, and Al Amin Khalifa Fhimah, 44, were
indicted by U.S. and British justice officials on Nov. 14, 1991,
but Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi refused to turn them over. After
seven years of U.N. sanctions and secret diplomacy, the U.S. and
British governments acceded to Gadhafi's demand that the two be
tried in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
   That, to some Americans, was a betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a deal, because our government wanted the problem to go
away,'' says Susan Cohen. ``Business interests were more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is no death penalty under Scottish law. One Texas
woman, Libby Purtell -- who lost a son, a daughter-in-law and a
grandchild -- sighs, ``In Texas, we would know what to do with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its location and strict Scottish court rules against
media coverage, the trial of a terrorist attack even more lethal to
Americans than Oklahoma City has received little attention. If you
want to see it, you must come here. Family members -- and only
family members -- can view it on downlink sites, but only in
Washington, New York, London and Dumfries, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to other family members, it was the best anyone could
expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alternative was never having a trial,'' says Aphrodite
Tsairis of Franklin Lakes, N.J. She views the Camp Zeist
proceedings as a triumph of years of lobbying and pressure and
pleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The train is on the track now, and it has a life of its own,''
says Tsairis, whose daughter, Alexia, 20, was killed in the
bombing. ``Finally, I can breathe a sigh of relief. We no longer
need to push.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial is often puzzling to the Americans, most of whom fly
here courtesy of the U.S. Justice Department's Office of Victims of
Crime. They get airfare and a week in a nearby hotel. They must pay
for meals, and they are expensive, so some have dinners of snacks
in the bar because the nearest town is a mile walk.
</P>
<P>
   It's puzzling because the lawyers do not offer statements
explaining evidence, either at the opening or in mid-trial. They
don't ``connect up'' as American lawyers do, so viewers have some
sense of narrative. And Scottish law requires corroboration of
every fact put into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But gradually a picture has emerged that fits the prosecution's
case: A suitcase bearing the bomb -- in a cassette player
grotesquely called a ``Bombeat'' -- somehow got on an Air Malta
plane to Frankfurt, then was transferred to a Pan Am feeder flight
to London, then, although unaccompanied by a passenger, loaded into
the cargo hold of Pan Am 103 to New York.
</P>
<P>
   A cassette player that, prosecutors say, detonated in the skies
above Lockerbie on the longest night of the year, four days before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   There are no lawyerly histrionics. The decorum of a Scottish
court won't permit it. But there has been drama. Lockerbie
residents describing the inferno, the debris, the bodies. The
reading of victims' names. A Swiss engineer who sold bomb timers to
Libyans. A Malta shopkeeper identifying Megrahi as the man who
bought the baby jumper. A travel agent describing Fhimah, an
employee of Libyan Arab Airlines, as a man with unfettered access
to luggage-bearing conveyor belts -- and luggage tags -- at Malta's
Luqa Airport.
</P>
<P>
   There's been anger, too. After former Pan Am security officials
from Frankfurt spoke of international alerts about terrorism --
warnings passengers never saw -- Helen Englehardt Hawkins of
Brooklyn, widowed by the bomb, denounced them as ``Eichmanns -- all
of them -- and they should be tried.''
</P>
<P>
   How is the trial going? ``Fine,'' says Colin Boyd, Scotland's
Lord Advocate, Scotland's Attorney General. He often visits
American relatives attending the trial. ``Hard to say,'' says Jack
Davidson, one of the Scottish defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   That's all they'll say, because Scottish lawyers can go to jail
for commenting on a case. So can journalists who write about them.
</P>
<P>
   The constraints on the two sides make it difficult to judge just
how solid the prosecution's case is -- or how confident the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Much will depend on a witness scheduled to testify after the
trial's summer break ends Aug. 22. His name is Abdul Majid Giaka, a
Libyan defector -- with Megrahi, a member of the secret police --
now in an American witness protection program. He has been
identified as an eyewitness with personal knowledge of Fhimah and
Megrahi's connection to the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   If Giaka says what he is expected to say and withstands
cross-examination, the defendants might be convicted. If not, the
judges -- sitting instead of a jury, another compromise -- may
acquit.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in another peculiarity of Scottish law, the judges could
issue a verdict of ``not proven.'' It has the same effect as an
acquittal -- the accused go free and cannot be retried -- but is
not a statement of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like the crash all over again,'' says Helen Tobin.
``I don't know how I could survive it.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Many -- perhaps most -- Americans attending the trial believe
Fhimah and Megrahi are guilty. ``I can't look at the defendants,''
says New Hampshire physician Lestra Benello, whose son Julian, 25,
a Cambridge student, was killed in the bombing. ``I can't look into
the eyes of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't buy defense contentions, outlined in a so-called
``special plea'' filed with the court, that the bombing was carried
out by the Syrian-backed Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine -- General Command (PFLP-GC). Defense attorneys already
have established Mohammed Abu Talb, a member of the group now in
prison in Sweden, was in Malta in December 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are convinced of the Libyans' guilt, many relatives
may see a not guilty or not proven verdict as the last -- perhaps
most unbearable -- betrayal in a long series that began when the
United States failed to react immediately and forcefully to the
bombing, failed to act against Gadhafi and other Libyan officials
when the indictments were issued, and failed to insist on having
the trial in the United States or the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``If politics is about taking lives,'' asks Dan Tobin, 30,
Mark's brother, ``why isn't it our turn? We have such a feeling of
impotence.''
</P>
<P>
   A few relatives believe the Libyans may not be responsible. One
is Marina Larracoechea of New York. Her sister, Maria, was a flight
attendant on Pan Am 103. The American government, she says, knew
Pan Am 103 would be blown out of the sky but did nothing -- our way
of compensating Iran for the accidental shooting down of an Iranian
airline by the U.S.S. Vincennes four months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister, all those people, were sacrificed,'' she says,
adding she believes the highest government officials in the United
States, the United Kingdom and Germany -- not two Libyans -- should
be in the dock.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the trial itself -- barely noticed in world media
-- is less important to relatives than the ways they have come to
terms with their own losses. And that has everything to do with
Lockerbie and its residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't forgotten us,'' says Buser who, like many
relatives attending the trial, took a side trip to the Scottish
town. ``They show us a respect we haven't received from our own
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockerbie residents often greet American relatives at Dryfesdale
Cemetery, the site of a granite tablet bearing all the victims'
names. Christy Hunter, 22, says he comes there often. He was 10 in
1988 and recalls being led through the streets of town while
burning debris swirled about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans want to know details,'' he says. ``I tell them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is there, in Lockerbie, not 400 miles away in the
Netherlands, where many Americans have come to find peace during
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound strange, but if it had to happen, I'm glad it
happened here,'' says Suse Lowenstein of Montauk, N.Y. Her son,
Alexander, 21, was on Pan Am 103. ``I find so much peace here.''
</P>
<P>
   She is resting on the grass, her back against a stone wall. A
few yards away is the cairn she built years ago on the spot where
Alexander hit the earth with so much impact his body left an
indentation.
</P>
<P>
   At least once a year, she comes to repair the cairn. Cows that
graze nearby rub their backs against it and loosen the stones. She
has put sand from Montauk inside it. A name tag Alexander wore when
he parked cars for a summer job. On this trip, she has brought a
colorful snail shell from home to hide within the hard whinstone
once quarried here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cry here, but I also laugh a lot. I have no more bitterness.
No more hate,'' says Lowenstein, who often comes in the spring to
help local farmers deliver new lambs.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is important, she says, but to be here, close to where
Alexander died, is more so.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``For Alexander, I have tried to live a much richer life,'' says
Lowenstein, a sculptress whose statues can be found in a number of
corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   One of her works, a tribute to Alexander, hangs at Dryfesdale.
She places a rose on the plaque depicting a dolphin frolicking
among the waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a surfer and loved the sea. And he was so playful.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of her work since 1988 has dealt with the tragedy. On her
lawn in Montauk is ``Dark Elegy,'' a collection of 50 life-size
statues of Pan Am relatives -- all women -- who posed for her,
depicted as they remembered themselves at the moment they heard of
Lockberie, frozen in horror and agony.
</P>
<P>
   The women posed nude -- ``We all were stripped naked emotionally
by what happened'' -- and inside each statue are hidden mementos of
the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Only one woman is depicted twice: Lowenstein herself. One statue
shows her on her knees, her head buried in her hands. Facing it is
another, head up, hands outstretched to the woman overwhelmed by
grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me, too. Telling myself I must live.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Braun is a staff writer with The Star-Ledger of Newark,
N.J.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
