<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-PLATFORM (Philadelphia) _ Pro-choice Republicans lose
their fight to delete strong anti-abortion language from the party
platform. A platform subcommittee also inserts language that
toughens the GOP's stance against gay rights. But platform drafters
add language saying, ``We recognize that members of our party can
have deeply held and sometimes differing views.'' By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Spring Dale, Ark.) _ Republicans George W. Bush and
Dick Cheney draw sharp contrasts with the ethics of Pres. Clinton
and Al Gore, kicking off their five-day, five-state march into the
GOP convention in Philadelphia with a boisterous and symbolic foray
into the heart of Clinton country. By STEWART POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION-REALITY (Philadelphia) _ As Republican conventioneers
arrive for parties and politics, an opposition group leads a
``reality tour'' focusing on Philadelphia's gritty, poor underside.
By LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MISSION (Philadelphia) _ An analysis exploring what George
W. Bush hopes to gain from the convention and what the citizens
should expect to learn from it. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHRONICLE-SALE (San Francisco) _ After nearly a year of close
antitrust scrutiny and allegations of anti-competitive behavior
surrounding the Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the San Francisco
Chronicle, it comes to down to this: U.S. District Judge Vaughn
Walker concluded that the way the newspaper industry had handled
the dissolution of joint operating agreements had been correct all
along. By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _ Chelsea Clinton will miss classes at
Stanford University this fall to help her mother campaign for a
Senate seat from New York and to be around the White House when her
father winds up his last few months as president, according to a
White House aide. But Chelsea, 20, a senior at Stanford, will still
be able to graduate in June because she has racked up enough
credits. By HELEN THOMAS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HINES-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ A look at the naivete surrounding
the nonspontaneity of political conventions. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN _ A look at the record of George W. Bush's
running mate, Dick Cheney, shows that he is a fair-weather
``compassionate conservative.'' By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
