<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: IT'S A SEQUEL? OK, I'LL TAKE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, home video is especially keen on its own progeny:
those feature-length films, animated and live action, that go
straight to cassette and disc without playing in theaters. Not that
there has been too much of a critical sea change. Direct-to-video
movies still couldn't be any good, or so goes the view even of most
video dealers, who regard a movie's record on the big screen as
vital to its appeal at home.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, huge amounts of money have broadened the outlook.
Big direct-to-video movies like ``American Tail 4: The Mystery of
the Night Monster,'' released this week by Universal, are bought by
the millions of copies. Obviously they have to meet certain
standards, but film criticism per se is essentially beside the
point. It is much more important that the movie fit a mold and take
its place in a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real key is to expand the franchises,'' said Ken Graffeo,
Universal's senior vice president for marketing. Video movies are
numbered: for example, the live-action ``Beethoven's 3rd,'' also
released this week, the animated ``Land Before Time VII: The Stone
of Cold Fire'' (coming this fall) and the live-action ``Dragonheart
2: A New Beginning,'' to be released Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, direct-to-video has leaned toward the
exploitational. Now it has become a highly lucrative assembly line
of brand-name movies that are relatively cheaply produced and often
bland as vanilla for the family audience.
</P>
<P>
   Disney fanned the direct-to-video fires in the 1990s with ``The
Lion King II: Simba's Pride'' and ``The Return of Jafar,'' which
despite its lack of a numeral was the sequel to ``Aladdin.'' The
two films, made at a fraction of the cost of the big-screen
originals, are said to have brought in a total of $500 million.
Released in 1994, Universal's ``Land Before Time 2: The Great
Valley Adventure'' kicked off a series of video sequels that has
made $1 billion worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Are they good films? Critics jumped fairly hard on the two
Disney sequels, but that could have been expected, given the
illustrious reputations of their predecessors. Actually, the best
direct-to-video sequels have good to excellent production values
and are otherwise competent enough for what they do; please
children, prime the cash cow and perpetuate the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beethoven's 3rd'' is an example. A sappy, squeaky-clean tale
of mom, dad, sis and junior and the sloppy St. Bernard that goes
along on their vacation, the film gets the job done for the average
8-year-old. ``Beethoven 4'' is currently in production. (The real
Beethoven got up to nine, remember.)
</P>
<P>
   This fall Dreamworks will edge into direct-to-video for the
first time with ``Joseph: King of Dreams,'' an animated film based
on the biblical story of the favored son sold into slavery by his
envious brothers. The studio emphasizes that it is not a sequel or
part of a series. It also points out that viewers might make a
connection with ``Prince of Egypt,'' the studio's successful
big-screen feature last year, and that many of the same people
worked on both movies.
</P>
<P>
   Will those be associations enough? Dreamworks is promoting
``Joseph'' as if it were a theater release. ``Start six months out
to get a buzz,'' said Kelley Avery, the studio's head of worldwide
video worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   `MAGNOLIA'
</P>
<P>
   Paul Thomas Anderson's mosaic mixes a half-dozen lives into an
Altmanesque swirl. While the old television mogul Earl Partridge
(Jason Robards) lies dying and lamenting past indiscretions, his
young wife (Julianne Moore) quaffs his painkillers and wails about
her own infidelities. Then, to name a few, there are the morose
former child television-quiz-show star (William H. Macy), the
present whiz kid (Jeremy Blackman) and the strutting macho cult
figure (Tom Cruise, above). None of this jells, but, Janet Maslin
wrote in The New York Times, ``what Anderson lacks in substance is
offset by his great skill with actors, his gift for shaping
resonant little individual vignettes and his extraordinary
intuition.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. New Line. $108.77. 188 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   `PUPS'
</P>
<P>
   A Bonnie and Clyde for the MTV generation, Stevie (Cameron Van
Hoy) and Rocky (Mischa Barton) interrupt their walk to school to
rob a bank. Angered by neglectful families, the teen-agers shoot a
guard, take hostages and talk about the ills of society. Among
their demands are a visit from MTV, margarita mix, condoms and an
end to smoking by the FBI commander (Burt Reynolds). Written and
directed by Ash (single name only), the film ``takes a knowing look
at adolescents informed but not educated by television and movies
in a less than perfect United States'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   2000. Monarch. $94.95; DVD, $19.95. 103 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   `ROMEO MUST DIE'
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for Shakespeare in Andrzej Bartkowiak's
hip-hop-kung-fu tale of greed and revenge. Isaak (Delroy Lindo)
intimidates waterfront business owners so he can buy up their
properties. Trish (Aaliyah) is his attractive daughter, and Han
(Jet Li, the Hong Kong action star) wants to avenge the killing of
his little brother. A sleek look and well-selected soundtrack
helps, but the movie is ``overly dutiful in dragging itself through
the exercise of playing out its plot elements, ignoring the chief
lesson of its Hong Kong antecedents: Extend the martial
gymnastics'' (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   2000. Warner. $110.97; DVD, $24.98. 115 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Aug.1.
</P>
<P>
   `THE NINTH GATE'
</P>
<P>
   Who better than Frank Langella for the role of Boris Balkan, an
evil collector of devil-inspired antiquities? Johnny Depp is Dean
Corso, the rogue book dealer whom Balkan hires to locate a volume
called ``The Nine Gates.'' Could Satan have a hand in this one?
Actually, three versions of ``Gates'' are at stake, and Corso must
stay a step ahead of Liana (Lena Olin), a dangerous widow in black,
and a sylph (Emmanuelle Seigner). Trying for both fright and
satire, Roman Polanski's film ``is about as scary as a sock-puppet
re-enactment of `The Blair Witch Project,' and not nearly as
funny'' (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Artisan. $112.18; DVD, $24.98. 127 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   `RUDOLF NUREYEV'
</P>
<P>
   All of Nureyev's Bell Telephone Hour performances from 1962 to
1964: the pas de deux from ``Flower Festival in Genzano,'' with
Maria Tallchief; the pas de deux from ``Le Corsaire,'' with Lupe
Serrano; the ``Diana and Actaeon'' pas de deux from ``La
Esmeralda'' and the ``Black Swan'' pas de deux from ``Swan Lake,''
both with Svetlana Beriosova. With the Bell Telephone Hour
Orchestra, conducted by Donald Vorhees. 2000. Video Artists
International. $29.99. 37 minutes. Information: (800) 477-7146.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE BANK DICK' and SIX SHORT FILMS OF W.C. FIELDS'
</P>
<P>
   Writing ``The Bank Dick'' under the pseudonym Mahatma Kane
Jeeves, Fields creates his last role for himself: the drunken
Egbert Souse, a habitue of the Black Pussy Cat Cafe who foils a
stickup at a bank and is made a security guard at the place (1940,
DVD, Criterion Collection/Home Vision, $29.95, 72 minutes). The
second disc includes all six of his short films: ``The Pool
Sharks'' (1915, 11 minutes), ``The Golf Specialist'' (1930, 21
minutes), ``The Dentist'' (1932, 22 minutes), ``The Fatal Glass of
Beer'' (1933, 19 minutes), ``The Pharmacist'' (1933, 20 minutes)
and ``The Barber Shop'' (1933, 22 minutes). The Criterion
Collection/Home Vision. $29.95. Release date: Aug 15.
</P>
<P>
   `GOOD NEIGHBORS'
</P>
<P>
   The queen herself followed the '70s Britcom (starring Paul
Eddington and Penelope Keith) about the Leadbetters, ever striving
for material success, and their neighbors the Goods, who are
determined to live off the suburban land. 2000. Acorn. Seven
30-minute episodes, two cassettes, $29.95. Information: (800)
474-2277.
</P>
</TEXT>
