<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     07-28 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: (Stephen Holden).  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``GLADIATOR,'' starring Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie
Nielsen, Richard Harris and Oliver Reed. Directed by Ridley Scott
(R, 150 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This movie is the answer to a question no one bothered to ask:
what would happen if someone decided to film the imminent extreme
football league as if it were a Chanel commercial? Scott subjects
action-packed bouts of mayhem and decapitation in the Roman
Colosseum to his glossy, inhuman directing style; it is admirable
but repellent. As the noble Roman general who ends up fighting for
his life, Crowe gives a performance with ball-of-fire intensity
suffused with a movie star's impatience. He holds the movie
together, such as it is (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``GHOST DOG: THE WAY OF THE SAMURAI,'' starring Forest Whitaker.
Directed by Jim Jarmusch (R, 116 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In his new film Jarmusch does for the samurai epic and the
gangster movie what he did for the western in ``Dead Man,'' his
dreamy, elegiac deconstruction of cowboys-and-Indians mythology.
Here he has composed a ruminative, bittersweet visual essay on
brutality, honor and tribalism, which may frustrate audiences
expecting more visceral thrills. ``Ghost Dog'' is worth seeing for
Whitaker's witty, moving performance as a modern-day samurai caught
up in a Mafia vendetta, for Jarmusch's offbeat sense of cinematic
style and for the hip-hop artist RZA's brilliant musical effects
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``GROOVE,'' starring Hamish Linklater, Lola Glaudini, Mackenzie
Firgens and Steve Van Wormer. Directed by Greg Harrison (R, 86
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   If you're nostalgic for chasing down a rave gig across the city
and arriving to find a pair of 16-year-olds discussing the merits
of drum and bass versus jungle, then this mostly knowing and funny
comedy is just the film for you. Even if you're not, its seductive
lack of pretension will win you over. ``Groove'' is a comedy of
moments, tracking a crowd through the ups and downs of one night of
pleasure at a rave. Harrison and his team don't try to pretend that
raves are anything new or dangerous. Rather, they're an entrenched
circuit with specific tribal complications, and this genial picture
captures them (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``LOSER,'' starring Jason Biggs, Mena Suvari and Greg Kinnear.
Directed by Amy Heckerling (PG-13, 93 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Admirers of Ms. Heckerling's movies _ notably ``Clueless'' and
``Fast Times at Ridgmont High'' _ may be disappointed in her latest
effort, a romantic comedy about two college students who overcome
the snobbery and cruelty of their surroundings to find true love.
The script could have used a few more drafts and a less perfunctory
climax, but Heckerling's characteristic wit and intelligence is
still in evidence. Fine performances by Biggs as the title
character, Suvari as the girl of his dreams and Kinnear as a sleazy
literature professor help make ``Loser'' more enjoyable than most
recent youth-targeted date movies (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``ME, MYSELF AND IRENE,'' starring Jim Carrey and Renee
Zellweger. Directed by Bobby Farrelly and Peter Farrelly (R, 100
minutes). If ``There's Something About Mary'' offended you with its
callous mockery of hair and pet care and its whimsical views of
stalking and serial killing, then this latest festival of vulgarity
from the Farrelly brothers will make you miserable. But ``Me,
Myself and Irene'' shares with their earlier movies a kind of
dopey, boyish sincerity and a good-natured sympathy for the
underdog that may prove capable of winning over even the dourest
spirits. Carrey, in one _ or is it two? _ of his most charming and
repellent performances, plays a Rhode Island state trooper with a
split personality and a giant crush on Irene, played with winning
moxie and plausible bewilderment by Zellweger (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``M:I-2,'' starring Tom Cruise, Thandie Newton and Anthony
Hopkins. Directed by John Woo (PG-13, 120 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Cruise returns as the daredevil secret agent Ethan Hunt in Woo's
loud, flashy, incoherent new blockbuster. The film is jampacked
with movie references _ to Hitchcock, to the first ``Mission:
Impossible'' movie and to Woo's earlier, and superior Hong Kong
action films _ but it's at once overheated and flat. The plot,
involving killer viruses, is baffling rather than twisty. The
introduction of a love interest ( Newton) who also happens to be
the bad guy's ex-girlfriend adds an element of melodrama that's
more grating than affecting. Some good car chases and explosions,
though (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE PATRIOT,'' starring Mel Gibson and Chris Cooper. Directed
by Roland Emmerich (R, 158 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   A grueling Revolutionary War epic that, at more than two and a
half hours, seems to take place in real time. The brutality and
sentimentality are effective, though the film will leave you
feeling used as you exit the theater. This sort-of prequel to
Emmerich's ``Independence Day'' stars Gibson as a gentle farmer who
leads the Colonies in wresting freedom from the Brits, using
counterintuitive methods alarmingly similar to terrorism. His
anguished masculinity is brandished like a musket. The film's chief
asset is his relationship with the young actors playing his
children; it draws on the actor's real-life feeling about his own
large brood, and his work with them is stirring (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE PERFECT STORM,'' starring George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg,
Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, John C. Reilly and Diane Lane.
Directed by Wolfgang Petersen (PG-13, 130 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Impressive but monotonously redundant special effects smother
the human drama in this true story (adapted from Sebastian Junger's
best-selling book) of a group of swordfishermen battling ``the
storm of the century'' off Massachusetts in 1991. Clooney is the
ship's glowering, enigmatic captain, and Wahlberg and Lane are the
appealing lovebirds who lend the movie its stingy quotient of
warmth. The early scenes, which paint a romantic portrait of the
fisherman's life in Gloucester, Mass., promise a great deal, but
the movie becomes waterlogged once it leaves shore (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
