<HEADER>
A5827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3RDTA     07-28 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: shore (Holden).  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``ROAD TRIP,'' starring Breckin Meyer, Seann William Scott, Amy
Smart, DJ Qualls and Tom Green. Directed by Todd Phillips (R, 91
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   ``National Lampoon's Animal House'' meets ``There's Something
About Mary'' in this gross-out farce. Four college boys led by Josh
( Meyer) embark on a desperate 1,800-mile journey from upstate New
York to Texas to intercept an X-rated dorm room video mistakenly
sent to Josh's loyal girlfriend in Austin. The fun is all in the
gags, among them the notorious French toast sequence, the
envelope-pushing sperm bank scene and the hilarious
car-jumped-over-the-bridge demolition derby. You'll laugh despite
yourself (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``RULES OF ENGAGEMENT,'' starring Tommy Lee Jones and Samuel L.
Jackson. Directed by William Friedkin (R, 123 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The two powerhouse actors muster all the technique they can
bring to bear for this by-the-numbers courtroom drama with flashes
of bruising action: it's like the world's most expensive episode of
``JAG,'' with bits of ``The Verdict'' mixed in for extra flavor.
Jones plays a shaky, alcoholic Marine lawyer brought in to defend
his fellow marine ( Jackson) against charges of military
misconduct. Since ``Rules'' makes it clear from the outset that
Jackson's character is innocent, the only suspense comes from
wondering whether Guy Pearce, as the prosecutor, will be able to
maintain his bizarre accent (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``SCARY MOVIE,'' starring Jon Abrahams, Carmen Electra and
Shannon Elizabeth. Directed by Keenen Ivory Wayans (R, 88 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Wayans' latest genre-film spoof doesn't so much lampoon the
``Scream'' movies as offer the latest remake, this time as
gross-out comedy. ``Scary Movie'' abounds in crude, often stale
jokes involving male genitals, female pubic hair, flatulence and
dismemberment. There are a few hilarious moments, and some that
will provoke guilty laughter, but Wayans hasn't quite figured out
how to parody movies _ like the wildly popular ``Scream'' series _
that already parody themselves (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``SHAFT,'' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Vanessa Williams, Jeffrey
Wright, Christian Bale, Toni Collette and Richard Roundtree. A
sequel/remake to the 1971 semiclassic, starring the always
dependable Jackson. He plays the nephew of the original Shaft
(Roundtree), and this time, Shaft is a cop. He leaves the force to
track down a racist WASP murderer (Bale), who joins forces with a
drug dealer (the flamboyant and skillful Wright) to eliminate the
hero. This may be the least politically correct movie in some time,
and though it tries to convert archetype into stereotype, it
doesn't succeed. Watching the two villains squabble for center
stage is like watching Luciano Pavarotti and Placido Domingo in a
death match for the mike. But Jackson comes out on top of this
emptily entertaining hodgepodge of retro and modern cliches
(Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``SMALL TIME CROOKS,'' starring Woody Allen and Tracey Ullman.
Directed and written by Allen (PG, 95 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The sweet, funny wisp of a movie starts out as a parody of ``Big
Deal on Madonna Street,'' then turns into a child's-eye ``Bonfire
of the Vanities'' before returning to its original mode as a caper
comedy. Allen and Ullman are Ray and Frenchy Winkler, an inept
thief and ex-con and his upwardly mobile wife, whose cookie
business takes off and allows her to indulge her dream of being a
Park Avenue hostess. If the movie suffers severely from attention
deficit disorder, the jokes are funny (but mild) and the screwball
comic tone is impeccably sustained. Ullman (putting on her Fern
Rosenthal voice) and Elaine May (as Frenchy's dimwitted cousin) are
delightfully goofy (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``SUNSHINE,'' starring Ralph Fiennes, Rachel Weisz, Jennifer
Ehle, Rosemary Harris and James Frian. Directed by Istvan Szabo (R,
180 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In Szabo's tale of 20th-century Hungarian history, Fiennes plays
three members of a wealthy Jewish Budapest family _ grandfather,
father and son _ who endure the corruption of the Austro-Hungarian
empire, the viciousness of Fascism and the brutality of Communism.
Fiennes' performances and those of Ehle and Harris (playing the
same character at different stages of life) help save the film from
melodramatic excess. Even though much of the story is crudely told,
``Sunshine'' is a serious, humane and thought-provoking attempt to
make sense of complicated and painful historical experiences
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``WHAT LIES BENEATH,'' starring Michelle Pfeiffer and Harrison
Ford. Directed by Robert Zemeckis (PG-13, 130 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Zemeckis' film takes its time in laying out the story of
high-strung Claire ( Pfeiffer), who is dissolving into hysteria on
a regular basis. Her daughter has just gone off to college, and
Claire is still recovering from the trauma of a car accident. Then
her house starts showing signs of being haunted. Her husband,
Norman ( Ford), is a driven research scientist with a secret. This
thriller is as implausibly chilling as any ``X Files'' episode. By
the last 10 minutes your interest will have long vanished
(Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``X-MEN,'' starring Patrick Stewart, Ian McKellen, Hugh Jackman,
Famke Janssen, James Marsden, Halle Berry and Anna Paquin. Directed
by Bryan Singer (PG-13, 105 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited arrival of Marvel Comics' do-gooder mutants is
mildly fun on a couple of levels: for one, the acting duel between
Stewart (as the mutant telepath Prof. X, the X-Men's leader) and
Ian McKellen (as the mutant nemesis Magneto, who possesses the
power of supermagnetism). As these two austere hams trill their
vowels at each other you get the feeling you really are watching
members of another species in action. And Jackman scores as the
two-fisted, confrontational Wolverine, a mutant with superstrength,
an ability to heal all wounds and metal-alloy claws that shoot out
from his knuckles. He lives to fight, a boisterous tragic hero with
no complications. Otherwise the movie is an earnest affair that is
clumsy when it should be light on its feet; it takes itself even
more seriously than the comic book does, though its fans may be
overjoyed by that devotion (Mitchell).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
