<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMYS-LOSERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMYS HAVE A HISTORY OF SNUBBING THE WORTHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Drew Carey'' and ``Emmy'' had never been mentioned in the same
sentence until last season when the comic actor wrapped an entire
episode around being dissed by Emmy voters. The series hasn't had a
shot at winning the best comedy category because it's never earned
a nomination. At least Carey can take solace in the knowledge that
he runs with pretty good company.
</P>
<P>
   Some of television's most notable talents have come up dry on
Emmy night. Gracie Allen. Buddy Ebsen. Arthur Godfrey. Jack Paar.
Peter Graves. Ozzie Nelson. Martin Landau.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ed Sullivan Show'' was named best variety series in 1955,
but Sullivan himself never won.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Gleason and Andy Griffith were consistently passed over,
although their comedic sidekicks, Art Carney with Gleason's ``The
Honeymooners'' and Don Knotts with Griffith's self-titled series,
won five Emmys apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roseanne'' was never nominated as best comedy during its
nine-year run, and it wasn't until recently that Emmy voters found
the charming CBS series ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' worthy of
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't explain why many of the same, familiar faces
are nominated year after year in the acting categories. When John
Larroquette kept winning for ``Night Court,'' Candace Bergen for
``Murphy Brown'' or Bill Cosby for ``Cosby,'' it became so
ridiculous that Cosby yanked his name from consideration. (Did
``Frasier'' deserve to win five consecutive times?)
</P>
<P>
   The fact that ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' continually
failed to make the cut (Andre Braugher finally got the nod) and
safe, familiar, standard dramas like ``Chicago Hope'' did, was
indicative of Emmy voters' thinking.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other blunders with Emmys, such as the year
``Lonesome Dove'' lost in the miniseries category to ``War &AMP;
Remembrance,'' or when Lindsey Wagner of ``Bionic Woman'' knocked
off Sada Thompson of ``Family'' as best actress.
</P>
<P>
   Other classic snubs:
</P>
<P>
   _ Kyle Secor, ``Homicide'': Never nominated, which is astounding
considering that he probably had the most involved development of
any character on TV during his final three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Wolf, Neve Campbell and ``Party of Five'': Fox's
reputation as a tasteless, opportunistic network usually kills the
chances of any series that it airs. Older voters probably still
consider Fox a new network.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Roseanne'': Perhaps the most noticeable snub, ``Roseanne''
achieved a rare feat by being highly regarded by critics and
viewers. The comedy series spent most of its existence in the top
10, two of those years as the country's No. 1 program. In nine
years, it never received an Emmy nomination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Angela Lansbury, ``Murder She Wrote'': Lansbury may have been
hailed four times for her work on Broadway, but she's racked up 16
Emmy losses for a series voters simply found too weak dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sarah Michelle Gellar and ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'': It
doesn't matter that ``Buffy'' is well-written and well-crafted (its
``Hush'' episode was the best of any show this year); it skews
young and appears to be outside the range of Emmy voters.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Drew Carey'': For one or two years, this was one of the best
five sitcoms on air. But Carey is much like Roseanne: too
blue-collar for typical Emmy tastes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jane Leeves, ``Frasier'': Playing the love interest of David
Hyde Pierce's Niles on the hit sitcom has probably kept voters from
taking her seriously as a stand-alone for supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patrick Stewart, ``Star Trek: Next Generation'': Stewart often
seemed overqualified for this role, but Emmy's oversight here
wasn't about his performance _ it was his show they didn't
particularly respect.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
