<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5832 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SCARYMOVIES-TEX     07-28 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCARYMOVIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCARY FILMS MAKE US JUMP, SCREAM, TINGLE ALL OVER, BUT WE KEEP
COMING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by SCARY MOVIES-WRITERS)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the new movie ``What Lies Beneath,'' Michelle Pfeiffer sees a
dead person before the opening credits are over. At a crowded
preview screening, viewers jumped, even though they knew what they
were in for. Throughout the movie, they jumped, sometimes screamed,
again and again, as director Robert Zemeckis threw out scares that
were often red herrings, but sometimes weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer's box-office clout jumped, too. ``What Lies Beneath''
grossed $29.7 million in its opening weekend. According to the
Internet Movie Database, you'd have to go back to ``One Fine Day''
in the spring of 1997 to find a Pfeiffer movie that grossed more
than that in its entire run.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``What Lies Beneath's'' opening-weekend gross was
higher than the initial-weekend numbers for Pfeiffer's past five
starring movies combined. And yeah, you could credit that to
co-star Harrison Ford, but pairing him with a female star hasn't
proved lucrative in the recent past, as the lackluster performances
of ``Random Hearts,'' ``Sabrina'' and ``Six Days, Seven Nights''
indicate.
</P>
<P>
   No, it was fear that lured moviegoers to ``What Lies Beneath'' _
or, more accurately, the hope that they'd be in for a pretty good
scare. ``What Lies Beneath'' comes nearly a year after ``The Sixth
Sense,'' another (far superior) ghost story that created tingles on
the backs of viewers' necks. And with Sam Raimi's ``The Gift,''
about a psychic trying to divine the whereabouts of a missing girl,
due out this fall, movies about the supernatural are undergoing one
of their periodic resurrections.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are misfires (last year's well-made ``Stir of
Echoes'' had the double misfortune of having limited distribution
and arriving at nearly the same time as ``The Sixth Sense'') and
fiascoes (last year's ``The Haunting'' and ``The Haunting of Hill
House''), supernatural-themed movies appear to be with us for
eternity. Why we _ well, those of us who aren't too chicken _
continue to go to them can be a bit puzzling. After all, being
scared isn't necessarily a pleasant feeling. Is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to see the dark side to be sure it exists,'' says
Donald Pritchett, director of purchasing at the Web site DVDempire
and a self-described longtime horror-film aficionado. ``There is
something about a horror film that lets us see what is out there
from the safety of our own environment. ... Look at what we gain
from horror movies: the adrenaline rush; the possibility of closer
proximity to someone who is more scared; they let us exorcise what
we sometimes wish we could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all movies _ or TV shows _ about the supernatural
are frightening. Check out the metaphysical aspects of ``Touched by
an Angel,'' ``City of Angels'' (the movie, not the TV show), ``What
Dreams May Come,'' ``Meet Joe Black'' or even ``Ghost.'' Many of
these _ successfully or not _ strive for more than does ``What Lies
Beneath,'' which aims for nothing more than to be a Hitchcock
homage/hodgepodge, what Pauline Kael called a ``boo movie'' because
it has little more ambition than to make you jump.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt ``What Lies Beneath'' got a big opening-weekend boost
by looking similar in mood to ``The Sixth Sense,'' the mega-popular
ghost story about a troubled little boy who sees dead people.
``Sense'' sailed to the all-time box-office Top 10 partly on the
strength of a key plot twist, but even more because the movie
connected with people in a way most metaphysical-themed films
don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what really struck a chord with `The Sixth Sense' is
it really looked at the question of what happens to you after
you're dead,'' said Frank Myer, president of the Dallas
Screenwriters Association. ``Everybody, on some level, worries
about that: people who believe in God, heaven or hell, but also
people who don't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What Lies Beneath'' doesn't play off of such deep themes, but
it does keep alive the notion of a restless spirit _ someone who
suffered an injustice while living and wants to correct it with the
help of someone still alive. The movie actually has more in common
with ``Stir of Echoes'' than ``The Sixth Sense,'' even though they
all share a similar plot thread.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Sixth Sense' was a whole different kettle of fish,''
says John W. Hesley, an Arlington, Texas, psychotherapist and
co-author (with his wife, Jan) of ``Rent Two Films and Let's Talk
in the Morning.'' ``It was a real dialogue between the living and
the dead. It wasn't just that a dead person comes back and helps a
living person out, but the living person was helping the dead
person as well.''
</P>
<P>
   To a point, Cole, the haunted boy played by Haley Joel Osment in
``The Sixth Sense,'' is frightened by what he encounters. Claire,
Pfeiffer's character in ``What Lies Beneath,'' is more curious
about what the restless spirit is after _ she even (at a
psychiatrist's recommendation) has a seance. Laurel Clark, the
international secretary of the School of Metaphysics in Windyville,
Mo., says that this behavior is a manifestation of something we all
have within us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has intuitive abilities,'' Clark says. ``I think
that's the primary reason people go to these movies. (The
abilities) exist and they're real and everybody has them, and we're
able to go these movies and find out about them. People need to use
them more.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear-inspired adrenaline, spiritual angst and latent intuition
aside, though, herds of ghostly white horses couldn't drag some
people to a horror movie, no matter how benevolent. Some people
find real life to be scary enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it depends on everyone's personal makeup,'' says
Philip Eisner, a Fort Worth native who wrote the screenplay to the
underrated 1997 science-fiction/horror movie ``Event Horizon,''
which explored far darker terrors than are examined in ``What Lies
Beneath'' or ``The Sixth Sense.'' ``My father's family had escaped
from Eastern Europe during World War II, so my father never wanted
to see a war movie or a scary movie. He wanted movies like `E.T.'
His idea of an escape was a happy movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner is a longtime fan of horror and science fiction (he's
gearing up for a four-hour Sci-Fi Channel update of Stephen King's
``Firestarter,'' due next year). He believes that the key to a
successful horror movie is simple: Give us somebody we can identify
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I thought was so interesting about `The Sixth Sense' was,
my wife didn't think it was scary at all,'' Eisner says. ``She said
she thought it was interesting. But it scared the hell out of me. I
was never worried about (Cole) dying. I was frightened of what he
might see next. When there's a character you're very sympathetic
to, that can make for a very frightening experience.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
