<HEADER>
A5834 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     07-28 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS SPECIAL CHRONICLES LIFE OF MAVERICK SOUTHERN PREACHER
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Note language in second graf) 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM JONES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Will D. Campbell's one-sentence definition of
Christianity may be a little blunt, even irritating, to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all bastards, but God loves us anyway,'' declares
Campbell, an iconoclastic champion of civil rights and maverick
Baptist preacher who will be featured next month on a public
television special, ``God's Will,'' produced by the University of
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   We can learn much from Campbell, an earthy spiritual gadfly and
master of one-liners who preaches a Christianity of unconditional
grace.
</P>
<P>
   He steps on toes with every comment. For example, he refers to
TV evangelists as ``electronic soul molesters.''
</P>
<P>
   When I first met Campbell, he wore a black Amish-style hat and
cowboy boots to indicate the Anabaptist-pacifist and fiery rustic
roots of his fellow Southern Baptists. He carried a hand-carved
cane.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken off the black hat. But he's still the same Will.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has made waves since the 1960s when he and two other
ministers walked beside Elizabeth Eckford as she and eight other
black teen-agers, braved angry, shouting mobs as they walked into
all-white Central High School in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he had been fired as campus minister of the University
of Mississippi, where he had spoken out against racial injustice.
When he held a reception for both blacks and whites, someone put
human feces in the punch bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was the only white person at an Atlanta meeting when
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and other civil rights leaders
formed the Southern Christian Leadership Congress. He downplays his
role in the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like Dr. King had personally invited me,'' he said.
``But it is true I was the only white there.''
</P>
<P>
   When I previewed the television special, I fondly remembered a
spring day in the late 1980s when I drove over a hilly, tree-lined
road to Campbell's 40-acre farm at Mount Juliet, Tenn., east of
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   He was wandering around his place, which gave the title to
``Forty Acres and a Goat,'' one of his 15 books. He fed a stray dog
that had wandered up to his log-cabin office, and had found a new
home.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell welcomes stray dogs, celebrities, country music stars,
famous novelists, civil rights activists and reporters _ just about
anybody _ to his home. It is a part of his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Back in his log-cabin office, I took photos as he carried on his
daily routine, answering phone calls from Amnesty International and
other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he drove me through the hills to a tavern for lunch.
Everyone knew him there. He plays his guitar with the band there on
Friday nights and sings country songs that he said he believes have
much to do with the religious soul of the South.
</P>
<P>
   The television special calls the tavern Campbell's church. He
marries and buries the people who come there.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks frequently across the nation and has been the subject
of four books, including ``Will Campbell: Soul of the South'' by
Thomas L. Connelly. The black-hat-wearing minister, Will B. Dunn,
in Doug Marlett's comic strip ``Kudzu'' is based on Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell loves the South, even though he was berated by many
fellow Southerners as he sought to promote racial justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South was wrong, but it's my South,'' he says in the TV
special, which is narrated by Ossie Davis. The initial broadcast is
scheduled for 9 p.m. Aug. 25 on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Ordained as a Baptist preacher in his hometown of Liberty,
Miss., at the West Fork Baptist Church, Campbell remembers
preaching his first sermon looking at a huge pulpit Bible presented
years earlier by the Ku Klux Klan and inscribed with the letters
``KKK.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was a child when the Klansmen, dressed in full regalia,
came to the church. When KKK members presented the Bible,
Campbell's father, Jesse Campbell, walked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he did it,'' Will Campbell says. ``I guess
there was something in his genes that said, `This isn't right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter, United Methodist minister and
civil rights activist Jim Lawson and country music stars Tom T.
Hall, Waylon Jennings and Jessi Colter eulogize Campbell during the
special.
</P>
<P>
   Carter describes Campbell as a ``deeply religious man; one who
has a great deal of spirit _ calm, wise, witty, eloquent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell takes it all in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why it's such a big deal,'' he says. ``I get
notice. I get press. I get awards. But I'm just one more Marine. I
haven't been a big man in any movement. I'm not sure I've had a
ministry. I've had a life. To me it's all a celebration. I like it.
I do believe in priesthood of the believer _ that we are all
ministers to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
