<HEADER>
A5836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT &LR;      07-28 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, July 29. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Jerusalem) _ President Clinton, seeking to
shore up Prime Minister Ehud Barak's shaky political base, appeared
on Israel television to heap praise on Barak, promising rewards for
peace and even hinting that he was ready to move the U.S. embassy
to Jerusalem. Such a move would be regarded as a monumental triumph
here, an achievement of Israel's cherished dream of having
Jerusalem recognized as its capital. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CAMP-DAVID (Washington) _ At the recently ended Mideast
peace talks at Camp David, there were serious moments, as when
discussions about the fate of Jerusalem opened what all sides
called the taboo issue, and there were light moments, as when
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators traded cigars, dodged deer and
chipmunks as they navigated paths in golf carts, bowled and played
table tennis. By Elaine Sciolino and Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-VI (Undated) _ Another installment in a series of
articles about the lives of the presidential candidates. This
article focuses on the personal changes that George W. Bush went
through in midlife. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-PRIMARIES (Philadelphia) _ Aides to George W. Bush
rallied opposition Friday to scuttle a plan that would overhaul the
presidential primary schedule by stretching the calendar and
letting small states vote first. Supporters of the plan promised to
seek a vote in the rules committee of the Republican National
Convention anyway, but because the so-called ``Delaware plan''
already faces substantial opposition from big-state delegates, its
future looked dim. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Economic growth surged 5.2 percent in
the second quarter because of increased investment by businesses
and robust, though slowing, spending by consumers, defying
expectations of a slowdown, the Commerce Department reported
Friday. Stock prices plunged, apparently in anticipation of another
rate increase at the Federal Reserve's Aug. 22 meeting. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   DIABLO-PHENOM (Irvine, Calif.) _ The fourth installment of the
Harry Potter series is not the only fantasy-filled hit this summer.
On July 3, five days before the Potter book went on sale, Blizzard
Entertainment released Diablo II, a Dungeons &AMP; Dragons-like
computer game that sends players to battle evil knights and
monsters and save the world from a demon. So far, the game has sold
more than 1 million copies worldwide, at an average retail price of
more than $50. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
