<SLUG> BC-SCARYMOVIES-WRITERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GHOST STORIES BECOME LOST SOULS IN FILMMAKING PROCESS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies SCARY MOVIES)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A person is contacted by a spirit. The spirit wants something,
but what it wants is unclear. Meanwhile, ``things'' jump out of the
darkness _ sometimes, it's only a dog, but sometimes it's a little
more unnerving. Doors open without being touched. Nightmares
interrupt sleep. Breath becomes visible. Disembodied voices moan
and cry.
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen a ghost story during the past few years, chances
are you've seen all of that _ especially if you watched the
recently released ``What Lies Beneath.'' It sounds easy to conjure,
but screenwriters say that horror films are less formulaic than
they might appear on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like they're a little bit harder to write,'' says Frank
Myer, president of the Dallas Screenwriters Association. ``Because
you're creating another world where you have to establish rules,
and follow them through the end.'' Myer says that one reason ``The
Sixth Sense'' worked so well is that M. Night Shyamalan's
screenplay followed rules that supported the crucial plot twist
(''What Lies Beneath'' isn't so good about this).
</P>
<P>
   Films are a collaborative process, though, and sometimes good
intentions get lost in the collaboration, for instance when the
writer loses control of the screenplay as it goes through the
studio-producer-director wringer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard for me to say how challenging writing horror
is,'' says Philip Eisner, a Fort Worth native credited with the
screenplay for 1997's sci-fi chiller ``Event Horizon.'' ``Very
rarely does a screenplay make it to the screen intact. `The Sixth
Sense' had the advantage of the writer and director being the same
person. So you had a writer/director and you had a very powerful
star (Bruce Willis) willing to stand up for the material.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, a longtime horror buff, says that he wasn't so lucky
with ``Event Horizon,'' in which a crew of astronauts encounter a
malevolent presence in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio was very afraid of the original script,'' he says.
``They thought it was too smart. So they said to take out some of
the science stuff and put in more of the sort of satanic stuff.
They never complained about too much gore, though. So instead of it
being a very intelligent mugging of the audience, like `Seven,' it
was a very dumb mugging. But it was still effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Myer nor Eisner, though, says that horror writers are
simply cutting corners _ nor, for that matter, do they believe that
of writers of any genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really love writing this stuff,'' Eisner says. ``It's just a
natural place where I'm comfortable. I don't think anyone goes out
to write a horror movie because it's a cheap and easy thing. If it
were, more people would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
