<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MONNIER-DANCE-REVIEW-     07-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONNIER-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: AN INTEGRATION, IN BLOOD AND DANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The French modern-dance choreographer Mathilde
Monnier has been a major link to emerging experimental dance in
Africa. ``Pour Antigone,'' which she choreographed in 1991, is the
final dance event in Lincoln Center Festival 2000, and it is a
landmark work in this new cross-pollination.
</P>
<P>
   During much of ``Pour Antigone,'' which had its New York
premiere on Wednesday night at La Guardia High School, two sets of
dancers keep apart. The first group consists of performers from
Africa: three female and two male dancers and a virtuoso drummer.
The white performers in the second group include a male American
dancer and four Europeans (three women and one man).
</P>
<P>
   That those groups are eventually integrated, even in partnering,
is not only predictable; it is also symbolic of a theme that is
highly oblique, as is common to Monnier. On another level,
integration signifies unity, possibly even the catharsis associated
with the Greek myth of Antigone, daughter of Oedipus and Jocasta.
</P>
<P>
   Antigone is nowhere to be seen onstage, but she is sensed in her
multiple aspects. Monnier's springboard was Sophocles' tragedy
``Antigone,'' whose heroine buries her slain brother Polynices in
defiance of her uncle, Creon, ruler of Thebes, who considers him a
traitor. After Creon condemns her to be buried alive in punishment,
she commits suicide.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pour Antigone,'' which will be repeated riday night and
Saturday at La Guardia High School (100 Amsterdam Ave., at 64th
Street), the highly individualized performers keep changing
costumes. Eventually all wind up in shades of red. Can one say that
the integration of the groups into a unified whole relates to a
blood ritual? The same red blood courses through the veins of all
mankind. The healing at the end has the casual style of the piece's
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Like much of Monnier's work, this one is open to interpretation
or even no interpretation. Its weakness is paradoxically its
strength: discrete episodes have impact, but their cumulative
aspect is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some people in the audience called the work wonderful _
which is true of the energy and wit found in specific moments.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Pour Antigone'' Monnier began a collaboration with
dancers she met in Mali and Burkina Faso. Some went to France to
study in workshops with her company, now based in Montpellier, and
joined her troupe or returned home to form troupes of their own.
</P>
<P>
   This is true of her two male dancers from Burkina Faso, Salia
Sanou and Seydou Boro, whose company performed in September at the
International New Dance Festival in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation of that festival was the number of choreographers
in Africa who use their background in traditional dance to
experiment in contemporary ways. Monnier was one of the first to
encourage their postmodern brand of eclecticism, which also runs
through ``Pour Antigone.'' Among others who studied with her is
Gnapa Beatrice Kombe, whose stunning Tchetche Co. in Ivory Coast
was also in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald K. Brown, who has worked with the Sylvain Zabli Co. in
Ivory Coast, and Ralph Lemon are American experimental
choreographers who have collaborated with African dancers. The
German neo-expressionist Susanne Linke will include dancers from
Senegal when her company, Jant-Bi, appears at the Jacob's Pillow
Dance Festival in Becket, Mass., from Aug. 9 to 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pour Antigone'' can thus be seen in a context that Monnier did
much to create. It is to her credit that she has not turned her
African collaborators into clones of her white performers, who move
in the stylized collage structures she inherited from her American
mentor, Viola Farber, once Merce Cunningham's partner.
</P>
<P>
   The work opens with a striking decor by Annie Tolleter,
corrugated walls lighted by Eric Wurtz and with costumes by
Christine Vargas. Two women pursue a long-distance dialogue at
opposite corners of the stage. Their African syllables are
emphatic, often repetitive. Blandine Yameogo, who also sings
occasionally, and Balguissa Zoungrana, sitting under a lamp, are
very much of our time. They lounge on abandoned car seats.
</P>
<P>
   After they begin a stamping dance, varied in gait and postures,
the three European women _ Corinne Garcia, Germana Civera and
Eszter Salamon _ rush out in short tunics and clunky shoes to stamp
out their geometric minimalist reply.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting dynamics are obvious: outlined shapes for the
Europeans, performed with darting speed, while the self-contained
African solos have the looser dynamic of traditional African dance
and are packed with steps.
</P>
<P>
   Weaving throughout the work is Zani Diabate, a drummer of nuance
and humor who triumphs over the electronic rumbles of Christophe
Sechet and who ushers in Boro as a kingly figure. Sanou, something
of a Polynices, haunts the piece like a spirit with a resiliency in
his dancing that is amplified by the rest of the cast as it lies on
the floor and bounces up from it.
</P>
<P>
   Awa Kouyate, a woman who closes the piece in a healing water
ritual, moves with elegance, and Joel Luecht, the American, appears
occasionally wrapped like a mummy in white cloth. Dimitri Chamblas,
tall, quick and able to carve every shape into space with power and
energy, is a galvanizing force.
</P>
<P>
   When Monnier brings in four toy soldiers to be moved around the
floor, and Luecht stands on the head of a soldier figure, her
references to colonial or postcolonial rule take the wind out of
her wonderful chaotic sails. Herman Diephuis is listed as assistant
choreographer for a piece that nonetheless meanders in and out of
magic places.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
