<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5841 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GOLF-FASHION-ART-2TAK     07-28 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP YOUR EYE ON THE ... GOLFWEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and 10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's just say that golf is not my sport. First of all, my
hand-eye coordination is bad enough that I still button my shirt
wrong. Second, the idea of getting up at dawn for anything is out
of the question. And third, do I have to even say it? Those
clothes! Bathroom wallpaper with collars for the women, not to
mention lime green pants for the men, with navy whales _ or ducks _
embroidered on them. And all in the name of a sport, to hear
evotees describe it, that is the ultimate contest of man versus
himself. Well, here's a news flash. With ducks on your pants, you
just lost. Both of you.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I wasn't surprised last week at the Poxabogue Golf
Center in Bridgehampton, N.Y., when a woman on the driving range
took one look at Claudia Romana and said loudly to her pro: ``Who
is she? I like her shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   She and everyone else. Romana, 36, is one of a new breed of
golfwear designers who realize that the women who wear Armani in
the boardroom have no intention of taking to the course dressed
like Emmett Kelly. There is also a new generation of Tiger Woods
disciples, young urbanites (read from minorities) and increasing
numbers of women, who are coming to the game with no frame of
reference for country club frump. And where there's a market, there
are companies like Gucci, Prada and Tommy Hilfiger all jumping on
it. In that regard, Romana's timing is impeccable: this is her
second season in a business where demand for her simple, elegant
clothes designed mostly in neutral tones instead of pastels has
steadily grown. The line, sold under the label Golf by Claudia
Romana (www.golfbycr.com), is also affordable: capri pants,
trousers, skorts, tops and dresses sell in the $55-to-$85 range.
</P>
<P>
   Rona Cherry, editor in chief of Golf Digest Woman, said the
changes in wardrobe were long overdue: ``Golf clothes have been
totally out of sync with fashion. We've noticed a big change this
year with more form-fitting clothes, cutout backs. At the U.S.
Women's Open, Pearl Sinn, a young Korean player, was wearing a
white sheer top and you could see the bra. Today, you don't have to
be stuck with Bermuda shorts anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Romana takes it even further. ``Golf clothes should look like
streetwear but still be active,'' she said. ``So many of these
companies think golfers have naturally bad taste, selling all that
canary yellow and powder puff blue. I was playing with an
attractive woman recently who looked like a mad bird-watcher. I
said, `Honey, let me help you.' You have to have all your senses
together to play golf.'' Which Romana does diligently, at this
course among others, public and private, in the New York
metropolitan area. I joined her here to `play Pox' as people say of
this hip public course, which despite _ or maybe because of _ its
inherent democracy, attracts celebrities like Cindy Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular day, Romana was by far the best-dressed woman
around, in her stone-colored capri pants and black top with white
piping and tee holders, which are her trademark. She was also
wearing men's black Nike shoes. ``I like them better than the
women's,'' she said. ``I think the white ones look dorky and they
make your feet look huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Her designs include a detachable pouch for balls, so that
form-fitting outfits stay that way. Despite my better judgment, I
put on a skort (a combination of shorts and skirt _ think culottes)
and a top. I looked like a quasi-hip suburban mom. The good news
was that the skort's accommodating stretch made it almost as comfy
as a pair of pj's.
</P>
<P>
   But as Romana stepped up to the first hole to practice her
swing, I had that sinking sensation from gym classes past and knew
I'd never make it, no matter what I was wearing. A couple appeared
behind us. The woman was dressed in Gap khakis and a white T-shirt
and looked as miserable as I did. I brightened. ``I'll try to be
fast,'' I said, and she shook her head. ``Don't worry, I'm not
good,'' she said. I smiled. ``It's hard to be worse than me.'' She
grimaced. ``I'll give it a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Romana, looking like an advertisement, hit her ball
into the wild blue yonder. The most I can say for myself was that I
was brilliant _ had we been playing miniature golf.
</P>
<P>
   After butchering the first hole, I decided that to truly test
the give in the skort, I needed to sit down immediately, preferably
with an iced tea. The woman behind us looked longingly as we turned
tail and headed for the restaurant, a superior vantage point, I
decided, to scope out the general state of golf course fashion. It
was truly ghastly. The women looked like boxy boys, in long baggy
shorts and long short-sleeved T-shirts. Romana agreed. ``I can wear
my golf trousers on the plane, just take the pouch off, and they're
fine,'' she said. ``If you're afraid to stop and get gas on the way
to the course, you're wearing a funny outfit. If it screams golf,
it's not comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caruso, editor in chief of Maximum Golf, a new monthly
magazine, agreed, when I reached him by phone. ``As golf has gotten
younger, with the advent of Tiger Woods,'' he said, ``it has also
gotten sexier. For the first time, 57 percent of players are under
40. Younger men don't have the gender barriers that older guys
have, the ones who are usually playing to escape their wives.
There's a lot more flirting out on the course. People are finding
golf sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Maximum Golf will sponsor a singles event, Golf
in the City, at Chelsea Piers on Sept. 21. ``It'll be like an
episode of `Sex in the City' with golf clubs,'' Caruso predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, golf has not become as oversexed as say, tennis, whose
professional players, like Anna Kournikova, have recently been
criticized for wearing skimpy outfits. ``Golf is not about showing
panties,'' Cherry said. ``For four hours you've got to feel
comfortable and look good, a woman first and foremost.''
</P>
<P>
   Why has golf's fashion revolution taken so long? ``Women had
other battles to fight,'' she explained. ``We had to get on the
course first, and once we were there, we wanted to fit in. Look at
the working world in the 70's, with women wearing the suits and
bow-tie blouses. But now, the clothes are sophisticated, sporty and
functional.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as Romana points out, the country club culture still
holds sway in the golf world. ``A lot of clubs are restrictive
about dress codes,'' she said. ``General dress code is collar or
sleeves for women and men both, and in some clubs men have to wear
pants, no shorts. Regulation length has to hit no more than two
inches above the knee. I had much shorter things, which people
liked, but they can't wear them in their clubs. And a lot of them
require that the clothes carry their logos.'' She shrugged. ``Does
everyone really want to look like a souvenir?''
</P>
<P>
   Though Romana has a solid handle on her market, she has only
lived here for 12 years. Originally from Germany, where her parents
own a resort hotel, she was introduced to golf by a former
boyfriend during a trip to Portugal. ``I couldn't afford to play in
Germany because you had to be a member,'' she said. ``I found an
antique set of wooden clubs at a flea market and practiced in my
backyard at 5 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Romana (she uses her mother's maiden name) has had a variety of
fashion jobs in New York, including designing men's wear for J.
Crew. One of her happiest discoveries here has been public courses,
not only for the joy of playing, but to build her client base. She
has never advertised, relying instead on word of mouth, and women
seeing how good she looks. Beside her Internet business, she has
started doing trunk shows at country clubs, and a dozen club pro
shops now carry her line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my customers are professional women who have to go on
company outings,'' Romana said. ``One customer said, `I can't play,
but they all loved me because I looked good.''' She smiled. ``I
always say, `I can't promise to improve your game but I can promise
you'll look better no matter how you play.'''
</P>
<P>
   Well, even if all you're doing is drinking iced tea, that is the
American way, isn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
