<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DALLAS READY FOR ITS FIRST TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRENT ZWERNEMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ Like 30 other NFL squads in training camp _ when
even teams like the Bengals prepare for the postseason _ Dallas
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones believes his team can win it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at those veterans coming in, and you look at the
speed and skill of the younger players who have never won one of
those Super Bowl rings, and they've got all of that fire and
ambition to do it,'' Jones said Thursday. ``Boy, I like that
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   How good are the Cowboys, circa 2000? They'll begin finding out
7 p.m. Sunday when they play host to the Pittsburgh Steelers at
Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And like any camp, there's been a few surprises and
disappointments through the first two weeks. Here are some of both
in a position-by-position analysis of the Cowboys headed into the
first preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback: Troy Aikman hasn't played in a Pro Bowl since 1996,
and will turn 34 this season. That said, Aikman seems genuinely
enthused about the new weapons in his offense and a return to a
timing-based offense he helped make so successful in the mid 1990s.
Backup Randall Cunningham is 37 but hasn't lost any zip on his
pass, although his scrambling abilities have slowed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Running back: Emmitt Smith isn't showing any signs of slowing,
and with a healthy couple of years could break Walter Payton's
career rushing record. (He has 13,963 yards to Payton's 16,726.)
His backup, Chris Warren, has shown signs of moodiness after
starting so many years in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback: Robert Thomas has settled into this position after
fighting for a roster spot as a backup linebacker less than a year
ago. Aikman said Thomas has shown some of the same instincts as his
predecessor, Daryl ``Moose'' Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver: Joey Galloway hasn't had a huge season yet in the NFL,
but Cowboys fans are thinking this might be the one. Galloway, long
known for his physical tools, earned a reputation in Seattle as
aloof and selfish. He's shown no signs of either through two weeks
of training camp. Now if Aikman's passes can keep up ... Raghib
``Rocket'' Ismail is coming off his best season as a pro (80
catches for 1,097 yards) and opposing defenses ought to be outright
alarmed at the idea of he and Galloway streaking down the field at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end: Free-agent addition Jackie Harris, who's a slim 247
pounds, gives Aikman a weapon at tight end he hasn't had since Jay
Novacek retired in 1996, that of an agile, big receiver who can
outrun linebackers. Starter David LaFleur is in his fourth season,
and at 6-foot-7 might be best as a big goal-line target.
</P>
<P>
   Center: Aikman said he'd retire if Mark Stepnoski retires. No
one knew if he was kidding. Stepnoski, 33, gives the offensive
line, still missing Erik Williams, veteran stability and
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle: In Williams' absence, the Cowboys moved projected
right guard Solomon Page to right tackle, which is more of his
natural position, and where he would have played when Williams
retired.
</P>
<P>
   Right guard: This is the biggest concern on the offensive line,
since Page was moved. The Cowboys are banking on the experience of
Jorge Diaz, who hasn't been particularly impressive so far.
</P>
<P>
   Left guard: Pro Bowler Larry Allen is out a couple of weeks with
a broken right hand, possibly a blessing in disguise since
seldom-used backup Kelvin Garmon is getting better daily at the
position.
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle: Flozell Adams, 25, is in only his third season but
at 335 pounds is a force. Last year he switched from guard to
tackle, and continues to improve at protecting Aikman's blindside.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Left end: Ebenezer Ekuban has added 90 pounds to his bench press
and should improve upon his 33 tackles of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle: Chad Hennings is a consistent force, having
started the past 39 games for the Cowboys. Hennings' aggressiveness
is underrated.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle: Alonzo Spellman continues to amaze his
teammates and coaches with his consistent and tough play following
off-the-field troubles a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Right end: This spot is reserved for Greg Ellis, who was
becoming one of the premier ends in the league when he broke his
leg with three games left last season.
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker: Some consider the jury out on Dat Nguyen, who
earned the starting slot when Randall Godfrey signed with
Tennessee. He's considered small at 5-foot-11 and 231 pounds. The
Cowboys signed 245-pound veteran Barron Wortham to contend with
Nguyen.
</P>
<P>
   Weakside linebacker: Does anyone remember that Dexter Coakley
earned All-Pro honors last year? He was just the second Cowboys
linebacker in 17 years to make the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Strongside linebacker: Incumbent Darren Hambrick is getting a
serious run from veteran Joe Bowden, who signed with the Cowboys
from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Right cornerback: The Cowboys weren't sure what they were
getting by signing Ryan McNeil.
</P>
<P>
   So far he may be the camp's most pleasant surprise, and he leads
all defensive backs in practice interceptions by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   Left cornerback: Kevin Smith, 30, simply isn't what he used to
be, though the coaching staff has shown lots of confidence in the
veteran the first couple of weeks. Rookies Mario Edwards and/or
Kareem Larrimore may get a starting shot if receivers keep getting
past Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety: Like Coakley, Darren Woodson is good enough that
you forget he's back there. And don't suggest he's gonna have to
step up his leadership role with Deion Sanders gone to Washington.
Woodson says he's been a leader all along.
</P>
<P>
   Free safety: George Teague, finally given the opportunity to
start at the beginning of the season, responded with 102 tackles
last season. Secondary coach Bill Bates is relying heavily on
Teague and Darren Woodson to lead the young guys in the coming
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
