<HEADER>
A5852 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-WEBSTER-$ADV3     07-28 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-WEBSTER-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWELER'S DAILY REGIMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By JAMES COLLARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``What are you doing here?'' Stephen Webster demanded
in gravelly tones as he arrived at the opening party on a recent
Tuesday for One Fine Thing, a new boutique in St. John Street, in
Clerkenwell. He was greeting an old friend _ not the store owner,
but the doorman, Danny Moore, an elderly gent of military bearing,
apparently moonlighting from his day job at Goldsmith's Hall, home
of the Worshipful Co. of Goldsmiths.
</P>
<P>
   Webster is one of London's most innovative jewelers, a favorite
of clients like Madonna and Kate Winslet, but as a member of the
Goldsmiths, an ancient London guild, he is honored by his more
traditional peers. In a city where parking spaces are more valued
than any celebrity clientele, Moore is the man who lets Webster
park his motorbike in one of the Goldsmiths' four coveted parking
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Webster, 40, goes to openings and parties several nights a week
after working long days in his workshop, making bold, big,
one-of-a-kind designs that have made him a darling of accessories
editors at fashion magazines on both sides of the Atlantic. ``It's
part of the job, really,'' he explained of his day-into-evening
schedule. ``It's like a game, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   His first port of call had been the opening of a Georgian art
show at a gallery in Cork Street, Mayfair. There, he and his
Russian-born wife, Anastasia, found themselves greeting one old
acquaintance, Count Andrei Tolstoy (an offshoot of the writer's
family) and making a new one, Jacob Dzhugashvili, an artist and
great-grandson of Joseph Stalin. Nash Tavkhelidze, godson of the
former Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, was also on hand _
he's the lead singer of Blast, the first Russian band to be signed
to a British label.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a bizarre party,'' Webster said, laughing, to a friend,
Neil Cunningham, a couturier. In the sultry weather, the party had
moved onto the sidewalk, where the Websters mingled with scions of
White and Red Russia, Georgia and the fashionable London art crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Count Tolstoy's a wonderful guy,'' Webster said, as his wife
fluttered from guest to guest in a feather-fringed dress like some
exotic, especially sociable little bird, one moment speaking
Russian, the next Italian or English. The count organizes London's
War and Peace Ball (``I'd go, only they do all that old-school
dancing and you've got to have lessons,'' Webster said), which
helped finance the building of the rather grand Russian Orthodox
church, blue onion domes and all, that is currently astounding
visitors on the road from Heathrow. ``He got hold of two kilos of
caviar _ at an amazingly good price _ for our wedding, and a band
of balalaika players,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   After a flurry of good-bye kisses, the Websters and Cunningham
squeezed into a car to head across town to the boutique. Soon it
was time to head farther east to a cousin's party in a loft
apartment in newly fashionable Shoreditch.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Webster explained something of his life story:
apprenticeship in London, long stays in Canada and Santa Barbara,
Calif., before returning to London and opening his store in Duke
Street in 1996. His reputation is spreading well beyond this
prestigious Mayfair address; Webster's workshop is working flat out
to fill orders from Bergdorf Goodman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the party, after a quick climb to the roof to survey this
lively corner of the old East End, Webster suggested they go
dancing. His wife's answer was a gentle but convincing no. It was
getting late, and there was work to do in the morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
