A5856 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-HORSE30     07-28 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-HORSE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A whinnying ride through rural Quebec
 &HT;    By Sandra Eckstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEBEC PROVINCE, Canada _ After horseback riding through deep
green forests all morning, our group of 10 breaks into a field lush
with barley ready for harvest. We weave along the edge of the
grain, then cross a piece of downed fencing into a clover-covered
field.
</P>
<P>
   It's a beautiful fall afternoon, and we are enjoying it as part
of a five-day, inn-to-inn ride through the rural Gaspe Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Then the horses suddenly tense, as if anticipating a change. The
group's leader, Yves Pruneau, gives a signal _ raising his index
finger heavenward and thrusting it forward _ and the horses begin
racing up a nearby clovered hill.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny Canadian-bred black horse is one of the fastest. And
Nicole Bell, a 23-year-old former riding instructor from Boston, is
happy to let her go.
</P>
<P>
   Lady tears up the hill, eclipsing every other horse. Nicole
throws out her arms and whoops. As we crest the hill, Nicole
embraces Lady's neck and kisses her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can die happy,'' she laughs. ``That's always been a
fantasy of mine, to run through a gorgeous field of flowers with no
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a trip meant to fulfill such fantasies. It's 100 miles
of intense riding through all types of terrain and constantly
changing tempos. No lolling in the saddle, where you're another
piece of baggage being hauled by a bored horse.
</P>
<P>
   The guides are Pruneau and his wife, Heather. Yves is a former
plumbing contractor who followed his heart back to horses, having
grown up with them on his family's Quebec farm. Heather is a former
banker who gave up city life in Toronto after meeting Yves on a
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Yves worries about the horses, Heather the guests. They're a
good team.
</P>
<P>
   Every night, the ride ends at an inn, bed-and-breakfast or small
hotel. The accommodations and food range from basic to luxurious,
with the added benefit of getting to know French Canadians in their
own homes.
</P>
<P>
   But the main attraction is the horses. Riders spend five to
seven hours a day in the saddle astride well-trained,
well-cared-for mounts. It's easy to stay focused because Yves
constantly changes the rhythm, alternating from walks to trots to
canters.
</P>
<P>
   The scenery changes quickly as well, weaving during one segment
through the wild Chic Choc Hills. For an hour the group tromps
happily through a balsam forest, then emerges onto a country road
before heading off into fields of hay, wheat, clover or barley.
Sometimes there are steep ravines or high hills.
</P>
<P>
   Loggers and farmers wave often, pausing to chat briefly with
Yves. And always, sometimes in the distance, sometimes just over a
hill, and sometimes right beside you, the St. Lawrence Seaway
glistens in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's demanding,'' said Rosemarie Dentino, a 60-year-old
grandmother from Peoria, Ill. ``But that's OK with me. I came to
ride. I don't want to do a lot of sitting around.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Eckstein writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
