<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5858 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-FASHION-TOERING30-COX     07-28 2462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-TOERING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stay in step with rings, bracelets that add decorative touch to
ankles and toes
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 30.
 &HT;    By Amy Winn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   His friends say Marietta's (Ga.) Michael Cramer will do just
about anything to get a laugh (or meet girls). So they weren't
really surprised when, one day, the 25-year-old grad student at
Georgia Tech showed up at school with brightly painted toenails.
</P>
<P>
   His explanation: ``Last summer, a friend of mine was making fun
of a guy who had his toenails painted, so the next day, I showed up
at school with mine painted, too. It was just to spite my friend,
but I thought it looked cool, so I kept doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer finds his paint jobs are a ``great conversation starter.
If a woman sees my feet and says it's cool, then that's a whole
conversation right there: colors, techniques, why I do it. Not many
guys do it; it's different. Chicks dig it.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern summers demand sandals, and among Atlantans it has
become trendy to take a step beyond pedicures, wearing eye-catching
toe and ankle accessories as well.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cramer, Fayetteville's (Ga.) Darlene Carlton, 31, enjoys
showcasing her feet. She gets pedicures regularly, and in recent
months started wearing a gold toe ring. She prefers fitted rings
from Lenox Square's Totally Toes kiosk rather than ``clip-on''
adjustable ones.
</P>
<P>
   The labor and employee relations specialist for HUD says, ``(It)
wouldn't be cute on everybody, but it makes me feel sexy, like
everyone is looking at my feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Toe rings, bands and ankle bracelets are sold all over town, and
their prices and styles vary widely. At the three Totally Toes
locations, sterling silver rings sell for as little as $8, gold
bands as little as $20 and gem-studded styles can cost several
hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Worthmore Jewelers in Atlanta sells sterling silver adjustable
rings but has recently added a line of 14K gold-and-gemstone rings
called Toesies in the $180-$300 range. In addition to toe rings,
Catwalk, a shoe boutique, sells ``foot bracelets,'' which cover the
top of the foot and go around the ankle. They're made of various
materials, including beads, shells and leather in addition to
metals. Shelby's Foot Jewels, based in Laguna Beach, Calif.,
specializes in similar foot bracelets, cleverly named ``Shoewels.''
They also offer fitted toe rings in sterling silver and gold fill;
beaded and sterling silver ankle bracelets, thumb rings, and waist
chains. The company's Web site, www.shelbysfootjewels.com, lists
designs and colors, photos and sizing information.
</P>
<P>
   Decaturite (Ga.) Kacey Cloues, a tax incentives specialist for
the Historic Preservation Division of the Georgia Department of
Natural Resources, describes herself as usually low-maintenance,
but she has become a foot adornment acolyte. Cloues, 23, reasoned,
``Why not wear a ring on your toe if you can wear them on your
finger?''
</P>
<P>
   Cloues said she likes her ring because it stands out, but not
too much. ``It's subtle _ not as bold a statement as a tattoo or
piercing. It's appropriate for the office, yet different and
unique.'' And unlike tattoos or piercings, ``It wasn't painful!''
Cloues said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Winn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Surday in
September. Here's how our adventure went:
</P>
<P>
   The riders assemble
</P>
<P>
   On a cool evening a group of riders gathers at the Une Ferme en
Gaspesie (A Farm in Gaspesie), an inn just outside the tiny town of
Mont-Joli.
</P>
<P>
   We had driven up the western coast of the peninsula from Quebec
City, a gorgeous five-hour trip, arriving in time for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The eight riders assembled for the trip range from a 23-year-old
who has been riding half her life to a 60-year-old grandmother who
took up riding just four years ago. We are business owners, an
engineer, a teacher, a volunteer, a social worker and journalists.
Other than all being from the United States, we seem to have little
in common except for one, unifying thing _ a passion for horses.
</P>
<P>
   Our innkeeper, Pierre Dufort, is a jolly, fervent French
Canadian who is proud of his austere, spotless inn and the fine
food he serves. For dinner we have a choice of six entrees: lamb,
pheasant, rabbit, pork, beef or shrimp. Only the shrimp isn't from
Pierre's farm. It came from Matane, a fishing village 12 miles
away. The vegetables were picked fresh from the garden outside the
kitchen door.
</P>
<P>
   The desserts are rich. Among them is a local favorite, a large
slab of freshly baked white bread, covered in fruit, then liberally
sprinkled with grated maple sugar and drowned in cream.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before dinner is served, we meet our guides, the
Pruneaus, who will lead us for the next five days. The couple owns
Ranch Des Collines Chic Chocs in St.-Damase, Quebec. Yves has been
running horse trips in the area for seven years. His wife, Heather,
joined him four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The first night, the Pruneaus size us up, matching our abilities
with specific mounts. The horses are as diverse as our group,
ranging from a dainty Arabian mare almost small enough to qualify
as a pony to a large draft horse Yves sometimes uses to log in the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Yves and Heather also welcome back Lenny and Chris Rankin, who
have returned for their second trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just love the people, the horses, the area, the culture,''
said Chris, who has two horses of her own back home in Burlington,
N.J. ``It's just a great experience from start to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Day one: At a gallop
</P>
<P>
   Saddling up for the first day, we're on the trail by 9:30 after
a breakfast of crepes, waffles, bacon and sausage. We are scheduled
to roam through the Tartigou River Valley and along the Evergreen
Trail, a tunnel of conifers so dense it nearly blocks out the sun.
At one point, Yves orders the horses into a canter and they fly
along almost silently on the soft floor of pine needles.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, when the trail turns, I lose sight of my co-riders
and it seems I'm galloping alone, brushing past the trees, my hat
blown back, my hair flying from the strong strides of Ti Loup, my
Canadian-bred horse.
</P>
<P>
   Too soon, we round a curve and I see the now-familiar sign
coming down the line of riders: a fist, raised in the air and
pumping up and down. Ti Loup (French for ``Little Wolf''_ an irony
because he is a huge draft horse) sees the signal about the same
time I do and eases back into a bone-jarring trot.
</P>
<P>
   Yves keeps the tempo changing, rarely staying at a walk for more
than 15 minutes. Riders are expected to post during trots, a
movement that requires you to lift your weight off the saddle with
your legs with each stride of the horse. It can be tiring when you
aren't accustomed to doing it for long periods, so I am happy when
we turn into a farm for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   As we ride in, we pass large pastures full of skittish red deer,
who shy from our horses. We ride up to the back door of the
farmhouse, shuck off our boots and enter the homey kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Although the woman inside speaks only French, we show our
appreciation for her simple but hearty meal (freshly made bread,
sausage and vegetables in a scrambled-egg base and a super-sweet
cobbler) with smiles and a few quickly learned French terms.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, we ride through a massive maple forest.
Instead of buckets and taps, the modern maple forest has hoses
connecting the trees. Yves explains that the sap runs to a central
building where it is processed into syrup.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun begins to set, we ride along the edges of fields with
freshly bailed hay waiting to be stored for the approaching harsh
winter. In the distance we see the sparkling St. Lawrence Seaway, a
constant companion on this trip. We arrive at our evening
destination, Lac (Lake) Malcolm, the only hotel we visit during the
trip and the only accommodations with private bathrooms. Some of
the riders swim or boat in the lake, others nap before dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Day two: Blueberries, hills
</P>
<P>
   After treating the hotel owner's children to a quick ride, we
head out along back-country roads where local drivers are
considerate of the horses, slowing or even stopping to allow riders
to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing into a balsam forest, we take trails and dirt roads to
the home of a blueberry farmer, where the owner has lunch waiting.
Dessert is a yummy blueberry cake.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon takes us into the Chic Choc Hills, including some
rather steep climbs. But Yves decides against climbing the highest
of the hills, which is 1,350 feet above sea level, so we miss out
on the promised panoramic view that would allow us to see all the
way to the Atlantic Ocean. The weather is just too hot for the
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, temperature is relative. For Canadians, where winters
are severe and below-zero temperatures common, 75 degrees is warm.
That's where the thermometer hovers this week, very high for early
September, and our guides apologize. But we find it perfect riding
weather, especially compared with the August heat wave we left
behind in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon winds down, Yves and Heather take us to a
hidden pool, complete with waterfall. Only Yves and two of the
riders are brave enough to dive in, but the rest of us enjoy
dipping our feet in the chilly water.
</P>
<P>
   During one of the climbs we're afforded a brilliant view of the
St. Lawrence, where boats and ships slip up from the Quebec area,
heading for the open sea.
</P>
<P>
   Our stop for the evening is Le Jardin de Givre (The Garden of
Frost), owned by Ginette and Gerald Couture. Yves helped build the
inn, which is beautifully decorated with polished wood furniture,
local artwork and dozens of pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Ginette prepares lush breakfasts that include French toast, four
homemade jams and soft-boiled eggs. Dinners are three-course
gourmet affairs that include cream of tomato soup, stuffed squash,
lentil pilaf and braised beef. Vegetables are picked an hour or two
before each meal, and each plate is decorated with edible flowers
from the garden. After dinner, Ginette entertains guests with her
lovely singing and piano playing.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we step outside and discover the Milky Way looking like a
streak of cotton streaming across the sky with tiny Christmas
lights twinkling within.
</P>
<P>
   Day three: Logging miles
</P>
<P>
   We will be staying at Le Jardin de Givre again tonight, so Yves
pulls out detailed maps to show us today's route.
</P>
<P>
   We return to the Chic Choc Hills, often taking logging roads. On
many of the dirt roads, felled trees are stacked, sometimes more
than 10 feet high, waiting to be dragged away.
</P>
<P>
   We pass a logger hauling downed trees to the roadside, and Yves
stops to chat. He has permission to cross many owners' land because
his tours bring much-needed money into the area.
</P>
<P>
   Yves identifies plants and trees for the riders. But with 10
horses clumping along, we see little wildlife, except for a covey
of grouse we scare up this morning on another dirt logging road.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch is at a trout farm, where several riders volunteer to
catch tonight's dinner. In the ponds _ just small holes where we
can see hundreds of fish swimming n out the perfectly cooked whole
fish, and Yves gives us a quick lesson in how to easily debone a
trout.
</P>
<P>
   Day four: Country roads
</P>
<P>
   Today's ride covers all types of terrain, from forests to farms
to country roads. We cross the South White River, allowing the
horses to drink from the cool, fast-running water.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch is pulled from our saddlebags and enjoyed by a lovely
lake. The rides are a bit longer each day, and even Heather admits
to being sore by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only day we don't ride to our inn. We leave the
horses at a barn outside of Padoug and are driven into town, where
we stay at La Villa de Vieux Clocher, an old church rectory that
has been restored into a stunning bed-and-breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner is a traditional fondue, and Yves jokes that anyone who
drops anything into the hot oil must help clean the horses in the
morning. Actually, riders can do as much or as little as they want
on the ride. If you want to feed, brush and saddle your horse
daily, you may, or you can let the Pruneaus do it all.
</P>
<P>
   Day five: Tired, satisfied
</P>
<P>
   We ride through rolling meadows and scrubby pine forests on our
way to an organic farm in Baie Des Sables (Sandy Bay), where owner
Lise Beaulieu has lunch waiting. After serving us quiche, salad,
homemade bread and pie, Lise takes us on a tour of her farm.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon the ride goes into the small town of Les Boules
before turning to the St. Lawrence shoreline, where we walk the
horses for four miles while searching the water for seals, eider
ducks and cormorants bouncing with the ocean waves.
</P>
<P>
   The walk along the shore culminates in the 1 1/4-mile ``Bonzi
Canter.'' Yves says the ride is named for a pine that once stood at
the end of the run that looked like a bonsai tree.
</P>
<P>
   When Yves gives the signal, the pack begins running. Hats blow
back, hair flies up and the horses seem to enjoy the run as much as
the riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was incredible,'' said Kathy Mohs, a 55-year-old teacher
from Irvine, Calif. ``You never get to just run like that. What a
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Then we ride several more hours, winding our way back to Une
Ferme en Gaspesie and our original innkeeper, Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   We are a tired group, but we are also happy. We have made new
friends and have become better equestrians.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, Pierre pours a special local drink and offers a
toast to the ride, our guides and our success.
</P>
<P>
   We raise our glasses to toast Yves and Heather and knock back a
shooter of rum and maple syrup, shouting, ``Tzigidou.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose translation?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ride information: Tours continue through Oct. 14. Price is
$1,095 per person, with a $150 supplement for singles. Riders must
weigh 210 pounds or less and be between the ages of 12 and 80.
Tours may be booked through two agencies: Equitour, 1-800-545-0019,
www.ridingtours.com; or Hidden Trails, 1-888-987-2457,
www.hiddentrails.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Delta offers two daily nonstops to Montreal,
$393 with a 21-day advance purchase. Or Air Canada/Canadian,
Northwest and United offer direct service to Quebec City, $427 with
a 21-day advance. Bus and rail service are offered from both cities
to Mont-Joli. Or Air Canada/Canadian fly to Mont-Joli via Toronto,
$750 with a 21-day advance. A final option: rent a car and drive up
the coast _ a beautiful trip _ about seven hours from Montreal, or
five from Quebec City.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Eckstein writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
