<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stay in step with rings, bracelets that add decorative touch to
ankles and toes
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 30.
 &HT;    By Amy Winn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   His friends say Marietta's (Ga.) Michael Cramer will do just
about anything to get a laugh (or meet girls). So they weren't
really surprised when, one day, the 25-year-old grad student at
Georgia Tech showed up at school with brightly painted toenails.
</P>
<P>
   His explanation: ``Last summer, a friend of mine was making fun
of a guy who had his toenails painted, so the next day, I showed up
at school with mine painted, too. It was just to spite my friend,
but I thought it looked cool, so I kept doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer finds his paint jobs are a ``great conversation starter.
If a woman sees my feet and says it's cool, then that's a whole
conversation right there: colors, techniques, why I do it. Not many
guys do it; it's different. Chicks dig it.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern summers demand sandals, and among Atlantans it has
become trendy to take a step beyond pedicures, wearing eye-catching
toe and ankle accessories as well.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cramer, Fayetteville's (Ga.) Darlene Carlton, 31, enjoys
showcasing her feet. She gets pedicures regularly, and in recent
months started wearing a gold toe ring. She prefers fitted rings
from Lenox Square's Totally Toes kiosk rather than ``clip-on''
adjustable ones.
</P>
<P>
   The labor and employee relations specialist for HUD says, ``(It)
wouldn't be cute on everybody, but it makes me feel sexy, like
everyone is looking at my feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Toe rings, bands and ankle bracelets are sold all over town, and
their prices and styles vary widely. At the three Totally Toes
locations, sterling silver rings sell for as little as $8, gold
bands as little as $20 and gem-studded styles can cost several
hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Worthmore Jewelers in Atlanta sells sterling silver adjustable
rings but has recently added a line of 14K gold-and-gemstone rings
called Toesies in the $180-$300 range. In addition to toe rings,
Catwalk, a shoe boutique, sells ``foot bracelets,'' which cover the
top of the foot and go around the ankle. They're made of various
materials, including beads, shells and leather in addition to
metals. Shelby's Foot Jewels, based in Laguna Beach, Calif.,
specializes in similar foot bracelets, cleverly named ``Shoewels.''
They also offer fitted toe rings in sterling silver and gold fill;
beaded and sterling silver ankle bracelets, thumb rings, and waist
chains. The company's Web site, www.shelbysfootjewels.com, lists
designs and colors, photos and sizing information.
</P>
<P>
   Decaturite (Ga.) Kacey Cloues, a tax incentives specialist for
the Historic Preservation Division of the Georgia Department of
Natural Resources, describes herself as usually low-maintenance,
but she has become a foot adornment acolyte. Cloues, 23, reasoned,
``Why not wear a ring on your toe if you can wear them on your
finger?''
</P>
<P>
   Cloues said she likes her ring because it stands out, but not
too much. ``It's subtle _ not as bold a statement as a tattoo or
piercing. It's appropriate for the office, yet different and
unique.'' And unlike tattoos or piercings, ``It wasn't painful!''
Cloues said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Winn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
