<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5865 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PUTIN-OLIGARCHS-0729-     07-28 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-OLIGARCHS-0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S PUTIN DECLARES ERA OF 'OLIGARCHS' OVER
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With list of oligarchs attached at end of story.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian President Vladimir Putin agreed to a truce
Friday with the country's top tycoons, promising to spare them
government investigation into their alleged wrongdoing, but warning
that the era of their excessive political and financial influence
had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed-door Kremlin meeting with 21 so-called
``oligarchs,'' Putin promised not to overturn the privatization
deals from the mid-1990s that made them fabulously wealthy at the
expense of the country as a whole. At the same time, he told them
that they were responsible to help lift Russia's economic doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   However, analysts said the meeting was aimed at overhauling the
oligarch's pecking order _ not reforming the system that has
crippled Russia's investment climate and caused rampant poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the oligarch meeting) was a play produced for public
consumption, not necessarily a reflection of reality. Many
questions remain (like whether) the show was just a cover for
installing new, more Putin-friendly, oligarchs, and whether the
business climate will actually improve because of this,'' said
Peter Ekman, a Moscow-based financial commentator.
</P>
<P>
   During Russia's 1996 presidential elections, the oligarchs
emerged as political and financial heavyweights when they agreed to
throw their wealth and media resources behind then-President Boris
Yeltsin in his battle against a strong Communist challenger.
</P>
<P>
   After Yeltsin's re-election, these tycoons grew even richer from
their access to the Kremlin, which allowed them to participate in
and win lucrative privatization deals and circumvent national laws
and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian public hates these businessmen for the way they
acquired their wealth while the country was collapsing,'' said
Yevgeny Volk, the head of the Heritage Foundation in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Putin had invited a select group of these business leaders to
the Kremlin Friday after a spate of unprecedented attacks by his
government on many of the oligarchs' businesses. For example,
federal officials arrested _ and temporarily jailed _ media mogul
Vladimir Gusinsky, after raiding the offices of several of his
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who was elected in March, pledged to make all equal
before the government and the law, and the ensuing police actions
have been interpreted by some as the government's effort to show
the tycoons their place.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of the Friday meeting, the businessmen expected a
kiss-and-make-up session. Putin appeared to concede on their main
concern, that the government would revise privatization results and
leave them penniless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president said again that the government would not review
the results of privatization. At the same time he made clear that
from now on, government structures would not aid businesses in
their work or battles,'' government spokeswoman Natalya Timakova
said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, as customary, did not make a public statement, preferring
to work through his press service.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Putin's sharp words, businessmen left the Kremlin in
smiles. Mikhail Khordokovsky, who owns Russia's third-largest oil
company, told reporters that many issues had been cleared up during
the two-hour, 40-minute meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have hints on how we have to deal with the government
in the future. We were told what the rules of the game are (under
Putin,)'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Potanin, who controls Russia's largest
telecommunications company and has been accused of tax evasion,
told reporters that the era of oligarchs ``was over.''
</P>
<P>
   However, other evidence exists that indeed it is not.
</P>
<P>
   While the Kremlin has opened tax evasion cases against many
leading businessmen in recent weeks, many notable tycoons have
escaped official scrutiny. In fact, men like Roman Abramovich and
Oleg Derikpasa have seen their empires grow under the Putin regime
under questionable circumstances similar to the Yeltsin-era
privatization deals.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Putin's words would soon be put to the test,
when the results of the latest government sale of a state-owned oil
company is announced Sept. 18. Rumors are already flying that
Abramovich has fixed the privatization deal, and will win the
tender without competition.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA'S INFLUENTIAL ``OLIGARCHS'
</P>
<P>
   Boris Berezovsky
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The man credited with building the oligarchs as a political
force, through his organization of former President Boris Yeltsin's
1996 re-election campaign. He has a controlling share of Russia's
only national TV station, owns major national newspapers and is the
largest shareholder of Aeroflot airlines and a Russia's leading car
factory, Avtovaz.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Gusinsky
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His empire, called Media MOST, is concentrated in the media
business. He founded Russia's only independent TV station and a
leading national newspaper and magazine. His MOST bank went
belly-up during the 1998 economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Potanin
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He is the owner of Norilsk Nickel, the world's largest
producer of platinum and palladium, and a major shareholder in
Russia's largest telecoms company, Svazinvest. He pioneered the
``loans-for-shares'' privatization scheme, under which oligarchs
received state property for rock-bottom
</P>
<P>
   prices. His bank, Uneximbank, went bankrupt in the financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Chubais
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A former prime minister of the Yeltsin administration. He is
the man who created the country's privatization program, which is
criticized for selling off for cheap the property to Kremlin
insiders. He now runs Unified Energy Systems, Russia's national
electric company.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Khordokovsky
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  He owns the oil company Yukos, one of Russia's largest.
Foreign shareholders in the company complain and have sued him for
stripping assets from the company, leaving it almost worthless. His
bank went belly-up during the 1998 economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
