<P>
   &UR; BUSH GETS HIS CHANCE TO SHOW HE'S `READY' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSH-ASSESS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican National Convention beckoning next week in
Philadelphia, George W. Bush has his first real chance to convince
American voters that he is ``ready'' to lead the country. For the
past four months, the supposedly lightweight Bush has dominated the
presidential campaign. He is currently slightly ahead in the polls,
and unless something terrible happens at what promises to be a
heavily overscripted convention, he can expect to increase his lead
still. But no matter how endearing Bush seems at the podium next
Thursday night, his appeal will not truly be tested until his
televised contests with Al Gore in October. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIMITING CAMP DAVID'S DAMAGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIDEAST-ASSESS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a comfortless marriage, Israelis and Palestinians can
manage neither reconciliation nor divorce. The collapse of the
15-day marathon at Camp David showed that even the most zealous
marriage-guidance counselor couldn't do the trick. If Bill Clinton
was not able _ in pressure-cooker conditions _ to get Ehud Barak
and Yasser Arafat to compromise their positions, it probably means
that those positions, at least in the short term, are
irreconcilable. Yet history dictates that there can be no divorce. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (925 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECONOMIC SUMMITS PROMISE MUCH AND DELIVER NOTHING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OKINAWA-SYNDROME-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the most powerful people in the world (the leaders of the
seven big industrial democracies plus Russia, together with the
president of the European Commission), the G8 summiteers promise
every summer to tackle some of its worst troubles: poverty,
disease, warfare, crime and pollution, to name but a few. Then, a
year later, they face the occupational hazard of humbler
soothsayers everywhere: how to explain to their followers why
nothing much has changed. At this year's summit in Okinawa, July
21-23, they found an answer: say it all again with feeling, plus
Internet initiatives _ but respect tradition as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHENEY ADDS LITTLE TO THE TICKET AND DETRACTS LESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHENEY-ASSESS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ When George W. Bush first described the running mate
he wanted, he said his choice would be ``electrifying.'' It ``would
make your eyes light up.'' That was when his campaign wanted a
bright new face _ someone who would reshape the political landscape
and epitomize the generational change by moving the Republican
Party away from those ghastly people in Congress. Evidentally, Bush
has now had second thoughts. His choice, Dick Cheney, is a
rock-solid candidate, with all the charisma of that inorganic
substance. He fulfills the Hippocratic requirements of a vice
president (``First, do no harm''). He will not contradict,
embarrass or outshine Bush. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...This is the `Lexington' column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,075 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REPUBLICANS IN CONGRESS MIGHT HAVE GOT IT RIGHT THIS TIME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REPUBLICANS-CONGRESS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There must be something to this
compassionate-conservatism business. It claims it can help even the
most disadvantaged, and there is evidence to support this.
Recently, one of the stupidest, most self-destructive groups in
America has started to improve its behavior. We refer, of course,
to the Republican in Congress. For the first time in living memory,
the House of Representatives may pass every one of the 13 bills
that make up the budget before it breaks for a recess at the end of
July. The Senate is only a bit behind that crackling pace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIPPING NAPSTER IN THE BUD WON'T STOP FREE INTERNET MUSIC &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NAPSTER-SWAN-SONG-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Hippy dreams have a habit of ending _ particularly
when they clash with the money-making instincts of the music
industry. This week, the suits seemed to win another battle against
peace, love and happinesss, when they were awarded a court
injunction effectively closing down Napster, a company whose
software allows its commune of users to trade songs for free. This
time, however, most of the signs are that free music may win, man.
Internet music, like rock 'n' roll, is here to stay. Hey, hey,
hey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
