   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (350 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FORMER CIA WHISTLEBLOWER IN CUBA DOT-COM VENTURE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LURING-AMERICANS-CUBA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The forbidden fruit always tastes the best _ or so
Philip Agee, a former CIA whistleblower, is hoping. He has set up a
joint-venture dot.com company with Fidel Castro's government to
encourage Americans to defy their government by vacationing on the
forbidden island. Now that the U.S. House of Representatives has
voted to soften the travel ban to Cuba, the prospect of their
actually making the trip seems less implausible. Agee's Web site,
called Cubalinda.com and designed for the American market, offers
travellers an ``unforgettable adventure.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POST-SUMMIT TALK MORE CONDUCIVE TO GUNFIRE THAN NEGOTIATIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMP-DAVID-AFTERMATH-ECONOMIST-800&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Their return from Camp David was markedly different.
Yasser Arafat came home a hero, absorbing praise for not having
buckled to Israeli and American arm-twisting. Ehud Barak returned
to Israel to a crumbled government, bitterly blaming the collapse
of the 15-day summit on Arafat. The Palestinian, he said, had
failed to make the ``historic decisions necessary to end the
conflict.'' Arafat's reply was simple. ``The Arab leader has not
been born who would give up Jerusalem,'' he reportedly told
President Bill Clinton during a heated exchange. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story stands in 800 words; total uncut is 1,125) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELECOM TYCOON AIMS TO WIN POWER IN THAILAND &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THAI-TYCOON-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It is too soon to write off Thaksin Shinawatra, the
telecom tycoon who wants to rule Thailand. His new party suffered a
blow last Sunday, when Bangkok's voters turned out in droves to
choose a new governor. Yet Thaksin is hoping that the parliamentary
elections, which must be called later this year, will be a very
different story. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCE &AMP; ECONOMICS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS JAPAN'S REAL-ESTATE MARKET AT LAST NEARING A BOTTOM? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPAN-PROPERTY-MARKET-ECONOMIST-600&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ For all the fickleness of Japan's stop-and-go
economic performance over the last ten years, the economy has had
one reliable feature: falling property prices. Since 1990, the
value of Japanese real estate has plunged by over 60 percent. In
Tokyo, commercial property has shed more than three-quarters of its
value. This deflationary wrecking ball is still hard at work. At
last, though, a glimmer of light is intruding on the gloom.
Refreshingly, it does not come from the usual quick fixes that are
favored by the government. Rather, Japan is aiming its new reforms
squarely at the market's more deep-seated financial problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story stands in 600 words; total uncut is 1,125) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOOMING DISASTER FOR AMERICA'S MOBILE-PHONE INDUSTRY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOBILE-PHONE-THREAT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ There are lots of reasons to question Deutsche
Telekom's $46.5-billion bid for VoiceStream, ranging from political
objections to its steep valuation of the American firm's customers.
But one of the most serious has hardly been mentioned. Deutsche
Telekom wants VoiceStream in part to win an America license for the
next generation of wireless services, known as 3G, which will carry
broadband data as well as voice. This is a looming disaster for
America's mobile-phone industry. The problem is that it has run out
of room to grow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,475 words) &QL;
</P>
