<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Their return from Camp David was markedly different.
Yasser Arafat came home a hero, absorbing praise for not having
buckled to Israeli and American arm-twisting. Ehud Barak returned
to Israel to a crumbled government, bitterly blaming the collapse
of the 15-day summit on Arafat. The Palestinian, he said, had
failed to make the ``historic decisions necessary to end the
conflict.'' Arafat's reply was simple. ``The Arab leader has not
been born who would give up Jerusalem,'' he reportedly told
President Bill Clinton during a heated exchange. &QL;
