<P>
   &UR; FINANCE &AMP; ECONOMICS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS JAPAN'S REAL-ESTATE MARKET AT LAST NEARING A BOTTOM? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPAN-PROPERTY-MARKET-ECONOMIST-600&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ For all the fickleness of Japan's stop-and-go
economic performance over the last ten years, the economy has had
one reliable feature: falling property prices. Since 1990, the
value of Japanese real estate has plunged by over 60 percent. In
Tokyo, commercial property has shed more than three-quarters of its
value. This deflationary wrecking ball is still hard at work. At
last, though, a glimmer of light is intruding on the gloom.
Refreshingly, it does not come from the usual quick fixes that are
favored by the government. Rather, Japan is aiming its new reforms
squarely at the market's more deep-seated financial problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story stands in 600 words; total uncut is 1,125) &QL;
</P>
