<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CARS-SAFETY-NYT &LR;      07-28 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS LOSING A LICENSE DOESN'T KEEP DRIVERS OFF THE ROAD
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR; _  &LR; Revoking or suspending a driver's license is one
of the most severe punishments for moving violations. But the
police and some safety advocates suspect that often it is no
punishment at all, and no protection for other people on the road,
because in many cases it does not stop the violator from driving.
</P>
<P>
   A new study agrees, finding that one in five fatal accidents
involves at least one driver without a valid license.
</P>
<P>
   In a study sponsored by the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety,
researchers analyzed 184,000 fatal crashes over five years,
involving more than 206,000 deaths. Nearly 37,000 of the crashes
involved a driver who did not appear to be properly licensed. Of
the 278,000 drivers involved in the crashes, regardless of who was
at fault, 13.8 percent had an invalid license; of those, 54 percent
had licenses that had been revoked or suspended. Others had never
been licensed, or had been denied licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The finding impressed the president of the AAA foundation, David
K. Willis. The roughly 42,000 who died in crashes involving an
improperly licensed driver was the equivalent of dozens of ``Boeing
737's falling out of the sky each year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, he said, his foundation issues reports and makes
recommendations, but in this case it had none. ``I wish I knew the
answer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many fatal crashes are single-car wrecks, and the unlicensed
driver is the only driver involved, but often there are passengers
or drivers of other vehicles. And sometimes, according to the
survey data, there were even collisions involving two or three cars
that were all driven by people who were not licensed.
</P>
<P>
   By focusing on a single point with reliable data _ fatal crashes
_ the study underscored how little is known about everyday driving.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, Lindsay I. Griffin III and Sandra DeLaZerda, both
with the Texas Transportation Institute at Texas A &AMP; M University,
cited a 1994 study that predicted that 30 percent to 70 percent of
drivers whose licenses were suspended or revoked might continue to
drive. That study showed a sharp regional divergence _ the problem
was far worse in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Those driving with an invalid license, no license, or ``unknown
license status'' at the time of a fatal crash made up more than 20
percent of total fatalities in Alaska, Hawaii, California, Arizona,
the District of Columbia and New Mexico. The number was less than
10 percent in Maine, New Hampshire, Minnesota, Kentucky,
Massachusetts, Nebraska, Ohio, Maryland and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a big demographic difference. Men, who are nearly
3 times as likely as women to be drivers in fatal crashes, were
more than 6 times as likely to be driving with a suspended license
and almost 10 times as likely to be driving with a revoked license.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with all drivers, those without proper licenses were
also likely to be young.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the unlicensed drivers were far more
likely to have had one or more suspensions for driving under the
influence of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers Against Drunk Driving and other safety advocates have
been successful in persuading some states to invoke
``administrative license revocation,'' or ALR, a process under
which a person stopped for driving under the influence loses his or
her license promptly, with court proceedings later. But Karolyn
Nunnallee, the immediate past president of MADD, said that while
the procedure was sound, ``we don't want ALR to be a stand-alone
law.'' She added, ``We want fines assessed, community service hours
ordered and jail time for second-time offenders.''
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising twist, Nunnallee and others agree that people
who drive with suspended or revoked licenses tend to speed less,
run fewer red lights and commit fewer other infractions, for fear
of drawing attention to themselves. ``They oddly continue to drive
a little safer than they did before,'' she said. They also drive
fewer miles, some experts believe.
</P>
<P>
   But making sure they stop driving altogether is much harder.
California has experimented with ``arresting'' the vehicle when
someone's license is revoked or suspended, and holding it for 30
days; North Carolina and some other states will confiscate and
auction off a vehicle for certain driving offenses. Neither tactic
is foolproof, though.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, the study's co-author, said the long-term solution
might be technological, a license that is a ``smart card,'' like an
automated-teller card or a key card, that would be required to
start the engine. But even this would not be perfect, he said,
because someone without a valid license could steal one, or borrow
one from someone else.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
