<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0729-COX     07-28 2718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Barnstorming his way up
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final leg of George W. Bush's road to the Republican
presidential nomination began in Texas today and moved into
President Clinton's home state as his campaign embarked on a
strategically designed tour of six swing states that will climax
with his arrival at the convention in Philadelphia on Wednesday. At
a high school in Springdale, Ark., Bush praised the integrity of
running mate Dick Cheney and took a jab at Clinton's scandal-filled
White House years. En route to Philadelphia, Bush also plans stops
at an athletic center in Missouri, a baseball bat museum in
Kentucky, a park in Ohio, a war memorial in West Virginia and the
state capitol in Pennsylvania, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   PRE-CONVENTION BOUNCE
</P>
<P>
   Candidates often get a boost during their convention _ and even
before it starts. It happened again: George W. Bush and Dick Cheney
have opened an 11-point lead over Al Gore in a new CNN-USA
Today-Gallup poll. It showed Bush ahead of Gore 50-39 percent, with
Green Party candidate Ralph Nader at 4 percent and Reform Party
contender Pat Buchanan at 1 percent. Gore had closed the gap with
Bush just a week ago in the same poll. The poll has a 4 percentage
point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   PERCEPTIONS ON STRONG POINTS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll also showed, has
done a better job than Al Gore of convincing voters that he is
personally suited to be president. The poll gave Bush an advantage
on several issues including world affairs, taxes, the budget
surplus and the economy. Gore had an edge on health care and the
environment. They were about even on Social Security and education.
</P>
<P>
   MOST FOUND TO BE TUNING IT OUT
</P>
<P>
   Another survey is showing that Americans are largely ignoring
the presidential campaign, and that their impressions of the
candidates do not show a strong correlation with the media's
election coverage. A joint study and poll by the Pew Research
Center for the People &AMP; the Press and the Project for Excellence in
Journalism found, for example, that only about 26 percent of
Americans view Al Gore as tainted by past scandal, even though
nearly half of the stories about him that have run since February
have dealt with White House fund-raising abuses. In the same
period, more than half of the stories about George W. Bush focused
on ``different kind of Republican'' theme, but only 20 percent said
he had different views from traditional GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ALL DEPENDS ON WHO YOU TALK TO
</P>
<P>
   There's both good and bad for both candidates in the results of
the poll by the Pew Research Center. Al Gore is
``scandal-tainted,'' according to about one-quarter of the
registered voters in a new poll. But almost four in 10 identify
Gore as competent and knowledgeable. George W. Bush has relied on
family connections to get ahead, more than half say. Gore is a
candidate who will say what's popular rather than what he believes,
one-third say. One in five sees Bush as a candidate who is not
serious or lacks intelligence, as the Democrats have been saying.
Also, one in five believes Bush is ``a different kind of
Republican,'' as he has been proclaiming.
</P>
<P>
   SHOW BIZ WITH THE POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   Republican convention officials released details today of the
second half of the four-day event, next Wednesday and Thursday. The
lineup, according to convention chief Andrew Card, reflects Bush's
aim of ``bringing more people into the party who might not
otherwise be there.'' Celebrities who'll be playing a part : pro
``wrassler'' The Rock, footballer Steve Young, soul singer Chaka
Khan, country duo Brooks &AMP; Dunn, vocal groups Harold Melvin's Blue
Notes and the Delfonics, actress Bo Derek, former Miss America
Heather Whitestone McCallum. Oh, there'll also be regular folks to
discuss issues, like a Hispanic small businessman, a farmer and a
single parent.
</P>
<P>
   GOP PRIMARY OVERHAUL DEBATED
</P>
<P>
   The George W. Bush campaign was marshaling forces today to try
and defeat a plan to stretch the presidential primary calendar by
voting in four waves from February through May and letting small
states go first. The ``Delaware plan'' is under consideration by
the GOP convention's rules committee. Bush strategist Karl Rove
said he worries that an elongated primary schedule would add ``wear
and tear'' on the next GOP candidate by increasing the travel
schedule. He also said it would put the GOP at a competitive
disadvantage because the Democrats would wrap up their 2004
nominations process much earlier than the Republicans. Said ex-Sen.
Bill Brock of Tennessee, who helped formulate the Delaware plan:
``I think they're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   PLATFORM EASIER ON THE RHETORIC
</P>
<P>
   Spelling out the credo of ``compassionate conservatism,'' the
Republicans' draft platform is a manifesto of George W. Bush's
campaign and moderates the GOP's official stance on issues from
education to immigration. While maintaining the staunch
anti-abortion language of the party's most recent platforms, the
draft document strips away some of the harsher anti-government
rhetoric. The document even calls for some increases in federal
spending and regulation in areas such as education and the
environment. ``Government does have a role to play, but as a
partner, not a rival, to the armies of compassion,'' the platform
draft states.
</P>
<P>
   ALL POLITICS IS POLITICAL
</P>
<P>
   A panel of the GOP platform committee voted 10-3 today against
an attempt to strike abortion language from the document, and 11-3
against an amendment expressing ``recognition and respect'' for
both sides on the issue. Toni Casey of Los Altos Hills, Calif., one
of the three, summoned the party to take abortion out of politics
and ``come together.'' But Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois countered
that abortion is necessarily political, at least because some
abortions are taxpayer-financed. ``It's right up to its neck in
politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GORE AT THE BEACH
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has carved out time for mulling over running mates and
polishing his big speech, but he said babysitting, swimming and
reading are really at the top of his seaside priorities. Gore
arrived for a week of sun and relaxation on a posh island off the
North Carolina coast, staying at a friend's house in a gated
community of upscale homes in Wrightsville Beach. Gore gave
reporters some advice for the coming week: ``You can call your
editors and tell them he is not doing anything.'' However, he
quickly conceded that wasn't strictly the case.
</P>
<P>
   BUT SURELY, IT HAS TO BE A FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore intends to select a running mate who is ready to serve
``from day one,'' campaign spokesman Chris Lehane said, despite
prodding to avoid a pick that would erode the party's chances of
recapturing the Senate. The polite brushoff came after Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle said he hoped Gore would consider the
impact of his choice on the congressional elections. Sens. John
Kerry of Massachusetts, Bob Graham of Florida, Richard Durbin of
Illinois and Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut are all from states
with Republican governors, and the governor would be able to
appoint a Senate successor.
</P>
<P>
   GROWING BLACK GOP PRESENCE
</P>
<P>
   There are 85 black delegates attending the Republican
convention, a 63 percent increase over the 1996 count. Prominent
black Republicans participating include retired Gen. Colin Powell
and Condoleezza Rice, George W. Bush's national security adviser.
Surveys by the Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies show
that only only 8.3 percent of black voters identify with the GOP,
but that 31.6 percent of younger African-Americans identified
themselves as conservatives, which may bode well in the future for
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   FROM TEXAS, IT'S THE `TRUTH SQUAD'
</P>
<P>
   Democrats deployed a team of angry Texans to ``speak the truth''
about George W. Bush's record, launching a four-day bus tour
through key battleground states to tell voters what life is like in
Texas, at least from a Democratic perspective. Calling themselves
the ``Texas Truth Squad,'' the two dozen residents spoke of
pollution, education and health care at several brief stops through
Kentucky. ``I'm here to tell you, the Bushes are coming!'' bellowed
Harry Fred Scott of East Texas. ``You've got to beware!''
</P>
<P>
   RAH-RAH, LET'S HEAR IT FOR THE TEAM
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a chance to take control of the White House and
Congress for the first time in a half century, and GOP chairman Jim
Nicholson says that has infused the party with a new burst of
enthusiasm. He encouraged Republican National Committee members to
``just imagine next January 20,'' when Republicans are sworn in as
president and vice president ``in front of a Republican speaker of
the House and a Republican Senate majority leader, all watched by
at least 30 Republican governors.'' This will happen while ``Al
Gore and Tipper, Bill Clinton and Hillary look on from the cheap
seats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A GOOD WAY TO GO OUT
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney put in just under five years as chairman and CEO at
oil services giant Halliburton, but could be eligible for a
retirement package worth at least $2.1 million, financial records
show. He also has company stock options worth millions. Cheney has
said that in leaving the company, which paid him $1.3 million last
year, he will ``take a bath'' financially and planned to ``get rid
of anything that might constitute a conflict of interest'' if he
and Bush are elected. Vice presidents earn $181,400 a year.
According to company financial reports, Cheney is entitled to $2.1
million in deferred compensation, and the money earns above-market
interest of at least 10 percent annually,
</P>
<P>
   PUT THE WIFE TO WORK, TOO?
</P>
<P>
   Even as Dick Cheney was put on the Republican ticket this week,
there already was a buzz around town that George W. Bush, if
elected, will make Cheney his education secretary _ Lynne Cheney,
that is. The 59-year-old V.P. candidate's wife, who will be highly
visible at the Republican convention next week, has a sterling
resume, a loyal constituency and a fiercely held political agenda.
And even in the past several months, while her husband headed
Bush's vice presidential search team, Lynne Cheney advised the
presidential candidate on education policy.
</P>
<P>
   IN A WAY, BAUER STILL WILL HAVE A SAY
</P>
<P>
   There was a time earlier this year when Gary Bauer could conjure
up a dream of being on the podium at the Republican convention,
accepting his party's nomination. But the ex-head of the
conservative Family Research Council ended up as little more than a
statistical blip in the first tallies of caucus and primary votes.
But he'll still be going to the GOP convention _ and to the
Democratic convention after that _ as a correspondent for an
Internet site, Beliefnet.com, which features news and commentary on
religions in America. Bauer's job will be to file daily audio
reports and write an analytical article examining the role religion
plays in Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOT CHALLENGE TO BUCHANAN COMING UP
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Pat Buchanan will attempt this weekend to
invalidate more than 250,000 ballots requested for Buchanan
supporters in a plebiscite to determine the Reform Party's
presidential nominee. ``Buchanan is essentially stuffing the ballot
box,'' Russell Verney, a former chairman of the party founded by
Ross Perot. The party's 10-member executive committee will take up
the issue at a meeting in Dallas on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   GALS GOTTA STICK TOGETHER
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because they are part of such a rare group. Perhaps
it's because they just plain like each other and work well
together. Or, more likely, a combination of all three. But nine
women senators _ six Democrats, three Republicans _ have said they
won't campaign against one another. The nine senators were
promoting their joint project, the just released book ``Nine and
Counting: The Women of the Senate.'' Sen. Mary Landrieu (D-La.)
said that ``if my leadership asked me to go campaign against one of
these women, I have told them I won't go.'' In the Senate's
211-year history, there have been only 27 female members, and 12 of
them were appointed to fill temporary vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   THERE GO YOUR DEFENSE DOLLARS
</P>
<P>
   Although the military services say they are stretched too thin
and short on money, they plan to deploy troops to Philadelphia this
weekend to display aircraft, tanks and other weaponry for
Republican members of Congress attending the convention. The
Pentagon is prohibited from associating with partisan events.
Spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Pentagon lawyers decided there would
be no violation, because approval for the military exhibits was ``a
legitimate response to a request from members of Congress to
provide an opportunity to educate elected officials on the
military's capabilities and their equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   PARTY TIME ALMOST ALL THE TIME
</P>
<P>
   There'll be dozens of parties thrown for the conventioneers:
afternoon cocktail hours for nearly every state delegation and
late-night soirees galore. Coveted events include a George magazine
benefit at the new Kenneth Cole store and a star-studded Hollywood
party at the Shampoo nightclub. In addition, there'll be a
colossal-sized ``Fight Night'' party at the Philadelphia Navy Yard
with boxing greats Joe Frazier and Larry Holmes. Among the party
attraction is a Richard Nixon-inspired vodka drink said to produce
an 18-minute gap in memory.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT KIND OF SHELF LIFE FOR MCCAIN?
</P>
<P>
   John McCain is counting on his continued popularity to keep him
in the limelight, both during the Republican convention and the
rest of campaign season as he stumps for congressional candidates.
But how long can political celebrity last for someone whose
presidential campaign peaked with a string of primary wins in
February and had crashed and burned by late March? ``The nominee is
king at his convention, and the losers appear to be Lilliputians,
even McCain,'' said University of Virginia political scientist
Larry Sabato.
</P>
<P>
   TAKES MORE THAN COFFEE TO GET WIRED
</P>
<P>
   The red, white and blue balloons are filled, but a lot of wiring
remains to be done just days before the opening of the Republican
convention on Monday. While workers put finishing touches on the
stage and set up thousands of metal chairs for the delegates inside
the convention hall, some news outlets still lacked the necessary
electrical hookups to connect to their home offices or the
Internet. ``All this stuff was supposed to be done by Monday,''
said Terry Barrett, systems administrator for the Dallas Morning
News.
</P>
<P>
   PELOSI THINKS SHE'LL BE CRACKING THE WHIP
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi of California says she has enough support from
fellow Democrats to become majority whip, the No. 3 position in the
House leadership, if her party wins control of the chamber in the
November elections. In her most confident statement yet about her
prospects for capturing the post, Pelosi said that if Democratic
lawmakers were to vote today, she would defeat her rival, Rep.
Steny Hoyer of Maryland. The whip acts as the chief vote counter
and works to rally party members to support the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   HE'S NOT REALLY A DOCTOR, HE JUST PLAYS ONE ON . . .
</P>
<P>
   Attacking her opponent as ``out of touch with the mainstream,''
Hillary Clinton seemed to take some delight in pointing to Rick
Lazio's links to a dissident band of scientists who contend that
the human immunodeficiency virus does not cause AIDS. Lazio wrote
to federal health officials earlier this year on behalf of the
Group for the Scientific Reappraisal of HIV/AIDS. The group is
connected to two scientists, Peter Deusberg and David Resnick, to
whom the South African President Thabo Mbeki also apparently turned
earlier this year in questioning the causes of AIDS. Lazio's aides
said he just wrote the letter on behalf of a constituent who
belonged to the group.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
