<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled conditions will dominate the Ohio Valley, Appalachians
and lower Great Lakes as a large, slow-moving disturbance becomes
better organized over Indiana. Increasingly humid air streaming
north from the Gulf of Mexico will be lifted by a jet-stream
disturbance in the middle Mississippi Valley. Potent thunderstorms
will drench sections of Kentucky, Ohio and Tennessee. Sluggish
storms in the Appalachians may trigger flash flooding in a few
spots.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure over Nova Scotia will direct mild, moist air into
the Northeast from the ocean. Low clouds will stubbornly persist
from New Jersey to Maine, with many places staying overcast. The
air will be humid, but readings will be below seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Warm, dry air will occupy the Plains. The return flow of
moisture into the eastern Rockies will lead to afternoon
thunderstorms from New Mexico to southern Montana. The interior
West will stay hot and dry.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SHORT SUMMER
</P>
<P>
   The first July snow since just before the bicentennial fell on
Kotzebue, Alaska, on Thursday. Snow whitened the Kigluaik mountains
north of Nome as well. Afternoon readings rose to only 41 degrees
in Kotzebue, 4 degrees lower than the previous chilliest July 27.
Summer does not last long in northwest Alaska, but the 20 hours
plus of daylight usually fends off the invasion of polar air masses
in late July. However, unusually frigid air arrived from Siberia
this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
