<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5922 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-CHENEY-HNS &LR;      07-28 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND CHENEY TRY TO WIN BACK ARKANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL
 &HT;      c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
SPRINGDALE, Ark. _ Republicans George W. Bush and Dick Cheney on
Friday recalled the impeachment of President Clinton and vowed to
restore ``dignity and honor'' to the White House as they kicked off
their five-day, five-state journey to the GOP convention with a
symbolic foray into the heart of Clinton country.
<P>
   Bush and Cheney ignited a rally of several thousand partisans at
the local high school in this Ozark mountain community in
northwestern Arkansas with promises to win back Arkansas and four
other swing states that have not voted Republican at least since
1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``It buoys my spirit to know as we're working our way to
Philadelphia for the national convention and working our way across
battleground states that the Republican ticket has not been able to
carry for the last two election cycles that our first stop is a
place that will send a resounding signal to America that Arkansas
is Bush-Cheney country, `' Bush told the roaring crowd. Neither
Bush nor Cheney nor their host, Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark.,
directly mentioned the moral lapses or impeachment of Clinton on
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice in connection with
the president's dalliance with former White House intern Monica
Lewinski. Nor did any of the candidates mention Clinton or
Democratic rival Al Gore by name.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, Cheney and Hutchinson frequently made indirect
references that recalled the moral crisis and 1998 impeachment
struggle that saw the GOP-led House vote to impeach Arkansas'
native son and the Republican Senate refuse to oust him from
office. Hutchinson, a popular former federal prosecutor and
two-term member of Congress who is running unopposed this fall, is
a local hero here after serving as one of the 13 House managers who
pressed the case for Clinton's impeachment before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   When an unidentified member of the audience shouted ``No slick
Willie!'' _ a disparaging reference to Clinton _ Hutchinson,
speaking at the podium, told Bush: ``We believe you have the right
instincts to lead America because your instincts have been shaped
by experience, rooted in principle. Inspired by faith and tempered
by compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney took turns praising each other.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, the former Wyoming congressman, defense secretary and
oil services company executive, said Bush would ``give our kids and
our grand kids a government we can once again be proud of.'' Bush
praised Cheney as a man of integrity who ``will help me bring
dignity and honor'' to the White House, adding that Cheney is ``a
man who understands what the definition of `is', is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's quip was a cryptic reference to Clinton's verbal
gymnastics during videotaped grand jury testimony about sexual
relations with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   To drive home his effort to contrast himself with Clinton, Bush
said he would be sworn in as president on the steps of the Capitol
by holding up his right hand and taking the oath not only to uphold
the U.S. constitution but also ``the honor and dignity of the
highest office in the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said in an interview with Hearst Newspapers that Bush
and Cheney would ``represent the America that we want in the White
House,'' adding: ``Both of them conduct themselves in a way that
gives us pride in our country as well as pride in the presidency.
How they conduct themselves is extraordinarily important and I
think that will be a subtle backdrop to the campaign this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the two-term governor of Texas and son of former President
George Bush, appeared energized and animated as he embarked on his
long-awaited journey to receive the GOP nomination in Philadelphia
next Thursday. He told reporters aboard his campaign plane that
receiving the nomination is ``an unbelievable, interesting, dynamic
moment in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spotlighted a variety of campaign promises that he hopes
will help him win the White House in November. He cited plans to
overhaul education to make sure there are ``no second rate children
in America.'' He said he would revamp the federal tax code to offer
billions of dollars in fresh tax breaks. He promised to eliminate
federal inheritance taxes. He said he would press for changes to
enable younger workers to invest part of their federally withheld
Social Security taxes in the stock market. The Republicans' first
joint campaign foray since a whirlwind visit to Cheney's native
Wyoming on Wednesday targeted an area of Arkansas adjacent to the
Democratic stronghold in Fayetteville, Ark., where Bill Clinton
taught law at the University of Arkansas in the early 1970s, where
Clinton tried to win a seat in Congress in 1974 and where Clinton
and Hillary Rodham got married in 1975. Bush and Cheney are
visiting Arkansas, Missouri, Kentucky, West Virginia and Ohio _
swing states that have not voted for a Republican for president at
least since 1988. Karen Hughes, Bush's campaign spokeswoman, said
there was ``some symbolism'' in the Bush campaign's decision to
make Arkansas his first stop, adding: ``We are not ceding any
territory. We're going after every vote. Gov. Bush is going to
compete (and) is competitive in states where Republicans have not
done well in the last two elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore ticket carried the five states and their 51
electoral votes in the last two presidential elections. Clinton,
who served as governor of Arkansas for five-terms, carried his
native state in both of his presidential campaigns _ the first time
the largely rural state has voted for a Democrat since Jimmy Carter
in 1976. But this predominantly Republican congressional district
which has sent a Republican to Congress since 1967 spurned
Clinton's presidential bid in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewarthearstdc.com )
</P>
