<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-CLINTON-0729-C     07-28 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CLINTON-0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ISSUES STERN WARNINGS TO PALESTINIANS ON ISRAELI TV
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-0729.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In response to the failed Camp David peace talks,
President Bill Clinton went on Israeli television Friday and
sternly warned the Palestinians against declaring statehood without
Israeli approval.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he might take the controversial, pro-Israel step of
moving the U.S. embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to the disputed
city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke of his ``almost religious conviction'' to bring
peace to the Middle East. He praised Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and, indirectly, chided Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat for saying, ``no, no, no'' during the Camp David
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The interview showed Clinton increasing the pressure, and
apparently heaping more of the blame, on the Palestinians for the
failure of the 15-day summit.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were aimed at ending the 52-year-old
Israeli-Palestinian conflict and centered on the toughest disputes
between the two sides. The biggest snag was over the city of
Jerusalem, which Israel controls but Palestinians want to use as
the capital of a new Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's participation in _ and apparent willingness to make
concessions at _ the summit increased his political problems at
home, where next week he faces attempts from opposition parties to
bring down his government.
</P>
<P>
   According to Israeli press reports, Barak asked Clinton for some
public support. He got that and more in Friday's half-hour
interview from the White House, taped and broadcast during prime
time on Israel's government news channel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been popular here throughout his term in office. He
was last interviewed on Israeli television in 1998 after the
signing of the Wye River peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   He began Friday's interview by praising Barak's ``courageous
actions'' at the summit and sought to reassure Israelis of
America's support. He reiterated, in strong terms, American
readiness to provide aid for the modernization of the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
   Israel currently receives nearly $3 billion annually in U.S.
aid, far more than any other country.
</P>
<P>
   He said further that, in light of the failed summit, he would
consider moving the U.S. embassy to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and almost all other countries refuse to
recognize disputed Jerusalem as Israel's capital. Much of the city
is occupied territory and Palestinians claim it should be their
capital.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. Congress has voted to move the embassy, Clinton
has used executive waivers to delay the move for fear of derailing
the peace process. Talk of moving it in the past has sparked riots
in Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always wanted to move our embassy to West Jerusalem,''
Clinton said. ``I have not done so because I didn't want to do
anything to undermine our ability to help broker a secure and fair
and lasting peace for Israelis and for Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, in light of what happened,'' he said in apparent
reference to the Camp David summit failure, ``I've taken that
decision under review and I'll make a decision sometime between now
and the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   One influential Palestinian legislator said Clinton's
``threats'' would ``shock the Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the summit failure, we have had some hope,'' said
Marwan Barghouti, a member of the Palestinian parliament and a key
Arafat aide. ``This will increase the tensions among the
Palestinians, and push them to feel more disappointed and
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians frequently accuse U.S. officials of favoring Israel
in the peace talks and say that, as the weaker party, they have
already made major compromises to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But, it appeared that Barak was willing to go further than any
other Israeli prime minister in offering concessions at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued a solemn warning against Arafat's plans for a
so-called ``unilateral'' declaration of statehood on Sept. 13, the
day the 1993 Oslo peace accords officially expire. Israeli leaders
threaten to respond with military action.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said such a move by Arafat would force a review of the
``entire relationship'' between the U.S. and the Palestinians _
something Palestinians have tried hard to cultivate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a big mistake to take a unilateral action and walk
away from the peace process and if it happens, there will
inevitably be consequences,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Congress is considering a bill that would cut U.S.
aid to the Palestinians if they declare statehood unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would be willing to hold another summit, but
only when both sides are ready ``make the decisions necessary to
conclude an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton interview came on a day when Israeli papers printed
new details on the talks at Camp David, including instances where
Clinton was said to have yelled at Arafat over his hard-line
position. The reports said some Palestinian negotiators seemed more
flexible than Arafat did.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that the ``Palestinian side'' had made
concessions. But speaking about settling disputes, in general,
Clinton seemed to draw a comparison to Arafat and the cheering
welcome the he received from Palestinians when he returned from the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out and say, 'no,' and you can get up the crowd and
they'll cheer you. But if that is the attitude which prevails, then
we won't get peace,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Amplifying an item that has received little mention since the
talks, Clinton also said that both Israelis and Palestinians were
interested in providing compensation to Jews who fled Arab
countries when Israel was founded.
</P>
<P>
   That would apparently be packaged with plans to compensate
Palestinians who fled from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton scoffed when interviewer Gil Tamari asked if his Camp
David effort was meant to repair damage done to his reputation by
his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with my legacy,'' Clinton said. ``This
is not about me. It's about the children who live in the Middle
East. It's about whether those children will be living together, or
living apart.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers White House correspondent Bob Deans contributed
to this story. His E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
