<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ITALY-NEWSPAPER-NYT &LR;      07-28 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-NEWSPAPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L'UNITA, ONCE A POWERFUL LEFTIST VOICE, SUSPENDS PUBLICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ L'Unita, once the most powerful leftist newspaper in
Italy, published what was probably its last issue Friday, a victim
of the fall of the Berlin Wall and market forces.
</P>
<P>
   The front page carried a blurred picture of its maiden issue of
Feb. 12, 1924, above a poignant editorial by the editor in chief.
``We are dying of debts,'' the editor, Giuseppe Caldarola, wrote.
``We are dying of an insane financial crisis. But can so vital a
part of the history of the left die this way?''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, which went into receivership two weeks ago but
was unable to reach agreements with potential buyers, formally
``suspended'' publication. It hoped that in the fall some solution
could emerge to rescue the newspaper, which has a debt of $33
million, 123 journalists and a support staff of 70, and a
hemorrhaging circulation of about 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats of the Left, which split from the hard-core
Communist Party in 1991 and is now Italy's largest center-left
party, said it would try to find a way to salvage the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians and intellectuals mourned the likely passing
of an Italian institution.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1924 by Antonio Gramsci as the mouthpiece of the
Italian Communist Party, L'Unita was at the forefront of
anti-Fascism before World War II, and was forced to publish
underground irregularly for the last years of the war. At times,
clandestine copies of the paper rallied resistance to Mussolini and
Hitler. L'Unita returned to the newsstands in 1944 after the allies
liberated Rome from German occupation. The newspaper reached its
zenith during the 1970s, when it was the most closely heeded voice
of opposition to the ruling center-right Christian Democratic
Party, selling as many as a million copies on May 1, the European
labor day.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the training ground for generations of Italian
politicians. Massimo d'Alema, who became Italy's first, if
short-lived, former Communist prime minister, was the editor of
L'Unita in the late 1980s. Walter Veltroni, who is leader of the
Democrats of the Left, was one of his successors in the newsroom,
one who sought to make it more lively and competitive. In 1997,
L'Unita entered the private sector, when the party sold most of its
shares to private shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   As bankruptcy loomed earlier this year, the newspaper returned
to direct party management, and Veltroni said the party was
spending $1 million a month on it.
</P>
<P>
   In a related symptom of the decline of the left's strength in
Italy, The Democrats of the Left party is moving out of its
historic headquarters on the Via delle Botteghe Oscure in central
Rome, an address that for decades carried leftist mystique. The
party sold off most of its real estate two years ago, including the
headquarters, but stayed on as renters. In the fall, the party will
move to less expensive offices on the Via Nazionale.
</P>
<P>
   Like all other newspapers that are party organs, and there are
more than 30 in Italy, L'Unita received government subsidies. In
1998, the newspaper received about $4 million from the state, in
addition to party funds, but that was not enough to keep it afloat.
Few other party newspapers have as large a staff, or aspire to a
large circulation.
</P>
<P>
   L'Unita's decline began in the mid-1980s, when La Repubblica, a
sprightlier center-left newspaper, came into its own, siphoning off
thousands of readers. The collapse of communism around the world,
which caused the Democrats of the Left to split from the Communist
Party, also helped seal the newspaper's doom.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, party members would volunteer to help with
distribution and sales of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is increased disaffection among party supporters, and
that too has made it difficult for L'Unita to maintain its market
position,'' Antonio Pilati, director of the Institute of Media
Economics, explained. ``L'Unita's real problem is to discover a
market niche that is different from La Repubblica. If not, it will
be very difficult to keep the paper alive only on public funding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
