<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ROADHOUSE0729-COX     07-28 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROADHOUSE0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rockin and a reelin revival radioBy Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Have you ever heard the Rolling Stones sing
gospel?
</P>
<P>
   How about Humble Pie, Jimi Hendrix, the Beach Boys or Janis
Joplin?
</P>
<P>
   Do you know Willie Nelson used to be a Sunday school teacher and
once sold Bibles door-to-door? Or have you ever heard blues great
Billie Holiday's ``God Bless the Child?''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to two guys in the Live Music Capital of the World to
come up with an alternative to contemporary Christian radio. The
``Roadhouse Revival'' radio show is reeling in music lovers of all
faiths and is on the verge of going national.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with a magazine and now the radio program, the pair,
rock 'n' roll drummers and fixtures in Austin's music scene, have
found a way to seal their devotion to the mastery of secular
musicians and their worship of God.
</P>
<P>
   For John Peyton, also a harmonica player, and Randy Hill, it's
all about breaking new ground and hitting the right chord _ even it
occasionally strikes a sour note.
</P>
<P>
   ``People might say, `Well, you got Willie Nelson. He smokes
dope,''' Peyton said. ``Well, maybe, but he sings `Amazing Grace'
really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Peyton and Hill, both secular recording artists and Christians,
are the founders, producers and disc jockeys for the show. The
twosome, who also own the Christian arts, entertainment and
lifestyle magazine True Believer, reach an often overlooked market:
mainstream Christians.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the people who believe in Jesus but do not proselytize
or talk about being born-again during most of their waking hours.
The ones who don't make disparaging remarks about people of other
faiths and admit they like watching television, reading racy novels
and drinking alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   That audience is so large that Ingram _ one of the biggest names
in Christian publishing _ will begin distributing the next issue of
True Believer nationwide. And only seven months since its debut,
Peyton and Hill are in negotiations with another company to
nationally distribute the ``Roadhouse Revival.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no shows coming out of Austin like this,'' said Jim
``Jimbo'' Kipping, creative services director for LBJS
Broadcasting, which own five radio stations including KLBJ-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Kipping pieces the show together each week. It begins with a
bedroom studio run through at Kipping's home where the three work
on the song selection. Then it's a day at the radio station studio
working on the voice material before the show rolls out in a Sunday
morning slot.
</P>
<P>
   Though they have gotten some criticism from conservative
Christian camps, the magazine and radio show are receiving support
from conservative, moderate and liberal Christians. The program is
even attracting a non-Christian listening audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Roadhouse Revival' is to reach the unreached and tell the
untold,'' Peyton said. ``It's a come-as-you-are radio show where
you don't have to change to like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will hear the most talented people on the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   The show also honors gospels greats like Mahalia Jackson and
Austin's Bells of Joy.
</P>
<P>
   The variety not only crosses Christian lines but musical ones,
offering rock 'n' roll, blues, jazz, country, heavy metal, punk and
gospel. Between songs, Hill and Peyton offer mostly untold stories
about how the secular artists came to do the songs, quick tidbits
about their personal background and religious trends among the
artists that often go unnoticed by music reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric Clapton has dozen of gospel songs,'' Peyton said. ``He
puts a gospel song on each one of his albums.''
</P>
<P>
   The show airs at 6:30 a.m. Sundays on rock station KLBJ-FM and
is simulcast via the Internet. That exposure had led the show to
receive e-mails from listeners in other states and countries,
including England and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   To find their material, Peyton and Hill scoured their own album
collections (for Gen-Xers, this is what music came on before the
invention of CDs, cassettes, and 8-tracks). They started hanging
out in record stores. ``We go to Goodwill and dig through there and
we go to the Internet,'' Hill said of their research.
</P>
<P>
   It's how they found Janis Joplin's 1969 Woodstock performance of
``Work Me Lord.'' And Linda Ronstadt's ``We Need a Whole Lot More
Jesus and A Lot Less Rock 'n' Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Morrison, Kris Kristofferson, Lyle Lovett, Stevie Wonder,
Gladys Knight &AMP; the Pips, One Bad Pig, Bob Dylan, Louis Armstrong,
Taj Mahal, Doobie Brothers, Beatles and Elvis also get air time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all these artists that you wouldn't expect to be doing
Christian music,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't expect many of these artists to record
traditional hymns, but they have,'' Peyton said. ``For example, the
Rolling Stones' `You Gotta Move' is an old black, spiritual number
written by Fred McDowell and the Rev. Gary Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
