<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5941 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-IBIZA-DISCOS-$ADV30-1     07-28 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBIZA-DISCOS-$ADV30-1205(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPANISH SUN FIRES A CARNIVAL THAT WON'T DIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBIZA, Spain _ It &UR;  &LR; was 11 a.m. on a bright and sunny morning in
the Balearics, the type of blue-sky day when one wants nothing more
than to sip sangria on a white sand beach and read Hemingway. Or
perhaps to stay up 24 hours straight listening to house music,
sweating like a pig in a fur coat and dancing with 10,000
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was the choice of Howard Boyle, 22, of Brighton,
England, who was dressed as (who else?) Elvis. He was doing all he
could to flag the attention of a bartender at the Space nightclub,
where the biggest weekly party in Europe was in its 12th hour and
still going strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear to you, it never ends,'' Boyle said, with his Elvis
wig in hand and a grin from sideburn to sideburn. ``And really,
now, why should it?''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Ibiza, the Mediterranean island whose carnivalesque
club scene makes Mardi Gras look like an ice-cream social. Parties
here don't end; they simply move to another location.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the revelers at Space, for example, would remain until
late afternoon, and then head to the Bora Bora beach, an idyllic
stretch of white sand a block away, where topless girls and
awestruck boys often dance until the sun goes down and the cycle
starts all over again.
</P>
<P>
   The common refrain at the clubs is a kind of dance-driven
decadence, underscored by loud to too-loud house or trance music,
or some derivative, each with enough beats per minute to give a
hummingbird agita.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the giant Monday night fiesta called
Manumission, a lavish night-to-day extravaganza held in an
arena-size club named Privilege. It regularly draws more than
10,000 people and sets new standards for sexually graphic, obscure
and just plain strange entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the spectacle included midgets on stilts, acrobats
dangling from the club's 100-foot ceiling, a wall of falling water,
and more thongs than a Sisquo video. The profusion of spangles,
glitter and body paint worn by the huge crowd probably had dire
environmental implications. This is where Elvis spent the first 11
hours of his night, bopping to nonstop music, all spun by
solemn-looking disc jockeys on a circular island in the middle of
the club's swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Privilege is just one of at least a dozen huge discos on Ibiza,
which has transformed itself into a club-hopper's destination
resort. There are billboards advertising discos, a disco bus whose
drivers play techno and even disco package tours, like one from
Bring It On Travel that offers a package of seven nights,
round-trip airfare from New York and two free club passes for
$1,359. (Motto: ``On the beach till 7 p.m. In the clubs till 9
a.m.'')
</P>
<P>
   Ibiza has been known for discotheques since as far back as the
1970s, but it was in the late '80s, when the island became a focal
point of international rave culture, that the scene began gathering
new momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Today the crowds have never been bigger, with a majority of
clubbers from Britain. Of 1.35 million visitors who invaded during
the club season from June to mid-September last year, more than
500,000 were from England, according to the island's tourism
bureau, compared with 355,000 English tourists during all of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known British clubs like Ministry of Sound, Cream and
Gatecrasher sponsor summer satellites in Ibiza, banking on the
appeal of star disc jockeys like Paul Okenfold. This summer, there
are more American DJs playing, including Junior Vasquez, part of
what island veterans call a growing American presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's loads of Americans,'' said Rod Lay, who runs the Trade
party, another London import, at Privilege. Celebrity sightings are
also on the rise, with local gossip sheets reporting Donna Karan,
Stella McCartney and Kate Moss on the island this summer.
</P>
<P>
   For average clubbers, the growing global electronica movement is
part of the draw, but it is also an open secret that many come here
to capitalize on the ready availability of party drugs like
Ecstasy, GHB and ketamine hydrochloride, an animal anesthetic known
as Special K.
</P>
<P>
   Pills of Ecstasy are especially cheap and plentiful, running $7
to $10 each _ the street rate is about $25 in New York _ with
dealers frequenting many of the clubs and bars, even working taxi
lines, where clubbers can wait for as long as two hours.
</P>
<P>
   All of which inspires some ``good old days'' sentimentality
among the veteran party people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Phil Collins being played here,'' said Boy George,
the pop star turned disc jockey, who has been a regular in Ibiza
clubs since 1988. He had just completed a set at Amnesia.
``Everybody stopped, and looked, and said `Why not?' and kept
dancing,'' he said. ``Things used to be much more experimental.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ibiza residents feel overwhelmed by the clubgoing hordes,
there have been few official moves to hold back the tide. Tourism
has made the island and its neighbor Majorca two of the richest
spots in Spain, and construction cranes loom all around the central
harbor. Residents seem to express any ambivalence simply by
patronizing their own bars and restaurants, separate from the
megaclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only thing that hasn't changed is the island itself,
with its exceptionally strong sun, plenteous white sand beaches and
rolling landscape dotted with olive and pine trees, vineyards and
windmills. In short, a great place to spend lots of time sweating
in dark, loud rooms, which is exactly what I did on a 48-hour tour
of the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Most don't open before 11 p.m. or midnight, and the concept of
arriving too late is unheard of. ``I'll be there at 3 a.m.,'' one
promoter told me. He was an hour late.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the low-budget clubbers take advantage of the disco bus,
a midnight-to-6 a.m. limited on which partiers, male and female,
adjust their makeup. Its main route is east from Ibiza town, the
island's major port and capital, to San Antonio, an unruly beach
town that is home to some of the older clubs with lower cover
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The major one here is Es Paradis Terrenal (Paradise on Earth). A
quick visit proved enlightening: Paradise apparently includes air
hockey machines, a gift boutique and go-go dancers. I felt
reassured about my afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   Es Paradis is also home to one of the newest gimmicks on the
island: the Fiesta del Agua. As the name implies, water is
involved. Every Friday night the club inundates part of its dance
floor with a few inches of water and sprays the dancers. Female
clubbers who have experienced the Fiesta del Agua say they enjoy
the cool water on their warm bodies; male partygoers say they enjoy
exactly the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Ibiza town is home to Space, Pacha and a yacht club turned
nightclub, El Divino, where a popular night known as Miss
Moneypenny's is well known by the city's temporary and resident
transvestite communities.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two towns, on a treacherous stretch of unlighted
highway, are the two biggest clubs: Privilege and Amnesia. Amnesia
boasts twice-weekly dance-floor foam parties (6 feet of bubbles,
swimsuits not required). Its owner, Martin Ferrer, claims to be the
first man ever to fill a dance floor with foam. He said the idea
came to him in a dream. ``I just saw people dancing,'' he said.
``In bubbles.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With a capacity of 4,000 to 5,000 a night (depending on which
way the authorities are looking), $12 cocktails, and cover charges
sometimes topping $40, Amnesia seems to do well. The night I
visited, it was packed shoulder to shoulder with sweaty bodies.
``These clubs aren't making a fortune selling alcohol,'' a
publicist named Marcello told me. ``They're making a fortune
selling water.'' At $6 for a small bottle, I could see his point.
Amnesia's newest toy, a specially designed ``fog gun,'' blasted
jets of frozen air into the crowd, to great rejoicing.
</P>
<P>
   While Amnesia is big, there is apparently no club bigger than
Privilege, and no night bigger than Manumission at Privilege. The
night, started by the British team of Mike and Claire Manumission,
uses some 80 entertainers to amuse the crowd. Its graphically
sexual displays are legendary; on Monday, they included a group of
Puerto Rican strippers from New York, a troupe of Brazilian feather
dancers and a bodybuilder with a talent for contortion.
</P>
<P>
   The club, roughly the size of a small sporting arena, used to be
open-air but was forced to build a soaring steel roof several years
ago after complaints about the noise. Visual distraction abounds: a
two-story Buddha in the corner, three dozen disco balls hanging
over the dance floor in a small side room.
</P>
<P>
   Above the main dance floors are dozens of circular screens, on
which a constant stream of surreal images is projected; I seem to
remember a giant cube emblazoned with the word ``Orange'' intercut
with a Clara Bow movie. The images are all synchronized with the
pounding music, resulting in an effect just this side of
hallucination.
</P>
<P>
   Those standing in line to enter Manumission often take over an
hour to work their way from sidewalk to entrance, and though
everyone gets in eventually, the scene can be ugly. The night I
visited, fights nearly broke out amid would-be soccer rowdies who
were singing rival team songs. There were also other signs of
trouble, with a dealer openly offering samples of GHB.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, however, the vibe was reverential. The partiers, almost
all in their late teens and 20s, with two men for every woman, kept
their eyes peeled on Tall Paul, who led them through hours of
alternately soaring and screaming music without a break. For all
the eroticism of the floor shows, most people danced alone, which
is in the nature of the hyperkinetic music.
</P>
<P>
   The party would run until 10 a.m., when Privilege closed, and
then shift to Space, about seven miles away. Die-hards would travel
there, some hitchhiking, others walking like disco refugees.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived after a nap, the party at Space was still on,
with about 300 people crowding the outside terrace, eating
watermelon, drinking and dancing to mellower fare, and 300 more
inside, still skipping along on the harder house music. To wake up,
I had a Red Bull _ a high-powered caffeine drink that is a club
favorite _ and then encountered Boyle, wearing his white Elvis
outfit and sporting 3-inch sideburns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, baby,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He told me he usually performed at Manumission, re-enacting the
King's demise in a Graceland bathroom for 10,000 appreciative fans.
On this night, however, his act had been foiled by ``some jealous
Spanish performers'' who he believed had stolen his toilet. (This
account could not be confirmed. Ever. In a million years.)
</P>
<P>
   He then launched into his personal story about how he got to
Ibiza. As far as I could follow, there was an affair with an older
woman, an Ozzy Osbourne concert and an initial ``three-day bender''
in Ibiza. Before he knew it, he said, he was Elvis. A friend
confirmed his status. ``He really looks like him,'' this jittery
young man said. ``A combination of the fat old one and the
good-looking young one.''
</P>
<P>
   I took my leave. It was 1 p.m., after all, and from the looks of
the blazing sun, the evening _ if not the party _ was over. I'll
admit I felt conflicted. The crowd at the front door of Space was
growing. And beyond the walls, the music, as it always is in Ibiza,
was still pumping.
</P>
</TEXT>
