<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CONCORDE-CRASH _ GONESSE, France _ French investigators
discovered the body of a fifth victim under the rubble of a hotel
destroyed when an Air France Concorde crashed earlier this week,
raising the death toll to 114. The victim was not immediately
identified and the sex was not known. Four other people died on the
ground, all of them employees of the hotel. All 109 people on board
the supersonic jet died. The French Transport Ministry also said
that both tires on the aircraft exploded during takeoff apparently
sending fragments into the engines and possibly piercing the fuel
tanks. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COLDWATER _ MOSCOW _ Russians look forward to summer with
a mixture of joy and despair, for as soon as warm weather hits this
country, the hot water gets turned off. In Moscow families lose
their hot water for up to a month at a time, thanks to a system
that is a holdover to the Soviet-era central hot water system. You
know your turn has come by a simple, handwritten note by the front
door. This prompts a flurry of new conversation from everyone you
meet on the street _ instead of complaining of the cold weather,
people complain about cold showers. (Coker, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: expected to move by noon Tues., July 25, on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CLINTON _ JERUSALEM _ In an apparent attempt to shore up
the weak government of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, President
Bill Clinton gives an interview on Israeli TV Friday night. He's
expected to put his spin on the failed Camp David summit and
express the U.S.' continuing support for Israel. Earlier in the
day, one Palestinian official said Clinton's support for Barak is
more aimed at the elections in the U.S. than in Israel. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   (Repeating) ISRAEL-JERUSALEM _ JERUSALEM _ When low-level
negotiators can't settle a dispute, they usually ``bump it
upstairs'' for a decision. When it comes to the Holy City of
Jerusalem, maybe The Man upstairs should settle the dispute. An
Israeli academic, who consults with negotiators in the peace talks
between Israel and the Palestinians, suggests they break their
deadlock by giving God sovereignty over the holiest parts of the
city. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by 3 p.m. (ET) on the NYT Wire in both
International and Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LAURABUSH _ AUSTIN _ Warm, but straightforward and no-nonsense,
like your favorite grade-school teacher, dressed and polished like
the future U.S. first lady she may yet be, Laura Bush has
acknowledged there are disadvantages as well as advantages to being
married to a presidential candidate. As first lady of Texas, Bush's
pet projects have channeled money to libraries, literacy programs
and young children. In a poor El Paso neighborhood or at the
country club across town, she's treated like the next best thing to
royalty: tortilla vendors, wealthy businessmen and even Democrats
sing her praises. But as the wife of presidential candidate George
W. Bush, the media throng has gotten thicker. (Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Bush and Cheney begin their trek to Philly with stops in
Arkansas and Missouri Friday. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINEMUSIC _ SAN DIEGO _ As Napster Inc. prepares its legal
fight against the recording industry, another online music company
is making nice with record makers. MP3.com has agreed to pay
royalties and cash to settle a copyright lawsuit filed by Los
Angeles record company EMI in what MP3 officials say is the sign of
the online music industry's future. It is the third such suit MP3
has settled. Napster, meanwhile, may be warming up to the industry
a bit too, even as it prepares for a court-ordered shutdown at
midnight Friday. It contacted visitors of its site today and urged
them to buy CDs _ especially those made by artists who have come
out in favor of Napster's file sharing programs _ at music stores
and other retailers as part of a two-day ``buy-cott.'' Many Napster
fans had been urging a boycott of major record labels and CD stores
in protest to Wednesday's ruling against the controversial company.
Story moving through Austin this afternoon. (Keefe, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-DISPUTES _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Florida is moving forward
on unveiling the country's first dispute resolution program to
mediate claims by doctors and hospitals that they are owed money by
HMOs (Murawski, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   JAKES-ANGRY _ Rev. T.D. Jakes says Atlanta has not been a good
host for his evangelical tour. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-WOMEN _ WASHINGTON - Few women have been mentioned as
possible running mates for Vice President Al Gore. Why? He has few
to choose from. And the best known among them come from states
already safe for Gore or lack the seasoning needed for a spot on
the party's national ticket. (Shepard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-SENATE _ Georgia Republicans may open their presidential
convention in Philadelphia without a GOP candidate to oppose former
Gov. Zell miller for the US. Senate vacancy created by the death of
Paul Coverdell. Now that all House Republicans in the delegation
have passed on seeking the nomination, the popular names in the
conversation now are a former airline president and the state
school superintendent, Linda Schrenko. Schrenko, who would have to
resign to run, is to meet with advisors Saturday. (Judd-Salzer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SENATOR-MONEY _ ATLANTA _ When Zell Miller left the governor's
office, his political capital was large but his financial portfolio
was another matter. His net worth was only about $300,000 _ a
paltry sum for a man of his age and stature. He soon set out to
change that, however, joining the boards of seven corporations and
investing in some of those firms. He also went to work as a
consultant for Philip Morris, the largest cigarette manufacturer
and one of the companies paying the state $4.8 billion to settle a
lawsuit that Miller filed. Now that he has been appointed to the
U.S. Senate, Miller is disengaging from those new business
interests _ and, by all accounts, making a substantial financial
sacrifice. (Judd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AL-AMIN _ Rally for Jamil Adbullah Al-Amin (former H. Rap Brown)
Friday. Muslims in West End will have a prayer, sports competition
and rally for Al-Amin. The sports competition is an annual event
that Al-Amin first organized years ago. It draws Muslims from
across the country. (Good, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ More than 10 years ago I test
drove a 12-cylinder BMW that cost more than my house. One of the
features packed into this luxury high-performance car was a
hands-free telephone. The phone wasn't hooked up, but I was told
that the voices of the driver and passengers were picked up clearly
by a built-in microphone. The person on the other end of the
conversation was heard through the car's excellent speaker system,
which automatically muted other signals going to the speakers when
the phone was in use. I considered this a nifty development.
(Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ Picking up trash at the
annual Marshall clean-up isn't a problem for me. I guess you could
say I've been nothing but a muckraker all my life. My first real
job was picking up trash off the parking lot of a foundry that
employed about 500 people. It seemed like a good deal to me, I got
paid $40 a week to keep it clean no matter how many hours I worked.
If I could keep it clean by working two hours a week, that was a
cool 20 bucks an hour. (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ATLANTA _ The notion that
some things never change has gone out the window in the 21st
century. Everything changes. If you don't believe it, look what's
happening in the Army, the Navyr jet business. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ORKIN _ Internal memos written by Orkin Exterminating officials
acknowledge that company employees in several states, including
Georgia, falsified forms for reinspections of homes for termite
damage. The memos, obtained by the Journal-Constitution, say that
many customers ''are being charged for services not rendered.''
Orkin and its parent company, Atlanta-based Rollins Inc., are
targets of a Tampa lawsuit that alleges that Orkin workers
performed improper chemical treatments, skipped annual inspections,
forged customer names on inspection slips, and misrepresented
warranties, leading to widespread termite damage. Orkin faces a
similar lawsuit in Alabama that has reached class-action status.
The company denies the charges in each case. In addition, the
Florida attorney general's office is investigating Orkin's
advertising and warranty practices. Bob Buchner, a Florida
assistant attorney general, says five other states _ not Georgia _
are also investigating Orkin. (Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET HEALTHY LIVING PAGE AVAILABLEArt includes two color
illustrations and one color photo
</P>
<P>
   CoxNet HEALTHY LIVING 0729: ONLINE COUNSELING_ Online counselors
and therapists increasingly are providing help to clients over the
Internet, trading face-to-face voices and gestures for words on the
World Wide Web.The trend has some professionals alarmed.
(Kicklighter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 4 color
illustration of Sigmund Freud using a laptop computer and a
1-column photo of an Atlanta psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT-A-GLANCE BOX_ A list of information about online
