<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ABANDONED-HOUSES-A     07-28 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABANDONED-HOUSES-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SYRACUSE, N.Y., THE PROBLEM IS TOO MUCH HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 was sent July 27 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ If only it were near New York City, 403 Rowland
St. might be a handy home-buyer's dream. Sure, the side porch is
collapsing, the chimney is crumbling, and the big front windows
have been replaced by small squinty ones. But the vintage charms of
this turn-of-the-century house, including sturdy construction and
gingerbread trim, would probably look alluring to the
housing-hungry hordes in southern New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The view is quite different here, near the center of the state,
near the center of Syracuse, near the center of a working-class
neighborhood known as Skunk City. So it is hard to argue with
Millie Compeau, sitting on the porch of the tidy house where she
has lived for 89 of her 92 years, when she peers across Rowland
Street at No. 403 and decrees, ``That house should come down.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people are starting to agree. That is because Syracuse
has more houses _ a lot more houses _ than its 152,000 citizens
need or want. Like the place on Rowland Street, as many as 2,200 of
them are empty or abandoned, more than 10 percent of the houses
within the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Boarded-up houses mar some of Syracuse's nicest neighborhoods
and fill blocks in some of the worst. Skunk City, where residents
say the namesake critters still roam at night, is somewhere in
between: a well-kept house is followed by a run-down place, then
another nice one, then an abandoned wreck _ or two or three.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is so bad that last fall, government and civic
leaders began the Syracuse Neighborhood Initiative to try to bring
back blighted areas of the city. Rep. James T. Walsh, a Republican
on the House Appropriations Committee, whose father grew up in
Skunk City, has already gotten $15 million in federal financing for
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the project, many in Syracuse are embracing an idea
that has long been anathema to almost everyone trying to save urban
areas: demolishing houses _ and not rebuilding them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, getting money to do tear-downs is very hard,''
said Allison Lee, a senior official in the Albany office of the
federal Department of Housing and Urban Development. But after
touring areas where problem properties have been knocked down, she
said, ``I have to tell you, the neighborhoods are better.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse is not the only place upstate suffering from abandoned
housing, which afflicts almost every old city east of Detroit. But
perhaps because Syracuse is so small and is not a corporate or
government center, the problem seems more overwhelming than in
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is the most serious problem because we have the least
resources,'' said Eric Mower, an advertising executive who is
chairman of the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   How Syracuse came to such a pass is a tangled tale of failures
in public policies and changes in private tastes, but most of all,
of economics. The 1991 recession that hit all of New York state
came to Syracuse and would not leave. Long after the economy began
to rebound to the south, central New York stagnated.
</P>
<P>
   That is no longer true, at least on paper. New jobs have been
sprouting here at a faster pace than almost anywhere else north of
New York City, and unemployment is only 3.7 percent, well under the
national average of 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The housing market is improving, too, after dropping sharply in
the mid-1990s and treading water for years. Last year, the number
of houses sold in and around Syracuse rose more than 10 percent,
according to the Greater Syracuse Association of Realtors, and the
median price edged up to $82,500 (which is still less than the
median in 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Within the city, however, house prices still seem to be
dropping, according to a study by the federal Neighborhood
Reinvestment Corp. for the Syracuse Neighborhood Initiative. That
is, when houses sell at all. In Skunk City, there were just four
regular sales last year, according to the report. Tax auctions and
foreclosure sales have become the norm.
</P>
<P>
   City inspectors report that more than 1,000 houses in the city
remain vacant, and the number has been rising. Minchin G. Lewis,
the city auditor, says that the correct figure is more like 2,200,
based on the number of water meters that have been unused for a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The vacant houses that people see all over the city remind them
of the terrible economic times they have endured _ and help explain
why the good news announced by economists does not seem to have
sunk into the psyche of Syracuse's citizens. ``They're shellshocked
from the decline that has taken place,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That was clear at a city council hearing, held on July 19 to
discuss plans to build a big mall in the city. Dozens of residents
spoke, and many described Syracuse in apocalyptic terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is in a real crisis,'' said Melanie Duer, 43, who
after a disabling accident used her insurance settlement to buy and
fix up a small apartment building in Skunk City, near where she
grew up. In 1994, she told city officials, there were 6 vacant
houses on the main road between her building and downtown; today,
she said, there are 36.
</P>
<P>
   In a later interview, Duer expressed frustration with
politicians who, she said, find it easy to overlook her
neighborhood. When President and Hillary Clinton visited Syracuse
last year, the president played golf less than a mile away from her
building, ``but it might as well have been in Zimbabwe,'' she said.
``They could really make a difference if they walked on this
street. I'm just one voice with a weed whacker.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Skunk City does not look like a slum. Each one-
or two-family house has a little strip of grass in the front and a
plot in the back, with just enough room for a shed or a garage.
Many of the houses are trim and tidy. Marigolds and petunias edge
walks. Children of all colors ride their bicycles up and down the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Hang around for a while, however, and problems appear. Drug
dealers, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Rowland Street, a young man announces, ``I'm gonna cop,'' and
with money in his hand crosses to the corner where a couple loiter.
A block away, there is a lot of furtive activity around a pay phone
on the corner. Down the street, a high-stakes craps game continues
in one driveway. Residents complain that illegal car-repair joints
sprout on the bigger streets.
</P>
<P>
   And on almost every block, like a bruise, is an unkempt house
with a sagging porch, a trash-filled yard, a pile of old dumped
tires, or broken windows partly boarded up.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some shootings and stabbings, said Richard
Puchalski, who as executive director of Syracuse United Neighbors
seems to know every block of Skunk City. ``A lot of folks who have
lived here 40 or 50 or 60 years are finding it difficult to
maintain their houses,'' he said. ``They are being pressured by
their siblings, who say, `You'd better get the hell out of
there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even in its heyday, Skunk City was not the fanciest part of
town. It was too close to the swamp; developers crammed as many
houses as possible in narrow lots along the new sewer line. In more
recent decades, the threat of a highway project discouraged people
from moving in.
</P>
<P>
   But to the people who lived there, it was a ``garden spot of
Eden,'' according to the yellowing newspaper clippings preserved at
the Onondaga Historical Association. For the children, there was
fishing and skating and swimming; for the adults, there were plenty
of saloons and a movie house.
</P>
<P>
   The men in the neighborhood had steady jobs at the post office,
the railroad or the auto plants. Some were more colorful: Florence
Joslin's father sang on the radio, while the Schwald boys' dad had
been a roller skater in a vaudeville act, the Whirling Hamilton
Trio, before he settled down to raise a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were kids, 15, 16 years old, our father could leave
the car in the driveway with the keys in it,'' said Dennis J.
Schwald Sr., 58. ``Nobody touched nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, said his brother William, 61, ``everyone owned their
own home.'' He added, ``We've seen it gone down and down.'' Both
men, who retired from the Carrier air-conditioner plant, still live
on Hartson Street, as did their parents and in-laws; now, Dennis'
son owns two houses on the street.
</P>
<P>
   But such roots have gone out of fashion, even in Syracuse.
Today, many young families _ and older ones, too _ prefer to live
out in the suburbs, where the houses are newer, the lots bigger and
the schools better. The amount of developed land around the city
has almost doubled in the last decade, said Vito Sciscioli, the
city's commissioner for community and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the region's population has been shrinking, with most
of the drain coming from within the city limits. From 1990 to
mid-1999, the population of Onondaga County shrank by 13,000, with
12,000 of the drop occurring in Syracuse, according to federal
census estimates.
</P>
<P>
   That left Syracuse with ``a brutal oversupply of housing,'' said
Eric Hangen, who wrote the report for the Syracuse Neighborhood
Initiative. People who wanted to sell could not. People who wanted
to fix up their homes would not because they feared rightly that
they could not recoup their investments, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate homeowners took to renting out their unwanted houses,
or selling them to slum lords, or abandoning them altogether
because they could not pay the mortgages. Or the taxes, especially
after the city started seizing delinquent properties a couple of
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development alone now lists
about 50 houses for sale in the city. Some of them are priced at
less than $15,000, which is roughly what it would cost to knock
them down.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the Syracuse Model Neighborhood Corp., a housing
group, built houses on vacant lots and sold them for $78,000, but
no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last two years I've built one house,'' said Thomas
Francis, who runs the group. ``There's no demand, and I can't
afford to hold on to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fundamentally, Francis said, ``there just are not enough
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ergo, demolition _ or de-densifying, as some people call it. The
idea is to tear down not only those abandoned houses that threaten
to collapse on their own, but also those that are simply unneeded
and uneconomical. The land could be split between the remaining
nearby houses, to give them bigger yards, or driveways, or garages
(popular in snowy Syracuse). Big tracts could be turned into parks.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, in other words, is to make the city more like the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suburbs are the best part of America,'' said Greg G.
Smith, a landlord with 60 units on the west side of the city.
``Everybody loves having a decent-size yard and off-street parking.
They want breathing room enough that when somebody's alarm clock
goes off, it doesn't wake you up.''
</P>
<P>
   If the houses that get knocked down are simply replaced, he
added, ``you're preserving the streetscape that everybody hates.''
As part of the neighborhood initiative, he is hoping to get
financing for a master plan and small grants to try out this idea
on the west side of town.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how much housing will be demolished in Syracuse remains
unclear. Each of the city's neighborhoods gets to make
recommendations about what improvements it would like. In some of
the more prosperous areas, residents are calling for improvements
like period streetlights or a new botanical garden.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said that no more than a third of the federal money, $5
million so far, could be used for demolition; at $12,000 a pop, the
city's estimate, that would be about 417 houses.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that demolition will solve all the problems
in Syracuse's neighborhoods. ``It's good to have that strategy,''
said Sciscioli, the city commissioner, ``but if you don't address
basic services, you can kiss it all goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Skunk City, however, longtime residents like Patricia D.
Masters are looking forward to some demolition. ``I'd like to see
them do it a little quicker,'' she said. ``How long do you have to
have a dead house on your street?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
