<HEADER>
A5950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-INTERNET-$ADV30-C     07-28 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-INTERNET-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DOT-COM SCENE INVADES GOP CONVENTION
 &HT;    With INTERNET-GRID. For release Sunday, July 30.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ At the 2000 Republican National Convention, which
opens here Monday, the Old Guard is being forced to give ground to
the Young Turks.
</P>
<P>
   But this changeover isn't political. It's media-driven.
</P>
<P>
   As workers attached the last of 150,000 red, white and blue
balloons to the convention hall rafters, both the old-line major TV
networks and their all-news cable cousins were being obliged to
make room for some dot-com-pany.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, two all-Internet Webcasting services,
America Online and Psuedo.com, will join the familiar media logos
in the plush sky boxes high above the First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of other Webcasters are primed to get into the political
news business as well. These pioneering cyberspace crews are being
grouped together in a huge white air-conditioned media tent known
as Internet Alley.
</P>
<P>
   At week's end, all that could be seen of their convention bid
was a maze of fiber optic cables _ some 6,600 miles have been
installed to serve the site _ and many Internet servers still in
their packing crates.
</P>
<P>
   Some 50 yards away, a squad of Japanese-speaking technicians was
testing high-definition television (HDTV) equipment, installed in
two graffiti-covered trucks driven here from New York.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal with convention organizers, the Tokyo-based NHK
network will be the only broadcaster to cover the proceedings,
gavel to gavel, in HDTV. Internet users with a broadband connection
will be able to watch the NHK feed on their computer monitors by
calling up the official GOP convention site.
</P>
<P>
   A slew of start-up Webcasting domains will also offer the kind
of political fare that until recently remained the exclusive domain
of the all-news cable outfits and network broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a different kind of convention for a different kind of
Republican,'' said top convention planner Tim Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GOP was last in Philly in 1948, and that was the first
convention ever to be televised,'' he noted. ``We will be just as
forward-thinking. Because of the Internet, everyone can join in.
Everyone has access.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, whatever ``news'' emerges out of Philadelphia this
week, will be sliced and diced in more ways than the
record-breaking four-ton hoagie sandwich that will be paraded
around City Hall on Monday before it is served.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone by the pure ``netcasters,'' such broadcasting
and cable outlets as ABC, CNN, C-SPAN, Fox News and MSNBC are also
planning to put much of their coverage on line, either in real-time
or in archival form.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, which has become even more content-aware as a result of its
pending merger with Time-Warner, is making a major bid here to snag
as many of its 22 million subscribers as possible.
</P>
<P>
   It will offer nightly interactive chats with newsmakers on
topics to be determined by online polls taken during the day. In
addition, it plans to deploy a 24-hour Webcam and to post selected
``delegate diaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another all-Internet service, Voter.com, will host a nightly
show with its executive editor, onetime Watergate sleuth Carl
Bernstein. Also on tap: veteran political pundit Jack Germond and
Comedy's Central's Ben Stein.
</P>
<P>
   Not be left behind in the audio-video propwash, such online
``magazines'' as Salon.com and Slate.com will expand their daily
political coverage, offering a faster news turnaround to readers
than traditional print outlets usually offer.
</P>
<P>
   Internet users who may feel somewhat overwhelmed by the hundreds
of possible ways that they can access the 2000 Republican National
Convention might want to turn to such search engines as Yahoo's
events.yahoo.com or Alta Vista's www.icast.com.
</P>
<P>
   Both sites, among such others as Google.com, will offer
clickable links to what's on tap this week on the political scene.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
