<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURERS-PERFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE COMPANIES REPORT BETTER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good earnings reports for some of the biggest names in U.S.
commercial insurance this week suggested that long-depressed prices
for coverage were beginning to rise. And that caught the attention
of investors.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices rose sharply for American International Group, the
biggest and strongest of the group, as well as for Chubb Corp.; St.
Paul Cos.; Marsh &AMP; McLennan Cos., the world's largest insurance
brokerage; and Hartford Financial Services Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prospects are clearly improving,'' said Weston Hicks, an
analyst at J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh &AMP; McLennan Cos. reported a 17 percent rise in operating
earnings, to $506 million, for the second quarter. American
International Group, widely known as AIG, posted an increase of 13
percent, to $1.43 billion. Hartford Financial Services also
reported an increase of 13 percent, to $239 million.
</P>
<P>
   Chubb Group reported a 10.5 percent rise in operating income, to
$180.7 million, but its per-share earnings remained flat at $1,
reflecting an issue of stock for the recent purchase of Executive
Risk, a company specializing in liability coverage for company
executives and board members.
</P>
<P>
   But Chubb reported improvements in profits in its commercial
lines, as did St. Paul Cos., which reported a 9 percent decline in
operating income, to $158.9 million. At Hartford Group, earnings
from life insurance offset heavy property-casualty claims. But the
company reported a 7 percent increase in worldwide property
casualty premiums, to $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is so excited because it is seeing things happening
that are going to lead to better results in the future,'' Hicks
said.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks had extra spring in them, he said, because in terms
of revenue and net assets, they have been trading at extremely low
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice R. Greenberg, the chief executive of AIG, which operates
in more than 130 countries, said that in his company's domestic
business ``there is an increasingly better tone to the commercial
property-casualty market as rates continue to firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Frank, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, noted that
several of the property-casualty companies had negotiated higher
prices with customers. Frank upgraded his rating on St. Paul Cos.
from neutral to buy and increased his price targets for St. Paul as
well as AIG and Chubb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the commercial insurance market improving
virtually across the board,'' Frank said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
