<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BILLBOARDS-0729-COX     07-28 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLBOARDS-0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VETERANS' BILLBOARDS WARN RECRUITS: DON'T JOIN
 &HT;    (Photo slugged Billboards on Cox server. For questions, call
Skip Peterson, Dayton Daily News, 937-225-2230)
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Billboards urging military recruits to ``think
again'' before considering military careers has touched off a
debate among veterans over whether the signs amount to disloyalty
to the country many spent their careers defending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinking about a military career? Think again!'' warns a
billboard being distributed by the National Veterans Organization
of America of El Paso, Texas. The billboard shows the traditional
drawing of ``Uncle Sam'' above the words, ``I lied to you about
veterans' benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Even critics of the sign say they agree with the complaint
behind it _ that they were promised lifetime health care, which
Congress now refuses to fund.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the billboard crosses a line between protest and
disloyalty. Many of these veterans have contributed to a different
campaign, which distributes billboards saying simply: ``Military
Retirees Fought for Freedom. Now Congress Denies Earned Healthcare.
Call your congressman.''
</P>
<P>
   A Defense Department spokesman said Friday the department is
concerned about the impact both billboards will have on recruiting
in an already ``difficult recruiting market.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the spokesman added that the armed services appear
likely to meet their recruiting quotas this year.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the billboard war is an issue that has provoked a federal
court fight, protest rallies in several cities, a lobbying war in
Congress and growing frustration among many men and women who made
careers of military service.
</P>
<P>
   Military retirees _ and even Secretary of Defense William Cohen
_ say that decades ago recruiters routinely promised lifetime
health care at no cost in return for careers in the Army, Navy, Air
Force, Marines and Coast Guard. However, the Defense Department
contends that the promises did not amount to binding government
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, retirees are required to sign up for Tricare, the
Defense Department's health care plan for active duty dependents
and retirees, and pay a portion of the costs of their care. When
they become eligible for Medicare, they are dropped from Tricare's
roles altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep the promise'' bills have been stalled in Congress,
primarily because of opposition from Senate Republican Leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi and Senate Armed Services Committee chairman
John Warner, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our calls are running about 250-to-one in favor of these
billboards,'' said Douglas McArthur(cq), executive director of the
National Veterans Organization of America, which has distributed
the ``think again'' billboards. ``And we've had thousands of
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's billboards have spread from Texas into neighboring
states. One appeared last week in Panama City, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Navy Cmdr. Joseph Priestley of Panama City, who in May
organized a small ``muster'' of military retirees here to protest
lack of congressional action on the issue, said he contributed to
putting up the sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other sign asks people to call their congressman. That's
what we've been asking them to do for the last 18 months, and I
couldn't swear to you that a single person ever did,'' Priestley
said. ``Trent Lott is putting the screws to us and we need
something that will get results.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Floyd Felts, a retired Army sergeant major from Evans,
Ga., said the sign ``goes after recruiting, and I am not in favor
of that. Let's get after the Congress, as they can fix this. The
active military are, and will always be, our friends and
comrades-in-arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Felts and retired Air Force Major Gen. Sidney S. Novaresi of
Fair Oaks, Calif., both said they have contributed to the
``Military Retirees Legislative Fund,'' a Comanche, Okla., group
that is promoting the ``Call your congressman'' billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about this retiree health care issue,''
said Novaresi, ``because they (the Defense Department) made a liar
out of me. When I was on active duty, I called people in and
counselled them to remain in the military and I promised them
health care for life if they stayed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But urging people not to enlist is tantamount to treason,
because you are degrading the ability of the country to maintain an
adequate defense,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 members of the House of Representatives have
signed a bill to provide retirees who joined the military prior to
1956 free health care coverage under the Federal Employees Health
Benefits Plan, the plan covering civilian government employees,
retirees and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Military retirees who joined after 1956 would be allowed to
purchase health care under the federal employees plan at the same
rates as retired civilian employees.
</P>
<P>
   A companion bill, introduced by Sens. Tim Johnson, D-S.D., John
McCain, R-Ariz., and the late Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., is opposed by
Warner and Lott, who has blocked consideration by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet:
http://personal.lig.bellsouth.net/lig/f/s/fsears/billbrd.htm and
http://www.nvo.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
