<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NURSINGHOME-GRASSLEY-     07-28 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSINGHOME-GRASSLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRASSLEY SEES NEW STUDY ON NURSING HOMES, SAME 'HORROR STORIES'
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The findings are chillingly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a long time to feed these residents,'' says one
nursing home aide. ``But we don't have a long time. Often they
don't finish their meal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Baths, ice water don't get given out,'' says another nursing
assistant, adding that ``a whole lot doesn't get done.''
</P>
<P>
   A third worker says, ``Why would you want to live longer if this
is how it ends up?''
</P>
<P>
   The comments, included in a new federal study on the effects of
understaffing in the nation's nursing homes, paint a picture of
neglect that has frustrated Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa,
chairman of the Select Committee on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder if the nursing home industry and the bureaucracy of
the state and federal government will ever get it right,'' Grassley
said in an interview Friday, one day after his panel publicly
released the draft findings of the latest federal report.
</P>
<P>
   The study concludes that 54 percent of nursing homes have
staffing levels so low that residents are put in serious jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   In Grassley's view, those findings are little different from a
congressional investigation that made headlines two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as then, he said, ``Most of the problems are the lack of
elementary care in three categories: not getting enough food into
the system so there's malnutrition, not enough water, so there's
dehydration and not turning often enough, and they get bedsores.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassley, who took over the select committee on aging
chairmanship just three years ago, said he has found similar horror
stories in studies going back to the 1960s. Yet, widespread
problems continue with little attention, except when the issue
becomes an occasional political theme, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the latest report was almost forgotten, he observed.
Congress had ordered the Health and Human Services Department ten
years ago to complete a study on staffing at nursing homes by 1992.
Grassley's committee discovered in 1998 that the work had never
been done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's blame to go around,'' said Grassley, who said
Congress failed to follow up on its request, even as both the Bush
and Clinton administrations failed to act.
</P>
<P>
   Even now the report is only partially done, since it does not
yet include recommendations on whether the federal government
should set minimum staffing levels, long a controversial subject
within the nursing home industry.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said that he has not decided to push for absolute
minimums. However, he said he is determined to require some
accountability for nursing homes before Congress votes, as
expected, to increase their funding by $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the federal government pays about $39 billion for
services in the nation's 16,500 nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Grassley argued that the Clinton administration
already has the power to set staffing standards under current law.
``I think it gives them the authority to do more than they're
doing,'' Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy-Ann DeParle, head of the federal Health Care Financing
Administration, which oversees nursing homes, publicly questioned
that notion this week. She told Grassley Thursday that she would
consult with her legal counsel and get back to him.
</P>
<P>
   Whether she accepts his challenge or not, Grassley said that
more than government action is needed to deal with neglect and
abuse in nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to get fixed by regulation and by
more money and even a new ethic within the industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's going to really enhance the quality of care in
the nursing homes is when, in communities where nursing homes are
located, social-minded people who aren't even relatives of people
in the nursing homes start taking an interest'' by visiting them
and checking on conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like Hillary Clinton's philosophy about a village
raising kids,'' Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let me tell you, I sure think it takes a village to make
sure you've got quality care in nursing homes.''
</P>
<P>
   julia malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   endit
