<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 30, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   GOP-OUTLOOK-REVIEW (Philadelphia) _ There are three things you
will have to look hard for at the Republican National Convention: A
true-blue conservative icon on center stage. Any utterance of the
word ``abortion.'' The standard savaging of the opposition. It is
only fitting that Republicans are somewhat sheepish about taking on
President Clinton because their political game plan comes directly
from him. Clinton, in fact, is the model for the GOP as it tries to
refashion itself entirely. By Richard L. Berke. (Moving in `a'
category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The dirty little secret of the
``high stakes'' Camp David peace summit is that ``the brink'' was a
myth. No explosion in Israel or the Palestinian territories
occurred when the talks collapsed, nor is chaos expected any time
soon. This is because not only was ``the brink'' a myth, so were
the descriptions of what lay on the other side. It was never
failure of the summit that brought with it the risk of violence. It
was success. By Ethan Bronner. (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-INTERNET-REVIEW (Undated) _ At this summer's political
conventions, with the outcomes are preordained, the hottest
activity may be interactivity. On C-SPAN's Web site, for instance,
users will be able to click on one of several distinct video feeds
from the convention hall, or even choose to watch the action from
the vantage point of the C-SPAN control booth. Customized political
conventions are just one example of the nation's growing,
technologically-abetted, obsession with getting what you want when
you want. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASHES-TECH-REVIEW (Washington) _ Two air disasters
involving symbols of national pride _ the Concorde in 2000 and the
Hindenburg in 1937 _ are instructive about the difficulties of
predicting technological progress. It remains to be seen whether
the Concorde accident will kill the supersonic transports the way
the Hindenburg ended the promise of the dirigible. But progress _
including, perhaps, progress in safety _ has bypassed both. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   CONVICTION-REVERSALS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Newly discovered
evidence may seem like a convict's dream come true, but the reality
of American courts is that such evidence rarely makes a difference.
Once a jury has reached a verdict or a judge has ruled, lawyers
say, the odds are overwhelmingly against reopening a case, no
matter how compelling the new information might seem. By Jane
Fritsch.
</P>
<P>
   DR-LAURA-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Dr. Laura Schlessinger, the
conservative radio talk-show therapist, is a woman of a many
opinions who has spawned a virtual industry of web sites devoted to
mocking, reviling or opposing her on any number of counts. They
attack her credentials, manner and her stock phrases (`Now, go take
on the day,' `I'm my kid's mom'). Herewith a sampling of online
commentary about the good doctor.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNGADULT-BOOKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Since the 1970s, young-adult
novels have featured a parade of America's dysfunctional. And early
on, there was great hue and cry about Judy Blume's books, with
their frank discussion of sex, and Robert Cormier's books, which
dropped the happy ending. But just in the last four years,
young-adult fiction has moved into ever bleaker territory. By Tamar
Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   ATOMIC-PARTICLES-REVIEW (Undated) _ For most physicists, there
is only one answer to the question of why matter weighs anything at
all. It is called the Higgs boson, a strange and special particle
that laboratories in Europe and the United States are racing to
detect. It would be one of the most sublime discoveries in the
history of physics. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   KICK-SCOOTERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A humorous discussion of a
revival of kick scooters. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-MASSACRES-REVIEW (Undated) _ A book containing 1,756
photos and short descriptions shows the belongings of 354
unidentified bodies found near Srebrenica. Families hope it can
help them claim their loved ones' remains. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PRISON-REVIEW (London) _ A look at Northern Ireland's
notorious Maze prison, from which 88 guerrillas were recently freed
as part of the Ulster political settlement. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
