<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      07-28 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS, GRIMES FIGURE IN PATRIOTS PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ They've shared a number since camp began and
that's not the best sign for anyone trying to make a roster.
</P>
<P>
   They are listed at the same size _ 6 feet 4 inches and 300
pounds. They are in the same category _ rookie free agents looking
for jobs on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, however, they finally got numbers to call
their own.
</P>
<P>
   And one other thing: Because of injuries, they have received
much more time than might be expected _ having lined up with
starting units _ and should see a fair amount of action Monday
night in the exhibition opener against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly wearing No. 74 in the white is Adam Davis, an offensive
guard out of Oklahoma State. Davis has since been assigned No. 61.
And No. 74 in the blue, Reggie Grimes, is a defensive end from
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, while injuries have opened doors for them here,
injuries and circumstances slowed them at times in college.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was starting as a redshirt freshman when he broke his leg.
He blew his knee out late in his junior year, and last year twice
needed his knee scoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were afraid he was not going to get a chance
to play as a senior and he fought back from that, too,'' said
Richard Wilson, an offensive assistant who works with receivers at
Oklahoma State. ``He played injured and banged up a lot and what I
remember most is when he was healthy he was outstanding. It was a
lot to his credit that he played when (he was) hurt also. I think
he was banged up his whole senior year and he didn't have the
mobility he had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davis started all but one game last year.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot linebacker coach Ron Ryan _ son of Buddy _ was defensive
coordinator at Oklahoma State the last three years and passed on
word of Davis's work habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good feel for the player in terms of toughness and his
competitiveness and being the type of player we want on the
offensive line,'' coach Bill Belichick said. ``He's come in and
really worked hard. He's gotten a lot of opportunity because of the
injuries, and he's really done a good job of taking advantage of
those.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Davis was trying to fend off a fired-up Willie McGinest
near the end of the morning practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step up from what you're used to,'' Davis said. ``He
comes a lot faster than they come in college and he's a lot
stronger than they were in college. That's part of the game. He was
at my place one time when he was a rookie. Everybody's got to go
through it. I'm just trying to learn right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes was not a full-time starter at Alabama but was a valuable
and versatile backup, hurt by numbers as the Crimson Tide brought
in guys at his position who would be first- and second-round draft
picks.
</P>
<P>
   He finished strong, starting the last three games last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did an outstanding job and brought a lot of character and
leadership,'' said Alabama defensive coordinator Ellis Johnson.
``He was impressive. We're going to miss him as much as a starter.
His No. 1 strength is intelligence. He was always very consistent.
And he has good speed for a player up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes caught the eye of the Patriots when they were looking at
Cornelius Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes liked what he saw of the numbers in New England and
rejected a couple of other offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I'd be used as a camp body, so to speak,''
Grimes said. ``They have you come in and use you up and cut you. I
felt like I could really come in and compete for playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's been a great fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picks things up pretty quickly,'' Belichick said. ``He
takes coaching well. He's been improving every day . . . I think
our style of play fits him better than what they asked him to do in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, Davis and Grimes are trying to beat the odds
and make the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   And in the uniform number game?
</P>
<P>
   Grimes, a fullback in high school, wore No. 98 in college, and
for now he gets to keep No. 74.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a tight end when he got to Oklahoma State, wore No. 78.
But he's not picky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can give me No. 2 as long as I'm on the team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That was at lunch. By the 3 p.m. practice, he had on his new No.
61, the number long snapper Thad Sheldon, who was waived Friday,
had been wearing.
</P>
<P>
   No. 61 will do, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
