<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-ART-915&AMP;ADD-NY     07-28 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-915&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS OF STRONG GROWTH SEND STOCKS TUMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ECON-REPORT) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks tumbled Friday as a report of unexpectedly
strong economic growth increased the threat of another Federal
Reserve Board interest-rate rise.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index plunged 4.7 percent Friday, finishing
the week off 10.5 percent, its third-worst week ever. Its
technology stocks have been under pressure for over a week because
of concerns about weaker corporate earnings in the second half of
the year. And that concern has begun to spread, adding to the
selling pressure on Friday. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
0.7 percent Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But interest rates rose only slightly, probably because
inflation remained in check despite the strong second-quarter
growth.
</P>
<P>
   A strong economy is usually positive for stocks, because growth
is good for corporate earnings. But at a time when the United
States' central bank has pledged to slow the economy's growth to a
noninflationary pace, the 5.2 percent second-quarter surge in the
gross domestic product that the Commerce Department reported Friday
was read as a negative.
</P>
<P>
   The jolt from the report was intensified by two factors. One was
the surprise. Most economists were expecting the economy to slow to
a pace of around 3.5 percent to 4 percent, from over 5 percent in
the first quarter. ``Signs of a slowing economy are hard to find in
this latest batch of numbers,'' said Donald J. Fine, chief market
analyst at Chase Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many investors had begun to think that the Fed
might be finished with its interest-rate increases, after pushing
up its benchmark federal-funds rate six times, to 6.5 percent,
since June 1999. The chairman of the Fed, Alan Greenspan, may have
inadvertently reinforced this view when he outlined the reasons he
believed growth was slowing, when he testified before the Senate
Banking Committee July 20.
</P>
<P>
   But another rate increase is still not a certainty, some
analysts argued. This is because the data on Friday also reflected
several positive trends: a slowdown in consumer spending, contained
inflationary pressures and strong business investment that could
lead to even higher worker productivity.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the surprising increase in worker productivity in
the last several years that has allowed the economy, which is now
in its longest expansion on record, to grow briskly without a surge
in inflation. And Greenspan indicated in his recent testimony that
if these positive trends continued, a rate increase might be
avoided.
</P>
<P>
   So the path between now and the Fed's policy-making meeting Aug.
22 could be bumpy. The data for July, which will be released before
then _ including the figures for jobs, retail sales and consumer
inflation _ will likely determine what the Fed does, a point that
Greenspan made in his appearance before Congress on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the consumer looks like he is ramping up again, then that
is a threat,'' said James E. Glassman, senior U.S. economist at
Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman thinks the pace of consumer spending is slowing, in
part because higher oil and gasoline prices are cutting into income
and in part because some big companies are worried about sales
slowing in the second half of the year. But Friday's data, along
with the June jump in existing-home sales and orders for durable
goods and the July increase in consumer confidence, do give him
pause. Even so, he is still not predicting a rate increase in
August.
</P>
<P>
   William Dudley, the chief U.S. economist at Goldman, Sachs,
thinks consumer spending has not slowed significantly. Instead, he
argues that the 3 percent growth in spending in the second quarter,
down from 7.7 percent in the first quarter, was just a pause. The
key for Fed policy makers and investors, he said, ``is why did the
consumer pull back in the second quarter and will it continue.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects another interest-rate increase in August. ``This idea
that the Fed is done with tightening is premature, because the
economy has more momentum than people think,'' Dudley said.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small rally in the last minutes of trading prevented all
three major stock indexes from ending at their lows for the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 179.23 points, to 3,663.00, led
lower by Cisco Systems, JDS Uniphase and Intel. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index, which includes many of the same big
technology stocks that pulled down the Nasdaq, dropped 29.73
points, or 2.1 percent, to 1,419.89. The Dow, which has a lighter
load of technology stocks, dropped 74.96 points, to 10,511.17. The
Dow was led lower by declines in Intel, American Express and J.P.
Morgan &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, the Dow was down 2.1 percent, while the S&AMP;P was
off 4.1 percent. For the year, all three indexes are down, with the
Nasdaq off 10 percent, the Dow down 8.6 percent and the S&AMP;P
slipping 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Friday's selling, the stock of Corvis, a maker of
equipment for fiber-optic cables, more than doubled on its first
day of trading. The stock jumped 48 23/32, to 84 23/32, although
the company has yet to show any revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices and yields were little changed, as
one measure of inflation in the gross domestic price data showed
price increases falling to a rate of 2.5 percent in the second
quarter from 3.3 percent in the first. The yield on the Treasury's
10-year note rose to 6.03 percent, from 6.00 percent on Thursday.
The note's price, which moves in the opposite direction from the
yield, fell 8/32, to 103 12/32.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The confusion among investors about what the Fed might do is
understandable because the central bank's job is not just to slow
the pace of economic growth. Instead, policy-makers want to slow
growth to a noninflationary pace. But as they are trying to do
this, the acceptable noninflationary speed limit for growth is
rising because of stronger worker productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's speed limit has already jumped from around 2.5 percent
to 3.5 percent in the early 1990s to 3.5 percent to 4 percent now.
And who knows whether it will move higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are disoriented, it certainly makes sense,''
Glassman said. ``We are not used to this type of growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
