<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, July 29. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-PRIMARIES (Philadelphia) _ Aides to George W. Bush
rallied opposition Friday to scuttle a plan that would overhaul the
presidential primary schedule by stretching the calendar and
letting small states vote first. Supporters of the plan promised to
seek a vote in the rules committee of the Republican National
Convention, but because the so-called ``Delaware plan'' already
faces substantial opposition from big-state delegates, its future
looked dim. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-VI (Undated) _ Another installment in a series of
articles about the lives of the presidential candidates. This
article focuses on the personal changes that George W. Bush went
through in midlife. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT13, NYT14.
</P>
<P>
   KAN-SCHOOLS-ELECT (Undated) _ Elections for the Kansas state
school board are usually quiet, low-key affairs. But the board's
decision to delete virtually any mention of evolution from the
science curriculum has made Tuesday's Republican primaries for four
of the 10 seats the hottest political contest in the state.
Democrats are even switching parties to vote next week. One
candidate has raised $90,000, previously unheard of for a board
election. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   WASH-PA-CONGRESS (Seattle) _ A look at the two congressional
districts, one in Washington state and one in Pennsylvania, that
frequently swing back and forth between Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Jerusalem) _ President Clinton, seeking to
shore up Prime Minister Ehud Barak's shaky political base, appeared
on Israel television Friday night to heap praise on Barak,
promising rewards for peace and even hinting that he was ready to
move the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem. Such a move would be regarded
as a monumental triumph here, an achievement of Israel's cherished
dream of having Jerusalem recognized as its capital. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-PASSAGE (Tuktoyaktuk, Northwest Territories) _ For four
centuries, explorers and shipping executives have dreamed of
sending ships from Europe to Asia across the top of North America.
The quest for an Arctic shortcut consumed hundreds of lives. Even
though successful passages were finally made, the route was written
off as impractical because its labyrinthine channels seemed to be
perpetually frozen. But now, as global temperatures rise, a
Northwest Passage no longer seems like a romantic pipedream. Some
Canadians, though, are afraid it could become a nightmare. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-KENNEDY-SECURITY (New York) _ In the attempted hijacking of a
National Airlines jet at Kennedy Airport Thursday night, how did a
man with a gun manage to get past airport security? By John
Sullivan and Randy Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
