<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-SPOT/FEATURE-BUDGET-B     07-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT/FEATURE-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release SATURDAY AMs, July 29, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ (Caracas) _ Once overwhelmingly endorsed as
leader of a land he once tried to overthrow as a guerrilla leader,
Hugo Chavez will maintain power in elections _ but the thrill may
be gone for his subjects. By Richard Chacon. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Jerusalem) _ In a controversial interview aired
on national TV, President Clinton endorses the pro-Israeli position
of shifting the US Embassy to this disputed capital and warns the
Palestinians not to unilaterally declare a state. By Charles M.
Sennott. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-KENNEDY (Washington) _ US Sen Edward M. Kennedy finally
makes it clear he will support the China trade bill; vote due in
September. By Glen Johnson. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KERRY-VP (Washington) _ Right now, US Sen. John Kerry is
extremely concerned with appearances, and with good cause. The
speculation on his chances of becoming Al Gore's running mate, and
premature congratulations, follow everywhere. By Yvonne Abraham.
1800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTIONS-PARTIES (Washington) _ A South Philadelphia Italian
street festival, being hosted by the Massachusetts governor, is one
of hundreds of corporate-sponsored parties at this year's political
conventions. By Glen Johnson 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ABORTION (Philadelphia) _ Frustrated Republicans who favor
abortion rights threaten to disrupt the GOP convention with a floor
fight after a subcommittee rejects their efforts to keep the GOP
platform silent on the issue. By Michael Kranish. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-PRIMARY (Philadelphia) _ Bush team rises up to squash the
alternative primary plan, with all its ambiguities about the
primacy of the N.H. primary. By Jill Zuckman. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WALKS-AGAIN (Boston) _ Slowly John Gilpatrick walked across the
room. Confident he could make the 30-foot journey on his own, the
former college hockey player sat down next to his mother and
smiled. It has been 4 1/2 years since he suffered a spinal cord
injury that cost him the use of his legs and right arm. By Ieva
Augstums. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS-MOVIES (Boston) _ While pay rates for Teamsters
working on movies are comparable in New York and Boston, the union
in New York is far more flexible than Boston's Local 25. Teamsters
there are willing to waive a 30-mile rule, understanding that
flexibility is a key to keeping the movie business rolling in. By
Stephen Kurkjian. 800 words. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-KATHIE-LEE (Undated) _ Short of announcing that she would
divorce Frank or get an on-air sex change, there was simply no
chance that Kathie Lee Gifford's last day was going to live up to
the media hype. By Joan Anderman. 480 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TECH-IPOS (Undated) _ Much-anticipated telecom IPO, Avici
Systems, triples in its first day of trading, to $100. Another big
fiber-optic IPO, Corvis, does even better, raising more than $1
billion. By Kimberly Blanton. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Smithfield, R.I.) _ No. 74 in the white is Adam
Davis, an offensive guard out of Oklahoma State. No. 74 in the blue
_ Reggie Grimes, a defensive end out of Alabama. Coincidentally,
while injuries have opened doors for them here, injuries and
circumstances slowed them in college. By Allen Lessels. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-MLS-ALLSTAR (Columbus) _ As the MLS courts sponsors, it is
obvious that Carlos Valderrama and Mamadou Diallo are the league's
best advertising duo, a nightmare for defenders but a dream
combination for marketers. By Frank Dell'Apa. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-HNS &LR;      07-28 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEWSPAPER INDUSTRY'S NORMAL PRACTICE VALIDATED BY RULING IN
CHRONICLE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After nearly a year of close antitrust scrutiny
and allegations of anti-competitive behavior surrounding the Hearst
Corp.'s purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle, it comes to down
to this: U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker concluded that the way
the newspaper industry had handled the dissolution of joint
operating agreement between the Chronicle and the San Francisco
Examiner had been correct all along.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling found:
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers are not required to continue publishing separate
publications after dissolving agreements to share some operations.
</P>
<P>
   Parties in a joint operating agreement are free to merge as long
as one of them is failing.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in a JOA do not have to spin off assets for
purposes of establishing a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merger of Hearst and (Chronicle Publishing Co.) coupled with
the closure of The Examiner would not create a monopoly,
substantially lessen competition or unreasonably restrain trade,''
Walker concluded in his 46-page decision Thursday. Thus ends a case
with more twists and turns than San Francisco's famed Lombard
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Never before had the owners of a failing newspaper felt
compelled to give the paper to new owners with a
multimillion-dollar subsidy to run it in order to take control of
the competition.
</P>
<P>
   And never before had two companies' decision to dissolve a joint
operating agreement gone to trial, even in cases where one
newspaper was creating an apparent monopoly in acquiring the other.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's ruling is the first to deal with the issue of
dissolving a joint operating agreement. Until now, media companies
have been free from aggressive Justice Department scrutiny or
public challenge in ending such agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge clearly has interpreted the law correctly,'' said
William Dean Singleton, the chief executive of MediaNews Group
Inc., of Denver, the publisher of the Denver Post and owner of the
Alameda Newspaper Group. ``That's the way it's been interpreted for
years. I guess if there's anything good out of this, federal judges
still interpret the law. Even in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ridder, the chief executive of Knight Ridder, publisher of
the San Jose Mercury News and 30 other newspapers, said scrutiny in
the San Francisco case could be attributed to the size of the
market compared with most cities where JOAs exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if it's Knoxville, Tennessee, or Evansville, Indiana,
or some place like that, it would tend, because of the much smaller
size, to get much less scrutiny,'' Ridder said. ``I think that in a
large market, you tend to get more scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The Newspaper Preservation Act of 1970 created an exception to
federal antitrust law suspending financial competition between
newspapers when one paper suffers from dwindling readership and
revenues, to keep diverse editorial voices in the same community.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, the Chronicle and the Examiner combined business
operations, including printing, advertising and circulation, while
combining their revenue, sharing costs and splitting the remainder.
The agreement would have lapsed in 2005, but the two papers sought
to end it early. By splitting profits, the Chronicle was losing
money while the Examiner recently began earning money because the
Chronicle's news operation cost more to run than The Examiner's.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst sought to buy the Chronicle for $660 million and transfer
ownership of the Examiner to the Fang family of San Francisco,
while providing a $66 million subsidy. Clint Reilly, a former
mayoral candidate, filed suit claiming the deal would violate
antitrust laws and leave Hearst with an illegal monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The irony was not lost on some observers: The joint operating
agreement was created as an exception to federal antitrust law, a
means of suspending the natural law of competition. Yet here were
two companies trying to end that exception, and being accused of
acting anti-competitively.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper executives, analysts, observers and others around the
nation have said in recent days they view the Examiner-Chronicle
case as little more than a product of San Francisco's peculiar
politics, an amusing and entertaining diversion with little bearing
on how their businesses would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's wrong with the San Francisco litigation, it
makes no sense,'' Singleton said. ``It's a bunch of litigation
brought by people who don't understand the JOA rule, or the Justice
Department antitrust laws. I am surprised that the federal judge
didn't throw this lawsuit out on day one, because this lawsuit
assumes that eliminating editorial voice eliminates competition.
Competition was eliminated in 1965.''
</P>
<P>
   The operating agreements haven't proved to be long-term
solutions in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people's attitude is, this is something that newspapers
can do which may extend a separate editorial voice for a time,
although history has shown that it only does that for a while,''
said John Morton, an analyst and consultant on newspaper
transactions who had been retained by Hearst as a consultant in its
negotiations with the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Chronicle and Examiner, more than 20 newspapers
partnered in joint operating agreements before the passage of the
law, which were grandfathered in. Since 1970, seven more have been
added, and 14 have ended, with the invariable result that the
smaller paper died. In some cases, as in Chattanooga, the surviving
paper, the Times Free-Press, has combined news and business
operations but continues to run two separate editorial pages. In
other cases, as in Miami, one newspaper simply paid the other to
cease publication altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The notable exception is in Denver, where the E.W. Scripps Co.'s
Rocky Mountain News and Singleton's Post are proposing to enter a
joint operating agreement after decades of visceral competition.
The News declared itself a failing paper, and in its filing with
the Justice Department said it had had $123 million in operating
losses over 10 years, despite an investment of $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   But San Francisco is not the only city to draw close scrutiny in
the dissolution of its JOA. In Hawaii, the state attorney general
required the Honolulu Star-Bulletin to continue publishing and seek
a buyer, after the paper initially agreed to stop publishing in
exchange for a financial payment from the Gannett-owned Advertiser.
But the only other instance where antitrust concerns were raised
was in St. Louis in 1983, when the early termination of a JOA and
closure was suspended while the Justice Department antitrust
division required that the closing paper be shopped for 15 days. A
buyer published the paper for two years before closing it forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is going have particularly wide impact,''
said Morton, the analyst. ``It just means that if partners in a JOA
have good cause to dissolve it, because one paper has become as
serious drag on earnings, as in the past, it's going to happen. . .
. All it does is confirm that generally, when the parties don't
want to publish two newspapers anymore, they don't end up having
to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
