<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BERNIE0730-COX     07-28 2110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERNIE0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This story is embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Marcus still charming the masses with the message of Home Depot
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At a recent parking lot powwow, the buzz is building
as a throng of Home Depot employees rub elbows on the asphalt at
the corporate compound.
</P>
<P>
   Secretaries clutch the retailer's ``Homer'' mascot dolls.
Accountants and techies alike keep an eye on the empty podium.
About a thousand cubicle dwellers press closer to the makeshift
stage, their new aprons adding an orange splash to the sea of
khaki.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the crowd lets out a piercing round of whistles and
whoops, the kind you hear at ballgames, not Fortune 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the microphone is Chairman and co-founder Bernard Marcus.
Around here, he's known as Bernie, the head honcho of hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank you all for voting for me,'' jokes Marcus,
waving each hand with the victory sign. As with any Home Depot
event, the crowd kicks it off with a rousing H-O-M-E D-E-P-O-T
cheer.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Marcus, who usually rallies the troops in the
stores, has herded the support staff at headquarters for a taste of
the Home Depot gusto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to recognize all of you for the work you do, the
advertising, the behind-the-scenes roles,'' Marcus says. ``We talk
a lot about the stores, but we haven't thanked you for your role.''
</P>
<P>
   In five minutes the speech is over, and the employees start
lining up for what they were really waiting for: an autograph, a
wisecrack, a one-on-one with the guy who's helping set them up for
comfy retirement.
</P>
<P>
   People shove orange aprons, T-shirts and the company's
biography, ``Built from Scratch'' at Marcus for an autograph. One
woman presents Homer's rear end for a signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at him _ he's like a rock star,'' says Dennis Carey,
executive vice president and chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   This is classic Bernie. In recent years, Marcus, 71, and partner
Arthur Blank, 57, chief executive and president, have gotten a lot
of attention for creating a nation of do-it-yourselfers with their
incredibly successful warehouse concept. But from the start, Marcus
was the one who took the limelight with his wit and charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Blank, an accountant by training, honed the financial side of
the business (which was nearly called ``Bad Bernies Buildall'').
Marcus was the extroverted visionary who duked it out with
investment bankers and won over skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   That charisma has drawn a loyal following over the years. Much
of what he tells employees today is age-old retail wisdom _ the
customer comes first, don't point, etc. _ but he delivers it in
such a convincing way that it seems bigger than life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bernie comes around, it's like this whoosh,'' says
Cumberland store manager Steve Moody, balling his fist as if he's
grabbing something. ``Whatever he says, I want a piece of it
because it gets me in the gut.''
</P>
<P>
   Moody, a former construction worker, reaches in his apron pocket
and pulls out a cloth wheel embroidered with the company's values.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this simple: let's build some strong relationships, let's
take care of the customer, let's have an entrepreneurial spirit. .
.,'' says Moody, pointing out several other directives on the
wheel. ``If you really think about it, you do this at home. And
that's all he's asking, just be a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   As hokey as it sounds, the company's founders were determined to
build a workplace that made people feel good about their jobs after
Marcus and Blank were canned midway into their former careers.
</P>
<P>
   The pair met 26 years ago when both worked for Handy Dan
Improvement Centers, a hardware store chain in Los Angeles. They
both got fired after a run-in with their boss and decided the best
revenge was to create a bigger and better Handy Dan, picking
Atlanta as their testing ground.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus filled yellow legal pads with ideas for giant warehouse
stores while Blank tried to make the numbers work.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the duo seemed to hit one dead-end after the next,
Marcus was stubborn about certain principles. No matter how
desperate he felt, he seemed determined to stay in control. More
than that, Marcus refused to change his convictions for anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Perot included.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, founder and then-chairman of Electronic Data Systems, was
on the verge of investing $2 million in Home Depot at a point when
the founders were begging for financing to open the first stores,
Marcus says.
</P>
<P>
   The fiesty Texan nearly became the majority owner of Home Depot
_ until he clashed with Marcus. During final negotiations, Marcus
was increasingly uneasy about the ``military'' style at EDS.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus says he was bothered by the corporate uniform of white
shirts and ties, the security guards and a general battle over who
was in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Perot declined to comment, but according to Marcus' account, the
fallout came when Marcus asked to be reimbursed for a used
Cadillac, his old company car that he was going to buy from Handy
Dan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people don't drive Cadillacs,'' Marcus recalls Perot
saying. ``My guys. . .drive Chevrolets.''
</P>
<P>
   When Perot repeated it two more times, Marcus got up and walked
out on the $2 million. As Marcus saw it, if there was a conflict
over a used car, how much was in store over big business decisions?
According to Marcus, Perot was already throwing his weight around,
and Marcus didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody controls my life but me,'' he recalls thinking.
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING OPTIMISM
</P>
<P>
   Marcus showed a tenacious side early on. He grew up in a
fourth-floor tenement in a predominantly black neighborhood in
Newark, N.J., during the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   As a preteen, he became a favorite target for a group of kids in
a neighborhood gang. After getting beaten up repeatedly, Marcus
impressed the gang leader with his nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me to join,'' Marcus recalls. At 11 years old, he was
second in command of 30 hoodlums who found other boys to beat up.
``I was in charge of strategy and expansion,'' Marcus quips.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Marcus says he was learning the values of optimism
and sharing from his parents, poor Russian immigrants who met in
America. He remembers his mother taking ice cream money away from
him and giving it to charities. ``Her belief was the more you give
the more you get,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Now worth more than $3 billion in direct Home Depot holdings
alone, Marcus has given away more than $120 million to date. His
pet project is the Marcus Institute, a treatment center for
children with brain and behavioral disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus and his wife, Billi, founded the center in 1990 and
supported it with $25 million in personal donations. Marcus
recently gave another $45 million to expand and merge the center
with the Kennedy Krieger Institute, a research center in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his charities focus on children, health care, education
and Jewish causes.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Marcus has worked to strengthen economic ties to
Israel. In addition to Home Depot's commitment to work with Israeli
suppliers, Marcus has led several trade missions on behalf of
Georgia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he traveled to Israel with Gov. Roy Barnes to
recruit high-tech companies to Georgia. Marcus is also
international chairman of the Israel Democracy Institute, a
political think tank in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ALWAYS THE COMIC
</P>
<P>
   Marcus says he grew up in a fairly observant Jewish home and
went to synagogue with his father, a skilled cabinetmaker but
``terrible businessman'' who worked nonstop and still couldn't make
ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Young Marcus wanted to become a doctor but couldn't afford
medical school. Instead, he settled for pharmacy school at Rutgers
University and paid his college expenses by testing the skills that
would pay off big later in life.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, he worked as a stand-up comic in the Catskill
Mountains. And Marcus said he frequently cut classes to sell Amana
freezers to homeowners in the flatlands of central and south New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   After Rutgers, Marcus worked at drugstores and cosmetics
companies before landing at Handy Dan. At that point, Marcus had
racked up quite a bit of retail know-how but was still punching
someone else's clock.
</P>
<P>
   The man who fired Marcus at Handy Dan, Sanford Sigoloff, later
told a Bloomberg News reporter that he had no regrets. Sigoloff
said that Marcus clearly didn't fit the corporate mold and was so
self-assured that he was ``just shy of being pompous.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1970s, it was clear to Marcus that he needed to
start his own business.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH EARLY DAYS
</P>
<P>
   Through the persistence of longtime friend and investment banker
Ken Langone, Home Depot got the money to open four stores in
Atlanta in 1979, but the early days were tough. Managers used empty
boxes to make the store look packed with products because the
company couldn't afford to buy enough inventory. Marcus dispatched
his three children to hand out $1 bills in the parking lots to try
and lure people into the store.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle formed a brotherly bond between Marcus and Blank
and led to a camaraderie among employees as they continually
revamped the stores to find the right formula. Even when Home Depot
became a hit with customers, the founders encouraged employees to
keep speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   At shareholder meetings and on store tours, both men get an
earful from the rank-and-file on what's wrong at the stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie and Arthur want you to talk to them,'' says Sandy
Owenby, a store employee who has been with the company less than a
year. ``They may be worth billions, but they know you're out here
busting your butt to make money for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The pioneering spirit among employees in the early days has
evolved into a respect for what Marcus and Blank have accomplished
at Home Depot, longtime employees say. Some employee loyalty now is
tied to the prospects of early retirement. By Marcus' estimates,
the retailer has created about 2,000 millionaires, including
secretaries and store managers, through Home Depot's stock options
plan.
</P>
<P>
   THE PIED PIPER
</P>
<P>
   Keeping that gung-ho spirit alive is Marcus' priority as
chairman these days.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus handed the chief executive reins to Blank three years
ago. Since then, Marcus has concentrated on teaching training
classes.
</P>
<P>
   And he still visits stores, fielding questions and generally
hamming it up in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   He used to personally tour each Home Depot store, but that's
impossible now. With 1,000 stores today and a new one opening on
the average of every 43 hours, the only way some employees will see
Marcus is on satellite TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to touch people the way I have in the past.
There's no question about that,'' Marcus says.
</P>
<P>
   ``All store managers and every officer will get exposure to
Arthur and myself. And hopefully they'll take the things we teach
them down to every level.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus hosts interactive ``Welcome aboard'' shows to some new
stores so that employees have a chance to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one recent (broadcast) we had people from Atlanta to
California and Saskatchewan,'' Marcus says.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where they're from, employees ask him the same thing:
How is Home Depot going to maintain its ``bleeding orange'' culture
if the company plans to double in size?
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is, we will if everyone works at it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to managers and other officers to get the message
out to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie is the original Pied Piper . . . but we're too big for
any one person to carry the banner,'' says Faye Wilson, senior vice
president of value initiatives and a board member.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Blank began building up the bench of officers
at Home Depot. Although Marcus has said for years that they'd have
to carry him out before he'd retire, he recently said his focus had
changed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do whatever Arthur needs me to do, although I'm slowing down
at Home Depot and picking up my (charitable) work,'' Marcus says.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the guy best known as Bernie seems to have a
grip on a new generation of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I'm supposed to do anything for the customer, even
if it's outrageous,'' says Acworth, Ga. store manager Stephanie
Wargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a customer can't find a product, I'll go out and buy it and
bring it their house if I have to,'' says Wargo, a former social
worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of other (employees) feel the same way because Bernie is
so passionate about this place,'' she says. ``It's like he's your
dad, and you don't want to disappoint him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
