<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMAN-BOMBING-NYT &LR;      07-28 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-BOMBING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX OF THE NINE DUESSELDORF BOMB VICTIMS WERE JEWISH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The nine people injured by a bomb on Thursday in
Duesseldorf are immigrants, with six of them Jews, the police and
prosecutors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Mocken, a spokesman for state prosecutors in the
western city, said the victims had just left their daily German
class at a language school when the bomb exploded on a metal
footbridge leading to the commuter station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot exclude that somebody purposefully intended to kill
members of this group,'' Mocken said.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Otto Schily said it was reasonable to assume
that the attack had a racist motive.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent Jewish leader, Paul Spiegel, said: ``I don't want to
create any hysteria. But the fact is most of the victims were
Jewish, and it appears that they passed on the same route from
school every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Jews in Germany has been growing rapidly over the
last decade, bolstered by waves of immigrants from the former
Soviet Union drawn here by the relative ease of obtaining residence
papers and generous financial aid. The country has 85,000
registered Jews compared with 29,000 at the beginning of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   A bomb against those immigrants would be a blow to Germany's
international image and a worrying indication that the extreme
right is becoming bolder and more organized.
</P>
<P>
   But no organization, rightist or other, has claimed
responsibility for the bombing, and the police said all possible
motives _ including some sort of feud between the Russian
immigrants _ remained under examination.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women wounded, identified by the police only as
Tatyana, 26, was six months pregnant, and her unborn child was
killed when shrapnel pierced her stomach. Her condition, and that
of her 28-year-old husband, Michael, were described as critical
Friday after both underwent long operations. Two other people
remained in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants came from Russia, Ukraine and Azerbaijan, the
police said. They had been taking German lessons provided as part
of the assistance given by the state to immigrants arriving here
and were about to board a train to nearby Solingen, where five
Turkish women and girls were killed in a firebomb attack in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-immigrant violence has risen steadily in Germany during the
1990s, spurred by high unemployment, frustration among idle youths
and well-organized if marginal neo-Nazi movements.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a 39-year-old black immigrant from Mozambique was
beaten to death by neo-Nazi skinheads in the eastern town of
Dessau, and the police dismantled what they described as a highly
organized and heavily armed rightist youth group near Dresden,
finding grenades, ignition devices and parts of rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's openness to Jewish immigration is rooted in a
deep-seated political conviction that the Holocaust makes any other
policy unthinkable, but also in a calculation that such
receptiveness is generally good for Germany as it asserts its
growing economic power.
</P>
<P>
   But protracted recent negotiations over compensation for
Nazi-era slave and forced laborers revealed a growing, if still
rarely expressed, impatience with what is sometimes described as
``Jewish blackmail.'' Last October, more than 100 headstones in
Europe's largest Jewish cemetery in Berlin were smashed or
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Duesseldorf has been a major center of Jewish immigration over
the past decade. Michael Szentei-Heife, a Jewish leader there, said
6,300 Jews now lived in the area, of whom about 5,100 were Russian
emigres who arrived in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Their move to Germany stems from a decision to accept Jews from
the former Soviet Union that was made shortly after the fall of the
Berlin Wall by Helmut Kohl, then the chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   But this decision was never the subject of a parliamentary vote
or national debate, and the public view of the de facto rebuilding
of a German Jewish community all but extinguished by Hitler remains
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said this week that anti-immigrant
violence by rightist groups had reached unacceptable levels. ``We
need to make it clear that this damages our country, not only the
domestic peace but also our international image,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
