<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-GOP-TV0730-COX     07-28 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TV0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Networks convention coverage plan: less is betterBy Diane
Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As Republicans prepare to open the convention
that will nominate George W. Bush for president, the networks are
putting the finishing touches on their high-tech skyboxes.
</P>
<P>
   Above the convention floor, the temporary homes for Peter
Jennings, Dan Rather, Tom Brokaw and the rest hover above expected
hordes. But with the exception of a few hours, the skyboxes for
ABC, CBS and NBC will be dark and empty. The PBS and cable news
headquarters, however, will be abuzz.
</P>
<P>
   This year's plan for network convention coverage _ an hour or
two in prime time on each of the four nights (except NBC, which has
no coverage Monday or Tuesday) _ is not new. Gavel-to-gavel
coverage disappeared from the Big Three in the 1970s, when the
primary process sapped the suspense from the conventions. And the
networks cut back even further when CNN arrived in the '80s. Why,
the networks wondered, should we scrap our popular programming to
put on convention coverage that Americans won't watch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has different economic realities,'' says Tom Hannon,
political director for CNN, which plans to cover virtually all of
the political spectacle. ``One view is that there's a moral
responsibility to force-feed civic responsibility to the widest
possible audience. The other is there's a diversity of different
vehicles for people to follow the political campaign. As a result,
the broadcast networks no longer have a moral responsibility to
invest it with the kind of coverage they did when they were the
only game in town.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that cable executives aren't critical of the
networks for cutting back, since cable networks can actually
improve normally minuscule ratings during big events like the
conventions. The more ABC, CBS and NBC back off, the more CNN,
MSNBC and Fox News expect to gain. As long as the information can
be found somewhere, what's wrong with letting cable take over?
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks are finessing their responsibility, hiding behind
cliched excuses such as, 'Well, those Americans who are interested
can get it from PBS or CNN,' `` says Marvin Kalb, executive
director of Harvard's Shorenstein Center for Press, Politics and
Public Policy and a former CBS political reporter. ``All of those
cable stations put together wouldn't equal a quarter of what one
network does on a poor night.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalb believes the responsibility of the networks is no different
from what it was 30 or 40 years ago, when David Brinkley and Chet
Huntley manned the NBC booth from 9 a.m. until almost midnight
every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, we battled for the honor of covering them,''
Kalb says. ``It was, how much coverage can we provide, not how
little. The economics of the TV news business has changed the way
networks think of responsibility. It's no longer the public good;
it's what's good for profit and the stockholders. We all know about
competition and ratings, but the new element is this
'conglomeratization' of the industry _ NBC is owned by GE, ABC is
owned by Disney and CBS is owned by Viacom.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks, of course, defend their coverage plans, citing
lower news value and lack of viewer interest. (And past ratings
support at least half of that defense.) They say the amount of time
they're devoting to the Republicans is plenty, and viewers who want
more know where to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable is there for the (political) junkies,'' says Mark
Halperin, political director for ABC News. ``The networks allow the
candidates to communicate with larger numbers of Americans. For us,
this is a chance to give major parties the chance to convey their
ideas and give the audience a look at the people trying to become
president. Spontaneity is minimum, but the nominees are giving the
biggest speech to the biggest audience they've ever spoken to, so
it's an important rite of passage.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks routinely cite the parties' attempts to ``stage
manage'' the news as another reason for cutting back. The glossy
candidate films are rarely shown, because the networks see them as
little more than propaganda. In '96, the Republicans spoke openly
of using their convention as an ``infomercial'' to get the party's
message out, and that was off-putting to the networks. Ted Koppel
pulled out of the convention then and took ``Nightline'' back to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``With small exceptions _ like what John McCain will say in his
speech that's nice about Bush _ there's no suspense,'' says
Halperin. ``We make choices about what we think is important to
share with viewers and what should come through unfiltered.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing rankles some people more than the charge that the
gatherings of the major political parties of the most powerful
nation on Earth aren't newsworthy. Kalb calls the conventions ``a
lesson in civics, the way in which we govern ourselves.'' Others
point out that there are stories to be found; they just require
more work than pointing a camera at the podium and rewriting a
press release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't the train wreck type of story any more,'' says Jim
Lehrer, who will anchor three hours or more every night during both
political conventions. ``There aren't the big floor fights, but so
what? The conventions may be more difficult to cover now, but
perhaps it's more important that they be covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a self-fulfilling prophesy. If you say it's boring, then
nobody's interested and nobody votes. I believe people still do
care, but we've got to cover the conventions beyond the podium. We
take the position that what the parties say and stand for is news,
but we want to put every word in context. That's just good,
old-fashioned journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
