u f BC-FLIGHTSERV0729-COX     07-28 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHTSERV0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flightserv suspends operations, negotiates for funding
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Flightserv.com, the struggling Internet air service
provider, has suspended operations and cut its work force by more
than half as it seeks new financial backers.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company said Friday it is considering an offer
to form an alliance with unnamed investors who would provide $2.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would involve the acquisition of companies in related
businesses and changes in management, Flightserv said in an
announcement. The company also would issue new shares.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv President Todd Bottorff said he couldn't disclose
details of the restructuring pending negotiations with the
prospective backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current thinking is our (business) model would be adjusted
but the general direction would be the same,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv was conceived to sell individual seats on chartered
private jets through its namesake Web site.
</P>
<P>
   It targeted business travelers looking for an alternative to
airline service.
</P>
<P>
   But since the site launched in May the company averaged only one
flight a week. Bottorff said Friday that operations are suspended
pending the potential restructuring. He said the company's work
force has been pared to 10 from 24.
</P>
<P>
   Executives have blamed the problems on an original backer's
refusal to contribute the second half of an expected $10 million
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv's founder and chief executive, C. Beverly Lance, is
the son of former Carter administration budget chief Bert Lance.
</P>
<P>
   He created Flightserv out of previous businesses. Its stock rose
rapidly last fall and winter, even before a business plan was
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   After peaking at $12 on the day the Web site debuted, the share
price steadily fell to under $1. Shares gained 6 cents Friday to 88
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Bottorff said Friday that Lance is still CEO but declined
comment on whether that will change under the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
