A6066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-STOCK0729-COX     07-28 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola stock sees slow but steady' rise
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of Coca-Cola Co. closed above $62 Friday for
the first time since January.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second day of gains for the stock, which is up 9
percent since the beginning of the third quarter, or $5.19. The
stock closed at $62.63 Friday, up $2.19 on heavy volume.
</P>
<P>
   Banc of America analyst Scott Wilkins said Coke's performance is
a reflection of a ``slow but steady'' rise in investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are fewer dark clouds on Coke's horizon,'' said Wilkins.
``People have begun to focus on the numbers and are believing in
the numbers,'' he said, referring to the company's financial
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   After two consecutive money-losing quarters, Coca-Cola rebounded
to earn $926 million, or 37 cents a share, in the second quarter. A
rise in case volume, a key sales indicator of performance, was
helped by healthier economies in many parts of the world. The
results were a penny a share above Wall Street's estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins said interest in the stock could reverse if the company
``backpedals'' on its earnings forecasts, but he doesn't think that
is likely.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has said it is ``comfortable'' with full-year Wall
Street estimates of $1.44 a share, compared with 98 cents a share
last year and $1.42 in 1998. The company expects worldwide case
volume to grow 5 percent to 6 percent this year _ including brands
acquired from Cadbury Schweppes _ compared with 2 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's stock Friday also may have benefited from news that
it has signed a deal to put its vending machines in 378 buildings
owned by Equity Office Properties Trust.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year deal with the nation's largest publicly held owner
and operator of office buildings puts Coke's products within reach
of 400,000 employees who work in those buildings daily. Coca-Cola
said it plans to install 500 of the vending machines within 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   While the agreement is with Coca-Cola, the vending machines will
be provided by the company's bottlers, the largest of which is
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc. Coca-Cola Co., which has
major equity stakes in its bottlers, provides the syrup bottlers
use to make soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the company could not say how much it expects to
benefit financially from the deal, or how much it will cost the
Coke system to supply the machines.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the business generated will not be material to the
company's bottom line. The biggest benefit is expected to be
exposure for Coca-Cola's brands.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
