<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW FOR SOMETHING LIGHTER: COLLECTOR NOURISHES A FLAME FOR HIS
HOBBY 
</HEADLINE>
 LIGHTERMUSEUM KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 TIM JANICKE  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  Because I-35 is the mother road for
many of us around Kansas City, The Kansas City Star decided to
explore its length _ 1,593 miles _ this summer. Watch for the
stories in Travel each week until Sept. 3. For more pictures from
Guthrie or to read earlier stories, log on to
www.kcstar.com//fyi//fyi.htm. Look for the I-35 Odyssey icon.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next week: Finding romance at the Inn at the Park bed and
breakfast in Wichita. GUTHRIE, Okla. _ Ted Ballard claims to be a
man of few vices, save one: He collects things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never fished,'' he begins. ``I never drank. I never smoked.
I just collect things _ I just accumulate things.''
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, Ballard has amassed the world's largest collection
of lighters, which he keeps in a museum right next to the fire
station in Guthrie, a town of about 10,000 people 30 or so miles
north of Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 of his lighters _ ``mechanical pyrotechnic
apparatus'' in Ballard's parlance _ or about one-third of his
collection, are on display in at the National Lighter Museum, a
private venture operated by Ballard and his wife, Pat, since 1993.
Almost everything is for sale, but you can browse for free.
</P>
<P>
   There are Zippos, Ronsons and Dunhills, some of the favored
torches of cigarette, cigar and pipe smokers everywhere. A cheaper
collectible lighter, in mint condition, in the original box, will
bring $35 to $50 or more, Ballard says. His most valuable piece, a
wild boar tusk lighter, might be worth $20,000-$25,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard, who turns 67 today, would like to use his lighter
collection to finance his retirement. He says the collection might
bring $500,000 from the right buyer, although he'd probably settle
for half of that if the buyer would keep the museum open. The
prices of lighters, or anything, depends on timing, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is everything,'' he says. ``I had the world's largest
toy collection in 1959. That was 30 years too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Fascinated with mechanical things, Ballard repaired radios,
televisions and watches, and he was an amateur archaeologist before
he retired to the lighter museum, becoming a professional collector
and trader _ and philosopher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scientific community,'' he says, ``uses man's firemaking
capability to tell how a civilization is socially and technically
evolved, compared to others.''
Side:I-35 FILE GUTHRIE, OKLA.
</P>
<P>
   - The Lighter Side: The National Lighter Museum is at 107 S.
Second St. in Guthrie, Okla. It's open from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.
daily. Admission is free. Call (405) 282-3025.
</P>
<P>
   - Museum pieces: Guthrie sports seven museums including the
lighter museum and the National Four-String Banjo Hall of Fame
Museum. In addition, there are art galleries galore and a handful
of antique stores.
</P>
<P>
   - Fill 'er up: Motorists in Guthrie paid about $1.31 for regular
unleaded last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
