<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MISSING-LIFEGUARD-ART     07-28 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-LIFEGUARD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN SEARCHES FOR TRACE OF LIFEGUARD WHO DISAPPEARED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN, Mass. _ It is a midsummer mystery: The Case of the
Missing Lifeguard.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike a good beach read, it has no guarantee of a neat
solution. And the suffering of those who wait, pray and weep at
night is only too real.
</P>
<P>
   On June 27, 16-year-old Molly Ann Bish, a 5-foot-7-inch,
127-pound, honey-blond athlete, reported for her eighth day of work
as a lifeguard at Comins Pond, a serene pool ringed by pines, with
a water slide and a small beach. It is a popular swimming hole,
especially for young children, in this country town about 70 miles
west of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Molly's mother dropped her off as her shift began at 10 a.m.
Molly set up her things for the day: beach chair, flip-flops,
two-way radio, the lunch her mother had packed her.
</P>
<P>
   Then she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a half-hour later, the first bathers arrived and found
there was no lifeguard, though a first-aid kit lay open by the
chair. Molly has not been seen again, at least not by anyone in
this town that has just about gone wild looking.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to a local company that makes ribbons, no village
could ever have been more thoroughly trimmed in yellow _ Molly's
favorite color _ even at the very height of the Gulf War. The
ribbons adorn telephone poles, gateposts, car antennas, trees, even
the white columns of the town hall.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of townspeople have attended candle-lit vigils on the
town common, gone out to assist the professional searchers, fed to
the gills the two dozen state detectives working nonstop on the
case and kept up a steady stream of comfort calls on John and Magi
Bish, Molly's parents.
</P>
<P>
   The Bishes have also received more than 700 sympathy cards. They
said the cards help, baskets of them lying at their feet near a
shelf holding a lit candle flickering before Molly's junior prom
picture. The Bishes are also more grateful than they can say for
the police work and the town's outpouring of love, aid and food.
But as the days pass, the ordeal only gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for me at nighttime, because that's when
the fears come,'' said Magi Bish, a special-education teacher and
former stay-at-home mother to Molly and her two older siblings. ``I
do a lot of crying and use a rosary.'' Now, at the the one-month
mark, she said, the hope that Molly is still alive is flickering.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the hardest fear,'' she said, ``is if she's out there
somewhere and someone's hurting her. If she's gone to heaven, I can
make peace with it, but the fear is the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   A disappearance like Molly's is relatively unusual, say national
experts on child abductions. Of the 850,000 children who are
reported missing each year, said Jerry Nance, a case manager with
the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children, only 3
percent or 4 percent are considered ``missing and endangered,''
that is, neither runaways nor taken by a family member.
</P>
<P>
   According to Department of Justice figures, 300 children each
year are abducted by non-family members and are gone for a long
time or killed.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 4,600 abductions by non-family members nationwide are
reported to the police each year, compared with 354,000 children
taken by family members and 450,700 who run away.
</P>
<P>
   Molly's case has other unusual elements, Nance said: ``She's
older than most. It was daylight. She was at a workplace where
people would have known her. The whole window of opportunity for
the guy to have struck was very small, only 20 minutes. From the
standpoint of how the events happened, it couldn't have happened
any quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   State police refused on Thursday to discuss the investigation,
even as nearly 200 cadets from a nearby police academy set out into
the woods to practice some newly learned search techniques.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears highly unlikely Molly ran away _ a responsible
teen-ager on a welcome new job, packing nothing, leaving her shoes,
saying not a word to anybody. And police checks into sex offenders
living in the area have apparently yielded no breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bish family, there is one strong lead: a
suspicious-looking fiftyish man with a mustache whom Magi Bish had
observed sitting in a white car in the pond parking lot the day
before Molly disappeared. She fixed him with a ``What are you doing
here?'' look, she said, and eventually he drove off.
</P>
<P>
   Though sketches of the man are plastered next to posters of
Molly on store windows in the town center, ``this individual has
not been found,'' Molly's mother said. ``It would help us immensely
if he came forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bishes are trying to turn their pain into
something positive by talking about Molly, describing her goofy
charm, her honor-roll grades and her kindness to special-needs
children, and warning other parents that this could happen to them,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned that children aren't safe,'' Molly's father, a
probation officer, said. ``Now we know we have to redouble our
efforts _ everyone has to. Molly goes to work at a beach known for
its safety and ends up in harm's way _ everyone needs to be
informed about this type of situation to prevent it happening
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Molly's parents are convinced, they said, that someone lured her
into trouble by pretending to need her help. No matter how parents
teach children to be safe, her father said, they are by nature
trusting, and Molly would have responded to a call for help. There
was no sign of struggle but her parents presume some force may have
been involved.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that the abductor was a local resident who could
still be around adds a slight tinge of suspicion to the town's
striking crisis-time solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand how anyone would do something like this, so
you start looking at everyone and wondering who could it be?'' said
Marilyn Coltey, a schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   Some local parents have told Magi Bish that their children,
frightened, have been asking to share beds with each other or their
parents more than usual, and many parents seem to be heeding John
Bish's advice that they cannot be too overprotective.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter has a 2-year-old, and she won't let the kid out of
her sight now,'' said Gary Bateman, owner of the Warren Spa and
Package Store.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cards the Bish family has received are two from other
members of the saddest of fraternities: parents whose daughters
were abducted. The remains of one, a 9-year-old, turned up years
later in some woods in the Boston suburb where she disappeared; the
body of the other, a 10-year-old, turned up two months later in a
town just miles from here. Neither crime has been solved.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, Molly Bish will turn _ or would have turned _ 17.
Magi Bish is thinking about inviting some of Molly's friends over
for cake, she said, and asking them to do a good deed or act
extra-safely in Molly's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be Molly's voice until we find her, and we have to
find her,'' Magi Bish said. ``She brings joy to our house. She's
our sunshine-silly goose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
