A6136 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-REFLECTIONS-ON-KOREAN     07-28 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFLECTIONS-ON-KOREAN-SUMMIT-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COME TOGETHER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 Excerpted from KoreAm Journal  
 &HT;    ``Happy Father's Day, Dad!'' I said.
 &HT;    ``Thanks, Son.''
 &HT;    ``What time is it there in Korea?'' I asked.
 &HT;    ``Oh, about 12:30 a.m.''
 &HT;    ``Oops, sorry about that.''
 &HT;    ``That's OK,'' he said. ``Thank you for calling!''
 &HT;    ``How is it over there? Is everybody excited about the North and
South Korean Summit?''
 &HT;    ``Well, a little. But there's still a long way to go.''
 &HT;    That was the extent of my in-depth investigative journalism into
the historical meeting between the two Kims of our divided
motherland.
 &HT;    My father, who still lives in South Korea, has seen a lot.
Political posturing does not easily impress him. And though he
sounded positive about this recent turn of events, he still
remains, for the most part, largely guarded in his optimism, as do
I.
 &HT;    As it stands, South Korea is at a stage where Japan was back in
the late 1960s and early 1970s. Think about it. Rapidly growing
technological and manufacturing prowess combined with (relatively)
cheap labor have given South Korean companies the power to make
inroads into the worldwide market.
 &HT;    But it needs a boost _ a boost that can come from the North.
 &HT;    A massive infusion of super-cheap labor that, most importantly,
speaks the same language can bequeath unto South Korean companies
with existing international trade and distribution channels the
wherewithal to severely undercut its global competitors. How about
a Hyundai Tiburon for $5,000? Or a Goldstar 13-inch TV/VCR combo
set for $50?
 &HT;    Is this really big news? Or is this just a lot of hot air from
both sides of the 38th Parallel? Could this really spell the end of
tension between two forces at odds for half a century? Or are the
two Kims simply pandering to their own personal agendas?
 &HT;    Only time will tell. And only one thing is for certain: Nothing
definitive has been hammered out.
 &HT;    Oh sure, the recently signed agreement mentions the reuniting of
families separated during the war. But it doesn't mention how many
and when.
 &HT;    And if you read between the lines of the agreement, you see that
the path to reunification will not be an easy one. Both sides have
their own ideas of how North and South should become one. The
agreement essentially states that both sides agree to disagree on
that issue. It will be interesting to see how that works out. The
U.S. government has the same stance.
 &HT;    While lifting many 50-year-old economic sanctions and embargoes
against North Korea, the United States, like my father, is
tempering its enthusiasm with caution. Changing North Korea's
``rogue nation'' status to that of a ``state of concern'' is about
as far as Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was willing to go.
 &HT;    President Clinton, himself, sent the message that as long as
North Korea maintained its moratorium on its missile-testing
program, things would progress toward the positive.
 &HT;    So, is this really big news? You bet it is. Is reunification
just around the corner? No way.
 &HT;    My Korean side yearns for the two Koreas to become one and is
elated at the prospect. But the American in me is skeptical of the
show of friendship and doubtful of the Stalinist state's
intentions. So, like Dad, I too am feeling guarded enthusiasm.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (This writer, who wishes to remain anonymous, has been featured
in the Atlantic Monthly.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 KoreAm Journal 
