<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6138 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u a BC-REIGNING-JAZZ-PIANO-M     07-28 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REIGNING-JAZZ-PIANO-MEN-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND TICKLING THE IVORIES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By CALVIN WILSON  
 &HT;    Among the many charms of jazz is its questing nature. By
definition, the music is ever on a journey of discovery, with
performers taking new detours as listeners keep their ears attuned
to every turn.
 &HT;    But as in any art form, it's impossible to move ahead without
properly appreciating what's been done. And just as the recent work
of Wynton Marsalis is largely influenced by Duke Ellington, more
experimental jazz artists also have roots in the past.
 &HT;    Pianists Matthew Shipp and Andrew Hill, not only point to
predecessors who inspired them, but also continue to set standards
of their own. Frequently their music has been unencumbered by chord
changes, but so passionate are their compositions and performances
that questions of accessibility are more or less moot. Also on a
quest is keyboardist Alex Bugnon, who's back in the stores with a
new album that draws on straight-ahead influences while adhering to
his fusion agenda.
 &HT;    Shipp, 39, is a key player on the New York jazz scene and among
the more audacious artists on the music's edge. Not only has he
recorded well-regarded albums under his own name, such as The
Multiplication Table and DNA, but he has also distinguished himself
in a quartet led by saxophonist David S. Ware. His new album,
Pastoral Composure, on the Thirsty Ear label, consolidates his
position while opening up unexpected possibilities. Shipp's
accompanists on the disc are trumpeter Roy Campbell, bassist
William Parker and drummer Gerald Cleaver. While longtime fans will
relish the Pianist's anarchic imagination and exploratory way with
a melody line, they may also be surprised by two tracks that are,
for Shipp, surprisingly straight-ahead.
 &HT;    ``I'm thought of as being in the vanguard, but there are many
facets to where I've come from,'' Shipp says. ``Visions'' and
``Progression,'' the compositions in question, ``are still my
music, my language.'' The challenge in making the album was ``to
make it all work, so that it all seemed to be an outgrowth of my
musical vision and so that it all made sense within that context.''
 &HT;    Pastoral Composure is a milestone for Shipp in another way: It's
the first in a new line of jazz albums on Thirsty Ear, called The
Blue Series and to be produced by the pianist.
 &HT;    ``I couldn't really pass up the opportunity,'' said the
Wilmington, Del., native, who moved to New York in the '80s.
 &HT;    The urge to experiment, while also holding onto established
turf, is one that Alex Bugnon can probably appreciate. On ... As
Promised (Narada), the smooth-jazz favorite stays deep in the
groove, while also nodding to a bop vibe. With heavy-duty guest
stars like singer Angie Stone and saxophonist Branford Marsalis,
Bugnon maintains his reputation for reconciling jazz with funk.
 &HT;    Hill, 62, has been a jazz icon since releasing a series of
influential, classic recordings on Blue Note Records in the '60s.
Arguably, his masterpiece was Point of Departure, a 1964 album on
which he led a stellar ensemble that included saxophonists Joe
Henderson and Eric Dolphy. Blue Note recently reissued Grass Roots,
a fine recording with a hard-bop emphasis that features trumpeter
Lee Morgan and saxophonist Booker Ervin.
 &HT;    Hill's latest effort, Dusk, on the Palmetto label, proves that
the pianist's touch and talent are very much intact. Whether he's
tossing off pointillistic solos on the title track or romping
through the wildly boppish ``Ball Square,'' Hill singularly
investigates the possibilities of musical space, and pushes
harmonic and melodic limits. It doesn't hurt that the band on Dusk
_ including saxophonists Greg Tardy and Marty Ehrlich, trumpeter
Ron Horton, bassist Scott Colley and drummer Billy Drummond _ has
been Hill's working group for more than two years.
 &HT;    ``We got together and rehearsed twice a week, without any job or
money,'' the pianist says. ``Which is a rare situation for New York
City.''
 &HT;    When the combo started playing in clubs, the strong audience
response was gratifying. In fact, it reminded him of his early days
as a player in his hometown Chicago, when he served as sideman to
such luminaries as Charlie Parker and Miles Davis.
 &HT;    ``There were jazz clubs that New York musicians used to come
through,'' Hill says. ``And growing up in Chicago, you had so many
great, unknown artists that were never recorded.''
 &HT;    It was through playing alongside such masters that the pianist
found his own voice _ and his own path. Indeed, Shipp cites Hill as
one of his idols.
 &HT;    ``His Blue Note albums are a world unto themselves,'' Shipp
says. ``Modernistic and futuristic in their general thrust, but at
the same time, very rooted in the piano jazz tradition.''
 &HT;    Which also happens to be an apt description of Shipp's own
music.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Clavin Wilson is a contributing columnist to Emerge magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 EMERGE magazine 
