<HEADER>
A6147 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-NATIVE-MUSIC-GRABS-GR     07-28 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIVE-MUSIC-GRABS-GRAMMY-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIVE AMERICAN MUSIC DESERVES IT'S OWN GRAMMY CATEGORY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
 &HT;    
 By KAREN LINCOLN MICHEL  
 &HT;    My 80-year-old mother sings a song in our native language in
which she thanks Earthmaker for her life. She is a stroke victim
suffering from diabetes, heart disease and dementia, yet she looks
beyond her pain to honor the gift of life through song.
 &HT;    Dementia has robbed her of most of her memories, but she
recognizes certain songs. Among her favorite pastimes is listening
to American Indian powwow music and songs of the Native American
Church.
 &HT;    Their words often speak of simple, but potent messages. Some say
they have the power to heal. For my mother, they reconnect her to
her past.
 &HT;    In song, Mom carries on a musical tradition indigenous to this
country. The first songs heard in this part of creation were sung
by native voices like my mother's. So when the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences decided recently to add a Native
American category to the Grammy Awards lineup next year, it struck
a chord with me. Finally, our beautiful songs will receive long
overdue recognition from the mainstream.
 &HT;    There's a big glitch, though. The academy created only one
category, which is best Native American Music Album.
 &HT;    That's similar to having a single award for Latin music, which,
by the way, has grown so large that the Grammys created a spin-off
award show. The ``First Annual Latin Grammy Awards'' is slated to
take place in September with 40 award categories.
 &HT;    It's going to be extremely difficult to find the best Native
American recording when you consider the category also includes
contemporary native music, a growing genre in recent years.
 &HT;    Contemporary versus traditional poses a big dilemma. How can you
compare a political protest song sung in English to a traditional
honor song in memory of tribal warriors? It's an apples-to-oranges
comparison.
 &HT;    At the very least, the recording academy ought to offer one
award for each type of native music.
 &HT;    In its broadest terms, traditional native music falls into two
areas. There are social songs, the kind sung around the powwow drum
and hand-held drums, and spiritual music, including the songs my
mother sings.
 &HT;    Each has its own distinctive style and origin as varied as the
557 American Indian and Alaska Native tribes officially recognized
by the U.S. government.
 &HT;    The same could be said of contemporary native musicians, whose
English lyrics speak of tribal perspectives on life and world
events.
 &HT;    A spokesman for the Grammys said it's going to take time to iron
out the wrinkles. A committee of Native American music experts is
being assembled to ensure that native music is categorized
properly.
 &HT;    For instance, a recording by the blues band Indigenous would be
judged as a blues album and not under the new category. That's
because the category recognizes and celebrates the music of Native
America _ not Native American musicians who may be performing a
mainstream genre of music.
 &HT;    It's a little strange that the new award falls under the folk
music field. When I think of folk music, performers such as Woody
Guthrie and Pete Seeger come to mind.
 &HT;    I can't imagine a native performer singing the folk classic,
``This Land is Your Land.'' Well, maybe if it were called, ``This
Land is My Land, This Land's not Your Land.''
 &HT;    I would argue that native music deserves a category all its own,
based on the definition of folk music widely accepted. The
academy's Web site links to a guide that defined folk music as that
which is ``composed and performed by amateurs and passed down in an
oral tradition devoid of formal training.''
 &HT;    Most native people I know who sing traditional songs learned
from their elders and practiced their craft for years.
 &HT;    My nephews have a traditional Ho-Chunk drum group called the
Thundercloud Singers. They grew up around the drum and learned the
songs from their Ho-Chunk relatives. Some of the old-timers are no
longer with us, and I know my nephews remember them when they sing
certain songs.
 &HT;    I consider their tutelage formal training.
 &HT;    The electronic music guide goes on to say that folk music may
also be considered the rural blues of the Mississippi Delta and the
drum-heavy music of northwestern Africa, ``not to mention any other
tribal or traditional genres.''
 &HT;    And they weren't mentioned _ for the longest time.
 &HT;    But thanks to a group of Native American musicians who pushed
for the new category, tribal genres will be recognized in 2001.
 &HT;    For all the potential problems in lumping together native music
into a single category, I'm glad the Grammy Awards will recognize
our music. It's a start.
 &HT;    Maybe it will give a larger audience to the kind of beautiful
songs my mother sings.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Karen Lincoln Michel is past president of the Native American
Journalists Association.)
 &HT;    -----
 c. 2000 KAREN LINCOLN MICHEL 
