<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6149 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-IMPACT-OF-LATINO-VOTE     07-28 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPACT-OF-LATINO-VOTE-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTENING THE GOP  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES E. GARCIA  
 &HT;    The GOP is making headway with Latino voters these days. That's
undeniable. But more than a few Latino politicos will tell you this
is inherently bad.
 &HT;    If you are a ``Latino Republican,'' they say, you are a
``vendido,'' a sell out. Maybe, maybe not.
 &HT;    Those who know me count me among the crowd far to the left of
George W. Bush and company. It's a fair assessment. I'm even to the
left of Bill Clinton and company. In other words, the GOP won't be
signing me up anytime soon.
 &HT;    Having said that, I do see a silver lining in the shift of many
Latinos to the GOP's ranks.
 &HT;    Although the polls don't articulate this, I believe that if
there is such a thing as a kinder, gentler ``21st Century
Republican Party,'' as one conservative pundit recently described
it, then it's epitomized by its newest recruits _ Latinos.
 &HT;    The good news for the Latino community is that the Latinos who
are joining the GOP are having a moderating affect on the party.
When Latino Republicans say, ``George W. Bush is not Pete Wilson,''
they mean, ``Don't expect me to stick with this party if it starts
to bash immigrants.''
 &HT;    If Latino Republicans say, ``Let's give school vouchers a
chance,'' they more often than not mean, ``Let's find a way to
improve the quality of low-performing schools that aren't doing a
very good job of teaching our children what they need to know.''
 &HT;    Latino Republicans, along with suburban white women and
Independents, are putting the ``compassion'' into ``compassionate
conservatism'' _ not Bush.
 &HT;    For the past few years, the GOP has been working feverishly to
convince swing voters that they're really not that mean. Time and
again, Latino Republicans will tell you that George W. Bush is
nothing like ex-California Gov. Pete Wilson, the Genghis Khan of
the GOP's scorched-earth, anti-immigrant crusades of the 1990s.
 &HT;    True, Wilson's strategy of blaming his state's economic woes on
powerless immigrants, namely Latino immigrants, did get him
re-elected in 1994. But it also made Latinos angry.
 &HT;    And the community got angrier when Newt Gingrich and company
followed up on the Wilsonian Principle _ that is, inspire your core
constituency by demonizing the weak _ and passed a slew of
punitive, anti-immigrant and anti-poor measures in Congress. (It's
worth noting that President Clinton didn't do much to block the
Republican onslaught. He was looking to get re-elected in 1996.)
 &HT;    But the Republicans backed off as soon as they realized that an
angry Latino constituency is an active Latino constituency.
Wilson's willingness to bash Latino immigrants inspired hundreds of
thousands, perhaps millions, of Latinos to register to vote. And
vote they did _ for Democrats.
 &HT;    In 1996, more than 70 percent of Latino voters backed Clinton's
re-election. And Latinos voted again in droves for Democratic
candidates during the 1998 elections.
 &HT;    Now fast-forward to Campaign 2000: Bush and Gore are locked in a
neck-and-neck race for the presidency. Both know they'll need every
swing vote to win in November. And Latino voters are a vital part
of that equation.
 &HT;    There are other dynamics at work. Latinos of voting age have
reached critical numbers. Even a moderate election-day turnout
among Latino voters could make a difference in a close race.
Illinois and Florida quickly come to mind. There also are important
state and federal legislative races to consider.
 &HT;    For the Republicans, the good news is that the Latino community
has a burgeoning middle class whose social and cultural values are
mostly conservative.
 &HT;    But like any true hierarchy, it's the managers who make the
decisions. And without flexing their political and economic clout,
Latinos will never gain enough power in Democratic or Republican
circles to assume the powerbroker roles.
 &HT;    So, ``Latino Republicans'' can be a good thing. If nothing else,
they show the Democrats that Latino votes cannot be taken for
granted. Latino Independents or Green Party members would move the
community a step further.
 &HT;    In the end, public policy should be based on what is good for
the public at large _ all of the public. The guiding moral
principle of this nation should be people-ism, not liberalism or
conservatism.
 &HT;    If Latinos can moderate the Republican Party, humanize it, make
it truly more compassionate than it has been, then our community _
and the nation as a whole _ will be better off.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (James Garcia is editor and publisher of
www.politicomagazine.com. He welcomes questions and comments by
e-mail at politico1(AT)aol.com.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 JAMES E. GARCIA 
