<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-VOTE-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, Ext. 218.
WASHINGTON, July 28 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Military
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 91-9, a $288 billion military
spending bill. It would fund weapons systems, military health
programs and rapid deployment brigades. Supporters said it would
restore the readiness of United States armed forces. Opponents said
the legislation was bloated with wasteful provisions. A ``yes''
vote supports the spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Poverty
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday approved, 394-27, a bill to provide tax
incentives for investment in poor communities. The legislation
would support loan programs, tax relief and faith-based drug
treatment programs. Supporters said the bill would spur private
sector interest in depressed areas. Opponents criticized funding
groups based on religion, saying it would foster religious
discrimination. A ``yes'' vote supports the poverty relief bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: Vietnam
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday rejected, 91-332, a bill to limit
financial assistance to Vietnam. The legislation would overturn
President Clinton's decision to renew the country's eligibility for
American aid. Supporters of the bill called for sanctions against
the ``corrupt'' regime. Opponents said the legislation would
threaten trade relations. A ``yes'' vote supports economic
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: Seniors
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 265-159, a bill to remove taxes
on some Social Security benefits. The legislation would save
seniors $44 billion over five years. Supporters said heavily taxing
seniors was unjustifiable. Opponents said the tax repeal would help
only one in five Social Security recipients and endanger Medicare.
A ``yes'' vote supports the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
