<HEADER>
A6162 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FOODFRUITSOUPKANSAS-K     07-28 2169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUPED UP FOR SUMMER: WHETHER YOU SERVE IT FOR DESSERT _ OR
BREAKFAST _ FRUIT SOUPS ARE COOL. 
</HEADLINE>
 FRUITSOUP KANSAS -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   August is a soupy month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But relief from the humid, sticky weather is only a bowl of
chilled fruit soup away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (fruit soups) are a terrific idea,'' says executive
chef Tim Doolittle, who used to offer a melon soup with sorbet on
the Stolen Grill's menu. Unfortunately, it didn't sell well, in
part, Doolittle thinks, because it was less mainstream than the
other desserts served at the Westport restaurant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if the idea of fruit soup seems odd, simply recall the
sticky-sweet juice of a perfectly ripe peach as it dribbles down
your chin, spills through your fingers and trickles down to your
elbows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic ways to capture the essence of fruit in a
bowl. The first is to simply puree the ripest summer produce and
thicken with a little yogurt, cream or buttermilk. The other way is
to make a ``broth,'' usually a simple sugar syrup, and float sliced
fruit in it the same way vegetables bob in a chunky minestrone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most fruit soups can be made a day in advance, then served as a
starter, an intermezzo (a breather between courses) or a light
dessert. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And if you really want to be cool, ditch the Wheaties and wake
up to a bowl of fruit soup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an awesome breakfast with some granola,'' Doolittle
says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A rather lengthy restaurant-style recipe, this Asian-inspired soup
is a stunning end to any summer meal. But if the recipe calls for
more energy than you're willing to expend, skip the homemade ice
cream and the meringues (which tend to wilt in the humidity), and
serve it with store-bought sorbet and cookies instead. &QL; 
 &LR; recipe:Tropical fruit soup with coconut sherbet and coconut
meringue &QL; 
 &LR; serv:Makes 4 servings &QL; 
 &LR; ingred:Coconut sherbet: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups milk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   vanilla bean, split &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cups unsweetened dried coconut, toasted &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 egg whites, optional &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soup base: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cinnamon stick &QL;
</P>
<P>
   star anise &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 whole cloves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 black peppercorns &QL;
</P>
<P>
   vanilla bean &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 2 oranges, peeled or grated &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 pieces lemongrass, 2 inches long, sliced (use the white part
from the root end) (see note) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 thin slices fresh ginger &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dark rum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meringue: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white, at room temperature &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup unsweetened dried coconut &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fruit for soup: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 2 cups tropical fruits: any combination of peeled and
sliced pineapple, mango, papaya, kiwi, bananas; halved litchis,
sliced kumquats and strawberries; passion fruit pulp; and orange
segments &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mint, for garnish &QL; 
 &LR; tx:To make sherbet: Warm the milk and sugar. Add the vanilla bean,
salt and the toasted coconut, cover, and steep 1 hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pour the mixture into a strainer set over a bowl. Remove the
vanilla bean. Squeeze the coconut to extract all the flavor, and
discard it. Chill the strained mixture until ready to freeze. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before freezing, whip the egg whites until they stand in soft
peaks and fold them into the coconut-flavored milk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freeze in an ice cream maker according to the manufacturer's
instructions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To make soup base: Bring the water and sugar to a boil.
Meanwhile, coarsely crush the cinnamon, star anise, cloves and
black peppercorns in a mortar, or put them in a plastic bag and
crush them with a rolling pin or a hammer. Add the spices to the
boiling syrup, turn off the heat, and add the vanilla bean, orange
zest, lemongrass and ginger. Cover the pan and steep 1 hour or
more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strain the soup base and discard the flavorings. Add the rum and
chill thoroughly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To make the meringue: Preheat oven to 250 degrees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whip the egg white with the salt slowly until it is frothy, then
increase your speed, whisking until the white stands in firm but
drooping peaks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Continue to whip the whites as you sprinkle the sugar over them.
Keep whipping until all the sugar has been added and the meringue
is stiff and shiny. Fold in the coconut. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spread the coconut meringue into a very thin layer on a
parchment-lined baking sheet, ideally with an offset metal spatula.
The meringue should measure about 10 by 13 inches, spread quite
thinly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bake 10 minutes, or until deep golden brown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the meringue is cooled completely, lift it off the baking
sheet, still attached to the paper, and carefully turn it over.
Hold the sheet of meringue in place as you gently peel the
parchment from the back of the meringue. If you try to lift the
meringue away from the paper, it can break into little pieces;
instead, you must pull the paper away from the meringue. Break the
meringue into large shards and store them in an airtight container
until you assemble the dessert. (They will keep for up to a week.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the soup: Toss all the prepared fruits together in a
bowl. Taste for sweetness, and add a sprinkling of sugar if they
are too tart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Presentation: Divide the fruit into four wide soup bowls, and
ladle the chilled soup base over them. Tear some mint leaves into
tiny pieces, and scatter them over the soup. You may also serve
with a scoop of ice cream and stick a cookie in it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   /{Per serving: 740 calories (25 percent from fat), 21 grams
total fat (17 grams saturated), 33 milligrams cholesterol, 129
grams carbohydrates, 13 grams protein, 347 milligrams sodium, 3
grams dietary fiber./} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ /{Room for Dessert/} (Harper Collins) by David Lebovitz &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; recipe:Soup of red fruits &QL; 
 &LR; serv:Makes 4 to 6 servings &QL; 
 &LR; ingred:8 ounces cherries, stems and pits removed and reserved &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups strawberries, cored and halved (or quartered if very
large) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup blueberries &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raspberries &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mint leaves, for garnish &QL; 
 &LR; tx:Crack the cherry pits by smacking them lightly with a hammer or
the bottom of a saucepan; you don't need to pulverize them, just
expose their centers. Place them in a saucepan with the stems,
sugar and 1 cup water. Bring to a boil over high heat. Reduce the
heat to medium and cook 5 minutes. Remove from the heat and cool
slightly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strain out the pits and stems, return the liquid to the
saucepan, and add the cherries. Cook over medium heat until the
cherries are quite tender, 10 to 15 minutes. Cook, then chill,
either over a bowl of ice water or in the refrigerator. (You may
prepare the recipe in advance up to this point; refrigerate in a
covered container for up to a day.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place the berries in a bowl and pour the cherries and their
juices over them. Add the lemon juice, garnish with mint leaves,
and serve immediately or refrigerate for up to a day. The mixture
will become soupier the longer it sits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   /{Per serving, based on 4: 196 calories (5 percent from fat), 1
gram total fat (no saturated fat), no cholesterol, 48 grams
carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 4 milligrams sodium, 4 grams
dietary fiber./} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ /{Jean-Georges: Cooking at Home With a Four-Star Chef/}
(Broadway Books) by Jean-Georges Vongerichten and Mark Bittman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; recipe:Summer strawberry soup &QL; 
 &LR; serv:Makes 4 servings &QL; 
 &LR; ingred:1 pint (2 cups) fresh strawberries, hulled and quartered &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 cups plain low-fat yogurt or buttermilk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons orange liqueur, such as Grand Marnier or Triple Sec &QL;
</P>
<P>
   teaspoon finely grated orange zest &QL;
</P>
<P>
   teaspoon finely grated lemon zest &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely shredded fresh mint leaves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thinly sliced strawberries, for garnish &QL; 
 &LR; tx:Place the quartered strawberries, sugar and vinegar in a
blender and puree. Strain into a large mixing bowl and stir in the
yogurt, Grand Marnier and orange and lemon zests. Refrigerate until
well chilled, at least 4 hours or overnight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, stir in the mint. Ladle the soup into
chilled soup bowls and garnish with sliced strawberries. Serve at
once. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   /{Per serving: 204 calories (13 percent from fat), 3 grams total
fat (2 grams saturated), 10 milligrams cholesterol, 35 grams
carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 121 milligrams sodium, 1 gram
dietary fiber./} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ /{Nicole Routhier's Fruit Cookbook/} (Workman) by Nicole
Routhier &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; recipe:Chilled honeydew-lime soup &QL; 
 &LR; serv:Makes 4 to 6 servings &QL; 
 &LR; ingred:1 large honeydew melon (about 2 pounds), halved and seeded &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup thawed frozen limeade concentrate &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry sparkling white wine or champagne &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mint sprigs, for garnish &QL; 
 &LR; tx:With a melon baller, scoop out enough balls from the honeydew
to make 1 cup and reserve them for garnish. Peel and cut the
remaining flesh into 1-inch cubes. (There should be about 3 cups.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place the honeydew cubes and the limeade in a blender or a food
processor and puree them. Transfer to a large mixing bowl and stir
in the sparkling wine. Cover and chill at least 2 hours before
serving. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ladle the soup into chilled bowls. Garnish each serving with
honeydew balls and a mint sprig. Serve at once. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   /{Per serving, based on 4: 130 calories (none from fat), no fat,
no cholesterol, 24 grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 13
milligrams sodium, 1 gram dietary fiber./} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ /{Nicole Routhier's Fruit Cookbook/} (Workman) by Nicole
Routhier &QL; 
 &QL; 
SIDE:Cool answers to soupy questions &QL; 
 &QL; 
By JILL SILVA So when is a fruit soup /{not/} a melted sorbet? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it's been thickened. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Read on for more cool answers to soupy questions: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Slick and thick:} If your soup needs a bit more body, you can
swirl in cream, half-and-half or yogurt. But Crescent Dragonwagon,
former innkeeper at the Dairy Hollow House in Eureka Springs, Ark.,
and the author of /{Dairy Hollow House Soup &AMP; Bread/} (Workman),
prefers cornstarch, which is fat-free and gives fruit soups a
``lovely, jewellike high-gloss sheen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Method:} Combine cornstarch with a small part of the liquid
called for in a recipe (wine, juice, broth), and mush the starch
into the liquid with your fingertips until there are no lumps. The
cornstarch will settle into a paste at the bottom of the glass.
After you've brought the liquid in the recipe to a boil and back to
a simmer, pour the dissolved cornstarch mixture into the ``broth''
and whisk a few times to incorporate quickly. Stir with a spoon and
wait for it to thicken. The amount of time it takes to thicken
depends on the type of fruit used. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Thin it down:} If your fruit soup is too thick, Memphis-based
chef Raji Jallepelli, author of /{Raji Cuisine/} (HarperCollins),
suggests adding a bit of sparkle with seltzer. Or, for a kick, add
a sparkling or dessert wine, such as Sauternes, or a sweetish wine,
such as Gurwurtztraminer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Flavor boosters:} Searching for a way to pump up the flavor in
fruit soups, Chicago chef Gail Gand, co-author of /{Butter, Flour,
Sugar/} (Potter), decided she needed to find the ``dessert
equivalent of soup stock.'' She uses herbal teas such as chamomile,
jasmine, lemon verbena or rose hip, to thin fruit soups and add a
depth of flavor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Save the pits:} New York chef Jean-Georges Vongerichten, author
of /{Jean-Georges: Four-Star Cooking at Home/} (Broadway), offers
an unusual method of adding depth of flavor to his recipe for Soup
of Red Fruits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vongerichten's recipe (see accompanying story) ``begins with the
unusual step of making a `stock' from crushed cherry pits, a
worthwhile and not at all difficult exercise, which lends a
distinct bitter-almond flavor to the finished product.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Sweeten the pot:} If the fruit is too tart, Dragonwagon adds
honey, maple syrup or undiluted frozen fruit juice concentrate
instead of sugar, which can overpower the soup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Smooth move:} Dragonwagon advises using a strainer to remove
seeds or fibrous pulp for any fruit that would ``mar a smooth,
soulful texture.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Quick fix:} Sean Cummings, executive chef of the Grille on
Broadway in Kansas City, shares tips for two quick fruit soups: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To make Watermelon Soup: Puree watermelon, strain, add a bit of
lemon juice and serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To make Exotic Fruit Soup: Cut up any exotic fruit, such as
starfruit, pineapple, mango, papaya or kiwi. Fill soup bowl halfway
with the fruit, add coconut milk and garnish with fresh mint. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Embellishments:} Sorbets and sherbets make a nice, light
garnish for any fruit soup. You can even stick a biscotti, meringue
or other cookie in the ice cream. Or try bite-size poundcake
``croutons'' for a creative presentation. For an elegant dessert
presentation, add a dollop of whipped cream. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Minty fresh:} Use the most pristine mint you can find. Add a
sprig or tear small pieces and add it to the soup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {On the rocks:} The key to enjoying summer fruit soups is to
keep them cool. Float several ice cubes in the soup or pour a bit
of the soup into ice cube trays and serve instead of ice cubes,
thereby avoiding diluting the soup. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
