<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let the music play _ Napster gets a stay
 &HT;    By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO - The music will go on at Napster Inc. _ at least
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court Friday granted the online music company
a stay of an injuction that would have shut the company's popular
_and controversial _ Web site down at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   A two-judge panel ruled that Napster raised ``substantial''
questions about the merits and need for the injunction. Napster has
until Aug. 18 to file an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction was ordered earlier this week by a federal judge
in San Francisco after she found that Napster's service violated
record companies' copyrights. She ordered the company to quit
letting visitors to its site swap music files that reside on their
own computers using Napster's file-sharing programs, which Napster
claimed would cause an entire shutdown of its business. The
injunction stemmed from a suit filed by the record company
tradegroup Recording Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   As Napster's legal fight with the recording industry continues,
another online music company is making nice.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com Inc. has agreed to pay royalties and cash to settle a
copyright lawsuit filed by EMI Group in what MP3 officials
described as a sign of the online music industry's future.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the settlement were not made public, but reportedly
call for MP3.com to pay $20 million up front and royalties each
time an EMI-labeled song is downloaded from MP3.com's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``A business model where artists, copyright holders and record
companies can potentially monetize their music digitally . . . is
finally emerging,'' MP3.com Chairman Michael Robertson said in a
prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   It is the third such suit that San Diego-based MP3 has settled
since a federal judge in April ruled that the company violated
record companies' copyrights. It is still negotiating settlements
with two other record companies, Universal Music Group and Sony
Music Group.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Napster showed signs Friday of warming up
to the recording industry too.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of encouraging a boycott of music companies and retail
stores that had been urged by tens of thousands of Napster fans
around the world, the Redwood City, Calif. company asked them to do
the opposite and buy CDs _ especially those of artists who favor of
Napster's file sharing program _ during a two-day ``buy-cott'' this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The ``buy-cott'' is aimed at bolstering Napster's argument that
its service actually encourages music listeners to buy music
instead of just taking it from free from other fans through
Napster's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
