<HEADER>
A6197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ-BOS &LR;      07-28 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAVEZ FACES VOTERS UNDER A CLOUD OF DOUBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS _ He still wears his blood-red beret _ tilted slightly
to the right side _ while making an important speech. He still uses
his sing-song baritone voice to belt out damning descriptions of
the political elite he toppled 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Hugo Chavez and his Venezuela revolution have lost some
steam because the oil-based economy he promised to expand is
shrinking drastically, the crime he pledged to stop is even more
threatening than before and the corruption he pledged to eradicate
has infected his own office.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 46-year-old president _ and onetime coup plotter _
will likely retain his office after Sunday's general election, the
movement that swept him into power in 1998 appears weaker today.
There are growing frustrations among voters that he has become more
obsessed with authority than goverance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for him the first time because I really believed he
would make life better for us,'' said Migdalia Sanchez, a
29-year-old beautician. ``And I have supported him since, but I'm
not sure this time. The economy hasn't improved and my country
feels less safe now than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez put himself and every other public official up for
re-election by ramming through a revised constitution for a country
of 23 million people. And if he succeeds in the vote, he will have
more power and more time to carry out his populist agenda, backed
by a majority in congress certain to rubber stamp all of Chavez's
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel-turned-president insists on blaming the country's
entrenched ``oligarchy'' for creating its economic and social
problems. Many of Venezuela's poor _ who make up 80 percent of the
country's population _ believe him, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   But the former paratrooper who once enjoyed 90 percent approval
ratings has seen his support drop by, according to some estimates,
as much as 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The country's economy, despite skyrocketing prices for
petroleum, contracted 7 percent in 1999 and lost about 600,000
jobs. Meanwhile, crime has soared throughout the country, where
according to one study, one in 40 Venezuelans is the victim of a
violent crime. Some experts warn time is running out for Chavez to
make good on his promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won on two platforms, bringing badly needed social change
and doing it with authority and discipline,'' said Roberto
Briceno-Leon, director of the Laboratory of Social Sciences, a
leading Venezuelan think-tank. ``His support among the poor may be
about the same, but he has certainly lost in the middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   That might explain why many of the country's educated and
affluent voters have turned to one of Chavez's former military
comrades, Francisco Arias, to unseat him.
</P>
<P>
   Arias, 49, who joined Chavez in an unsuccessful coup attempt
against the elected government in 1992 and once shared his
revolutionary vision, argues for toned-down reform and more
business-friendly policies. One Venezuelan journalist referred to
the former Zulia state governor as ``Chavez lite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to call investors and tell them they are not
enemies because they have money,'' Arias told a crowd of 20,000
during his final rally on Wednesday. ``We're going to leave that
hate behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Arias's chances of beating Chavez are slim, although the
challenger predicts the race is closer than most people think.
Recent polls showed Chavez leading by 10 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Arias' challenge, if nothing else, has shown cracks in
Chavez's political armor, particularly among former supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Soliders and officers who once pledged undying loyalty to Chavez
have grumbled over new tasks such as clearing trash from city
streets and repaving roads.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chavez 1992 coup member, Andres Urdaneta, quit as chief
of the country's top police unit in February and derided as corrupt
the president's two top aides _ Foreign Minister Jose Vicente
Rangel and socialist mentor Luis Miquelena.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, government officials said they had uncovered
plans of a plot by members of Venezuela's National Guard to
assassinate the president.
</P>
<P>
   There are also unresolved issues between Washington and the US's
largest oil supplier. The biggest problem continues to be Chavez's
refusal to allow US anti-narcotics jets to fly over Venezuelan
airspace into neighboring Colombia. More recently, Venezuelan
officials have criticized a contract awarded to a Texas firm to
build a satellite base in a the Essequibo region, an area at the
heart of a border dispute with Guyana.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important challenge facing Chavez is how to take
voters' dwindling support and re-ignite the fervor they once had
for his plans. Many Venezuelans, casting ballots for the sixth time
in less than two years, say they're tired of voting and would
rather see results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget soccer or baseball. Voting is our new national sport,''
said Freddy Espinosa, 51, a truck driver who says he's sticking
with Chavez. ``To be honest, I've had enough of elections. It's
time to start seeing some benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The elections were originally scheduled for May 28 but were
postponed after problems with the vote-counting computer systems
and other irregularities. Ruben Perina, heading an Organization of
American States monitoring team, said Friday that all the problems
had been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan expert Richard Hillman, a political scientist at St.
John Fisher College in New York, urges others not to rush to judge
the Chavez presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people whose expectations have risen are now beginning to
say, `What about me?''' Hillman added. ``He still has a lot of
support, but he can't keep fighting those oligarchs. He's going to
have to start dealing with people's everyday issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1915EDT &QL; 
