<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV30-B     07-28 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIGINS OF THE TWENTY-YEAR BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 30, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the spotlight shifts to the Republican and Democratic
conventions, you can expect to hear a lot of guff about which was
better, the Eighties or the Nineties?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is neither, or so it seems to me. The decades were
two halves of an almost seamless boom, a case of success building
on the success that had its origins in a series of policy
initiatives beginning in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the tax-cutting, budget-balancing, free-trading and
other market-wise economic policies were perfect. In fact they
usually overshot. But each time the zig-zag of politics drove
policy back on the opposite tack, and with each subsequent
correction, the amplitude of the swings decreased.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been the best and longest boom in world history.
Household income has increased dramatically; so has wealth. Nor is
there reason to believe the distribution of wealth has changed very
much except at the very high end. (It's still unequal.)
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans deserve credit for blazing the ttrail. The
Democrats, at least under Bill Clinton, deserve credit for folowing
on. There is still plenty of disagreement about where to go next.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have only just begun to grope towards a consensus
about the hows and whys of the events of the last quarter century.
Many leaders of the current generation have been partisan
participants in events _ Martin Feldstein and Lawrence Lindsey for
the Republicans, Lawrence Summers and Martin Baily for the
Democrats, to name only those currently in the lists. Someone else
will have to give a persuasive accounting of developments in the
last quarter of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   From the vantage point of a newspaper desk, however, the current
stability seems to have to do with having escaped from the shadow
of events in the global economy during the 1920s and '30s.
</P>
<P>
   The Keynesian policies that dominated economics for nearly 50
years had their origins in the desperation of the Great Depression.
They were designed to prevent a recurrence of the momentous slump,
in which uemployment in the industrial democracies surged to 25
percent and remained there. They emphasized budget deficits as an
engine of growth, attached little significance to inflation, and
paid scant attention the the economic effects of taxation.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the macroeconomic dogma that has emerged since 1978
emphasizes price-level stability, lower and simpler taxes, a
balanced budget, and greater reliance on market forces than on
regulation. And, however irregularly implemented, these doctrines
have produced remarkable results.
</P>
<P>
   In America, the virtuous circle began with a series of capital
gains tax cuts in 1978. The next year President Jimmy Carter named
Paul Volcker chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, and Volcker
immediately initiated an program of very tight money. The United
States tumbled into recession.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan, rather like Franklin D. Roosevelt, was elected
president in an atmosphere of crisis. And most of what has happened
since dates from the initiatives of his first year in office _ a
sequence of events hardly less galvanizing in its day than was the
New Deal in 1933. Personal income tax rates were cut drastically,
and a program of industrial deregulation and restructuring begun.
Volcker's monetary stringency went unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   Did the vast Reagan military buildup have the effect of
bankrupting the Soviet Union? Who knows? Certainly the processes
that led to the collapse of the Soviet empire already were well
underway. The Berlin Wall fell in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no doubt, however, that the combination of tax cuts
and increased defense spending precipitated huge deficits and a
strong dollar, which threatened US industry. The Plaza agreement in
September 1985 signalled an attempt to redress international
imbalances, but the resulting strains led to the dramatic 1987
stock market break.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, who oversaw the adminstration's response to the
crash, was elected the following year. Adroit monetary policy and
the Treasury Department's ``Brady bonds'' relief program for Third
World debt put world growth back on track. When the Iraqi invasion
of Kuwait threatened price stability, Bush responded with the Gulf
War and, on its eve, some rejiggering of taxes in order to achieve
a more nearly balanced budget. It (and a stubborn challenge by H.
Ross Perot) cost him the 1992 election.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton moved towards budget balancing in early 1993,
abandoning a wacky Keynesian plan to stimulate the economy in favor
of a hefty tax hike (which repudiated the Tax Simplification Act of
1985, one of the few bipartisan successes of the '80s). The result
was the beginning of luxuriant growth. Then Clinton's health care
initiative cost the Democrats leadership of the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In the period that ensued of sharp maneuvering for advantage
between Bill Clinton and the GOP Congressional leadership, Clinton
became steward of most of the Republican agenda, its free trade
agenda in particular. The budget finally was balanced. Still more
bouyant growth was the result and, in due course, a substantial
surplus. A likely reversal of GOP dominance in the House was put in
train, with a massive redistricting due in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   With the election of 2000, another big problem of overshooting _
unacceptable political tactics _ seems likely to be brought under
control.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, with economic recovery well underway, the Democrats
campaigned against Ronald Reagan on the basis of ``the sleaze
factor'' and caractured his administration as the worst since
Harding. After his landslide re-election, Congressional Democrats
honed in on the Iran-Contra affair.
</P>
<P>
   A special counsel, Lawrence Walsh, pursued a president who
turned out to be slipping gradually into the early stages of
Alzheimer's Disease, while Republicans complained bitterly of the
``criminalization'' of ordinary political differences.
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Clinton was elected in 1992, Republicans and their
allies in the press took politics-by-investigation to new levels.
They hounded the president from the beginning of his term, first
with the various Whitewater investigations, then with impeachment
and trial over a sexual indiscretion, all the while blithely
justifying their conduct as turnabout-is-fair-play.
</P>
<P>
   Now George W. Bush has moved to quell the use of such demonizing
tactics with his selection of Dick Cheney as a running mate. Cheney
is a cautious conservative, with no taste for the wild hyperbole
that has infected Republican rhetoric in the the last 20 years. He
is no Kemp or Quayle or Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on Al Gore's choice of a vice-presidential candidate _
and the success of third party candidate Ralph Nader on the
hustings _ Cheney's presence on the Republican ticket could serve
to further sharpen voters' choice.
</P>
<P>
   Many differences remain between the parties. Many mysteries must
be resolved. But the moral for the next four years surely is steady
as she goes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
