<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RUSSIA-COSMETICS-ART-     07-28 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-COSMETICS-ART-905(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSMETICS FIND EAGER BUYERS IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ When Russia began picking apart its economy in 1992,
Oleg Nasobin spotted an opportunity. After 70 years of Soviet
deficits, his country was brimming with pent-up demand for
lipstick, face creams and body lotion. It was a business
opportunity that he could take up only by leaving.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Nasobin packed his family off to Prague, in what was
then Czechoslovakia. He was looking to build a business on safe
ground, away from the constantly shifting turf of Russia's early
days of capitalism. He also was leaving his home _ the place that
would later make him a wealthy man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left carrying two suitcases,'' said Nasobin, a 33-year-old
former peddler of ginseng. ``It was a very grim situation in Russia
in those days _ no personal prospects in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Now his company, Green Mama, is one of Russia's top five
cosmetics producers. Since starting the company in the Czech
Republic in 1996, Nasobin and his wife, Irina, have expanded sales
to 36 countries including the United States and Canada, and employ
about 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   They later moved the factory to France and two years ago began
some production in Russia. The pair hit upon a winning recipe:
homegrown extracts with a made-in-France label that increased
allure in a market still curious about foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
   Imports flooded Russia's cosmetics market after the fall of
communism in 1991. Kiosks were crammed with deodorant, face cream
and shampoo with brightly colored English labels. Local residents,
starved for foreign brands, snapped up everything from detergent to
candy bars.
</P>
<P>
   But locally produced cosmetics have made a comeback since the
country's 1998 currency devaluation. The weaker ruble drove up the
price of imports, which became too expensive for locals to afford.
Domestic car sales boomed while some foreign food and beverage
makers were pushed out of the market altogether. Advertising on
city billboards, television and radio changed from flashy foreign
images to familiar designs and scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Russian-made cosmetics are especially popular outside Moscow in
Russia's vast regions, where average salaries are much lower. Last
year, Russian-made shampoo in the regions held 39 percent of the
market, up from 17 percent in 1998, according to AC Nielsen, an
international market-research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Local face-care products _ one of Green Mama's biggest sellers _
rose to 83 percent of the market outside Moscow last year, from 68
percent the previous year, according to the researcher. Locals'
market share was lower in Moscow, where imports still dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Nasobin's treasure is face cream, body lotion and shampoo. The
plastic tubes and bottles are dotted with sketches of flowers,
plants and berries and are named Taiga Formula after the vast
forests of central and northern Siberia. Extract of sea buckthorn,
a bright yellow Siberian berry, colors a new face cream. Ribwort, a
Russian roadside weed, makes face masques green. A new line of
larch-sap lipstick has just been released.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar ingredients are appreciated by Russian buyers, who
over the past decade have had their fill of foreign-made products
that they say are packaged alluringly but do not measure up to
Russian items.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the ruble's collapse drove up prices on imports,
buyers had already begun to turn away from many foreign-made
products, seeking the comfort of familiar brands of ice cream, soap
and hand lotion. Green Mama, though made mostly in foreign
factories, plays on that nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way it smells,'' said Valentina Surkova, a
43-year-old accountant who grew up in eastern Siberia and now lives
in Moscow. ``Sea buckthorn berries _ this is my childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition is intense, as local producers scramble to find a
niche in the market space that has been created by the currency
devaluation's impact on imports. Green Mama ranks third and fourth
among local sellers of face-care and body-care products, its
biggest selling items, according to AC Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   However, sales are far below those of its biggest domestic
competitor, Kalina, a company based in the Ural mountains. Large
foreign companies _ such as Germany's Beiersdorf, maker of Nivea
cream; Procter and Gamble; and L'Oreal _ occupy about half the
market, according to the Russian Perfume and Cosmetics Association.
The association, a group of about 60 local producers, was formed
five years ago to monitor trends in Russia's cosmetics industry.
</P>
<P>
   Russian women like to preen. Beauty-care product sales this year
will exceed $3.5 billion, according to the Perfume and Cosmetics
Association. That's up from $3.2 billion last year, and it includes
sales of major foreign producers.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of fitting the image of a factory worker dressed
in a shapeless smock and head scarf, women these days meticulously
accentuate their femininity. A traveler to Moscow today would be
hard pressed to spot unlacquered fingernails or unadorned lips in a
crowd of women.
</P>
<P>
   Nasobin said he did not believe in marketing. He avoids
expensive national advertisements and gets the word out mainly
through local newspapers, radio and television. But the lack of
aggressive advertising also has helped limit Green Mama's share of
the market. Its annual sales total about $20 million, compared with
the $90 million in sales by Kalina, which also sells household
cleaning supplies produced at its factory in the Siberian city of
Omsk.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The son of a schoolteacher, Nasobin grew up in Yekaterinburg,
the town in the Ural Mountains where former President Boris Yeltsin
rose to fame. In the late 1980s he made his first forays into
capitalism in the eastern port city of Vladivostok, where he bought
Chinese ginseng from local traders. His wife and two small children
live in France, but his parents and extended family have stayed in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-foreign duality that has helped shape Nasobin's
personal story is also reflected in his attitude about the future
of his business.
</P>
<P>
   Though foreign countries helped Nasobin prosper, they also have
crimped his company's development, he said in an interview in his
central Moscow office, which is wedged between a cigarette factory
and a Soviet-era clock maker.
</P>
<P>
   Green Mama, named for a drawing Nasobin's son made of his wife
dressed to go out in green jewelry, has received unfair treatment
simply because it is Russian, Nasobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, foreign banks closed his company's accounts without
explanation after U.S. authorities began investigating charges of
Russian money-laundering through the Bank of New York, though the
company was not linked to the inquiry. As the investigation
gathered momentum, banks tightened security for Russian companies
and citizens, hampering plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought our business to its feet abroad _ if we had been
based inside Russia this whole time, we would never have been able
to do the same thing,'' he said. Still, he said, ``there's a bad
image of Russians abroad,'' adding, ``I often have to explain that
I also eat with a fork and knife.''
</P>
<P>
   He has not been able to persuade a foreign bank to give him a
loan. He skims a small amount from profit each year to help the
business grow. That makes expansion slow, though he said he would
prefer a bank loan to a partner.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Nasobin said, he plans to expand his Russian
operations, which now pump out only the simplest of products,
shampoo. The French factory is set to buy new equipment with some
of last year's savings, and the Russian factory will inherit its
used machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the Russian production will also help cut costs.
Russian workers are paid about $300 a month, while company
employees in France make an average of $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Still, business in Russia has its problems. Heavy taxes weigh on
profits, and property rights are not always protected. Nasobin is
embroiled in a struggle with local authorities in a small town near
Ryazan in central Russia over a ceramics factory he has leased. He
has structured Green Mama's Russian operations as a series of small
companies, registered separately, in order to help insulate the
business from threats of seizure in any possible property disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is finding supplies easy. Green Mama has an in-house
furniture maker and a clothing producer, and a packaging plant to
ensure supplies.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Green Mama will remain Russian with a French address,
just like Nasobin's children. But that will change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I migrated, I didn't emigrate,'' he said. ``We need to decide
where Russia should go from here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
