<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURST TIRE EYED AS POSSIBLE CAUSE OF CONCORDE CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France's Transport Minister said Friday that evidence so
far pointed to a burst tire as the root cause of the fire that
engulfed the left side of the Air France Concorde that crashed
shortly after takeoff on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, Jean-Claude Gayssot, issued a statement late
Friday that said he had just been appraised of the latest findings
by investigators looking into why the supersonic jet lost power and
slammed into a small, wooden hotel on the outskirts of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the information available at present to this body,''
Gayssot said, ``it emerges that at least one tire burst, something
that could have triggered a chain of events, damage to the plane's
structure, a fire and engine failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister's statement came shortly after investigators from
the French crash investigation agency confirmed Friday that at
least one of the tires on the left side of the plane had burst when
it was still on the runway. On Thursday, French investigators said
in a statement that pieces of tire had been found on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   But the investigators also seemed to downplay any notion that
the tire fragments had been sucked into the engines and had caused
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said that all the runway debris identified so
far came from parts of the aircraft other than the engines,
suggesting that the fire had begun elsewhere. They said they could
not yet be certain where the fire originated.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, French investigators said in a statement that the
plane had trouble with both of its engines on the left side of the
aircraft. Crew members reported to the control tower that one
engine had failed and that they could not raise the landing gear
upon takeoff. But flight recorders indicate that the a second
engine on the left side lost power briefly on takeoff. Less than a
minute later it lost power again. Then the plane, failing to gain
speed or altitude, banked sharply left and crashed.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, burst tires and wheel fragments have caused a wide
range of damage to Concordes. During one 1979 incident at Dulles
International Airport, tire debris and wheel shrapnel damaged an
engine, punctured three fuel tanks and severed several hydraulic
lines and electrical wires. A large hole was also torn in the top
wing skin.
</P>
<P>
   But in that case, the plane, leaking fuel, was able to return to
the airport and land safely.
</P>
<P>
   Experts, however, say the 1979 flight could easily have ended in
disaster. ``There is some luck involved in such things, '' said
Patrick Augin, a pilot and the vice president of France's largest
pilots' union, the SNPL. ``It did not cause a fire in 1979, but it
could have. Exactly where the holes occur can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the 1979 incident, the National Transportation Safety
Board said the Concorde's problems with burst tires were
``potentially catastrophic.'' The sleek needle-nosed Concordes are
particularly hard on landing gear. Their ``V'' shape wings produce
less lift, so the plane must fly faster on takeoff and landing
compared with other aircraft. High-speed takeoffs and landings heat
up tires.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board referred specifically to the possibility of
tire schrapnel touching off a fire or explosion.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the board praised Air France for maintaining
maximum mechanical safety and for quickly taking the measures it
recommended. It wanted pilots to keep their landing gear extended
after a blowout, partly to ensure that the damaged gear did not get
stuck once it had been retracted. But the board was also concerned
that a wheel rim or other damaged part, hot from friction with the
runway, not come near leaking, flammable fluids close to where the
wheels are stowed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, to changing the crew procedures, the airline
installed a ``flat tire detection system'' that was to inform the
crew if a blowout had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The latest information from the French ministry appears to rule
out early speculation that the accident was related to last-minute
repair work on the reverse thrusters of the plane's No. 2 engine.
The day after the plane crash, the prosecutor conducting France's
judicial inquiry into whether there is any negligence involved in
the crash, had suggested that the fire began in the No. 2 engine.
At the time, members of the technical inquiry had said such a
conclusion was premature.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators continued to examine the debris Friday,
officials also reported that the toll from the accident was higher
than previously understood. At the crash site in the working class
suburb of Gonesse, firefighters discovered another victim, bringing
the number of dead to 114 people, 100 passengers, nine crew members
and five people on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The additional victim had been in the hotel at the time of the
crash and has not been identified, the officials said. Most of the
plane's passengers were German tourists flying to New York to board
a cruise ship. The lone American on the flight was identified
Friday as Christopher Behrens, a retired sales and promotion
executive for Air France, according to the Associated Press. He
lived alone in Germany and had no children.
</P>
<P>
   Still in shock over the crash, hundreds of Gonesse residents
gathered for their own memorial ceremony, a silent march from the
town's City Hall to the singed field where Air France flight 4590
crashed, destroying the Hotelissimo.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the mayor and the manager of the hotel, many of the
mourners held a single rose and said they had come to pay their
respects to the victims. As they dropped them at the edge of the
crash site, the air was punctuated with the sound of planes passing
overhead. Gonesse is a suburb tucked between two of Paris' three
airports. Aircraft noise is routine here. But some of the marcher's
said they had suddenly become intensely aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the accident, we didn't pay attention to the planes
anymore,'' said Claude Meunier, 50, who came with his wife and son.
``But since the disaster, everyone raises his eyes every two
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Air France also held a ceremony for its own with hundreds of
employees gathering in the tree line courtyard at the company
headquarters to hear personal tributes to the plane's crew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
