</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-CONVENTIONS-STEIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH-CHENEY, ON LOCATION IN PHILADELPHIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, July 29, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By BEN STEIN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ War is the continuation of politics by other
means. Clausewitz said that. Politics is the continuation of show
business by other means. I said that, but it might just as well
have been said by Julius Caesar or Napoleon or FDR or even my
former boss, Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   You have to keep that in mind when you ponder why the GOP is
meeting in, of all places, gritty, urban, old-fashioned
Philadelphia, while the Democrats gather two weeks later in
glamorous Los Angeles, center of the universe of sybaritic
fantasy-making. (Actually, the downtown part of Los Angeles is far
grittier than downtown Philly, but just a few miles away are the
lavish palm-fringed boulevards of Beverly Hills, while just a few
miles from downtown Philadelphia is, well, not Beverly Hills, where
magic is made and dreams come true.)
</P>
<P>
   To understand why the conventions are the way they are, and why
the GOP chose Philly, we might think of the conventions as a movie.
The Democrats' movie is lush: Al Gore and Bill Clinton soar into
town on Air Force One and Two and sweep into the homes of Jeffrey
Katzenberg and Steven Spielberg in long processions of limousines,
and then the crown passes from Clinton to Gore in downtown's
Staples Center while klieg lights illuminate the liquid Southern
California sky. It's a pleasant image, and it's OK for a TV movie
of the week. But where is the drama? Where is the ``arc,'' as we
say? Gore goes from a mansion on Observatory Circle off
Massachusetts Avenue to mansions in Malibu? That's no arc.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP (I hope, I hope) has it figured out a lot better. In a
variant of ``Road Warrior'' or maybe ``Alien,'' a group of party
stalwarts from Boise and Salt Lake City and Jackson and Dallas and
Kennebunkport is dropped down in the middle of that same gritty
Philadelphia. The landscape is completely foreign.
</P>
<P>
   Little by little, savage road attackers _ ecoterrorists,
spiky-haired anarchists and anti-globalists in heavy makeup _
gobble up the delegates. But then out of nowhere, (Hey, this is
even better than ``Road Warrior''!) down sweeps Batman and Robin
(Dubya and Dick Cheney), in a giant SUV from George W.'s ranch!
Using their good character and armor against divisive political
tactics, they blow their attackers away.
</P>
<P>
   To make it better, we throw in a generous slice of ``Rocky,''
the ultimate movie of Philadelphia and redemption of the underdog.
After Dubya and Dick Cheney have frightened off the first group of
attackers, they think they are safe, and start to unwind with some
Tex-Mex food and beer. But when they leave the tavern, they're
quickly surrounded by Pat Buchanan and Ralph Nader and a howling
mob of environmental protectionist agitators.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney have to battle against unheard-of odds to get
through the mobs (think of Richard Nixon besieged in Caracas in
1958 or maybe of those little children lost in the forest in Hansel
and Gretel) to make it back to the convention, which has been moved
to the front of the Philadelphia Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   They break free of the pursuers, and then, to the soaring music
of Yale's anthem, ``The Whiffenproof Song,'' dance around and
shadow-box before they go inside to the exultation of the masses of
delegates. As an exhausted, groggy, but defiant Bush takes the
stage, he turns his head and bellows, ``Noooo inheritance tax ...''
and the GOP goes wild. (It even sounds a little like ``Yoooo,
Adrian ...'')
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you, I was a bit mystified when the party chose
Philadelphia. But now that I understand, I'm down with it. The
dramatic arc takes us right through to Inauguration Day. And think
of the sequels.
</P>
<P>
   (Ben Stein is the host of Comedy Central's ``Win Ben Stein's
Money.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
