<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6227 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-REPUBS-KIDS-EDEL     07-28 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-REPUBS-KIDS-EDELMAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIONS, NOT SLOGANS, DEMONSTRATE CONCERN FOR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, July 29, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By MARIAN WRIGHT EDELMAN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If plagiarism is the sincerest form of flattery, I
am more than happy to be flattered that the theme of the Republican
National Convention's opening night on Monday is ``Leave No Child
Behind,'' the four words that constitute the Children's Defense
Fund's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to children, no one has a monopoly on good
intentions or inspirational language. When children's needs are
elevated to the top of the national agenda for action, it doesn't
matter what party benefits, as long as children do. So I applaud
the GOP's interesting choice of words _ but only if it reflects
party principles rather than political posturing, and leads to
significant action.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows, children need urgent action from leaders of both
political parties, now more than ever. While the nation enjoys the
greatest prosperity in history, tens of millions of children are
being left behind: 13.5 million live in poverty, 12 million have no
health insurance, 5 million are home alone every day after school
lets out. And more than 4,000 each year pay the ultimate price for
adult irresponsibility; they are killed by guns.
</P>
<P>
   Millions more receive substandard education in crumbling schools
without enough books, equipment or teachers. Or they are eligible
for Head Start or child care assistance when parents work but
receive neither. Or they are abused or neglected, or are
languishing in temporary foster homes, waiting for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas speaks often of the need to leave
no child behind as he discusses his state's laudable educational
progress. Yet a disproportionately high number of children are left
behind in his state. Texas was one of the last states to carry out
the Children's Health Insurance Program and has the highest
percentage of children without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   It ranks 48th in child immunizations and 45th in early prenatal
care. It is fifth-highest in numbers of children living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   As president, what would George W. Bush do differently? Would he
take his cues from some fellow Republican governors, like John
Rowland of Connecticut or George Pataki of New York, who have shown
real leadership in helping children get a healthy start?
</P>
<P>
   It is not only morally wrong but economically foolish to allow
one in five American children to live in poverty. How would we feel
about a family that kept four of its five children well fed, well
clothed and well educated, but let the fifth go hungry and without
health care or good preparation for the future? The acid test for
parties or politicians claiming the mantle of ``Leave No Child
Behind'' is what they will actually do.
</P>
<P>
   What will candidates do to expand the earned-income tax credit
for poor working families and raise the minimum wage; to ensure
that health care is a birthright; and to provide programs like Head
Start and good child care so that every child is ready to learn in
school?
</P>
<P>
   What will they do to provide safe after-school and summer
programs as alternatives to the streets? What will they do to raise
educational standards and accountability? How will they protect
children from guns and from violence in entertainment and on the
Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A fair and compassionate nation should be able to work across
party and ideological lines on behalf of children. ``Leave No Child
Behind'' should be more than the theme for an evening at a
convention or even a trademark for an organization.
</P>
<P>
   (Marian Wright Edelman is founder and president of the
Children's Defense Fund Action Council.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
