<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-IPOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH IPOS BLAST OFF TO FINANCIAL STRATOSPHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Avici Systems Inc. was flying so high Friday that even a sinking
Nasdaq Composite index couldn't drag it down.
</P>
<P>
   In a dazzling trading debut on Wall Street, Avici Systems'
initial public offering of shares tripled in value Friday. After
selling to investors at an initial price of $31 a share, Avici
closed at $96.75 a share at the end of a day of trading in which
the stock flirted with $102 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The North Billerica, Mass. company's rise was extraordinary amid
a tumbling Nasdaq and a dramatic statement of just how hot the
fiber-optic networking business in which Avici competes has become,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq fell Friday by 4.7 percent, to 3663.00, in a third
down day for the volatile index of technology stocks. Nasdaq has
dropped 9 percent since midweek amid concerns about high-tech
company sales and profits and uncertainty about whether the economy
has slowed to a sustainable pace.
</P>
<P>
   Avici, a maker of 7-foot-tall boxes that route Internet traffic,
was a standout performer among the 10 initial public offerings that
hit Wall Street Friday, the biggest IPO day in the stock market
since last October.
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet IPO, Corvis Corp. of Columbia, Md., also had a
stellar rise, to $83.7187 a share. Corvis, which is involved in
sending signals across optic networks, rose as high as $98 a share
during the day, after being priced by underwriters at $36.
</P>
<P>
   Corvis's ability to raise so much money, $1.14 billion,
surprised analysts, who said it was a record amount for a start-up
company that has yet to show any revenue. At its peak, Corvis had a
market value of more than $30 billion, also a record for a
technology start-up, according to the company's banker, Credit
Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Avici, by comparison, raised $217 million in its 7 million-share
IPO after twice boosting the sale to meet robust demand.
</P>
<P>
   Avici had $2.2 million in sales in the second quarter. Avici and
Corvis are benefiting from a surge in demand for the equipment used
in fiber-optic networking systems, as Internet use is exploding and
is expected to surpass voice traffic soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything in the networking world, the optical networking world
especially these days, is just blistering hot,'' said Bob Whelan,
an investment banker for the Prudential Volpe Technology Group in
Boston. ``A lot of big companies want to acquire these things,
either before or after they go public, at huge valuations.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Avici's biggest single investor is Nortel Networks,
according to Avici financial documents provided with the stock
offering. Nortel owns about 6.45 million shares of Avici's
outstanding stock, and, based on Friday's closing price, Nortel's
holding was valued at $623.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   There are no guarantees for investors that their shares will
hold their value in a weakening Nasdaq. Yet, investors continue to
gamble on stocks that they believe will be the winners in the
future of Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the networking world, people want to find the next Cisco
Systems, and they're hoping this (Avici) might be it,'' said
Katherine Kirk, managing director for Chase H&AMP;Q in Boston. Kirk
said Avici's stellar performance reflects investor demand for a
relatively small number of shares available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike software companies, which typically seek to find
incremental improvements over competitors' products, firms involved
in developing the technology that makes the Internet network run
tend to leapfrog to a new level of innovation that can leave
competitors far behind. This makes the race for the winning
equipment particularly fast-paced and at times brutal, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Avici makes high-capacity, high-speed systems that route huge
volumes of traffic over the Internet. Although still losing money,
according to public financial documents, the company is touting its
technology as next-generation equipment that can move high volumes
of information through fiber optic networks. Avici's competitors
include Cisco, as well as Juniper Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If Avici's shares stay at current high levels, executives and
venture capitalists involved in the start-up will make a lot of
money.
</P>
<P>
   Avici's 41-year-old chief executive, Surya Panditi, who had
formerly been employed by US Robotics and Telco Systems Inc., owns
2.4 percent of the company's stock outstanding, or about 1.1
million shares, according to the filings. Panditi's shares were
worth $107 million Friday. An Avici cofounder, Henry Zannini, owns
690,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sale of 7 million shares Friday brings to 46.037
million the total number of Avici shares outstanding. The initial
39 million shares, held by a small group of investors, are locked
up for a period of 180 days before they can be traded publicly,
documents said.
</P>
<P>
   Three venture-capital firms also hold large stakes in Avici:
Accel Partners of Palo Alto, Calif., about 4.88 million shares;
Brentwood Venture Capital of Los Angeles, 3.82 million; and Oak
Investment Partners of Westport, Conn., 3.82 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
