<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-ALLSTAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDERRAMA, DIALLO TOP MLS'S MARKETING GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Carlos Valderrama and Mamadou Diallo might be
the most pure marriage of midfield and striker in the five-year
history of Major League Soccer. Valderrama is the provider, the
cleverest passer in the league, and Diallo the speedy, strong
finisher who has scored 18 goals for Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   And, as MLS spends its All-Star weekend courting sponsors, it is
becoming obvious that Valderrama and Diallo are the league's best
advertising duo, a nightmare for defenders but a dream combination
for marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Valderrama was 33 when he was signed to a 10-year personal
services contract by the league in 1996, one of its first long-term
investments. He remains effective at 38, distinguished by his
frizzed-out orange hair and staccato one- and two-touch passing,
content with a peaceful existence in Florida, far from the chaos of
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, 28, was a bargain for a league based on bargain-basement
dealing. MLS paid $250,000 to Diallo's Norwegian club and gained
one of its most prolific scorers and most visible stars. Diallo, 6
foot 3, wearing white shoes and close-cropped hair dyed orange to
match his partner, is also living the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of playing professional soccer, you think of
Europe,'' Diallo said Friday. ``I thought of America as more of a
basketball country, so I never thought of coming here. But when I
found out about playing soccer in America it became a dream. At the
beginning it was very hard, but once I got into the starting lineup
I thought I could be the top scorer and the top player in the
league. I have many great players to give me passes to score and I
have Carlos for motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   As in any successful marriage, there is conflict, tension,
resolution. During a Mutiny game last month, Diallo and Valderrama
were filmed shoving index fingers into each other's chests.
Apparently, they came to an understanding, through a combination of
two universal languages _ soccer and French. Valderrama learned the
language in the early '90s while playing for Montpellier, and
Diallo spoke French in his native Dakar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos does not talk too much but I understand him very
well,'' Diallo said. ``He does not like it if he gives you a pass
and you miss the goal. And if you score one goal he wants you to
score two, and if you score two goals he wants you to score three.
He is always saying we are not finished, try to score again.''
</P>
<P>
   Valderrama's encores and sacre bleus have helped make Diallo
probably the league's most valuable player. Clubs such as Blackburn
Rovers (England) and Metz (France) have inquired but no ``official
approaches'' have been made, according to MLS vice president Ivan
Gazidis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone might offer $1 million for him, or they might want him
on loan,'' said Patrick McCabe, who represents Diallo for Bob Wolff
Associates of Boston. ``Mamadou is happy in Tampa and he would like
to stay, but if the offer is good enough he will have to look at it
closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Diallo is the most successful of several players McCabe has
proposed to the league. In fact, he offered Diallo to the
Revolution in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed him by one day,'' Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo
said. ``At the time, we had Wolde Harris and Eduardo Hurtado, but I
had a feeling Hurtado might not work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutiny coach Tim Hankinson acted quickly after pursuing several
other African strikers. His first choice was Siyabonga Nomvete, a
22-year-old South African with Kaizer Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomvete would have been the most explosive player in the MLS
as far as pace,'' Hankinson said. ``He's young and he would have
been a good investment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kaizer Chiefs raised the price on Nomvete and are now
apparently hoping to inflate it further after the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``African players have, a lot of times, not been put in the
right situations in the league,'' Hankinson said. ``A good example
is Doctor Khumalo in Columbus. We wanted someone with breakaway
speed, because Carlos is great at splitting the defense and leading
the forward to goal. We thought that Mamadou would provide
breakaway speed. And, even while he was getting adjusted he would
be effective because he is such a presence athletically that he
takes two defenders with him wherever he goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a risk. But it's like the stock market _ the greatest
risk can provide the greatest reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Places like Senegal, and even Colombia, are soccer's potentially
volatile equivalent of the NASDAQ. And Diallo's success is tempting
others to take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am organizing a trip to Senegal for coaches in January,''
McCabe said. ``I believe there is enough interest now and it would
definitely be worthwhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
