<HEADER>
A6268 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      07-28 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WARNS PALESTINIANS ABOUT ABANDONING PEACE PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In an unusual and controversial interview aired on
national television here Friday night, President Clinton sternly
warned the Palestinians against declaring a state and suggested
support for the pro-Israeli position of moving the US Embassy from
Tel Aviv to the disputed city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there should not be a unilateral declaration. And
if there is, our entire relationship will be reviewed. I think it
would be a big mistake to ... walk away from the peace process,''
Clinton told Israel Television's Channel One.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-hour interview, Clinton vowed to strengthen strategic
and diplomatic ties with Israel following the failure of the 15-day
Camp David peace summit. He also praised Prime Minister Ehud Barak
for being ``more courageous and more creative'' than Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   The comments were greeted warmly by Israeli leaders and
commentators. But even they saw them as a calculated effort to help
Barak survive a pending no-confidence vote set for Monday in
Israel's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Barak may need all the help he can get.
</P>
<P>
   His One Israel coalition government collapsed hours before he
left for Camp David when the conservative, religious flank deserted
him. It feared that Barak had failed to build a consensus on his
peace initiative, and said he was going too far in offering
concessions on Jerusalem and final borders in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's public statements on Jerusalem and on the Palestinian
desire to declare a state have angered Palestinian leaders. They
have expressed admiration for Clinton's tireless efforts at the
summit, but are accusing him of failing to be an even-handed broker
for peace.
</P>
<P>
   They openly wondered what impact the comments might have on
renewed Israeli-Palestinian talks, scheduled to resume Sunday. ``It
is very easy to blame the Palestinians and you don't pay a price,''
said Palestinian parliamentarian, Hanan Ashrawi, a spokeswoman for
Arafat at Camp David. ``There is no strategic aliance betwwen
Palestine and the US, but there is a strategic alliance between
Israel and the US.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that Clinton's shift to a pro-Israeli stance _ just as
the negotiations have reached perhaps their most fragile moment in
seven years _ reflected domestic political concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an election year in the US. I am being very cynical,
but it is true. These are the motivations,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's stated intention to declare a Palestinian state on
September 13, the deadline for a final agreement, has set a clock
ticking. Some fear violence if the two sides fail to reach an
accord that clearly spells out an end to the 52-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Ashrawi accused Clinton and the Western media of painting Arafat
as intransigent while failing to see the significant concessions he
has already made in backing down on claims to land taken by Israel
in 1948, including huge tracts of west Jerusalem neighborhoods that
were once Arab.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereignty over Jerusalem is the crucial issue in the
negotiations. Israel declares Jerusalem as its ``eternal and
indivisible'' capital. The Palestinians insist East Jerusalem,
captured by Israel in 1967, must be the Palestinian capital.
</P>
<P>
   The United States does not recognize Israel's annexation of Arab
East Jerusalem and has located its embassy in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   The US Congress passed a bill in 1995 aimed at moving the US
Embassy to Jerusalem, but Clinton has repeatedly made use of an
escape clause in the bill to postpone the move indefinitely on the
grounds of national security.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, however, he suggested a more flexible position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always wanted to move our embassy to West Jerusalem. We
have a designated site there,'' Clinton said, explaining that he
had not taken action before because he did not want to undermine
Washington's ability to be ``an honest broker'' in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in light of what has happened (at Camp David), I've taken
that decision under review and I'll make a decision some time
between now and the end of the year on that,'' said Clinton, whose
eight years in office will end in January.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's consideration of shifting the US embassy to west
Jerusalem has stirred trouble among the negotiators trying to solve
sovereignty of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Jones, a political scientist emeritus at the University
of Wisconsin and an expert on the Clinton presidency, criticized
the president's decision to grant the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said it would almost certainly compromise the president's
role as a tireless and fair negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary way to deliver a message at a time of
very high drama. Thinking from a human aspect, he (Clinton) may
well just be very piqued,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He laid his prestige on the line, and in his mind it was the
intransigence of Arafat (that stymied the talks). That is a
perfectly human reaction, but not the kind of reaction that
presidents, as diplomats, can afford to have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this article.
</P>
</TEXT>
