<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6280 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GOP-CONVENTION-ADV30-     07-28 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-ADV30-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV30 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: Embargoed against use before Sunday, July 30.)  
 Republicans Striving for Kinder, Gentler Convention   
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
FRIDAY, July 28, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By BILL WALSH  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrew Card was at the Republican National Convention in Houston
the night in 1992 when sharp-tongued conservative commentator Pat
Buchanan took the podium and warned that a ``religious war ... a
cultural war'' was being fought over the soul of America.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was a hit inside the convention hall, but Card feared
that it left viewers at home feeling uneasy, maybe even a bit
scared, about the Republican Party's message, as well as its
messengers.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years -- and two Democratic administrations -- later, Card
is the chief planner for the 2000 Republican convention, which
starts Monday in Philadelphia, and the message he hopes to project
this time is quite different.
</P>
<P>
   If everything goes according to Card's carefully scripted plan,
which is by no means a certainty with street protests expected and
roiling discontent inside the GOP over abortion, viewers will be
left feeling warm, fuzzy and, above all, welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This convention is more about the word `together' than it is
about `divide,''' Card said in an interview. ``Just as Gov. Bush
has done, we're reaching out beyond those who call themselves
Republicans. This convention is about a new kind of Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to entice independents and moderate Democrats into the
fold, planners hope to portray a Republican Party that people may
not recognize. The most visible sign of change will be at the
podium, which will feature a steady stream of African-American and
Hispanic speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent slots will be filled by longtime GOP stars like former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Colin Powell and Bush's
foreign policy adviser Condoleeza Rice. The minority roster also
features a Hispanic securities broker from Los Angeles who will
talk about economic opportunity and an African-American literacy
expert.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself is expected in his acceptance speech Thursday to
acknowledge that his party has been less than a friendly haven for
minorities in the recent past. He has hit on the theme several
times while campaigning before African-American audiences and it
has been well-received.
</P>
<P>
   Just as convention planners are trying to change the face of the
party, so too are they sending notice that they care about more
than traditional Republican issues like tax cuts and a strong
national defense. In fact, those who tune in to the first day of
the convention may wonder whether a renegade Democrat has somehow
gotten hold of the schedule of events. That day will be dedicated
entirely to education and health care, the meat and potatoes of
Democratic politics for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   As the convention progresses, more traditional GOP themes will
take center stage. Days two and three of the convention will focus
on economic prosperity, national defense and tax relief, issues
that have always been near and dear to the hearts of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the GOP convention is designed to be the
anti-convention, or at least appear that way on television.
Planners have scrapped the typical castle-turret design for the
speakers' platform and have replaced it with what will look to
viewers like a theater stage, which will morph daily into a
colorful backdrop designed to illustrate that day's chosen theme.
On day one, when speakers talk about education, they will stand in
front of a faux-classroom outfitted with desks, a blackboard and
students.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the speakers' lineup will feature ``everyday people''
rather than party poobahs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going after day-to-day people who have a story to
tell,'' said Pat Brister, the Louisiana delegation chair who is
also in charge of making sure everyone makes their on-stage cues.
</P>
<P>
   Those stories will be of the up-by-the-bootstraps variety
underscoring, in a subtle and non-threatening way, the Republicans'
message of self-reliance. Among the speakers will be a breast
cancer survivor, a blind mountain climber and a Chinese emigre who
came to the United States knowing no English and rose to become
head of the Peace Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Even the convention's theme -- ``Renewing America's Purpose.
Together'' -- is designed to sound more like a friendly invitation
than a rousing call to action.
</P>
<P>
   In still other ways, the tone of the proceedings is designed to
be reassuring and pleasant. Planners have axed from the program the
night usually dedicated to attacking the opposition. In
Philadelphia, sneering, sarcastic attacks on Democrats will be
frowned on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a totally positive, totally unifying
atmosphere,'' Brister said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The GOP will have less control over events outside the
convention hall. Across the street from the First Union Center, the
sports arena that will house the Republican gathering, protesters
are expected to do everything they can to get the attention of the
15,000 credentialed media representatives covering the convention.
Some of the protesters who carried the word of anti-globalization
to Seattle last year to disrupt the World Trade Organization
meeting are expected to show up in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a group working on behalf of death row inmate Mumia
Abu-Jamal is expected to be out in force to protest what they say
is a frame-up for the killing of a white Philadelphia police
officer in 1981. The protest will no doubt be fueled by a recent
suspect's beating at the hands of city police, which was caught on
videotape and broadcast worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Another wild card for convention planners is Sen. John McCain,
the upstart Arizona Republican who was Bush's closest rival for the
nomination. Although McCain has endorsed Bush, convention planners
are concerned that his speech on Tuesday could trigger a
spontaneous rally on the floor and draw attention away from the
presumptive nominee. Partly to address that fear, McCain has been
instructed to talk about national security rather his signature
issue, campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their best efforts to diffuse potential disputes in
advance of the convention, Republican leaders may have an internal
squabble on their hands. A group called the Republican Pro-Choice
Coalition says it will try to convince the party to drop the strict
pro-life plank from the platform.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cullman, one of the coalition's leaders, said no
demonstrations are planned, but the group does intend to try to get
the microphone on the convention floor, a feat that will take the
support of at least six state delegations. She said she has been
frustrated up until now by what she sees as the GOP's intransigence
on this issue above all others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been more civility toward us than in the past, but
when people are nice to you and say to you that you won't get your
way, you have to do what you have to do,'' Cullman said.
</P>
<P>
   One group that the GOP may not have to worry about,
surprisingly, is the conservative wing of the party whose
Buchanan-like stridency in the past has made reaching out to a
broader segment of supporters difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Schlafly of the conservative Eagle Forum, who rather
enjoyed Buchanan's controversial speech in 1992, proclaimed herself
in a recent interview to be satisfied with the format and content
of this year's convention.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hoped that planners allowed delegates to roam the
aisles and hold up signs, unlike at the 1996 convention in San
Diego. As for the direction of the party and the message convention
planners are trying to send in Philadelphia, Schlafly said she had
no concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, there is nothing to demonstrate about,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
