<HEADER>
A6281 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GOP-CORPORATIONS-ADV3     07-28 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CORPORATIONS-ADV30-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV30 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: Embargoed against use before Sunday, July 30.)  
 CORPORATIONS OPEN WALLETS TO HELP THE PARTIES PARTY  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
FRIDAY, July 28, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By STEPHEN KOFF  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ FirstEnergy Corp., an Akron firm that provides
electricity across northern Ohio, has dug into its corporate
pockets. So have American Electric Power of Columbus, Ohio, and
dozens of other companies collectively shelling out millions of
dollars this week to help pay for the Republican National
Convention and the social gatherings that will surround it.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Ohio utilities spring for a political event in
Philadelphia?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is as elementary as Politics 101: to stay in the good
graces of members of Congress who can make their corporate
existence more profitable or difficult. Some call it
influence-peddling, but the parties involved in the conventions say
they are merely playing by the rules -- if not the loopholes -- of
a political system driven by money. In fact, the Republican
convention, which starts Monday and ends Thursday, and the
Democratic convention Aug. 14-17 are providing scores of
opportunities for companies to pick up big tabs -- tax-deductible
-- for the political parties and their representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were illegal, we wouldn't do it,'' said FirstEnergy
public relations manager Ralph DiNicola.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty routine stuff,'' said Pat Hemlepp, spokesman
for American Electric Power.
</P>
<P>
   It is so routine that the only thing exceptional this year is
price. The two conventions will cost at least $100 million,
according to the Center for Responsive Politics, a Washington group
that tracks political spending. Of that, the federal government
gives $13.3 million to each of the two political parties, but
``Democrats and Republicans are depending on some generous
corporate donors for the rest,'' a recent report by the center
said.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Motorola, AT&AMP;T, General Motors, Verizon Communications and
Comcast Corp., each giving $1 million for the Republican
convention, and dozens more companies providing smaller amounts,
according to Republican National Committee reports analyzed by the
center.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic convention in Los Angeles also will see its share
of corporate largess, with $1 million commitments by BP Amoco,
Microsoft, United Parcel Service and several others, and $2 million
by the financial service and insurance company American
International Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record of convention fund raising is on pace to shatter
all previous records,'' Scott Harshbarger, president of Common
Cause, wrote in a letter of complaint this month to the Republican
and Democratic convention committees. ``The largest majority of
this money is being contributed by special interests, many of which
have pressing issues before Congress or the Clinton
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Electric utilities, for instance, are pressing for deregulation,
which will allow companies like FirstEnergy to compete for
customers in new markets across the country. The House Commerce
Committee has been working on an electricity restructuring bill
that could ease the way, but its work recently stalled over whether
states or the federal government should have jurisdiction when
there are disputes over interstate transmission of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The matter might not be resolved until next year, when the
committee's leadership will change -- and Michael Oxley, R-Ohio,
could become chairman.
</P>
<P>
   So when Oxley Monday night hosts his private ``tribute'' to
fellow committee members at the American Bandstand Theater in
Philadelphia, with Dick Clark, Chubby Checker, Bobby Rydell and
Frankie Avalon paid to entertain, FirstEnergy and American Electric
Power will help foot the bill. So will companies that include
E-Trade, Price Waterhouse Coopers and utilities in Georgia, Texas
and Pennsylvania. They will divvy up the expected $300,000 to
$400,000 cost, said Pamela Sederholm, a public affairs specialist
planning the party.
</P>
<P>
   Oxley's is just one such party. Others include a ``Mardi Gras''
night hosted by Billy Tauzin of Louisiana, chairman of a House
subcommittee on telecommunications, and financed by
telecommunications companies, among others. Tauzin is competing
against Oxley to chair the House Commerce Committee next year.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles next month, John Dingell of Michigan, the ranking
Democrat on Commerce, will host Democratic guests at the House of
Blues. The nuclear, gas and mining industries are picking up the
tab, according to Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's an important committee, (and) it's important
for us to maintain good relations with the committee,'' DiNicola
said of FirstEnergy's financial involvement in Oxley's party.
``Fair treatment by the government,'' he said, equates to better
prices and service for electricity customers.
</P>
<P>
   Oxley did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the conventions are no different from social events on
Capitol Hill, where direct donations to campaigns and gifts to
members of Congress are limited by law but there other ways to
shower favor on a willing lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``People invite congressmen and senators to charitable functions
where they get their travel and food paid for,'' said Steve
Weissman, legislative representative of Public Citizen, a group
that promotes restricting the influence of money on politics. ``So
there are ways in which there is at least a modicum of favor, but
more a kind of favorable atmosphere created by these high-spending
special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The conventions merely present a more concentrated opportunity
for corporate involvement: General Motors will provide cars, AT&AMP;T
will hand out cellular phones, and -- thanks to the ingenuity of
Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip -- Union Pacific
will supply a rail car 600 feet from Philadelphia's First Union
Center so members of Congress can escape from the hubbub and relax.
(Golf carts are available if a member doesn't want to walk to the
rail car.)
</P>
<P>
   Separately, more than 80 members of Congress and their families
will stay at an old ship repair facility no longer used at the
Philadelphia Naval Shipyard, where defense contractors will be
showing off their wares. The accommodations, spruced up for the
occasion, will be on par with Holiday Inn, said a spokesman for
Rep. Curt Weldon of Pennsylvania, a House Armed Services
subcommittee chairman who arranged for the former military housing.
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen Koff is a staff writer with The Plain Dealer of
Cleveland)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
