<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6282 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GOP-POWELL-ADV31-NEWH     07-28 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-POWELL-ADV31-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV31 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: Embargoed against use before Monday, July 31.)  
 COLIN POWELL IN SPOTLIGHT AT OPENING NIGHT OF GOP CONVENTION  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
FRIDAY, July 28, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By ROBERT COHEN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Retired Gen. Colin Powell, who rejected a White
House bid many thought he could win and later ruled out the vice
presidency, will take center stage Monday night at the Republican
National Convention to spread George W. Bush's message of inclusion
and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   As the featured opening night speaker, the popular Powell will
talk of improving education, expanding health care and helping poor
youngsters as a way of highlighting Bush's campaign pledge to
``leave no child behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This speech will be less on global politics and more on the
importance of taking care of, promoting, encouraging and mentoring
young people, who are in fact America's promise,'' said Kenneth
Duberstein, a close Powell friend and President Reagan's former
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   But the presence of Powell, who could be named secretary of
state in a Bush administration, is also designed to send the
message that a Bush presidency, as the campaign likes to say, will
have ``a generous heart'' and maintain an ``open door'' for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are competing for the minority vote and you want to
appear inclusive, it is good marketing and good politics to have a
nonwhite face up there, especially if it is someone as highly
revered by the American people as Gen. Powell,'' said Ward
Connerly, a black California Republican and a leader in the fight
against affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Walters, a professor of Afro-American studies at the
University of Maryland, said Powell is a centrist who believes in
smaller government but also has views at odds with the traditional
GOP agenda like support for affirmative action, abortion rights,
immigration and helping the downtrodden. Powell describes himself
as ``a fiscal conservative with a social conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters said Powell spoke on the first night of the GOP
convention in 1996 for nominee Bob Dole and, while receiving
standing ovations from the crowd, was out of step with the
conservative forces that dominated the San Diego gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time around he is more in sync with what the nominee
wants to do -- to show a more moderate face to the American
voters,'' said Walters. ``Powell will appeal to blacks, at least
symbolically, but also will signal white independent and moderate
voters that Bush wants an inclusive administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Duberstein said Powell will definitely stress inclusion, as he
did in 1996 and as Bush has done on the campaign trail, and will
not shy away from expressing his views in support of affirmative
action and immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent African-Americans will be featured speakers
during the convention, including Bush's foreign policy adviser
Condoleeza Rice and Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma. Several
Hispanic-Americans, including Rep. Henry Bonilla of Texas, will be
given prominent speaking slots.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wife, Laura, will share the opening night stage with
Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, 62, served as President Reagan's national security
adviser and as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff under
President Bush. He was the first African-American to hold either
post, and as head of the Joint Chiefs, he oversaw the Persian Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Harlem to a family of Jamaican heritage and raised in
the poverty-ridden South Bronx, Powell retired from the military in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a best-selling book, ``My American Journey,'' in 1995,
joined the Republican Party, and rejected a run for the White House
in 1996 and the No. 2 spot on the ticket with Dole despite his
enormous public appeal.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Powell again ruled out seeking the GOP
presidential nomination and let Bush know that he did not want to
be considered for the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats feared the choice of Powell as vice president
would have given Bush a tremendous boost. It is now widely expected
that Powell will be in line to become secretary of state if the
Texas governor wins in November.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Powell has headed an organization
called ``America's Promise: The Alliance for Youth.'' This
organization is geared toward mobilizing communities and
businesses, civic, religious and nonprofit groups to assist young
people -- a theme that connects with one message of the Bush
campaign and with the first night of the GOP convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
