<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta beats analysts' expectations for quarter by 8
cents
 &HT;    By Caroline Hubbard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scientific Atlanta is on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Norcross company said Friday its first quarter would beat
analysts' estimates by more than 3 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to earn 28 cents to 30 cents a share in the
first quarter, Chief Financial Officer Wallace Haislip said. That's
above the average estimate of 25 cents from analysts surveyed by
First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch upgraded the stock to a buy, temporarily boosting
the company's stock price. The stock closed at $77.06.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta started announcing good news late Thursday,
reporting record fourth-quarter earnings of $59.1 million, or 35
cents a share, which beat analysts' estimates by 8 cents a share.
Sales were $552.6 million, up 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For its fiscal year ended June 30, Scientific-Atlanta earned
$155.8 million, or 94 cents a share, on sales of $1.71 billion.
That's a 52 percent gain over $102.3 million, or 65 cents a share,
on sales of $1.24 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for Scientific-Atlanta's end-to-end cable products _ from
transmission equipment to television set-top boxes _ pushed orders
to $639.3 million in the fourth quarter, 64 percent higher than
last year, said Chief Executive Officer James McDonald on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The next quarter likely will beat analysts' expectations too,
the company said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta expects profit of $1.25 to $1.30 a share in
fiscal 2001, compared with current estimates of $1.13, Haislip
said. Profit will be boosted by increased sales of set-top boxes,
with about 1 million shipped each quarter, Haislip told Bloomberg
Television. There were 835,000 shipped in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta is the No. 2 U.S. set-top box manufacturer
behind General Instrument, a division of Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
