<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-MOVIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS IN NEW YORK MORE LENIENT WITH MOVIE MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A few months ago, a handful of television producers
filed into the office of the Teamsters Union chief who handles film
production in New York to protest the decisions of one Teamster
supervisor they felt were unfair and costing them too much money.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Thomas R. O'Donnell, the Teamster chief, ruled in
favor of the supervisor, the producers came away heartened that he
had considered their complaint and called the supervisor on the
carpet to explain himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just would not happen in Boston,'' said one producer who
was familiar with the meeting and asked not to be identified. ``In
Boston, there is rarely any effort to compromise or reach common
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, who has headed the New York Teamsters' local that
contracts with the filmmakers for 40 years, stressed in an
interview Friday that his union is flexible in considering the
demands on cost and working conditions that the producers and other
executives make on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a happy medium to be struck here, and except for
wages, I am willing to consider any request that a filmmaker has,''
O'Donnell said. ``We're not to be doing anyone any favors by making
it so that they don't want to come back here. It just makes sense
in the long run to be flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   In discussing their reluctance to shoot more movies in
Massachusetts, studio executives and independent producers
inevitably emphasize the refusal of the Teamsters union in Boston,
Local 25, to compromise on key provisions in their lucrative,
benefit-laden contract. It is a contract that guarantees all
Teamsters 25 hours of overtime every week, which means the lowest
paid driver makes a minimum of $2,002 a week for the standard
65-hour work week, while the two top supervisors bring in $2,853
and $2,475 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers in New York pay Teamsters about as much for a week of
work as they do in Boston, but in New York the crews work a
standard 70-hour week, five more hours. Several filmmakers
interviewed recently said additional benefits in the Boston
contract, that Teamster President George Cashsman and Louis
DiGiampaolo, who negotiates the film contracts with the studios,
consider inviolable discourage them from coming to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Teamster officials in Boston could not be reached for comment
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more egregious provisions cited by movie executives
were:
</P>
<P>
   --- Cashman and DiGiampaolo select who will be hired as the
coordinator, captain and crew on individual productions. In
California and frequently in New York, the movie producer is able
to choose who will be hired for the positions.
</P>
<P>
   --- If the production office of a film is 25 miles or more
beyond the Charlestown headquarters of Local 25, the studio must
pay all Teamster crew members for the sixth and seventh day that
they are on the job even when they are idle. The assumption is that
they are too far from home to commute to the set. In addition to
the pay, the crew members have their hotel and meals paid for by
the studios during those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a negotiable item for me,'' O'Donnell said Friday.
``If the set is 200 miles away, then of course, we want our people
taken care of. But if it's not that far, then we can find a way to
work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   --- The coordinator and captain often rack up far more than the
25 hours of overtime that is built into their standard work week.
Under Local 25's contract, the workday for the coordinator and
captain begins the minute that the first person arrives on the set,
even if the two Teamster supervisors are still home in bed, and
they continue on the clock until the last person leaves the set for
the night.
</P>
<P>
   The New York union has a similar provision in its standard
contract, according to O'Donnell, but ``it's usually the first one
we talk about'' and ``seek compromise'' with the producers. In
addition, the Boston contract requires filmmakers to hire two
Teamster supervisors to oversee the drivers on the set, but neither
of them is required to drive any vehicles. The New York contract
mandates that only one Teamster supervisor, a captain, be hired to
oversee the drivers and often, according to O'Donnell, he will
handle driving responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cashman said in an interview earlier this week that he
wants to encourage more filmmakers to shoot in Massachusetts, movie
executives and others told The Globe that Local 25's hard-nosed
negotiation tactics have driven production studios, especially on
medium and smaller projects, to look to film in Canada or southern
states, where costs are lower.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it means less overall business for the state, there
are still enough major films being shot here to keep Cashman's
hand-picked crews working.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Jacob Fries contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
