<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6299 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CVN-GOP-PLATFORM-HNS &LR;      07-28 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-PLATFORM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP HOLDS THE LINE ON ABORTION PLANK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By Dan Freedman  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republicans on Friday rebuffed efforts by party
moderates to strike strong anti-abortion language from their
platform, ending a passionate but predictable debate on one of the
GOP's thorniest issues.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike previous conventions when party elders did their
best to keep GOP abortion rights supporters at arms length,
pro-choice Republicans said the process this time around was much
more open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thrilled. We were welcome for about 10 or 15 minutes,''
Ann Stone, chairwoman of Republicans for Choice, said after the
full platform committee voted in favor of keeping the anti-abortion
language. ``I'll tell you, that's progress. It was a great
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans for Choice is one of two groups spearheading the
latest bid to change the GOP platform's abortion plank. After the
committee defeat, pro-choice Republicans vowed to take their fight
to the convention floor on Monday when delegates take up the
platform. Among the options their exploring is submitting a
minority report to the platform that would express the party's
varied views on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the anti-abortion language called the pro-choice
Republicans sore losers. ``Democracy worked and they lost,'' said
Andrea Shelton Lafferty, executive director of the Tradition Values
Coalition, a conservative advocacy group. ``They don't understand
that yeah, they're welcome, but they still lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Language approved by the platform committee closely parallels
the 1996 platform. It endorses making opposition to abortion a
condition for nomination as a federal judge. And like the 1996
platform, this year's version calls for a constitutional amendment
banning abortion _ with no mention of exceptions for rape, incest
or the life and health of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   As it has for past GOP candidates, abortion is proving to be a
difficult issue for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who will accept the
party's presidential nomination next Thursday night. On the one
hand, Bush has built his campaign around themes of inclusiveness,
openness and his self-styled image as a ``compassionate
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other, Bush needs the support of foot soldiers among
religious conservatives and pro-life activists, all of whom
consider opposition to abortion to be among their top issues.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, platform committee
chair, has engaged in a carefully choreographed minuet with both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-abortion language reflects Bush's previously stated
promise to maintain the party as a pro-life bastion hospitable to
religious conservatives. But prior to Friday's platform committee
meetings, Thompson had met with Stone and other pro-choice
Republicans to assure them that although the odds were against
them, they'd have a fair chance to change the platform.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  Earlier Friday that chance largely fizzled as Toni Casey of
Los Altos Hills, Calif., one of 15 members of the ``Family and
Community'' subcommittee, moved to strike paragraphs supporting the
``human life'' amendment and appointing ``judges who respect ...
the sanctity of innocent human life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the right thing to do, and it is the right thing for the
Republican Party to do today,'' said Casey, a city council member
and former mayor of her town. ``We need a platform that recognizes
that abortion is a sensitive, delicate personal moral issue between
the woman and her own religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in opposition, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., a veteran
anti-abortion lawmaker on Capitol Hill, said the Republican Party
needed to maintain its status as advocate for ``unborn children.''
</P>
<P>
   With Democrats firmly in the pro-choice camp, ``it's left to
Republicans _ the heartless Republicans _ to care about the
defenseless unborn,'' Hyde said. ``I think saving unborn children
is a very noble cause.''
</P>
<P>
   By after an emotional debate, the subcommittee defeated Casey's
proposal to strike the abortion language. The subcommittee also
defeated an attempt by pro-choice Republicans to insert language
acknowledging that differing views on abortion exist within the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It defeats the purpose of the entire (platform) statement,''
said Rand Larson, a subcommittee delegate from Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-choice republicans then tried their luck before the full
platform committee but their motions were defeated again.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Thompson said that although the outcome was
never seriously in doubt, he had bent over backwards to assure
fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's deliberations ``were very positive,'' Thompson said.
``We're still looking at ways to make sure everyone feels they're
included in the process, and we're going to continue to do that
until we wrap up Monday afternoon.'' Asked about the possibility of
a floor fight on abortion on Monday, Thompson said ``sure, I'd be
upset if it goes to the floor.'' If it does, ``I don't think I've
done my job,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the abortion plank, the subcommittee also
toughened language in opposition to gay rights. In addition to a
promise to ``energetically defend'' the 1996 Defense of Marriage
Act _ which says that states do not have to recognize same-sex
marriages performed in other states _ members inserted a statement
that federal civil rights law should not be extended to
discrimination based on sexual preference.
</P>
<P>
   They also inserted a pledge to ``stand united'' with the Boy
Scouts of America, which won a recent Supreme Court battle over its
dismissal of a scout troop leader who is gay.
</P>
<P>
   But in line with Bush's effort to appeal to Hispanic voters, the
platform committee softened 1996 language that called for denying
government benefits to illegal immigrants, as well as a
constitutional amendment denying citizenship to U.S.-born children
of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 platform approved by the subcommittee Friday drops
those demands. It calls for splitting the Immigration and
Naturalization service into separate enforcement and immigration
processing entities, and an increase in H-1B visas for skilled
foreign-born workers in high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   In line with Bush's position, this year's education plank calls
for increased accountability and standards in schools to make sure
children are learning. It also drops the GOP's long-standing call
to dismantle the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major shift from 1996,'' said Sen. Bill Frist,
R-Tenn., a platform committee co-chair. ``To me it shows maturation
in our understanding of how to educate children today.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
