<SLUG> BC-WALKS-AGAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED HOCKEY PLAYER TAKES FIRST STEPS IN 4 1/2 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IEVA AUGSTUMS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Slowly, but surely, John Gilpatrick placed one foot in
front of the other Friday and walked across the first-floor
function room. Confident he could successfully make the 30-foot
journey on his own, the former Suffolk University hockey player sat
down next to his mother and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty small steps for most, but a momentous and poignant giant
leap for the 27-year-old from Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 4 1/2 years since Gilpatrick was hit from behind
during a game, sending him head first into a goalpost causing a
devastating spinal cord injury that left him in a wheelcair, with
no use of his legs and right arm.
</P>
<P>
   But during a packed news conference at Suffolk University Law
School, Gilpatrick fought back tears as he talked of his
determination not to spend the rest of his days labeled as a person
with special needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot exactly explain it. One morning I woke up and told
myself I was going to walk,'' Gilpatrick said. ``The first six
months were hard, but I always got up in the morning. I never gave
up. With my step-father's help, I took my first steps, again.''
</P>
<P>
   Crediting a huge outpouring of good will, unwavering
perserverence and intense physical therapy, Gilpatrick recalled how
about a month ago he began to experience some pain, or what he
called a burning sensation, in his spine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes this burning is connected with positive return,''
Gilpatrick said. ``As you can see this return has allowed me to
stand unaided, and to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick wanted to keep his good news a secret for a few more
weeks, but word of his success got out after he was seen walking
around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it. My mouth dropped to the floor,'' said
Michael Murphy, 26, a lifelong friend who saw Gilpatrick walk
Monday. ``He just walked through my front door and said, `Hi.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick's recovery also astonished Dr. David Apple, a
specialist in spinal cord injuries who treated Gilpatrick at the
Shepherd Center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that a patient's best chances for recovery comes within
the first two years from when an injury is sustained.
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick's ability to take his first steps, Apple believes,
comes from a combination of hard work and sheer luck that his
spinal injury was not as bad as it could have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do anything special, he did all the hard work,''
Apple said. ``The young man has a lot of determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick undergoes many hours of physical therapy every week
with the goal of improving his ability to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick became a quadriplegic on Jan. 25, 1996 after he
rushed to the net and was hit from behind, causing his head to
strike the goalpost and then whip backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember watching it happen. He dropped right to the ice,''
recalled Suffolk head hockey coach Brian Horan, who was then the
team's assistant coach. ``I rushed out to him and he said, `Coach,
I can't feel anything.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick's injury occurred on the same section of the ice at
the Walter Brown Arena where three months earlier Travis Roy was
paralyzed in his first game for Boston University when he lost his
balance and crashed head first into the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick said he kept in close touch with Roy, who was
paralyzed from the neck down, after meeting him while they were
both rehabilitating at the Shepherd Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking is a little hard for me because I have so many friends
who remain paralyzed,'' Gilpatrick said. ``I keep telling them
never to give up. Doctors aren't always right.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gilpatrick, the 1996 accident, was the second major injury
Gilpatrick sufferend playing hockey. In 1989, as a sophomore at
Hanover High School, he broke his neck, leaving him paralyzed for
three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always worried about his safety, but there wasn't much
I could do,'' explained Elaine Jones, Gilpatrick's mother. ``My son
loves hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   But she also has come to admire another and ultimately, perhaps,
more important passion her son possesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been relentless in his pursuit to stand and walk,'' Jones
said. ``I'm very proud of John. I didn't think that he would walk.
He did.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilpatrick, who returned to school in September 1997 with the
help of Ice, his Rottweiler guide dog, was an assistant hockey
coach at the school. He received a bachelor's degree in criminal
justice last December and plans to attend Suffolk University Law
School next month.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to get back on the ice, Gilpatrick said he hopes to coach
hockey someday without the use of his wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done with playing, but I would love to be on skates to
coach those guys,'' Gilpatrick said pointing to some team members
standing on the other side of the room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
