<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OLIGARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTING THE LISTENER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are promising signs that Russian President Vladimir Putin
may be heeding Western objections to recurrent authoritarianism in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The most evident gesture in this direction was the dropping of
criminal charges against Vladimir Gusinsky, whose Media-Most
conglomerate controls papers, magazines, and broadcasting outlets
critical of established power. The official stance was that last
week's move came as a consequence of normal, independent
prosecutorial procedures. But the timing suggests that it was a
direct consequence of the criticism Putin heard from President
Clinton and other heads of state at the recent summit meeting of
the Group of Eight in Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   Less noticed abroad was the gangland-style murder Wednesday of
Sergey Novikov, the owner of an independent radio station in the
city of Smolensk. Novikov had discussed allegations of local
corruption on a TV program three days before and received death
threats earlier this year. The Committee to Protect Journalists has
sent a letter to Putin asking for a proper investigation of
Novikov's murder and punishment of those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   For Putin to establish the substance as well as the appearance
of a genuine rule of law in Russia, he must institute fair and
impartial justice for everyone. That means eliminating arbitrary or
political misuse of the legal system in Smolensk as well as Moscow,
for obscure cases as for those that receive international
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's meeting Friday with 21 so-called oligarchs may have been
another effort to respond to advice he received in Okinawa. The
parley suggests that he wants to create a level playing field for
economic players in Russia without exacerbating the capital flight
that has been a damaging side effect of the crony capitalism
tolerated by Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Even more encouraging was the disclosure that a Putin envoy is
negotiating with Chechnya's elected president, Aslan Maskhadov, for
the purpose of ending the brutal and futile warfare in the
Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   If these changes in Russian behavior are due to pressures from
the West, Russians and Westerners share an interest in keeping the
pressure up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
FD3628 &Cx1f; xfdtr
r w BC-HOUSE-HRG-JUSTICE-DEP 5thAdd f6577 07-28 4767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HRG-JUSTICE-DEPT, </SLUG>
 5th Add, f6577,5086 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Representative Dan Burton (R-In) Holds Hearing On Alleged
Release Of Confidential Documents By Justice Department
</P>
<P>
   xfdtr HOUSE-HRG-JUSTICE-DEPT 5thadd
</P>
<P>
   XXX the other cases?
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: I don't recall saying to the reporter I made
exceptions. I told him, I think what I just told you--he called me,
I didn't make a statement--but I did tell him what I just told you,
that, in this case, it seemed to me it wasn't going to undermine
our general policy and it would serve the purpose of putting to
rest a controversy and saving, you know, everybody, including the
taxpayers, the expense of having to litigate over it.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no other case I remember where I made an exception
to that policy.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: So this was indeed the only case that went to the policy
you described earlier?
</P>
<P>
   (CROSSTALK)
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: ... as a direct result of a case where the issue was
ever raised with me, but it was also the only case where I ever
made that exception.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Did you have any involvement in any other FOIA cases
while you were associate attorney general?
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: Yes, occasionally if someone called and complained,
although it was rare--it was a part of the Justice Department that,
sort of, ran itself--but there were occasional cases where people
would call and complain. You're asking me for examples?
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: No, I'm just actually asking very specifically, were
there any other cases involving the policy to, neither to confirm
nor deny?
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: No. I don't recall any other case where that issue was
raised with me.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Mr. Hogan, just before I get into this, you mentioned
that you did, at one time, let staff know, in the associate
attorney general's office, about this issue. Who did you contact?
</P>
<P>
   HOGAN: I now know--I didn't know this when we spoke a few weeks
ago, when my memory was so faded because, at that point, I had not
had a chance to look at documents--what I did is I called, when I
learned there was a potential appeal, Nancy McFadden (ph) was Mr.
Schmidt's top aide, and I let her know that there was an issue
coming.
</P>
<P>
   I did want her to look into whether or not they actually handled
appeals, the question you just asked Mr. Schmidt. At the time, I
did not know the answer to, and whether or not they would take an
appeal from Mr. Huff's office, and simply let her know that--to
make sure there was no misunderstanding, that I had no position on
the issue, and had simply played the traffic cop, sending her--you
know, Ms. Poston in her direction. Because I didn't want there to
be any misunderstanding as to what my role was.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Did you ask anybody in your associate attorney general's
office to meet with Ms. Poston.
</P>
<P>
   HOGAN: No, I simply said that Ms. Poston wanted to appeal. I
didn't know what the issue was, I didn't know how, what Mr. Huff's
power was vis-a-vis Mr. Schmidt, to be completely honest. And so I
said, ``Look into the issue of whether or not this is an appeal
that you'd want to take. I don't know what your procedures are.''
</P>
<P>
   I simply knew that I wasn't going to be involved in it, and I
wanted to let her know that there was no misunderstanding, that I
had no position.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Ms. Poston, prior to your actually lodging the FOIA
request, did you have an expectation that the Justice Department
would grant your request?
</P>
<P>
   POSTON: I thought at the beginning it would be difficult because
I was making a request for a record for someone I did not
represent. In all my past FOIA experiences I had represented the
party whose record I was seeking. But then when I got the
memorandum from Wilmer Cutler that the Privacy Act did not apply to
foreign nationals, then I felt that I had a good legal argument.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: OK, Mr. Hogan, you mentioned earlier that there was a
prospect--or Mr. Schmidt, you also mentioned it, there was the
prospect of litigation in this case. Mr. Schmidt, would the
litigation have been successful if Steel Hector and Davis had
litigated to obtain this (inaudible)?
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: I don't think so, based upon Mr. Huff had told me. I
think he thought we had a very defensible position. My view, as I
indicated before, was there was no point in litigating over
something that didn't exist, so we could avoid the issue. And I
didn't really get into the issue beyond talking to Mr. Huff.
</P>
<P>
   But I think he was comfortable that we had a defensible basis
for refusing to disclose any information here.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Mr. Huff, would a plaintiff have been able to prevail,
asking for the record that Ms. Poston asked for in this case?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: I think it would be very unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Very unlikely?
</P>
<P>
   If you could, Mr. Huff, just--we'll start at the beginning of
this, if you could explain very briefly, because you want to get
out of here and we don't have much time, what is the Justice
Department policy regarding the confirmation or denial of criminal
records about a third person?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, we understand that if you go and ask for a record that
pertains to yourself, you have access to that, but if I were to go
and ask for somebody else's criminal record, what is the Justice
Department's policy?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: Generally, we would refuse to confirm or deny whether or
not such records existed. There are a few exceptions to that. If
the subject of the request is deceased, or if the subject of the
request has consented to it, or if the Department of Justice has
officially made--you know, ``Do you have any records on John
Hinckley Jr.?'' ``Yes, we do.''
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Now is this policy in place for non-citizens as well as
United States citizens?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: That has been our general practice. Yes, there are
exceptions where we have not followed it for non-citizens.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Now why is this policy in place?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: Generally, it is to protect the privacy of an individual
who does have a law enforcement record about him, or her, where
that fact is not previously been officially confirmed by the
department, or one of the other circumstances that I mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Now, my understanding, from having spoken with you
before, is that, if there was a situation where people who came and
asked for records pertaining to third parties, and there were no
records, and the department confirmed that there was no record, if
the policy was consistently applied, then when there was a record
the department would not be able to reply that there was no record,
and so it would be tantamount to confirming there was a record. Is
that the basic explanation?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: If we did that in all cases, certainly that would be so.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Now--I mean, we've heard today, Ms. Poston, that,
briefly, but, is it true that your initial FOIA requests for Mr.
Abe's records were rejected...
</P>
<P>
   POSTON: No.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: ... at the Department of Justice with--the FOIA request
at main Justice?
</P>
<P>
   POSTON: Well, when you say main Justice, you don't include
Immigration and you don't include Bureau of Prisons?
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: I'm not including
</P>
<P>
   POSTON: Oh, then the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Now, having read some of the paper, Mr. Huff, Ms. Poston
argued that her FOIA request should be granted because of the
public interest in Mr. Abe's arrest record, and because the Privacy
Act did not apply to a foreign national. Why did you reject her
appeal? Did those arguments carry any water with you?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: Well, she was certainly right with regard to the Privacy
Act. But, as a general proposition, aliens have privacy interests
as well that are protectable, and under the Freedom of Information
Act that information can be protected. It's--certainly, under the
FOIA, we are required to assert exemptions. In fact, that's the
whole idea behind discretion.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: I'll just yield for a moment to the chairman of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Something's been kind of bothering me, Mr. Hogan. You're
the chief of staff for the attorney general?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: Yes, I was.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Yes, you were. Why would you even call Mr. Schmidt to
tell him that you weren't taking any position that he might be
contacted by Ms. Poston?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: I did not contact Mr. Schmidt. I never spoke to Mr.
Schmidt. I called his staff.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Well, why would you do that?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: Simply to let them know that--I wanted to make sure they
understood that if my name was used in any way that it wasn't, that
I had taken no position on the case.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Well, wouldn't they, if they got a call from Ms. Poston
or anybody, and said, you know, ``Hogan said that you ought to help
us or something,'' wouldn't they have called you to confirm that?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: I would assume so, but I...
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Then why would you have to call in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: I did it in an abundance of caution, sir, so there would
be absolutely no misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: When the chief of staff for the attorney general of the
United States calls somebody who's a subordinate in the Justice
Department or one of their staff people, the tone of voice, voice
inflection, no matter what it is, can convey all kinds of things,
and just by virtue of the fact that you called, it could have
meant, you know, ``She's going to call, and, you know, do what you
can for her.''
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: Just the opposite, sir. I said I don't know if you...
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Have you made calls like that in the past?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: Yes, sir.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: For other people, where they called you and said, you
know, ``We would like something,'' and you called and said, ``You
may be getting a call...''
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: If there's ever any misunderstanding as to what I have
done, I would attempt to clarify it. Ms. McFadden (ph), who was Mr.
Schmidt's main assistant, was a very seasoned lawyer, a very
competent woman. All I wanted to make sure that she understood was,
that even as to whether or not they heard this, I had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: OK, but this has happened before? You called like that
before, on other issues?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: If someone--if I was concerned that someone would
misunderstand what the role--my role had been in something, yes, I
would clarify it. Just for the reasons you said, sir.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: I know, but you would do it without them initiating a
call to you?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: In some cases, yes.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: OK. Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Just for following up on that, Mr. Hogan, have you ever
made a call on a Freedom of Information Act request before?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: Had I ever made a...
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: A call to anybody else in the Department of Justice
about somebody else's Freedom of Information Act request?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: The only other calls I had made were--Mr. Huff's staff
would routinely consult me on FOIA issues. There are certain things
that, statutorily, if some document was a former attorney general
office document, and there was a FOIA issue with it, they would
have to go to our office, just like they would go to a component,
and occasionally Mr. Huff's deputy would call me and I would call
her back, and it dealt with FOIA issues.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, I have made phone calls on FOIA issues before. I rely
very heavily on Mr. Huff and his staff as to the law, because I
don't perceive myself as an expert in that area. But yes, I have
made phone calls on FOIA issues...
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Now, what I'm trying to get at here, not FOIA requests
for information from the Office of the Attorney General, or
pertaining to yourself or your records, the attorney general's
records, but on a matter that goes to a Freedom of Information Act
request about a third party that's not in the Department of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: When this was pending--I'm not even sure--until I sat here
this morning, I was never even really clear that this even was a
third-party issue. I knew it was a FOIA request. I sent it to the
FOIA people. I never focused on what the issue was.
</P>
<P>
   So, any time I would get a phone call on FOIA, I'd simply send
it to the career lawyers who handle the FOIA issues. I never got
involved in the substance of them.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: But, just so I can...
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: I guess what I'm saying is, I don't know the answer to
your question because I never focused on what the issues were, and
your question just had a specific issue contained in it, and I
don't know. If I had a FOIA question from someone outside the
department, I sent it to Mr. Huff's staff.
</P>
<P>
   That was whether it was a situation where, like, Ms. Poston
called me, it was whether I picked up the phone and some citizen
from somewhere in the United States had a question about FOIA and,
you know, what went wrong; I sent them all to Mr. Huff's office,
and I simply--they were the career people who handled those
matters, that's where I would send anyone who had a FOIA issue.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Well, I understand your answer as far as a basic FOIA
request, but I'm trying to pare away and determine whether you--and
I'll go to the--sort of the bottom line of the concern here is that
you're the chief of staff to the attorney general of the United
States, which is not the first place a FOIA request is lodged. It
requires getting through certain traps to get to you.
</P>
<P>
   And whereas I can understand questions coming to you that
pertain to FOIA requests that go to documents that are important to
the Department of Justice--your documents, the attorney general's
documents--it does seem a little unusual for you to take any phone
calls at all about a Freedom of Information Act request about
something else that's outside of the department. And I just didn't
get a firm sense of the answer on that.
</P>
<P>
   HOGAN: The reason I took the call--when Rebekah--when I got a
message Rebekah Poston's on the phone, I knew who she was, I--she
was an acquaintance, I don't--you know, the definition of
``friends'' is a nebulous one--but I knew who she was, I took the
call.
</P>
<P>
   She began explaining she had a problem with FOIA. I said, Oh,
FOIA, it needs to go to, you know, to a certain office within the
department. I didn't--I told her--she asked me questions like, as I
recall, Do you know Tom Kelly (ph), who's a lawyer in the FBI? And
I said, Yes, I know him, but if you have a question with main
Justice and there's a FOIA issue it goes to Mr. Huff's office. I
simply did not get involved in it. I did not go into the substance.
</P>
<P>
   She tried to make her case about the administration policy of
openness and the attorney general's policy of openness and I
simply--my response was, I don't get involved in FOIA issues, you
need to talk to the career people who handle those issues. And I
just--I just sent her on her way.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when it later came to an appeal, that was the first time
that I knew of an appeal coming from Mr. Huff's office, and so to
some extent, if there's a uniqueness here, I don't remember ever
getting a call about that before. But again, I would simply pass on
the information.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: OK. Just to clarify one thing. You mentioned, not
precisely in these words, but the definition of ``friends'' is a
nebulous term. And when we called you we didn't get a very
sense--very good sense of any connection or past relationship
between yourself and Ms. Poston.
</P>
<P>
   Is it true that when Hurricane Andrew came through Miami you
invited Ms. Poston and her friend to come live in your house--and
her sister to come live in your house?
</P>
<P>
   HOGAN: Let me explain. Thank you very much for that opportunity.
There are so many things that are just not clear.
</P>
<P>
   Her sister was a secretary in the state attorney's office and
she was in charge of all homicide victims and just did a wonderful
job. She was a single mother who just really was a very impressive
person. Although she was never my secretary, she was someone who
I've always admired.
</P>
<P>
   I knew that she lived on Miami Beach. When Hurricane Andrew was
approaching Miami I called her and said, ``Lookit, they're saying
that Miami Beach needs to be evacuated, Bobbi (ph), if you need a
place to stay, I live inland, you're more than welcome to come to
my house.'' And she said, ``Well, my sister also lives on the
shore, could she come, too?'' And I did not say, ``No, she has to
stay out in the storm.'' I said, ``Yes, she can come, too.''
</P>
<P>
   My contact with Ms. Poston had always been through her sister,
you know. Her sister's office desk was near my office, I would come
out occasionally, they would be going to lunch together, she would
introduce me, I'd say, Hi, Rebekah, how are you? That was really
the sum total of my contact with Ms. Poston before this happened.
</P>
<P>
   So I did say to her sister that Ms. Poston could come to my
house in the hurricane. The great irony was they didn't come and my
house was destroyed and her house was fine.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: When this FOIA matter was in--at the Department of
Justice, it's our understanding that it had been resolved to the
point where there was no possibility of appeal, or at least the
final appellate step had been taken within the Department of
Justice. Was that your--do you recall whether you had an
understanding of that at the time?
</P>
<P>
   HOGAN: I'm sorry, could you repeat that, sir?
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: That when this FOIA request was in the Department of
Justice it had gone to Mr. Huff and he had rejected--there was an
appeal to him and he had rejected the appeal and the matter was
effectively closed within the FOIA office. Is that your
understanding of what happened had happened?
</P>
<P>
   HOGAN: I knew that--I had a sense that--and again, mainly from
messages from that I'm not even sure of what the information--that
eventually he ruled against Ms. Poston's position. I did not know
whether that was final or not, and that was one of the questions
that I posed to Ms. McFadden (ph), that she should look into
whether or not there was a right of appeal for Mr. Huff?
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: If I could, just up put exhibit 30 for a moment on the
screen. And this is a letter dated April 25, 1995, and it's
the--it's a letter to Ms. Poston from Mr. Huff. And there are four
things that I wanted to pull out of this letter.
</P>
<P>
   In the first paragraph it says, ``I note that you have not
furnished a notarized authorization from Mr. Abe.''
</P>
<P>
   The second point, in the second paragraph, ``I find the Supreme
Court's holding to be controlling in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   And then further in that paragraph it says, ``Lacking an
individual's consent, proof of death, official acknowledgement of
an investigation or an overriding public interest, even to
acknowledge the existence of law enforcement records pertaining to
an individual could reasonably be expected to constitute an
unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   And then at the end of the first page and going on to the second
page it says, ``Accordingly, this office is unable to assist you in
this matter at this time and I am closing these administrative
appeals in this office.''
</P>
<P>
   I mean, this--Mr. Huff, when we first read this, it seems like a
fairly unambiguous response to the FOIA request. In our opinion,
was this decision a close call?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: No.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: If one were to argue that based on--well, let me ask
this question this way. When the decision was made by Mr. Schmidt
to provide Ms. Poston the information that she was requesting, did
that constitute a change of policy at the Department of Justice?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: I don't think it was a change of policy, I think it was an
exception in this case because of the circumstances in this case
where Mr. Schmidt said he had looked at the policy, Attorney
General Reno's disclosure policy.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: What were the--what were the circumstances that made
this case worthy of a change of direction?
</P>
<P>
   HUFF: He mentioned during our conversation the risk of
litigation and the time that litigation would take, but that was...
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Is that, Mr. Schmidt, is that a fair characterization,
that it was the concern about litigation that led you to make the
decision you made?
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: Well, that was certainly a factor. Again, I wouldn't
accept the characterization there was a change in policy. I think
Mr. Huff has it exactly right, there was an exception to the
policy. In the circumstance where we had discovered it we didn't
have any records, I mean that is the key element here, and so we
were not disclosing any records, there was no argument that we were
depriving anybody of their privacy rights, and we had the ability
to do something totally harmless that thereby put to rest a matter
and avoided the need for any further controversy about it. And that
seemed to me then and still seems to me the sensible thing to in
those circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: So let me just interrupt here. It is an exception to the
accepted policy. You don't tell people when they ask about criminal
records with a FOIA request whether you have them, don't have them,
you don't tell them anything.
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: That's correct. You don't have a general policy of
confirming or denying.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: So why--and so why the exception? I just--it's lost...
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: Because we had found ourselves here in a situation
where we were confronted with not just the potential, but I think
the likelihood of having to litigate over this matter. We had
discovered that we in fact had no records.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Well, let me ask...
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: And by disclosing the fact that we had no records, we
could completely put an end to the matter and avoid spending
anybody's time or effort or money litigating.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Taxpayers' money. But let's say that you have 100 cases
like this where people threaten with litigation, are you going to
do that with all...
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: But we didn't. I would agree with you, if you had 100
or 1,000 like this you might have to come to a different result.
But we had one case which we could completely put to rest by making
a completely harmless and lawful disclosure of the fact that we had
no records. So it seemed to me, for me, frankly, in terms of the
overall interests of the department, easy to conclude that it was a
sensible conclusion not to unnecessarily litigate over something
that didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: How do you account for the fact, and maybe you just have
to speculate on this, how do you account for the fact that this
investigator, the private investigator who was looking into this,
Mister--what was the gentleman's name?
</P>
<P>
   (UNKNOWN): Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Mr. Manuel said that the records had been purged.
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: I mean, all I know about that is what I learned from
having listened to the hearing this morning. I know nothing about
any of that. And I don't know what it means, I don't know--I don't
know how it happened, if it happened. And, you know, I know nothing
about any of that.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: I understand, but you could see why that raises a
question with us.
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: Oh, I could see how your definition of ``purged''...
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: I know, but...
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: ... sounded more like mine than the one you were
getting from that particular witness, but I--where that leads you,
you know, in terms of...
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: No, but the point is this. We see these documents and
they raise all kinds of questions and it says it's been purged, and
then we find that you have made an exception to a rule that's been
around or a policy that's been around for a long, long time because
you say that you're concerned about possible litigation. And it
just...
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: It seems to me you're connecting, you know, apples to
oranges in a way that doesn't, in fact, connect. My decision had
nothing to do with whether anything had or hadn't been purged...
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: No, I understand that.
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: ... because none of us--I don't think Mr. Huff or
anybody else knew anything about any of that. All we were deciding
was what to do in a situation where we had found out we didn't have
any record and, you know, should we go on arguing or should we put
the matter to rest by disclosing that fact.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: If you have a case like this in the future would you do
the same thing?
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: Well, I'm no longer there, but if I had this case under
these circumstances in the future, yes, I would. It seemed to me
right then, it still seems to me right.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Just one of the concerns that brings us to this matter
and this panel here is to try and determine whether--what the
policy is to the extent it can be determined. And it sounds to me,
and you can help me with this, Mr. Schmidt, it sounds to me like
the clearest articulation of the status quo now is that if somebody
wants criminal records about a third party and they threaten
litigation and there aren't records the Department of Justice will
provide them an answer. Is that a fair articulation of the policy?
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: No. I think that the policy remains that as a general
policy we don't confirm or deny the existence of records. And I
would say that if you want to state as a general policy, that there
are occasional exceptions in circumstances where the disclosure of
the nonexistence of records is harmless and it allows us to avoid
what otherwise appears to be an imminent threat of significant
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: But that--I mean, I understand what you say, but your
answer is somewhat--it doesn't follow. If I go to the Department of
Justice tomorrow and I work through the process and I get to the
final decision maker and I'm rejected and I get a bigger
and--forgive--well, just a bigger law firm than Steel Hector and
Davis or any other sort of large, well thought of law firm, and I
say, ``Look, you know, the Privacy Act doesn't apply, I want this
record,'' then how could you distinguish my request from Ms.
Poston's request?
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: Well, I would distinguish it. I don't think this was a
case where someone was coming in and simply litigating as part of a
strategy to undermine a general Justice Department policy of
neither confirming nor denying the existence of records. This was
litigation that was clearly substantial--although I think Mr. Huff,
based on everything I know, is correct, we would have won it--but
there were real issues here about the extent...
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: They wanted the record. I mean, that's...
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: No, no, no, but the extent to which aliens under these
circumstances had or hadn't a right to privacy and under what
circumstances therefore someone asserting a FOIA request could
override what at least Ms. Poston and her clients would say was a
nonexistent right (inaudible). This was real litigation. So I don't
think it's fair to suggest that we're somehow creating a scenario
where everyone would be free to come in and by the mere threat of
litigation undermine the longstanding policy.
</P>
<P>
   And I'd come back to you--if that began to happen, then I would
abandon the policy of making exceptions. But until it happened, I
see no reason to spend taxpayers' money and the resources of the
Justice Department litigating unnecessarily over something that
doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Mr. Schmidt, if you didn't know all the facts of this
particular case how would you know whether or not divulging that
you had no information or some information in the file would affect
the case?
</P>
<P>
   (CROSSTALK)
</P>
<P>
   SCHMIDT: Well, I have no idea whether it would affect the case.
All I know is that because we had no records there was no one whose
privacy rights were going to be violated. And we didn't make the
decision to do anything here until we found out that we had no
records. So I had no idea and don't whether it was going to be
positive or negative for this case. All I mean is in terms of the
interests that the FOIA law and the privacy law were protecting, it
was harmless because there in fact were no records being disclosed
and therefore we weren't depriving anybody of their privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Does anybody--we'll just change course for a minute
here--does anybody on this panel know why the attorney general
recused herself in this specific case?
</P>
<P>
   HOGAN: I do.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON: Mr. Hogan, if you could tell us briefly.
</P>
<P>
   HOGAN: Thank you. I have had a chance to look at record since we
spoke.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke--although I normally did not take Ms. Poston's
call--it's somewhat awkward to sit here and say that, but that's
what happened, I did not take her calls--occasionally I would pick
up the phone when my secretary was busy and occasionally I would
speak to her. I remember having a conversation with her at one
point and I think she clearly was frustrated, I think, with the
fact that she was not--her position was not gaining momentum within
the department, and she mentioned to me that she was handling the
matter with a man by the name of John Edward Smith (ph). And I knew
John Edward Smith (ph)--he has recently died--but I knew him to be
a friend of the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
