<TEXT>
<P>
   For the sake of an antimissile system that independent
scientists say can never work, politicians and defense bureaucrats
are willing to spend $60 billion and imperil the 1972 ABM treaty
that has been a cornerstone of strategic stability. They are also
prepared to alienate America's allies, to goad China into enlarging
and modernizing its deterrent force of 20 ICBMs, and, after the
folly subsides, to leave Americans less secure than they were
before.
</P>
<P>
   These are the obvious symptoms of the antimissile malady. But a
new variety appeared recently, when Democratic Senator Kent Conrad
of North Dakota, who wants the first 20 interceptors of the
proposed missile defense system located in his state rather than
Alaska, where they are now slated to go, suggested that if a system
sited in North Dakota would leave unprotected the few residents of
Alaska's Aleutian Island chain or the uninhabited outer islands of
Hawaii, it would make sense to compensate the unshielded.
</P>
<P>
   Said Conrad: ``Are we really going to say we aren't going to
protect the whole rest of the country because of the 1,500 people
in the Aleutian chain, who could be offered a generous buyout
package?''
</P>
<P>
   To Alaska's Republican senator, Frank Murkowski, this heartless
triage was intolerable. Alaskans, he warned, ``aren't willing to
sell our right to be defended.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a word from either senator about the defense contracts or
the jobs that the antimissile boondoggle might bring to their
states.
</P>
<P>
   It is evident from their unseemly quarrel that neither
legislator has heard the bad news about the inability of the
system's sensors to discriminate between warheads in space and
Mylar balloons serving as decoys. But Conrad did have a point when
he justified his buyout scheme for Aleutian islanders ``in light of
the fact that it would make no strategic sense for them to be a
target in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   This was one of the few rational remarks uttered since the onset
of missile-defense madness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
