<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6363 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-28 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CHENEY'S `COMPASSION' AS PREDICTABLE AS BUSH'S
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Maybe Dick Cheney is a fair-weather
``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else George W. Bush expected to accomplish with his
choice of Cheney as running mate, he assumed the most important
announcement of his presidential race so far also would divert
attention from an embarrassing controversy over his budget
priorities in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, for about two weeks before Bush introduced Cheney, the
Texas governor had been barraged daily by Democrats over unexpected
budgetary shortages in Medicaid and a few other programs in his
home state.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's opponents exaggerated the problem, the fact that
Bush had insisted last year on using $1.7 billion of a $6.4 billion
budgetary surplus to cut taxes was blasted as short-sighted and
used to paint the governor as more conservative than compassionate.
</P>
<P>
   (Compassionate, in this discussion, is used in the sense of
improving governmental programs that assist people in need and
boosting educational opportunities that help people learn to help
themselves. The word is not used in the sense, as some would use
it, of giving taxpayers a break.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush and state legislators also raised teachers' pay and funded
a new health insurance program for low-income children. But those
compassionate pluses were smothered in a firestorm of political
rhetoric, particularly since the tax cuts had a greater impact on
some businesses than they did on most consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Then up stepped Cheney, and he certainly diverted attention from
the Texas budget. But the initial reviews for Bush were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The governor got positive marks for choosing a running mate _ a
former congressman, former secretary of defense and able Washington
player _ who had strengths that Bush lacked. Cheney is widely
regarded for his expertise in national and international affairs,
areas in which Bush is still being tutored.
</P>
<P>
   But while in Congress in the 1970s and 1980s, Cheney also
compiled a strongly conservative voting record that Democrats
immediately began resurrecting and attacking with glee.
</P>
<P>
   He was anti-abortion, anti-gun control and anti-big government,
viewpoints that he generally shares with Bush. But he even voted
against Head Start, which seems to contradict the high priority
that Bush has placed on education.
</P>
<P>
   And he voted against a symbolic resolution that called on South
Africa to free Nelson Mandela, the leader of the struggle to end
apartheid, from prison. What kind of message does that deliver to
the minority voters whom Bush has been trying mightily to woo into
the Republican tent?
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who already had been ridiculing Bush's claims to be a
``compassionate conservative'' and a different kind of Republican
pounced like wolves on a chunk of fresh meat.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush found himself on the defensive again, as he and his new
running mate were peppered with questions about how well a
budget-cutting congressman from the Reagan era could fit on a
``compassionate conservative'' ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney admitted that he voted ``a great many times against
sundry and worthy programs'' while he was in Congress because he
didn't think the country could afford them. His priority back then,
he explained, was to reduce the huge federal deficit that loomed
over the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he added, the economy has improved, times have changed,
and, he suggested, so have his priorities. For one, he would no
longer vote against Head Start, a program designed to boost
educational opportunities for disadvantaged children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have surpluses. And we do have the opportunity, I think,
to go out and do some things that we might have opposed 20 years
ago,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, according to this theory, government can now
afford to be more ``compassionate'' because heavy budgetary storm
clouds have disappeared. Hence the conclusion that Cheney is ready
to practice fair-weather compassion.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, Bush also may be merely a fair-weather
``compassionate conservative,'' because he has been blessed with a
strong economy during his tenure as Texas governor and hasn't had
to practice the difficult belt-tightening that his three immediate
predecessors did.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, it is not difficult to predict which word
would be the first to fall from the ``compassionate conservative''
balancing act if economic storm clouds were to reappear under a
Bush-Cheney administration.
</P>
<P>
   Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
