<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BANK-JOB-CUTS-660&AMP;ADD     07-28 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-JOB-CUTS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK OF AMERICA ANNOUNCES JOB CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)   By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bank of America, the United States' largest bank, announced on
Friday that it would cut between 9,000 and 10,000 jobs over the
next year, or roughly 6.7 percent of its work force, and use the
savings to improve its Internet offerings, enhance its brand and
improve services, especially for wealthy individuals and corporate
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-level and senior managers are expected to be the
principal target of the cuts, along with workers whose jobs will be
erased by new technology. With these new steps, roughly 34,000 jobs
will have been eliminated at the bank since September 1998, when it
was created by the merger of NationsBank in Charlotte, N.C., and
the original Bank of America, in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Those two cities remain the primary addresses for senior
executives, but a company spokesman at the bank's headquarters in
Charlotte declined on Friday to say where the cuts would be made.
``They will really come across the franchise,'' said Robert L.
Stickler. The bank currently employs 150,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our days of growth by merger and acquisition are behind us,''
said Hugh L. McColl Jr., the bank's chairman and chief executive,
in a statement announcing the plan. ``For the most part, our merger
transition work also is behind us.'' The challenge now, he said, is
to make the bank's management structure, the product of multiple
mergers over the years, more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   The key interpreter of the new strategy to Wall Street on Friday
was Kenneth D. Lewis, the bank's president and chief operating
officer. Reducing management costs without alienating customers
will be something of a final exam for Lewis, 53, who is widely seen
as heir apparent to McColl, 65, who is expected to retire next
year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Friday, Lewis emphasized that the job cuts do
not contradict the bank's announced determination to improve
customer satisfaction. In fact, he said, some of the savings will
be used to identify specific customer complaints and fix them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, the bank gets a huge number of requests from
customers who want a copy of their canceled checks,'' Lewis said.
For each request, bank employees have to look the check up on
microfilm, copy it and mail it to the customer _ a process that
requires many people and still provides the customer with a
poor-quality copy that arrives days after the request.
</P>
<P>
   By investing in new imaging technology, Lewis continued, the
bank can eliminate 800 jobs and enable customers to look up
canceled checks online or even at an automated teller machine.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis acknowledged that making the strategy work ``is something
I'm in charge of,'' but he said that McColl ``was very supportive
of what we wanted to do.'' He declined to comment on McColl's
retirement plans, however.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks at the bank will inevitably be felt in the economy
of Charlotte, a city it has come to dominate, said C.W. Sealey,
chairman of the finance and business law department at the
University of North Carolina-Charlotte. But ``so long as they don't
slip too far,'' the impact should not be too severe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stickler said the company has a ``competitive'' severance plan
to cushion job losses for management employees, who began to hear
rumors of the job cuts about two weeks ago. The bank expects to
incur a charge against its third-quarter earnings of as much as
$350 million, reflecting severance costs and other expenses
involved in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts and institutional investors seemed to take
the news in stride. On a down day in the market, bank stocks were
particularly weak Friday, reflecting investor concern that bank
profits would be hurt if a strong economy prompted the Federal
Reserve Board to increase interest rates again.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, Bank of America's shares were stronger than most.
Its shares closed at $46.50, down 25 cents. That is nevertheless
substantially below its high of $76.375, which it reached last
July.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The bank's top executives have reassured analysts that they
still expect to meet their revenue and profit forecasts, said Ron
Mandle, a senior research analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein. The bank
expects revenues to grow between 7 percent and 9 percent per year,
with earnings per share increasing between 12 percent and 15
percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mandle, that would allow the bank to meet Wall
Street's profit expectations for the current year, about $5.21 a
share, and perhaps exceed them next year, when earnings are now
expected to be $5.76 a share. ``They're really just changing the
mix, not making absolute cuts,'' the analyst added.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the bank's new ``to-do'' list is to steer an
additional $70 million into ``e-commerce initiatives'' in the next
six months and speed up the introduction of Internet technology at
its bank offices and call centers. The bank, which serves 30
million households and 2 million businesses, currently has about
14,500 branches in 21 states and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The bank expects to reduce the number of branches by about 200
by the end of the year, Stickler said, but that entails closing 350
offices and opening 150 new branches in more promising locations.
</P>
<P>
   Another element of the new strategy involves investing more in
investment-banking operations at home, in Europe and in Asia, to
serve business customers in 190 countries abroad. Through a prior
merger, the new bank inherited the Midwestern corporate business of
the old Continental Illinois Bank in Chicago, Mandle noted, and it
continues to serve the corporate customers of Bank of America and
NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   McColl and Lewis also plan to promote the bank's brand more
aggressively, through increased advertising, and cater more
energetically to high-income individuals by improving their
asset-management services and opening 10 new private banking
offices in wealthy regions, especially on the West Coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
