<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-PLATFORM-ART-N     07-28 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PLATFORM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-ABORTION FORCES WIN BATTLE OVER ABORTION PLANK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Calif., Tenn., Wis.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republicans fought passionately Friday over
abortion, with the anti-abortion forces easily prevailing, as the
platform committee made its way through a document intended to
balance the party's core conservatism with Gov. George W. Bush's
attempt at a more centrist appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights supporters tried to remove the platform's
abortion plank, which calls for a total ban on the procedure, and
tried to insert a provision declaring that the party recognized
differing views on the issue. Both amendments were overwhelmingly
defeated in subcommittee votes, and later by the full committee, in
a debate that highlighted the party's continuing fault lines.
</P>
<P>
   After an abortion rights supporter read a letter from 11 members
of the House and Senate, asking for change in the platform,
Meribelle Bolton of New Mexico declared: ``You have to understand
that many of us are under a higher authority than the Congress of
the United States, the Supreme Court or any state. I am under the
authority of the creator of the universe, and he is pro-life _
always has been, always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Toni Casey of California, who offered the amendment to remove
the abortion plank, argued, ``We need a platform that recognizes
and understands that abortion is a sensitive, it is a delicate, and
it is a personal, moral issue between a woman and her own religion,
when she is faced with that very, very difficult and complex
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's vote was not surprising; Bush and Republican leaders
had indicated early on that they wanted no changes in the abortion
plank, which calls for a ban on abortion without exception, and the
appointment of judges who respect ``the sanctity of innocent human
life.'' They were keenly aware that four years ago, the party's
nominee, former Sen. Bob Dole, sought to add a ``tolerance''
clause, only to suffer an embarrassing defeat at the hands of the
anti-abortion forces.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, abortion rights supporters said they were disappointed
but not completely defeated, still holding out the hope that they
can get the support of a majority of six state delegations, the
first step toward bringing the issue to the floor of the full
convention, or perhaps getting a minority report reflecting their
views out of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on it,'' said Susan Cullman, head of the
Republican Pro-Choice Coalition. Ann Stone, head of Republicans for
Choice, asserted, ``This is round one. We have many more to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives pushed back on other issues, including gay rights.
They reinserted language, dropped in an initial draft, that
declares, ``We do not believe sexual preference should be given
special legal protection or standing in law.'' In debating the
measure, several delegates argued that it was important to take a
stand for the traditional family at a time when there was a
movement to recognize civil unions among gays.
</P>
<P>
   The day's deliberations reflected a party acutely aware of
Bush's political needs, and his efforts to appeal to swing voters
on issues like education, but also unwilling, at times, to
compromise on core beliefs. Some of the biggest fights, for
example, came on the platform's section on education, with
conservatives resisting a strong federal role on what they argued
should be a matter for state and local communities and families.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 platform, for example, called for the abolition of the
Department of Education; the draft developed by party leaders and
the Bush forces did not. But conservatives amended that draft in
subcommittee Friday to say that the role of the federal government
in education ``must be progressively limited,'' and were clearly
resistant to much of the detailed education agenda put forward by
Bush. ``It's a sharp shift,'' said Sen. Bill Frist of Tennessee, a
co-chairman of the platform committee, referring to Bush's emphasis
on education as a national issue.
</P>
<P>
   The platform committee, pushed hard by its chairman, Gov. Tommy
Thompson of Wisconsin, was reading and voting on the platform into
the night, and expected to finish its work on Saturday. The full
convention will act on the platform on Monday. The committee is
working so fast that part of the ``tolerance'' provision on
abortion was passed Friday night, until several delegates said they
were confused about what they were voting on and asked to
reconsider their vote. It then was defeated. Stone of Republicans
for Choice said, ``Just think, we were welcome for ten or fifteen
minutes; that's real progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
