<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6376 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-28 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CONVENTIONAL WISDOM: ONLY BUSH MATTERS
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge says he didn't want
it.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman says she didn't expect it.
</P>
<P>
   Former-lots-of-things Dick Cheney says he had to be persuaded to
take it.
</P>
<P>
   So go the still unfolding reports on the ultimate choice of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush for Cheney to be the Republican candidate
for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   What does the Cheney selection say about Bush, who will accept
the GOP nomination for president here this week?
</P>
<P>
   Was he bold? Was he boringly cautious? Was he brave? Or was he
politically chicken?
</P>
<P>
   In reality, there probably is an element of truth in all the
contentions and assumptions being &QL; 
bandied about here.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in reality, so what?
</P>
<P>
   Ridge and Whitman, to varying degrees, favor abortion rights.
So, of course, despite his stout denials, does Bush.
</P>
<P>
   His is just a much softer favoring, one the super-strong
anti-abortionists are willing to accept even though it is totally
illogical. Bush says he firmly opposes taking the life of a child _
in his view, a fetus, no matter how undeveloped it may be. On the
other hand, he willingly accepts exceptions in the cases of rape,
incest or for the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   Even more illogical is the enormous importance pro-choice
supporters and anti-abortionists alike placed on the views of
Bush's selection of a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   In the big scheme of things, what difference does it make what a
vice president thinks about much of anything?
</P>
<P>
   If any accept the notion a candidate can only express his true
views by his choice of a running mate who has open political and
philosophical conflicts with him, then surely they're as screwed up
as the duplicitous candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably in selecting former Secretary of Defense Cheney,
whose one-time record as a Republican congressman from Wyoming
demonstrates his no-exception opposition to abortion, Bush has
avoided any public dissent from the dominant anti-abortion side at
this GOP nomination convention.
</P>
<P>
   And, certainly the views offered by Whitman and Ridge to
newspapers in their individual states prove each is committed to
trying to help Bush achieve his goal of being nominated at an
upbeat convention without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   As Whitman told a New Jersey newspaper, she not only is
convinced her pro-choice position had no effect on Bush's choice,
but she intends to try to keep abortion from becoming an open point
of dissension at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a fight over something that, at the end of the day,
doesn't determine policy may be soul-satisfying, but I don't think
gets us to the point that we want to get to, which is to win the
election in November,'' Whitman was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tone of considerable skepticism in a Philadelphia
Inquirer story about Ridge's revelation he told Bush on July 5 not
to consider him because he did not want to be apart from his
teen-age children. He said he did not reveal this publicly because
Bush asked him not to as the Texan wanted to ``preserve his
options.''
</P>
<P>
   In recalling Ridge's words in a later interview, the reporter
called the response ``vintage Ridge, an artful dodge sprinkled with
humility and a slice of what seems like candor. ... Ridge was
playing a political game.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats quoted in the story leaped to blast the Bush campaign
for keeping Ridge's decision a secret, calling it a con designed to
keep ``moderates'' hanging in hope _ ``a cynical shell game.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Whitman, Ridge stressed his first loyalty is to Bush. And
not totally unlike the more subtle Whitman, he said he believes his
chances of being chosen, had he not withdrawn himself from
consideration, were ``pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there is a sprinkling of abortion-rights supporters who
still hope to organize a move to change _ even remove _ the
intensely strong anti-abortion language from the GOP platform,
Whitman and Ridge have made it clear they oppose such a move.
</P>
<P>
   And, though there are GOPers of more moderate persuasions and
pundits of various ilks who have taken Bush to task for tapping the
clearly conservative Cheney as his running mate, Whitman and Ridge
have made it clear they do not concur.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, it is abundantly clear this convention is
virtually certain to achieve that for which it has been carefully
designed. That is, for it to end in accord and ardent dedication _
dedication to returning a Republican to the presidency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
