u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      07-28 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN TELLS BUSINESS LEADERS HE RUNS THE COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Vladimir Putin met on Friday with more than
20 of Russia's top business leaders to impress on them that he,
ultimately, is the one who runs the country.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the session at the Kremlin, some of the business
leaders said they were prepared to forgo special treatment and
abide by government rules if the Kremlin would create a fairer
business climate.
</P>
<P>
   In return, they said that they had won Putin's assurance that
they could hold onto their wealth and that their post-Soviet
purchases of state property would not be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received confirmation that the results of privatization
won't be reviewed and that the development of Russian business is
one of the state's top priorities,'' said Mikhail Khodorkovky, the
head of the Yukos oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Since his election in March, Putin has sought to strengthen the
Kremlin's authority by downgrading the power of regional governors
and the influence of business over government policy.
</P>
<P>
   This contrasts with the approach of his predecessor, Boris
Yeltsin, who maintained close relationships with powerful business
leaders, allowing them to roam the halls of power and hold
government positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin's system relied on a spider web, and he was in the
center, said Lilya Shevtsova, a senior associate at the Carnegie
Foundation. ``Putin demolished this. He wants to be alone on the
top of the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nation in where the rule of law is more a slogan than
practice and where there is no shame over egregious conflicts of
interest, it remained to be seen whether today's meeting signaled a
real turning point in rooting out corruption and favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear, for example, whether Putin is really prepared
to challenge vested interests and clean up government or whether
his main intent is to make the business leaders subservient to
himself and punish those who had failed to support him.
</P>
<P>
   The business leaders who were summoned to the Kremlin on Friday
included the heads of Gazprom, the natural gas monopoly, and
several major Russian oil companies and an array of bankers and
business executives. But in a disquieting sign that politics still
weighed heavily in the Kremlin's calculations, there were
conspicuous absences.
</P>
<P>
   Among those not invited to the meeting was Vladimir Gusinsky,
the media tycoon who was briefly jailed only to see the charges
against him dropped. Also absent was Boris Berevosky, the media and
oil magnate, who resigned from the parliament last week, charging
that Putin was involved in a ``destructive'' campaign against
business.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, for example, has gone out of his way to pressure
Gusinsky, whose television network has been critical of the
Russia's military campaign in Chechnya and was relatively
independent during the presidential election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Putin opened the session with a mild lecture, those present
said. The tone was decidedly different than that used during the
Yeltsin administration, when Yeltsin would gently chide the
business leaders, play them off against one another and than seek
their backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to draw your attention to the fact that you built this
state yourself, to a great degree through the political or
semi-political structures under your control,'' Putin was quoted as
telling the tycoons. ``So there is no point in blaming the
reflection in the mirror. So let us get down to the point and be
open and what is necessary to do to make our relationship in this
field civilized and transparent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Putin government this week began investigating why oil
companies are paying different tax rates, and at Friday night's
meeting for the first time Putin called the Sibneft Oil Co. to task
for not paying enough taxes. Until now, Putin has not taken any
action against Roman Abramovich, a friend of Yeltsin's family and a
major Sibneft shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   While ruling out a reversal of privatization, the president
pointedly refused to offer amnesty to the business leaders for
their excesses in amassing wealth in the chaos and legal vacuum
that followed the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the business leaders appeared to be on the defensive,
and took a conciliatory stance. Vladmir Potanin, the chairman of
the board of Interros, which controls Norilsk Nickel, one of the
world's largest mining and metallurgical concerns, has been
particularly eager to seek an accommodation with Putin, especially
after the Moscow prosecutor raised questions about the terms of the
Norilsk Nickel privatization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business finally understands that using loopholes in the law
is not correct,'' Potanin said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, said the government still had a lot to do if it
was serious about fighting crony capitalism. For example, it has to
cut tax rates to encourage compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the tax rates are lowered every businessman is a
criminal,'' said Kakha Bendukidze, the new head of Uralmash, a
heavy equipment manufacturer whose previous president was slain in
a contract killing earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   While Putin has the upper hand some key issues remain
unresolved, and the two sides agreed to meet again.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Nemtsov, the former deputy prime minister and
self-proclaimed economic reformer who helped organize Friday s
session, insisted that the meeting marked a new period. Russia's
businessmen are prepared to be more responsible, he said, so long
as their newly acquired wealth will be respected by state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oligarchs are fed up with being oligarchs, Nemtsov said.
``They just want to be businessmen and pay their taxes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
