<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6385 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-28 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CUE THE `SPONTANEOUS' DEMONSTRATIONS
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ During the Republican National Convention at
Miami Beach in 1972, some overeager young things handed out copies
of the minute-by-minute schedule that the White House had ordained
for Richard Nixon's second coronation. Even the ``spontaneous''
floor demonstrations were slotted in precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Aghast that its intricate stage management had been revealed,
Nixon's high command ordered the scripts recalled, and tearful
go-fers skittered among journalists begging for the telltale
document to be handed back.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance. Here was the evidence that the proceedings were as
packaged and plastic as they appeared. The only moment of
spontaneity for the Republicans 28 years ago came outside the
formal confines of the convention, when an exuberant Sammy Davis
Jr. hugged a (how shall I put this) surprised Nixon at a rally
beside Biscayne Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Our innocence and naivete were showing. Why wouldn't a candidate
who had the nomination firmly in hand want to be in absolute
control of what was then hours of virtually gavel-to-gavel network
television coverage?
</P>
<P>
   In truth, shame on politicians who don't use every reasonable
advantage afforded them, and shame on journalists who don't point
out what the politicians are up to. Remember all this as you watch
the quadrennial Republican and Democratic whiz-bangs unfold over
the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Unless things go terribly awry, the Bush and Gore operations
will make Nixon '72 look like parvenus when it comes to convention
orchestration. In three decades political illusion has gone from
being a (poorly) guarded secret to a point of pride for presumptive
nominees. (Note to taxpayers: Enjoy the show, you're paying for the
extravaganzas. The two major parties got $13.5 million each this
year in federal funds from taxpayer check-offs to help stage their
conventions, and even the Reform Party bellied up to the trough for
$2.5 million.)
</P>
<P>
   At times in the campaign, Vice President Al Gore and especially
George W. Bush have shown they can be very focused. Expect their
convention managers to be no less sharply honed in presenting a
tightly scripted message.
</P>
<P>
   There may not be any smoke and mirrors on the elaborate sets,
but there might as well be, both here and in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans will be on the thinnest ice when they attempt to
make you believe they are a diverse lot. Do not take prime-time
appearances by retired Gen. Colin Powell and former National
Security Council official Condoleezza Rice, two very distinguished
black Americans, as evidence that the white-people's party has
suddenly begun to march again to Lincoln's drum. It may sincerely
want to, and Powell and Rice may be fine symbols of the desire, but
it hasn't happened yet. Ditto for the GOP pitch to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The fraud-o-meter will buzz most loudly for the Democrats two
weeks hence when you start to hear phrases such as ``working
families'' and ``targeted tax cuts.'' That's the tired, old
class-warfare pitch. Applauding the loudest will be some
overstuffed union boss with a $40 stogey clenched between his teeth
(unlit, given the California no-smoking rules).
</P>
<P>
   Not to seem too perverse, but with any luck the attempts at
total management will run into trouble, and the national party
meetings will not go as smoothly as planned. While the winning
campaigns have the right to decide who will speak when and make the
program most compelling to targeted voters during the network's
limited prime-time coverage, there remain a few elements beyond
their control.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, the most ticklish point over the last few
conventions has been abortion. The Bush folks have nailed that down
this time around. And the off chance of a small but interesting
floor fight fizzled Friday with the death of the bizarre proposal
to mandate that the smallest-population states hold their
presidential primaries first.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, the clearest threat to the script will be outside
the convention hall _ protesters like those who created havoc at
the World Trade Organization in Seattle and were merely an
unsightly annoyance at the World Bank sessions in Washington.
Organized labor has promised to attempt to keep the lid on, but,
hey, it's the streets, it's Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party show in Long Beach, Calif., the weekend ahead
of the Democrats may be more interesting. Check it out on C-SPAN as
the nets may not deign to cover unless there's blood on the floor
(which given the presence of Pat Buchanan and some of his
bully-boys is not an impossibility).
</P>
<P>
   As for the Republican tea party starting Monday, where is Sammy
Davis Jr. when you need him?
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
