<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-FUJIMOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUJIMOR I INAUGURATED TO THIRD TERM AMID PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
 I -NYT   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ President Alberto Fujimori was inaugurated on
Friday to a third term, as police and demonstrators engaged in
running battles that engulfed the downtown area in tear gas and
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's day began with military marches and a special Mass.
But waves of demonstrators, angered in their belief that he had
been elected in a fraudulent vote, tried to interrupt the
proceedings, only to be turned back by police who used water cannon
and tear gas and fired bullets into the air.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations were far smaller than organizers had hoped.
Still, the protesters threw rocks and sticks at police, set
bonfires at the gates of the presidential palace and vandalized
several government offices. Two people were reported to have died
in fires set Friday, and about 100 people were injured and scores
of protesters were dragged away in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   As Fujimori took the oath of office, opposition congressmen,
some wearing gas masks in a rebuke to the president and carrying
placards demanding new elections, jeered and walked out of the
congressional chamber. But Fujimori made scant reference in his
40-minute address to the turbulence that followed two rounds of
balloting during which, international observer teams and opposition
leaders have charged, there were vote irregularities and dirty
campaign tricks perpetrated by his intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our people are not in agreement with our program,''
Fujimori, 62, acknowledged. ``That's democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But he stopped short of asking for a reconciliation in a nation
that has become increasingly polarized in the two years since
Congress dismissed three judges who ruled that Fujimori was
disobeying the constitution by seeking a third five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech short on rhetorical flare and delivered in a
businesslike fashion, he reminded Peruvians of his past successes
at halting years of hyperinflation and in making peace with
Ecuador. He also promised to ``fortify democracy and generate
employment and well-being with discipline, prudence and realism.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, who is the son of Japanese immigrants, outlined
promises that he would work to improve the judicial system and
reorganize the security services now that two terrorist groups have
been virtually defeated. But he did not address complaints by the
Clinton administration, the Organization of American States and
several Latin American and European governments that he had
governed Peru the last several years in an increasingly
authoritarian manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's remember that in no country in the world does the
minority govern, and certainly not in Peru,'' he said defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   Even as civilian democracy has progressed in Latin American
countries like Mexico, Argentina and Chile, Fujimori has become the
symbol of a countertrend that disturbs many officials in Washington
and around the region. An elected president was overthrown this
year in a coup in Ecuador, and President Hugo Chavez of Venezuela
has appeared to take lessons from Fujimori as he led a populist
crusade.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration has been reluctant to take tough
action against Fujimori because of his commitment to root out drug
trafficking and for fear that the leadership of the opposition is
too erratic to govern.
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Toledo, the opposition presidential candidate who
dropped out of the race a week before the May 28 runoff, originally
said the demonstrators would block the inauguration altogether. But
with his support flagging, Toledo lowered expectations and called
for a strategy to force democratic change in the longer run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This march will not end until the dictatorship falls,'' Toledo
told a rally of 40,000 protestors in downtown Lima Thursday night.
``Fujimori must understand that the people will not stop
demonstrating until there are new elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, mostly students and young workers, traveled
to Lima from around the country by bus, train and even boat along
Amazonian tributaries.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Friday, Fujimori tried to bolster his base of
rural Indians and residents of Lima's shantytowns with repeated
promises that he would make creating jobs his first priority. To
promote development in the Andean highlands, he promised to
stimulate projects to improve irrigation and wool production.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would build 3,000 schools, pave roads in urban
shantytowns and expand supplies of clean water and electricity. He
also vowed to expand a public school breakfast program to include
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highlands must be transformed into something where more
than despair grows,'' he said in what was probably the most
eloquent line of his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori also tried to reassure investors, who in recent weeks
have grown alarmed by his increasingly populist rhetoric. He
promised to curb an expanding government deficit and to keep the
annual inflation rate under 4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
