<HEADLINE>
MONTANA THE STAR AT LATEST HALL OF FAME INDUCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ Hundreds of fans stood outside the Pro Football
Hall of Fame, many of them holding ``Joe Montana Footballs'' as
they waited patiently in hope of an autograph from Saturday's
top-billed inductee.
</P>
<P>
   Considered perhaps the greatest quarterback of all-time,
Montana's acceptance speech is expected to be emotional and
heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know until you get up there, but I expect it'll be
tough,'' said Montana. ``It's more difficult to say the things you
want to say in front of our friends and family because, while it'll
be fun, I'll be glad when it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana has chosen former 49ers owner Edward DeBartolo Jr. as
his presenter, and team officials including Bill Walsh will be in
attendance. Montana's teammate, safety Ronnie Lott, will also be
enshrined, along with former 49er linebacker Dave Wilcox, former
Raider and Charlestown native Howie Long, and Pittsburgh Steelers
owner Dan Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Joe Montana and Ronnie Lott were the best to
every play at their position,'' said Walsh, architect of the ``West
Coast'' system so instrumental in Montana's success. Montana set
the tone for the offense while Lott's reckless abandon and
leadership set the tone on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is one of the 137 living Hall of Famers, 111 of whom are
here this week for one of the greatest sports reunions ever. The
feeling is very much like the gathering of Hall of Famers at Fenway
Park for last July's All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' said David Motts, an executive with the
Hall of Fame. ``You turn around and there's yet another fanous
player. It's chilling to see all of these great players.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots owner Bob Kraft was scheduled to be here, accompanying
Patriots Hall of Famer John Hannah. Also representing the Patriots
is cornerback Mike Haynes, who played half of his career in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who was an All-American from USC, was formerly a
cornerback who eventually found his niche and revolutionized the
safety position. Lott helped lead the 49ers to a 1981 Super Bowl
(XVI) championship and he became the second NFL rookie to return
three interceptions for touchdowns. He went to 10 Pro Bowls in his
14-year career that also included brief stints with the LA Raiders
and New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, who went to eight Pro Bowls, won four Super Bowl rings
(and MVP honors in three) and orchestrated 31 fourth-quarter
comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I had the ability,'' said Montana, who donned
the famous yellow jacket at Friday morning's Mayor's Breakfast.
``For me it was a case of knowing I had to be ready for the day
when I did get the opportunity. I wanted to make sure that once
that moment came I'd be ready to grab it.''
</P>
<P>
   Long was a second-round pick in the 1981 draft of the Raiders,
made it to eight Pro Bowls and won one championship with the
Raiders in 1983-84. In his 13-year career, he sacked the
quarterback 84 times.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox is perhaps the least heralded of the five, but he had a
stellar 11-year career with the 49ers (1964-74). Wilcox was an
outside linebacker, nicknamed ``the Intimidator'' by the many tight
ends who were shut down. Wilcox, 6 feet 3 inches, 240 pounds,
played at Boise Junior College and the University of Oregon. He was
considered a true student of the game and wanted the play to come
his way. ``What I do best is not let people block me,'' Wilcox
often said. ``I just hate to be blocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney, president of the Steelers since 1975 but in his 45th
year with the organization founded by his father, Art, is credited
with helping to modernize the NFL with a management style that
enabled franchises to thrive. Since 1972, the Steelers have won the
AFC Central Division 14 times, the AFC five times, and have won
four Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday, three members of the media were honored at the
breakfast. Longtime NFL broadcaster Ray Scott was awarded the Pro
Football Hall of Fame's Pete Rozelle Radio-Television Award; Tampa
Bay Tribune writer Tom McEwen was the recipient of the Dick McCann
Memorial Award given for distinguished service in the field of pro
football reporting by the Pro Football Writers of America. Also
honored was John Biever of Sports Illustrated for his photograph
entitled ``Way Over the Top'' which was judged as Pro Football
Photograph of the Year in the annual Hall of Fame contest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
