<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERLY REPORT SHOWS STRONG ECONOMIC GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET-NYT, with graphic) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite a pullback in consumer spending, the U.S. economy grew
at a surprisingly robust 5.2 percent annual rate in the second
quarter, the Commerce Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A widely expected slowdown failed to materialize. The economy
actually grew faster in the second quarter than in the first. But
for all its strength, the second quarter offered just enough signs
of weakness to raise doubts about the future of the longest
economic expansion in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Business investment, particularly in computers and software,
sustained the growth, and so did corporate willingness to churn out
consumer merchandise, although consumer sales weakened. Goods
piling up unsold in warehouses and stores accounted for nearly a
percentage point of the 5.2 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
   A surge in federal government spending, mainly for defense and
for the now largely completed 2000 census, added nearly another
percentage point to the growth of the gross domestic product, which
is the value of all new goods and services. But the economy's
future path is in the hands of consumers, whose spending accounts
for most of the now $9 trillion economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is what happens next to consumer demand;
will it rebound,'' said Richard D. Rippe, chief economist at
Prudential Securities. ``My guess is that it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street seemed to agree that economic growth in the second
half of the year would remain well above the 4 percent level. That
is the maximum growth rate that the economy can sustain, in the
Federal Reserve Board's view, before shortages of goods and
services appear and prices rise.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell in expectation that the Fed would raise
interest rates again to slow the economy, if not at its next
policy-making meeting on Aug. 22, then later on. Higher rates
encourage investors to shift their money from stocks into
interest-bearing securities.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department also issued a revision Friday of
economic growth rates going back to the fourth quarter of 1996. The
average quarterly growth rate since then was nudged up to 4.6
percent from 4.5 percent. The revisions helped President Clinton to
declare that economic growth since he took office in 1993 averaged
4 percent a year, ``the best growth America has had since the
Kennedy-Johnson years.''
</P>
<P>
   There were big revisions for last year's fourth quarter and this
year's first quarter, mostly because of inventory swings.
Stockpiles swelled in the fourth, particularly stockpiles of farm
produce, and as a result the growth rate was revised to 8.3 percent
from 7.3 percent. In the first quarter, however, inventories were
drawn down, and growth was reduced to a 4.8 percent annual rate,
instead of the originally reported 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   An upward revision in business investment also played a role in
swelling economic growth in the fourth quarter. In the first
quarter, however, investment in new equipment and software turned
out to be weaker than was originally reported, partly because of a
strike at Boeing Co., which reduced aircraft production.
</P>
<P>
   Business held up its end handsomely in the second quarter. There
was robust spending for equipment, software, office buildings,
warehouses and other commercial buildings. The federal government
also made a strong contribution, raising its spending by nearly 18
percent in the second quarter, after a fall of 14 percent in the
first.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that swing reflected quirks in government accounting,
but the Commerce Department reported a significant increase in
defense spending, not for new weaponry but for various support
functions, including research, weapons repair and personnel
services.
</P>
<P>
   Rising investment holds out the hope of rising productivity. The
new equipment in effect helps workers increase their output and
their employers' revenue. The additional revenue is then available
to feed profits or raise wages, or both, without an increase in
prices. Labor costs, in fact, rose at a fairly mild 4.6 percent
annual rate in the second quarter _ edging up from last year's rate
of increase, but unchanged from the first quarter, the Labor
Department reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation has also risen slowly. The gross domestic products
report includes a price measure that is far broader than the
Consumer Price Index. It showed inflation rising at a 2.5 percent
annual rate in the second quarter. While that rate was higher than
last year's levels, partly because of gasoline prices, it fell from
a 3.3 percent rate in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer, however, will determine the pace of economic
growth in the future, the latest gross domestic product report
suggests. Consumer spending in the second quarter increased at a
rate of only 3 percent, or less than half the 7.6 percent growth
rate in the first quarter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Consumer spending slowed for basically everything, but the
really big slowdown was in motor vehicle sales,'' said Brent
Moulton, associate director of national economic accounts at the
Commerce Department's Bureau of Economic Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   With consumers spending less, inventories of unsold goods built
up at almost double the pace in the first quarter, with most of the
increase in motor vehicles parked in dealers' back lots. The
buildup almost certainly will result in a production slowdown until
the inventories are worked down, said Wynn Van Bussman, corporate
economist at DaimlerChrysler Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you will probably see is a delay or a cutback in the
production of new model cars,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2021EDT &QL; 
