<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6403 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HUNLEY30-COX     07-28 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNLEY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Confederate warship, the first submersible in history to sink
an enemy vessel, is about to escape its own watery grave
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 30.
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ The H.L. Hunley's lonely repose at the bottom
of Charleston Harbor is nearing an end. For archaeologists,
engineers and Civil War buffs who want to raise _ and save _ the
barnacle-encrusted icon of naval history, a high-stakes, high-tech
race against time is about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Since it sank off Sullivans Island on the night of Feb. 17,
1864, the hand-cranked Confederate submarine has rested, largely
undisturbed, in the cool, murky waters of Charleston Harbor, just
1,000 yards from the spot it rammed a fatal torpedo into the side
of the Union sloop of war Housatonic.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after having ushered in the age of underwater warfare, the
Hunley promptly sank with its crew still on board.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in early August, five years after author Clive Cussler
and a team of underwater archaeologists discovered the sub's
location, an ocean-going crane will hoist the 40-foot submarine
from its watery grave _ and begin the process of solving some of
the 136-year-old mysteries that surround the sub.
</P>
<P>
   But the moment its iron hull leaves the waters of Charleston
Harbor, the submarine and everything aboard it will face a new
enemy, one that is even more relentless than the Union ships that
once blockaded these waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute the Hunley reaches the surface, we will have a
ticking time bomb on our hands,'' says Maria Jacobsen, the
archaeologist who will direct the excavation of the interior of the
submarine after it is ashore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that is organic in nature, including human remains,
will begin to deteriorate almost immediately,'' Jacobsen says. ``We
won't have much time before some information is lost forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Divers' inspections of its exterior show nature has been kind to
the Hunley. Archaeologists say the sub filled with sediment soon
after it sank and was quickly covered by mud and sand. The cold,
dark, oxygen-starved conditions preserved the wreck so well that
when divers removed part of the torpedo spar from its hull this
summer, the bolt holding it turned at the touch of a wrench.
Archaeologists think the interior will be in even better shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ship and all of its contents are a true time capsule _ one
huge artifact,'' Jacobsen says. ``Everything that was aboard the
ship when it sank is still there. The whole story is intact. As
archaeologists, we just have to be sure we ask the right
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure that no scrap of information is lost, the Friends of
the Hunley, the nonprofit organization created by South Carolina to
raise public and private funds for the recovery of the sub, has
assembled an internationally recognized team of experts and built a
state-of-the-art 40,000-square-foot laboratory at the old
Charleston naval shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't been ready to do this the right way, and we
didn't have this lab ready, it would have been criminal to even
think about raising the Hunley,'' Jacobsen says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Jacobsen, who has worked on shipwrecks from
Turkey to Texas, the team includes Project Director Robert Neyland,
who directs the Navy's underwater archaeology program; Leonard
Whitlock, a diver and veteran of salvage projects in a dozen
countries; David Conlin, an archaeologist for the Naval Historical
Center; and Paul Mardikian, a French conservator who helped
preserve artifacts from the Titanic. Eight forensics specialists
from the Smithsonian Institution will oversee the handling of any
human remains found on the sub.
</P>
<P>
   The project will cost at least $16 million. After five years of
preparation to raise the Hunley, it is likely to take a decade more
to preserve it and ready it for exhibition at the Charleston
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The first hours and days after the submarine is raised from the
deep will be critical to the success of the project. As it is
hoisted off the bottom, the Hunley will be encased in a cocoon of
metal supports, slings and foam-filled bags that divers have
assembled around it to reduce the strain on its hull. Because the
rivets in the iron-plated hull have loosened over time, the
precautions will prevent the submarine from bursting open like an
overripe melon when it reaches the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Once it is safely aboard the crane barge Karlissa B, the
submarine will be sprayed continually with a mist of seawater as it
is transported up Cooper River to the laboratory. There, it will be
placed in a custom 55-foot-long tank and covered with water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is precious,'' Jacobsen says. ``We hope to have the
Hunley in the tank in less than 24 hours. Once it's safely there,
everyone will breathe a tremendous sigh of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   But archaeologists won't have much time to celebrate. ``The
changes that will begin occurring almost immediately will be like
Damocles' sword hanging over our heads,'' Jacobsen says.
</P>
<P>
   By immersing it in fresh water, project scientists hope to
retard the growth of marine bacteria and fungi that could cause
further deterioration of the exposed submarine. To slow any
changes, the water will be chilled to 50 degrees, requiring the
archaeologists to wear wet suits while they work. To ease any
strain on the hull, the submarine will rest in the tank at the same
45-degree list at which it now rests on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists usually excavate shipwrecks in the sea and
recover only pieces of a ship and its contents. Only a few sunken
ships _ King Henry VIII's Mary Rose in England, the Vasa in Sweden,
and La Salle's ship, the Belle, in Texas _ have been raised and
preserved in their entirety.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Hunley has been placed in the laboratory tank,
scientists will X-ray the entire submarine, mapping the hull with
millimeter precision. A video camera on a fiber optic cable _ an
adaptation of a surgical endoscope _ will then explore the inside.
It may be a month or more before archaeologists venture inside to
begin excavating the contents.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen hopes the excavation can be completed by the end of the
year. A walk-in refrigerator _ the same kind used in morgues _ will
hold any human remains and other organic matter the archaeologists
find.
</P>
<P>
   There already have been some surprises. In preparing the
submarine for raising, for instance, archaeologists discovered that
the attack spar _ the harpoonlike device on the front of the
submarine _ was actually secured at the bottom of the bow, not the
top of the bow as once thought. The lower position made it easier
to plant an explosive charge below the waterline of an enemy ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the real surprises will be on the inside,'' says project
historian Mark Ragan. ``If the Hunley sank because it was too close
to the Housatonic when the torpedo exploded, we will be able to see
where the pressure wave buckled the iron plates.''
</P>
<P>
   Key questions archaeologists hope to answer in the coming months
include: Did the Hunley sink because of that collateral damage or
was it scuttled in keeping with the crew's alleged suicide pact?
How many men _ eight or nine _ were aboard the Hunley when she
sank, and who were they? And what technological innovations in the
little vessel _ so far known only from drawings and sketches _
enabled it to make the first successful submarine attack in
history?
</P>
<P>
   Although each type of item _ leather, glass, wood, brass, tin
and cast iron _ poses special problems for conservators, the
biggest challenge will be preserving the submarine, whose various
metal components have been decaying at vastly different rates for
the past 136 years. The largest objects will require years of
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hunley is like a large whale in a small aquarium,''
Mardikian says. ``It will require constant care. If we don't handle
the sub properly, it could end up as nothing but a pile of dust.
Frankly, to treat each of these materials properly, I think we may
have to take it apart piece by piece, stabilize each piece, and
then put it back together.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Toner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
