<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6405 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BONES30-COX     07-28 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dead sailors may have own secrets to share
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Before sand and silt packed them like
skeletal sardines inside the Confederate submarine H.L. Hunley, the
remains of Lt. George Dixon and his crewmen deteriorated into a
jumble of bones.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what archaeologists believed until a recent
discovery suggested something more exciting _ and creepier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a possibility they are embedded in the sediment
pretty much in the position they died in,'' said state Sen. Glenn
McConnell (R-Charleston), chairman of the state-appointed Hunley
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McConnell added, there's a ``good possibility''
archaeologists will recover fragments of flesh, hair and clothing,
plus skeletons that remain relatively intact.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers believe a churning, back-and-forth rip current
helped preserve the vessel and its victims by piling sand around
its hull. If sediment covered the bodies in as quickly as two to
four months, McConnell said, it's possible the lack of oxygen
prevented crabs and other creatures from devouring the flesh and
ligaments attaching the bones. A lack of oxygen could also have
limited the decay of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody hopes they are still wrapped in their
overcoats,'' said Mark Ragan, the project historian.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it has yet to be confirmed that the crew is inside the
Hunley. But lacking historical evidence that the sailors escaped
the nighttime sinking, archaeologists believe they'll find their
remains during excavation of the Hunley's contents.
</P>
<P>
   And if the remains are well-preserved, modern technology could
allow researchers to learn far more about the men _ and the lives
they led _ than historical accounts have provided.
</P>
<P>
   By examining bones and teeth, for example, a Smithsonian
Institution team expects to learn what kind of health the crewmen
were in and how tall they were, said David Hunt, a skeletal
biologist at the Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers will try to pin down the sailors' ethnic origins by
comparing their skulls with others in the Smithsonian's database,
Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Working with plaster and clay and three-dimensional photographic
images of the skulls, the Smithsonian's specialists will be able to
reconstruct the crewmen's faces.
</P>
<P>
   And by testing the sand for remains of food, it's conceivable
that ``something under the microscope could tell you what their
last meal was,'' said Maria Jacobsen, the project's senior
archaeologist.
</P>
<P>
   Although there's hope the bodies could be relatively
well-preserved, Jacobsen said she still expects to recover a
``jumble of bones,'' along with pieces of shoes and clothing, belt
buckles, tools and navigational gear, such as a depth gauge or
compass.
</P>
<P>
   Hunley researchers have a photograph they believe to be of
Dixon. According to historical accounts, the young lieutenant from
the 21st Alabama Infantry Regiment suffered a leg wound in 1862 at
the battle of Shiloh in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the best clues to help archaeologists identify
any of the remains, said McConnell, the Hunley Commission chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The night before the sub will be raised, an Episcopal church in
Charleston plans a formaors, alongside the Hunley's two previous
crews. Those crews of 13 sailors drowned in test runs of the sub.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B: www.hunley.org;
www.history.navy.mil/photos/sh-us-cs/csa-sh/csash-hl/hunley.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
