<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REVIEW-BURKE30-COX     07-28 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BURKE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Louisiana cop unravels a haunted past
 &HT;    Eds: Embargeod for Sunday, July 30.
 &HT;      FICTION
 &HT;    ``Purple Cane Road'' by James Lee Burke. Doubleday. $24.95. 336
pages.
 &HT;    The verdict: Dave Robicheaux is back with a vengeance.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After appearing in 11 novels, James Lee Burke's Louisiana police
Detective Dave Robicheaux should be as stale as a month-old box of
Krispy Kremes.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to Burke's ability to create new challenges from a
fascinating gallery of rogues, he's back with renewed vigor in
``Purple Cane Road.'' Novelist Carl Hiaasen's South Florida _
crawling with corruption _ is nothing compared with Burke's
territory. From New Orleans to New Iberia, the drug dealers,
prostitutes, crooked cops and dirty politicians outnumber the
crawfish.
</P>
<P>
   In this novel, Robicheaux has to deal with many of these
unsavory characters as well as the mystery of his mother's
disappearance years earlier. Married to a brawling, alcoholic
Cajun, Mae ran off to California with a soldier who slicked his
hair down with Lucky Tiger and filled her head with dreams of
Hollywood. A few weeks later she was back, broke and brokenhearted.
Other men came along, and the last time the middle-aged detective
saw his mother, he was a teenager and she was dancing with a drunk
in a roadhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The memories remained buried for 30 years, along with unanswered
questions about his mother's disappearance. Then one day a pimp
mentions to Robicheaux that Mae died at the hands of two New
Orleans cops who were working for the mob.
</P>
<P>
   In his attempt to uncover the sins of the past, Robicheaux
follows a trail of conspiracy and corruption that leads to high
government officials. More complications arise when the detective
finds new evidence in a murder case that put a sexually abused
woman on death row for killing her molester.
</P>
<P>
   Like the works of Raymond Chandler, two-time Edgar Award winner
Burke's crime novels transcend the mystery genre. His books are
character-driven and written with lush, literary descriptions of
southern Louisiana:
</P>
<P>
   ``That night I dreamed about a sugar harvest in the late fall
and mule-drawn wagons loaded with cane moving through the fog
toward the mill. The dirt road was frozen hard and littered with
stalks of sugarcane, and the fog rolled out of the unharvested cane
on each side of the road like colorless cotton candy and coated the
mules' and drivers' backs with moisture.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the finest prose in the world is meaningless without
an appealing, sympathetic protagonist, and Dave Robicheaux fits
that role perfectly. Like most of Burke's characters, Robicheaux is
flawed and damaged. A recovering alcoholic whose first wife was
killed by shotgun-wielding bad guys, Robicheaux struggles with his
own demons as he dispenses justice _ and sometimes revenge _
swiftly and violently.
</P>
<P>
   In a few of his Robicheaux novels, Burke has shown signs of
being bored with his character. Switching to a Texas setting with
lawyer Bob Holland in ``Heartwood'' and ``Cimarron Rose''
apparently gave the author a second wind. ``Purple Cane'' is one of
his best efforts yet, with writing so vivid that readers can almost
smell the stink of the alleys and swamps and taste the forbidden
Jax beer and bourbon that tantalize Dave Robicheaux every waking
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes about books for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
