<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6410 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SEUSS30-COX     07-28 2119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEUSS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dr. Suess enjoys resurgence
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 30/
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may not feel it yet _ but you will. A punchy, giddy
sensation, like laughing gas, will seep into your noggin. You'll
speak in goofy rhymes. You'll invent weird names for animals _
Hippo-no-Hungus, say, for your overweight beagle. You'll have a
compulsion to balance stacks of boxes unwisely, with the biggest on
top and the smallest on the bottom. On one finger. While hurtling
down a mountain on a car the size of a turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Named Yertle.
</P>
<P>
   You'll catch it: Seuss Fever.
</P>
<P>
   Or you'll have to work overtime to stay immune, with the wave of
Seussian art and entertainment that's ready to break over America
in the coming months. Nine years after his death, Pulitzer
Prize-winning artist and children's author Theodor Seuss Geisel is
enjoying ``a fabulous resurgence.'' The words are from Audrey
Geisel, his widow and kindred spirit (wacky in her own right), who
as chief executive officer of Dr. Seuss Enterprises personally
approves or vetoes all spinoffs from her husband's magical world.
</P>
<P>
   Now on the national stage, or waiting in the wings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Seussical,'' a stage musical that gathers favorite Seuss
characters into an original yarn, begins performances Oct. 15 at
Broadway's Richard Rodgers Theatre after a tryout in Boston. The
core of the superb creative team from 1998's ``Ragtime,'' including
Tony Award-winning set designer Eugene Lee, returns. Lee's sneak
preview: ``We fire these bizarre Seussian double-barrel cannons at
the audience, but only ribbons shoot out _ no lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dr. Seuss' `How the Grinch Stole Christmas,''' the Universal
Studios adaptation of the beloved book, opens Nov. 17. It stars Jim
Carrey as the titular Scroogelike creature who strips Whoville of
its holiday stuff but finds that spirit is a permanent fixture.
Audrey Geisel met Carrey on the set of ``Man on the Moon,'' and
``as I was leaving,'' she says, ``he put his hands on my shoulders,
looked me in the eyes and scrinched, and scrunched, and scroonched
his face into such a wicked smile that I gasped, `My God! It's the
Grinch!'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Secret Art of Dr. Seuss,'' a 1995 Random House volume
depicting Geisel's sculptures and paintings _ some of them
surprisingly provocative, if not anatomically correct _ helped
create a hot market for reproductions at 110 outlets, including the
Ann Jackson Gallery in Roswell (see article at left).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Cat in the Hat,'' the movie, looks as though it will
finally get made. A five-year option by DreamWorks expired after
several screenplays failed to win approval from Steven Spielberg
and/or Audrey Geisel, but she expects to announce a deal with a new
producer soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Seuss Landing, a theme park that opened last year at Universal
Orlando, has a cafe selling green eggs and ham (watch out,
McDonald's!). Palm trees with a weird ``S'' curve in their trunks
(the result of the trees' being almost flattened by Hurricane
Andrew, then resumingvertical growth) and topiaries shaped like
hands create a trippy Seussian landscape.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Oh, the Places You'll Go!,'' Seuss' farewell book of 1990,
recently re-ascended to The New York Times Best Seller List, as it
often does in summer when its words of dizzy wisdom are quoted at
school commencements. Seuss' 47 books sold 100 million copies
during his lifetime, and some of them, including the all-time
favorites, ``Green Eggs and Ham'' and ``The Cat in the Hat,'' are
selling better now than when they broke out in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Oreos with green filling
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, not a bad comeback for a man _ or should we say
ageless kid? _ who worked in a variety of advertising, film and
magazine cartooning jobs well into his 50s, when he finally
achieved literary stardom with his back-to-back children's books
``Cat'' and ``Grinch'' (1957). His middle name was Seuss _ or was
it Mischief? The first time he signed ``Seuss'' on a drawing, in a
Dartmouth College humor magazine in 1921, it was because, as
punishment for a bootleg-gin party, the dean had forbidden him from
publishing cartoons. And he didn't. At least, not under the name
Ted Geisel.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dr.'' in ``Dr. Seuss'' was added later, he said, for the
degree he never got from Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Springfield, Mass., in 1904, the grandson of a
successful German-born brewer, Geisel bestrode the 20th century,
going to Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show as a boy and yet creating,
at midcentury, a look for children's books that still seems almost
futuristic. In the words of Lane Smith, who designed the movie
``James and the Giant Peach'' and consulted on the designs for
``Grinch,'' the movie: ``At a time when kids' readers said, `See
Spot run,' Ted had this big weird cat barge into a house when the
kid's parents weren't home and let Thing 1 and Thing 2 out of a
box! If that's not releasing the id, what is?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted was subversive and educational,'' Smith adds, ``way ahead
of his time.''
</P>
<P>
   So far ahead that America, it seems, is still catching up. Which
raises the question, Why is Seuss so hot at this moment? Why is the
Seuss estate, which until now has not aggressively cashed in on the
artist's images (compared to, say, Disney) and was so picky about
the ``Cat'' scripts, now green-lighting so many projects?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted was never much interested in the commercial end _ in fact,
a couple of times he sent back a large sum of money because he was
not happy with the way his work was being used,'' says lawyer Karl
ZoBell, who handles Dr. Seuss Enterprises affairs from his office
just down the street from the Geisel home on the oceanside bluffs
of La Jolla, Calif. ``Just after his death, there was a flood of
counterfeit stuff _ obscene Seuss T-shirts, for instance. Finally
we accepted the reality that the way to beat these things in court
was to get out there and license products ourselves, with taste and
restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   But those two words don't always describe millennial America.
The Grinch movie, like the sleigh the Grinch uses to rob Whoville,
will whoosh across the nation carrying heaps of Seussian stuff. The
licensed merchandise will include interactive plush toys,
inflatable Who furniture, fur-covered Who shoes and Oreo cookies
with green filling that can be left on the holiday hearth with a
card that says, ``Dear Mr. Grinch: Please don't steal my toys.''
Plus the antlers that the Grinch straps on Max, his woebegone mutt,
to disguise him as a reindeer, in different sizes for your head,
your child's head and, yes, your dog's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in this movie is an original creation, down to the
doorknobs, so it's a once-in-a-lifetime property,'' says Jill
Jones, a vice president of Universal Studios Consumer Products.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders whether college student Ted _ when he doodled a dog
with strapped-on antlers in the margins of his notebook almost 80
years ago _ knew he was creating a ``property.'' One wonders
whether, after holding off the temptations of commercial
exploitation for so long, Dr. Seuss Enterprises is beginning to
give way, like a dam in a flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The licensing agreements exceed our dreams and expectations,''
says ZoBell, ``but it's a only a fraction of what it could be.
There are a thousand (deals) we could be doing, but we only choose
40 to 60. Like I said, taste and restraint.'' ZoBell declines to
put a dollar figure on the deals, but Business Week magazine
estimates that they're worth $7 million to $10 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a dimension
</P>
<P>
   On the artistic side, the Seuss legacy appears to be in good
hands with the creators of the fall's big events, ``Grinch'' and
``Seussical.'' They've given careful thought to the tricky
transformation of Seuss' book illustrations into the
three-dimensional worlds of film and theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grinch'' production designer Michael Corenblith, 49, who teams
again with Ron Howard, his director from ``Apollo 13,'' says his
``Grinch'' sets are a tribute not just to the Christmas tale but
``a celebration of Ted's body of work.'' Viewers should not expect
a live-action replica of the 1966 television version of ``How the
Grinch Stole Christmas'' (which featured the animation of Chuck
Jones and the voice of Boris Karloff), but a story with a more
fully imagined Whoville and Grinch cave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron told me he wanted everything just barely in balance,
miraculously standing up,'' Corenblith said. His Whoville was
inspired by a trip to the famous spiral ramp of New York's
Guggenheim Museum and by a lesser-known, 1949 Seuss book,
``Bartholomew and the Oobleck,'' with depictions of zany circular
stairways and crooked bell towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted soaked these images up from medieval and Moorish
architecture, and they crop up obsessively in his work,''
Corenblith said. The curving, 50-foot-high ``flying bridges'' that
the designer constructed between buildings made Universal
executives nervous, but Corenblith refused to fit them with safety
features, because ``Ted never drew a handrail in his life!'' Cirque
du Soleil acrobats were hired to play the risk-taking Whos.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer Rita Ryack, also in her late 40s, says, ``Dr.
Seuss had a profound influence on me _ he was so witty and skewed.
People remember his work as adorable, but it was a little dark, you
know?'' Accordingly, she dresses Carrey's Grinch in ``a Grim
Reaper's cape'' and ``a sort of Playboy bathrobe, black fishnet.''
</P>
<P>
   To show the ``spoofy Norman Rockwell quality'' of the Whos and
to recapture her own memories of ``the early Seuss books, before
`Cat,''' Ryack insisted on ``costume materials that existed then,
in the '50s.'' Her ``nutty kinetic hats'' rarely sit still on
actors' heads but bob around on the ends of springs.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Seussical,'' the 60-ish Lee is working in an utterly
different style from the rugged architectural mode he pioneered on
Broadway (``Sweeney Todd,'' ``Show Boat''). Adapting the concentric
circles on the cover of ``Oh, the Places You'll Go!,'' he ``made
them the portals into Seuss' world,'' he says. ``In the center of
them, as you enter the theater, you see the Cat in the Hat's hat _
rotating.'' Picking up on the ``tacked-together, Rube Goldberg
quality'' of Seussian objects, Lee also designed a huge, puppetlike
bird, the Tufted Mazurka (``from the island of Yerka''), ``whose
neck is ridiculously long and whose head is ridiculously small,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a handmade quality about these set pieces,'' the
designer adds. ``For instance, when a character spreads some magic
seeds and trees spring up _ it's just a roll drop (with tree
silhouettes) being rolled up from the stage, very old-fashioned
technology. It's more faithful to the character of the Seuss
drawings than some electronic effects might be.''
</P>
<P>
   `Amazed at the fuss'
</P>
<P>
   Faithful is also the watchword of Audrey Geisel, who presides
over Ted's legacy from the La Jolla home they shared. Clearly, his
zany spirit lives in her. She answers the phone, ``Seuss house!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as I sit now, looking at the grand and glorious Pacific,
my feet are on the desk, and that's from him,'' she says. ``Ted's
feet were never not on this desk. He was very lean and limber, but
only in that respect was he like Ichabod Crane. I'm not sure what
that means; make of it what you will. Anyhow, Ted would come
whizzing into this room and say, `I've got an idea and I think it
will work!' Then he'd scuttle back to the studio. But where those
ideas came from, who can say?''
</P>
<P>
   What would he think of his ``fabulous resurgence''?
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be more puzzled than anyone,'' she declares. ``He was
just this side of a humble man, so he was always amazed at the
fuss. Ted was not especially big on kids himself (he had none from
his two marriages) _ they worried him a bit, made him uncomfortable
_ but he understood exactly where they're coming from. He didn't
want his books to be in the classroom, but in the after-school
hours when the kids' minds could be free and outrageous. He'd often
ask me, `Am I being too preacher-ish?,' because he had a fear of
that, but in some subtle way his values were always in there.''
</P>
<P>
   What was his greatest tribute?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Princeton commencement, near the end of his life,''
his widow recalls. ``He was about to speak when the entire
graduating class stood up. They recited `Green Eggs and Ham' _
every ... single ... word, perfectly, as if with one voice. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Geisel pauses for a moment, her voice becoming thick with
emotion _ then releases the tension with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy,'' she cries, ``Ted didn't see that one coming!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
