<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6411 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GANSTA-TOUR30-COX     07-28 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANSTA-TOUR30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tour putting better face on gangster rap
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 30.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man who set gangster rap to music 13 years ago is bringing
his first-ever national tour to Atlanta on Friday, and it's hard to
decide which is the most interesting detail.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that producer Dr. Dre is on a 40-city tour with the
artists who have made the most of his sinister rhythms is kind of
like an official announcement that hip-hop's most offensive
subgenre is back. Big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Dre 2001'' has remained in the Top 25 on Billboard's pop
chart since its November 1999 debut (22 of those weeks it was in
the Top 10) and sold more than 5 million copies _ matching the
sales of the most recent project he has produced, Eminem's album
``The Marshall Mathers LP,'' No. 1 for the past eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite offstage troubles that include at least five pending
criminal charges, the ``Up in Smoke'' concert lineup onstage is
proving that a hip-hop performance can be as much of a smooth,
elaborate production as the artists' videos. And people who attend
these shows can behave themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Which has been in doubt for some time.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, rap fans had to spend much of the 1990s content with
seeing their favorite artists only on BET or MTV, because promoters
refused to book them, venues didn't welcome them or it cost way too
much to secure them.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that when the occasional rap show did occur _
usually in a club _ it was rarely good.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a banner hanging from the ceiling with the artist's
name on it, that was considered flashy. You could forget about an
actual set, dancers, costumes or that kind of thing. ``Rappers
showed up late, walked from one side of the stage to the other like
a caged panther and left,'' remembers Hot-97.5 radio announcer Ryan
Cameron. ``Usually early.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1997, the party- and clothes-minded Sean ``Puffy'' Combs
launched his 25-city ``No Way Out'' tour, taking the lineup of
radio-friendly rap and R&AMP;B artists to major venues across the
country, including Atlanta's Georgia Dome. The somewhat more
profane Jay-Z followed in 1999 with the ``Hard Knock Life'' tour,
and though it didn't have the pyrotechnics and costume changes of
``No Way Out,'' it was the first major-venue, all-rap tour since
Run-DMC's in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Cash Money/Ruff Ryders tour _ which
combined the material excesses of Combs and the profanity of Jay-Z
with its own sexual explicitness _ hit the country with only one
major incident, when five people were stabbed backstage in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the big Up in Smoke gangster rap tour, which started
June 15 in San Diego and is set to end Aug. 20 in Denver. The
four-hour production, with multiple backdrops, includes a talking
skull; the touted reunion of the first act to receive a threatening
letter from the FBI, N.W.A.; and Eminem, the object of ire from
many gay rights and women's groups.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its negative images, organizers of the event, who
include basketball star Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson, say they are
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the performers haven't been dogged by personal
troubles. Eminem's wife attempted suicide, and police in Detroit
made him clothe the blow-up dolls he uses in his act. The bill's
only singer, Nate Dogg, was charged with beating up his girlfriend
and setting fire to her mother's car. And Detroit officials
threatened to arrest performers if they showed an eight-minute
video in which Dre and Dogg hang out with topless women, then shoot
some robbers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, none of that has affected performances. All the
headliners have made every show, promoters say, and the shows have
run on time. Most of the reviews of this decidedly misogynistic,
drug-espousing men's night out have been positive. And industry
magazine Pollstar says it's looking like one of the top-grossing
tours of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take a little controversy over the content _ and it is
insignificant content _ over a substantive issue like a security
problem or violence any day,'' promoter Bill Silva told The New
York Times. ``We're firing on all cylinders.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything is going up in smoke, it could be the widespread
underestimation of this music's appeal and potential, despite its
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Up in Smoke Tour
</P>
<P>
   With Dr. Dre, Snoop Dogg, Eminemand Warren G. 8 p.m. Friday. $30
lawn, $45 reserved at Ticketmaster, 404-249-6400 or
www.ticketmaster.com. Lakewood Amphitheatre, 2002 Lakewood Way S.W.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
