<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6413 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GA-SENATE0729-COX     07-28 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SENATE0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four Republicans mull run against Miller
 &HT;    By Alan Judd and James Salzer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The potential Republican field for the U.S. Senate
apparently is down to four.
</P>
<P>
   State School Superintendent Linda Schrenko; former Sen. Mack
Mattingly; Lewis Jordan, the man who ran ValuJet Airlines; and Rep.
Jack Kingston are the final Republicans considering a run for the
Senate seat formerly held by the late Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   None went so far Friday as declaring for the Nov. 7 special
election. But all were weighing their options as next week's
candidate qualifying period approaches. Schrenko said she would
decide today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the boys bow out, I think I'll keep my name in the
hat,'' Schrenko said. ``All things being equal, I would rather be
in the majority in Washington than in a minority in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly, who held the post from 1981 to 1987, and Jordan both
expressed strong interest in the race Friday, said Chuck Clay,
chairman of the Georgia Republican Party. Repeated efforts to reach
both potential candidates were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's in their laps as to whether one, both or
neither will get in,'' Clay said of Mattingly and Jordan. ``The
longer it goes, the more likely it is for more people to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kingston said in Washington that he will wait to see
whether any of the others run before he makes a final decision. The
rest of the eight Republicans in Georgia's congressional delegation
have already declined to run.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Zell Miller, a Democrat, took over Coverdell's
Senate seat this week and will run in the nonpartisan special
election.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have become increasingly frustrated by their
inability to recruit a single top-tier candidate to challenge
Miller, a popular and well-known political figure whose approval
rating topped 80 percent when he left the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly held the seat for one six year-term, then lost in 1986
to Democrat Wyche Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has never sought public office. He is best known for his
handling of the aftermath of a ValuJet plane in the Florida
Everglades in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Schrenko has twice won statewide elections and has been
mentioned as a possible candidate for governor in 2002. The state
Constitution would require her to give up her current post if she
sought the Senate job, said Chris Riggall, a spokesman for
Secretary of State Cathy Cox, Georgia's chief elections officer.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent said she is torn between wanting to keep the
U.S. Senate seat Republican and abandoning state teachers in their
political fight with Gov. Roy Barnes over education reform.
</P>
<P>
   Schrenko said she isn't necessarily counting on backing from the
Republican Party establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I sit around and wait for the good old boys to decide it's
my turn,'' she said, ``I'll be 99 and they'll say, 'Just wait one
more year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clay said he expects Schrenko would run only ``if all those
(other) bets are off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a team player,'' Clay said. ``She's not sitting out
there spitting and stomping, wanting to get into the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
