A6415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEXICO-U.S.-WTO-NYT &LR;      07-28 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-U.S.-WTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ASKS TRADE ORGANIZATION FOR HELP IN MEXICAN PHONE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just weeks before Mexico's president-elect, Vicente Fox, is
scheduled to make his first visit to Washington to discuss
commercial relations with the United States, the Clinton
administration took the first steps on Friday toward filing a
formal complaint against Mexico for failing to ensure open
competition in its $12-billion telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
   As she had warned several times since April, Charlene
Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, is asking the World
Trade Organization to hold formal consultations between the United
States and Mexico on the way Mexico supervises its recently
deregulated telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   Several American corporations, including AT&AMP;T and WorldCom, have
invested millions in Mexico since deregulation began in the
mid-1990s. They have complained for the last year that they have
been stymied by the actions of Telefonos de Mexico, the dominant
carrier, and by weak-kneed Mexican regulators who have failed to
stand up to the company, known as Telmex.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, along with Mexican partners, owns Alestra, a long-distance
company. WorldCom owns a controlling share of Avantel, another
long-distance company, also with Mexican associates.
</P>
<P>
   The trade representative accuses Telmex of several
anticompetitive actions. The United States contends that Telmex
overcharges to connect local calls to the long-distance networks,
applies unfair fees for incoming international long-distance phone
calls and denies competitors the high-traffic lines they need for
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications regulators are accused of failing to properly
enforce deregulation commitments to which Mexico agreed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become a sore point in commercial relations
between the United States and Mexico, its second-largest trading
partner, giving rise to harsh statements in a field usually noted
for diplomatic restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the regulatory system in Mexico is entirely broken,''
Barshefsky said in a conference call with reporters on Friday
morning. She said she had little faith that Mexican officials in
the outgoing administration of President Ernesto Zedillo would keep
promises to resolve the regulatory issues before Fox is inaugurated
on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard that song before,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, Jorge Nicolin, president of the Federal
Telecommunications Commission, said the trade representative's
complaint was ``unfounded and not substantiated.'' He said he was
confident Mexico would successfully defend its position.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolin said Mexican officials had met with American trade
officials ''three times already this year, and as we explain at
every step, it is because we have competition in Mexico that we
have these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   By Nicolin's count, 12 competing long-distance carriers operate
in Mexico, along with 7 local carriers. He acknowledged that
competitive problems existed but said formulation of new
regulations to promote competition had been delayed by legal
challenges from Telmex and other telephone companies. They should
be ready by the end of October, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Telmex spokesman, Arturo Elias Ayub, rebutted the trade
representative's argument that Telmex had actually increased its
share of the long-distance market to 81 percent from 74 percent
three years ago. ``We wish it were that high,'' he said, contending
that Telmex handled no more than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If no settlement is reached within 60 days after the World Trade
Organization consultations begin, Barshefsky said the United States
would file a formal complaint before the WTO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6416 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-KENNEDY-SECURITY-N     07-28 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KENNEDY-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY HOSTAGE-TAKING SEEN AS PRICE OF AVOIDING GUNFIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Nev.)   By JOHN SULLIVAN and RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Airport security checkpoints, with their squads of
guards and phalanxes of metal detectors, are considered by most
passengers to be a kind of firewall, designed to stop weapons from
getting anywhere near airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   But airline security officials have long acknowledged that the
checkpoints are really meant to do only part of that job: They are
supposed to detect hidden guns or bombs and provide a system for
alerting armed police officers. If someone brandishes a gun and
tries to force his way past, the officials said, the unarmed
security officers at the checkpoints are not only unable to stop
him, they are not supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   This fact was frighteningly underscored late Thursday night in
Terminal 4W at Kennedy International Airport, when Aaron Commey, a
22-year-old Milwaukee man, approached a security supervisor, waved
a 10-millimeter automatic handgun, ran around the metal detectors
and dashed directly out an elevated Jetway at Gate 33. He then
boarded a National Airlines Boeing 757 set to fly to Las Vegas and
took the pilot and co-pilot hostage.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt during the takeover, and officials at Kennedy
airport insisted Friday that their security procedures had worked
as they should have: Armed police officers responded in less than
three minutes, no shots were fired and hostage negotiators
succeeded in persuading Commey to give himself up.
</P>
<P>
   But to many of the passengers who were boarding the National
Airlines jet, the security system seemed to have left them
shockingly vulnerable. Unlike the security checkpoints throughout
most of the rest of the airport, the checkpoint for the National
Airlines flight was unusually close to the door to the Jetway,
meaning that there was next to no time for flight attendants to
close the door and prevent him from boarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police came very fast, but there was no security,'' said
Marcus Weiss, one passenger interviewed shortly after the takeover
began. ``The guy just walked right on through. It's really really
strange. The airport security working there weren't armed. They
couldn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy airport officials and many other airline security
experts said Friday that the proximity of the checkpoint to the
gate probably had little to do with what happened, because Commey,
pointing a gun, probably could have gone through many other
checkpoints located farther from gates and still made his way onto
a plane.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials agreed Friday that the incident was exactly
the kind that, despite various strategies over the years, has long
been considered virtually unpreventable.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, beginning in 1973 after a spate of hijackings,
security screening points were set up in all the country's airports
and they were guarded by armed police officers. But in 1978, the
Federal Aviation Administration and the airline industry agreed to
discontinue the practice, in part because they considered it more
dangerous than the possibility of a gunman forcing his way through
the checkpoint area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a firing range,'' said Homer A. Boynton, who directed
security for American Airlines from 1981 to 1993. ``There was a
unanimous decision among the people in the airline industry and the
people in the FAA that it was a wise choice to take the armed guard
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John Torres, the operations captain at Kennedy airport,
said that he believed people could have been hurt if guards had
been armed or had tried to stop Commey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a potential for a shootout in a crowded terminal with
passengers walking around,'' said Torres, one of the Port Authority
police officers who directed the response to the hostage situation
Thursday night. He added: ``Security did the right thing. They did
not try to take an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Torres and other officials said, the security guards _
who do not work for the Port Authority but for a private company
under contract to the airlines _ pushed what is known as a covert
button as soon as Commey sprinted past the metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   The button sounded an alarm that summoned armed Port Authority
police officers. Al Graser, deputy director of the aviation
department for the Port Authority, said that at least one officer
is stationed in each of the six terminals at Kennedy airport.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, officers once were required to respond to a
security checkpoint within one minute in an emergency, but over the
years, as the number of hijacking attempts dropped, the requirement
was relaxed to five minutes, Graser said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Torres said, the police response time was two
to three minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6424 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-WASH-PA-CONGRESS-ART-     07-28 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASH-PA-CONGRESS-ART-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY LOYALTY ELUSIVE IN NATION'S LAST 2 `SWING' CONGRESSIONAL
DISTRICTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic and a map are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINA, Wash. _ Dan McDonald and Stewart Greenleaf, two veteran
Republican state legislators, share a special reason for confidence
in their efforts to oust Democratic incumbents from the U.S. House
of Representatives this fall.
</P>
<P>
   For they are running in the two true ``swing'' House districts
left in the United States, not districts that just look like juicy
targets to the party on the outside, but districts that regularly
switch from the control of one party to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Each of their districts _ Washington's 1st, where McDonald
challenges Rep. Jay Inslee, and Pennsylvania's 13th, where
Greenleaf runs against Rep. Joseph M. Hoeffel _ has changed hands
three times in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that swing districts were the bellwethers of
national politics, closely watched as the parties slugged it out
with issues and insults election after election. But in the 1950s
their numbers began to decline as parties receded in importance and
congressional candidates ran increasingly on their own, raising
their own money and, once they were in power, inventing dozens of
perks to help solidify incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   The vanishing swing district is one of the most telling examples
of how the nature of congressional election politics has changed.
For all the talk of a momentous battle for control of the House,
where Republicans now hold an 11-seat majority, there is real
competition in only a handful of districts _ fewer than three
dozen.
</P>
<P>
   These two genuine swing districts, 2,800 miles apart, have a lot
in common. Both are overwhelmingly white suburbs of broad lawns and
shopping malls, where most adults have been to college. Both have
above-average incomes and expensive houses. Bill Gates' $60 million
house here, and the more prevalent sports cars on Seattle's
streets, suggest that the Washington district is a little better
off than the Pennsylvania district. In both places, issues like
education, abortion and taxes are on people's minds.
</P>
<P>
   There is no simple reason why these districts in and around
Philadelphia and Seattle have remained so competitive. Other
constituencies with similar demographics and politics have settled
into the hands of one party or the other. But the biggest cause may
be the failure of the Republicans who won these seats back in the
Gingrich Revolution of 1994 to stay in touch with their voters,
hanging on in 1996 but losing in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The single biggest reason for the decline of the old-fashioned
swing district is the set of advantages the system gives
incumbents. They can overcome anything short of tidal waves in
national politics. Thomas Mann, a congressional scholar at the
Brookings Institution, cited resources ``that allow members to
present themselves in favorable light back home, everything from
being able to raise the money to run active, visible campaigns,
travel home on a regular basis with a subsidy and use their
legislative positions for commandeering the attention of the local
media.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps none of those advantages is as important as being able
to help constituents _ finding a lost Social Security check,
getting a visa for a relative to attend a wedding, arranging a
long-forgotten medal for a veteran.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage most easily proven is financial: incumbents raise
more money. This month Inslee reported a campaign cash advantage of
$955,551 to $546,891 for McDonald. Similarly, Hoeffel had $818,468
in the bank to Greenleaf's $440,334.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But those advantages are unlikely to be decisive in a campaign
year when control of the House hangs in the balance. National party
organizations and their front groups, along with special interests
of all complexions, are expected to put total spending in the 30 or
so most competitive House districts at around $5 million each.
</P>
<P>
   The edge that neither challenger can really combat was on
display on a recent Saturday at the Acme Supermarket in East
Norriton Township, Pa., where Hoeffel set up a table full of
government _ not campaign _ literature and met constituents. Some
came because of a government-paid mailing; others were just weekend
shoppers. Several wanted help with tax problems. One wanted Hoeffel
to persuade his insurance company to pay for a particular drug.
</P>
<P>
   Politics came up, too. Voters talked about gun laws and taxes on
married couples. One woman wanted to change her registration from
Republican to Democrat because Republicans tried to extend the
patent on the allergy drug Claritin.
</P>
<P>
   Inslee has been demonstrating another edge of incumbency _
publicity. In recent weeks the Seattle newspapers have reported
that he got the electronic signature bill passed by adding consumer
protections, that he was working on pipeline safety legislation
after a fatal accident at Bellingham last year, and that he was
critical of the judge in the antitrust case against Microsoft,
whose headquarters at Redmond is in his district, and whose
employees contribute heavily to Inslee.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One advantage the Democrat enjoyed two years ago is gone. In
1998, Bruce Craswell, a conservative third-party candidate, took 6
percent of the vote, just a bit more than Inslee's margin over Rep.
Rick White, the Republican incumbent. Most of the Craswell votes
came at White's expense. Without Craswell, the race would have been
about even. This time Inslee is opposed only by McDonald, a
powerful 22-year veteran of the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, McDonald complains about Inslee's votes against
tax cuts, says he wants local school boards to have more authority
in spending federal money while giving them incentives to ease
bureaucratic teacher certification rules. And McDonald, a Vietnam
veteran, said he wanted to strengthen national defense. ``War is a
complete failure of diplomacy,'' he said. ``Diplomacy is helped by
having a sharpened sword.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, McDonald said taxes and education would be the
major differences between him and his opponent. But he also said he
had always voted to restrict abortions, an issue Inslee plans to
attack him on.
</P>
<P>
   Every candidate here advertises his credentials as an
environmentalist. McDonald and Inslee both addressed participants
in a 110-mile hike from the Cascades to Puget Sound this weekend.
The Democrat warned them of politicians ``who just talk green but
vote brown.'' In an interview, he said McDonald was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Inslee argued that campaign finance legislation, including a ban
on unregulated contributions to parties, was essential both to
protect the environment and to protect personal privacy in an
electronic age.
</P>
<P>
   Across the continent, in the suburban district that stretches
from Philadelphia's Main Line out to Valley Forge and Abington,
Greenleaf is also a soft-spoken but powerful state legislator. He
emphasizes local school control, tax cuts and the ``flexible''
Republican drug plan, though on issues like the fear of a ``big
boondoggle'' in the anti-missile program or support for trigger
locks on handguns he emphasized his moderate credentials _
underlined by his support for abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   At a retirement home in Plymouth Meeting, Greenleaf said he had
been recognized as ``effective'' in 24 years in the state capital,
and would be the same kind of congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel boasted of being ``socially progressive and fiscally
responsible,'' and said his budgetary bona fides had been certified
by the Concord Coalition, a bipartisan group. And he argued that
Republicans were captives of the pharmaceutical industry. He called
for ``registration of handguns and licensing of handgun owners.''
</P>
<P>
   One advantage the two Democrats share is that they have both
been through tough campaigns, winning and losing before. Neither
Republican has ever had a real test.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democrats are trying to take their districts out of the
``swing'' category. Only one other district changed hands three
times in the '90s, but that one, the 1st District in Northern
California, now seems safe for its Democratic incumbent, Rep. Mike
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   But even if their districts turn out to be safe from this year's
Republican challengers, they may not be secure for 2002 against the
partisan vagaries of redistricting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
