<SLUG> BC-IVILLAGE-RESIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVILLAGE CEO HANDS TITLE OVER TO PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candice Carpenter, who has come to epitomize the hard struggle
to establish Internet companies in New York, has relinquished the
title of chief executive of iVillage to Doug McCormick, the
company's president. Carpenter, whose move was announced on
Thursday, will remain as chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, a veteran of American Express and QVC, founded
iVillage in 1995 to be an Internet site focusing on topics of
interest to women. As West Coast Internet start-ups were flooded
with venture capital, iVillage struggled to raise money, amid
skepticism both of New York as a technology center and of the idea
of an advertiser-supported Web site, which requires hundreds of
writers and producers to operate.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter was able to raise enough venture capital, and iVillage
went public in March 1999, along with a number of other New York
Internet companies. But iVillage has also been plagued by questions
regarding what employees called Carpenter's mercurial management
style.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the turnover among senior executives is much
higher than at similar companies. Most recently, Craig Monaghan,
the company's fifth chief financial officer, and Allison Abraham,
its chief operating officer, left the company. Last year, Robert
Levitan, one of the three co-founders of the company along with
Carpenter and Nancy Evans, the editor in chief, left to start
Flooz, an online gift-certificate company.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick, who was the chief executive of Lifetime, the cable
network for women, joined iVillage as the No. 2 executive in April.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said on Friday that she had long thought that
McCormick would ultimately rise to be the chief executive, but the
change happened faster than she had originally expected.
</P>
<P>
   With his background in advertising sales, McCormick has the
skills necessary to guide iVillage through the current turbulent
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five and a half years has been a very long haul,'' Carpenter
said. ``I feel happy that we found somebody I feel confident
handing the company to.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said that she would spend more time on strategy,
figuring out the company's international expansion plans, and doing
public speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been the company's face to Wall Street, but now I want
to be the brand persona to women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She will keep an office at the company, but she doesn't expect
to be there five days a week, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's financial results in the second quarter, announced
Thursday, generally pleased analysts. It lost $28.0 million, up
from a loss of $15.0 million share, a year earlier. Its revenue was
19 million, triple the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   But those gains came at a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a true baptism of fire,'' said McCormick of his first
months at the company. Advertising from Internet companies fell,
and the company scrambled to cut costs and increase business from
more established companies. While it has not had any layoffs,
iVillage had scaled back its hiring, planning 380 employees at year
end, down from its earlier forecast of 400, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally favored McCormick's ascension.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very positive for iVillage to hand over the reins to a
seasoned veteran like Doug McCormick and at the same time allow
Candice to do what she does best: play the visionary,'' said Paul
Noglows, an analyst with Chase H &AMP; Q.
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiment, however, didn't help Ivillage's stock. On Friday
its shares slipped 28 cents to close at $6.25, a 52-week low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
