<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service that are
scheduled for release on  &UR; SUNDAY, July 30,  &LR; of particular interest.
We plan to move these stories by 2 p.m. EDT on Saturday, July 29.
</P>
<P>
   This budget is prepared from preliminary schedules, and some
stories may later be eliminated or altered; please check the
following budgets for additional information: REVIEW-BUDGET,
SUNDAY-BUDGET, SUNBIZ-FINAL-BUDGET and STYLE-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEY AND BUSINESS (Will move in ``f'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCREEN-STRIKE (Los Angeles) _ In the early days of cable, Screen
Actors Guild representatives say, actors and writers cut deals
below network rates to help the fledgling industry. Now, they say,
it's time for payback. Movie and television production are being
accelerated as Hollywood prepares for the possibility of strikes by
actors and writers when their contracts expire next year. A strike
over pay for commercials reflects the new economics of television
as cable gains, networks retreat and new options are created in
electronic media, including the Internet. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   SQUIRT-INVENTOR _ Sanford Redmond, inventor of the butter pat
machine, whose food packages are in the Museum of Modern Art, has a
new innovation: a machine that creates resealable single-serving
condiment packages. Now instead of ending his career as a one-hit
wonder and resting on his $80 million in royalties, Redmond, 75, is
back in the game. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SCHEMES (Undated) _ There's a veritable gold rush on
the Internet for get-rich-quick schemes. Con artists can set up
shop cheaply and anonymously around the world. It's difficult for
law enforcement to track, but the FTC is stepping up enforcement
efforts online. One effort this year was ``Surf Days,'' in which
150 law enforcement and consumer agencies worldwide surfed the net
and discovered 1,600 suspected sites. By Skip Kaltenheuser.
</P>
<P>
   DIAMONDS (Undated) _ DeBeers made headlines when it announced
that it will no longer hoard diamonds to prop up the market. So
when can consumers expect some benefit at the jewelry counter?
Don't hold your breath. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-AUDI (Undated) _ When Audi's A8 made its debut, less than
four years ago, Audi mocked competitors by summarizing its car's
virtues as ``excellence without excess, class without mass.'' There
is still excellence and class. On a 1500-mile drive through
Northern California and Nevada, the $72,525 test car (base price,
$68,425) proved luxurious, pampering passengers with a ride that
was practically serene. By James G. Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-BOXSTER (Undated) _ The Boxster, with its swoopy futuristic
sheet metal, was slotted as an entry-level sports car. With a
$40,000-plus price tag it seemed high, but now Peter Passell is
happy to report that in the new Boxster S the price has been raised
$9,000 and the company has turned the Boxster into the sports car
he always wanted. Porsche accomplished this transformation with
more horsepower, even bigger disc brakes, beefed up suspension,
excellent ergonomics and a telescoping and tilting steering wheel.
He does have a few little gripes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW (Will move in `a' or `i' categories, as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The dirty little secret of the
``high stakes'' Camp David peace summit meeting is that ``the
brink'' was a myth. No explosion in Israel or the Palestinian
territories occurred when the talks collapsed, nor is chaos
expected any time soon. This is because not only was ``the brink''
a myth, so were the descriptions of what lay on the other side. It
was never failure of the summit meeting that brought with it the
risk of violence. It was success. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-INTERNET-REVIEW (Undated) _ At this summer's political
conventions, with the outcomes preordained, the hottest activity
may be interactivity. On C-SPAN's Web site, for instance, users
will be able to click on one of several distinct video feeds from
the convention hall, or even choose to watch the action from the
vantage point of the C-SPAN control booth. Customized political
conventions are just one example of the nation's growing,
technologically abetted obsession with getting what you want when
you want. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-TECH-REVIEW (Washington) _ The disasters involving two
symbols of national pride _ the Concorde in 2000 and the Hindenburg
in 1937 _ are instructive about the difficulties of predicting
technological progress. It remains to be seen whether the Concorde
accident will kill the supersonic transports the way the Hindenburg
ended the promise of the dirigible, when it crashed killing 35
people on board and one on the ground. But progress _ including,
perhaps, progress in safety _ has bypassed both. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONVICTION-REVERSALS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Newly discovered
evidence may seem like a convict's dream come true, but the reality
of U.S. courts is that such evidence rarely makes a difference.
Once a jury has reached a verdict or a judge has ruled, lawyers
say, the odds are overwhelmingly against reopening a case, no
matter how compelling the new information might seem. By Jane
Fritsch.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ATOMIC-PARTICLES-REVIEW (Undated) _ For most physicists, there
is only one answer to the question of why matter weighs anything at
all. It is called the Higgs boson, a strange and special particle
that laboratories in Europe and the United States are racing to
detect. It would be one of the most sublime discoveries in the
history of physics. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-MASSACRES-REVIEW (Undated) _ A book containing 1,756
photos and short descriptions shows the belongings of 354
unidentified bodies found near Srebrenica. Families hope it can
help them claim their loved ones' remains. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PRISON-REVIEW (London) _ A look at Northern Ireland's
notorious Maze prison, from which 88 guerrillas were recently freed
as part of the Ulster political settlement. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (These stories have moved in `e' category or as
noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CLIBURN (Fort Worth, Texas) _ It's 2 a.m., and Michael
Kimmelman is interviewing Van Cliburn at home, where Cliburn is
playing Chopin on an out-of-tune Steinway. Cliburn sings while he
plays, and Kimmelman describes the room, the house, the sound,
Cliburn's hands, the picture of his mother, the view of the city.
``Want to hear the F major?'' Cliburn asks. Kimmelman invites
readers to a very private concert and interview.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-ART (Undated) _ When Deborah Solomon signed on to
www.eBay.com, there were listings for 37,814 fine-art objects _
everything from a signed Christo photograph to a work identified as
``Artist Has Same Astrology Chart as Picasso $50.'' Ten days later,
she had placed 20 bids and finally received the victorious message:
``You won the Vasarely litho.'' The price was $225 for a signed,
framed and numbered print purchased from a dentist in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT16 and NYT19)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WENDERS (Undated) _ Wim Wenders' lack of consistency has
resulted in his last few movies' getting spotty releases at best.
His most recent film, ``Million Dollar Hotel'' may be the only film
to feature Mel Gibson in the last 20 years that has gone unreleased
in the actor's biggest market, America. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ART-LONDON (London) _ All over London, the words ``make it new''
have been applied to museums. Through Sept. 17, the National
Gallery is presenting an exhibition in which 24 artists were
invited to choose a painting from the collection and take off from
it however they like. John Russell also recommends seeing the newly
renovated Wallace Collection in Manchester Square; ``The
Holocaust,'' at the Imperial War Museum; and amid the 20th-century
masterpieces at the Tate Modern, an awesome video by Bill Viola.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (These stories have moved in `t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GOLF-NETHERLANDS (Undated) _ The Netherlands has not been
known for golf since the 17th century, when an early form of the
game called kolfspel was played with a wood club on the frozen
canals. The terrain in most places is famously flat, but it has a
handful of world-class courses that offer challenges and beauty. By
Robert Sidorsky.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NETHERLANDS-LEIDEN (Undated) _ With the exception of
Amsterdam, which has a population nearly seven times that of
Leiden, no other city in the Netherlands has such a broad range of
museums and historic sites. Rembrandt was born there. In the 17th
century America's Pilgrim Fathers took refuge in Leiden before
leaving for the New World. The first tulips in Holland (originally
from Turkey) were planted in the university's botanical garden, and
imports from the New World _ tomato, potato, tobacco and corn _
were introduced into Northern Europe through Leiden. By Christopher
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COAST-NETHERLANDS (Undated) _ Geraldine Fabrikant got
away from the crowds of Amsterdam to quaint fishing villages on the
coast and other towns in the Netherlands. Marken had a naive charm,
Edam, its prosperous homes and its cheeses. In Volendam there are
boats to watch and koffie verkeerd to drink while watching the
clouds glide by.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-INDIA-SPA (Undated) _ If ever there was an escape from
the heat, dust and noise of India's cities, Ananda is it. In a
$50-million renovation, Ananda's designers have grafted an
air-conditioned spa and 75-room hotel onto a maharajah's palace.
Celia W. Dugger treats readers to the details of being anointed
with warm sesame oil for 45-minutes, the tangy taste of banana
lassis sipped on a deck overlooking the Himalayas and expert
reminders to avoid the monsoon season in August.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLES (Will move in `l' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IBIZIA-DISCOS (Ibizia, Spain) _ Ibizia has become a clubhopper's
destination resort. There are billboards advertising discos, a
disco bus whose drivers play techno and disco package tours. Many
come here to capitalize on the availability of party drugs like
Ecstasy and Special K, but it's the dance-driven decadence, the
perpetual parties and the carnivalesque clubs that are the main
attraction. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-WEBSTER (London) _ A niteout in London with Stephen
Webster, a jewelry designer, and Anastasia, his Russian-born wife.
They run into Count Andrei Tolstoy (an offshoot of the writer's
family), Jacob Dzhugashvili, an artist and great-grandson of Joseph
Stalin; Nash Tavkhelidze, godson of the former Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov, and lead singer of Blast, the first
Russian band to be signed to a British label. ``What a bizarre
party,'' Webster observed.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-FASHION (Undated) _ Alex Witchel dons a skort and
interviews Claudia Romana, one of the first golf fashion designers
to realize that women who wear Armani are not going to the course
dressed as Emmett Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT 9 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   SUITS-IRONY (Undated) _ The suit is becoming a default uniform
for the hip, but it has to be worn with a sense of irony, reports
Bob Morris. Spike Jonze, the director of ``Being John Malkovich''
is a suit guy. So is the skateboarder-turned-art dealer Aaron Rose,
and when Keanu Reeves recently played a gig here with his rock
band, Dogstar, it was in a dark suit by DKNY. Then there's Mike
Mills, who has directed videos and ads for Nike and the Gap. He
wears Brooks Brothers suits. ``People expect a hip and edgy guy to
be wearing stuff from Banana Republic, and it throws them off and
puts me in a more powerful position,'' he said. ``It's the most
punk thing I can do right now.''
</P>
