<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORKIN0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orkin memos say termite work falsified
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Internal memos written by Orkin Exterminating Co.
executives in Florida, Georgia and Texas indicate that company
employees falsified reinspections of homes for termite damage.
</P>
<P>
   The memos, written in April 1996, apparently after an internal
company audit, said many Orkin customers are ''being charged for
services not rendered.''
</P>
<P>
   Orkin and its parent company, Rollins Inc., are based in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In one memo, Greg Lawrence, an Orkin regional executive in
Central Florida, wrote to branch managers: ``During the past
several months there have been instances of fraud, theft, and
forgery within the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence added that ''reinspections are being falsified and
customers being charged for the service when we don't know if, in
fact, the customer ever received their reinspection.''
</P>
<P>
   The memos told Orkin branch managers to stop such practices.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa attorney Dan Clark said Friday that the memos surfaced in
connection with a lawsuit by several Tampa residents against Orkin.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa suit, filed last year, alleges that Orkin workers
performed improper chemical treatments for termites, skipped annual
inspections, forged customer names on inspection slips and
misrepresented warranties to consumers. The Orkin customers, as a
result, suffered substantial termite damage to their homes,
according to the lawsuit, which seeks class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   Orkin faces a similar lawsuit in Alabama that has reached
class-action status. The company denies the charges in each case.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Orkin said Friday the company ''could not
comment'' on the memos.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence could not be reached for comment. An Orkin manager in
South Florida, Joe Cannariato, said he did not recall writing the
memo to his branch managers and referred questions to Orkin's home
office in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``These memos confirm what our lawsuit is all about,'' Clark
said. ``It's brought by Orkin customers in Florida who didn't get
the treatment they expected, either initially or through renewals.
In fact, the evidence we have shows that these people were
defrauded.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Orkin customers' signatures were forged on
re-inspection slips after 1996, when the company memos were
written.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Orkin termite-related practices are being
investigated by Florida and five other states, according to Bob
Buchner, an assistant Florida attorney general. He did not identify
the other states, though Georgia is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida investigation is targeting Orkin advertising and
other practices, Buchner said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Central and South Florida, the memos were written
by Orkin officials to branch managers in north Texas, south Texas
and South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gard, then an Orkin manager in South Georgia, said in his
April 22, 1996, memo to branch managers that there ''have been
instances of fraud, theft and forgery within the company.'' Gard
continued: ``On more than one occasion, it has happened in our
region.''
</P>
<P>
   A shorter memo by an Orkin executive in Louisiana warned branch
managers to review company policy against fraud, theft and forgery.
</P>
<P>
   Former Orkin employees in Florida have said in affidavits or
depositions that employees at times forged customers' signatures on
annual reinspection forms for termite damage, when that service
wasn't actually performed.
</P>
<P>
   Former Orkin employee Fred Beman of Tampa said in a 1998
affidavit that the forgery practice ''was done at the specific
instruction of management (who benefited) through the receipt of
bonuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The memo by Lawrence also stated, ``Sales inspectors are having
customers sign customer satisfaction certificates prior to work
being completed for accommodation of paying our employees, but at
the expense of our customer who may never have received the
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Orkin is the No. 2 pest-control company in revenues behind
Terminix. It serves about 1.7 million residential and commercial
customers from more than 400 offices. Rollins Inc., the parent
company, reported 1999 revenues of $586.6 million. Its headquarters
is in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
