<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS LOOK GOOD, WHICH MIGHT BE BAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 30) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some dates to remember:
</P>
<P>
   _ July 17. After a seven-week, 35 percent surge from its low for
the year, the Nasdaq composite reaches 4,274.67, its highest close
since early April.
</P>
<P>
   _ July 18. Unisys, the information technology company, says
third-quarter profits will be only about half of what analysts had
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   _ July 20. The telecommunications equipment makers Lucent
Technologies and Ericcson each warn that third-quarter earnings
will fall below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   _ July 26. Xerox, the copier company, says earnings for the
second half will fall short.
</P>
<P>
   _ July 27. WorldCom, the long-distance and wireless company,
says revenues for the remainder of the year will come in at the low
end of current forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   _ July 28. The Nasdaq is down 14.3 percent since July 17.
</P>
<P>
   So even as second-quarter earnings reports are coming in
stronger than expected, especially for technology companies,
investors seem suddenly to be focusing on the possibility of a
slowdown in earnings growth during the rest of the year. It's about
time.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of slower earnings growth has been bubbling for a while.
Quarterly forecasts by First Call/Thomson Financial and IBES
International, which collect Wall Street profit estimates for the
companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, have been
tailing off. But investors, intoxicated by the unbelievable
earnings growth this decade and particularly over the last year,
seemed to ignore the warnings until now.
</P>
<P>
   If you remain unconvinced, here is something to think about:
Optimism about earnings may itself be a negative sign.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts who forecast earnings are still upbeat about the
rest of the year, even with the Federal Reserve trying to slow
economic growth to curb inflation. S&AMP;P 500 operating earnings are
expected to have grown by 20.6 percent in the second quarter, to
grow 16.6 percent in the third quarter and an additional 14.5
percent in the fourth, according to IBES. First Call's forecasts
for each period are a tad higher. For the year, IBES sees 18.5
percent growth, First Call sees 19.6 percent; either way, one of
the best years since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Hill, director of research at First Call, noted that
earnings forecasts are holding up even for some economically
sensitive sectors despite higher interest rates. Companies in home
construction are expected to show a 13 percent decline in earnings
in the second quarter, compared with the period a year ago, and
then close the gap to 3 percent in the third quarter and post 6
percent growth in the fourth. Companies in the automobile sector
are expected to show 14 percent growth in the third quarter and 15
percent in the fourth quarter. These are not the numbers one would
expect, Hill said, if the economy were slowing down the way Federal
Reserve policymakers would like.
</P>
<P>
   That optimism indicates that Wall Street analysts do not expect
a significant slowdown in growth in the second half _ not
unreasonable, given that the economy has stuttered in the second
quarter of past years only to reaccelerate in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, reminded investors in
testimony to Congress last week that when policy makers meet on
Aug. 22, the decision on another interest rate hike will depend on
new economic data for July showing that the slowing trend he has
identified is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   That means one of two things: Wall Street analysts are wrong _
the economy really will slow significantly, and so will corporate
earnings, to investors' intense disappointment. Or, the analysts
are right _ the Fed's rate increases haven't worked yet and the
economy is perking up again.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the data favors the analysts, including the totally
unexpected 5.2 percent jump in second-quarter gross domestic
product reported on Friday, the increases in durable-goods orders
and existing home sales in June and the rising consumer confidence
this month.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend holds, the Fed is likely to push rates higher
still. And that won't be good for stocks. So beware. Earnings may
be bad for the stock market's health. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
