<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC SQUADS TRAIL BUSH, SPREADING MAYHEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ ``I'm looking for some Bush to whack,'' Harry
Fred Scott, retired postal worker and dedicated Democrat, growled
Friday in his East Texas drawl as he boarded the bus loaded with
boisterous Texans and emblazoned with a blue banner that read
``Don't mess with America.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee. And whack away he did. In
Cincinnati, he and his fellow Texans asserted that their state
lagged behind the nation in school test scores. In Dayton, they
complained about a dysfunctional health-care system. In Columbus,
they fretted about smog-filled skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have soccer moms whose children can't play soccer'' because
of air pollution, Tamara Maschino told reporters outside a senior
center here. ``And I hold George W. Bush personally responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Democratic National Committee, the people who came up
with the chicken that chased President George Bush in 1992 and the
cigarette that dogged Bob Dole in 1996, comes the party's newest
tool of disruption: the Texas Truth Squad, 14 elected officials and
citizens bearing tales of Bush-induced woe from the Lone Star
State.
</P>
<P>
   They have traveled through Kentucky and Ohio on their way to
West Virginia and Philadelphia, where the Republican National
Convention will begin on Monday. Bush and his running mate, Dick
Cheney, are expected to take the same route on their way to the
convention, and the Democrats wanted to get there first to muddy
the waters a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bushes are coming and the Bushes will get you,'' Scott
bellowed at older citizens in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth Squad is just one cog in the Democratic machine
created to mock and contradict the Republicans during their
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the week, a team of surrogate speakers, led by the
party's chairmen, Joe Andrew and Edward G. Rendell, will hold daily
news conferences attacking the Republican ticket. The party has
bought billboard space near the convention center carrying the
message: ``I know what you did in Texas.'' A Web site loaded with
anti-Bush broadsides will go online on Sunday, at
www.iknowwhatyoudidintexas.net.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of it all, teams of researchers at the national
committee's offices in Washington and the Gore 2000 headquarters in
Nashville, Tenn., will issue floods of faxes and e-mail messages in
a minute-by-minute effort to rebut virtually everything that every
Republican says from the convention stage in Philadelphia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The nameless and faceless researchers are the engine that drives
much of the Democratic troublemaking. In Nashville, they are known
as ``the men and women of zeal'' because they are all 20-somethings
who work 18-hour days scanning the Internet, watching television
and reading newspapers in search of stray scraps of damaging
information about their foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call this the slaughterhouse,'' said Donna Brazile, Gore's
campaign manager, as she strolled into the team's glass-enclosed
office in Nashville recently. ``They may look like gentle people.
But they are killers.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by David Ginsberg, a pot-bellied, chain-smoking, bearded,
balding and brainy 25-year-old, the Gore researchers were often
stunningly successful in undermining the daily messages of Bill
Bradley during the Democratic primaries.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, they inundated reporters with information about a vote
Bradley cast against flood relief for farmers, and the issue dogged
Bradley for days. Later, when Bradley attacked Gore for supporting
the tobacco industry two decades ago, Ginsberg was ready with a
compilation of quotes from Bradley vowing to avoid negative
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the Gore team's researchers pulled repeated
all-nighters compiling thick dossiers on every potential Republican
vice presidential candidate. The one man they failed to study
closely was the one who was chosen.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as Cheney's name surfaced last weekend, they went
into overdrive. And when Bush made his choice official Tuesday
morning, Ginsberg had already distributed a detailed analysis of
Cheney's voting record in Congress, which was so conservative that
it surprised even some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we vetted Cheney better than Bush did,'' bragged one
adviser to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also firmly believe that good research fuels
better pranks. When a DNC researcher learned that the Bush campaign
was buying George W. Bush bottled water that came from Kentucky,
they ordered several cases and gave it out to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is George W. Bush's message in a bottle,'' Andrew said at
a news conference in Oregon last Tuesday. ``Don't drink the water
in Texas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
