s f BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-TIMEWA     07-28 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-TIMEWARNER-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER ATTRACTS WRONG KIND OF ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 30) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From time to time, very smart people do things that
aren't so smart. Just ask the folks at Time Warner, who are
probably ruing their decision to play hardball with Walt Disney's
ABC television network during the May sweeps period.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner made headlines then by bouncing ABC off its cable
systems in a number of large markets. The dispute was soon
resolved, but sour memories lingered. Last week, at hearings before
the Federal Communications Commission, Disney and other big media
companies repaid Time Warner's aggressiveness by voicing objections
to its huge pending merger with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Burnett, president of Merger Insight, a New York-based
institutional research service, offered some thoughts last week on
the huge deal and its prospects. Here are excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How much damage did Time Warner inflict on itself through the
spat with Disney?
</P>
<P>
   A. The odds that regulators would take a very serious look at
the AOL deal went up because of what happened in May. That event
lit a fire under Congress, which is bad. And it forced the FCC to
recognize that whoever controls the cable network controls access
to the customer. Time Warner's decision to deny Disney access
graphically demonstrated how important it is to put mechanisms in
place that will give competing content suppliers access. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. To ensure that that happens, Disney and NBC want the FCC to
make Time Warner separate its cable systems from its content
business before it approves the AOL deal. Is that likely? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Forcing a spinoff would be a deal killer, but we don't see
any need for that draconian a measure. Still, rules may have to be
put in place to ensure that networks and other competing content
suppliers are not blocked from access.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to do that is with FCC rule-making. You don't want
these rules to be written by local cable franchise authorities. You
want them written and enforced on a national level, so you get
consistency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What else might the F.C.C. mandate that could scuttle the
deal? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Restrictions that prevent cross-selling opportunities is a
possible problem _ preventing Time Warner from sending an e-mail to
all AOL subscribers offering them a discounted subscription to
Sports Illustrated for example.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When the deal was announced in January, it was wildly
applauded, but since then opinion seems to have soured. What
happened?
</P>
<P>
   A. AOL's stock is definitely down. But companies like
Amazon.com, eBay and Yahoo are down, too, and we have had a huge
overall correction in Nasdaq stock prices. It could also be that
the market is having trouble dealing with the concept of this
merger. It is not a complete numbers game, like a merger between
two energy companies. You are dealing with concepts like pushing
magazines out through the Internet, areas where we don't have a lot
of experience.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The FCC has had the deal under review for months; the Federal
Trade Commission and the European Union are also looking at it.
When can decisions be expected? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We had been told it would close by the end of the year, but
processing it could take longer than we thought. Technically, the
FCC has only about 75 days left to make its decision, but it can
delay that by asking for more information. The European timetable
is mid-October, but Time Warner's decision to form a music joint
venture with EMI Group has run into opposition, so there could be
further delays.
</P>
<P>
   But the out date for the merger agreement is not until May 31,
2001. That means the companies left themselves plenty of time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it likely that Congress is going to take a whack at the
deal as well? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We expect there will be hearings sometime this fall, and a
little bit of criticism of Gerald Levin, Time Warner's chairman,
about the Disney matter. But we don't expect to see any
legislation. Normally, one merger will not prompt Congress to pass
a bill. But Congressional scrutiny does put pressure on the FCC and
the FTC to conduct a more thorough review. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your attitude about the combination, if it is
approved? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. On balance, we don't love the transaction or hate it.
</P>
<P>
   But we haven't seen a lot of clients jump into either of these
stocks. We have people who are watching it carefully, but not many
who want to get involved in the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   That said, we have seen a lot of AOL holders sell out since the
deal was announced, because they thought the new company would be a
big, boring 5 percent revenue grower. Those clients will probably
pile back in to AOL if the deal is blocked by regulators. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
