<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6440 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-JUNGER-WRITER'S-BAR-$     07-28 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNGER-WRITER'S-BAR-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PERFECT STORM' AUTHOR'S NEW PITCH: OLD-TIME WRITER'S BAR IN A
MODERN GOTHAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By DOUGLAS CENTURY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  NEW YORK _ It was opening night at the Half King on West 23rd
Street, and though the bar was still half finished, fragrant with
damp paint and sawdust, it was at full capacity with a crowd of
authors, magazine journalists, literary agents and editors.
Sebastian Junger, the best-selling author of ``The Perfect Storm,''
and one of the Half King's owners, was behind the bar in a black
blazer and open-necked shirt, unshaven, cupping a Camel Light to
his mouth. Scott Anderson, his fellow journalist-turned-barkeeper,
worked the beer taps, topping off some foamy pints.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Half King _ named after an Indian chief who played the
French and British against each other during the Revolutionary
period _ was dreamed up as a saloon for writers, which is notable
at a time when New York is awash with velvet-roped night spots;
watering holes for literary types have virtually dried up. It's a
romantic vision, a smoke-filled room where writers can drown their
sorrows after deadline. And on opening night, it all looked as
perfect as a movie set, down to the Hollywood producer's stretch
limousine left idling outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since we've seen writers open up a bar
in New York,'' said Chris Calhoun, an agent with Sterling Lord
Literistic, squeezing in at the mahogany bar-rail for a vodka.
``The last one I can remember was Sidney Zion with Broadway Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   That was decades ago, of course, when newspapermen still wore
fedoras and had ink-stained fingertips. The Half King has been
billed as a throwback to the old-school haunt, where a scribbler
flashed a press pass and was given a tab. In those days, a
journalist's hangout was a scruffy, workingman's joint where an
errant glance or a bumped shoulder might quickly lead to a
fisticuffs. Today, you're likely to be rubbing shoulders with a
cell phone-toting DreamWorks executive looking to snap up your life
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott and I are journalists, true, but our other two partners
are in film,'' Junger said, referring to Nanette Burstein, the
director of the Academy Award-nominated documentary, ``On the
Ropes,'' and Jerome O'Connor, the Irish-born producer of the
forthcoming Barry Levinson comedy, ``An Everlasting Piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Half King opened, the place had a movie business
buzz, and not just because the film version of Junger's book,
starring George Clooney and Mark Wahlberg, was flexing its box
office muscle across the country. Earlier this month, Junger,
Anderson and another journalist friend, John Falk (who doubles as
the Half King's bartender), parlayed one of their recent
misadventures in Sarajevo into a pitch meeting and a
high-six-figure movie option. The story goes that while on vacation
in Bosnia _ who vacations in Bosnia? _ the three journalists found
themselves mistaken for CIA operatives, and an adventure caper
straight out of ``The Third Man'' ensued. Now, they're
collaborating on the script for Intermedia, with O'Connor set to
produce.
</P>
<P>
   Junger, who struggled for years as an underpaid freelancer
before hitting it big with ``The Perfect Storm,'' said that his bar
was inspired by the grittier demands of his job. It was while he
was working as a foreign correspondent recently with Anderson that
they dreamt up the bar venture. ``When you're working abroad,
there's always these bars that journalists end up hanging out in,
particularly in war zones,'' Junger said. ``OK, so this isn't a hot
spot, it's New York, but we're still hoping the word gets around
with visiting journalists and with local journalists, and they'll
just keep checking in.''
</P>
<P>
   The following evening, Junger's new bar was decidedly not a hot
spot. With the mob now vanished, the Half King looked like just
another sleepy neighborhood pub starved for business on a dead
Friday night. The owners outnumbered the paying customers 2 to 1.
``Nobody really knows we're open yet,'' O'Connor muttered in his
thick County Cork accent. ``And anybody that does know we're open
is still hung over from last night.''
</P>
<P>
   He took a journalist on a tour of the bar's hardscrabble past,
down to the unfinished basement, where, the story goes, the
gangland boss Waxey Gordon once ran a gambling operation. ``Right
there, on that spot, is where they played poker,'' O'Connor said,
ducking his head under a whitewashed archway that seemed
specifically designed to accommodate the frames of 5-foot-6-inch
mobsters. ``Now, this room is going to be our movie production
office.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners want to wrest the writer's social scene away from
effete intellectualism (say, an exclusive uptown soiree to honor
Martin Amis), and give it back a more rugged, Hemingwayesque sex
appeal. There's little doubt that the bar's main attraction _ from
the feminine perspective, at least _ will be the prospect of a
chance encounter with Junger, who has become nearly as famous for
his square-jaw book jacket pose as for his disaster-at-sea prose.
At the opening night party, several women turned doe-eyed whenever
Junger passed their way with pints of beer.
</P>
<P>
   But if fans of Junger's writing head to the Half King expecting
to see a recreation of the Crow's Nest, the bare-knuckled fishing
bar depicted in ``The Perfect Storm,'' they'll be disappointed.
What they'll find is a slightly upscale version of a rustic
neighborhood tavern, with apricot-colored walls, a cluster of black
leather sofas and a peaceful, shaded back garden.
</P>
<P>
   Burstein, who is Anderson's girlfriend, said that all the
partners had contributed to picking out the bar's decor _ she
herself had found the antique window frames in a demolished Harlem
warehouse _ and it amused her when advance reports kept describing
the Half King as some kind of macho clubhouse and tough-guy haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just because they haven't seen us in our pink frilly
dresses,'' Anderson said to Junger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2056EDT &QL; 
