<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-NAIRU-$AD     07-28 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-NAIRU-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPITAPH FOR A RULE THAT'S NOT QUITE DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounded like an epitaph for a venerated principle of
economics, one that the Federal Reserve still invokes as a
justification for slowing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The epitaph, in fact, came from Alan Greenspan himself in his
latest Congressional testimony. The principle he declared
inoperative maintains that full employment and low inflation are
incompatible. That may once have been true, but the old connections
are not evident now. Greenspan's epitaph makes the Fed's next
interest rate increase harder to justify.
</P>
<P>
   The principle in question, known by the acronym Nairu, holds
that when the unemployment rate falls below a certain level,
inflation accelerates. A goal in slowing the economy is to increase
unemployment _ to push it up to its ``natural'' level, at which the
inflation rate neither rises nor falls. Equilibrium is a holy grail
in mainstream economics.
</P>
<P>
   Raising unemployment is not a pretty thing to do, particularly
if people are being asked, or forced, to sacrifice their jobs in
the name of a malfunctioning thesis. Greenspan had been publicly
skeptical for months about Nairu, but in reply to a question from
Sen. Connie Mack, the Florida Republican _ ``Do we need to move the
unemployment rate back higher than 4 percent to achieve price
stability?'' _ the Fed chairman seemed to push Nairu into the
bygone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My forecast,'' he said, ``is that Nairu, which served as a
very useful statistical procedure to evaluate how the economy was
behaving, over a number of years, like so many types of temporary
models which worked, is probably going to fail in the years ahead
as a useful indicator.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing this, Sen. Paul Sarbanes, the Maryland Democrat, asked
sarcastically if Greenspan's fellow policy makers at the Fed would
see a transcript of the chairman's epitaph. That was a jab at
Lawrence H. Meyer, an influential Fed governor who openly embraces
Nairu, which he puts at 5 to 5.25 percent. The Fed has already
raised interest rates six times in the last 14 months to slow the
economy, but Meyer would slow it more if unemployment fails to
climb from its present level of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's epitaph is disingenuous. While burying Nairu, he
embraces almost the same principle in a different incarnation. He
speaks of running out of enough people to take jobs. Labor
shortages would then give workers leverage to bargain for higher
wages. Companies would raise prices to pay for the higher wages.
Or, as Greenspan told Congress, ``labor costs eventually would have
to accelerate to levels threatening price stability.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Nairu, or lip service to Meyer's insistence that Nairu
lives. For Greenspan, though, the natural unemployment rate appears
to be 4 percent or less. The difference between Greenspan and Meyer
is an additional 1.4 million people out of work, maybe more. For
them, the debate over Nairu matters.
</P>
<P>
   Nairu is really a description, through equations, of a set of
conditions in America that link unemployment to inflation. Those
conditions seemed a lot clearer in 1967, when Milton Friedman, the
Nobel laureate, first described a natural rate of unemployment and
mentioned the numerous factors, even states of mind, that must be
``embedded'' in the equations. In the '50s and '60s, the math
worked.
</P>
<P>
   A low unemployment rate signaled a robust demand for goods and
services. Encouraged by this, the United Auto Workers, for example,
negotiated a wage increase with General Motors, and that increase
became a pattern for other auto workers and for millions of
employees in many industries. Employers, as a matter of course,
raised prices to help pay for the higher wages. Demand made the
price increases stick; today's flood of quick-to-discount
competitors was not yet on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, demand has been similarly robust, but price
increases no longer stick very well. Wages have risen in response
to low unemployment, but not very much. The old Nairu links from
unemployment through wages to inflation have not kicked in. All
sorts of reasons are cited: rising productivity, falling computer
prices, less expensive imports, low-wage immigrants, weak unions,
corporate mobility, job insecurity. The list goes on, and the
natural rate of unemployment, set at 6.5 percent in the 1980's, has
declined today to 5 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe there is no natural rate above zero. Maybe Nairu no
longer works. Certainly Greenspan's disavowal makes it harder for
the Fed to invoke tight labor markets as a reason to slow the
economy in anticipation of rising inflation. Now more than ever,
the Fed is under pressure to wait for inflation to actually
accelerate before it acts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
