<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BEGINS 5-DAY JOURNEY TO REPUBLICAN NATIONAL CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGDALE, Ark. _ Brimming with confidence, Gov. George W. Bush
flew into President Clinton's home territory Friday, proclaiming
that he intended to contest areas that the Democrats won solidly in
the last two presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   With his stop in the rolling green farm country in the Northwest
corner of Arkansas, Bush began a five-day march to the Republican
National Convention that will take him through the battleground
states of Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio, West Virginia and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   In the district where a young Bill Clinton lost a race for
Congress at the age of 28, Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney,
were greeted by a roaring crowd packed into a high school
auditorium and chanting a football fight cheer. Dozens of children
were arrayed on the stage behind them and a banner proclaimed,
``Renewing America's Purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointed to two local boys-made-good _ Sen. Tim Hutchinson
and his brother, Asa, the congressman who gained renown as one of
the impeachment managers who prosecuted Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They whispered something in my ear that made Dick Cheney and I
feel really great,'' Bush said. ``They told us we're going to carry
Arkansas next fall. They told us not to worry about the last two
election cycles. Something else is taking place in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It buoys my heart,'' he told the cheering crowd. ``It buoys my
spirit to know as we're working our way to Philadelphia for the
national convention, and we're working our way across battleground
states that the Republican ticket has not been able to carry for
the last two elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney took turns taking shots at the integrity and
trustworthiness of the president who was impeached, but later
acquitted for his efforts to cover up his affair with Monica
Lewinsky. Neither man mentioned impeachment directly or even
Clinton's name, but again and again again they harked back to the
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he and his running mate were ``on a great crusade to
restore dignity and integrity to Washington.'' And as the crowd
cheered, he called Bush ``the man who is going to give our kids and
our grandkids a government we once again can be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush praised Cheney in turn, and in the process took a shot at
Clinton for his effort to sidestep questions about Lewinsky. ``This
man is a good man,'' Bush said of Cheney. ``He's a solid man. He's
a man who understands what the definition of is is.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point out in the audience, someone thundered, ``No more
Slick Willie.''
</P>
<P>
   As he began his swing into the Republican convention, Bush had
some good news _ two new polls showing him in the lead. Even in
Arkansas, a Mason-Dixon poll just last week showed Bush leading
Vice President Al Gore, 46-40 percent. It had a 4-point margin of
error.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats kept up their assault on Bush and Cheney as the
``big oil dream ticket,'' and circulated a Reuters report from 1999
saying that Cheney, the chief executive officer of the Halliburton
Co., a worldwide oil services firm, had praised an OPEC decision to
cut oil production.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, said that Cheney had been
speaking at a conference of industry analysts and telling them of
projections by economists that OPEC would cut production and that
the ``price situation'' for the industry would improve. ``Unlike
the Clinton-Gore administration, he was not caught napping about
OPEC's actions,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he came aboard his campaign plane Friday
morning, with his wife, Laura, Bush seemed relaxed and in good
spirits. He ambled down the aisle joking with reporters and
anticipating his nomination speech next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to this speech,'' Bush said. ``This
is going to be an unbelievably interesting moment in my life _ to
walk out on that stage and to speak from my heart for however long
it takes to get through the speech.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has worked hard to plan a feel-good Republican
convention with none of the sharp conservative edges of the past.
The evening proceedings will have star turns for nonpoliticians _ a
single mother, a teacher, a union member, a grandmother and
granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday nights, Bush will be beamed by satellite
into the convention from locales round the country. He is to arrive
in Philadelphia on Wednesday morning at a Latin American music
festival, symbolic of Republican efforts to reach out to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday night, one of the speakers welcoming him will be
a Democrat, Jan Bullock, the wife of the late Lt. Gov. Ray Bullock
of Texas, a Democrat who worked closely with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Even Friday on what was supposed to be a partisan tour, Bush
tried to soften the tone. Before his rally he toured the Jones
Center for Families, a community center founded by a family that
ran one of the nation's largest trucking businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to hear and see and feel first hand the acts of
this particular platoon in the armies of compassion,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   As he took a quick tour of the center's computer center, one of
the first people to greet him was Charles A. Huffer, who tightly
gripped the governor's hand and began speaking. Bush looked
bewildered and and brushed him off quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I thought he had a good chance to be
president,'' Huffer, 61, said later, ``and I asked him if he would
be willing to finally tell the American people the truth about
unidentified flying objects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
