<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-STOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAMESE STOCK MARKET OPENS WITH FALTERING STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam _ With just two stocks, two hours and
$5,000 in trades, the Socialist Republic of Vietnam opened its
first stock market for business on Friday and took faltering steps
into the uncertain world of free markets.
</P>
<P>
   Hopeful investors packed into the three brokerage offices taking
orders for the shares Friday morning to watch the market's birth on
electronic boards. But curiosity and excitement quickly turned into
confusion and disappointment, when minutes before the Ho Chi Minh
City Securities Trading Center opened, the government imposed a
ceiling on bids that invalidated many orders, some of which were
more than 50 percent above the government's artificially imposed
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers were so scarce at those prices that by the end of the
session, only 4,200 shares of the two stocks had been traded, with
a combined value of 70.4 million Vietnamese dong, or nearly $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Market officials nevertheless declared the day a success,
pointing to the interest among investors and justifying their price
intervention as necessary to protect novices from what otherwise
might have been dot-com-like share prices. ``In the initial stages,
the psychology of the market isn't stable,'' said Vu Bang, the
director of the trading center.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign residents here called the opening of the market an
important moment in Vietnam's development. ``The immediate point is
symbolic,'' said Dominic Scriven, an expatriate businessman who has
been investing in Vietnamese companies for nine years. ``The
government now acknowledges the right of private ownership, the
transfer of ownership, the right to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Many hope that market trading will lure back some of the
billions of dollars that Vietnamese have squirreled away _ out of
government view _ and make that available for corporate expansion.
``The market might shake loose money from under mattresses,'' said
Jonathan Waugh, chief representative in Vietnam for Jardine Fleming
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   But they will first need to rekindle the confidence of Friday's
disappointed investors. ``My order has just been destroyed,'' said
Tran Van Thang, a 20-year-old finance student who had signed up to
buy 100 shares of each traded stock, the Refrigeration Electrical
Engineering Co. and the Cables and Telecommunications Material
Joint Stock Co., but at prices well above the government's maximum.
Like many on Friday, Thang came less to profit than to learn what
trading stocks was all about. ``We don't have any books for this,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam has been promising since 1992 to open a stock market,
which foreign investors here say is another illustration of the
communist country's halting progress toward joining the modern
global economy. China and Russia opened stock markets more than a
decade ago. Officials here explain that they were busy planning.
</P>
<P>
   In their efforts to get it right, the Vietnamese borrowed
expertise from Thailand and modeled the exchange on South Korea's
and a more famous one on Wall Street, and the exchange's deputy
director, Tran Dac Sinh, visited the New York Stock Exchange last
year.
</P>
<P>
   It is a long way from Wall Street. Outside, women in conical
hats sell birds, and boys play soccer barefoot in the street.
Officials will not even call it a stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But more business is on the way. Two additional stocks should be
listed in the next two weeks, Bang, the trading center's director,
said. Fifty other companies meet Vietnam's criteria for a listing,
and there are more than 400 formerly state-owned enterprises that
have been privatized since 1993. Nearly 6,000 remain in government
hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese are avid gamblers, and in the absence of an
official market, company shares have been trading on the gray
market for years. ``This isn't a market,'' complained one such
trader, Le Hung, as he clutched a bag full of unlisted shares that
he hoped to sell. ``The government is intervening.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be some time before Saigon, as this city is still known
here, produces its own bulls and bears. Vietnam's market has an
index, but shares are traded only three days a week. Prices can
rise or fall by a maximum of 5 percent a session, and on Friday
they rose 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the desire is there. ``I heard that in the U.S. you can buy
stocks on the Web,'' said Trung Thi Han, as she watched the tote
board, waiting to learn whether her order had been executed. ``I
wish we could do that here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
