<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-BORDICK-TRADE-NYT     07-28 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BORDICK-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS ACQUIRE BORDICK AS THE TRADING FRENZY BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One week after agreeing to deal the organization's
top prospect for the All-Star shortstop Barry Larkin, the Mets
Friday traded for another All-Star shortstop, a right-handed set-up
reliever and a power-hitting outfielder _ without giving up any of
their best minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   When Larkin rejected the Mets' trade and stayed with the
Cincinnati Reds, the Mets focused on acquiring Mike Bordick from
Baltimore. They got Bordick Friday, then traded for reliever Rick
White and outfielder Bubba Trammell from the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles had insisted that the Double-A outfielder Alex
Escobar be included in their deal, as he was for Larkin. The Mets
refused, and general manager Steve Phillips thought there would be
no Bordick trade.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orioles finally backed off Escobar, and late Thursday
night they accepted a four-player package that included the player
Bordick will replace at short, Melvin Mora, plus infielder Mike
Kinkade and two minor league pitchers, Lesli Brea and Pat Gorman.
The Orioles showed no interest in taking on the expensive contract
of the Mets' injured shortstop, Rey Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   After trading for Bordick and realizing he could not meet the
Milwaukee Brewers' demands for closer Bob Wickman _ who was dealt
to Cleveland Friday for a package fronted by the slugging
outfielder Richie Sexson _ Phillips turned to the Devil Rays. To
get Trammell and White, the Mets dealt outfielder Jason Tyner and
the Triple-A starter Paul Wilson, both former No. 1 draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, while the Mets landed neither of the players
they most wanted _ Larkin and Wickman _ they filled several holes
while keeping Escobar, the minor league pitchers Grant Roberts and
Pat Strange and the minor league outfielder Brian Cole, probably
the four best prospects in the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we've protected the top echelon of our prospect
pool, hopefully to play for us but also for consideration for other
big deals that could be out there now and this off-season,''
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bordick, the Mets get an outstanding defensive shortstop who
is also enjoying his finest season at the plate. Bordick is batting
.297 with 16 home runs and 59 runs batted in, and he has a .979
fielding percentage. Mora, playing regularly for the first time in
the majors, had a .958 fielding percentage at short.
</P>
<P>
   Bordick played seven years for Oakland before signing with
Baltimore before the 1997 season. St. Louis Cardinals manager Tony
LaRussa, who managed Bordick with the Athletics, said Bordick is
``tied for first on the list'' of his favorite players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a 10,'' LaRussa said. ``He might be the perfect player,
and he's a perfect person. He's ideal. You can't look at anything
he does and say, `I wish he did that differently.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays as well defensively as anyone in the big leagues. Day
in and day out, he's very consistent. He makes all the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordick can be a free agent after the season, and the Mets _ who
covet another free-agent shortstop, Seattle's Alex Rodriguez _ do
not plan to talk about a contract extension with him now.
</P>
<P>
   Bordick had hoped to remain with the Orioles, but said he was
excited to be in a pennant race. He said he strives for consistency
and has proven it in his career, making between seven and 16 errors
in each of his 10 full major league seasons, with a career fielding
percentage of .981.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very confident in Melvin Mora, personally,'' said Mets
manager Bobby Valentine. ``That doesn't mean he was going to make
all the plays Bordick's going to make. I think Mike will make more
plays than Melvin would have made.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still possible that the Mets could make more moves before
Monday's nonwaiver trading deadline, but Phillips said he would be
satisfied heading into the final two months of the season if he
made no more deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely; there's no question about that,'' he said. ``We're
an improved team significantly at shortstop. I think we've
addressed that need in the bullpen to have a complement to Turk
from the right side late in the game. Trammell gives us some of
that right-handed power that we wanted to have.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old White is durable, in the Turk Wendell style. He
ranks first in the American League with 71 1/3 relief innings,
after ranking second last year. Phillips said White is ``a
combination of Wendell and Pat Mahomes,'' throwing fastballs and
sliders like Wendell and able to pitch in long relief, like
Mahomes. White is especially tough on right-handers, who are
hitting .172 off him.
</P>
<P>
   White, who has a 3.41 earned-run average, will primarily be used
in the late innings, giving the Mets two capable right-handed
set-up men to go with their left-handed tandem of Dennis Cook and
John Franco. There will be a corresponding roster move to fit White
on the team, which could make the struggling Rich Rodriguez the odd
man out.
</P>
<P>
   Trammell, 28, has had success for Tampa Bay as a part-time
player, hitting .285 with 33 home runs in 671 at-bats over the last
three years. With Benny Agbayani starting, the Mets have had only
one right-handed power hitter off the bench, Todd Pratt, but he is
a catcher and thus pinch-hits infrequently.
</P>
<P>
   Trammell fits in nicely as a reserve, Phillips said, and he
could also start. ``He's heading into the prime of his career,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects the Mets traded for Bordick _ Brea and Gorman _
are hard-throwers who will probably be relievers if they reach the
major leagues. Brea, 21, was 5-8 with a 4.24 earned-run average as
a starter at Double-A Binghamton. The 22-year-old Gorman, whom
Orioles vice president for baseball operations Syd Thrift said was
the pivotal player in the deal, had 15 saves for Single-A Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The more recognizable prospects the Mets traded are Tyner and
Wilson, who will join the Devil Rays' major league roster, at least
initially.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mets believed Tyner, their top pick in the 1998 draft,
would hit in the majors, they were unsure of his defensive ability
and have been impressed by Timoniel Perez, another Triple-A Norfolk
outfielder with speed and more power.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, picked first overall in the 1994 draft, was a
sentimental favorite. The 27-year-old right-hander has come back
from serious elbow and shoulder surgeries to have a solid season at
Norfolk, going 5-5 with a 4.23 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips also believed Wilson is more likely to pitch at the
back end of a major league rotation. He added: ``I just absolutely
motivated him to prove me wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
