A6455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-MONEY0730-COX     07-28 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MONEY0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Corporate bucks will wine, dine delegates
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Republicans gather in Philadelphia, there's a
lot of wooing going on.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's biggest companies, often with crucial issues before
Congress, are pouring millions of dollars into the Republican
National Convention, and they'll do it again in a couple of weeks
when the Democrats meet in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based United Parcel Service is giving $1 million in cash
and services to both. So are Microsoft and AT&AMP;T, which is providing
delegates calling cards to go with pillows from Hilton Hotels and
other gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Various Republican Party organizations, including the committees
charged with helping get Republicans elected to the House and
Senate, will put on lavish feasts, meal after meal, day after day,
to say thank you to their biggest contributors and to ask them to
open their checkbooks again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventions are good for raising money,'' said Stuart Roy,
spokesman for the National Republican Senatorial Committee. ``But
even more important may be the chance for our candidates to meet
donors who can give them the resources they need in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening, the committee has four events for
benefactors. Later, the ``Main Event Fight Night'' bash will
feature former heavyweight boxing champs Larry Holmes and Michael
Spinks. A NASCAR-themed event includes getting to sit in race cars
and meet driver Terry Labonte and race car owner and former
football coach Joe Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party's six-figure donors will dine with House
Speaker Dennis Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
breakfast with top aides to Texas Gov. George W. Bush and brunch
with former Presidents Bush and Ford on the convention's last day.
</P>
<P>
   To critics of campaign financing, the convention illustrate what
is wrong. ``They are glorified money drops for special interests,''
said Scott Harshbarger, chairman of the political reform group
Common Cause. ``It's a microcosm of the entire problem of these
unregulated contributions. It demonstrates every possible loophole
in both giving and receiving.''
</P>
<P>
   By that, Harshbarger means the corporate contributions would be
illegal if given to the parties directly. But they are legal
because they are made to ``host committees''in the cities staging
the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Another facet of the problem, he said, is that the donors
maintain they are doing their civic duty or making business
decisions. They deny they are trying to influence politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who solicit and get these contributions are going
to remember who gave,'' he said. ``At a minimum, these donors have
recognition by, and access to, the president and the leaders of
both parties.'' Few delegates in Philadelphia will leave hungry or
empty-handed, thanks to utilities and car makers, defense firms and
computer giants.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia delegates can eat Sunday brunch at their hotel, courtesy
of Atlanta Gas Light, Coca-Cola, the Georgia Electric Membership
Corp., Lockheed Martin, Oglethorpe Power Corp., Columbus-based
Synovus Financial Corp. and Turner Broadcasting Systems.
</P>
<P>
   And just when they get hungry again, they'll attend a reception
Sunday evening at the Philadelphia Academy of Music, where the food
and drink is courtesy of several banks and investment firms.
</P>
<P>
   This year's conventions may cost more than $100 million each,
and private businesses are paying most of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
