u f BC-NAPSTER-RULING-595&AMP;AD     07-28 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-RULING-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPSTER WINS BRIEF REPRIEVE FROM TWO JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two federal appeals judges in Northern California
delivered a last-minute reprieve for Napster Inc. on Friday
afternoon, overriding a judge's injunction and ruling that the
Internet music-swapping service can continue to allow its users to
trade copyrighted music.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected decision, by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in California, stayed the preliminary injunction issued
against Napster on Wednesday by Chief Judge Marilyn Patel of U.S.
District Court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   After finding a high probability that she would decide against
Napster at trial, Patel ordered the company to stop its users from
trading copyrighted songs. Napster said the order, which would have
taken effect at midnight Friday, Pacific time, would have crippled
the service, since it was impossible for it to distinguish which
music was copyrighted and which was not.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals judges said Friday that ``substantial
questions'' had been raised about the ``merits and form of the
injunction.''
</P>
<P>
   Napster, which says it has more than 20 million users, is a
specialized Internet search engine that enables users to find and
trade songs between their computers. It was sued in December by
major record companies, represented by the Recording Industry
Association of America, which accused Napster of contributing to
copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   Napster's chief executive, Hank Barry, said Friday that he was
``gratified and appreciative'' of the ruling, which will last until
a three-judge appeals court panel can hear arguments on whether the
injunction should be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   That hearing has yet to be scheduled, but it will be held
shortly after the panel finishes taking written arguments on Sept.
12.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Fanning, who created Napster last year as a freshman at
Northeastern University, said Friday: ``I am happy and grateful
that we do not have to turn away our 20 million users and that we
can continue to help artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America could appeal
Friday's decision, either to the full 9th Circuit Court or to the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Rosen, president of the RIAA, said she was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Court of Appeals decision today granting Napster a
temporary stay of the preliminary injunction is obviously a
disappointment, but we remain confident that the court will
ultimately affirm once it has had an opportunity to review the
facts and the law,'' Rosen said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is frustrating, of course, that the tens of millions of
daily infringements occurring on Napster will be able to continue,
at least temporarily.''
</P>
<P>
   While the ruling buys Napster time, it does nothing to change
Patel's apparent distaste for the company, said Dave Goldberg,
chief executive of Launch Media, an Internet music company that
works with both new media companies and traditional music
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in the long run its going to make much
difference. All this does is a stay of execution. It's not any
determination of right or wrong,'' Goldberg said. ``You've got a
trial judge who it looks like has already decided what the result's
going to be at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Since being created last year by Fanning, Napster has become one
of the Internet's fastest-growing Web sites. The free service
enables users to swap songs, in the form of MP3 files, between
their computers.
</P>
<P>
   About 500,000 to 800,000 people use Napster daily, or 1 percent
to 2 percent of U.S. Internet users, according to Nielsen/Net
Ratings, an Internet audience-measurement service, though other
experts say that estimate is probably low.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I love Napster, and all my friends do, too,'' said Cyrus
Kharas, 14, of Chevy Chase, Md. ``My friends and I, we get home at
11:30 or midnight from a movie, or whatever, and the first thing we
do is start downloading from Napster.''
</P>
<P>
   But the record industry argues that Napster operates nothing
more than a flea market filled with stolen property _ copyrighted
songs that must otherwise be bought in stores. And some Napster
users acknowledge that they use the service as a way to avoid
paying for music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea of having this service for free,'' Kharas
said. ``I don't think I would pay for MP3 service. Getting it
without paying is part of the fun, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Napster argues that it actually helps the record companies by
enabling listeners to preview songs free that they will then buy as
CDs. It also argues that its users should be allowed to trade songs
with one another for their personal use, just as they can with
taped CDs they have bought for their own use.
</P>
</TEXT>
