<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-YEARS0730-COX     07-28 1679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-YEARS0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday
 &HT;    Win or lose, Bush is ready for the race
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The George W. Bush presidential campaign, which
tried to navigate below the political radar screens for months,
maybe years, hit the TV screens with a wooden speech by a governor
not acclaimed as a great orator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow,'' Bush said in March 1999 at the Austin Convention
Center, ``I will file papers forming an exploratory committee so I
can take the next step in considering a campaign for president of
the United States. This will allow my friends to begin assessing
the level of support for my candidacy and to begin raising funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Support turned out to be good. Fund raising turned out even
better.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen months later _ having more or less stayed the course _
Bush on Thursday will accept the GOP presidential nomination at the
First Union Center here.
</P>
<P>
   He is still not a great speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how hard it is for you to put food on your family,'' he
said campaigning in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely is the question asked: Is our children learning?'' he
stated in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But say what you will about his intelligence, his past, the
state of the state of Texas and his one-man war on his native
tongue, Bush got from there to here. The not-ready-for-pop-quiz
candidate is heading here for a four-day coronation that he sees as
a milepost en route to a Jan. 20 inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting a prince who came on board with money, title and
pedigree, Bush gets little credit for making it this far. He
vanquished the GOP field, knocking off at least one other candidate
with a famous name (Elizabeth Dole), one with unlimited personal
wealth (Steve Forbes), a yapping pack of further-to-the-right
contenders who damned Bush as a moderate (Forbes, Gary Bauer, Alan
Keyes, Dan Quayle), and, finally, a
war-hero-turned-political-reformer (John McCain).
</P>
<P>
   He's been branded as a waffler, a possible ex-drug-using draft
dodger, a candidate unwilling to play by the fund-raising rules and
a smirker who shies from reading books without pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded to the criticism and questions just as former foe
Ann Richards predicted he would. He stayed on point. Voters still
do not know whether he ever used illegal drugs, and his non-answer
does not seem to have impacted the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you run against George Bush he is going to have one
message,'' Richards said last July. ``He is going to say that
message until the world gags and everybody else is going to be able
to say it back.''
</P>
<P>
   She was right. Bush has said the phrases ``compassionate
conservative'' and ``I'm a uniter, not a divider'' enough times for
comedians to use them as punchlines _ a sure sign that the words
have hit saturation level.
</P>
<P>
   It's gone so well that some see a candidate who is still
untested.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has had a pretty soft ride to this point,'' said University
of Texas presidential scholar Bruce Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   However you rate the ride, Bush successfully completed it and,
win or lose in November, he has changed the face of presidential
politics and the Republican Party. Perhaps most significantly, he
has changed the face that pops into people's minds when they hear
the words ``George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Phase II begins this week. And it could be ugly. Vice President
Al Gore, who picks up the Democratic nomination in Los Angeles in
two weeks, has a story line picked out: Big guy vs. the little guy.
Us vs. them. Truth and justice teamed up against the scion of the
evil empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This contest is really about whose side are you on,'' Gore
said in shaping up the race. ``I'm for the people. My opponent is
for the powerful. The old guard is trying to get back in.''
</P>
<P>
   The last guy to try that approach against Bush got some traction
with it, especially in New Hampshire. In the Granite State, McCain,
now a Bush backer, dealt the frontrunner a stunning defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Test of character,'' Bush said aboard the charter flight that
got him the heck out of New Hampshire as quickly as it could.
</P>
<P>
   ROUTE TO PHILADELPHIA
</P>
<P>
   Bush's road to the nomination began in 1998 as he swept to
gubernatorial re-election as national polls made him an early
favorite for the GOP presidential nod. To avoid the Big Lie, Bush
told Texas voters he was thinking about running for president and
might not serve four years if re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   He swamped Democrat Garry Mauro, and, with the national focus on
Austin, pushed through a legislative program, including a tax cut,
that served as the basis for the White House race that began in
March 1999 with the announcement of the exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign, Bush left markers as he tried to
portray himself as a new, more lovable brand of Republican. He
calls it compassionate conservatism, but many Texans recognize it
as similar to what used to pass for conservative Democrat in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1999, on the first swing through New Hampshire, Bush
busted out of the GOP mold by declining to vow to appoint Supreme
Court justices who share his anti-abortion rights view. Later that
month, at a Philadelphia Catholic school of all places, Bush said
an abortion rights supporter could be his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen months later, however, he would appoint Dick Cheney,
whose conservative voting record in Congress is delighting
anti-abortion groups but causing some problems for Bush backers
eager to offer a new, more inclusive image of the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Having set his philosophical marker, Bush quickly moved toward
cementing the front-runner status handed to him by the polls. He
fueled his campaign with other people's money, lots and lots of it.
At a Los Angeles elementary school in June 1999, Bush announced he
had raised more than $36.25 million in three months, $4 million
more than 1996 GOP nominee Bob Dole raised for his entire primary
campaign in 1996. For many of Bush's GOP foes, the race effectively
ended that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money doesn't win. But it's a pretty good start,'' Bush said
in announcing his fund-raising numbers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gore had raised only $18.5 million. McCain had
collected $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am humbled by the response,'' Bush said of the money that
became as important as his message.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, in a crucial decision that allowed him to spend
without limits, Bush announced he would not accept federal matching
funds for the primary campaign. Only the self-financed Forbes had
ever tried to navigate that path. ``There's a chance I'll be
running against somebody who will be able to jump in a government
airplane and travel the country making promises,'' Bush said of
Gore. ``I want to be able to respond. The best way to do that is to
not take taxpayer dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush family knows something about the advantages a vice
president can have. In 1988, the elder George Bush became the first
incumbent No. 2 man to win the White House since Martin Van Buren
did it in 1836.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he gets to Philadelphia, Bush will have spent almost
all of the more than $90 million he raised. After Thursday, when he
will be the nominee, the Bush campaign becomes a federally funded
effort backed by Republican National Committee money. The same will
happen to Gore after the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's money helped him capture the first make-believe battle _
last summer's Iowa straw poll. In January, he won the Iowa
caucuses, though McCain skipped the event. After McCain's win in
New Hampshire, Bush came back to capture South Carolina after an
appearance at ultra-conservative Bob Jones University that has
become a campaign-trail albatross. The New Hampshire loss put Bush
in unfamiliar territory. After all the fund raising and months of
polls that showed him as a prohibitive favorite, the McCain win
dented the inevitability of a Bush nomination. The governor, who
preaches kinder, gentler politics, struck back with an
uncharacteristic barrage of slaps at McCain, including a radio ad
that accused McCain of opposing federal backing of cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, which offered a simplified version of the truth,
inspired former U.S. Rep. Guy Molinari of New York to drop his
support of Bush and sign on with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain traded unpleasantries for several weeks. McCain
took major wins in the Arizona and Michigan primaries, but Bush
clinched the nomination with March wins around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout it all, Bush stayed on message and resisted pressure
to shake up his team, headed by longtime confidante and
ever-confident Karl Rove.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question will be over the course of the primary season who
is able to compete nationally and has a broader base of support in
the Republican Party,'' Rove said three weeks before Iowa kicked
off the political season. ``The answer is George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove's crystal ball proved accurate on March blew a big lead,
almost $100 million and became the back end of the only father-son
combination ever to lose presidential races.
</P>
<P>
   But win or lose, Bush has changed the landscape of American
politics. His fund-raising success could lead to major changes in
how future candidates run. His overtures to non-GOP constituencies
could pay off, if not for him then for future Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And, slowly but surely, he has come out of the family shadow and
became the rare son who re-named his father.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, it was George Bush and George W. Bush, with the
son needing the middle-initial modifier to distinguish him from the
more-famous father.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent news release announcing a Beaumont appearance by the
ex-president at the 100th anniversary of the nation's first oil
gusher, the elder Bush suddenly sprouted middle initials.
</P>
<P>
   ``George H.W. Bush to keynote Spindletop 2001 re-enactment,''
said the headline.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
