<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAKES-ANGRY0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jakes' may move due to low city
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bishop T.D. Jakes, unhappy with the financial support
offered by the city and its corporations, said he may not bring his
hugely successful ``Woman, Thou Art Loosed!'' conference back to
Atlanta next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we walk away, it's because we're pushed away,'' Jakes said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third year the conference has been in Atlanta and is
once again expected to draw nearly a quarter-million women before
it ends today.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jakes broke the Georgia Dome's single-day attendance
record, set by the Rev. Billy Graham, when he drew a crowd of
81,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes said it costs him ``well in the millions'' to stage the
three-day annual conference. He contends his event should be
treated in the same manner as the NFL's Super Bowl because it
generates more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate Super Bowl XXXIV in January actually
delivered twice that amount in tax and tourist dollars to Atlanta.
The city government contributed $300,000 to host the sporting
event, while the business community and the state offered financial
inducements and contributions of nearly $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes said city and corporate officials give him the
``run-around'' when he seeks greater financial incentives.
</P>
<P>
   DeWayne Martin, Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell's chief of staff,
said the city halved the Atlanta Civic Center rental fee for a play
produced by Jakes and gave him additional discounts for the Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Graham paid $80,000 to rent the Dome five years ago and
the Southern Baptist Convention paid nearly twice that last year
for the facility, Martin said. Jakes paid $75,000, the city
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that he sees our efforts as a sign of good faith
and that he will come back next year,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes praised the people and clergy of Atlanta but said he might
move his event to Houston next year where he can cut his costs in
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is sending me around . . . to different people,'' he
said. ``I got other people from other areas who are saying, 'Just
try us one time.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
