u s BC-BBO-STRAWBERRY-CANCER     07-28 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STRAWBERRY-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY SAYS CANCER MAY HAVE SPREAD
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES C. McKINLEY JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry's life _ a seemingly endless series of drug
relapses, suspensions, injuries, cancer and comebacks on the
baseball diamond _ took an unfortunate turn Friday, when the former
slugger said his colon cancer, first discovered and treated in
1998, had returned.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry told a Florida television station Friday that his
cancer had recurred. He declined a request for an interview with
The New York Times. Strawberry's wife, Charisse, said he would have
more tests before undergoing treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, but I think Darryl has a good attitude about it,''
she said in a telephone interview Friday night from the couple's
home in Tampa. ``He's ready to attack this aggressively. That's
what the doctors advised him to do. They told him he's young. He
recovered from this the first time. He'll do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, the New York Yankees said Strawberry
had undergone a CAT scan under the supervision of his doctor, John
Lepook, that ``suggests the possibility that his colon cancer has
spread to lymph nodes'' near his original tumor. Strawberry will
undergo more tests early next week ``to further define the
situation,'' the statement said. It remained unclear Friday night
when the scan was performed and when Strawberry learned of possibly
cancerous lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's announcement came as the former star had once again
landed in trouble with law-enforcement authorities in Florida. Last
February, Strawberry was suspended for a year from major league
baseball for cocaine use, his third suspension for drug abuse in
five years. In March he checked himself into the Sobrenity, Inc.,
clinic in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   But sometime in the last six weeks, he abruptly left the clinic,
after only three months of treatment, saying he needed to return to
baseball to make money. He has been seen and photographed attending
a local club, Trapeze II, where patrons pay membership fees to
engage in casual sex with each other.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Sports Illustrated published a photograph of
Strawberry with a bare-chested woman at the club, landing the
baseball player in trouble with his probation officers in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The former Yankee, Met and Dodger is on probation after being
arrested in April 1999 in Tampa, charged with possessing cocaine
and soliciting an undercover police officer posing as a prostitute.
As part of his probation, he not only must abstain from drugs, but
must avoid establishments where alcohol is the main source of
income.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry was scheduled to meet with Florida corrections
officials Friday to explain his presence at the club. To reporters,
he has denied that he is a member of the Trapeze club and has
dismissed the Sports Illustrated report as ``garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also maintained that he has been busy trying to negotiate
a minor league contract with the Saints, an independent team in St.
Paul, Minnesota. ``I needed to start making a living,'' Strawberry
told the Daily News earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   But his statements Friday suggest he may have had other reasons
besides financial problems for checking himself out of the
Sobrenity, Inc., clinic. He told a reporter from WFLA-TV in Tampa
Friday morning: ``I have some physical issues that I have to deal
with that's more important right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his cancer had returned, Strawberry said: ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Charisse Strawberry said her husband was in a peaceful mood
despite the bad news. He has been encouraged, she said, by the
comeback of Lance Armstrong, the cyclist who overcame testicular
cancer and won the Tour de France twice. She also acknowledged that
Strawberry was still fighting his addictions to drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two diseases, there are going to be relapses and
recurrences,'' she said. ``Baseball is the farthest thing from our
minds. Darryl's health is first.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing we can do about it,'' she added. ``We have
three children. We have to deal with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry underwent colon surgery and began chemotherapy less
than two years ago, in October 1998, as his teammates were winning
the World Series. He went to spring training in February 1999,
hoping for a quick comeback. But the Yankees decided that he was
not yet strong enough after his treatment to play by opening day.
He was left behind in Tampa to continue working out, but on April
14, the police in Tampa arrested him for soliciting sex from an
undercover officer posing as a prostitute. They also found less
than a gram of cocaine in his wallet. He pleaded no contest in
court. Commissioner Bud Selig suspended him from baseball for 120
days and a Florida judge sentenced him to 18 months probation.
</P>
<P>
   Though he eventually returned to the Yankees and played in the
1999 World Series, Strawberry apparently could not resist the lure
of cocaine. In January, he tested positive for cocaine during a
periodic test administrated by major league baseball. Selig again
suspended him, this time for a full year, and Strawberry sacrificed
his $750,000 salary.
</P>
<P>
   His former Yankees teammates, who were in Minneapolis to play
the Twins, reacted with shock and sadness to the news their
colleague might be facing a second round of cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had just gotten over cancer, and what can you say?'' Derek
Jeter, the shortstop, said. ``Everyone is shocked in here. It's so
unfortunate, and I don't know what else to say?''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' manager, Joe Torre, who himself was treated for
prostate cancer last year, said: ``It's very sad. Thank God there's
so many more ways to treat cancer today. He's going to have a tough
time, but hopefully, he'll get it taken care of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
