<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS TRADE IN VIETNAM BUT CONFUSION TAKES OVER
</P>
<P>
   With just two stocks, two hours and $5,000 in trades, the
Socialist Republic of Vietnam opened its first stock exchange for
business and took the first faltering steps into the uncertain
world of free markets.
</P>
<P>
   Hopeful investors packed into the three brokerage offices taking
orders for the shares to watch the market's birth on electronic
boards. But curiosity and excitement quickly turned into confusion
and disappointment, when minutes before the Ho Chi Minh City
Securities Trading Center opened, the government imposed a ceiling
on bids that invalidated many people's orders _ some of which were
more than 50 percent above the government's artificially imposed
prices.
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL TO BUY ALTEON FOR $7.8 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   Nortel Networks agreed to acquire Alteon WebSystems, which makes
equipment that improves the efficiency of Web server computers, for
$7.8 billion in stock. The move continues Nortel's push to become a
major developer of Internet systems. Earlier this week Nortel ended
discussions to combine its optical components unit with that of
Corning.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. FAULTS MEXICAN PHONE MARKET
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration took the first steps toward filing a
formal complaint against Mexico for failing to ensure open
competition in its $12 billion telecommunications market, just
weeks before Mexico's president-elect Vicente Fox is scheduled to
make his first visit to Washington to discuss commercial relations
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW CHIEF EXECUTIVE AT IVILLAGE
</P>
<P>
   Candice Carpenter, the founder of iVillage, the Web site focused
on topics of interest to women, has stepped down as chief executive
and named Doug McCormick, who joined the company in April as
president. Carpenter, who will remain chairman, will focus on
strategy and international expansion.
</P>
<P>
   NBC EXECUTIVE PROMOTED AT GE
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Wright, the longtime president of NBC, was named to
the additional post of vice chairman of General Electric. Wright is
not considered a possible successor to the GE chairman, John F.
Welch Jr., who is scheduled to retire in nine months, but industry
executives said the move emphasizes the importance of NBC in GE's
future.
</P>
<P>
   INTERPOOL BUYS RAIL CARGO COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Interpool, a unit of the Dutch insurer Aegon that leases cargo
containers, said that it had agreed to buy a rival, Transamerica
Leasing Inc., for about $675 million to add Transamerica's strength
in rail cargo to its own operations in maritime shipping.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL OUTPUT INCREASES IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economic recovery seems to be continuing, according to
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry. Industrial output
rose 1.7 percent in June from the previous month, bringing output
growth in the April-June quarter to 1.6 percent, the fourth
consecutive quarterly increase.
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI UNIT SEEKS EMERGENCY LOAN
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Engineering and Construction, a subsidiary of South
Korea's largest business conglomerate, Hyundai Group, requested
emergency loans from creditors to repay about $161 million in
loans. The move raises concerns that another mega-bankruptcy may be
in the making, and it comes a year after Daewoo Group collapsed
under debts estimated at $80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM EXPECTS $1.5 BILLION CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   Viacom will take charges of about $1.5 billion in the second
quarter for costs related to buying CBS and for new film accounting
rules, according to a recent filing and analysts' estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
