<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GAPOWER-SUIT0729-COX     07-28 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPOWER-SUIT0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. Power learns from Coca-Cola bias suit
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Power is clearly learning lessons from
Coca-Cola as it deals with a racial discrimination lawsuit from
employees.
</P>
<P>
   President David Ratcliffe hadn't seen this week's lawsuit when
he made plans to address the utility's 8,000 employees in a
statewide closed-circuit television address that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In that talk Thursday, he made clear the company's policy of
``zero tolerance for discriminatory or racially intolerant
behavior'' and promised to get to the bottom of the allegations and
address them.
</P>
<P>
   Then in an e-mail to the work force Friday, Ratcliffe addressed
the lawsuit's charge that a hangman's noose was displayed on
company premises. He vowed ``swift and effective action'' against
anyone who was involved in intimidating employees.
</P>
<P>
   Michael B. Terry, a lawyer for the employees who are suing, said
Friday he is pleased that Ratcliffe promised to make changes in the
company's diversity policies and discuss a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But Terry said the utility ``has a history of promises with no
follow-through or enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in Fulton County Superior Court on Thursday, was
assigned Friday to Judge Elizabeth Long. Georgia Power has 30 days
to file a response.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe emphasized Friday that the three employees who sued
the company ``are doing what they have a right to do'' and said he
had no position yet on whether their charges have merit.
</P>
<P>
   When four Coca-Cola employees filed a similar lawsuit against
their employer on April 22, 1999, one of the company's first
comments was that three of the employees' complaints were without
merit and the fourth employee had been fired for allegedly
violating the company's business code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to Coke's 10,000 U.S. employees in the days after
the suit was filed, then-Chairman M. Douglas Ivester said he took
the allegations seriously but the lawsuit had ``significant errors
of fact.''
</P>
<P>
   In a move six months later that was widely seen as ham-handed,
though it was unrelated to the lawsuit, the company's top-ranking
African-American executive was demoted in a management shakeup.
Carl Ware, who was also chairman of the company's Diversity Action
Council, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Ivester was replaced by Doug Daft earlier this
year that Ware was coaxed back to the company, that top managers'
pay was tied to meeting diversity goals and a vice president and
director for diversity strategies appointed.
</P>
<P>
   The beverage giant agreed to settle the case last month, only to
be hit with a $1.5 billion discrimination suit from another group
of employees.
</P>
<P>
   Two veteran public relations executives offered differing
assessments Friday of the two companies' public responses to the
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia Power has taken this thing seriously and that shows in
their actions,'' said Bob Hope, president of Hope-Beckham, and a
veteran of a number of corporate crisis management operations,
including the Exxon Valdez oil spill in Alaska. ``Coke was slow to
respond and tended to look defensive in their moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope, a former Coke executive, credited Georgia Power for ``fast
action from the top, expressing a sense of real concern and doing
things that don't admit to the problem but show tolerance to the
possibility of the problem having existed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Cohn, chairman of 360, a marketing agency, said that
given a recent series of highly publicized racial discrimination
complaints against Coca-Cola and other well-known Georgia
companies, Georgia Power should not have waited until a lawsuit was
filed to investigate its own standing. ``It's pretty late in the
game. Somebody should have been on top of this a long time ago,''
said Cohn.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Baskin, a spokesman for Coke, declined to engage in any
comparisons Friday. ``It wouldn't be appropriate for us to comment
on a legal case involving another company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are parallels in the Coke and Georgia Power cases.
</P>
<P>
   The same Atlanta law firm, Bondurant, Mixon &AMP; Elmore, represents
plaintiffs in both cases. Both suits sought standing as class
actions representing about 2,000 employees at each company.
</P>
<P>
   Another link is that Ware is one of three African-American board
members at Georgia Power. Ware, now Coke's executive vice president
for global public affairs, was not available for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While both cases allege a pattern of racial discrimination in
employment and compensation practices, the Georgia Power case also
alleges a ``reckless indifference'' by the company to racially
hostile workplace conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, the latest case has similarities to two lawsuits
filed in May by 11 black employees of Lockheed Martin Corp. who
alleged a pervasive climate of racism at the aerospace company's
Marietta plant.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ratcliffe, Tom Burbage, top executive at the Marietta
plant, made it clear at the outset that he's willing to negotiate a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement, or a judgment against the utility, would certainly
run into the millions of dollars, say legal experts. Ratcliffe said
the company would not seek to pass any such costs to its 1.8
million Georgia ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power has clearly studied Coke's experience and the
utility does appear to be further along than Coke was at this
juncture in dealing with the issues raised in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe announced formation of a Diversity Action Council on
Thursday, co-chaired by Juanita Baranco, another African-American
board member.
</P>
<P>
   A.W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg, chairman and chief executive officer of
Southern Co., Georgia Power's parent and co-defendant in the
discrimination suit, earlier this year made ``improve diversity'' a
top goal and began tying compensation to progress in that area.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has procedures in place for employees to be
fairly considered for promotions and a ``corporate concerns''
program to bring complaints of discrimination or harassment to the
attention of superiors.
</P>
<P>
   But Christoper C. Womack, human resources vice president at both
Georgia Power and Southern, said the cases of hangman's nooses,
which apparently numbered three, were not brought up through any of
the company's channels.
</P>
<P>
   Womack, one of the company's highest-ranking black executives,
said the companywide review ordered by Ratcliffe will try to find
out why. ``Why were they not utilized?'' he asked. ``We thought we
were in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
