<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-CAMP-DAVID-88     07-28 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CAMP-DAVID-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMATIC UPS, DOWNS AND TURNS AT CAMP DAVID 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ and ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two weeks President Clinton spent with the
leaders of Israel and the Palestinians certainly had moments of
great drama, when nerve-tingling discussions about the fate of the
holy city of Jerusalem breached for the first time what all sides
called the taboo issue.
</P>
<P>
   There were also moments of crisis, as when Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak nearly choked to death on a peanut and White
House officials worried how they would explain his death to
conspiracy theorists around the world. A member of the prime
minister's own team delivered the life-saving Heimlich maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   There were light moments, when Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators traded cigars, bowled, played Ping Pong and dodged deer
and chipmunks as they navigated paved paths in golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   There were bizarre moments, when Clinton broke his own news
blackout by musing about the talks with The New York Daily News,
without telling any of his aides of the interview that was supposed
to help defend his wife against accusations that she made an
anti-Semitic slur in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   And through it all there were negotiations, day and night, as
Clinton, Barak and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, drew on a
their full array of bluffs and brinkmanship, rhetoric and reason as
they invented, rejected and embraced creative solutions to ending
the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic moment came mid-way through talks, when
Clinton gripped Arafat's hands tightly, sitting so close to him
that they butted foreheads. The president implored, flattered,
threatened and wooed, promising everything he could _ the creation
of a Palestinian state, the financial support of the world to pay
for it, a permanent place for Arafat in the pantheon of history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't stop there. It would be another week before the
president acknowledged that the summit would not produce a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:10 a.m. last Tuesday, 15 days after Clinton had brought
Israelis and Palestinians to Camp David to resolve issues that had
eluded them for half a century, the 71-year-old Palestinian leader
said no.
</P>
<P>
   But that morning, as the Palestinian leader contemplated
Clinton's offer in his cabin on the secluded, wooded complex,
neither Arafat nor Barak could escape the ghosts of the first Camp
David summit meeting, in 1978, when President Jimmy Carter brought
together Prime Minister Menachem Begin of Israel and President
Anwar Sadat of Egypt for what proved to be successful peace-making.
</P>
<P>
   A glass case of photographs from that summit was prominently
displayed in a cabin called Holly, where many key meetings took
place, and a three-page, hand-written note of appreciation from
Carter to Begin hung on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both leaders were preoccupied with the weight and presence of
history,'' said Aaron D. Miller, a senior U.S. negotiator. ``There
was a sense that we were not alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The last moment came when Arafat sent Saeb Erekat, a trusted
aide, and Mohammed Dahlan, the Palestinian chief of security, to
Clinton's cabin, with grim faces and a brief letter, hand-written
in Arabic on the official stationery of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Erakat slowly read the letter aloud, translating for Clinton and
advisers who were with him, including Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Samuel Berger, the national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go further than I've gone,'' a senior administration
official paraphrased Arafat as saying. ``The suggestions I have
heard do not take us in the direction I find acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to fail,'' Clinton told his aides after the
emissaries left, ``particularly at this.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter did not surprise. Even though Clinton had used all of
his powers of persuasion to coax a shaken Arafat into a settlement,
he already had the sense that the Palestinian leader was
disengaging, becoming even more quiet and passive than he had been
during the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton had been intense in his pitch-making, so intense
that a half-dozen of his aides, including chief negotiator Dennis
Ross and chief of staff John Podesta, hid themselves in the kitchen
to eavesdrop on the president's head-butting session with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   They took turns watching the scene through a porthole in the
swinging glass door that led to the living room, cracking the door
a little to catch snippets of the conversation. At one point, one
of the aides recounted, so many of them pressed against the glass
that he feared they would push the door open and pour into the room
like bureaucratic Marx brothers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, this was not Arafat's time to make the boldest
gesture of his 30-year career as the leader of the Palestinian
people. And after his letter was delivered, Clinton would be with
him again only briefly, in a good-bye session with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president sat with them and told them that everyone has
worked very hard and given their best but they couldn't get
there,'' Albright recalled in an interview. ``They shook hands. And
that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, another chapter in the peace effort concluded. It had
been a failed negotiation, but it had been a remarkable one as
well, and already Israeli and Palestinian negotiators were talking
about getting together again.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For more than a month, Clinton had been eager to convene a
summit. Barak was badgering him to do it, arguing in repeated phone
calls that only what he called ``the pressure cooker'' of a summit
would force through excruciating decisions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat wanted a few more weeks to prepare. ``He said, `The
time is not ripe,' Albright said of her meeting with Arafat in late
June. ``But he also said that he had the highest respect for the
president and would do as he was asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving the decision was the reality of the U.S. political
calendar. Holding the summit during the Republican convention, in
early August, was out of the question, because it could be seen by
Republicans to be politically driven. Clinton was also boxed in by
a commitment to go to Japan on July 19. Most importantly, the
deadline of Sept. 13 loomed large _ the date by which Arafat said
he would unilaterally declare a state.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials acknowledge that Arafat bore the
greatest burden.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Arab leaders with whom he had consulted _ including
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, King Abdullah of Jordan and Crown
Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia _ offered him support for
surrendering claim to sovereignty over any part of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   For the first several days of the talks, both sides postured. At
one point, Clinton got so angry that he told both sides, ``This is
ridiculous. If this is what you're going to do, we shouldn't be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly and without warning, discussions opened up,
substantively, on the most serious of issues: the status of
Jerusalem. On July 17, the sixth day of the summit, Barak put down
on paper proposals to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As Barak put final touches on his proposals, he did what he
always does when he feels pressured: he ate.
</P>
<P>
   A peanut lodged in his throat, and for 40 tense seconds, he
stopped breathing as helpless aides looked on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary, but the people around the prime minister were
more scared than the prime minister,'' recalled Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak, a senior Israeli negotiator. One aide began pounding
him on the back, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Gid Gernstein, the youngest member of the Israeli
delegation, rushed to Barak and performed the Heimlich maneuver on
him. A peanut came flying out.
</P>
<P>
   When Barak arrived at Clinton's doorstep after midnight, he had
some ideas that moved away from the traditional Israeli position on
Jerusalem. When Clinton took the ideas to Arafat, he was singularly
unimpressed, an American official said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the talks, Arafat seemed oddly passive. He referred
to himself repeatedly as the ``permanent vice president'' of the
organization uniting Muslim countries around the world. ``He wasn't
speaking just for himself,'' one senior official said. ``He was
speaking for a billion Muslims and the 2 million Arabs in the
region as well.''
</P>
<P>
   To bridge the differences, the Americans presented ideas of
their own to Arafat. In the living room of his cabin on the evening
of July 18, Clinton sat him down and, with only Gemal Helal, the
State Department's Arabic interpreter, at his side, told the
Palestinian what a mistake he was making.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president said to Arafat: `I will go to the G-8 meeting in
Japan on Wednesday and I will ask them to provide the support you
need for your state,' '' Berger recounted. ``What I ask you to do
is to make a principled compromise on Jerusalem. It is not
everything you want, but the price you have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat said little as Clinton grabbed him by the arms and butted
his forehead to Arafat's forehead in what Berger called ``the
Lyndon B. Johnson style of persuasion.''
</P>
<P>
   When that tactic did not work, Clinton then suggested to Arafat
that he consider a partial settlement _ deferring Jerusalem for
later. Arafat refused.
</P>
<P>
   The morning of Clinton's departure arrived, and the president
decided there was little point in continuing the talks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 10:50 pm, the White House press office released a
two-sentence statement that screamed ``failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a strange thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``As word went out, the trees talked,'' said Berger, referring
to the instant rumor network at Camp David. Barak was convinced by
several of his negotiators that he should not go home empty-handed.
Arafat never wanted to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left for Japan and, in his absence, the mood calmed. Dr.
Albright invited Arafat to her farm in Leesburg, Va., where they
dined on canned sardines (which he requested, Albright said).
Barak, meanwhile, visited Gettysburg with Albright and Bruce
Riedel, the senior Middle East official at the National Security
Council and a Civil War buff.  &QL; 
By the time Clinton returned from Japan that Sunday night, the
negotiators reported enough progress to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   In three back-to-back sessions, Clinton, seated at the dining
room table in his cabin, with two negotiators from each side, made
headway on security, refugees and borders. For the sake of a peace
to ensure Israel's security, Barak was entertaining a sizable
transfer of West Bank territory, the evacuation of settlements, a
land swap, a small resettlement plan for Palestinian refugees and
the ceding of some Jerusalem neighborhoods to the Palestinians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We could begin to see the contours of an agreement on these
issues,'' said Berger.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now was the moment for the final push on Jerusalem. Clinton
asked each leader to appoint a single negotiator to meet with him
on what turned out to be the last night of the summit. Between
Clinton and Dennis Ross, the special coordinator for the Middle
East, sat Erekat and the Israeli, Shlomo Ben Ami. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton presented three scenarios for Jerusalem, with variations
along the way, diplomats said. The first laid out how the issues of
sovereignty might be resolved, including in the old city where the
Palestinians would be given sovereignty over the Muslim and
Christian quarters and the Israelis would have the Jewish and
Armenian quarters. Another proposal revolved around Palestinian
sovereignty over several of the neighborhoods surrounding the Old
City and having administrative autonomy within the walls. A third
notion suggested deferring the Jerusalem problem for years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also put forward the possibility: no agreement at all.
As he talked through the proposals, Erekat's body language made
clear that the Palestinians were not playing, and it was codified
in Arafat's letter.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, a lawyer, underscored that sense of a continuum, when he
blamed Arafat for not accepting the deal Clinton offered, and then
took part of his statement back. ``Arafat wasn't able to make that
leap,'' Berger said in an interview. ``Let me make my tenses
correct. Arafat was not at this point able to make that leap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
