<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BBy Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGDALE, ARK _ Gov. George W. Bush told a cheering crowd of
2,000 Friday that he, ``found the right man in Dick Cheney,'' as
the GOP running mates launched a pre-convention tour through six
swing states in six days before arriving in Philadelphia for the
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush traveled with his wife Laura to President Clinton's home
state where the couple joined with Cheney and his wife Lynne. U.S.
Rep. Asa Hutchison and his brother, U.S. Sen. Tim Hutchison, both
of Arkansas, and U.S. Rep. Roy Blunt, a Missouri Republican, were
among those who welcomed the Bushes at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Philadelphia GOP leaders fended off an attempt to
moderate the party's policy on abortion as the platform committee
fine-tuned its plank before the convention begins Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides also stepped in to veto a plan to change the party's
primary election process for 2004. The so-called ``Delaware Plan,''
which would have allowed smaller, less influential states to hold
their primaries first was nixed after Bush aides said the governor
did not want any changes for now because there were too many
problems with forcing states to comply with the plan.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction in Arkansas, Asa Hutchison lauded Cheney,
who came under immediate attack from Democrats for his conservative
voting record and ties to the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Gov. Bush make the right decision in picking Secretary
Cheney as his running mate?'' Hutchison asked a cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he is looking forward to the trek to Philadelphia
where he is scheduled to arrive on Thursday to deliver what will
be, arguably, the most important speech of his political career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It buoys my heart and it buoys my spirit to know we're working
our way to Philadelphia for the Republican National Convention and
working our way across battleground states that the Republican
ticket hasn't been able to carry in the last two election cycles,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won Arkansas in 1992 as he dashed Bush's father's
re-election hopes. Four years later, he beat former U.S. Sen. Bob
Dole here. No GOP presidential candidate has won any of the states
on the pre-convention tour since 1988. Campaign spokeswoman Karen
Hughes said they chose the route, a veritable trail of tears for
the GOP, because, ``we are not ceding any territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who was defense secretary under President Bush, promised
victory in 2000 _ but not without state-by-state warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough campaign, make no mistake about it,''
Cheney said. ``We're going to have to fight every single day in
every single state...''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that Bush is putting the final touches on his
convention speech. The speech is nearly 3,900 words long and should
take about 45 minutes to deliver, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he is looking forward to giving the speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dynamic moment in my life to walk out on the stage
and to speak from my heart for however long it takes to get through
the speech,'' he said, adding that he wants the American people to
learn that he is, ``a decisive, firm leader who's got good
judgement and is ready to lead the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
