<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CABLETRON-SPINOFFS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLETRON PREPARES TO DIVIDE AND CONQUER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By KATE BERRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are four spinoffs better than one whole company? That is the
puzzle facing holders of Cabletron Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Once a highflier in computer networking, Cabletron lacks the
size and vigor to compete across the board with the likes of Cisco
Systems and Lucent Technologies. So it announced in February that
it would split into four operating units and sell stakes of up to
20 percent in each to the public over the next 18 months, on the
theory that four nimble baby Cabletrons would excite investors _
and potential acquirers _ more than the parent could. The company,
based in Rochester, N.H., has also unloaded about $600 million in
noncore assets in the revamping.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I take a company that is growing 4 to 6 percent
year-over-year and transform it into one growing 30 percent a
year?'' asked Piyush Patel, Cabletron's chairman and chief
executive, in an interview. ``One of the things holding us back is
I had one model peanut-buttered on four different businesses. They
could not reach their highest potential.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Wall Street was underwhelmed, and Cabletron's stock
rode the technology downdraft harder than its peers, plummeting
from $52 a share in early March to $18.625 in April. It has since
rebounded to around $25, largely on the faith of Silver Lake
Partners, a private equity firm in Menlo Park, Calif., that manages
$2.3 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Lake has committed $90 million so far to Cabletron's four
IPOs-in-waiting, and has bet on a rise in the parent's stock by
buying warrants and convertible preferred shares. A Silver Lake
partner, David Roux, is on Cabletron's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parts are worth more than the whole,'' said Jim Davidson,
co-founder of Silver Lake. He expects Cabletron stock to rise well
above $50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron has been acting like an incubator for a while,
investing in some two dozen technology start-ups whose wireless and
optical-networking products complement its own. Patel's admiration
for CMGI, a leading Internet incubator, is evident in Cabletron's
planned post-spinoff ticker symbol, CSGI. (It is now CS.) While
bigger rivals have been acquiring actively, Cabletron has piled up
$1.6 billion in cash and no debt.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest property among the four imminent spinoffs is
Riverstone Networks, which sells Internet routers and switches for
large-scale networks, the kind that span whole cities. Analysts
expect sales to double this year, reaching $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors like Foundry Networks, Juniper Networks and Redback
Networks have been hot performers, and analysts who like the
revamping plan say Riverstone ought to be valued highly when it
comes to market in the fall. Others said they want to wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   Enterasys Networks, which sells routers and switches to large
corporations, will be the biggest of the four, with $660 million in
sales last year, and projected growth of 20 percent this year. The
other two are much smaller but growing faster: GlobalNetwork
Technology Services, which provides network management and security
and is the second unit expected to come public this year, and
Aprisma Management Technologies, specializing in infrastructure
management software. Aprisma competes with Micromuse and Visual
Networks, whose stock valuations are high.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're throwing out as comparables very attractive category
killers,'' said Megan Graham-Hackett of Standard &AMP; Poor's Equity
Group. ``These other highfliers have a lot of momentum. I'm just a
little wary.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron reported a loss of $37.9 million, or 21 cents a share,
in the quarter ended June 30, compared with a loss of $22.5
million, or 13 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. Revenue
fell 21 percent, to $275.1 million, reflecting the asset sales.
Patel said Cabletron would return to black ink by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, analysts say, the picture is less clear. ``If you
take a look at their businesses, they are attractive, but aren't
making money,'' Graham-Hackett said. ``The core business is a
slower growth model,'' she said, and the small spinoffs may lack
the heft to thrive on their own.
</P>
</TEXT>
