<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILES-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI FILES WOUND UP AT WHITE HOUSE BY ERROR, REPORT FINDS
</HEADLINE>
  By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration improperly acquired
hundreds of FBI files through a series of errors committed by the
Secret Service and, most of all, by an incompetent investigator in
the White House, according to a report by the independent counsel
that was released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ray, the independent counsel, announced publicly in March
that he had concluded his investigation of the acquisition of the
files and that there had been no criminal wrongdoing. He filed the
full report with a special judicial panel that oversees independent
counsel investigations, and the report was made public Friday by
the panel's judges.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that the files, many of which involved
prominent Republicans, were acquired by the White House office of
personnel security mainly through the mistakes of Anthony Marceca,
a low-level employee there.
</P>
<P>
   Marceca, described by the report as a former Democratic
political advance person, was hired by the head of the office,
Craig Livingstone, to help get its files in order. Livingstone,
also a former political advance aide, had no experience in
security.
</P>
<P>
   Marceca requested that the FBI provide him with confidential
personnel files on any person who worked at the White House. From
the time he started his work in August 1993 until he left the next
year, he requisitioned more than 1,100 such files. The independent
counsel report said at least 726 of them were for people who no
longer worked at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Because many of those were of prominent Republicans, suspicions
were raised in news reports and in Congress that the acquisition
was an effort by Clinton officials to gather political
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining why Ray concluded that was not so, the report said
investigators found that Marceca had requisitioned the files using
an inaccurate list provided by the Secret Service. Although the
Secret Service has denied that it was responsible for preparing
such a list, Ray found that the Secret Service had in fact prepared
a list that was ``unlabeled and overinclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray's report said that Marceca admitted lying to Congress and to
a federal grand jury but that he could not be prosecuted because he
had been given immunity by federal prosecutors. In any event, the
report said, nothing in his testimony affected the conclusion that
there had not been a conspiracy to obtain Republican files.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the Secret Service had been flatly mistaken and
gave misleading testimony when senior officials told Congress and
the press that its computer system was incapable of producing an
outdated list of White House passholders.
</P>
<P>
   Because it denied any responsibility, the prosecutor said, the
Secret Service greatly contributed to the suspicions that the
acquisitions of the files could not have been an innocent mistake
as the White House had said.
</P>
<P>
   In an appendix to the report, a lawyer for three Secret Service
officials disputed the conclusion blaming the Secret Service.
Warren Dennis, a lawyer for Lewis Merletti, the former director of
the service, and for John Libonati and Jeffrey Undercoffer, two
former special agents, said the report was unfair because it
misinterpreted their comments about the agency's computer system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
