<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-TEX </SLUG>
 
 TEXAS DEMOCRATS TRAVEL TO GOP CONVENTION AS `TRUTH SQUAD'
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By JACK DOUGLAS JR.
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A busload of Texas Democrats began rolling
down the highway this week on a 1,255-mile trek to a huge
convention of Republicans in Philly, talking bad about Gov. George
W. Bush every mile of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy warriors, and we're here to say, `Don't mess with
America,' '' LaNell Anderson, a Houston real estate agent and
Democrat stalwart, said by cellphone as the bus crossed over the
Ohio River.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and her fellow Democrats are expected to be joined by
Fort Worth Mayor Pro Tem Ralph McCloud and state Rep. Lon Burnam,
D-Fort Worth, early Sunday just before the bus enters Philadelphia,
host city of the Republican Party's national convention next week.
</P>
<P>
   They are calling themselves the ``Texas Truth Squad,'' and they
say their mission is to peacefully invade the Republican's
nominating party and ``set the record straight about George W.
Bush's mess in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Texas governor prepares to accept the GOP's presidential
nomination on Thursday, Burnam, Anderson and company said they will
tell anybody willing to listen about what they say is the state's
dismal record concerning pollution, health care and the lack of
insurance for poor children.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats plan a ``Bushwacked barbecue'' on Sunday at a
steelworkers' union hall near the GOP convention. ``My line will be
that George Bush is the worst environmental accident to happen
since the nuclear meltdown in Chernobyl,'' Burnam said, referring
to the 1986 nuclear accident in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said he does
not think that the group will cause much of a stir at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their views are in the minority in Texas regarding George
Bush, and their views will most likely be in the minority here in
Philadelphia,'' Bartlett said
</P>
<P>
   He credited the governor with cutting taxes, improving schools
and making ``progress in cleaning the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnam said he realizes that he and his small band of Democrats
will be far outnumbered at the Republican convention. ``But,''
Burnam said: ``Davy Crockett was outnumbered at the Alamo, and he
still did the right thing for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Miller of the Austin-based Proud of Texas Committee, formed
to divert what it says is politically charged _ and often
out-of-state _ criticism of Bush's home state, said the Democrats'
bus trip seems to be fueled only by political rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Texans need to go out and bang on their own
state,'' Miller said, ``but that's their constitutional right.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Hess, a spokesman for the Democratic National Committee and
a passenger on the ``truth'' tour, said the group has received warm
receptions from ``working families'' and the media. They embarked
from Louisville, Ky., on Thursday, spent the night in Cincinnati,
and then made stops yesterday in Dayton and Columbus, Ohio, before
stopping in Charleston, W.V., for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Hess said they plan to arrive in Philadelphia on Sunday, the day
before the official opening of the convention, as long as there are
no political ``dirty tricks'' like letting the air out of the
tires.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
