A6481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-WOMENGYM0729-COX     07-28 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMENGYM0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympians bring experience and maturity
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ They're older, wiser and a little banged up. Their
scores aren't what they used to be. But the returning members of
U.S. gymnastics' most illustrious team, the Magnificent Seven,
still carry an aura about them as they compete here in the U.S.
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Call them the Famous Five.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Miller and Dominique Dawes are two-time Olympians, while
Dominique Moceanu, Amy Chow and Jaycie Phelps joined them in
Atlanta to win the improbable Olympic team gold four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really cool because you look across the gym and
you see somebody you know, a friend,'' said Chow. ``I want to say
it's like ESP.''
</P>
<P>
   They all have a sixth sense about what each is going through.
After the Olympics, they bonded on the successful post-Olympic
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spending 24 hours of the day on the bus the majority of the
time gets you talking,'' Miller said. ``We felt like sisters by the
time we had to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Then all but Moceanu retired from the national gymnastics scene,
and she also dropped out of the picture for more than a year
because of injuries and turmoil in her personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's a longshot that all five will be teammates again
in Sydney, none regret the decision to try again. They must finish
in the top 12 tonight to advance to the Olympic Trials Aug. 17-20
in Boston, or petition into the meet. A committee, led by national
team coordinator Bela Karolyi, then will choose the six Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Chow is third, Moceanu (who rolled her ankle warming
up for her first event Thursday) is 10th, Dawes 13th and Phelps
17th. Miller, who has an injured leg and competed only on uneven
bars on the first day, won't compete tonight, but will petition
into the Trials. So will Phelps, who withdrew with an injured
thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great having everyone back again,'' Phelps said.
``It's like a family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Team captain Amanda Borden is sitting in the stands at the Kiel
Center, but has a pass to mingle on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always miss it and I'll always want to be out there,''
said Borden, a student at Arizona State, ``but at the same time,
I'm really happy with everything I have in my life and I'm able to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Kerri Strug, whose courageous vault onto an injured leg
clinched the gold, is missing. She has transferred from UCLA to
Stanford and plans to get a master's degree in sociology
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly expected to have some of them back,'' said Karolyi,
``because they were young and they were capable and they all had
good reasons to come back. But to be honest, I never thought there
was going to be 90 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally do appreciate very much the effort to make
another Olympic team. . . . And some of them definitely will.''
</P>
<P>
   Who? Karolyi chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a couple or three, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   After a young U.S. team placed a dismal sixth at the 1999 World
Championships, the country needed the experience the older gymnasts
could provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prestige, the maturity, the overall balance of the team is
basically increasing,'' Karolyi said, ``and it's getting to the
point to be respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Chow, 22, a biology major at Stanford, returned to competition
in 1999. ``I was a little bored,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps, 20, was coaching and attending Arizona State when she
threw her name back in the ring in November. She wanted to prepare
for the post-Olympic tour, and her left knee, which had undergone
three surgeries, was feeling good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had a lot of gymnastics left in me,'' Phelps
said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 23, now married and attending the University of
Oklahoma, re-entered the gym in December. She was also preparing
for the tour, then realized she had the desire and the ability to
try for another team medal. Besides, her husband had never seen her
compete.
</P>
<P>
   But it took Miller a couple of days to work up the nerve to tell
coach Steve Nunno.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would ask him to train me and he would laugh and
that would be the worst feeling ever, and he didn't,'' Miller said.
``He said, `Do you know what it means? Do you remember how hard it
was?'''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, meanwhile, had been embroiled in a well-publicized
Houston emancipation case against her parents. She moved to
Cincinnati in January to train with coach Mary Lee Tracy and lives
with her mother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I've been through it, it's not as overwhelming as it was
when I was little,'' said Moceanu, 18, who has grown about 10
inches since 1996 and is now 5-foot-2.
</P>
<P>
   Dawes, 23, a student at the University of Maryland who has
pursued an acting career, was the last to commit. After starting to
train in February, ``I took a little bit of time off again, because
I wasn't sure if I had it in me,'' she said. By the end of April,
she thought she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `96, there was a lot more pressure, just because that was
our peak year,'' Dawes said. ``Now I just want to work hard and
show everyone that I can still do gymnastics well.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she didn't check her scores Thursday. ``I know nothing
that I got in any event,'' she said, quickly adding, ``So don't
tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
