<HEADER>
A6484 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-2TAK     07-28 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP OVERHAUL OF PRIMARY SEASON IS KILLED BY BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, on his way here for
a triumphal nomination, ended the last bit of uncertainty
surrounding next week's convention by killing efforts to allow
voters in all states to cast primary ballots that actually counted.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, designed by the Republican National Committee after
this year's nominations were settled in March, was intended to
lengthen the primary system by making the big states vote last.
Under the plan, the smallest states would have held their primaries
in February, small states in March, medium-size states in April and
big states in May.
</P>
<P>
   On May 12, Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, told reporters
that Bush had no position on the plan and would have none later.
But Friday morning Rove passed the word to members of the
convention rules committee that the campaign wanted it killed, and
the committee duly voted to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's intervention bluntly brushed aside several months' work
of party leaders to design a new primary system, and there was a
bit of mystery Friday surrounding the Bush camp's reasons. The
people Rove talked to either declined to quote his stated reasons
or dismissed them as implausible. Most members put the last-minute
move down to a desire to have a convention utterly free of
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   One high-level Bush aide said the campaign feared its
re-election efforts would be hindered if a new calendar led states
to shift from primaries to caucuses and state conventions in 2004.
Some rules committee members said Democrats would keep states like
California and New York from changing the dates of primaries,
forcing Republicans in those states to use caucuses. The Bush aide
called caucuses a ``breeding ground'' for trouble. Republican
caucuses often fall under control of the party's most right-wing
elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl did express some concern to several members of the rules
committee, saying we were concerned this would put the Republicans
at a competitive disadvantage,'' said Karen P. Hughes, a Bush
spokeswoman. She said the Bush campaign also also had concerns
``that it would limit the number of candidates who are able to
participate in so many places all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was uncertainty about the Bush campaign's purpose,
there was none about its effectiveness. On Thursday, while the
campaign was still neutral, the Republican National Committee voted
92-55 to approve the plan and send it to the Rules Committee. On
Friday, after Rove intervened, the committee voted 66-33 to reject
it. The losers had enough support to bring a minority report to the
floor on Monday, but they said they would not.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That same firm control, exerted with a slightly lighter rein,
was evident Friday in platform committee deliberations. While
abortion-rights advocates argued, passionately if unavailingly, for
a softening of the party's stance, and conservatives demanded
tougher language on education, neither side had the inclination or
the strength for a floor fight.
</P>
<P>
   After killing the big-states-last plan, the rules committee also
voted down an effort to give the national committee new authority
to negotiate with the Democrats on a system that did not have so
many states voting so early that it resembled a national primary.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Blackwell, a committee member from Virginia, said one
virtue of the Republican Party was that its rules were ``locked in
concrete'' from one convention to the next.
</P>
<P>
   He said if the national committee was given this authority,
which the Democratic National Committee already has, ``we could
have heaven knows what imposed on us from the top.'' That vote was
72-28, even though the Bush campaign took no stand on it.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One evidence of the utter control displayed by the Bush campaign
over the plan to string out the primaries was the unwillingness of
the losers even to complain about it during the meeting. Indeed,
the Bush position was never mentioned, except when Tom Sansonetti
of Wyoming, the chairman of the rules committee, told the meeting
that the Bush campaign had no position. That was minutes before
Rove told him things had changed.
</P>
<P>
   Sansonetti said in an interview that Rove told him the Bush
campaign thought the plan was flawed because candidates would have
to undergo heavy, tiring travel in February, when a dozen very
small states would vote.
</P>
<P>
   That objection, also cited Friday on the Bush campaign plane by
a spokesman, Scott McClellan, had never been raised in any meeting
on the plan, where the early, small-state campaigning was
specifically designed to keep any candidate from dominating all the
early states, and thereby to give underfinanced hopefuls a chance
to make an impression by an early win.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bill Brock, the former senator from Tennessee and former
Republican chairman whose commission produced the plan, said Rove
had given him the same explanation.
</P>
<P>
   David Norcross, a rules committee member from New Jersey who had
been among the plan's most enthusiastic supporters until this week,
said they had raised the travel question with him, too, along with
the problem that some states might face if Democrats blocked any
change.
</P>
<P>
   He said no one from the Bush campaign had mentioned a desire to
avoid a floor fight to him. The closest anyone came to admitting
that motive was when Karen Hughes, a Bush spokeswoman, said,
``Obviously we want out convention to focus primarily on Governor
Bush and his positive proposal for America, but we wanted people to
be heard in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that people had a chance to express a lot of
different opinions about a better way to nominate a president,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Norcross deserted the plan he had once strongly advocated, and
when he moved to kill it in the Rules Committee, he said he was
just reacting to a ``convergence of problems'' around the plan. He
cited travel costs and the fear of big states that they would have
no influence because they would have come last. Blackwell, who
supported the plan, sarcastically praised Norcross for his
``versatility.''
</P>
<P>
   Sansonetti vainly pleaded for the plan, saying that this year
``two-thirds of the states did not have the opportunity to have a
say in the choice of the most powerful person in the world.'' He
said 30 states voted within eight days, and without the new
proposed rules, more would do so next time.
</P>
<P>
   He scoffed at the travel argument, saying ``They are already
traveling all over. If they're not in a primary, they are raising
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Sansonetti argued that the proposed system would leave the
winner uncertain until the end because the big states had more than
half the delegates. That would make every state's votes meaningful,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Rath, a committee member from New Hampshire, disagreed.
He said ``The race ends politically a lot earlier than it ends
mathematically.'' He said that although Bush and Vice President Al
Gore were seen as certain winners after the March 7 primaries, they
did not yet have the majorities of delegates needed for nomination.
Those majorities were reached on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   One floor fight is still possible, and over a subject that was
debated as long as the primary plan. The committee voted to make
all members of the Republican National Committee automatic
delegates in 2004, and foes promised to fight the plan as
``elitist,'' and also because it copied the Democratic practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
