<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-DISPUTE0729-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida program to settle HMO, doctor feuds
 &HT;    By John Murawski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida is developing what state health
officials believe is the nation's first dispute resolution program
to mediate claims by hospitals and doctors seeking denied payments
from HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   The program, being readied for Jan. 1, was created in response
to long-standing complaints that health maintenance organizations
delay payment or simply don't pay bills.
</P>
<P>
   Now the only alternative for doctors and hospitals, outside an
HMO's internal appeals process, is to sue the HMO.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a doctor who has $1,000 in claims outstanding
for a while and they're jacking him around, he's certainly not
going to hire a lawyer and pay $20,000 to file suit and get his
$1,000 back,'' said Jeff Scott, a lawyer with the Florida Medical
Association in Tallahassee, which pushed for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Florida requires HMOs to pay undisputed claims within 35 days
and disputed claims within 120 days. The Florida Department of
Insurance has fined two HMOs and the Agency for Health Care
Administration has fined 13 for violating the state's prompt-pay
law.
</P>
<P>
   Managed-care companies agreed to the program this year as part
of a health care package passed by the Florida Legislature.
Massachusetts enacted its own program July 21, which also is going
into effect Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Insurance Commissioner Susanne Murphy said the disputes
are not necessarily the fault of the HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence to support that providers are not always
billing correctly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Florida program, the arbitrators, who have yet to be
chosen, will be paid by the disputing parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state requires the loser to pay the cost,'' said Elfie
Stamm, a senior management analyst at the health agency's Bureau of
Managed Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   The costs will be apportioned, so that if a doctor seeks $1,000,
but is awarded $500, the doctor and the HMO will split the cost.
Refusal to pay the cost within 35 days is subject to fines of up to
$500 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The next step for the Florida program is creating regulations to
govern the program. The Agency for Health Care Administration,
which is responsible for operating the mediation program, hopes to
have rules ready next week for publication Aug. 14. The public will
have 21 days to comment.
</P>
<P>
   After the rules are adopted, the state will ask the American
Arbitration As Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
