<HEADER>
A6490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-PHILA-MAYOR-PROFILE-A     07-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILA-MAYOR-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S PAST AND PRESENT MEET AS A CITY GOES ON DISPLAY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When Mayor John F. Street set out in politics 20
years ago, he was a classic insurgent firebrand, living and
breathing protest as he belabored incumbents for neglecting the
outlying neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The urban wheel has come full circle for Street, the powerful
incumbent of the nation's fifth largest city. He now must make sure
that political protesters have their say but not to the point of
disrupting the delegates of the Republican National Convention who
began flooding into town today intent on enjoying the expensive
downtown renaissance of this historic city.
</P>
<P>
   Assorted protest groups, vowing to rally by the tens of
thousands, also began arriving, closely tracked by the mayor's
police aides. The protesters are flocking to this city not so much
for the Republican gathering as for the journalists, who outnumber
the delegates three to one and who are constructing a weeklong
window for the watching nation to get some messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who believe their rights are the only
rights,'' Street declared, the Afro hairdo of his protest youth
winnowed and gray, but his instinct for contention still sharp as
he flourishes it in protection of the downtown establishment.
Watching from City Hall, he pondered the ``very small percentage''
of arriving protesters who he estimates may be intent on
confounding the city's hard-earned new image with hit-and-run
street vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't allow people to destroy Philadelphia,'' Street
declared. He had to sigh and smile in confirming a report in George
magazine that, yes, he did refer to some approaching protesters as
``idiots'' and he did vow they would get ``a very ugly response''
for any disruption.
</P>
<P>
   Street said that was merely a light-hearted summary of a serious
point: Philadelphia intends to welcome peaceful protesters and
accommodate nonviolent civil disobedience with professional
nonaggressive arrests. But the city also intends to protect its
hospitality and property from the sort of masked vandals who
marauded through downtown Seattle in December during the meeting of
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   As the arriving Republicans packed into dozens of new and
renovated hotels, Street contemplated his welcome speech for the
conventioneers. But potential troublemakers never seemed far from
his mind. ``We don't get intimidated,'' the mayor said. ``Besides,
protesters have to eat, too,'' he added, brightening at the tourist
lucre that might be mined. ``They go to restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 56, Street is facing a critical test in his
political career. If the city fails to sparkle during the
convention, he will be blamed. But if the Republicans turn out to
relish this revived and thoroughly Democratic city, he could be
well on his way to re-election despite such haunting problems as
the city's continuing population loss in the face of a failed
school system.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in having the nation focus on Philadelphia were
underlined two weeks ago with the sensational airing of television
footage of a half-dozen frustrated police officers finally
capturing a fugitive car-jacking suspect and drubbing him with
kicks and punches. Afterward, officials promised subtler tactics
for any convention disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   Street won a tough race in November by a 2-point margin. He
sought to come roaring into office as the successor to the highly
popular Edward G. Rendell, who engineered the downtown revival with
key help from Street as City Council president. Street soon
delivered on a promise to have 30,000 skeletal automobiles hauled
away. He dispatched plows to the humblest streets during a
snowstorm. After a magazine criticized the chubbier residents of
this city of cheese steak and pretzel noshing, the mayor, a predawn
exercise fanatic, rushed to defend his own on the Oprah show.
</P>
<P>
   But Street received poor reviews in his early relations with the
Statehouse as Republicans complained he was obstinate and demanding
in the annual school aid fight. He had also been considered
iron-handed in his council presidency, yet this was a quality that
helped him deliver crucial investment votes on the revival of
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the hospitality-tourism business, you've got to pay to
play,'' said Street, who preferred to dwell on the tourist riches
of Republican visitors rather than on any shortcomings he might see
in their ticket. ``For us, this is a business,'' he said, his tone
firm as a gaveling to order. ``It's time to capitalize on our
investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Born poor on a suburban farm, Street identifies closely with
this city and the possibilities of the underdog to rise up. As a
student, he was rated less than college material by one teacher.
But Street used this as a prod to persist. He ultimately earned a
law degree at Temple University to complement the firebrand
protests of his entry to politics. He now lives in North
Philadelphia, and has four children with his wife, Naomi, a lawyer
and children's advocate in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I began in politics, we didn't have tall buildings; there
was virtually no skyline,'' said Street, sounding genuinely amazed
that the city's stark old silhouette could have vanished. Instead,
a cluster of shiny new office towers and hotels defines a bold,
aspiring skyline. They dwarf the classic century-old City Hall,
where Street will be anxiously governing, watching the intertwined
fates of conventioneers, protesters and his beloved Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6493 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INTERNET-SCHEMES-$ADV     07-28 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SCHEMES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CON ARTISTS FLOURISHING WITH GROWTH OF INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By SKIP KALTENHEUSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Donald and Robyn Rogers, a retired couple living on a fixed
income in St. Johns, Ariz., the opportunity to drive their ``dream
car'' free while earning extra income had boundless appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Their ticket to wheels and riches, they were told in numerous
advertisements spotted on the Internet, would come from the
purchase of a ``consultant membership'' in the Five Star Auto Club
of Poughquag, N.Y. All they had to do was pay an initial fee of
$395 and monthly payments of $100 and recruit others to join.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple, who signed up two summers ago, said they never
received a free lease on the maroon Chevrolet Lumina they had
picked out, and all they earned for the six months spent trying to
sign up new members through postcard mailings, county fairs and
craft shows was $300, or $100 for each of their three recruits.
They said they ended up laying out $2,000 in membership fees,
travel costs and other expenses, including the cost of setting up a
promotional Web site bought through another Five Star member.
</P>
<P>
   They were not alone in their disappointment. After receiving
complaints from other club members, the Federal Trade Commission
last year sued Five Star and its principals, Michael and Angela
Sullivan of LaGrangeville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   On June 13, Judge Colleen McMahon of Federal District Court in
White Plains, N.Y., agreed with the FTC contention that Five Star's
operation amounted to a pyramid scheme that duped most of its 8,200
members. The Sullivans were ordered to cease operations and to pay
back $2.9 million to members. They were also banned for life from
all multilevel marketing businesses. Their lawyer, Michael Meth of
Benjamin Ostrer &AMP; Associates in Chester, N.Y., said he planned to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The move against Five Star is part of an effort by the trade
commission to detect and eliminate get-rich-quick schemes on the
Internet. The agency said that it had received 18,600 consumer
complaints of Internet fraud in 1999, compared with fewer than
1,000 just two years before, and that accusations of online abuse
now account for about one in four fraud complaints. The National
Consumers League in Washington estimates that the average victim of
Internet fraud lost $580 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is proving a con artist's gold rush,'' said Len
Hansen, a journalist from Durango, Colo., who used a research
fellowship to investigate various schemes. ``Con artists are quick
to embrace new communications technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   By typing in ``get rich quick'' on any search engine, consumers
can plug into a variety of Web sites guaranteeing huge profits if
they invest some money or get others to do the same: ``Make $50,000
per month!'' ``Take home a six-figure income.'' ``Earn a 50 percent
return on your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts in fraud detection say the Internet provides scam
artists, who used to operate through old-fashioned ``boiler rooms''
with rented phone lines and dozens of cold callers, with a new
cloak of anonymity while making it easier to lure larger numbers of
victims worldwide. Well-constructed Web sites give the appearance
of being above board, which was what helped convince the Rogers to
invest in Five Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that a Web site, up for all to see, was a badge of
legitimacy,'' said Rogers, 60, a retired child-care provider and
school custodian, who was a novice Internet user looking for ways
to supplement her fixed income when she came across the Five Star
site. ``Because of our remote location, it seemed key for building
our business,'' she said of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said that as more people went online, ``con artists can
hit their marks faster and cheaper than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As scam operations set up shop around the world,'' he added,
``law enforcement and victims will not find justice comes easy.''
</P>
<P>
   To attack the problem, the FTC has organized ``surf days,'' in
which dozens of law enforcement agencies collectively surf the Net
looking for questionable sites. Some 22 such events have been held
over the last four years, the largest and most recent from Feb. 28
to March 10 and called ``GetRichQuick.con.'' Bringing together 150
consumer and law enforcement organizations in 28 countries on five
continents, it yielded 1,600 suspect sites.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen says many Net schemes are aimed at older people on fixed
incomes and unsophisticated young adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite come-on is: `Wow. So easy, my children could do
it,''' he said. ``You have to wonder why something so sure-fire is
urgently shared with tens of thousands of strangers. It's an old
saw, but in or out of cyberspace, if it sounds too good to be true,
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Ortwein, a 20-year-old student at Mesa College in San
Diego, bought into the Five Star idea in June 1998. Dreaming of a
red Ferrari, he bought a $395 membership and sent out recruiting
ads on the Internet while a friend spent time designing a Web site
geared to college students. But Ortwein, who said he failed to
recruit anyone during his one-year membership and never received
his dream car, abandoned his effort after he was unable to contact
anyone at the company. He said he never got more than a telephone
recording.
</P>
<P>
   Meth, the Sullivans' lawyer, says Five Star ``simply grew too
fast and got away from Michael Sullivan.'' He said Five Star had
many satisfied customers and had offered refunds to those who were
unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Ames Kohm, a lawyer for the FTC, countered that ``customer
satisfaction and cooperation must be loosely defined since well
over 90 percent of the members lost money and 98 percent of people
eligible for a free car did not get one, which is what one would
expect from the math of any pyramid scheme this blatant.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the FTC's largest Internet cases involved the Equinox
International Corp. of Las Vegas. Three months ago, the company
agreed to a settlement that would use an estimated $40 million in
assets to pay back the thousands of recruited distributors who lost
money trying to sell health and beauty product lines and water
filtration products, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people do not complain about losing money on get-rich
Internet schemes, Kohm said, because they are too embarrassed or
blame themselves for their failure to achieve marketing goals.
``They don't understand that they were always up against impossible
odds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, 70, a retired employee of the Apache County treasurer's
office in Arizona, said the worst part of the ordeal was knowing
that his credibility was hurt, and that the three people he and his
wife had recruited, including their son, lost money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though we tried very hard,'' Rogers added, ``we're glad we
weren't more successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
