<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, JULY 29 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday, July 29. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-IRELAND-LANGUAGE-NYT (Moved on Monday, July 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on Monday,
July 24, about efforts to revive the use of Gaelic in Ireland
mistranslated the word ``macushla,'' a term of endearment cited by
a professor to illustrate the beauty of the language. It means ``my
pulse'' and can mean ``my heartthrob''; it does not mean ``my
colt.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT (Moved on Saturday, June 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on Because
of an editing error, the Political Briefing column on June 25
omitted attribution for a news account of a comment by the campaign
manager of Gov. Frank O'Bannon of Indiana in an exchange about
politics and rising gasoline prices. It was The Indianapolis Star
to whom the campaign manager, Tom New, said ``Phooey'' when told
that some Republicans saw politics behind the governor's suspension
of the gasoline tax. Attribution was deleted when the column was
edited to fit assigned space; The Star pointed out the omission by
e-mail yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MICROSOFT-RESEARCH-NYT (Moved on Sunday, July 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on Sunday,
July 16, about Microsoft's plans for new software technologies to
manage information overload misstated the company's relationship to
an artificial intelligence company, Knowledge Industries. While
Microsoft bought parts of it in 1993, the company remains
independent; it was not wholly acquired.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LIBERACE-BOOK-REVIEW (Moved on Wednesday, July 26) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on
Wednesday, July 26 about ``Liberace: An American Boy,'' by Darden
Asbury Pyron, included an imprecise attribution from the book for a
comment supposedly made by the pianist in the face of an adverse
review. It was a 1954 TV Guide article about Liberace that quoted
him as saying he had ``laughed all the way to the bank.''
(Bartlett's Familiar Quotations, cited elsewhere in the biography,
is the source for a different version of the remark _ from
Liberace's 1973 autobiography: ``I cried all the way to the
bank.'')  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
