<HEADER>
A6500 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-PROFILE-PECK-$ADV30-N     07-28 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-PECK-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOT-COM SENDS IN THE MARINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For Release Sunday, July 30) 
 By RANDALL LANE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles M. Peck, introduced earlier this month as the
new chief executive of Theglobe.com, looks as if he stepped out of
the pages of ``The Organization Man,'' with his graying,
short-cropped hair, herringbone sports coat and Marine Corps
demeanor. His resume could induce somnolence in all but the most
open-minded Silicon Alley denizen: salesman for Xerox, executive at
Levi Strauss, PepsiCo and Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton, in-house
strategist for the New York Stock Exchange, Viacom, Standard &AMP;
Poor's, and most recently, the American Institute of Certified
Public Accountants.
</P>
<P>
   So what is this one-man Conference Board doing at what was once
the highest of highflying Internet companies, one with a stock
chart whose plummet now resembles a lunar re-entry? ``People are
tickled,'' Peck, 54, said in an interview at Theglobe.com offices
on lower Broadway in Manhattan. ``I've already received hundreds
and hundreds of e-mails. But I don't think it should surprise
anybody _ it's a good fit.''
</P>
<P>
   What many do not appreciate about his blue-chip background, Peck
contended, is his willingness to tackle a challenge. He grew up the
son of a Coast Guard officer, moving among Japan, Hawaii, Ohio and
New York, and broke up his college studies at the State University
of New York at Albany with a two-year stint in the Marines. His
career has a similar mission-to-mission rhythm, working with the
troubled divisions of otherwise profitable giants. ``While I was
operating under a corporate umbrella,'' he said, ``there was the
same entrepreneurial pressure _ profit or perish.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has that choice been more acute than at his newest
company, a network of sites that link users by common interests.
Run since its inception by its founders, Todd Krizelman and Stephan
Paternot, both now 26, Theglobe.com became Wall Street legend for
its 1998 initial public offering. The stock soared 900 percent on
the first day. The fall has been sharp, too _ from $40 in April
1999 to around $2 now. ``It's funny how an IPO can brand a company
for life,'' said Jordan Rohan, an analyst for Wit SoundView, an
online investment banking firm. ``They draw a disproportionate
amount of attention. They are a true lightning rod.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the company called in the marine. From its roots in a
Cornell University dormitory room, Theglobe.com, aimed primarily at
twenty-something professionals, had styled itself as the epitome of
young, cool dot-com corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, in the official announcement of Peck's arrival,
company management used many terms that it defied just two years
ago, squeezing ``seasoned Fortune 500 executive,'' ``30 years of
experience'' and ``proven track record'' into the first sentence
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Krizelman and Paternot said in January that they would step
back, remaining full-time as vice chairmen. A few weeks later, Peck
was contacted by the executive search firm Heidrick &AMP; Struggles.
``It came out of left field, but then I found it intriguing,'' he
recalled. He was impressed that even an old-economy war horse like
himself was familiar with the brand, and that his son, roughly the
same age as the two founders, knew the product and history.
</P>
<P>
   Paternot, meanwhile, remembers being disarmed by Peck's sense of
humor and entrepreneurial streak, especially considering his age
and stodgy corporate background. ``Him making this move tells you
what his character is like,'' Paternot said.
</P>
<P>
   A four-month courtship ensued, one that mirrors Peck's
no-nonsense style: no snowboarding trips or drinking marathons,
lots of sit-down meetings and negotiations. He wound up taking a
pay cut from his current job, offsetting that with stock options.
``Both sides were buying and selling,'' he said. ``All of us needed
to do our due diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Peck found a company that has burned through $86.5 million,
including an $8.9 million loss in its last reported quarter (not
counting a one-time acquisition cost), on sales of $7 million. The
company says it has about $30 million left.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts and investors have questioned its business model,
notably its reliance on ad sales, which account for two-thirds of
revenue. Peck has indicated, however, that he plans to expand and
diversify the company, not reinvent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hypothesis is that the expense side has been very well
managed,'' he said. ``And because the model is highly scalable, we
need to grow the revenue side of the business.'' He has said that
he is not abandoning the company's advertising-based strategy _
and, in fact, sees great opportunity for it internationally _ but
he intends to supplement it by selling Theglobe.com's
community-building software and expertise as a tool for corporate
trainers and associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Associations are communities _ they'll wind up in jeopardy if
they don't come up with ways for members to communicate over the
Internet,'' he said. In other words, said Peck, who previously
served as senior vice president of the country's largest trade
group for accountants, if the American Medical Association doesn't
get wired, it could be undermined by the likes of WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   But Rohan, one of the few analysts still following Theglobe.com,
says it should rethink its whole plan. ``There are other businesses
going after that strategy _ it's a fiercely competitive space and
the barriers to entry are unclear,'' he said. ``I think
revolutionary change is in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Peck, who does not start officially until Tuesday, allows that
he will need two months to get his arms around the company's
problems. But he does not foresee any culture clash, waxing poetic
about his stint at the short-lived New York Air 20 years ago, when
he left his plush office at Booz Allen to move into a hangar at La
Guardia Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Theglobe.com's offices _ an extension of its founders with its
casual dress and Ping-Pong tables in the lounge _ represent just
another mission. ``I haven't played Ping-Pong with them yet,'' he
said. ``But I'm sure I will.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
