<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TIME HAS RUN OUT FOR MORA
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Melvin Mora leaned against a gray wall in Shea
Stadium Friday afternoon, holding up the wall, bracing himself.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Mora learned that he had been traded to the
Baltimore Orioles along with Mike Kinkade, Lesli Brea and Pat
Gorman for Mike Bordick.
</P>
<P>
   The normally unflappable Mora had a pained look on his face.
This one hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't ready for this,'' he said. ``I didn't know they were
going to trade me.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Mora had to sense something was up. Ever since Rey
Ordonez fractured his forearm in May there were calls for everyone
from Joe Tinker to Barry Larkin. Mora was tossed into the fire at
shortstop and turned in mixed results: a stronger bat than Ordonez,
a weaker glove. He was learning on the job but he wasn't learning
fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those classic cases of a team not being able to
wait.
</P>
<P>
   Mora said, ``You play more and more and more, you're going to
get better, better, better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets didn't, and do not have the luxury of time.
</P>
<P>
   Mora's problem is that for all last year's heroics and
versatility, the Mets never saw him as an everyday player. They saw
him as an every-way player. He played second base, third,
shortstop, center field, left and right.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, Friday introduced the
trade by saying, ``Utility infielder, Melvin Mora.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Melvin Mora,'' Phillips said. ``He's a very good player
and a very versatile player and a good contributor on a good team.
Melvin did the best he could.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new guy is a solid, everyday shortstop, an All-Star
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes all of the routine plays and oftentimes the
spectacular player,'' Phillips said. ``He gives us the stability
that was lacking. Bordick brings stability to the left side of the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   Mora said he and manager Bobby Valentine had a long
heart-to-heart conversation. ``He told me that I helped him go 12
games over .500,'' Mora said. ``He said, `The only thing I can say
is thank you, because it was a hard situation when we lost Rey
Ordonez, but you were there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mora talked a lot about his relationship with Valentine. He
praised the manager for giving him an opportunity, for talking to
him about the facts of life in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who told me baseball is hard,'' Mora said. ``He
was the one who was always right behind me every time. When he said
something was going to happen, it happened. He never lied to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine didn't tell Mora that he was going to be traded,
though when critics were sniping, Valentine reminded Mora that this
was New York and this was a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a guy like Melvin,'' Valentine said, ``the most difficult
thing he had was this idea that he had never been in the big
leagues before, he had never been a full-time shortstop before and
people wanted to hold him to a standard that was unlike the
standard they held Rey to his first year as a shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora wondered why he couldn't have the same room to learn from
his mistakes, the same latitude. Valentine had to explain to Mora
that that was then, this is now. The higher expectations, which
Mora helped to raise during last season's playoffs, narrowed
everyone's margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conversations we had were just the idea of understanding
that life and our life in baseball is not always fair, and don't
expect it to be fair,'' Valentine said. ``That was hard for him to
understand. He's not the pennant race. He's Melvin Mora. All he is
is this player out there learning this position, playing
shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets this was a day of tradeoffs: heart-and-soul player
for rock steadiness. Melvin Mora has been around the baseball world
and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one more thing,'' Mora said. ``One more
challenge. Here, I go to another place and make myself ready to
show a lot of people that I'm an everyday player.''
</P>
<P>
   You heard a lot about stability Friday night at Shea Stadium.
Not excitement. Not inspiration. Stability at short.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets made the right move on paper _ a no-brainer, as they
say _ but much of what a Melvin Mora brings to the game cannot be
measured in a box score.
</P>
<P>
   But come the playoffs in October, when the outcome of series are
often determined by intangibles, we'll see how good the trade looks
then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
