<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6505 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-GOPMISSION-HNS &LR;      07-28 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WANTS VOTERS TO KNOW WHO HE IS 
 

</HEADLINE>
 MISSION-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGDALE, Ark. _ George W. Bush launched his final journey
toward becoming the Republican presidential nominee Friday by
establishing the convention goal: introduce himself to millions of
voters who are just now tuning into the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just let people know who I am,'' Bush said when asked for the
mission of his convention. ``I hope they know I'm a decisive, firm
leader who has good judgment and is ready to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign aides realize that while many Americans may know
who Bush is, they still do not know what he stands for; for many he
remains a distant figure. The campaign hopes the 3,900-word speech
he delivers next Thursday in accepting the GOP presidential
nomination will change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all been reminding ourselves that while Gov. Bush has
been out on the campaign trail for the last year, year and a half,
making hundreds maybe even thousands of speeches ... but this one
speech next Thursday will be the time many Americans tune in and
hear him speak for the first time,'' said Bush spokesman Karen
Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we are very mindful that the convention is a very important
moment and that the speech is an important moment.``
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush has been practicing his speech before
teleprompters and has video-taped it so the staff can look for ways
to improve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a leadership speech,'' Hughes said. ``He will talk about
the fact that we have a unique moment in our nation's history to
address some problems before they become crises for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   She said there will be a focus on what Bush proposals on
education and tax cuts mean for Americans. She said there also will
be some ``comparing and contrasting'' to the administration of
President Bill Clinton and Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
Democratic presidential nominee. Hughes said one of those issues
will be a lack of action on modernizing Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   While the convention is designed to let Americans get to know
Bush better, it also will be a venue to re-introduce Bush's choice
of running mates, former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Since his selection on Tuesday, Cheney has been under a barrage
of criticism from Democrats for votes he cast while representing
Wyoming for a decade in Congress, votes that have been portrayed as
anti-women, anti-gay and anti-environment.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about Cheney have so pervaded the campaign that U.S.
Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., began at Springdale High School by
asking, ``Did Governor Bush make the right decision in picking
Secretary Cheney as his running mate?``
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 2,000 Republican loyalist shouted back, ``Yes!``
</P>
<P>
   Hughes dismissed the Democratic criticism, while also chiding
the news media. She said presumptive Democratic nominee Vice
President Al Gore will have a difficult time finding a running mate
with Cheney's experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really put them in a box. I know that's not the way some
of your reporting has gone, but when you think about it, I want you
to picture, I want you to picture a Democrat nominee measuring up
to the experience and stature of this man,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Thursday he would be ``mulling over'' his choice for a
running mate while on vacation this coming week. Gore will spend
his time at Figure Eight Island, N.C. with wife Tipper, and other
family members in the home of friends Parker and Becky Overton of
Greenville, N.C. He won't be hosting any potential running mates on
the island, he said, and won't meet here with Warren Christopher,
who his heading up his search committee.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Methodist University political science professor Cal
Jillson said next week's GOP convention will give Bush an
opportunity to deliver his campaign message to the American public
``unobstructed.'' But Jillson said it also will be important for
Bush to reverse the negative publicity Democrats have generated
about Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs an opportunity for Dick Cheney to reintroduce himself
to the American public,'' Jillson said. ``The Democratic opposition
research was far superior to the Bush campaign's preparation to
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have shown Bush to be widening his lead over Bush
among likely voters. A CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll, released
Thursday, found the Republican ticket with an 11-point lead, 50
percent to 39 percent, among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended his selection of Cheney in speeches in Springdale
and later in Joplin, Mo. He told the Springdale audience that he
wanted a vice president who was ready to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said a tough campaign lies ahead: ``We're going to fight
every single day in every single state for every single vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-Cheney pre-convention tour from Texas to Philadelphia
is scheduled to go through six battleground states: Arkansas,
Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio, West Virginia and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
