<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CAMPBELL-SOUP-ART-$AD     07-28 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-SOUP-ART-$ADV30-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST FAMILY OF SOUP, FEELING THE SQUEEZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. _ It cannot be easy for the Dorrance family to read
the newspapers these days. In headline after headline, one food
company after another has committed to a sale or a merger, leaving
the descendants of John T. Dorrance, the chemist who invented
condensed soup more than a century ago, with an agonizing decision:
Should they sell Campbell Soup Co., which has been in the family's
hands for three generations but is now struggling? Or should they
hire new management to revive flagging sales of its chicken noodle
and tomato soups and Pepperidge Farm cookies and perhaps become an
acquirer itself?
</P>
<P>
   Despite its status as family-controlled company, Campbell has
been managed over the last decade to emphasize the quarterly
results favored by Wall Street analysts and large outside
investors. Under its energetic chief executive, David W. Johnson,
Campbell boasted ever-fatter profit margins and a stock price that
climbed nearly sixfold in roughly eight years, to more than $60 a
share in 1998, just after he left.
</P>
<P>
   But those gains did not last long after Johnson handed over
management of the company to Dale F. Morrison in 1997. In recent
years, consumers have increasingly turned away from Campbell's
familiar red-and-white cans to soups that seem fresher and easier
to open and prepare. As overall sales of canned soup have
flattened, Campbell has lost business to cheaper private-label
brands and, more recently, its nemesis, Progresso. And competitors
like Nabisco have nibbled away at its Pepperidge Farm cookie and
cracker business.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, with many rivals joining forces and gaining clout with
supermarket chains, the threat to Campbell has grown. ``The
fundamentals of the business seem to be putrid,'' said Art Cecil,
an analyst for T. Rowe Price, the mutual fund company, which owns
shares in Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil is not alone. Campbell's stock now trades at $26.4375,
down 56 percent from that 1998 peak. For the fiscal year ended last
August, the company earned $724 million on sales of $6.4 billion,
but more recently, the results have deteriorated. Earnings fell 14
percent in the quarter ended in April, compared with the period a
year earlier. Despite all the merger talk, only one Wall Street
analyst is now recommending the stock.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the Dorrance family's own holdings has dropped by
more than $7 billion, to $6 billion. And when Morrison resigned in
March, the Dorrances turned again to Johnson, 67, who had retired
as chairman the previous July and had spent his new-found leisure
time climbing Mount Kilimanjaro and traveling to the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the dismal stock performance and the frenzy
of industry consolidation appears to be forcing the family, which
owns just over half the company's stock, to reconsider Campbell's
independence. No question, a turnaround would be lengthy _ and
costly. Perhaps giving a clue to the future, the Dorrances
surprised Wall Street in June, when they appeared willing to sell
Campbell for about $35 a share to Bestfoods, which was fending off
the overtures of Unilever. It was only after Unilever prevailed
that Bestfoods' plans to buy Campbell were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``When have the Dorrances had enough?'' asked Ken Harris of
Cannondale Associates, a consulting firm, who said he believes the
company must find a partner. ``The clock is definitely ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   The family _ Dorrance's nine grandchildren _ is hardly an
activist group. The last Dorrance to run the company was Dorrance's
son, John T. Jr., who was chairman for more than two decades until
1984. In part, the company has been a victim of changing tastes,
but critics say that Campbell _ as the Dorrances watched _
benefited from years in which the company improved its earnings by
cutting costs and stinting on development and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the cylinders is working right now,'' said David
Kolpak, an analyst with Key Asset Management, who faults Campbell
and Johnson in particular, contending that they raised prices too
aggressively and failed to invest wisely in brands. ``A lot of that
they have themselves to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the family members returned phone calls seeking comment.
But former executives and others who know the family said they had
persuaded Johnson to return as chief executive to help them decide
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also hired an executive search firm,
SpencerStuart, to find a permanent replacement for Morrison.
(Nabisco's chief executive, James Kilts, is one name favored by
analysts.) A choice is likely to be made by year-end _ unless
Campbell is sold.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered across the country, the grandchildren appear to prefer
pastimes like riding horses to managing the family business. As
they have gone separate ways, they have not remained particularly
close and do not necessarily have the same opinions. The Dorrances
``are very much going to look to David to try to get out of this,''
said Terry Bivens, an analyst with Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   As one former Campbell executive put it, ``David is like a
honorary family member.''
</P>
<P>
   Widely heralded as one of the industry's best managers, Johnson
may find that his own reputation is also very much at stake. In a
recent interview at Campbell's headquarters here _ a building that
is 40-odd years old and in a depressed neighborhood _ Johnson was
quick to point to portraits of Dorrance in the chairman's and
founders' rooms, as well as a lone Andy Warhol painting _ his
Campbell's tomato soup can, of course. Appearing comfortable in his
role as strategist, Johnson expressed enthusiasm at being called
back to duty.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, Johnson showed impatience with the notion that the
company must eventually be sold, arguing that ``only dead fish swim
with the current.'' He acknowledged that there was tremendous
pressure from Wall Street to consider a combination _ likening the
environment to ``a sailor going off the warship in port: they're
looking for a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Campbell would not be panicked into action. ``We're
trying very, very hard to fight back,'' he said, emphasizing that
the company had not given up. ``I don't think for a second we're
rolling over.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell could remain independent, he said, and would weigh its
options carefully over coming months. Citing Wrigley, the Chicago
chewing-gum maker, as a successful family company, he said, ``I
think we are still in control of our destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
