<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-CHENEY0730-1STLED     07-28 1994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CHENEY0730-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Cheney's Wyoming roots run deepBy Kevin Robbins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASPER, Wyo. _ The peak touches the sky more than a half-mile
above the Natrona County seat. The range is millions of years old,
squeezed like an accordion when the dinosaurs died, and now it
looms hard over the city and the river and the basins that seep
petroleum oil.
</P>
<P>
   Casper Mountain spreads as far as a man can see. Right in the
middle of it is Casper, where in 1954 a family from Nebraska bought
a single-story house on Texas Place. Richard and Marjorie Cheney
hauled their children to wind-blown Wyoming and the east side of
town. Their picture window faced the street. Through the windows in
back rose the steep north face of Casper Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney was a boy then.
</P>
<P>
   Fame came later, after the Friday night football heroics and the
poker games with the other lettermen, after Boys State and student
council, after an awakening at Yale and a return home, after a
stint as a union utility groundman. Was there another way? The
nature of national politics meant that Cheney had leave Casper to
become what he is today, which is a nominee on the Republican
ticket for vice president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So the fame arrived when Cheney became a White House chief of
staff at 34, and when he became known as a unfailingly conservative
in Congress, a measured man who spoke of less government and frugal
spending and a freer market. He found fame in his convictions,
which, regardless of what people thought of them, people respected.
Fame came to Cheney when ran a faraway war. He is noted for his
calculating mind and his command in knowing what makes the world go
round and who makes it so. There is a deceiving pattern to it all:
the fame came when he left Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   But, say those who know him, the rise of Richard Bruce Cheney
has much to do with where he is from.
</P>
<P>
   His family came to Casper from Lincoln, Neb., when Cheney was in
his early teens. His father was an official with the U.S. soil
conservation office. His mother raised the three Cheney children
and volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   Casper was a different place then. The Salt Creek oil field
north of town kissed the town with prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Their neighborhood was new.
</P>
<P>
   The Cheneys purchased an 800-square-foot ranch house that looked
like all the rest, had the same young box elders and Chinese elms
in the yards. Their neighbors were lawyers, geologists, former
soldiers with GI Bills. Their streets were curved. Their cross
street, Trigood Drive, looked like it would run right into the face
of Casper Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were full of ourselves,'' said Robert Penney. ``We thought
we could do just about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Penney bought a house two lots away from the Cheney home, when
the oil boom brought him from Oklahoma. Years later, he became an
activist in the Democratic Party, but just as the Cheneys kept
their politics quiet, so did he. ``In those days, people didn't
talk about their political affiliations very much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The boys in the neighborhood played baseball on summer days
while their fathers worked and their mothers made homes.
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Cheney knitted sweaters for the newborns at the only
hospital in Casper. She loved to fish from the banks of Alcova
Lake, and so did her husband, but not as much. The couple played
golf together at the municipal course. They never joined the
country club.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't that kind of people,'' said Vivian Kammerer.
``They never were.''
</P>
<P>
   Kammerer and her husband Reuben met the Cheneys almost three
decades ago, when they, too, moved to Casper from Nebraska. The two
families were members at the First United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   They spent their evenings playing bridge, cooking supper for
their families, discussing the topics adults discussed in the 1950s
in Wyoming: The weather. The neighborhood. The kids. Cheney's
father was the quieter one, a man who, like his sons, weighed his
words before he spoke them. Cheney's mother was more effusive, like
his sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mother was very proud of him,'' Kammerer said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the church was where the funeral for Marjorie Cheney
was conducted below the stunning, century-old stained-glass
Resurrection Window. Her husband's funeral was there six years
later. Both deaths were front-page news.
</P>
<P>
   But their values still live. They shaped their two sons and
daughter, family friends say.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's parents came from a time when sincerity meant more than
status, wisdom more than wealth. The Cheneys raised their children
with precepts as sturdy as the deep granite at the core of Casper
Mountain. People say a lot about trust, integrity and inner
strength when they talk about Cheney. They say those same words
about Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney and his friends learned to fish on the North Platte
River, whose cold water rushes down from the Rockies and carries
magnificent rainbow trout. They taught themselves to ski during the
winters. When it got too cold outside, they retreated to someone's
home and played poker or watched boxing on television. They obeyed
the law. They studied. They excelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just typical of the 1950s in Casper,'' said Joe Meyer,
a childhood friend and now Wyoming's Secretary of State.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney sailed through Natrona County High School, home of the
Mustangs and the Fillies, a building where he and Gov. George W.
Bush last week launched their campaign. Cheney and a tight group of
friends were part of the football team that marched to the 1957
state championship. Cheney played halfback and linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a really good class: good people, smart people, people
destined to go on to bigger and better things,'' said David
Nicholas, a classmate who later was Cheney's best man at his
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   His teachers elected Cheney to Boys State. He was president of
his senior class. An alumnus of Yale University noticed and
encouraged Cheney and a second promising student to go to college
in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were obvious choices,'' said the alumnus, Thomas Stroock.
``They were both students. They were both athletes. They were both
leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   They both went. And after a year and a half at Yale, they both
left.
</P>
<P>
   Stroock, who later served as ambassador to Guatemala during the
Bush administration, was disappointed. Still, he supported Cheney's
decision. ``Don't get your education in some place where you're not
having a good time,'' Stroock said he told him.
</P>
<P>
   So Cheney returned to Wyoming, to his home at the foot of the
mountain. He enrolled at a community college between downtown and
the peak. A union official helped Cheney get work as a groundman
for utility contractors.
</P>
<P>
   That official, a passionate Democrat named Carl Brown, had a
special interest in Cheney. Brown's niece, Lynne Anne Vincent, had
been dating Cheney since high school, where Vincent was an
A-student and Homecoming Queen her senior year.
</P>
<P>
   They were married in the summer of 1964. They recited their vows
at a Presbyterian church the Vincents attended. At that moment, the
young man from Casper with a foundation as strong as rock found
himself suddenly strengthened, enhanced and better prepared to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Schoolmates remember Vincent as one of the brighter students in
her class. She was bound to do well, they say, and by extension so
were those around her. Her parents _ her father was an engineer,
her mother a deputy sheriff _ ``expected a lot from Lynne,'' said
Norma Brown, whose sister Edna was Lynne's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came through.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney finished at Casper College, where he now is among an
author, a veterinarian, a rodeo cowboy and a naval aviator and
others as the school's 15 distinguished alumni. He earned his
bachelor's and master's degrees at the University of Wyoming. In
1966, he enrolled at the University of Wisconsin, and with Casper
Mountain disappearing behind him as he and his wife moved east, he
left Wyoming again.
</P>
<P>
   They would not return for more than a decade. Their Casper would
change for good.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble visited the oil fields. By the late 1970s, the derricks
had begun to deplete the Salt Creek anticline, which in the 1920s
was the healthiest supply of oil in the United States, eventually
surrendering 600 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   When Cheney returned to Wyoming, after an appointment as chief
of staff to President Gerald Ford and other federal government
positions, he won the 1977 Republican primary to run for an open
Congressional seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did have a few things going for him,'' said Democrat
William Bagley, Cheney's opponent in the 1978 general election.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's credentials for federal office were sound. He knew
Washington. He had worked in the Office of Economic Opportunity,
the Cost of Living Council and the Nixon and Ford administrations.
And he was a Republican in a Republican state.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney outspent Bagley two-to-one on the campaign. The race was
clean, Bagley said, and there were none of the scathing tactics
that tarnish contemporary elections. The candidates even
cooperated.
</P>
<P>
   Bagley remembered calling Cheney to suggest they eliminate
outdoor campaign advertising. Though Cheney had more billboards,
and more money to spend on them, ``he went along with it,'' Bagley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney trounced Bagley on the Nov. 7, 1978. In Natrona County,
Cheney got 78 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   That began Cheney's six consecutive terms as a representative
from Wyoming. He retired from Congress in 1989, the same year
President Bush appointed him as Secretary of Defense. A year later,
he helped to conduct the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``That institutional memory is an important thing'' to Cheney's
prospects as vice president, said his longtime friend, Laramie
attorney David Nicholas. ``I can't emphasize enough the value of
having that kind of acumen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney left his cabinet post in 1993. He and his family returned
to Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   They purchased a slate-floored home on a golf hole in Jackson.
The National Western Stock Show and Rodeo named him ``Citizen of
the West.'' He joined the boards of Proctor &AMP; Gamble and US West.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, during the hunt for a Republican candidate to
challenge President Clinton, his name surfaced. But Cheney publicly
dismissed himself from speculation. Late that summer, he joined
Halliburton Co., an international oil company in Dallas. He moved
to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He never sold the house in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   He had left Casper and the mountain that accompanied him through
youth, left that with the six terms he spent representing his
district. His parents lived in the house of his boyhood until his
mother died and his father, who suffered congestive heart failure,
was moved to assisted living. They never left Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney still escapes to the house in Teton County. He fishes the
rivers of Wyoming and skis its slopes. He serves on an advisory
board at the University of Wyoming. He returns for speaking
engagements and visits with relatives on his wife's side. He came
back to Casper when the federal building there was named for him.
He was there last week, stumping in the gymnasium of his old high
school below the 8,300-foot-peak of Casper Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Dick has maintained his Wyoming ties,'' said his friend Ann
Tollefson, who met Cheney in college.
</P>
<P>
   With 481,000 residents and three electoral votes, those ties
mean little to election of 2000. But no one here seems concerned
with numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exciting time for all of us in Wyoming,'' said
Republican Gov. Jim Geringer. ``We recognize how special Dick is to
us and we're willing to share that with the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the rest of the country can judge for itself how Wyoming
raises a man.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
