<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6510 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CAMPBELL-SOUP-ART-$AD     07-28 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-SOUP-ART-$ADV30-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CAMDEN: our destiny.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But former executives, analysts and others paint a picture of a
family that may find it difficult to pull together to do what is
needed to turn around the company. Some recall that in 1989, after
Dorrance's death, his children, nephews and nieces, disappointed by
the company's performance, were bitterly divided over whether to
sell out.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute eventually led to a reorganization that put five
family members _ three Dorrance children, John III, Bennett and
Mary Alice Malone, and two of their cousins, George S. Strawbridge
Jr. and Charlotte Weber _ on the board. Two other cousins, Hope van
Beuren and Dorrance Hamilton, formed a voting trust and added
Charles H. Mott, who is not a relative, to the board to represent
their interests. John III, who has since sold his shares in the
company, is no longer a director.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at Campbell in 1990, Johnson, a colorful Australian who
had achieved tremendous success at Gerber Products, managed to
settle the question of a sale by driving up the stock price.
Investors, including the Dorrances, were thrilled at his
revitalization of the company _ he slashed costs and brought
discipline to its operations, laying off thousands of employees and
jettisoning mediocre businesses. The family basked in dividends
that now approach some $200 million a year, allowing them to remain
aloof from the business.
</P>
<P>
   The grandchildren, and their children, are informed about the
company, Johnson said; they attend presentations about its strategy
and ask questions. ``In this instance,'' as opposed to 1989, he
added, ``the family has stayed involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members, who have seen the company go through difficult
times before, are willing to take a long view, he said. The
company's board ``is more committed to the long run than anybody
could imagine because of its special history,'' he said, a
reference to the family's commitment to Dr. Dorrance's legacy and
their experience a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   But family members also leave major decisions to others. ``They
are not that engaged,'' said one former executive, who described
them as ``never really interested in the details.'' With Johnson as
chief, they had come to expect only good news, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from flirting with Bestfoods, Campbell has remained
stubbornly single as General Mills picked Pillsbury and Philip
Morris won Nabisco in the new round of food mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco had often been mentioned as a possible partner for
Campbell, and Johnson agreed that the two companies shared strong
cash flows, which would let a combined company take on large
amounts of debt and generate strong earnings. But he dismissed the
notion that such a deal would have been smart. If Campbell had
merged with Nabisco, he said, Campbell's soup business would have
stopped playing a vital role.
</P>
<P>
   Though there may be no shotgun marriage _ at least not yet _
Campbell would be willing to consider some kind of merger,
according to Johnson. He said the company would stay independent
not as a goal in itself but only if it was the best way to increase
shareholder value. Perhaps as big a consideration, analysts and
consultants suggested, is that the family is likely to want stock,
not cash, for any sale, for tax reasons, but would be interested in
owning a smaller portion of another entity. ``I would imagine,''
Johnson said, ``that the family would see having a significant role
as being of continued importance.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little consensus about which company may be the right
partner. Heinz is often mentioned, given its similar businesses and
strong management. But the two companies have been bitter rivals,
and buying Campbell may not be the challenge Heinz wants. Unilever
might consider a run after it has digested Bestfoods, and Nestle is
also a possibility. Procter &AMP; Gamble may even make a bid.
</P>
<P>
   If Campbell decides it go it alone, it is far from clear that it
will be successful. The company still needs a chief executive,
since Johnson is unlikely to tarry too long. While Campbell still
controls 74 percent of the nation's soup volume, its unit sales
continue to drop, falling 4 percent in the last year. The news
hasn't been good in cookies or crackers, either: unit sales
declined 5 percent for Pepperidge Farm cookies, and crackers were
off slightly, according to Information Resources Inc. Campbell's
other major brands include Godiva, Prego and V8.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big danger is you do all of this, and it may not work,''
said Bivens, the Bear Stearns analyst.
</P>
<P>
   And, clearly, consumer tastes have changed. ``They basically
have the Maxwell House of soup,'' said John McMillan, an analyst at
Prudential Securities, referring to the once-dominant brand of
coffee that fell victim to changing preferences and chains like
Starbucks that spare consumers the bother of brewing their own.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its well-known brands and dominant market position,
Campbell has not kept up with the times, consultants say. It was
slow to offer ready-to-eat soup and only recently gave consumers
easy-to-open cans.
</P>
<P>
   The company is ``missing innovation,'' said Gary Stibel, founder
of the New England Consulting Group.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy that served Johnson so well before _ cutting costs
and selling low-margin businesses _ is unlikely to do the trick
this time. Although Campbell recently announced more layoffs, there
is nearly universal agreement that the company must increase
volume. ``We squeezed every nickel in the cost structure,'' said
one former executive, who described the task ahead as ``a big, big
marketing turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6511 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CAMPBELL-SOUP-ART-$AD     07-28 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-SOUP-ART-$ADV30-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CAMDEN: marketing turnaround.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnson says his earlier success at Campbell was based on ``more
than just squeezing and hacking.'' But analysts and consultants say
the company appears to have invested too little in the development
and marketing of its brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really haven't come up with anything that has sparked the
soup business,'' said Kolpak of Key Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson conceded that Campbell has not backed the right
initiatives. ``I think we have tried too hard for growth,'' he
said. In introducing products, the company took a scattered
approach that cannibalized some of its core business. Its
introduction of microwaveable soup, for example, hurt its basic
soups. Campbell is now focusing its efforts, introducing, for
example, a new tomato noodle soup in the United States that took
off in Australia and rolling out easy-to-open, ready-to-serve cans
of the popular red-and-white varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also said marketing campaigns had largely been
unsuccessful. ``Our talk to the consumer became more fragmented,
wasn't as strong, wasn't as clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chastened, Campbell is charting some initiatives _ called the
fight-back plan _ for this fall. It will devote more effort to big
sellers like chicken noodle soup, trying to appeal to consumers by
adding more meat and reminding them of soup's value.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you will see this fall is advertising that is very proud,
very confident and that celebrates our core equities,'' said F.
Martin Thrasher, the president of Campbell North America.
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson did not rule out buying another business, like
Keebler, a large acquisition may not happen anytime soon. In the
opinion of one former executive, Campbell will wait until it finds
a new chief, because Johnson ``is not the guy who will ride it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also said many potential purchases would cost too much
in the current environment, although Campbell could probably take
on the necessary debt.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has a long way to go to prove itself again, Johnson
acknowledged. ``To return to grace and to run to Wall Street's loud
cheering,'' he said, ``will take a back-to-back couple of years of
initiatives and innovation and re-proving our vitality and
strategies.'' And it will be at least early next year, he said,
before the company can demonstrate the success of some of its
latest efforts.
</P>
<P>
   At Gerber, which also struggled after Johnson left, the story
ended happily once the company was bought in 1994 by what later
became Novartis. Descendants of the company's founder, Frank
Gerber, profited by tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   At Campbell, Johnson said, the ending will depend on the people
running the company. ``Talent is and leadership is, and what you
build in the company is how you are going to ensure the future,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is now up to Johnson to decide whether Campbell should sell,
and even some of his sharpest critics refuse to count him out in
finding a way to regain shareholder value. ``While Johnson left his
predecessor with a bad hand,'' said McMillan, the analyst, ``every
place he's gone, he's won.'' The Dorrances are certainly betting on
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
