<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6514 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-DIAMONDS-ART-$ADV30-N     07-28 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAMONDS-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIAMOND STOCKPILE THAT IS NOT FOREVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
(For release Sunday, July 30) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The announcement this month that De Beers Consolidated Mines
would retreat from its 70-year-old practice of controlling prices
by hoarding the world's diamonds and become more selective in where
it buys its gems sent reverberations through diamond markets from
Antwerp to Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers disclosed that, among other things, it planned to
reduce its $3.9 billion stockpile of uncut diamonds to about $2.5
billion by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategic change in the way the world's largest trader
of uncut diamonds does business does not mean consumers will see a
sudden abundance of engagement rings at cubic zirconia prices,
industry analysts say. De Beers wants to quell concerns about the
provenance of its diamonds, they say, but also wants to build
demand for them by advertising the stones as branded luxuries in a
new and aggressive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   From its trading headquarters in London, De Beers also promised
to cut ties with any of its 125 major trading partners that
trafficked in stones originating in war zones. The partners would
be required to guarantee that they do not.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers, the South African mining company that controls about
two-thirds of the trade in uncut diamonds, has come under
increasing pressure lately, after disclosures that, to help prop up
prices and control supplies, it bought millions of dollars of
diamonds from rebels in Angola to add to the company's bulky
stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   So-called conflict diamonds from warn-torn parts of Africa are
being sold by rebels and some armies to buy weapons; human rights
groups and several world governing bodies have protested. In July,
the United Nations Security Council imposed a global ban on diamond
exports from Sierra Leone, where the stones have helped finance a
brutal war.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Haas, president of ENH International Inc., a diamond trading
company in New York, said last week that he expected to see a
steady decline in the sale of conflict diamonds, which account for
an estimated 4 percent of the market. ``As the new protocols get
into effect, that number will continue to drop,'' he said, adding,
``I don't know that it will drop to zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were less optimistic. One diamond wholesaler in New York
said he was skeptical of De Beers' ability to police traders. ``In
our industry, any way they can make a buck, they will,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the months ahead, consumers are likely to see a profusion of
ads not only telling them that a diamond is forever, a longtime De
Beers slogan, but also asking them to look for the gemstone
equivalent of the union label. De Beers' trading partners _
cutters, polishers and dealers _ were asked to increase their
advertising budgets to promote consumer demand for diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers diamonds will carry the name Diamond Trading Co., or
DTC, as a guarantee to retailers that the diamonds were mined under
humane work conditions from reputable mines, said Joan Parker, the
director of the Diamond Information Center run by J. Walter
Thompson, the advertising agency for De Beers.
</P>
<P>
   The DTC monogram, with its accompanying logo called the
``forevermark,'' will show up on advertisements, though not
necessarily on the jewelry products themselves. The retailer will
know that the diamonds meet the standards ``and be able to respond
to the consumer when asked,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, jewelry shop owners have not been fielding many
questions about conflict diamonds anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you asked 10 shoppers in a Zales today if they are
concerned about buying blood diamonds, nine of them would say:
`Excuse me? What are you talking about?''' said Kenneth M. Gassman
Jr., a jewelry industry analyst for Davenport &AMP; Co. in Richmond,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, diamond jewelry sales have risen in the United States
in the last few years, to nearly $25 billion in 1999, about 12
percent higher than a year earlier. Analysts said they did not know
how the new De Beers policies would affect sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``De Beers is selling off its stockpile in a controlled
manner,'' Gassman said. Keeping the supply stable, he added, is
part of the company's venture into ``market-efficient capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   De Beers will also encourage the use of brand names. While few
diamond makers claim name recognition today, Gassman estimates that
in five years most diamonds will be branded.
</P>
<P>
   That arrangement should mean more profit for both diamond
suppliers and jewelry retailers, Gassman said, because branded
products usually carry higher margins. He pointed to Lazare Kaplan
International of New York, which fetches premium prices for its
Ideal Cuts diamonds that are laser-inscribed with the company's
logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brands will increase consumer confidence in the diamonds that
they buy _ that they are the quality they are supposed to be,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Beryl Raff, chief executive of Zale Corp., which operates more
than 1,300 jewelry stores, mainly under the names Zales, Gordon's
and Bailey, Banks &AMP; Biddle, said she expected De Beers and its
dealers to pay more attention to consumer trends, ensuring that
retailers get the stones they need for certain promotions or
jewelry lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think from a creativity standpoint, the consumer will win,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
