<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POVERTY-STRICKEN PHILADELPHIANS SEEK ATTENTION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Just north of downtown and far from the view of
Republican National Convention delegates lies one of the city's
poorest neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Kensington is home to about 10 percent of Philadelphia's
residents, many of whom are homeless, destitute or addicted to
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place called ``The Badlands'' where:
</P>
<P>
   Children ride bikes on streets littered with shards of glass and
piles of garbage;
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned factory walls _ if still standing _ are covered with
graffiti;
</P>
<P>
   Up to three families share one rundown rowhouse;
</P>
<P>
   Adults gather on front stoops and street corners all day because
there are no jobs;
</P>
<P>
   Vacant lots are used as homeless encampments;
</P>
<P>
   Drug dealers prey on others.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a place convention delegates are not likely to ever
visit, much less hear about from local officials directing them
instead to the sports arena facilities on the south side, the
historic center of downtown and the upscale dining along the South
Street entertainment district.
</P>
<P>
   But in a move to capture the attention of the some of the 15,000
journalists here for the convention, the Kensington Welfare Rights
Union organized tour-guided bus trips through the poverty-stricken
area.
</P>
<P>
   While GOP leaders spent Friday fending off efforts to weaken the
party platform's opposition to abortion and taxes, three yellow
school buses filled with reporters and activists rumbled northward.
</P>
<P>
   While Gov. George W. Bush's camp worked to defeat a proposal to
change the party's nomination structure, welfare rights union
founder Cheri Honkala rallied a group of homeless at a Tent City
near Kensington, the tour's first stop.
</P>
<P>
   Though not the first such encampment to sprout in a vacant lot,
this one is called Bushville as a sarcastic tribute to the expected
Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's elected president our problems are only going to get
worse,'' said tour guide Tamzin Cheshire, just before stopping to
let journalists visit the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Under a large tarp amid about a dozen tents and makeshift
lean-tos, Honkala cried as she talked about the opportunity her
group has this week to get national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than one-third of the children in Philadelphia live in
poverty,'' she said. ``After the convention the poor people are
going to go back to being the disappeared in America...We've got
one minute, one moment in time to make our voices heard so it's
worth living in a fishbowl right now. If people are ashamed of what
they see they better damn well do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Honkala's group is planning to march through downtown Monday to
the First Union Center, site of the convention, even though the
march was denied a city permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 income in Kensington is welfare. No. 2 is drugs,''
Honkala said. ``Many in these neighborhoods have no running water,
they have to use the fire plugs to wash. We are very adamant about
the fact ... the only thing we have is our voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Kensington once was the city's industrial center, a blue-collar
neighborhood of factory workers and family-run shops.
</P>
<P>
   But when the factories began moving out, poverty moved in. In 30
years Philadelphia has lost about 250,000 jobs, according to media
reports, and in the past two years has been home to more than
50,000 vacant lots and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt's Brewery, which once employed 1,400, still occupies an
entire block. But the brick buildings in the abandoned complex have
holes in the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Cheshire said children use the building as a playground because
they have no where else to go. And some families use it as shelter
despite the asbestos seeping from gaps in the structures.
</P>
<P>
   Just blocks away is Elbow Alley, a short street sandwiched
between a salvage yard and a row house where Cheshire said the
junkyard owners buys scrap metal from drug users so they will have
cash to buy his drugs.
</P>
<P>
   There are murals on several buildings, mostly outlets for
neighborhood artists. But for those who cannot afford headstones or
visits to cemeteries, Cheshire said, some of the murals serve as
memorial to friends and family who have died.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings with boarded up windows are on almost every street.
Weeds grow three to four feet tall in many lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia might be a great place to visit. It's not a great
place to live,'' Cheshire said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
