<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6517 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT     07-28 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BREAKING THE SILENCE
</HEADLINE>
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a country, a democracy, with a domestic program that is
increasingly costly and socially disruptive. The problem it is
supposed to solve has actually grown worse over the years _ but
neither major political party will talk about changing the policy.
</P>
<P>
   That is a picture of the United States and its drug policy. By
any rational test the war on drugs, with its use of the criminal
law and harsh sentences to solve the problem, is a costly failure.
The number of Americans in prison for drug offenses has multiplied
by 10 since 1980, from 41,000 to 458,000. But drugs are more
available than ever, and more young people are using them.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of this political and social disaster the Republican
and Democratic parties offer: silence. Their leaders are evidently
afraid that even discussing different approaches might get them
labeled as soft on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But the silence is about to be broken. In tandem with the
Republican National Convention starting Monday in Philadelphia, and
later with the Democrats, there will be shadow conventions that
discuss the failed war on drugs and two other issues that the major
parties have not solved: campaign finance and the gap between rich
and poor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain and other politicians brave enough to break
with their parties' wishes will participate. McCain will be the
keynote speaker tomorrow, talking about the idea that makes him
anathema to so many other Republicans: ending the scandal of
campaign money and influence.
</P>
<P>
   The shadow conventions are the brainchild of Arianna Huffington,
the columnist and gadfly. She has moved from the political right
toward the left _ or perhaps to a position of dislike for all
evasive politicians. The shadow conventions will have participants
from all camps.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Campbell of California, the Republican candidate for
Senate against the incumbent Dianne Feinstein, will talk about the
failed drug war. So will another Republican brave enough to
challenge the policy, Gov. Gary Johnson of New Mexico, and the Rev.
Jesse Jackson. Walter Cronkite, the greatly respected former
broadcast newsman, has made a 10-minute video special for the
shadow convention on the cost of the drug war.
</P>
<P>
   The staggering figure mentioned above _ that 10 times as many
Americans are in prison for drug offenses today as in 1980 _ comes
from the Justice Policy Institute in Washington. It has just issued
a report that shows, in fresh ways, some consequences of the war on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The 458,000 men and women now in U.S. prisons on drug charges
are 100,000 more than all prisoners in the European Union, whose
population is 100 million more than ours. The annual cost of
incarcerating them is $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 80 percent of drug arrests in 1997, the most recent year
for which figures are available, were for possession. Of those, 44
percent were for possession of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks are overwhelmingly more likely than whites to be
imprisoned for drug offenses, a study by Human Rights Watch showed.
Just 13 percent of regular drug users in this country are black,
but 62.7 percent of drug offenders sentenced to prison are black.
Evidently juries and judges treat offenders less seriously if they
are white.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Policy Institute report found that in 1986, 31 out
of every 100,000 young people in America were put in state prisons
for drug offenses. By 1996 the figure had nearly quadrupled, to 122
per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The institute studied states with higher rates of imprisonment
for drug offenses to see whether that had a deterrent effect. It
found, to the contrary, that states with higher incarceration rates
also had higher rates of drug use.
</P>
<P>
   There are already signs around the country of unease with the
human cost and practical failure of our drug policy. Perhaps the
shadow conventions will move more political leaders to face the
reality recently stated by The Economist of London: ``That
misguided policy has put millions of people behind bars, cost
billions, encouraged crime and spread corruption while failing
completely to reduce drug abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader has chided me for saying that he has paid little or
no attention as a candidate to the civil liberties record of the
major parties. In fact he has called the Clinton administration's
record ``abysmal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6518 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-SCREEN-STRIKE-2TAKES-     07-28 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCREEN-STRIKE-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUIET ON THE SET IS SOUNDING LIKE THUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dressed in a pink tutu with double-decker wings,
Todd Susman and his grouchy persona are trying to change the image
of the tooth fairy forever.
</P>
<P>
   For Susman, a 53-year-old actor, the offbeat role in ads for
Sonicare electric toothbrushes is an opportunity to play a
memorable personality like Mr. Whipple, the vigilant grocery-store
manager of the Charmin commercials, and Clara, who asked ``Where's
the beef?'' for the Wendy's fast-food chain.
</P>
<P>
   But with a strike by commercial actors against advertisers and
agencies entering its 14th week, Susman will not be shooting new
commercials for Sonicare, which is made by Optiva, as scheduled.
Although he knows that the character, and the advertising campaign,
could be jeopardized, he said the risk was ultimately worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers want to change the status quo forever,'' he said.
``They have the money. They have the resolution, and if they can
possibly do it they will.''
</P>
<P>
   As the strike stretches on, it appears to be more and more a
sign of things to come. Movie and television production are already
being accelerated as Hollywood prepares for the possibility of
strikes by screen and television actors as well as writers when
their contracts expire next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent newsletter, the Writers Guild of America warned its
members: ``Now is not the time to be buying the biggest house or
the nicest car you can afford. If you have a TV staff-writing job,
begin putting money away now. If you make a feature deal, bank
every penny you can.''
</P>
<P>
   The writers and actors share a key complaint, about their pay
for work shown on cable TV. In the early days of cable, union
representatives say, actors and writers cut special deals below
network rates to help the fledgling industry get off the ground.
Now, they say, it's time for payback. ``Cable has become a mature
cash cow industry, very successful,'' said John McLean, executive
director of the Writers Guild of America, West. ``And we want our
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the disputes arise from the changing face of
television and the multitude of options created by advances in
electronic media, including the Internet. Compensation for work
shown on the Internet is another issue in the contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a whole new world here; we'll agree with them on
that,'' said Todd Amorde, chairman of the national strike strategy
committee for the Screen Actors Guild and the American Federation
of Television and Radio Artists.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, television was dominated by the three major
networks _ ABC, NBC and CBS. Now, there are seven broadcast
networks and at least 50 national cable networks that are tracked
by Nielsen Media Research, plus many regional channels that are not
even monitored. Until the late 1970s, the three big broadcast
networks captured more than 90 percent of the viewing audience.
That share is now less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a different economic model,'' said Tim Brooks,
co-author of an annual directory of prime-time network and cable
shows. ``You get this collision of interests as times change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Writers Guild's contract with producers expires May 1 next
year, followed by the movie and television actors contracts July 1.
No proposals are yet on the table. But union representatives said
they want compensation for the increasing profitability of cable
and of shows that are broadcast overseas. They also want a
guarantee of fair pay for work that appears on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the strike by actors in commercials, the primary difference
is simple: the actors want to be paid every time an ad is shown on
television, and advertising agencies and marketers want to pay a
flat rate.
</P>
<P>
   On network television, actors who appear in commercials are paid
under a system known as ``pay for play.'' They receive a daily
rate, currently $478.70, which includes the first broadcast. They
are then paid each time the commercial is shown again, starting at
$122.70 and decreasing over 13 weeks to $46.65. On cable, they are
paid $1,014 for the 13-week cyle, no matter how many times the
commercial is shown.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial runs an average of 44 times over 13 weeks on the
networks, according to Amorde. On cable, with more channels and
lower costs for time, he said, advertisers have told him that
commercials run 225 to 233 times over 13 weeks. But he says the
Screen Actors Guild has found some ads that were shown as many as
5,000 times on cable.
</P>
<P>
   Though actors usually spend only a day or two shooting a
commercial, they spend much more time searching for assignments and
auditioning. Apart from celebrities, the most successful actors who
specialize in commercials can earn more than $50,000 in a good
year. But most make just a few thousand dollars and rely on other
jobs for most of their income.
</P>
<P>
   Unions representing commercial actors have proposed a
pay-for-play arrangement for cable at 37 percent of the network
rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Policy Committee, representing advertisers and their
agencies, has proposed to increase the payment for filming a
commercial to $500, followed by a flat rate of $2,575 for 13 weeks
of appearances on network TV. On cable, they have proposed
increasing the rate for 13 weeks to $1,627.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing on these terms is essential before the negotiators
start dealing with new technologies, said John A. McGuinn, chief
negotiator for the Joint Policy Committee. ``This strike is about
modernizing this contract and bringing it into the Year 2000 so we
can deal with the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators have been finding little common ground. The talks,
which had been suspended, resumed on July 20 after federal
mediators called the two groups back to the table. But the
negotiations quickly broke down again.
</P>
<P>
   Actors want Internet use of advertising included in the
contract, but McGuinn said he had not been authorized to negotiate
in this area. The advertisers and agencies want both sides to study
the issue and meet at least once a year, but they stress that they
do not agree that the unions have a right to negotiate Internet
rates.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A third sticking point involves the unions' desire to verify how
many times a commercial is shown. The Screen Actors Guild says its
survey of 38 commercials uncovered $110,000 in unpaid wages. The
advertising industry proposes joining with the unions to choose a
consultant who can search for the best way to monitor commercials.
Recommendations from a committee representing both sides would be
due 60 days before the expiration of a new contract in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Some advertisers are producing commercials with the blessing of
the actors unions by agreeing to pay what the unions have proposed.
But many other commercials are being made in defiance of the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   The unions, affiliates of the AFL-CIO, are trying to keep the
heat on advertisers. Members are picketing production of nonunion
commercials in an attempt to shut them down. Earlier this month,
the actors picketed major offices of AT&AMP;T, which has been making
commercials using nonunion actors.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the protesters were addressed by labor leaders,
including the AFL-CIO president, John J. Sweeney, and by actors
like Susan Sarandon and Jerry Orbach.
</P>
<P>
   Susman said he had been lucky enough to work during the strike
by providing the voice of a dog in commercials for Laidlaw's
Greyhound bus line, which signed the unions' proposed contract.
Still, he marvels that commercial actors, among the hardest-working
and lowest-paid members of the actors' unions, are bearing the
brunt of the larger struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``How God and luck aligned in this particular situation so that
we are the ones at the forefront of this fight, I will never
know,'' Susman said. ``But we know the fight we're in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
