<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS COULD BE PLAYERS IN NEXT WEEK'S FRENZY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With three days remaining before NBA teams can
officially announce free-agent signings, the clear winners during
the month-long negotiation period are the phone company and rumor
mongers.
</P>
<P>
   NBA general managers are burning the phone lines trying to
consummate complicated deals, and they figure to keep doing so
right up to Tuesday, when the fruits of their efforts can finally
be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a game of chess, so to speak, between teams (trying
to make deals) and with representatives of players,'' said Los
Angeles Lakers general manager Mitch Kupchak. ``It's been a month
of continuous calls, rumors, and strategy. I'm sure it's something
that, when you look back on it you'd think was fun. But while it's
happening it can be a tenuous, trying process.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the rumors, let's just say some of the speculated deals
currently making the rounds have about as much authenticity as a
World Federation Wrestling match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stuff you hear is pretty old and most of it
probably won't happen,'' Kupchak said. ``What does that all mean?
It means we all have to wait (until Tuesday) and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   A few things are certain, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando Magic will add Detroit's Grant Hill and Toronto's
Tracy McGrady as free agents and San Antonio will retain Tim
Duncan, the crown jewel of this year's free-agent class. Meanwhile,
the Chicago Bulls, with millions in salary-cap dollars available
but no one accepting the money, will be hard-pressed to improve on
last year's disastrous finish.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, the 24-year-old forward, was vigorously pursued by
Orlando but decided to remain in San Antonio, where he and David
Robinson hope to win another NBA title. Duncan reportedly will sign
a three-year contract with the Spurs next week, then sign a much
more lucrative seven-year deal after he has six years of NBA
experience.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear the Lakers will be players in next week's frenzy, but
to what degree remains to be seen. With free agent Glen Rice
destined to leave Los Angeles, the Lakers have reportedly talked to
Charlotte about a complicated four-way deal in which Eddie Jones,
Rice and Detroit's Jerome Williams would wind up in Philadelphia,
the 76ers' Toni Kukoc and Charlotte's Anthony Mason would come to
L.A., and Philadelphia's Allen Iverson and Matt Geiger would go to
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the trade, Charlotte would get Detroit's Jerry
Stackhouse and Christian Laettner and the Lakers' Travis Knight.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is unlikely for two reasons. One is the Lakers'
reluctance to add Mason to their roster. The other is that the
Pistons have already publicly committed to signing Orlando free
agents Ben Wallace and Chuck Atkins, reducing their cap space and
making it difficult to add Iverson and Geiger in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, L.A. wants no part of Anthony Mason,'' one
source familiar with the situation said. ``(Jerry) West thinks it
would be disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   That could change, of course, if West decides to step down as
team president as has been widely reported.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte also talked to L.A. about a straight-up deal with Rice
and Jones, but a long-term contract makes Jones a base-year player,
meaning a third team with available cap space must be part of the
deal. Someone like the Clippers or Bulls, although neither seems
inclined to help the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely deal is Rice going to the 76ers in a swap for
Kukoc, who played under Phil Jackson in Chicago and is familiar
with the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak said the Lakers are seeking help in the frontcourt,
outside shooting and more size in the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have needs to address,'' Kupchak said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the frontcourt players the Lakers covet in either
sign-and-trade deals or with their $2.2 and $1.2 million veteran
salary exceptions are P.J. Brown of Miami, Charles Oakley and
Antonio Davis of Toronto, Austin Croshere of Indiana, Kurt Thomas
of New York, Jahidi White from Washington, Bo Outlaw from Orlando
and Adonal Foyle of Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, having already been spurned by Orlando's John
Amaechi, await word on the players they've talked to since the
negotiation period opened July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much work you've done, you can't rest easy until
you actually have players signed,'' Kupchak said. ``And that makes
it stressful for people who do this for a living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
