<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6523 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-KENNEDY-SECURITY-1     07-28 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KENNEDY-SECURITY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY HOSTAGE-TAKING SEEN AS PRICE OF AVOIDING GUNFIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Nev.)   (SUBS 3rd graf to add attribution; Subs 4th graf to add Commey's
arraignment; ADDS 8 graf at end with details, quotes) 
By JOHN SULLIVAN and RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Airport security checkpoints, with their squads of
guards and phalanxes of metal detectors, are considered by most
passengers to be a kind of firewall, designed to stop weapons from
getting anywhere near airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   But airline security officials have long acknowledged that the
checkpoints are really meant to do only part of that job: They are
supposed to detect hidden guns or bombs and provide a system for
alerting armed police officers. If someone brandishes a gun and
tries to force his way past, the officials said, the unarmed
security officers at the checkpoints are not only unable to stop
him, they are not supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   This fact was frighteningly underscored late Thursday night in
Terminal 4W at Kennedy International Airport, when the police said
Aaron Commey, a 22-year-old Milwaukee man, approached a security
supervisor, waved a 10-millimeter automatic handgun, ran around the
metal detectors and dashed directly out an elevated Jetway at Gate
33. He then boarded a National Airlines Boeing 757 set to fly to
Las Vegas and took the pilot and co-pilot hostage, official said.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt during the takeover, Commey, who the police said
surrendered peacefully, was ar- raigned Friday on charges of at-
tempted air piracy. Officials at Kennedy airport insisted Friday
that their security procedures had worked as they should have:
Armed police officers responded in less than three minutes, no
shots were fired and hostage negotiators succeeded in persuading
Commey to give himself up.
</P>
<P>
   But to many of the passengers who were boarding the National
Airlines jet, the security system seemed to have left them
shockingly vulnerable. Unlike the security checkpoints throughout
most of the rest of the airport, the checkpoint for the National
Airlines flight was unusually close to the door to the Jetway,
meaning that there was next to no time for flight attendants to
close the door and prevent him from boarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police came very fast, but there was no security,'' said
Marcus Weiss, one passenger interviewed shortly after the takeover
began. ``The guy just walked right on through. It's really really
strange. The airport security working there weren't armed. They
couldn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy airport officials and many other airline security
experts said Friday that the proximity of the checkpoint to the
gate probably had little to do with what happened, because Commey,
pointing a gun, probably could have gone through many other
checkpoints located farther from gates and still made his way onto
a plane.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials agreed Friday that the incident was exactly
the kind that, despite various strategies over the years, has long
been considered virtually unpreventable.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, beginning in 1973 after a spate of hijackings,
security screening points were set up in all the country's airports
and they were guarded by armed police officers. But in 1978, the
Federal Aviation Administration and the airline industry agreed to
discontinue the practice, in part because they considered it more
dangerous than the possibility of a gunman forcing his way through
the checkpoint area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a firing range,'' said Homer A. Boynton, who directed
security for American Airlines from 1981 to 1993. ``There was a
unanimous decision among the people in the airline industry and the
people in the FAA that it was a wise choice to take the armed guard
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John Torres, the operations captain at Kennedy airport,
said that he believed people could have been hurt if guards had
been armed or had tried to stop Commey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a potential for a shootout in a crowded terminal with
passengers walking around,'' said Torres, one of the Port Authority
police officers who directed the response to the hostage situation
Thursday night. He added: ``Security did the right thing. They did
not try to take an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Torres and other officials said, the security guards _
who do not work for the Port Authority but for a private company
under contract to the airlines _ pushed what is known as a covert
button as soon as Commey sprinted past the metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   The button sounded an alarm that summoned armed Port Authority
police officers. Al Graser, deputy director of the aviation
department for the Port Authority, said that at least one officer
is stationed in each of the six terminals at Kennedy airport.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, officers once were required to respond to a
security checkpoint within one minute in an emergency, but over the
years, as the number of hijacking attempts dropped, the requirement
was relaxed to five minutes, Graser said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Torres said, the police response time was two
to three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cathal L. Flynn, the head of civil aviation security for the
FAA, also praised the job done not only by police and security
officers, but also by the flight attendants and pilots, who he said
managed to deal with the situation calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that assessment, the inci- dent is likely to raise
troubling ques- tions once again about the effective- ness of the
private security systems in place at Kennedy and all the na- tion's
airports.
</P>
<P>
   The checkpoints detect an average  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  of
2,000 weapons each year and have been remarkably successful in pre-
venting the hijackings that plagued the industry in the early
1970s, Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   But the performance of the guards has been a longstanding
concern of federal watchdog agencies. In a re- port released late
last month, the General Accounting Office conclud- ed that a
variety of problems had continued to affect guards' ability to
detect dangerous objects carried by passengers. Although the FAA
does not release the results of tests of security systems, the GAO
said that FAA officials had acknowledged that their own tests of
guards and check- points had shown that they did not work
satisfactorily in detecting dan- gerous objects.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the GAO said the problems were attributable
mostly to a difficult working environment and rapid turnover among
security personnel at many airports. ``Screen- ers are often paid
the minimum wage or close to it and can often earn more at airport
fast-food restau- rants,'' the investigators wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said the FAA had be- gun to carry out changes to improve
the screening systems, including in- stalling better detection
equipment and creating computer surveillance programs that would
record the se- curity officers' attentiveness and performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to improve the human element; we don't disagree,''
Flynn said. But he also pointed out that no one has been killed
during a terrorist incident on a flight originat- ing in the United
States and attribut- ed that to a successful overall securi- ty
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy airport officials also said that the incident Thursday
night was the only takeover of a plane there in recent memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
