<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6525 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-SARAH-$ADV30-A     07-28 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SARAH-$ADV30-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A START ON WELFARE TO RICHES IN THE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 was sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ It happened decades ago, but Sarah Jessica Parker
remembers a horribly embarrassing experience. In the third grade at
the Clifton School in Cincinnati, her teacher called out her name
and she had to go to the front of the line each day to get a ticket
for her free lunch from the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on welfare,'' recalled Parker, the curly-haired,
slinky star and producer of HBOs ``Sex and the City.'' ``I knew I
was different from the kids who pay for lunch or bring their lunch
from home. It was a stigma thing. I was not the only person
receiving a free lunch, but you are aware.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my childhood as Dickensian,'' she added. ``I
remember being poor. There was no great way to hide it. We didn't
have electricity sometimes. We didn't have Christmases sometimes,
or we didn't have birthdays sometimes, or the bill collectors came,
or the phone company would call and say, `We're shutting your
phones off.' And we were all old enough to either get the calls, or
watch my mother's reactions or watch my parents shuffling the money
around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'' included Parker's three older and four younger siblings.
Neither her father, Stephen Parker, then a writer, nor her
stepfather, Paul Forste, a truck driver whom her mother, Barbara,
married when Sarah Jessica was 3{, earned enough to support such a
large family.
</P>
<P>
   Parker has a matter-of-fact tone as she talks of the past; there
is no trace of bitterness. She remembers much about her childhood
warmly and remains extremely close to her siblings and her parents.
But when it comes to money, her harsh childhood experiences
continue to shape her attitudes, making her a conservative
investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I want most for my children _ I would like for them
to not be aware of money, which means I have been very aware of my
financial situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those children _ she is planning to have some of her own someday
soon _ shouldn't have to worry. Today Sarah Jessica Parker is one
of the hottest stars on television. With her megawatt smile
plastered on buses and pay phones across the country, she draws as
much attention as Hollywood icons like Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Though Parker, 35, has been in show business most of her life
and has many film, stage and television credits, the success of the
two-year-old ``Sex and the City'' has catapulted her into a whole
new financial category. Industry executives estimate that her pay _
while still nowhere near as high as for some stars on regular
network television _ is now $100,000 to $150,000 an episode.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Matthew Broderick, is a highly regarded Hollywood
and Broadway actor, but Parker does not want to depend on him
financially. They keep their monetary affairs separate.
</P>
<P>
   Parker says her father once told her that to assure her
financial security, she needed $8 million. Though she would not be
more specific, given her salary from the HBO series and films, she
seems likely to be more than halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened in the past year is extraordinary,'' she
said happily. ``There is not a day that passes that I am not
grateful for the windfall.''
</P>
<P>
   With that capital and earning power, her life is a far cry from
the days when her mother used to buy her and her sisters each two
pairs of shoes a year and dresses at 99 cents each. ``There was a
corporate outlet and you could get Polly Flinders dresses really
inexpensively,'' said Forste, who now lives in Teaneck, N.J., and
teaches nursery school, a career that she had dropped when Sarah
Jessica was 3. ``It was not unusual to get them there or at rummage
sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker says she invests conservatively and worries about the day
when she cannot get work. But her scary financial past and her
current flush state sometimes make for an odd couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why I have such a weird relationship with money,''
Parker said. ``And it is why I can be profligate and super-frugal.
And I think it is rather warped since it comes from this desire to
save, save, save. And on the other hand, I have been working so
hard for 25 years _ why can't I have another pair of Manolo Blahnik
shoes or that bag that I love?''
</P>
<P>
   She shoots ``Sex in the City'' for about six months out of the
year and a feature film during the hiatus. ``Whatever happens to
the stock market, I am making a steady paycheck every week'' while
the series is in production, she said, ``so the tote board gets
bigger, and there is more to spend.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, when she is doing a movie and is on location, she
receives a living allowance in cash each week. That is when she is
most tempted to splurge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hand you the cash and it's like pop candy,'' Parker said.
``In the good old days, they used to call it `mad money.''' A
recent acquisition, she said, was a second Hermes bag; her husband
had bought her the first as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   But when she is not working, she is nervous about spending.
``Idle hands are the devil's workshop,'' she intoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends know me so well, and they know how terrified I am
of being broke, and they think it is hilarious and humorous,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's fears, however, have considerable basis in her
industry. History is rife with stories of actresses who never got
much work after the age of 45, and Parker is clearly aware of the
odds of surviving in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of the entertainment industry, actresses have this
window, and the window closes every day a little bit more,'' she
said. ``The earnings potential falls and the window is closed, and
I am really cognizant of that. I have no illusions of who I am or
what I look like or what I have to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker caught the acting bug early. Her mother was infatuated
with the arts, particularly the theater. ``I would like to say that
I was absolutely not a stage mother,'' Forste said. ``But on some
level I was. What the children did was pretty much under our
control. But any of the kids that did not want to act didn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Jessica, who began acting professionally when she was 8,
was one of several clan members who loved it. Two of her brothers _
Pippin Parker, a writer, and Timothy Britten Parker, an actor _ are
also in the business.
</P>
<P>
   An early career breakthrough for Sarah Jessica came in 1979, at
the age of 14, when she played the lead in the Broadway production
of ``Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was away from all the chaos of the house,'' Parker said.
``It was this really structured environment. And the theater seemed
really nice and disciplined. And they paid me, and I didn't have
any money.''
</P>
<P>
   Her credits range from television's ``Square Pegs'' and ``Year
in the Life'' to the films ``Footloose'' (1984), ``L.A. Story''
(1991), ``Ed Wood'' (1994) ``Honeymoon in Vegas'' (1992) and ``The
First Wives' Club'' (1996). On stage, she has been seen in
``Substance of Fire'' and the Broadway revivals of ``How to Succeed
in Business,'' opposite Broderick, and ``Once Upon a Mattress,'' in
which she starred as the Princess.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In show business, the big money is made in movies, and until now
Parker has never commanded headline-grabbing fees. That was partly
because she has turned down some higher-paying roles. ``I have
never been a big payday person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Wives Club'' had the highest box-office receipts of
any of her movies, but it was not until she played Nell in ``Dudley
Do-Right,'' filmed in 1999, after ``Sex and the City'' had made her
a television star, that she could command more than $500,000 for a
lead movie role, one industry expert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the choices you make,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with her celebrity status soaring, she would probably get
$1 million or more, several leading agents said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Parker's paychecks are invested pretty conservatively by
firms selected by Frank Selvaggi, a founder of Altman, Greenfield &AMP;
Selvaggi, an accounting firm in Manhattan that advises many
entertainers. Parker's stepfather, who started his own trucking
company in the early 1980's, introduced her to Selvaggi 18 years
ago. They have worked together ever since.
</P>
<P>
   She relies heavily on Selvaggi's advice, which goes well beyond
the selection of money managers. His firm pays her bills, and
Selvaggi, in concert with her agent, Kevin Houvane at Creative
Artists, occasionally counsels her on whether she needs to accept
an offer for film or television work. When a commercial is offered,
for example, ``he might tell me not to do it,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll say: `Be true to yourself. You don't need the money,'''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Parker has been working 14-hour days lately on ``Sex and the
City,'' leaving her little time for worrying about finances. But
she checks in regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is more active than most people,'' Selvaggi said. ``She
calls me every month to go over her bills and financial statements.
Not that she asks about individual stocks, but if there are big
swings, she brings it up.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Parker bought an apartment in the TriBeCa neighborhood
of Manhattan. In 1997, the year she married Broderick, she sold it
to move in with him and started putting her extra capital to work.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 30 percent to 40 percent of her investment portfolio is
in tax-free bonds. The remainder is in various stocks and mutual
funds primarily handled by McDonald &AMP; Co. and other investment
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Selvaggi and McDonald executives tailored her investment
strategy. ``I sat in a long meeting and listened and looked at a
lot of numbers and pies and graphs and made those conservative
choices,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Selvaggi said, the investments are in value stocks
like Colgate-Palmolive and Citigroup. He has stayed away from
dot-coms because the approach he has worked out with Parker has
been, as he put it, that ``slow and steady wins the race.''
</P>
<P>
   They put some money into blue-chip technology stocks including
Microsoft, Cisco Systems and Intel, in 1997 and 1998, he said but
not too much, because ``when she was going into the market, it was
very high and shaky.''
</P>
<P>
   Selvaggi said Parker's stock investments have done very well,
beating the 19.5 percent gain of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although some investors think stocks are just as safe an
investment as bonds over the long term, and much better than bonds
at making money, Selvaggi is mindful that a performer's career can
suddenly spiral downward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonds are less volatile,'' he said. ``And sometimes you are
talking about a two- or three-year window when the market is on a
downward slope, but people need capital. If they invest in the
stock market, the capital can drop in value. I make sure they
understand the risk.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like many other people these days, Parker is torn about her
investing style. ``There's a guy on the show who made his mortgage
in one day on his house on some Internet stock,'' she said. ``I
said to him: `Why didn't you call me?' He made $35,000 in half an
hour, which I think is a great gig. I don't do any of that stuff. I
watch the market, and Matthew and I have these conversations like,
`Should we get out?' And I call Frank, and it is so scary, and he
says: `It's OK Stay in.'''
</P>
<P>
   She knows she has missed out on some of the stock market's big
gains in recent years, ``but I feel like it's too late to catch
up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if you haven't written somebody a thank-you note in
months,'' she added. ``You can't begin to do it so late.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not impervious to stock tips. In 1992, when she was
working in Pittsburgh, the hub of U S Air Group, now U &UR;  &LR; S Airways,
she took a shot. ``The guy who did my hair had a boyfriend who
worked at U S Air. He's like: `It's going to merge with British
Air. Get in there.' I called Frank at 6 in the morning and said,
`Buy U S Air.''' She invested about $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   This year, when U S Airways agreed to be acquired, albeit by the
UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines, Parker sold and made $4,000.
About that time, she made her only other independent financial
choice, a $10,000 investment in a restaurant that went out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband have stayed with the separate financial
advisers they had before they met, she said, and ``we don't discuss
money very much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a rough understanding of what Matthew can and cannot
afford, but there is no reason I need to know how much money he
has,'' she added. ``If and when we have our children, then things
become communal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men, especially, say to me: `You are loaded,' and I say:
`Matthew's money is not my money.' I have to work. I never want
Matthew to feel the pressure to take a job because he thinks he has
to support me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I asked him about his finances, he would tell me. But I
don't want to know. It is not what keeps me interested in him. I
suppose that if Matthew told me that he wouldn't tell me, I would
feel resentful. But it is the least important thing, because
Matthew has always said that he would take care of me. And I would
take care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple do not have a joint checking account. ``I buy all the
groceries and his clothes and pay for reupholstering the
furniture,'' she said. ``We take each other out to dinner. We do
have a joint credit card and sometimes use it for groceries.''
Broderick pays it.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband live in a Federal-style 1840s brownstone in
Greenwich Village that Broderick bought before they were married.
They rent an old farmhouse in the Hamptons for the summer and, as
Selvaggi put it, can afford do what they like. If they don't talk
about how to make money, they do talk about how to spend it. ``I
bought cheap because that is what my mother did,'' Parker said.
``She would drive 15 miles out of her way to get 15 bags of paper
towels because they were cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   But Broderick is more prone to ``buy one good knife and then you
don't have to keep replacing it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She says that her husband is very smart about money and that she
has learned from him. At the most practical level, she said, she
would no longer ``buy a used car and keep replacing it over and
over; I would buy one decent car.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though Parker has loosened up a bit with money, she remains
determined not to repeat her family's financial past.
</P>
<P>
   When Sarah Jessica was 11, the family moved from Cincinnati to
Roosevelt Island in New York City _ then a new mixed-income
community on a piece of land formerly named Welfare Island _ so the
children could do more work in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sort of a caste system,'' she recalled. ``It was a
sliding scale with some subsidized housing.'' The families with the
least money lived in the less desirable apartments. ``We were in
the house closest to the parking lot, and so everybody knew,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure eased as Forste's business did better and the
children grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Parker is ambivalent about the stresses of earning money as a
child in a family that needed it so desperately. In those days in
New York State, there was no legislation requiring that some of a
child actor's earnings go directly into a trust. Nor were there
laws saying how much a child actor could work.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money the children earned ``was absorbed into the
family,'' Parker said. ``I wouldn't deny anything that I
contributed financially.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ``if I knew then what I know now, I would have
had somebody outside the family help me manage the money _ an
objective party that would keep things real clean, so that when you
were a teen-ager, you don't feel resentful that you can't at least
keep some of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, she can laugh at the trials of growing up under
such stress and at the complex standards her mother had about what
her children could and could not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would never let me work in television,'' Parker recalled.
``She thought it was vulgar and trashy.''
</P>
<P>
   For her mother, ``the theater and ballet were not about money,''
Parker said. ``It was about this grand idea of who we were as a
family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her role model was Rose Kennedy,'' Parker added. ``She wanted
to raise a family that had grand and important lives. It was weird
because we were living in all this chaos, but her image was
actually a great motivator.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
