<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-28 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES TRADE COULD BE A COUP, WITH RIGHT ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's news-and-views, deals-and-steals edition of The Sporting
Muse:
</P>
<P>
   News: Dodgers welcome back Ismael Valdes with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   Views: OK, maybe we're overstating the reception. But no one hit
him while he was taking a shower, either.
</P>
<P>
   The team and the young pitcher can make this week's trade a real
coup if everyone has the right attitude. The club never should have
traded Valdes in the first place, because he's too young and his
arm too lively. Whether or not he lacks cajones is irrelevant when
you're talking about someone who can give you 200 decent innings a
year at a time when good pitching is an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes never wanted to be traded in the first place and he hated
it in Chicago, where he had no friends and the unsympathetic Don
Baylor was manager. He should be overjoyed to be back in the
family, and it won't surprise me if he throws a complete game
shutout in his first start.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the team should take it as a clue, too. Obviously,
Dodger CEO Bob Daly hasn't given up on the season, and there are
worse places in baseball to be than Los Angeles. If there's any
sign of a spine in this baseball team, now would be a good time to
show it.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Dodgers G.M. Kevin Malone is still upside down in his
deal with the Cubs, because I'm sure Eric Young would have
contributed more to the 2000 team than setup reliever Terry Adams.
</P>
<P>
   News: Diamondbacks trade for Phillies Curt Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   Views: On the surface, the snakes now have a formidable 1-2
pitching punch, which is a real key considering some contenders
don't have 1, much less a 2.
</P>
<P>
   And should they make it to the postseason, this pair could be
the difference in a seven-game series. But there was a point this
season when Schilling didn't have his usual velocity, indicative of
the kind of arm problems that come and go on a whim. All it takes
is one bad whim, too, to lose a pennant.
</P>
<P>
   The other trades sound more exciting than they are. I don't see
how Mike Bordick, just obtained from Baltimore, puts the Mets over
the top, playoff-wise. Sometimes teams push too many buttons this
time of year. The Rockies and Red Sox exchanged cold bodies, with
Red Sox hoping Rolando Arroyo can suck up some innings in a
scheduled crowded by makeup games.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee-Cleveland deal was intriguing in two respects: the
team owned by commissioner Bud Selig (the Brewers) trade away three
pitchers (Bob Wickman, Steve Woodard, Jason Bere), and the Indians
now can pad their major league record for most pitchers used in a
season. It was 29 before the trade.
</P>
<P>
   News: Baseball makes more trades than NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
   Views: It's the big names that you always notice when trades are
made on the eve of the deadline, like Schilling, Valdes, Bordick
and Mike Lansing. But there's plenty of proof that the teams
trading vets for a fistful of prospects are the ones who win.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some of these deals from the past few years:
</P>
<P>
   -- Needs bullpen help during a pennant race, Seattle obtained
Heathcliff Slocumb from Boston. The Mariners got Derek Lowe, now
the Sox closer, and Jason Varitek, their everyday catcher.
</P>
<P>
   -- Looking for pitching help, the Mets obtained Kenny Rogers and
Billy Taylor from Oakland. The A's got Terrance Long, now their
starting centerfielder, and Jason Isringhausen, now their closer.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Giants obtained Wilson Alvarez and two other players from
the White Sox two years ago in a deal widely hailed as a mistake by
the Sox. But two of the young pitchers obtained from the Giants,
Keith Foulke and Bobby Howry, are mainstays of the Sox bullpen and
their surprise rise in the A.L. Central.
</P>
<P>
   -- Other pre-deadline deals: To get John Smiley, the Indians
gave closer Danny Graves to the Reds; to rent Randy Johnson, the
Astros gave Freddy Garcia, John Halama and Carlos Guillen to
Seattle; to rent Todd Stottlemeyer, the Rangers gave Fernando Tatis
to the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   News: The dealing has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Among the names still on the market are Rangers closer
John Wetteland (best bet: Braves as a three-month rental); Phillie
first baseman Rico Brogna (Red Sox for prospects, maybe the
Cardinals depending on Mark McGwire's health); Seattle pitcher
Brett Tomko (Cleveland for Ricky Ledee); Montreal outfielder
Rondell White (Yankees).
</P>
<P>
   News: Pirates taking phone calls and best offers for Jason
Kendall after the catcher's agent frowns on much-deferred $60
million, 6-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Allow me to implore Kevin Malone to call the Pirates and
Kendall's agent now and make his best offer for the catcher
(especially since the Padres appear interested, too). He is exactly
what the Dodgers need, a take-charge clubhouse leader who is a good
handler of pitchers and great hitter familiar with leadoff and the
No. 2 slot.
</P>
<P>
   His catching alone would knock half-a-run off the team ERA and
cut opponent's stealing attempts in half. This Dodger team is
willing to roll in the dirt when it needs to, it just needs someone
aggressive to lead the initial charge. Kendall, a Torrance native,
is exactly that kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley is a good guy who has worked hard to improve on his
disappointing '99 season, but he belongs in the American League,
where he can DH and take an occasional game behind the plate or at
first base.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care about losing his left-handed bat in the lineup.
Neither should Davey Johnson, because if the team doesn't make a
statement in the next two months, he's not going to be around to
worry about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
