<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVALLEY-AGRICULTURE </SLUG>
  
 AGRICULTURAL GROUP WINS FINANCING PACKAGE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY KELLY YAMANOUCHI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tri Valley Growers, the financially troubled
agricultural cooperative, won bankruptcy court approval Friday for
$270 million in financing from a banking consortium.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Edward Jellen approved the financing
package despite some reservations. ``This is one of those
situations where I wish there was more time to negotiate,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no time for that. The decision needs to be made
today. I can't hold up the rate at which fruit ripens'' and needs
to be picked.
</P>
<P>
   Growers, who are &UR;  &LR; members of the cooperative that filed for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy July 10, were relying heavily on the
financing to provide Tri Valley with the money it needs to pay them
for their crops. They had been assured going into the hearing they
would be paid 70 cents on the dollar for their peaches and 60 cents
on the dollar for all other crops.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the growers were unhappy that creditors and lenders had
priority over them in the repayment of debts. ``To me, it doesn't
seem right. We have no voice in the hearings,'' said Mark Wilcox, a
farmer who grows pears and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The approved financing will be used to cover $169 million owed
to a consortium of banks. The remainder will be used to cover any
new financial obligations of the cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   William Weintraub, Tri Valley's attorney, stressed during the
hearing how difficult it was for the cooperative to secure
financing. As a result, he said, the cooperative has only been able
to secure bank financing for this year, and not for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperative originally sought more than $300 million in
financing, but during negotiations with creditors and lenders, the
amount was whittled down to $270 million, said Tri Valley spokesman
Fred MacFarlane.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at kaymanouchi(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
