<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6630 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-HEARSTBACK-HISTORY &LR;      07-28 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARSTBACK-HISTORY </SLUG>
  
 ONCE-COLORFUL HEARST CORP. NOW DRIVEN MOSTLY BY ECONOMICS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY CAROLYN SAID &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The crusading zeal that originally defined
Hearst newspapers has receded as far into the past as a hot-metal
Linotype machine.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, for Bay Area readers who want to know what will
happen to The Chronicle under Hearst ownership, the company's past
is not a predictor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first part of this century, Hearst was very much
characterized by the Chief'' _ legendary founder William Randolph
Hearst, said Orville Schell, dean of the graduate school of
journalism at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half of the century, they've been much more
nondescript. A positive view would be that they're waiting for
greatness,'' Schell said. ``They have an opportunity for that now
in San Francisco..''
</P>
<P>
   As a corporation, Hearst bears little resemblance to the company
that helped ignite the Spanish-American War to sell papers.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a diversified media empire, the 12th largest in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Today, despite its newspaper roots, Hearst's personality is more
strongly defined by its monthly magazines, with such familiar
titles as Cosmopolitan, Esquire, Good Housekeeping and Redbook, and
glitterati editors such as Tina Brown, John Mack Carter, Helen
Gurley Brown, even Oprah. Its broadcasting operations also are
extensive, with partnerships in A&AMP;E and Lifetime cable networks,
and a string of local TV and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's newspaper chain has shrunk dramatically since its
heydey in the 1930s, when its 33 papers commanded 15 percent of all
U.S. newspaper readership. The exodus to the suburbs helped kill
many of Hearst's metropolitan papers.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst papers are anchored by one heavy hitter. The Houston
Chronicle, with 553,462 daily readers, is the nation's
ninth-largest paper. During the Chronicle-Hearst antitrust trial,
Hearst Chief Executive Officer Frank A. Bennack Jr. testified that
the Houston Chronicle ``is perhaps closest'' to world-class caliber
of any Hearst paper, but hasn't yet reached that level.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Miller, managing editor of the Houston Chronicle, said
there weren't any dramatic changes when Hearst bought the paper in
1986, but a steady, gradual staff expansion made the paper more
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a feisty competition with the Houston Post,'' he
recalled. ``Hearst's message was: Go to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle ended up winning that war: The Post folded
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to San Francisco, Hearst's large papers are in
Seattle; San Antonio; and Albany, N.Y. But Hearst's dailies, half
of them in Texas, include some as tiny as the 6,142-circulation
Edwardsville (Ill.) Intelligencer. Six of Hearst's papers have
circulations below 22,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack, who has been chief executive of Hearst since 1979, is
credited with leading a vigorous expansion that transformed the
company into a modern media conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   In Bennack's first decade at the helm, Hearst spent about $2
billion to acquire more magazines, TV and radio stations and book
publishers, and expanded its activities in cable TV, syndication
and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst newspapers were relatively quick to establish Web sites,
but the company's other pushes into new media have yet to find
success.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hearst already has a dot-com failure under its belt.
Along with appliance giant Whirlpool, it founded
comparison-shopping site Brandwise.com, which bit the dust in May..
</P>
<P>
   Hearst owns half of Women.com Networks, a Web site for women,
whose stock is down 75 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's third big online venture, GoodHome.com, co-backed by
Mattel, faces intense competition from other Web furniture stores,
none of which has proved that the market is viable.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst also has a string of investments in Internet firms,
including Exodus Communications, Geneology.com, Quokka Sports and
Talk City.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hearst has added some newspapers under Bennack, notably
the Houston Chronicle, San Antonio Express-News and now The San
Francisco Chronicle, the chain has become adamant about shedding
money-losing papers.
</P>
<P>
   In the l980s, Hearst shut the Baltimore News-American and Los
Angeles Herald-Examiner and sold the Boston Herald American to
Rupert Murdoch. In 1993, it closed the San Antonio Light, after
buying the rival San Antonio Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Hearst's actions in buying The San Francisco
Chronicle and selling the Examiner were motivated purely by
economics, a parade of Hearst executives testified during the
antitrust trial. Hearst said it would lose ``tens of millions'' of
dollars annually if the Examiner were to publish without a
revenue-sharing agreement with The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   From an editorial perspective, Hearst papers are far less
striking than in William Randolph Hearst's day, when they were a
flamboyant mix of sensational exposes, heart-tugging human interest
stories, screaming headlines and blatant bids to shape public
opinion. Although the term ``yellow journalism'' was coined to
describe Hearst's style, his papers also exposed corruption and
advocated progressive reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The modern Hearst has banished most vestiges of yellow
journalism. But in the process, it has become homogenized so that
its papers are indistinguishable from those of any other chain,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, it's all very bland,'' said Joe Saltzman, associate
dean at the Annenberg School for Communications at the University
of Southern California. ``There's no corporate personality to what
they do. Corporate decisions are made on a dollar-and-cents
ledger.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the same is true of most other newspaper chains, with
wire stories and syndicated features creating a canned feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearst newspapers tend to be conservative in tone and
appearance; fairly conventional, hard-news type newspapers,'' said
John Morton, president of media consultant Morton Research in
Silver Spring, Md. (Morton provided expert testimony for Hearst in
the Clint Reilly antitrust suit.) The Examiner, Hearst's first
paper, retained a more distinct personality than the rest of the
lineup, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's newspaper-business dealings have one clear focus, being
No.1. ``Their goal is to publish the dominant daily in whichever
markets they're in,'' Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hearst's strategies to achieve that goal have been all over
the map. In Seattle, Hearst owns the Post-Intelligencer, a morning
paper that has the unfortunate distinction of lagging behind its
afternoon competitor, the Seattle Times.
</P>
<P>
   The two papers have a joint operating agreement, under which
they share noneditorial functions and split revenues and some
operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Hearst agreed to let the Times switch to morning
publication, making Seattle the first city where two papers in a
JOA are competing head to head. But that battle is only for
circulation _ revenues will continue to be shared evenly for at
least the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   And Hearst hasn't abandoned the Post-Intelligencer: It pumped
$4.7 million into a newsroom overhaul, including a new computer
system, and expanded its editorial staff by 20 to 210.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, Hearst owned the 112-year-old San Antonio Light,
which lost $60 million between 1987 and 1982. So in 1982 Hearst
bought the larger San Antonio paper, the Express-News. It spent
four months seeking a buyer for the Light and then shut it down.
About 150 of the 600 Light employees got jobs at the Express-News.
Some labor activists were disturbed that the paper that was closed
was unionized, while the one that remained, the Express-News, was
nonunion.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Hearst swooped into town in 1986 and bought the
Houston Chronicle for $415 million _ at the time, the highest price
ever paid for a newspaper. When publisher Dean Singleton folded the
rival Houston Post in April 1995, Hearst snapped up its assets,
including the subscription list, boosting its circulation by about
32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``No surviving paper has capitalized on the death of its
competitor quite as effectively as has Hearst Corp.'s (Houston)
Chronicle,'' Editor &AMP; Publisher wrote in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at csaid(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
