<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6631 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NORTEL-COMPETITION &LR;      07-28 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-COMPETITION </SLUG>
  
 NORTEL ACQUIRES SAN JOSE'S ALTEON
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nortel Networks Friday agreed to buy San Jose's
Alteon WebSystems for $7.8 billion in stock, stepping up its battle
against Cisco Systems in the fast-growing market for equipment to
handle increasingly large amounts of data across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes just two months after Cisco, which is also based
in San Jose, plunked down $4.7 billion for ArrowPoint
Communications, a similar firm, based in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies build sophisticated networking equipment, called
Web switches, to help major Web sites cope with sudden surges of
requests for data and use their networks more efficiently. Nortel
said the market, which Cisco estimated at $500 million this year,
should grow to $4 billion within four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's white hot,'' said Bill Connor, president of Nortel's
corporate division.
</P>
<P>
   Alteon quadrupled sales in the fiscal year ended last month to
$110 million, with $51 million in the fourth quarter alone, and
turned in $7 million in profits.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ArrowPoint is significantly smaller. Analysts were
expecting ArrowPoint to generate $62 million in revenue this year
before Cisco scooped up the company.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts noted that Alteon also cost Nortel $3
billion more than Cisco paid for ArrowPoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal looks expensive,'' said Duncan Stewart, a portfolio
manager at Tera Capital Corp. in Toronto. ``Nortel portrays itself
as a company that does everything well, and then it says they've
spent nearly $8 billion on something they don't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Alteon shareholders also grumbled that Nortel didn't agree
to pay a premium above the current share price. Nortel agreed to
pay $143.77, just above the company's closing price on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies' stock tumbled on the news. Alteon shares fell 10
percent to $129, down $14. Nortel slipped $6.13 to $72.50.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the deal helps explain why government antitrust
regulators haven't investigated Cisco, which builds 80 percent of
the routers that direct traffic on the Internet, with the same zeal
they used with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cisco dominates the market for selling equipment to
business customers, it is increasingly facing competition from
Nortel, Lucent Technologies and other telecommunications equipment
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, the markets were completely separate. But
as voice calls and computer traffic are increasingly shunted over
similar data networks, the distinctions between the two businesses
have collapsed and both companies have started buying similar
startups and fighting over customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They own the enterprise (or corporate market). We own the
carriers (or phone companies). And we are driving the blurring of
those lines,'' Connor said. Nortel made its big move into data
networking by buying Bay Networks in 1998, while Lucent bought
Ascend Communications a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel's data networking business is especially strong in
Silicon Valley, where the company has 6,000 to 7,000 workers.
Alteon will give it another 500 workers.
</P>
<P>
   But a story this week in Network World raised questions about
how well Nortel has done in the market. The magazine said Nortel
has lost business to Cisco in two key product areas _ high-end
routers and a breed of superfast routers called ``layer 3
switches.'' Both pieces of equipment act like traffic cops,
directing bits of digital information across networks.
</P>
<P>
   Connor, however, insisted the company is doing better in the
fastest-growing segments of the market, such as fiber-optics and
wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel, which is based in Brampton, Ontario, near Toronto, has
gained special attention lately for its optics business. Corning
called off talks about combining their component business, but
Nortel announced this week it will invest $1.9 billion more in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview earlier this year, Nortel chief executive John
Roth said the company is also considering creating a tracking stock
for the optics-parts business, which has more than $1 billion in
annual revenue, although he said it's too critical to sell off.
Connor said that could still happen. ``We are looking at all
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
