<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITOL HILL MEMO: NEW SLOGANS, BUT SAME POLICY FIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the political conventions and the campaign
trail beckoning, Democratic and Republican lawmakers left town this
week uttering freshly coined slogans that they hope will help
voters choose sides in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas behind the slogans, however, are anything but fresh;
instead, they harken to the one age-old difference between
Republicans and Democrats. Does America want to spend money, in
this case part of the budget surplus, on tax cuts? Or does it want
to spend it on programs, like lowering the cost of prescription
drugs?
</P>
<P>
   Spun another way, the charges boil down to this: Democrats want
to sink the taxpayers' money into the giant government money pit,
yet again. Republicans want to line the pockets of the rich, yet
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the classic policy fight,'' said Glen Bolger, a
Republican pollster. ``But instead of red ink they are fighting
over black ink.''
</P>
<P>
   With the House and Senate Democratic leaders by his side,
President Clinton stood in the White House Rose Garden on Thursday
and reminded voters of this fundamental distinction between the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last year, the Republican majority has risked
squandering our progress,'' said Clinton, who has threatened to
veto most Republican tax-cutting measures. ``They have passed
reckless tax cut after reckless tax cut after reckless tax cut, to
drain away our hard-earned surplus and put us back in the red.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, he added, ``are leaving town with a trunk full
of unfinished business.''
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority
whip, expressed incredulity at Democrats for their refusal to give
taxpayers a break. After making the obligatory promise to use most
of the surplus to protect Social Security and reduce the national
debt, DeLay accused Clinton of hoarding the gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president doesn't want to return the surplus to the people
who earned it,'' DeLay said at a news conference. ``President
Clinton would rather use the surplus for more Washington
spending.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, both sides have tiptoed toward the middle this year, a
sign of election-year skittishness and a recognition that the other
party's message could catch on.
</P>
<P>
   A number of House Democrats, eager to inoculate themselves on a
popular issue, have voted for a series of Republican tax cuts in
the House, while their leaders, including Clinton, have laid out
their own, more limited proposals to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Republicans, pressured by the rank and file,
have offered their own remedies to address the issues that
Democrats view as their domain, namely lowering the price of
prescription drugs for senior citizens and overhauling managed
health care.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Democrats continue a steady drumbeat about a
``do-nothing'' Congress to the chagrin of Republicans who use every
opportunity to tout their tax-cutting bills, geared mostly to the
elderly, married couples and middle- and upper-class taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans do not seem too concerned that few of their bills
are likely to become law this year because of presidential vetoes.
In an election year, especially, it is the stance, not the result,
that counts. A veto would allow them to pose the question: Imagine
what would happen with a Republican in the White House?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am looking in awe at these accomplishments the Republican
Congress has been able to pass in the past few weeks,'' Dennis
Hastert, the speaker of the House, said while grinning broadly at a
send-off rally the day the Congress departed for its August break.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the Democratic leader, also is in awe, he
said, but for different reasons. ``The Republicans today who claim
great achievement have sent President Clinton only 78 bills this
year,'' Gephardt said. ``One out of four of those bills named post
offices and buildings, not exactly the most important matters that
are before us.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are not making it easy for Republicans, who they say
have caved in to special-interest groups in drafting legislation on
prescription drug prices, managed care and gun control. Yet the
Democrats do not appear worried that they will look intransigent,
something Republicans frequently accuse them of being.
</P>
<P>
   ``They block votes,'' said Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, referring
to Democrats in the Senate, which has had a much harder time than
the House in passing bills this year. ``Shame on them. It's a price
that will be very expensive for them in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not likely to get any easier for Craig and his party;
September and October are typically not the best months for
Republicans, because they must get down to the basic work of
passing spending bills. To do that, they must wrangle with Clinton,
who usually holds the upper hand in these negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The swearing-in this week of Zell Miller, D-Ga., to replace the
late Sen. Paul Coverdell, a Republican, could change the dynamics
of at least one bill when Congress returns: the managed care
legislation backed by Democrats. That bill fell one vote shy of
passage the last time it came up, a few weeks ago. Democrats are
sure to push for it again, aides said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
