<SLUG> BC-IRS-BRIBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS WORKERS ARE SUSPENDED IN BRIBERY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service has suspended at least eight
workers in the Chicago area in a criminal investigation into
bribery and other offenses, union officials and colleagues of the
workers said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspensions came after agents of the Treasury Department's
inspector general for tax administration made predawn visits to the
homes of at least five IRS employees on June 22, urging them to
cooperate with the investigation, said Charlie Turek, president of
the National Treasury Employees Union local in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Turek and lawyers familiar with the case said a federal grand
jury was expected to hand up indictments, in what would be the
first major corruption case brought against a group of IRS workers
since Congress passed the IRS Reform and Restructuring Act of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure the inspector general will indict as many as he
can,'' Turek said.
</P>
<P>
   David C. Williams, the inspector general, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Those under investigation include an appeals officer, two tax
collectors and an auditor.
</P>
<P>
   In one case an IRS worker and a tax professional were taped
discussing a $25,000 fee to fix a tax case, people who have heard
the tape said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the tax collectors was caught on tape agreeing to take
money in return for reclassifying an overdue tax bill as currently
not collectible.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the taping was done by informers who agreed to
wear recording devices after they were presented with evidence of
their role in crimes, tape recorders were also placed at
customer-service counters.
</P>
<P>
   As many as eight IRS workers at four Chicago offices were
suspended with pay three weeks ago and were told that they would be
fired, colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the workers facing criminal charges, a number of
IRS workers at four Chicago offices are expected to be disciplined
for failing to report efforts to bribe them since the investigation
began in 1998, colleagues and other people who are familiar with
the case said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation also uncovered evidence that at least one IRS
auditor had been paid to prepare tax returns, which were signed by
one of the tax professionals. Federal rules prohibit IRS employees
from preparing tax returns for pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6644 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-TELECOMMUNICAT     07-28 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-TELECOMMUNICATIONS-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TELECOMMUNICATIONS CIRCLE OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not even ``Melrose Place'' had as many intrigues as the
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. Deutsche Telekom, after failing in its bid to woo
Qwest Communications, made VoiceStream Wireless a $50.7 billion
offer that it could not refuse. This is the same VoiceStream that
had been courted by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone of Japan, the
world's largest telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, JDS Uniphase, the maker of components for
fiber optic networks, struck a deal to acquire SDL, which is in the
same business. Vodafone AirTouch of Britain is acquiring Germany's
Mannesmann, which used to be a publishing company, to get at its
cellular properties. France Telecom agreed to buy Orange PLC, the
British wireless outfit, for $37.5 billion. Corning, once linked
with SDL, was in talks until last week with Nortel Networks about a
possible merger of their optical components businesses. (Yes, that
Corning, the upstate New York company once best known for oven-safe
cookware.)
</P>
<P>
   All clear? Probably not. Even professional investors are having
a tough time making sense of it all. This year, the average
telecommunications mutual fund is down 6.7 percent through
Thursday, compared with the 1.3 percent drop of the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index, according to Morningstar Inc. The sector
took a beating last week after Nokia and WorldCom issued earnings
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when telecommunications meant telephones, and holding
Ma Bell let you sleep at night? These days, top stocks are far more
volatile. Qualcomm soared 2,619 percent last year only to lose more
than half its value this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a game for widows and orphans,'' said Oscar
Castro, manager of the $497 million Montgomery Global
Communications fund, which is down 10.4 percent for the year
through Thursday after gaining 104 percent in 1999. ``It's not even
a game for day traders.''
</P>
<P>
   Flag Investors Communications, one of the top performers of the
last decade, is down 17.3 percent in 2000, dead last in the
telecommunications fund league, because of big positions in SBC
Communications, Lucent Technologies and Alltel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in an event-driven situation,'' said Liam Burke,
co-manager of the Flag fund. ``Acquisitions are major events. We
don't expect major events from SBC, but we do expect them to
deliver growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke, whose fund remains in the top quarter of
telecommunications funds over the last five years despite the swoon
this year, said he and the fund's co-manager, Bruce E. Behrens,
were strongly disinclined to play mergers. ``There are lots of
people in the takeover speculation game,'' he added. ``We're
long-term holders.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to find stocks that are not involved in the
speculation one way or another, as predator or prey. Underlying the
frenzy is a trend toward forming global powerhouses that offer
wired and wireless ways to transmit voice, data and video.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, there will be a small handful, six or eight
megacompanies with global assets that will be able to go to Fortune
500 companies and offer them soup-to-nuts services,'' said Scott
Lewis, co-manager of the $520 million Warburg Pincus Global
Telecommunications fund.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Deutsche Telekom is making a statement that it will
be one of them, Lewis said. The deal for VoiceStream, if it passes
regulatory muster, will give Deutsche Telekom, No. 2 behind NTT, a
foothold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   How can an investor best profit from the turmoil and
machinations of the telecommunications industry? That depends on
which manager you ask.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said that he and the fund's other managers ``don't
particularly attempt to forecast takeout candidates.'' Instead,
they prefer to base their moves on relative valuations. One of his
favorite stocks right now is Nextlink Communications, a provider of
telecommunications services to small and medium-sized companies. He
considers it cheap at about six times his projections for this
year's revenue. Not that Nextlink doesn't play ball _ in June, it
completed a deal to acquire Concentric Network, which provides
high-speed Internet access. Nextlink closed at $33 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For Mario Gabelli, manager of the $450 million Gabelli Global
Telecommunications fund, the best strategy is a simple one: Pick
the acquirees and wait to rake in fat purchase premiums, like the
30 percent premium Deutsche Telekom agreed to pay for VoiceStream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game is not the buyers,'' he said. ``It's who
they're going to buy, because of the premiums.'' NE of his largest
positions is in Telephone and Data Systems, a Chicago company that
controls 81 percent of U.S. Cellular, in which Gabelli's fund also
owns a stake. He said he believed that U.S. Cellular would be
coveted by companies like AT&AMP;T seeking to expand their wireless
coverage through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Castro of the Montgomery fund begs to differ with Gabelli's
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very dangerous play to try to pick what the acquirees
will be,'' he said. ``You never know if you'll be acquired. If not,
you're left in the desert.'' And even if the deal does go through,
he added, ``you'll be paid with a currency that may be devalued''
by a volatile market.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Castro is bullish on the slumping Lucent, because
of the planned spinoff of its fiber component and integrated
circuit businesses. ``If you're going to play it, don't play the
acquirees,'' Castro urged. ``Play the ones with a clear strategy of
where they're going.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. The experts say bet on the sellers and shun the buyers, or
else go with the buyers, or forget about mergers and acquisitions
and find companies with staying power. Maybe it's a good time to
hide in an index fund until the smoke clears.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
