<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: GUERRILLAS FREED
</P>
<P>
   Eight-six hardened guerrilla fighters walked free from prison in
the last wave of 428 early releases of convicted bombers and
killers mandated by the Northern Ireland peace accord. The Maze
prison, home to 1800 inmates during the years of sectarian violence
that claimed more than 3,600 lives, was left with only 15 prisoners
and is due to be closed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: WEAPONS FROM CROATIA
</P>
<P>
   A haul of rocket-launchers, plastic explosives and other weapons
confiscated in Croatia was destined for renegade republican
paramilitaries trying to bring down the Ulster peace settlement,
the heads of Ireland's police force and the Royal Ulster
Constabulary confirmed. One of the splinter groups, the Real IRA,
was responsible for the car bomb attack on Omagh two years ago that
killed 29 people.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: BAN ON REBELS SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Citing a new British anti-terrorism law, the Sri Lankan Foreign
Ministry formally asked Britain to ban the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam, a separatist group battling for a Tamil homeland. The
Tigers, who have their international headquarters in London, are
banned in India. The U.S. State Department has listed them as a
terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: STEPPING BACK IN KASHMIR
</P>
<P>
   A senior army official, Maj. Gen. Basant Singh, told reporters
in Srinagar that the army has cut back its operations in Kashmir
since one of the major militant groups, Hizbul Mujahideen, declared
a three-month cease-fire on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: MARRIAGE RULING SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia is asking the province's Supreme Court to
declare that same-sex couples can marry. A gay rights group,
Equality for Gays and Lesbians Everywhere, is filing a supporting
petition naming the federal government as a defendant. Earlier this
month, federal legislation went into effect that erased virtually
all distinctions between same-sex and heterosexual unions. But this
new law also defined marriage as the union between a man and a
woman.
</P>
</TEXT>
