<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6647 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV30N     07-28 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV30NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING: SHRUBS FOR BEAUTY AND HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   July is often promoted as national blueberry month, and across
the nation, festivals and pick-your-own farms beckon and tempting
recipes appear in newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, says Al Murray of the New Jersey Agriculture
Department, the fruit is being consumed in record amounts. This
increase is due in no small part to findings published last
September by James A. Joseph and Barbara Shukitt-Hale of the U.S.
Agriculture Department's Human Nutrition Center on Aging at Tufts
University. Their research on rats led them to conclude that daily
consumption of one-half to one cup of fresh or frozen blueberries
could slow or even reverse the effects of aging.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, blueberries' popularity was confirmed this month
when the squirrels beat out both the birds and my husband by
stripping my semidwarf plants bare before the berries ripened. That
did not deter my husband, who went out and picked 25 pounds at a
nearby orchard. Thus, I have been making jam, baking and freezing
many blueberry muffins, and serving blueberry pancakes as a treat
on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   I look forward to August and the end of this hoopla. It means I
can return to simply treasuring blueberries as one of the most
handsome, maintenance-free shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   As the great horticulturist Liberty Hyde Bailey wrote a century
ago: ``The plant is beautiful when in flower; the fruit is
attractive and of the best quality, and the bright scarlet and
crimson effects in late autumn, rivaling the sumach in brilliancy,
are unsurpassed. As an ornamental plant, the species deserves a
place in every garden.''
</P>
<P>
   High praise indeed. And it actually neglects the pink blush on
the long-lasting creamy white, one-third-inch, bell-shaped spring
flowers and the red sheen on the bare winter stems. The stems are
particularly lovely when powdered with light snow.
</P>
<P>
   Blueberries are rather temperature-specific. Low-bush
blueberries (Vaccinium angustifolium) thrive in Zones 2 to 6,
high-bush (V. corymbosum) in Zones 5 to 7, and rabbiteye (V. ashei)
in Zones 6 to 9. Though Bailey was referring to the high-bush
berry, all three exhibit the same beautiful ornamental qualities.
All three, said a Canadian government food researcher, Wilhelmina
Kalt, bear berries with anti-aging properties.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bailey's praise, blueberries have consistently been
grown for their fruit rather than for their appearance. Elizabeth
White, whose family ran a cranberry operation in the New Jersey
Pinelands, can take a lot of credit for that. In 1911, she
contacted Dr. Frederick Coville at the Agriculture Department and
asked about his research on the feasibility of cultivating
blueberries. White believed that such cultivation would be a
profitable second crop, one occurring a month before the cranberry
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   In 1916, five years after the two joined forces, the first
cultivated blueberry was produced and an agricultural industry was
born. Coville provided the scientific expertise to propagate and
hybridize the berries. White contributed the plants, calling on
local ``Pineys'' to search the area for bushes with the most
promising berries.
</P>
<P>
   White paid $2 for every bush that bore berries at least
five-eighths of an inch in diameter and named each bush for its
finder. When Rube Leek of Chatsworth found a promising one, a
quandary arose. Leek wasn't a suitable name, and Rube didn't convey
the plant's usefulness. Coville christened it Rubel; it became a
key commercial blueberry parent and is still sold.
</P>
<P>
   I've had blueberries in my borders for 20 years. I started with
two 5- to 6-foot-tall high-bush cultivars _ Bluecrop and Jersey _
because two varieties are needed for good pollination and both are
suitable for my central New Jersey area. All they required were
well-drained, acidic soil, a weekly watering in dry periods, and a
mostly sunny location to produce summer berries.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, as birds devoured the berries despite a netting over
the bushes, I began to admire the shrubs more for their looks than
for their produce. Five years ago, I did away with the netting and
the big bushes and placed Friendship and Northblue, semi-dwarf
plants known as half highs, in a mixed border. These multiseasonal
plants grow about 4 feet tall and, if netted, can each produce
seven pounds of berries. But I chose them for their handsome look.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs researchers are falling in love with
blueberries' ornamental qualities. About 10 years ago, breeders at
Michigan State University introduced a high-bush-low-bush cross _
Top Hat. Forming a two-foot dense mounded plant, it is perfect for
containers and as a bonsai subject.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Nicholi Vorsa, director of the Rutgers University
blueberry and cranberry research laboratory, is evaluating some
beautiful high-bush forms for release. One has corkscrew-type
stems; another, closely packed green leaves iny that they reflect
the powder blue of the berries.
</P>
<P>
   While blueberry bushes might not ultimately prove to be a
fountain of youth, they certainly can constitute an oasis of beauty
and contentment in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   A wide variety of blueberries are sold by Forestfarm, 990
Tetherow Road, Williams, Ore. 97544; (541) 846-7269; catalog $4;
and Hartmann's Nursery, Box 100, Lacota, Mich. 49063; (616)
253-4282; free catalog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
