<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GE-NBC-EXEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF NBC GETS THE ADDED TITLE OF VICE CHAIRMAN OF GENERAL
ELECTRIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The General Electric Co. named Robert C. Wright, the longtime
president of NBC, to the additional post of vice chairman of GE
Friday. He will join the chairman, John F. Welch Jr., and one other
vice chairman, Dennis D. Dammerman, a financial officer, as the
only GE executives on the company's board.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who has led NBC for 14 years, the longest tenure for any
top executive in network television history, will continue to
manage the network and all of its other media assets, which include
the cable channels CNBC and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes nine months before the retirement date of Welch,
who is close to Wright professionally and personally. In a
statement Friday, Welch praised Wright as a ``key force in guiding
the company's future growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, 57, is not a candidate to succeed Welch, a job expected
to go to a GE executive younger than 50. But television industry
executives interpreted Wright's elevation as an effort by Welch to
emphasize the importance of NBC's assets to the future of GE.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said in a telephone interview: ``It's good recognition
for NBC and our media assets, for what NBC has accomplished. It
gives our media assets an important voice at the GE table.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that his new position will not significantly
change his day-to-day role at NBC. ``In the near term, I keep doing
the job,'' Wright said. ``I'm not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the new position will probably mean ``that I'll
pitch in and take on some assignments in GE's larger picture.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC has often been the subject of rumors about a sale to a
Hollywood production studio. It has been suggested that NBC _
without any connection to a bigger entertainment conglomerate as
CBS now has with Viacom, Fox has with the News Corp. and ABC has
with the Walt Disney Co. _ will be at a disadvantage in a media
world dominated by huge entities like AOL Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of a new chairman is likely to start new speculation
about GE shedding NBC. Wright said that the GE emphasis on
maintaining growth in earnings has made it ``a real challenge''
when ``trying to do deals to keep ourselves growing.'' Unlike other
media companies, NBC had not been able to add assets if the
acquisition price could dilute the company's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But Wright said he expected NBC to remain a highly valued asset
for GE ``The national use of video content is going to be hugely
important to the marketplace going forward,'' Wright said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
