<DOCNO> NYT20000728.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-POWER-NYT     07-28 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPIKE IN ELECTRICITY PRICES SETS OFF DEBATE IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  By   ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With electricity prices soaring in San Diego, and
consumer anger rising even faster, California politicians are
backing away from the state's ambitious plan to deregulate its
power industry fully by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The fight in California, which four years ago led to the current
national movement to deregulate the electric industry, is likely to
ignite a debate across the country over whether deregulation is
working, politicians here say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nationwide problem,'' said State Sen. Steve Peace, a
San Diego Democrat who helped write the deregulation legislation
but is now calling for some government controls on prices.
</P>
<P>
   High demand and tight supplies have given too much market power
to a few generators and power marketers, causing prices to spike
unreasonably, Peace said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market can either prove that it's disciplined enough and
stable enough to address its problem,'' he said, ``or, inevitably,
whether it's the right thing to do or the wrong thing to do, the
political system will cut them off at the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   That view gained momentum on Thursday, when Gov. Gray Davis
asked the federal government to impose controls on the wholesale
price of electricity across the West. Residential consumers and
businesses need relief from price spikes that more than doubled the
average monthly electric bill in San Diego in June, the governor
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When California deregulated the electricity market in 1996,''
Davis said, ``consumers were promised that competition in the
marketplace would be mature enough to ensure stable, if not
reduced, prices. That is clearly not the case in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Big swings in the wholesale price of electricity are not unusual
in the summer, when high demand taxes generators' ability to supply
power. In New England, the wholesale cost of power reached more
than 100 times its usual level for a few hours during an unexpected
heat wave this May. But because of regulation, consumers and
businesses have always been insulated from the swings, paying one
price for electricity year-round, regardless of its true cost.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as California makes the complex transition from a regulated
to a competitive market, San Diego has become the first market in
the nation where consumers must pay retail prices that move with
the true wholesale price as it changes from month to month. And
they are not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Diego in many ways is the poster child for how not to do
deregulation,'' said Michael Shames, executive director of the
Utility Consumers Action Network, a 42,000-member group based in
San Diego, where the average monthly residential bill rose in June
to more than $100, from about $50.
</P>
<P>
   But power companies and many economists argue that price
controls are a misguided and shortsighted measure that will only
increase the risk of blackouts in both the short run and the long.
Price caps failed on both natural gas and gasoline, and they will
fail on electricity, said William Hogan, a professor of public
policy at the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard who
has studied deregulation and worked as a consultant for utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have lots of shortages of natural gas; now we have
lots of natural gas,'' Hogan said. ``The reason we had shortages is
we had price controls. That's what electricity is facing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, independent power generators are moving quickly to
add new plants to bring supply and demand back into line, said
Jeffrey K. Skilling, president of the Enron Corp., a Houston
company that is the world's leading trader of electricity and
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the market do its thing,'' Skilling said. ``The system is
tight around the country, but there's been an enormous supply
response.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
