<SLUG> BC-NY-KENNEDY-NEGOTIATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEGOTIATOR, CAREER ENDS AS IT BEGAN, IN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was Detective Sgt. Daniel Karas' last day on the
job. Karas, a hostage negotiator for the Port Authority police, was
eating a piece of his retirement cake and preparing to turn in his
badge and gun on Thursday night when the police radio crackled: a
gunman had taken over an airplane about to leave for Las Vegas and
was holding hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Karas, 45, put the cake down, postponed the farewells and headed
out from the Port Authority police station at Kennedy International
Airport to Terminal 4. ``When that call comes, you go,'' he said
later. ``I still had my badge and gun.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got to the airplane carrying National Airlines Flight
19, two colleagues, Detective Curtis King and Detective Lt. Robert
Caron, had already begun talking with the gunman, who was holding
the pilot and co-pilot hostage in the cockpit. Sergeant Karas
joined in.
</P>
<P>
   Making contact was not easy. At first, the officers drove under
the Boeing 757 and plugged a set of headphones and a mouthpiece
into a jack that is usually used by ground crews to communicate
with the pilots before takeoff. After talking to the gunman through
the plane jack, the officers began to radio the cockpit through the
airport's control tower.
</P>
<P>
   It was stressful work, with two lives held at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``You run on adrenaline,'' said King, the lead negotiator. ``You
keep your fingers crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   Caron said the officers had one goal: to keep the gunman
talking. ``The more you talk to him, the friendlier you get, the
better your chances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was, by all accounts, a rambling conversation. While none of
the hostage negotiators would describe what was said, other police
officials said the gunman, who was identified by law enforcement
authorities as Aaron Commey, 22, asked to go to Antarctica, spoke
about suicide and talked about wanting to go to South America.
</P>
<P>
   Just to keep him talking, they said, one of the officers asked
Commey if he liked the Knicks. Using a vulgar expression, he
responded that he did not.
</P>
<P>
   There was relief when Commey released the pilot around 12:10
a.m. Friday and the co-pilot at 12:50 a.m. Then he remained alone
in the cockpit _ with heavily armed police officers waiting in the
plane's cabin _ for two and a half hours more before he
surrendered. The 143 passengers aboard the plane had already
escaped unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Karas went back to the Port Authority police station. In a
sense, his 23-year career had come full circle: on July 4, 1977,
just a few days after he joined the force, a Vermont-bound bus was
hijacked from the Port Authority Bus Terminal in Manhattan and
diverted to Kennedy in a bloody spree that paralyzed the airport
and left two dead.
</P>
<P>
   He said Friday that he was relieved that no one on the Boeing
757 was injured. He finally left work at 8 a.m. to turn in that
badge and gun.
</P>
<P>
   Inspector Anthony Infante, the commanding officer at Kennedy
Airport, had this to say of the sergeant's last day: ``It was a
hell of a goodbye.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
