<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CRITICIZES BUSH; PROTEST SITE SET IN LOS ANGELES; POLLS
GIVE BUSH A WIDER LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON CRITICIZES BUSH
</P>
<P>
   As hundreds of Democrats feasted on lobster and clams Friday at
a fund-raiser for Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy in Barrington, R.I.,
President Clinton served up some partisan zingers. Clinton mocked
Gov. George W. Bush for his gee-whiz attitude toward the
presidency. ``I've been governor of Texas. My daddy was president.
I own a baseball team. They like me down there,'' Clinton said,
imitating Bush. ``Everything is rocking along hunky-dory. Their
fraternity had it for eight years. Give it to ours for eight
years.'' The president said the Republicans were trying to blur the
serious policy differences, especially over how to handle the
budget surplus, between Bush and Vice President Al Gore. ``That's
the message, isn't it? Blur, blur, blur,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president helped Kennedy raise $450,000 for his
congressional campaign and then flew to Boston, where two events
last night collected $950,000 for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   PROTEST SITE SET IN LOS ANGELES
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for civil liberties groups and the city of Los Angeles
agreed Friday on a protest site for demonstrators at the Democratic
National Convention, a parking lot across from the entrance to the
Staples Center, where the convention will be held in mid-August,
officials said. A federal judge had ruled last week that the
proposed site, in a parking lot farther away and out of sight and
earshot of entering delegates, was unconstitutionally restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   POLLS GIVE BUSH A WIDER LEAD
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore had appeared to be steadily chipping away
at Gov. George W. Bush's lead in the polls, and in several had
almost pulled even. But since Tuesday, when Bush picked Dick Cheney
to be his running mate, the Texas governor has reopened the gap to
double digits, two polls indicated. A Time magazine poll released
Friday found that Bush led Gore by 16 percentage points, 52 percent
to 36 percent. Ralph Nader of the Green Party had 5 percent, and
Pat Buchanan of the Reform Party 4 percent. A CNN-USA Today Gallup
Poll on Thursday had Bush ahead of Gore by 11 points, 50 percent to
39 percent. Nader had 4 percent and Buchanan 1 percent. Both polls
had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 4 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Owensboro, Ky., Louisville, Ky., and Kenton
County, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: No appearances scheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
