<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIS-MAXIMUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT FAULTS FIRM THAT RUNS WELFARE-TO-WORK PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   By CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   State auditors in Wisconsin said Friday that Maximus Inc., the
United States' largest operator of welfare-to-work programs, had
billed Wisconsin for $466,000 since 1997 in improper or
questionable expenses, including more than 300 hours that its
employees spent seeking contracts in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus, based in McLean, Va., has come under sharp criticism
for its business practices in recent months, and a state judge in
New York has held up Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration's
plans to award it more than $100 million in contracts to help
welfare recipients find work.
</P>
<P>
   While Maximus officials said that many of the charges in
Wisconsin were justified, they added that the company had repaid
about $190,000 for expenditures that the state's auditors
considered improper. Some of this money was used for holiday
parties and concerts, including an appearance by the singer Melba
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Mueller, the Wisconsin state auditor, said the state and
the company would negotiate over other possible repayments.
According to a report released Friday, Mueller and her auditors
found $276,000 in additional charges that might have been excessive
or were poorly documented.
</P>
<P>
   The company's problems in Wisconsin have broader significance
because it still hopes to win the New York contracts. The Giuliani
administration has appealed the judge's ruling in April that the
bid process was corrupted because Maximus had early access to
officials developing the program.
</P>
<P>
   The administration asked the judge to rule on the issue because
the city comptroller, Alan Hevesi, refused to approve the
contracts. Referring to the Wisconsin audit, Hevesi said Friday:
``The evidence continues to pile up that Maximus is not a
responsible contractor. This is just one more example.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachael Rowland, a spokeswoman for Maximus, said the company
believed that most of the Wisconsin charges were legitimate. She
said the company had mistakenly billed Wisconsin for $51,000 in
wages for time that its employees spent seeking contracts in New
York and five other states, but said it was included in the
$190,000 that had been repaid. But she said Maximus repaid the rest
as ``a good-faith effort.''
</P>
<P>
   She said some of these expenditures were ``examples of our
innovative, out-of-the-box approach'' to helping welfare recipients
shift into the work force. The auditors, for instance, disallowed a
$23,000 payment to Moore, who gave a motivational speech and
performed in concert for former welfare recipients. Rowland said
the singer had once been on welfare herself and helped encourage
some of the job seekers.
</P>
<P>
   But the auditors also rejected more than $15,000 in expenditures
for holiday parties and social events for Maximus employees and
questioned $22,000 in restaurant charges and $1,500 for flowers.
The auditors noted that Maximus spent $196,000 on types of
advertising, including mugs and backpacks with the company's name,
that ``appear to have been more promotional than informational.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said some of the meals were served to former welfare
recipients, and she said the advertising was needed to increase the
company's visibility in Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-28-00 2335EDT &QL; 
