<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KENNEDY-HOSTAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINER HIJACK ATTEMPT AT JFK THWARTED WITHOUT VIOLENCE; SUSPECT
HELD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wis.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anthony W. Koncel, a pilot with 30 years of
experience, was settling in at the instrument panel of National
Airlines Flight 19 on Thursday night and preparing for another run
from New York to Las Vegas when the door of the cockpit burst open.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy came into the cockpit, put a gun to my head, and
said, `Go south _ I'm taking over the airplane,''' said Koncel,
recalling his 2 1/2 hour ordeal as a hostage. ``We said, `South
where?' He came back with, `Miami.'''
</P>
<P>
   As heavily armed police officers from a special unit boarded the
Boeing 757 at Kennedy International Airport and helped the last of
the 143 passengers to escape _ many by sliding down an inflatable
chute in the rear of the plane _ Koncel and his co-pilot, Sean
Walkerley, were held captive by a nervous young man who kept
changing his mind about where he wanted the plane to go: first
Miami, then Buenos Aires, finally Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   With a metallic gray Smith &AMP; Wesson 10-mm pistol trained at his
head, Koncel, 48, showed the gunman how to use the cockpit's radio
so he could talk to the police negotiators who were trying to coax
him to surrender. The pilot listened in silence as the gunman
claimed that the U.S. government was cloning humans and that he had
been deported from Argentina for weapons smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   After what seemed like ages, Koncel said, the negotiations
proved successful. The gunman agreed to free Koncel, then
Walkerley. Finally, at 3:38, the gunman surrendered. Police
identified him as Aaron Amartei Commey, a 22-year-old Bronx native
who had lived most recently in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Commey was arraigned Friday afternoon in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn on charges of attempted air piracy, and Magistrate Judge
A. Simon Chrein ordered him held until he undergoes a psychiatric
evaluation. The judge said Commey had no criminal history.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Commey had admitted to planning to take over an
airplane for months. They said he told investigators that he would
have used the handgun and hunting knife he was carrying against
anyone who disobeyed his orders.
</P>
<P>
   Commey's defense lawyer, Michael K. Schneider, said that he
decided to ask the judge to order the psychiatric evaluation after
speaking with his client for an hour. ``It seems like a sad case,''
said Schneider, a public defender. ``A 22-year-old man apparently
hijacking a plane to go to Antarctica.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe that Commey left Milwaukee by bus on
Tuesday, arriving in New York on Wednesday morning. He told
investigators that he left a bag with a shotgun and 25 shells in
the Port Authority Bus Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   At around 10:26 Thursday night, officials said, Commey arrived
at Terminal 4, an international terminal at Kennedy Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most airport terminals, whose security checkpoints are a
good distance away from the departure gates, the security
checkpoints at Terminal 4 are at each gate, less than 50 feet from
the entrance to the airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Commey simply walked up to the metal detector and X-ray machine
at Gate 33 and kept on walking, police said. When one of the
unarmed security guards stationed at the checkpoint challenged him,
the police said, he pulled out his gun and kept on walking.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers said that Commey placed his finger to his lips,
signaling them to be quiet.
</P>
<P>
   At the gate, the stunned security guards had pressed a button,
calling for help. By chance, Andrew Anderson and Richard Miller,
two emergency service officers with the Port Authority Police
Department, were driving one of the department's armored cars about
100 yards away from the plane when they got the call.
</P>
<P>
   They drove to the gate, where a ramp worker told them that the
gunman was on the plane. They ran up the Jetway, where a few
passengers were already beginning to flee, and entered the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a fireman running to a burning building _
everybody's running out, you're running in,'' Miller said. ``Same
principle. Your training kicks in.''
</P>
<P>
   There were still about a hundred people on the plane. Anderson
said he and his partner positioned themselves in the center aisle,
facing the cockpit, and told the flight attendant to open the
inflatable chute and have the passengers evacuate the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Once alone on the plane, the officers took cover behind two
drink carts and waited for backup officers and help from the New
York Police Department and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Hostage negotiators took positions below the airplane and tried
to talk the gunman out of the cockpit. Everyone waited.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the cockpit, Koncel listened to Commey talk with the
negotiators. ``He was really paranoid,'' Koncel said. ``A lot of
what he said didn't make sense at all. He said that he had had a
run-in in Argentina, and was deported to the U.S. for smuggling
weapons into Buenos Aires.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he insisted on talking with the consul general of
Argentina. The police sent a squad car to the bewildered diplomat's
residence and raced him out to the airport to be on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Commey also spent part of his time in the cockpit speaking about
cloning. ``He said that they had been cloning people in the United
States for a long time,'' Koncel said. ``He was just rambling.''
</P>
<P>
   After Koncel and Walkerley were released, the police negotiators
kept talking. The gunman spoke of suicide, a police official said,
and some investigators feared he would do something to force one of
the police officers on the scene to shoot him. But the negotiators
kept talking, and he calmed down.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, just after 3:30 a.m., the gunman had a new demand: he
wanted to wash his face. ``He wanted to wipe his face, to freshen
up,'' a police official said. ``We told him it would be OK, and he
agreed to come out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
