<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-28 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-LIGHTPATH-FLEISHE     07-28 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LIGHTPATH-FLEISHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEISHER SHOOTS RECORD 63 TO LEAD LONG ISLAND CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The saying in sports that it is not how you start but how you
finish was borne out again Friday when Dana Quigley birdied the
first three holes but still trailed Bruce Fleisher by a stroke
after the opening round of the Lightpath Long Island Classic Senior
PGA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   En route to his 8-under 64 at the Meadow Brook Club in Jericho,
N.Y., Quigley had eight birdies and a bogey. Fleisher, the
defending champion, also had eight birdies during a bogey-free
round, and three came on the final three holes as he fired a
course-record 63.
</P>
<P>
   Two strokes off the lead was David Lundstrom, who, like Quigley,
is 53 years old and in his third year on the Senior PGA Tour.
Lundstrom shot a 66 with no bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher, 51, won only once in more than 400 tournaments on the
PGA Tour from 1969 to 1998. As a rookie on the Senior Tour last
year, Fleisher became a dominant player, winning seven tournaments,
player of the year and rookie of the year honors, the Byron Nelson
trophy for low-scoring average (69.19), and earning more
($2,515,705) than any other player.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Fleisher has not let up. He has won three events, and
only Hale Irwin has won as many. Fleisher has also finished second
five times, including a tie for second at the Instinet Classic in
Princeton, N.J., last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After Quigley, the iron man of the Senior PGA Tour with
appearances in 101 consecutive tournaments, birdied the first three
holes, he landed his 5-iron tee shot about 18 feet from the flag on
the par-3 fourth hole. But he three-putted for his only bogey. That
turned out to be the difference in the first-round lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Littler, at 70 the oldest player in the field of 78, had a
1-under 71, as did Tom Longo, the head professional at the Seawane
Club in Hewlett Harbor, N.Y., who is a qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
