<HEADLINE>
BODY OF VICTIM ISN'T ESSENTIAL FOR PROSECUTION OF A MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ John Edward Robinson
Sr. was in prison for fraud the last time Johnson County, Kan.,
District Attorney Paul Morrison tried a murder case without the
alleged victims' bodies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, 10 years later, Robinson is back behind bars and Morrison
is preparing to prosecute him for the death of a woman, even though
her body has not been found.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was charged Friday with first-degree murder in the
alleged 1985 death of Lisa Stasi. He already was facing murder
charges in the deaths of five other women whose bodies were found
in barrels in June.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a body is not required to prove a murder in Kansas.
The state's landmark case addressing the issue was the 1971 Kiowa
County conviction of George Pyle.
</P>
<P>
   Pyle set his grandmother's house on fire after she had cut him
out of her will. The body would not have been consumed in the fire,
experts testified at the time, but no body was found.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Supreme Court upheld the conviction and established
that a murder could be proved through circumstantial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison relied on the precedent of that case when he charged
Richard Grissom Jr. in 1989 with the murders of three missing
women. It was the first, and until now, the only murder prosecution
in Johnson County without a body.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Rusch, Joan Butler and Theresa Brown have never been
found, but a jury found Grissom guilty in 1990 and he was sentenced
to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Keys, credit cards, jewelry and other items that belonged to the
women helped link Grissom to their disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony of their families also was crucial, establishing
that all had close relationships with relatives and friends and
would not have voluntarily abandoned them.
</P>
<P>
   In legal papers filed at the time, Morrison cited a California
Court of Appeals decision in the case of infamous killer Charles
Manson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that a murderer may successfully dispose of the body
of the victim does not entitle him to an acquittal,'' the court
said. ``That is one form of success for which society has no
reward.''
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
