<SLUG> BC-NY-VAULT-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN TRAPPED IN BANK VAULT SUFFOCATES 
</HEADLINE>
  By   ELISSA GOOTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A woman working at a financial services company in
Manhattan died Thursday night after accidentally locking herself in
a vault and triggering a fire extinguishing system that filled the
chamber with carbon dioxide, the police said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Esther Penn, 35, became trapped at about 9 p.m. in
the 10,000-square-foot vault while storing stock receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Before pulling the fire alarm, Penn used an in-house telephone
in the vault to call her supervisor, and left a message on his
voice mail saying she was trapped, the police said. She then
apparently panicked, pulling a lever marked ``fire suppression,''
which activated the extinguisher system instead of merely summoning
help. She was found by firefighters and pronounced dead on arrival
at New York University Downtown Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   During the two years that Penn worked at the company, Depository
Trust, in Lower Manhattan, she would regularly descend to the
basement vaults, said Stuart Z. Goldstein, a spokesman for the
Depository Trust and Clearing Corp., the overseeing holding
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The depository has been around for 25-plus years,'' Goldstein
said, ``and I don't know of a single incident to my knowledge where
something like this has occurred.'' He added that at least 20
employees entered the vault each day.
</P>
<P>
   A Fire Department spokesman, Lt. Frank Gribbon, said that a
preliminary application to change the fire suppression system from
a Halon gas system to the carbon dioxide system, which displaces
oxygen in closed spaces, had been filed in 1976 but never followed
up, and that the department had not found any records indicating
approval of the current system.
</P>
<P>
   Gribbon would not comment on the specifics of the system, but
did say that ``one of the key features of any system is the ability
for prompt evacuation.'' He added, ``They make these systems with
the intentions that they will be used properly. This was used
improperly.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said that Fire Department officials had assured heads
of his company that the system was approved. ``The DTC would never
put in a system like this if it was not authorized by the Fire
Department,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
