<HEADLINE>
SIXTH MURDER CHARGE FILED AGAINST JOHN E. ROBINSON SR. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO, RICHARD ESPINOZA and SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Serial murder suspect
John Edward Robinson Sr. killed a teen-age mother in 1985 and
brokered the phony adoption of her infant daughter, Johnson County,
Kan., prosecutors alleged Friday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robinson was charged in Johnson County District Court with
first-degree murder for the death of Lisa Stasi, whose body has
never been found, and aggravated interference with parental custody
for taking then 4-month-old Tiffany Stasi out of Kansas and
concealing her whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany, now a teen-ager, is living with the Midwestern couple
who thought they legally adopted her 15 years ago, Johnson County
District Attorney Paul Morrison said. The couple, who knew Robinson
before they adopted the girl, gave Robinson money that they thought
was to cover legitimate adoption fees, Morrison said. Prosecutors
do not believe money was the main motive in Tiffany's
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   The girl is aware of the investigation that led to Friday's
charges and is struggling with the horror of the situation,
Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   He said authorities did not think that the couple had any
knowledge that the adoption was not legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is paperwork that would appear to be genuine if you
didn't know any better,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's attorneys declined to comment Friday about the new
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany's family released a statement through FBI Special Agent
Dirk Tarpley and asked for the media's cooperation in protecting
the girl from publicity. Morrison said he and the adoptive family
are pleased that media have been restrained in their coverage of
the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Last month The Kansas City Star learned that investigators were
exploring whether a girl who had just completed her freshman year
at a public high school was Tiffany living under a different name.
The Star then located the family. Until Friday the family's
attorney would say only that the couple was cooperating with law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The family never hid Tiffany's adoption from her and had planned
to help if she wanted to find her blood relatives when she got
older, the statement said. At least one biological parent's name
was on the ``adoption papers,'' but Morrison wouldn't say whether
it was Lisa Stasi. The family said in their statement that they
didn't know who Tiffany's birth parents were.
</P>
<P>
   Now people are trying to keep the girl's life as settled as
possible. Morrison wants to try to limit Tiffany's involvement in
the investigation. He said his office might help arrange a meeting
between the girl and her blood relatives, who say they do not want
to disrupt her life by seeking custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody wants the best for this kid,'' Morrison
said. Grandmother feels hurt
</P>
<P>
   Friday was full of conflicted, often painful emotions for Lisa
Stasi's mother, Pat Sylvester of Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   News that a man was charged with her daughter's murder, a death
she had suspected for 15 years, brought her mild relief that
justice might be at hand. But, Sylvester said, she's not ready to
accept the idea that her daughter has died without the discovery of
a body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless they know something that they're not telling us, that
doesn't tell us that she's dead,'' Sylvester said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   As for her granddaughter, she's happy to be told the girl is
definitely alive. But Sylvester said she feels cheated at missing
out on most of the teen-ager's childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair,'' she said. ``I'm mostly hurting. I'm not
really angry at anybody but Robinson....(But) I'm more hurt than
angry.''
</P>
<P>
   She was especially troubled to think that because the adoptive
parents knew Robinson, he might have had contact with the girl over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bothers me more than I can tell you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Klinginsmith of Lenexa, Kan., Stasi's sister-in-law,
attended the news conference in Overland Park, Kan. She said
afterward that she was relieved to learn that Tiffany was alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she's beautiful because her mother was beautiful,''
said Klinginsmith, who is the sister of Carl Stasi, Tiffany's
father. ``We have a big family,'' she said, and ``we all want to
see her.''
</P>
<P>
   Klinginsmith reported the disappearance of Lisa and Tiffany
Stasi to authorities in 1985. All this time, she said, she has
wondered what happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about her (Tiffany) every day,'' she said. ``It's
something you carry with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Klinginsmith said she wanted Tiffany to know that ``we all love
her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad that my niece is alive and I just want to see
her,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Klinginsmith attended the news conference with her 14-year-old
son, Paul, who is Tiffany's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is right about her age,'' she said. ``He is all excited''
to meet her.
</P>
<P>
   Klinginsmith said she was leaving it up to Carl Stasi to take
the initiative regarding a possible meeting with Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Stasi, of Kirksville, was married to Lisa at the time she
disappeared, although he has recalled signing what he thought were
divorce papers some time later.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he declined to comment other than to say that
learning that his daughter is alive and that he might meet her ``is
the best news I've had in 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   His attorney said Stasi is inclined to let the courts deal with
Robinson and let the adoptive parents care for the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to let the law enforcement and investigators do
their work,'' said attorney Seth Shumaker.
</P>
<P>
   Stasi would like to know more about his daughter and,
eventually, form a relationship, he said. But Shumaker said
Morrison is handling the unique and delicate situation well, in a
way that makes it ``as painless as possible'' for the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would certainly like to know more, but we're starting to
get some answers and that's more than we got 15 years ago,''
Shumaker said.  &LR; brk:2 states involved
</P>
<P>
   Stasi is the sixth woman in two states whom Robinson is charged
with killing. The 56-year-old Olathe, Kan., resident is facing a
possible death sentence in Missouri and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of five of the women were discovered in early June on
property owned or rented by Robinson in Linn County, Kan., and Cass
County.
</P>
<P>
   Cass County prosecutors have charged him in the deaths of
Beverly Bonner, Sheila Faith and her teen-age daughter, Debbie
Faith. All three vanished in 1994, and their bodies were discovered
in a Raymore storage locker.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Izabela Lewicka and Suzette Trouten were found on
Linn County farm property owned by Robinson, but the murder charges
were filed in Johnson County because prosecutors allege that the
chain of events that led to their deaths began there.
</P>
<P>
   Lewicka disappeared last fall, and Trouten was reported missing
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of all five women were found in 55-gallon barrels,
and all were killed by being struck on the head.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also have linked Robinson to two other missing women
who, like Lisa Stasi, disappeared in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said Friday that police in Lenexa and Overland Park are
continuing to investigate the disappearances of Catherine Clampitt
and Paula Godfrey.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Stasi was 19 in 1985 when she met Robinson, according to
police reports gathered at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital social workers introduced her to Robinson, who
purported to be involved in philanthropic efforts to help young,
unwed mothers, according to court documents and police reports.
</P>
<P>
   He was the last person known to have seen Stasi when she
disappeared on Jan. 9, 1985. Friday's charge alleges that she was
killed on or about Jan. 10 of that year. She was reported missing
on Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Overland Park police and the FBI investigated their
disappearance, but no charges could be brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have been possible to prosecute then, with much
less evidence,'' Overland Park Police Chief John Douglass said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's next court appearance in Johnson County is scheduled
Aug. 23, to address motions filed by his attorneys from the Kansas
Death Penalty Defense Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Evans, who heads the unit, declined to comment about the new
charges filed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary hearing in Johnson County is scheduled Oct. 2.
Missouri officials have said they will take the case after the
Kansas prosecution is completed.
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
