<SLUG> BC-NCAA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE TREASURER SAYS NCAA OWES KANSAS NEARLY $1.9 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   TOPEKA, Kan. _ State Treasurer Tim
Shallenburger on Friday said the NCAA owed Kansas nearly $1.9
million in unclaimed property, penalties and interest, and he
promised a lawsuit to collect if necessary.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly all of the money represents money collected by the
National Collegiate Athletic Association for Final Four basketball
tickets between 1985 and 1995, Shallenburger said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that because of faulty return addresses, some fans
never got their tickets or refunds. Since then, the association has
held the ticket money in its bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement Friday, the association acknowledged it
had failed to follow the state's unclaimed property law, but
contended the amount owed was only about 25 percent of what the
state was seeking. The NCAA said it would pay the state as soon as
an amount was agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   Shallenburger said Kansas had attempted unsuccessfully on two
earlier occasions since 1997 to collect the money, but was ignored
by the collegiate athletics watchdog agency, which moved its
headquarters last year from Overland Park, Kan., to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Shallenburger, who said he's prepared to go to court for the
money plus an additional 25 percent penalty, said in no way was
this in retaliation for the organization's decision to leave
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Shallenburger said he already had imposed $33,000 in penalties
on the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never before imposed the penalty provided by law, and I
regret that I must do so today,'' he said. ``But when an
organization flagrantly violates the law and ignores repeated
warnings to come into compliance, I am left with no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   In its written statement, the NCAA said: ``Although we have no
record of receiving letters from the state in 1997 and 1998 on this
matter, we should have been complying with the law all along.''
</P>
<P>
   It promised to make full payment to the state once there is
agreement on the amount owed.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of the $1,881,682.86 the treasurer's office contends
the NCAA owes, the organization said the amount should be only
$475,000, including interest.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the NCAA's ticket system works:
</P>
<P>
   People wanting tickets to Final Four basketball games send
payment for up to two tickets, along with a $2 non-refundable
service charge for each ticket, to the NCAA. A lottery is held, and
if the person is selected, tickets are mailed to the indicated
return address.
</P>
<P>
   Those who aren't selected get their money back.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where the NCAA can't return the money or send tickets
because of invalid or missing return addresses, the money is held
in the NCAA accounts.
</P>
<P>
   After a period of years, the money held for owners who cannot be
located or identified must be turned over to the state treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   A state-hired auditing firm from Boston spent the last six
months going over NCAA books at its Indianapolis headquarters. The
treasurer's office received the completed audit about a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shallenburger said $1.1 million of the amount sought is
attributable to outstanding ticket refunds.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA said in its statement that the auditors erroneously
included in their calculations money from television, merchandise,
concessions and sources other than ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, the NCAA said it had been cooperating with the
state's auditors and ``believed we were engaged in a process to
reach resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   It said it had expected to discuss the audit with the auditing
firm before payment was demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less than 24 hours after providing us with initial
notification of the amount the state intends to pursue, and with no
opportunity to discuss findings, the state makes a public
announcement,'' the NCAA said.
</P>
<P>
   Shallenburger said he expects the NCAA to waste no time in
making the payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it's to its benefit to have this issue hanging
out there,'' the treasurer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA was created, in part, to inspire young people to fair
play,'' the treasurer said. ``I ask no more than that of the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a shame that an organization that sits in judgment of
our institutions of higher learning would, itself, violate laws for
its own benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the treasurer's office is holding about $90 million
in unclaimed property for about 375,000 owners.
</P>
<P>
   The money comes from such things as abandoned bank accounts,
uncashed dividend and interest checks, unreturned utility or rent
deposits and contents of safe-deposit boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The treasurer's office is charged by law with attempting to find
the owners of the property and returning it to them. If owners
cannot be located, the property remains in the state treasury.
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
