<HEADLINE>
TEEN SWEPT AWAY IN DRAINAGE DITCH, BUT SURVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA WOOD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With the power still
out from an earlier storm and no phone, Eric Thomas quickly grew
bored at home.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So the 14-year-old and a friend did what they had done all
summer _ they headed to the Town Fork Greenway near 56th Street and
Agnes Avenue to play basketball.
</P>
<P>
   While the two were playing, the ball rolled near a drainage
ditch.
</P>
<P>
   Eric fell in while trying to retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   He floated a quarter-mile north to the back yard of Mitchell
McHenry, who heard the boy's cries for help and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   McHenry and his sons rushed outside and found Eric, holding on
to a tunnel wall in 2 to 3 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   The strong currents had ripped away Eric's shorts and made it
impossible for him to stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad I heard him holler,'' McHenry said. ``If I
hadn't been here, he wouldn't have made it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Fire Department arrived less than five minutes later,
officials lowered a 12- to 16-foot ladder into the water.
</P>
<P>
   A cold and shaken Eric climbed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `I got to find something to hang on to so I won't
drown,' '' Eric said.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to Children's Mercy Hospital, where he was treated
for minor injuries and released. The doctor gave Eric a new ball to
replace the one he lost.
</P>
<P>
   His mother was relieved to hear her son was OK, though she
wondered why there was a basketball court near a drainage ditch
with no fence to separate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't doing anything but playing basketball,'' Donna
Thomas said. ``They didn't think it was a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dangerous for that (drainage ditch) and the park to be so
close together.''
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
