<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-PHILLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER : CITY PINS HOPES ON THE REPUBLICAN CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Philadelphia sandwich delicacy known as the cheese steak is
made of thinly sliced beef that is quick-grilled in light oil,
topped with fried onions, cheese and peppers and served hot and
dripping on what locals call a hoagie roll, elsewhere known as
Italian bread or a hero roll. At hoagie shops in South Philly, the
waitresses address you as ``hon'' _ as in ``Whatcha want on your
cheese steak, hon?'' _ as though they have known you all their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John Street counts every calorie, and has replaced his
predecessor's candy dish with a bowl of fresh fruit. But
Philadelphia is nonetheless counting on the cholesterol-drenched
cheese steak to win hearts and minds during next week's Republican
National Convention, the city's first in more than 50 years. Nearly
bankrupt at the start of the '90s, Philadelphia has fought its way
back, revitalizing its downtown and stanching job loss for the
first time in decades.
</P>
<P>
   The austere Street and his voluble predecessor, Ed Rendell, have
jointly promoted the Republican Convention as the moment of
Philadelphia's rebirth and a chance to show off the new city to
visitors and the press. But when the conventioneers leave, the
urban wastelands in the shadow of downtown's glittering towers will
remain. Reclaiming those wastelands _ and persuading Philadelphians
who are still leaving the city to stay _ will be considerably more
difficult than renovating the city center.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty and industrial decline that struck most big cities
in the 1960s and '70s were particularly devastating to Philly,
partly because the city was so poorly managed. In the '70s that
management was synonymous with Frank Rizzo, the racially divisive
police chief whose Bull Connor style got him elected to three terms
as mayor. His pledge during a re-election campaign to make ``Attila
the Hun look like a faggot'' mortified the city's remaining
corporate elite and worsened racial tensions that were already bad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; City politics turned macabre under Mayor Wilson Goode, who was
installed as the first black mayor in 1983. This mild-mannered
former city manager seemed a safe choice after Rizzo, yet it was
his police department that in 1985 bombed the home of a black
radical cult Move. The Move bombing, which burned 60 houses along
West Philadelphia's Osage Avenue, demoralized the city and became a
national metaphor for stumbling municipal leadership.
</P>
<P>
   When Rendell, a former Philadelphia district attorney, was
elected mayor in 1992 the city had a $250 million deficit and its
bonds were rated below junk status. Financial World magazine ranked
it as the worst-managed of America's 30 largest cities. On the
verge of bankruptcy, the city threatened to pay its workers in
scrip. Thus chastened, the unions accepted budget cuts and aus-
terity.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell persuaded residents to see hope where none seemed to
exist. He talked of the greatness and wonder of the city, even as
downtown Philadelphia hollowed out, leaving many great buildings
empty.
</P>
<P>
   The rebirth of that downtown is partly a testament to Rendell's
wide-eyed optimism, and at his instigation the city has come to
view the convention as a coming-out party at which the new
Philadelphia can replace the dismal past with a glittering new
vision of the future.
</P>
<P>
   But only in the last three years has the city proper experienced
a net gain in jobs, reversing a trend that is decades old.
Philadelphia has lost more than 167,000 people over the last nine
years, more than any city of comparable size. That means that 10.6
percent of the population has chosen to go elsewhere. Any attempt
to stop these defections must focus on the schools, which are
clearly among the worst in the country, even after improvements
posted by the celebrated city school superintendent David Hornbeck.
</P>
<P>
   Hornbeck left his job after he seemed to liken Pennsylvania's
treatment of minority school children to that of South Africa under
apartheid and filed a federal lawsuit accusing the state of
systemically underfinancing schools attended by black children. For
the Republican state government in Harrisburg this was the last
straw. But financial statistics lent credence to this view and made
it clear that chronic underfinancing was inhibiting a full recovery
in the city. Until the schools are made decent, the middle class
will continue to ebb away.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the progress under Rendell, there were more than 35,000
abandoned cars littering city streets when he left office,
contributing to a sense of hopelessness and desolation. Street has
towed nearly all of these away, but it takes only a short drive
from City Hall to find urban deterioration at its most extreme,
with open-air drug marts and consecutive blocks of decay. The
Street administration has proposed floating $250 million in bonds
to eliminate this blight.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's city center will be on display for conventioneers
as a shining image of accomplishment. But reclaiming the city's
far-flung neighborhoods will require another round of leadership,
money and heartfelt dedication.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
