A6682 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p BC-BUSH-KAN &LR;      07-28 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND CHENEY SWING THROUGH MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   JOPLIN, Mo. _ Seeking to build a
pre-convention surge of momentum, George W. Bush on Friday brought
his quest for the presidency to staunchly Republican southwest
Missouri, where he showed off his new running mate and took some
pointed jabs at President Clinton.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush boasted that in former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, he
had found a man who has Washington experience, but was not of
Washington, a man who would be his partner, but who could be
president if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is plain-spoken and a man who speaks from the heart,'' Bush
said. ``He is a man who knows what the definition of `is' is.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, gathered in the Leggett &AMP; Platt Athletic Center at
Missouri Southern State College, roared its approval. Bush's
reference to Clinton's hair-splitting testimony during the Monica
Lewinsky scandal was a frequent refrain during his speech, which
lasted less than half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made a strong pitch for his so-called compassionate
conservatism. He urged listeners to find ways to include everyone
in the nation's prosperity and to ensure every child has a good
education and a loving home.
</P>
<P>
   And he hit on his key campaign themes: Cut taxes to return the
federal budget surplus to taxpayers; let young workers place part
of their Social Security taxes into the stock market; and build up
the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's rallies Friday in Springdale, Ark., and Joplin kicked off
a five-day swing through key states as he and Cheney make their way
to Philadelphia for the GOP convention next week. Next up are
appearances in Kentucky, three in Ohio and one in West Virginia
before Bush arrives for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The swing through the nation's heartland was aimed at places
like Missouri and Kentucky, states that went Democratic in the last
two presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking it to the people,'' Bush declared.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Catherine Hanaway, coordinator for Bush's campaign in
Missouri, said Bush chose Joplin for his pre-convention tour for
two reasons. It was the only significant population center in
Missouri that he had not visited this year. And he knew the town
would give him a rousing sendoff, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, he is preaching to the choir,'' Hanaway said.
``But even a choir needs a conductor. Personal visits mean a lot to
people....He's building momentum for the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Marvin Singleton, a Joplin Republican, put it another
way: ``Bush is an old oil man. He knows how to hit a gusher.''
</P>
<P>
   Police estimated the crowd at about 5,000, but even Republican
partisans said they doubted it was much more than 4,000. It was a
spirited crowd, with a lot of foot-stomping and waving of signs,
both printed and homemade.
</P>
<P>
   Several other GOP candidates spoke before Bush. But Singleton
said it wasn't clear how well Bush's visit might translate into
votes for Republicans in close state races for governor, treasurer
and secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers carefully controlled the invited group so the result
was like a mailing to supporters, he said. In addition, some
businesses let workers leave early to attend the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tapped into the anti-Clinton mood of the crowd by making
several references to the need for honor and integrity in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, in a brief introduction of Bush, said they had
``embarked on a great crusade to restore integrity and decency'' to
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promised to meet all obligations of Social Security, even
while letting younger workers invest part of their contributions
outside the system. Vice President Al Gore has called Bush's plan a
risky scheme that could put Social Security benefits in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of his speech moved away from policy to add a
sentimental touch. Bush said he always gives parents this bit of
advice: ``The most important job you'll ever have is to love your
children with all your heart and all your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said every child should receive a good education, but said
school officials often give up on struggling students too early.
And he called on teachers to get such children extra help before
the damage is irreparable.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said he would try to keep Washington out of local
schools and return more control of federal money to local
districts.
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
