<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-SECURITY-LADN </SLUG>
 
ACLU, CITY FORGE AGREEMENT ON DNC PROTEST SITE &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democratic National Convention protesters claimed
total victory Friday when Los Angeles city officials agreed to set
up a public assembly area in front of Staples Center within earshot
of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was negotiated with the American Civil Liberties
Union after a federal judge struck down as unconstitutional city
plans to keep the expected 10,000 to 50,000 protesters a block away
from the convention.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the federal judge, protests using a sound system
could be held across the street from Staples Center's entrance,
some 750 feet closer than previously planned and under less
restrictive conditions. It will require a much larger contingent of
police to control the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased,'' ACLU attorney Daniel Tokaji said of the
stipulation filed in federal court Friday afternoon. ``The voice of
the people will not be silenced during the Democratic National
Convention.''
</P>
<P>
   All parties said Friday they were confident the agreement would
satisfy the First Amendment issues raised July 19 by U.S. District
Judge Gary A. Feess in ruling the original plan violated
demonstrators' rights of expression since they couldn't be seen or
heard by delegates if restricted to the planned protest zone at
Georgia Street and Olympic Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The stipulated agreement also addresses activities at downtown
Pershing Square, granting protesters more time to obtain permits
and the right to a stage and a sound system. It also sets the
parameters on some marches and rallies, in particular keeping
Olympic Boulevard clear of demonstrators as sought by the city.
</P>
<P>
   While law enforcement agencies also have signed off on the plan
despite concern about the potential for violence and disruption,
Los Angeles Police Department officials said the closeness of
protesters to the delegates will require added security at a
greater expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will absolutely need additional resources,'' said LAPD
spokesman Cmdr. David Kalish. ``This will create additional
challenges for us, but we'll comply. We're committed to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to charges they were limiting free speech because of
the original plan they helped formulate, the Democratic National
Convention helped to broker the deal this week by offering the new
location at parking lot 3, a property it controls during the
convention, for the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with the resolution,'' said Peter Ragone,
Democratic National Convention Committee spokesman. ``We're pleased
the ACLU and various organizations accepted our offer. The
agreement represents an effort to assure everyone's First Amendment
rights are expressed, while public safety issues are balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   In a signed declaration, Deputy CEO and Director of Logistics
for the DNCC Louis S. Vasta said the Secret Service and LAPD were
consulted, and there were assurances that pedestrians and cars in
the Staples Center area will be adequately protected.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Deputy City Attorney Timothy McOsker said the city
ultimately was convinced the stipulation was proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fairly balances the interests of free speech as well as the
need for security, health and safety around the site,'' McOsker
said. ``The (protest) area is within sight and earshot. It fits the
case. People can be heard and seen by the delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the new zone that fronts on 11th Street is
that it's directly across from the Staples Center entrance, running
west from Figueroa Street for 180 feet. A ``media village'' will
take up the rest of the block to the west, but will be within the
secure zone.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU attorneys said the demonstrators will easily be able to
shout through the cement and chain-link fence - all that will
separate them from Staples Center. The stipulation gives
demonstrators the right to set up a sound system in the protest
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our clients' viewpoint, it's a good opportunity to reach
the delegates,'' said civil rights attorney Carol Sobel. ``The only
thing between them and the delegates is the mesh fence. It puts us
within shouting distance, just two traffic lanes away.''
</P>
<P>
   First Amendment experts said the stipulation would take some
dissecting but that initially it appeared the coalition of labor
and civil rights groups had won the legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like the ACLU got quite a lot,'' said Eugene Volokh,
a UCLA law professor who specializes in First Amendment law.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the matter, Volokh said, the Constitution grants
the right to citizens to speak on public streets, and that the fear
or expectation of violence cannot be used to curtail that right in
advance of an event.
</P>
<P>
   Volokh said serious security concerns may still remain, and that
some of those can be met through appropriate restrictions, such as
limits on rallies or marches that might unduly block traffic. But
in general, he said, it is up to law enforcement to counter those
with appropriate means.
</P>
<P>
   The stipulation also addresses permit issues, particularly at
Pershing Square, which previously was a flash point in the debate
between downtown business owners who feared vandalism during
protests and civil rights groups that argued they had a right to
assemble there.
</P>
<P>
   Under the stipulation, the city cannot require demonstrators to
apply far in advance for permits but must be flexible up until the
convention. Furthermore, groups that have permits will have access
to a stage and sound system, which they can operate from 9 a.m.
until 9 p.m., the agreement says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes Pershing Square the Hyde Park it claims to be,''
Sobel said.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown business representatives declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
